<DIV2 TYPE="book" N="1"><PB N="7">
<HEAD>Ashmole MS. 1396.</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCIENCE OF CIRURGIE.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="1">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="2b">Now &thorn;ese chapitles of &thorn;is book ben y-ordeyned, I wole fulfille |my purpos pursuynge ech chapitle bi ordre, &amp; confermynge my|wordis aftir &thorn;e auctorite of myn auctouris and wi&thorn; experiment &thorn;at|I haue longe tyme vsed wi&thorn; &thorn;e help of god.  // // //</P>
<P>Al &thorn;ing &thorn;at we wolde knowe, bi oon of .iij. maners &thorn;at we|moun knowe, ei&thorn;ir bi his name, or by his worchinge, or bi|his verri beynge schewynge propirte of him-silf / In &thorn;is|&thorn;re maner we moun knowe surgerie bi expownynge of his name;|for siurge come&thorn; of siros, &thorn;at is a word of gru, &amp; in englisch siros|is an hand, &amp; gyros gru, &thorn;at is worchinge in englisch / For &thorn;e ende|&amp; &thorn;e profite of syurgie is * [of hand-wyrchynge.  Of &thorn;e Name of|a thynge Galyen seyth: he &thorn;at wyl knowe] so&thorn;fastnes of a &thorn;ing,|bisie him nou&yogh;t to knowe &thorn;e name of a &thorn;ing, but &thorn;e worchinge &amp; &thorn;e|effete of &thorn;e same &thorn;ing / Therfore he &thorn;at wole knowe what siurgie is,|he moot vndirstonde, &thorn;at it is a medicinal science, which techi&thorn; us|to worche wi&thorn; handis in mannes bodi, wi&thorn; kuttynge or openynge &thorn;e
<PB N="8">|parties &thorn;at ben hole &amp; in helynge &thorn;o &thorn;at ben broken, or kutt, as &thorn;ei|were toforn, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3a">or ellis as ny&yogh; as a man may, &amp; also in doynge awey &thorn;at| is to myche skyn: as wertis or wennys, or &thorn;e fleisch to hi&yogh;e //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>&para; &THORN;e secunde chapitle of &THORN;e firste tretis is of &THORN;e|qualitees, maners, and kunnynge of a surgian //</HEAD>
<P>Nedeful it is &thorn;at a surgian be of a complexcioun weel proporciound,|and &thorn;at his complexcioun be temperat / Races sei&thorn;,|who-so is nou&yogh;t semelich, is ympossible to haue good maners *[&amp; Auicenne:|euyle maners] but folowen &thorn;e lijknes of an yuele complexioun/|A surgian muste haue handis weel schape, longe smale fyngris, and|his body not quakynge, &amp; al must ben of sutil witt, for al &thorn;ing &thorn;at|longi&thorn; to siurgie may not wi&thorn; lettris ben writen.  He muste studie|in alle &thorn;e parties of philofie &amp; in logik, &thorn;at he mowe vndirstonde|scripturis; in gramer, &thorn;at he speke congruliche; in<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: quod docet dialectica</NOTE> arte, &thorn;at techi&thorn;|him to proue his proporciouns wi&thorn; good resoun; in retorik &thorn;at techi&thorn;|him to speke semelich.  Be he no glotoun, ne noon enuyous, ne a|negard; be he trewe, vnbeliche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>humbilly</I> in margin, in smaller hand.</NOTE> &amp; plesyngliche bere he him-silf|to hise pacientis; speke he noon ribawdrie in &thorn;e sike mannis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3b">hous /
<PB N="9">|&yogh;eue he no counseil, but if he be axid; ne speke he wi&thorn; no womman|in folie in &thorn;e sik mannes hous; ne chide not wi&thorn; &thorn;e sike man ne|wi&thorn; noon of hise meyne, but curteisli speke to &thorn;e sijk man, and in|almaner sijknes bihote him heele, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be of him dispeirid;|but neuer &thorn;e lattere seie to hise freendis &thorn;e caas as it stant / Loue|he noon harde curis, &amp; entermete he nou&yogh;t of &thorn;o &thorn;at ben in dispeir.|Pore men helpe he bi his my&yogh;t, and of &thorn;e riche men axe he good|reward / Preise he nou&yogh;t him-silf wi&thorn; his owne mou&thorn;, ne blame he|nou&yogh;t scharpliche o&thorn;ere lechis; loue he alle lechis &amp; clerkis, &amp; bi|his my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;t</I> in margin.</NOTE> make he no leche his enemye.  So clo&thorn;e he him wi&thorn;|vertues, &thorn;at of him mai arise good fame &amp; name; &amp; &thorn;is techi&thorn; etik.|So lerne he fisik, &thorn;at he mowe wi&thorn; good rulis his surgerie defende|&amp; &thorn;at techi&thorn; fisik / Ne&thorn;eles it is nessessarie a surgian to knowe alle|&thorn;e parties and ech sengle partie of a medicyn.  For if a surgian ne|knewe nou&yogh;t &thorn;e science of elementis, whiche &thorn;at ben firstmoost force|of natural &thorn;ingis &amp; of dyuers lymes, he mai not <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3*a">knowe science of |coniouncions, &thorn;at is to seie, medlyngis &amp; complexiouns &thorn;at ben|nessessarie to his craft / A surgian muste knowe &thorn;at alle bodies &thorn;at|ben medlid vndir &thorn;e sercle of &thorn;e moone, ben engendrid of foure
<PB N="10">|symple bodies, her lijknes ech in o&thorn;ere medlynge; &thorn;at is to seie:|fier &amp; watir, er&thorn;e &amp; eir: &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I> above line.</NOTE> elementis for &thorn;e vttirmeste eende, &amp;|&thorn;e vttermeste contrariouste of here qualitees were fer drawen from|bodilich lijf; but whanne her qualitees, &thorn;at is to seie, maner of|beynge, comen into medlynge, so &thorn;at &thorn;e leeste partie of &thorn;at oon|entre into &thorn;e leeste partie of &thorn;at o&thorn;er partie, medlynge breki&thorn; her|contrariouste; &amp; &thorn;erof comen a newe foorme, &amp; a newe complexcioun|of &thorn;e medlynge of her substaunce / Also &thorn;e medlynge of|qualitees &amp; &thorn;e quantitees is fer drawen from &thorn;e contrariouste of &thorn;e|same elementis, &amp; so complexioun is ny&yogh; brou&yogh;t to a mele; &amp; so|&thorn;at &thorn;at is medlid is more able to resceiue &thorn;e noble foorme of lijf,|&thorn;e which nobilite aboue alle bodies I-medlid is founden in mannes|spirit.  But for &thorn;at &thorn;e qualitees &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;o bodies of elementis| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3*b">comen into medlynge, &amp; it is vnpossible to departe &thorn;o qualitees|from bodies &thorn;at ben foure: hoot, coold, moist &amp; drie, &amp; complexiouns|ben bi hem, it is nessessarie to fynde in bodies &thorn;at ben|medlid foure complexiouns / Complexioun is no &thorn;ing ellis but|a maner qualite medlid in worchinge &amp; suffrynge of contrarious|qualitees &thorn;at ben founden in elementis, so &thorn;at &thorn;e leeste partie of|ech element entre into &thorn;e leeste partie of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere.  &amp; for &thorn;at ilke
<PB N="11">|.iiij. complexiouns, hoot, moist, coold &amp; drie, sumtyme ben y-componed,|&thorn;at is to seie, medlid, &thorn;er comen in hem .viij. as: hoot &amp;|drie, hoot &amp; moist, &amp; coold &amp; drie, and coold &amp; moist / Foure of|&thorn;ese ben symple, and foure componed; &amp; for &thorn;ilke .viij. sumtyme|ben wi&thorn; mater, &amp; sumtyme wi&thorn;oute mater / &thorn;er ben .xvj.; &amp; for &thorn;ilke|xvj. aftir sum consideracioun moun be naturel to summan, &amp; summan|vnnaturel / &thorn;er moun be .xxxij.  Neuere&thorn;elatter among alle &thorn;e complexiouns|&thorn;at man mai fynde, &thorn;at is componed of dyuers qualitees, &thorn;ere|ne is noon so temperat, as is mannes complexioun; &amp; hauynge reward|to mannes complexioun, alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis *[ys] I-clepid, hoot, coold,|moist, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4a">ei&thorn;er drie. / Whanne<NOTE PLACE="foot">A mistranslation from the Latin: Illam namque rem ... dicimus esse|temperatam, qu&aelig; cum <I>passa fuerit</I> a calore naturali, qui est in nobis, non|calefit, etc.</NOTE> &thorn;at a mete or a medicyn ha&thorn; suffrid |kyndely heete &thorn;at is in man, &thorn;at heeti&thorn; him nou&yogh;t, ne drie&thorn; him|nou&yogh;t, ne moisti&thorn; hym nou&yogh;t, so &thorn;at mannes complexioun may not|conseyue whe&thorn;er it coldi&thorn; him, heeti&thorn; or drie&thorn; or moisti&thorn; him: it is|clepid temperat / &amp; &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at we seie is hoot in &thorn;e firste|degree, &thorn;at is I-heet of kyndely heete &thorn;at is in oure bodies, &amp; heeti&thorn;|oure bodies wi&thorn;outen greuauncis / &amp; &thorn;ilke we seien to be hoot in &thorn;e|secunde degree, which &thorn;at is het of oure kyndely heete, so heeti&thorn;|oure bodi &thorn;at he ne my&yogh;te heete us no more wi&thorn;oute greuaunce /
<PB N="12">|&thorn;ilke we seie to be hoot in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde degree, which &thorn;at is het of|<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vn</I> above line.</NOTE>kyndely heete bryngi&thorn; to oure bodi sensible greuaunce. &amp; &thorn;ilke|is in &thorn;e four&thorn;e degree, &thorn;at is hot of <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vn</I> in different hand.</NOTE>vnkyndely heete, distroie&thorn; &thorn;e|bodi openliche / &amp; in &thorn;is same maner &yogh;e moun knowe degrees &thorn;at|ben colde / I mai preue in &thorn;is maner, &thorn;at it is nessessarie a surgian|to knowe complexiouns of bodies, lymes, &amp; of medicyns.  Take .ij.|men &thorn;at ben of oon age, &amp; lete hem ben I-woundid wi&thorn; a swerd or|a knyf<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ouer</I> above line.</NOTE> &thorn;wert ouer &thorn;e arm in oon hour &amp; in oon place; oon of| &thorn;e men is of an <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4b">hoot complexioun &amp; a moist, &thorn;at o&thorn;er of a cold|complexioun &amp; a drie.  &THORN;e comoun seiynge of lewid men is &thorn;at &thorn;ei|schulden bo&thorn;e ben helid on o maner; but resonable surgerie I-preued|techi&thorn; us, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne schulde not bo&thorn;e be helid aftir oon maner / For|he &thorn;at ha&thorn; an hoot complexioun, &amp; a moist, may li&yogh;tly haue an hoot|enpostym&mdash;&thorn;at is an hoot swellynge&mdash;&amp; &thorn;at may be cause of an|hoot feuere.  What schalt &thorn;ou &thorn;anne do? &thorn;ou must loke, whe&thorn;er he|ha&thorn; bled myche blood at his wounde, and &thorn;anne it is weel; ellis|lete him blood of &thorn;e contrarious arme, or ellis*&mdash;of &thorn;e oon same side,|if strenk&thorn;e &amp; age acorde; or ventose<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ventosare.  Kersey, <I>Dict</I>.  Ventose, a Cupping Glass.</NOTE> him on &thorn;e two buttokkis, if|&thorn;at he be feble. &amp; if he may not schite<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ascellare.  Add. MS. translates accurately: <I>go to sege.</I>  See below.|Compare: <I>a Sege of a Privay</I>; gumfus. <I> Cathol. Angl.,</I> p. 328.  Compare|the French: aller &agrave; la selle.</NOTE> oones a day, helpe him
<PB N="13">|&thorn;erto, or with clisterie, or wi&thorn; suppositorie. &amp; brynge &thorn;ou &thorn;e parties|of &thorn;e wounde togidere &thorn;oru&yogh; sowynge, or wi&thorn; plumaciols&mdash;&thorn;at ben|smale pelewis&mdash;or wi&thorn; byndynge, if &thorn;at sewynge be nou&yogh;t nessessarie,|&amp; &thorn;anne worche aboute &thorn;e wounde, as it is told aftir in &thorn;e|book.  But aboute &thorn;e wounde leie a medicyn defensif, of bole armonyac<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bole Armoniack.</I>  See N. E. Dict.</NOTE>,|oile of rosis, &amp; a litil vynegre; so &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5a">&thorn;e medicyn touche|&thorn;e brynkis of &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;at humouris moun not haue her cours |to renne to &thorn;e wounde; &amp; we forbeden him wiyn, mylk &amp; eiren &amp;|fisch &thorn;at engendri&thorn; myche blood / But he schal ete for his mete|growel maad of otemele, ei&thorn;ir of barli mele wi&thorn; almaundis; &amp;|generaliche he schal vse a streit dietynge, til &thorn;at he be sikir &thorn;at he|schal haue noon hote enpostym.  &amp; if &thorn;at we kunne fende him fro|a feuere &amp; apostym, &thorn;e science of his complexioun techi&thorn; us, &thorn;at he|may of his sijknes soone be hool / &thorn;e o&thorn;ere of &thorn;e cold complexioun|schal not be leten blood ne ventusid, for blood schulde be kept in|him, as for tresour / Forbede hem nei&thorn;ir wiyn ne fleisch, for &thorn;e|stomak &thorn;at is so feble ne my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t engendre nessessarie mater of|blood &thorn;at longi&thorn; to &thorn;e wounde / Ne we drede nou&yogh;t in him &thorn;e feuere,|for his complexioun is nou&yogh;t able to resceyue &thorn;e feuere / We moun
<PB N="14">|fynde a medicyn maad in oon maner &thorn;at worchi&thorn; dyuers effectis, &amp;|he be I-leid to dyuers complexiouns / Grene vitriol, &amp; he be do to|a man of a drie complexioun engendrith fleisch<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fleisch</I> in margin.</NOTE>; &amp; if &thorn;ou leie|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5b">him on moist compleccioun, he greue&thorn; nou&yogh;t oonliche, but corrodith| it; and ne&thorn;eles vitriol ha&thorn; but oon maner worchinge, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at he|worche dyuersliche in dyuers complexiouns / Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e worchinge|of &thorn;e sunne is dyuers, nou&yogh;t for &thorn;e sunne, but for &thorn;e worchinge of|dyuers bodies into whom he worchi&thorn; / Vitriol drie&thorn; wondirfulliche|myche: in drie bodies he defendi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>defendi&thorn;,</I> mistake for <I>fyndi&thorn;</I>; see below.</NOTE> &thorn;e smale lymes my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;t</I> for <I>my&yogh;ty</I>; see below.</NOTE> to a&yogh;enstonde|his mi&yogh;t, wherfore he may nou&yogh;t but drie &thorn;e superfluytees|&thorn;at he fyndi&thorn; in &thorn;e wounde; &amp; whanne &thorn;o ben y-dried, kynde engendri&thorn;|fleisch.  In moiste bodies, for &thorn;at &thorn;e smale lymes ben feble|&amp; moun not wi&thorn;stonde &thorn;e strenk&thorn;e of &thorn;e vitriol, &thorn;e fleisch melti&thorn;|vndir it, &amp; so bi vitriol &thorn;e fleisch roti&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;at is seid of dyuers|complexiouns, is y-seid of dyuers lymes / Galioun sei&thorn;: If &thorn;at|tweye woundis ben euene I-quytturid, &amp; &thorn;e oon be a drie lyme, &amp;|&thorn;e o&thorn;er a moist lyme, &thorn;at &thorn;at is &thorn;e drie lyme nedi&thorn; &thorn;e moister|medicyn / And if &thorn;at .ij. lymes leeue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leeue</I> for <I>leche</I>?</NOTE> ben I-woundid &thorn;at ben lich
<PB N="15">|in complexioun, &amp; &thorn;e oon ha&thorn; myche quytture &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er litil, he|&thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e myche quytture, nedi&thorn; to han &thorn;e drier medicyn /</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6a">Iohannes damascenus sei&thorn;, Medicyns &amp; enplastris schulden ben |acordynge to &thorn;e lymes &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben leid on / Galienus: a kyndly|&thorn;ing schal be kept wi&thorn; a &thorn;ing &thorn;at is kyndly &thorn;erto / And &thorn;at is a&yogh;en|kynde schal be doon awei with &thorn;ing &thorn;at is contrarie &thorn;erto / If &thorn;at|a surgian knew not complexiouns of lymes &amp; of bodies, he schal|nou&yogh;t conne to schewynge hise medicyns aftir &thorn;at kynde aski&thorn;.  A|surgian must knowe generacioun of humouris, if he wolde knowe|&thorn;e science &amp; &thorn;e helynge of apostymes, as it schal be declarid in &thorn;e|tretis of apostymes.  He muste knowe &thorn;e dyuersitees &amp; &thorn;e profitis|&amp; &thorn;e officis of lymes, &thorn;at he mowe knowe, what lymes han a greet|worchinge in mannes body, &amp; whiche ben of greet felynge, &amp; whiche|moun bere a strong medicyn / &amp; &thorn;e vertues of lymes &thorn;ou must|knowe, &thorn;at he se, whanne &thorn;e worchinge of ony vartu faili&thorn; in ony|lyme, &thorn;at he mowe helpe &thorn;e vertu &amp; &thorn;e same lyme failynge.  &amp; if|he haue &thorn;e science of knowynge of vertues, &thorn;e science of spiritis|schal nou&yogh;t be hid fro him.  Alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis bifore seid ben but|natureles, &amp; &thorn;ei <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6b">ben but techinge of medicyns speculatijf / </P>
<P>Also he muste haue knoulechinge of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben not naturels,|&thorn;at he kunne chese good eir to him &thorn;at is woundid or ellis ha&thorn;
<PB N="16">|a boch<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>boch</I>, Latin apostema; M. E. botch.  See N. E. Dict.</NOTE> / Woundis moun not be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heelid</I> cancelled.</NOTE> dried in a moist eir &amp; a vapouris,|but &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben woundid musten ben chaungid fro &thorn;at moist eir to a|swete cleer eyr &amp; a drie / In wyntir he muste kepe him fro cold;|for no &thorn;ing greue&thorn; so myche boones &amp; senewis as cold<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as cold</I> misplaced; see below.</NOTE> &thorn;at ben|I-woundid / &amp; in somer he muste haue temperable eir.  It is|nessessarie &thorn;at he kunne dietyn his pacient, as I schal telle in &thorn;e|same chapitle of dietinge / also he muste ordeyne meuynge &amp; reste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> cancelled after <I>reste</I>.</NOTE>|as it nedi&thorn; to &thorn;e same sijk man / for if &thorn;at he be woundid in &thorn;e|heed ei&thorn;er haue ony puncture of ony senewe, it is nessessarie &thorn;at he|reste &amp; dwelle in stillenes &amp; haue an esy bed &amp; a soft; lest he suffre|ony traueile of his lymes / But if &thorn;at olde woundis wi&thorn;out akynge|weren in his armes, it were good to him, &thorn;at is sijk, to walke on his|feet, &amp; lete his arme be bounde to his necke; &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde| be in hise schynes &amp; in hise feet, it were good &thorn;at he lay &amp;|traueilide wi&thorn; hise hondis / Also a <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7a">surgian, in al &thorn;at he my&yogh;te, he|muste tempere a sijk mannes slepinge; for to myche slepinge|engenderi&thorn; superfluyte &amp; febli&thorn; his vertewes, &amp; coldi&thorn; &amp; lesi&thorn; al his|bodi / To myche wakinge dissolue&thorn; &amp; confoorme&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>confoorme&thorn;</I>, erroneously for <I>consume&thorn;</I>, as below.  Lat. Orig.: dissolvunt|et consumunt.</NOTE> hise spiritis &amp;
<PB N="17">|maki&thorn; scharpe hise humouris; it bryngi&thorn; vnkindly drow&thorn;e to woundis,|&amp; is cause of akynge /  Also he muste kunne evacuener him|&thorn;at is ful of yuel humouris &amp; fulfille him &thorn;at is waastid, &thorn;at he|brynge sike men to good temperaunce; ellis a wounde mai not be|heelid / Entempre he &thorn;e herte of him &thorn;at is sijk, for to greet wra&thorn;&thorn;e.|maki&thorn; &thorn;e spiritis renne to myche to &thorn;e wounde &amp; &thorn;at is caus of|swellynge; to greet drede, ou&thorn;ir vttereste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>uttereste</I>, only known as an adj.: extremus, erroneously for <I>untryste</I>.|See below.</NOTE> of heel&thorn;e of his wounde,|holdi&thorn; &thorn;e spiritis wi&thorn;inne his bodi, &thorn;at mater mai not come to heele|his wounde / &THORN;ese .vj. &thorn;ingis ben clepid vnnaturel,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. qu&aelig; sunt secundum membrum theoric&aelig; medicin&aelig;.</NOTE> which techi&thorn; a|man speculatijf of leche craft.</P>
<P>He muste knowe &thorn;e sijknes: as olde wounde, festre, cankre &amp;|alle o&thorn;ere soris, &thorn;at he traueile not in veyn &amp; brynge &thorn;e sike man|to his dee&thorn; / For ech dyuers soor nedi&thorn; dyuers helpingis.  He|muste knowe &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e wounde / ffor a wounde, &thorn;at is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7b">maad |wi&thorn; a swerd ei&thorn;er a knyf, must o&thorn;erwise be heelid, &thorn;an he &thorn;at is|maad wi&thorn; stoon ei&thorn;er fallinge / And a wounde &thorn;at is biten wi&thorn; an|hound schal o&thorn;erwise be heelid, &thorn;an he &thorn;at is biten with a wood|hound; as &thorn;ou schalt fynde soone told in &thorn;e book herafter / &amp; he|muste knowe &thorn;e accidentis &thorn;at ben aboute a wounde / for &thorn;e wounde|schal neuere heele, til &thorn;e accidentis be remeued awey / accidentis is
<PB N="18">|a &thorn;ing &thorn;at falli&thorn; to a wounde out of kynde as hoot, cold, drie, ei&thorn;er|to myche moistnes, crampe &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges a&yogh;ens kynde / A surgian|muste ordeyne dietynge in dyuers maner, as it is told in &thorn;e chapitle|of dietynge; &amp; whanne it is nedeful, he muste &yogh;eue dyuers drinkis /|Galien: Laxatiues &amp; vometis ben nedeful to hem, &thorn;at han olde|rotid woundis &amp; stynkynge / For whanne &thorn;e bodi is purgid fro|wickide humouris, &thorn;e wickidnes of &thorn;e mater renne&thorn; fro &thorn;e wounde|&amp; so &thorn;e wounde is sunner helid / He &thorn;at biholdi&thorn; alle &thorn;e parties of|a medicyn, he may weel se &thorn;at it is nessessarie a surgian to knowe|phisik, &amp; o&thorn;er dyuers science, as I haue told tofore in &thorn;e book.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>&para; &thorn;e .iij c<SUP>o</SUP>. of &thorn;e firste techinge is of intencioun of a|surgian /</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8a">Al &thorn;e entencioun of a surgian, how diuers &thorn;at it be, it is on*|[of] &thorn;re maners / &thorn;e first is vndoynge of &thorn;at, &thorn;at is hool / &thorn;e|secunde to hele &thorn;at, &thorn;at is broke / &thorn;e .iij. is remeuynge of &thorn;at, &thorn;at|is to myche; so &thorn;at it be don with hand craft / ffor al entencioun of|a surgian is vndir &thorn;ese .iij. entenciouns, or ellis vnder oon of|hem  A surgian vndoi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at is hool, whanne he leti&thorn; blood,|ei&thorn;er garsi&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">garsi&thorn;] Lat. scarificat; Fr. ger&ccedil;er; med.  Lat. gersa, garsa.  See <I>Cathol.|Angl</I>., p. 150.</NOTE> ei&thorn;er brenne&thorn;, ei&thorn;er setti&thorn; on watirlechis, for &thorn;is is a
<PB N="19">|surgiens craft; &thorn;ou&yogh; we for oure pride haue left it to barbouris &amp;|to wymmen / for Galion &amp; Rasis diden it with her hondis, as her|bookis tellen.  And we vndoon &thorn;at, &thorn;at is hool, whanne &thorn;at we|kutten &thorn;e veynes, &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e templis &amp; &thorn;e forheed &amp; maken|cauterizaciouns for &thorn;e sijknes of &thorn;e y&yogh;en / And whanne &thorn;at we|maken cauteries in &thorn;e heed &amp; in dyuers placis of &thorn;e bodi, as I schal|telle in &thorn;e chapitle of cauterisynge / &THORN;e secunde entencioun is to|hele &thorn;at, &thorn;at is broken as woundis, olde woundis, festris, cankris &amp;|in bringyng to her placis ioyntis &thorn;at ben oute &amp; in helynge boones|&thorn;at ben to broken / &THORN;e .iij. intencioun is to remeue &thorn;at, &thorn;at is to|myche, as <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8b">scrofulus of &thorn;e heed &amp; &thorn;e necke &amp; o&thorn;ere parties of &thorn;e|bodie / cataractis<NOTE PLACE="foot">cataract, sebel and ungula.  See Notes.</NOTE>&mdash;is a watir &thorn;at come&thorn; bitwene &thorn;e white of &thorn;e |i&yogh;en &amp; &thorn;e appil; sebel&mdash;&thorn;at ben veynes &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e whi&yogh;t of &thorn;e|i&yogh;en &amp; be&thorn; ful of blood / vngula&mdash;is a &thorn;ing, &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; bi &thorn;e nose|&amp; goi&thorn; ouer &thorn;e i&yogh;e til he keuere al &thorn;e i&yogh;e&mdash;&amp; knottis, &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e|i&yogh;e &amp; o&thorn;er siknes of &thorn;e i&yogh;e; &amp; in doynge awey polippis, &thorn;at is fleisch|&thorn;at growi&thorn; wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e nose; wertis &amp; wennys; ficus, &thorn;at is superfluyte|&thorn;at growen vpon &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e pintils hede wi&thorn;oute,|emerawdis<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Latin text has: superfluitatem hermaphroditis.</NOTE> &amp; a skyn &thorn;at enclosi&thorn; a wommans priuy membre, &thorn;e
<PB N="20">|sixte fingre of &thorn;e hond &amp; manye superfluytees &thorn;at be&thorn; nou&yogh;t semelich|to a mannys body</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="2">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<HEAD>&para; &thorn;e firste chapitle of &thorn;e secunde tretis is an vniuersal|word of smale lymes &amp; her helpingis, &amp; of generacioun|of embrioun, &thorn;at is &thorn;e child, in &thorn;e modir|wombe //  /  /<NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>Vicary</I>, ed. Furnivall, p. 78.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Galienus sei&thorn;, &thorn;at it is nessessarie a surgian to knowe anotamie;|ne leeue we nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ech brood ligament is a skyn, &amp; ech|round ligament to be a senewe, so bi his opinyoun he my&yogh;te falle|into errour / &THORN;erfore I &thorn;enke to ordeyne a chapitle of &thorn;e kynde &amp;| of the <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9a">foorme &amp; helpinge of alle smale lymes / Auicen sei&thorn; /|knoulechinge of a &thorn;ing, &thorn;at ha&thorn; cause, mai nou&yogh;t be knowen, but|bi his cause.  &THORN;erfore we moten knowe &thorn;e cause, membriorum|consimilium, &thorn;at is to seie, smale lymes.  &amp; I wole telle &thorn;e generacioun|of embrioun: &thorn;at is to seie, how a child is I-gete in &thorn;e modir|wombe / Galion &amp; auicen tellen, &thorn;at of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes of man &amp;|of womman, worchinge &amp; suffrynge togideris, so &thorn;at ech of hem|worche in o&thorn;ir &amp; suffre in o&thorn;ir, embrioun is bigete / But the|worchinge of mannes kynde is more my&yogh;tiere, &amp; wommans kynde
<PB N="21">|more febler / For ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e roundeles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>roundeles, rundelis.</I>  Add. MS. <I>rendelys</I>, coagulum.  See <I>Prompt.|Parv.</I>, p. 429, <I>renlys</I>, or <I>rendlys</I>.  Comp. O. Du. rinsel, runsel.</NOTE> of chese ha&thorn; bi him-silf wei|of worchinge &amp; &thorn;e mylk bi wey of suffrynge, so to &thorn;e generacioun|of embrion mannes sperme ha&thorn; him<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mannes sperme ha&thorn; him</I>, Lat. ita sperma viri se habet.</NOTE> bi wei of worchinge &amp; wommans|sperme bi wey of suffrynge / &amp; ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e rundelis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>roundeles, rundelis.</I>  Add. MS. <I>rendelys</I>, coagulum.  See <I>Prompt.|Parv.</I>, p. 429, <I>renlys</I>, or <I>rendlys</I>.  Comp. O. Du. rinsel, runsel.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e mylk|maken a chese, so bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes of man &amp; womman maken|generacioun of embrioun.  &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;at alle &thorn;e smale lymes of a child|ben I-geten of bo&thorn;e two spermes, ne&thorn;eles, to clo&thorn;e hem with fleisch|&amp; wi&thorn; fatnes, come&thorn; to hem menstrue <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9b">blood / &THORN;e maris<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maris</I>, matrix.</NOTE> of womman|ha&thorn; an able complexcioun to conseiuen; &amp; of hir kynde he casti&thorn; |&thorn;e spermes to &thorn;e deppest place of hir; &amp; of hir nature he closi&thorn; hir|mou&thorn;, &thorn;at &thorn;er my&yogh;te not entre the poynt of a nedle / &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e|foormal vertu which almy&yogh;ty god ha&thorn; &yogh;eue to &thorn;e maris ordeyne&thorn; &amp;|diuidid euery partie of &thorn;ese spermes in her kynde, til &thorn;at &thorn;e child|be born / Vndirstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e fleisch &amp; &thorn;e fatnes is mad of menstrue|blood, &thorn;e boones &amp; gristlis, ligamentis &amp; senewis, cordis, arteries,|veynes, panniclis&mdash;&thorn;at ben smale clo&thorn;is&mdash;&amp; &thorn;e skyn be&thorn; engendrid|of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes, as auicen &amp; o&thorn;ere auctouris tellen / If &thorn;at ony of|&thorn;e lymes &thorn;at ben engendrid of &thorn;e spermes ben doon awey *[he] moun|neuere veriliche be restorid, for &thorn;e mater of hem is &thorn;e sperme of &thorn;e
<PB N="22">|fadir &amp; of &thorn;e modir; but &thorn;e fleisch the which mater is blood, &thorn;at is|aldai engendrid in us, may weel &amp; verriliche be restorid / &THORN;ese smale|lymes han dyuers foormes, complexciouns &amp; helpingis aftir &thorn;e|dyuersitees of &thorn;e proporciouns of &thorn;e mater, which &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben maad|of / for &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at alle &thorn;e lymes ben maad of oon mater I-medlid,| ne&thorn;eles in ech of &thorn;e smale lymes<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10a"> &thorn;er is a dyuers proporcioun of|mater, for &thorn;e which mater &thorn;ei taken dyuers foormes &amp; dyuers|helpingis.  Almy&yogh;ti god &yogh;eue&thorn; to ech &thorn;ing of his foorme after &thorn;at|his mater is* proporciound disserue&thorn; /</P>
<P>&THORN;e boon is &thorn;e first of &thorn;e consimile membris&mdash;&thorn;at is oon of &thorn;e|smale lymes; &thorn;e which ben<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I> for <I>is</I>, see below.</NOTE> cold &amp; drie &amp; he ha&thorn; dyuers foormes|in mannes bodi: for he helpi&thorn; dyuerslich / &thorn;e cause whi &thorn;er ben|manye dyuers boones in mannes bodi is, for sumtyme it is nede to|meeue oon lyme withouten ano&thorn;ir &amp; &thorn;at were impossible, if &thorn;at al|&thorn;e bodi were but oon boon / Ano&thorn;er cause whi &thorn;er ben manye|boones: for summe defenden &thorn;e principal lymes from harm, as &thorn;e|brayn scolle from<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>from</I>, erroneously inserted.</NOTE> &thorn;e brayn of &thorn;e heed / summe ben foundementis,|as &thorn;e boones of &thorn;e rigge &amp; of &thorn;e schenes &amp; of &thorn;e armes / summe|ben as additamentis &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e side of &thorn;e rigge boon, &amp; summe|to fulfille the holownes of summe ioyntis, as &thorn;e handis &amp; &thorn;e feet;
<PB N="23">|&amp; summe &thorn;er ben &thorn;at &thorn;e roundnes of &thorn;e boon my&yogh;te entre into &thorn;e|holownes of &thorn;at o&thorn;er boon / &amp; non les schulde not lacke his|meuynge as &thorn;e schuldre boones &amp; &thorn;e hipe boones.  &THORN;ou maist fynde|how manye boones &thorn;er ben in &thorn;e .ij. tretis, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10b">where schal be told |pleynlier &thorn;e anotamie of consimile membris of al &thorn;e bodi from &thorn;e|heed to &thorn;e foot.</P>
<P>A gristil is cold &amp; drie, &amp; is neischere &thorn;an a boon, &amp; hardere &thorn;an|&thorn;e fleisch, and in &thorn;e fleisch he ha&thorn; sixe helpingis / &thorn;e firste, &thorn;at &thorn;at|schulde be a meene bitwene &thorn;e vttir ende of &thorn;e hard boon &amp; &thorn;e|neische fleisch / &thorn;e .ij. &thorn;at &thorn;e harde schulde not hirte &thorn;e neische,|nameli in &thorn;e tyme of compressioun, &amp; in &thorn;e tyme of smytinge / &thorn;e|.iij. &thorn;at &thorn;e eende of &thorn;e boones whiche &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e ioyntis schulden|haue a softere confutacioun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>confutacioun</I>, erroneously for <I>confricacioun</I>.  See below.</NOTE> in her ioyntis / &thorn;e four&thorn;e, &thorn;at he schulde|fulfille &thorn;e office of &thorn;e boon to susteyne a brawne, meuynge a membre|&thorn;at ha&thorn; noon boon, as &thorn;e ouer lid of &thorn;e i&yogh;e / &thorn;e fif&thorn;e: for it is|nessessarie a gristil to ben in place, &thorn;at is nou&yogh;t ful hard as &thorn;e &thorn;rote|bolle; for &thorn;e eende of &thorn;e &thorn;rote bolle is gristeli / &thorn;e .vj.: for it is|nessessarie summe lymes to han a sustentacioun, and applicacioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>applicacioun</I>.  Read <I>a plicacioun.</I></NOTE>|&thorn;at is foldynge, to be streyned &amp; drawen abrod as &thorn;e nose&thorn;rillis &amp;|&thorn;e gristile of &thorn;e eere.
<PB N="24"></P>
<P>Lygament is cold &amp; drie, and go&thorn; out of &thorn;e boones &amp; ha&thorn; &thorn;e|foorme of a senewe.  &amp; he may be bowid, but he feli&thorn; nou&yogh;t; &amp;| he <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11a">ha&thorn; foure helpingis / &thorn;e firste is, &thorn;at he knytti&thorn; oon boon wi&thorn;|ano&thorn;er / it is nessessarie, &thorn;at oon boon be knytt wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er, &thorn;at|many boonys my&yogh;ten make oon bodi as oon boon, &amp; neuere&thorn;elatter|ech membre my&yogh;te meue bi him-silf, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;e ligament is as|bowable &amp; incensible / for if &thorn;at it hadde be censible, &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten|nou&yogh;t han I-susteyned &thorn;e traueile &amp; &thorn;e meuynge of &thorn;e ioyntis / &amp;|if &thorn;at he hadde be inflexible as a boon, of whom he come&thorn; of, oon|lyme my&yogh;te not han meued wi&thorn;outen ano&thorn;er / &thorn;e secunde help is,|&thorn;at he is ioyned wi&thorn; senewis to make cordis &amp; brawnes / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde|help is &thorn;at he schulde be a restynge place to summe senewis / &thorn;e|four&thorn;e &thorn;at bi him &thorn;e membris, &thorn;at ben wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e bodies, schulden|ben y-teied, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at neden hangynge.</P>
<P>A corde<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is a constant confusion in all the medi&aelig;val medical books between| nerves and sinews.  See further Notes.</NOTE> is cold &amp; drie, &amp; he come&thorn; from &thorn;e brayne, ei&thorn;er from|&thorn;e mucha<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mucha</I>, an error for <I>nucha</I>; med. Lat. <I>nucha</I>.  Dufr.: postera pars colli.|Fr. nuque.  Littr&eacute; gives references from the 14th cent. for the signification,|marrow.  See Notes.</NOTE>; &thorn;at is &thorn;e marie of &thorn;e rigge boones // From &thorn;e brayn|comen .vij. peire cordes. &amp; &thorn;ei ben clepid sensible senewis / ffrom|&thorn;e nucha &thorn;er comen xxx peire cordis &amp; oon bi him silf &amp; &thorn;ei ben|mouable / And alle &thorn;e cordis &thorn;at comen of &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11b">brayn &amp; nucha, ha&thorn;
<PB N="25">|bo&thorn;e felynge &amp; meuynge. &amp; &thorn;e cordis ben white, bowable,|strong &amp; tow&yogh;. &amp; of her kynde &thorn;ei bryngen meuynge &amp; felynge to|lymes. &amp; for &thorn;at it is long &amp; dyuydi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; dyuydi&thorn;] a mistake for <I>to dyvyde.</I>  Latin: De divisione vero membrorum|multum longa est doctrina.</NOTE> alle &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e senewis|*[in &thorn;e secunde tretys y schal ordeyne Anotamye of &yogh;enewes &amp; here|place] as &thorn;ei ligge; in &thorn;e whiche placis &thorn;ou must be war whanne|&thorn;ou schalt kutte ei&thorn;er brenne / whanne &thorn;at we schulen ordeyne|anotamie of official membris &amp; of her woundis / Official membris|is to seie: a fyngir, a ioynt, an hand, ei&thorn;er a foot *[ore] o&thorn;ere|lymes of office /</P>
<P>Arteries ben hoote nou&yogh;t of her owne kynde, but for &thorn;e hoot|blood &amp; lijf &thorn;at goi&thorn; in hem from &thorn;e herte.  Of her kynde &thorn;ei ben|colde &amp; drie &amp; &thorn;ei han two clo&thorn;is, outcept oon &thorn;at goi&thorn; to &thorn;e lungis;|&thorn;e ynnere corde is stronger &amp; grettere, &thorn;at he mowe wi&thorn;holde a|meuable mater &amp; an hoot. &amp; her bigynnynge is in &thorn;e lift side of &thorn;e|herte. &amp; &thorn;ere bigynnen two arteries; oon goi&thorn; to &thorn;e lunge &amp; ha&thorn;|but oon coote and sprat in &thorn;e same lunge, &amp; &thorn;ere endi&thorn; &amp; bringi&thorn;|blood to &thorn;e lunge, bi whom he is norischid, &amp; spirit of lijf, and &thorn;at|he my&yogh;te brynge from &thorn;e lunge eir to &thorn;e herte for to entempre &thorn;e|fumosite of hete of &thorn;e herte. &amp; &thorn;is arterie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Arteria venalis,</I> Pulmonary vein.  It was taken to be an artery, as it|carries arterial blood.  See <I>Vicary's Anatomie</I>, ed. Furnivall, p. 58, note 1.</NOTE> is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12a">y-clepid venales. &amp; it 
<PB N="26">|is a maner veyne, for as myche as he ne ha&thorn; but oon coote, and|&thorn;erfore he is &thorn;e more obedient to be drawe abrood &thorn;oru&yogh; out alle &thorn;e|lungis; &amp; also &thorn;at &thorn;e blood &thorn;at norischi&thorn; &thorn;e lungis my&yogh;te li&yogh;tly|swete out of &thorn;is arterie / &THORN;e to&thorn;er arterie &thorn;at come&thorn; out of &thorn;e lift-side|of &thorn;e herte ha&thorn; two cootis, bi cause &thorn;at oon my&yogh;t not a&yogh;enstonde|&thorn;e strenk&thorn;e of &thorn;e spiritis; &amp; also &thorn;at, &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e arterie, is|ful derwor&thorn;e &amp; nedi&thorn; greet kepinge / &THORN;er ben &thorn;re helpingis of &thorn;e|arteries: oon is &thorn;at cold eir my&yogh;te bi hem be drawe &amp; I-brou&yogh;t to|&thorn;e herte whanne &thorn;e arterie is drawe abrod.  &THORN;e secunde is, &thorn;at &thorn;e|fumosite my&yogh;te be cast out whanne he is constreyned / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is,|&thorn;at &thorn;e spirit of lijf my&yogh;te be brou&yogh;t bi hem to al &thorn;e bodi / &thorn;ese|arteries ben deuydid many weies; whos dyuysiouns man mai nou&yogh;t|conseyue bi his witt, ne &thorn;ei ben nou&yogh;t dredful to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> erased.</NOTE> surgiens craft,|but whanne &thorn;ou schalt drede &thorn;e arteries I schal telle &thorn;ee in her|placis /</P>
<P>Veynes bi cause of her bodies ben deemed cold &amp; drie; for &thorn;e| blood &thorn;at is withynne hem &thorn;ei ben deemed hoot; &amp; alle &thorn;e veynes han|her bigynnynge<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12b"> at &thorn;e lyuere, in &thorn;e which lyuere .ij. veynes han pryncipal|bigynnynge / oon veyne bigynne&thorn; of &thorn;e holow&yogh; side of &thorn;e lyuere.|&amp; is clepid porta<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vena Porta.</I>  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 22, note 1.</NOTE>&mdash;&thorn;at is a &yogh;ate / &amp; her office is to drawe *[Chilum]
<PB N="27">|fro &thorn;e stomak &amp; &thorn;e guttis bi mene of &thorn;e veynes miseraices<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Veynis miserak.</I>  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 66, note 7.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;ilke|chilum spredi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e lyuere bi mene of veynes capillares /|Chilum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Chilum</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 68, note 2.</NOTE> is &thorn;e licour of &thorn;e mete, whanne it goi&thorn; out of &thorn;e stomak &amp;|&thorn;e guttes / Veynis miserak<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Veynis miserak</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 66, note 7.</NOTE> ben smale veynes &thorn;at comen out of &thorn;e|veyne &thorn;at is clepid porta &amp; cleue&thorn; on &thorn;e stomak &amp; &thorn;e guttis / Venes|capillares, &thorn;at ben veynes as it were heers of a mannes heed /</P>
<P>After hem come&thorn; panniclis&mdash;&thorn;at is to seie smal cloo&thorn;, &thorn;at is maad|of sutil &thorn;redis of senewis, veynes &amp; arteries / wherfore &thorn;ei ben colde|&amp; drie &amp; censible / &amp; &thorn;ei han &thorn;re helpingis / &thorn;e firste is: &thorn;at &thorn;ei|moun bynde manye &thorn;ingis in oon foorme, as &thorn;e panicle of &thorn;e heed|byndi&thorn; seuene boones / &thorn;e secunde Iuuament is: &thorn;at &thorn;ei hangen &amp;|bynden summe membris wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere as &thorn;e reynes to &thorn;e rigge &amp; &thorn;e|maris<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;e maris to &thorn;e maris to &thorn;e rigge.  The second <I>maris</I> is cancelled.</NOTE> to &thorn;e rigge / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde helpinge is: &thorn;at &thorn;e membris<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="13a">|&thorn;at ben incensible bi her kynde, bi &thorn;e panniclis &thorn;at wrie&thorn; hem |velen bi accident: as &thorn;e lungis, &thorn;e lyuere, &amp; &thorn;e splene, &amp; &thorn;e reynes.|&THORN;es lymes bi her kynde han no felynge, but what &thorn;ei felen it is bi|accidens of &thorn;e pannicle &thorn;at wrie&thorn; hem.</P>
<P>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Latin: Caro vero calida est et humida.</NOTE> fleisch is not hoot, but it is moist &amp; ha&thorn; &thorn;re maner lijknes:|oon is a symple fleisch, &amp; his helpinge is to fulfille &thorn;e voide placis
<PB N="28">|of smale lymes to brynge hem to a good schap, &amp; &thorn;at ech hard lyme|schulde nou&yogh;t hirte o&thorn;er wi&thorn; confucacioun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>confucacioun</I>.  Addit. <I>confricacioun</I>.  See page 23, note 2.</NOTE> togidere / Ano&thorn;er maner|fleisch &thorn;er is &thorn;at is glandelose, &thorn;at is as it were accornis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>accornis</I>, glandes.</NOTE> &amp; his|Iuuament is &thorn;at he turne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Latin: eius juvamentum est, ut convertat humiditates ad eius colorem.|The English translator read: calorem.</NOTE> humedites, &thorn;at is to seie moistnes to her|heete; as &thorn;e glandelose fleisch of wommans brestis &thorn;e which &thorn;at|turne&thorn; &thorn;e blood &thorn;at is drawen from &thorn;e maris into mylk; &amp; &thorn;e|glandelose fleisch of &thorn;e ballockis, &thorn;at turne&thorn; &thorn;e blood into sperme /|&amp; &thorn;e glandelose fleisch of &thorn;e chekis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; spotil / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde|maner fleisch is a fleisch &thorn;at is in brawnys, &thorn;at is clepid a brawn|fleisch, for he is medlid wi&thorn; sutil &thorn;redis of cordis, as I schal telle| after &thorn;e whiche helpingis schal be told in &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="13b">anotamie of &thorn;e brawn.</P>
<P>At &thorn;e laste is &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at is temperat in al her qualitees; &amp; it|is maad of smale &thorn;redis of veynes, senewis, &amp; arteries, &thorn;at maki&thorn;|him censible, &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; him li&yogh;f &amp; worchinge, &thorn;at ben gouernouris of|al &thorn;e bodi. &amp; &thorn;e skyn is maad temperat, for he schulde knowe hoot,|coold, moist, &amp; drie, soft, hard, scharp, &amp; smo&thorn;e / &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;e skyn|were as sencible as a senewe, &thorn;anne a man my&yogh;te not dwelle in er&thorn;e|ne in hoot eir; ne &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e fyngris endis &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at is|more temperat &thorn;an ony o&thorn;ir skyn of &thorn;e bodi ne schulde nou&yogh;t be a
<PB N="29">|good demere in knowynge hoot, cold, hard, scharp, soft, ei&thorn;er|neische.</P>
<P>Brawnes &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ei be maad of mater medlid, ne&thorn;eles &thorn;ei ben|rekened among membris consimiles, for &thorn;ei comen to &thorn;e making of|membris officials / Brawn is maad of fleisch, senewe, &amp; ligamentis,|&amp; &thorn;ei ben instrument voluntarie meuynge.  &THORN;e senewe &thorn;at come&thorn;|fro &thorn;e brayn &amp; &thorn;e nucha, &amp; goi&thorn; for&thorn; to meue &thorn;e lymes, is medlid|wi&thorn; a ligament / &amp; whanne &thorn;e senewe &amp; &thorn;e ligament ben medlid|togidere, it is clepid a corda / &amp; &thorn;e corde is maad for &thorn;re skilis. |&thorn;e firste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e firste</I> in margin.</NOTE> for a symple sinewe is to censible<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="14a">; &thorn;e senewe bi him-silf|my&yogh;t not suffre gret traueile &amp; meuynge, but &thorn;e felowschipe of &thorn;e|ligament &thorn;at is incensible letti&thorn; &thorn;e felynge of &thorn;e senewe, &amp; bringi&thorn;|him to a profitable temperaunce / &THORN;e senewe ha&thorn; .ij. o&thorn;ere defautis:|neischenesse and li&yogh;tnesse.  But &thorn;o .ij. defautis &thorn;e medlynge of &thorn;e|ligament fulfilli&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fulfilli&thorn;</I>, supplet.  See <I>Cath. Angl.</I>, p. 145, <I>to Fulfylle</I>, supplere vicem|Alterius.</NOTE>; for &thorn;e neischenes is temperid &amp; strenk&thorn;id, &amp; &thorn;e|litilnes is maad more.  &THORN;e neischnes come&thorn; of &thorn;e brayn for it is|myche, &amp; &thorn;e litilnes come&thorn; of &thorn;e nucha, for it is litil.  &THORN;at &thorn;at is|maad of &thorn;is nerf &amp; &thorn;is ligament is clepid a corde; &thorn;e which &thorn;at|meue&thorn; &thorn;e lymes to &thorn;e wille of &thorn;e soule, whanne &thorn;at it is schortid
<PB N="30">|ou&thorn;er drawen after &thorn;at &thorn;e lyme bouwi&thorn;.  To &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Huic autem chord&aelig;&mdash;associatur caro simplex.  Comp. Add. MS.</NOTE> corde, &thorn;er is asocied|a symple *[fflesch] for to make a brawn for &thorn;re profitis / &thorn;e firste|profi&yogh;t &thorn;at is in drawynge &amp; wi&thorn;drawynge of &thorn;e corde, &thorn;e fleisch|schulde be as a pelewe vpon &thorn;e which he my&yogh;t reste / &thorn;e secunde,|&thorn;at &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;at is neische &amp; moist schulde kepe &thorn;e corde, &thorn;at he|drie nou&yogh;t in her meuynge / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;at &thorn;e makynge of lymes|were &thorn;e more schaploker./  &THORN;e brawn is maad bowynge as a bowe| &thorn;at is bent; &amp; for &thorn;e kynde wolde kepe &thorn;is complexioun, he clo&thorn;ide|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="14b">&thorn;e brawn wi&thorn; a pannicle / &thorn;e corde whanne he entri&thorn; into &thorn;e brawn|is departid into many smale &thorn;redis, &amp; &thorn;ei ben clepid villes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>villes</I>.  Lat. villi.</NOTE>&mdash;&thorn;at is|to seie wrappingis.  &amp; &thorn;ese villes ben of .iij. maner: in lenk&thorn;e bi|&thorn;e which vertu, &thorn;at drawi&thorn; ha&thorn; my&yogh;t, in brede, bi &thorn;e which vertu|&thorn;at castide out ha&thorn; my&yogh;t / in &thorn;wert ouer bi &thorn;e which vertu *[&thorn;at] with|halt ha&thorn; my&yogh;t / &amp; at &thorn;e eendis of &thorn;e brawn &thorn;ilke &thorn;redis ben gaderid|togidere to make a corde, aftir &thorn;at it is nessessarie / many cordis|ei&thorn;er brawnes to ben engendrid. &amp; official membris ben maad of|&thorn;ese consimile membris, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at ben instrumentes to resonable|soule.  And in &thorn;e ij. tretis I wole telle &thorn;e anotamie of lymes|of office.
</P>

