<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="12">
<HEAD>The .xij. chapitle of &thorn;e iij. techinge of &thorn;e firste tretis|is of festre /</HEAD>
<P>Festre is a deep old wounde, &amp; &thorn;e mou&thorn; of him is streyt, &amp; &thorn;e|ground is brood, &amp; he ha&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="46b">wi&thorn;inne him a calose<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. Fr. calus, (Godefroy).  See later references in <I>N. E. Dict.</I></NOTE> hardnesse al |aboute as it were a goos penne or ellis a kane / &amp; a festre ha&thorn;|difference from a deep vlcus &amp; a cauernose / for a deep vlcus &amp;|cauernose of whom it is toold in &thorn;e chapitle tofore seid, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at|&thorn;ei acorden togidere in depnes &amp; in streitnesse of &thorn;e mou&thorn;, &thorn;e vlcus|ha&thorn; not wi&thorn;inne him a calose hardnes / Wherfore a festre mai not|be clensid wi&thorn; waischinge with which a cauernose vlcus mai be|clensid / but it is nessessarie aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast waischen it to
<PB N="90">|remeue &thorn;ilke calose hardnesse wi&thorn; a cauterie ei&thorn;er with a medicyn|cauterizinge &thorn;at is brennynge, &thorn;e which cauterie ou&thorn;ir brennynge|schulde make &thorn;e dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e vlcus holowere &thorn;an he was / Wherfore|it is nessessarie to a surgian to knowe &thorn;e difference of &thorn;is science,|&thorn;at he mowe knowe to heele bo&thorn;e &thorn;e vlcus &amp; &thorn;e festre wi&thorn; medicyns|different &thorn;at longen to hem bo&thorn;e /</P>
<P>&amp; if &thorn;at a festre be in &thorn;e fleisch or ellis bitwene senewe &amp;|senewe, so &thorn;at &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e senewe be not corrupt ne &thorn;e|boon, it is no nede to take noon o&thorn;ere medicyn but egrimoyne &amp;|staumpe it with salt as &thorn;ou woldist make sause, &amp; drawe out &thorn;e| ius of &thorn;ilke egrymoyne, &amp; do it into &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="47a">hole of &thorn;e festre wi&thorn; a|penne &amp; leie &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e same eerbe &thorn;ere-vpon til he haue|slayn &thorn;ilke festre &amp; clensid it; &amp; &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi reednes &amp;|sadnesse of fleisch &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e festre al aboute; &amp; aftirward|haue &thorn;is sirup of hony wi&thorn; &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ou schalt waische &thorn;e festre|&thorn;at is now vlcus I-compounned in &thorn;is maner / Take a pound water,|vynegre half a pound, of hony dispumed <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .iiij., of leeues of olyuetre|bounden togidere wi&thorn; a &thorn;red / <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., of galingale<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>galingale</I>, ne. galangale, for <I>sagitelle</I>.</NOTE> <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j, boile alle|&thorn;ese to &thorn;e perfi&yogh;tnesse of a sirup, &amp; lete it colden, &amp; do awey &thorn;e
<PB N="91">|leeues of &thorn;e olyue, &amp; kepe al &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;e sirup with &thorn;e|leeues of sagittel &amp; waische &thorn;e vlcus &thorn;at was festred tofore wi&thorn; &thorn;is|licour twies on &thorn;e day &thorn;at &thorn;e licour may go to &thorn;e ground, &amp; aftirward|drie it weel &amp; fille it ful of drie leeues of sagittelle &amp; leie a|sagittel-leef aboue; &amp; &thorn;is medicyn &thorn;ou schalt contynuen til it be|hool / Euery festre &thorn;at is in fleisch is heelid wi&thorn; &thorn;is medicyn|I-preued, but if &thorn;at substaunce of &thorn;e senewe &amp; of &thorn;e boon be|apeirid in &thorn;e ground, &amp; specialiche if &thorn;at &thorn;e festre be not old, &amp; if|&thorn;at &thorn;e calosite be nou&yogh;t to hard.  In &thorn;ese two causis &thorn;e medicyn|of egrimoyne <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="47b">ne suffisi&thorn; nou&yogh;t, but it is nessessarie to haue |a cauterie of fier ei&thorn;er a medicyn caustik / &amp; of &thorn;ese medicyns &thorn;ou|schalt haue a ful techinge folowynge in &thorn;e book / &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;e boone|were corrupt in &thorn;e dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e festre, do it awei aftir &thorn;e techinge|tau&yogh;t in &thorn;e chapitle tofore / &amp; herof take hede, if &thorn;at a festre|perse bi &thorn;e weyes of &thorn;e vryne so &thorn;at &thorn;e vryne go out bi &thorn;ilke weie,|as we han seen ofte tymes, or ellis &thorn;at it go bi crokid placis &amp; hid|placis of &thorn;e face<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. per tortuosas aut occultas partes faciei.</NOTE> persinge into dep&thorn;e, it is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it is</I>, above line.</NOTE> an vnperfi&yogh;t cure, but|&thorn;ou maist pale<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pale</I>, Lat. palliare.  Dufr., <I>Gloss</I>.: 1. tegere; 2. simulare.</NOTE> it, &amp; do it awey &thorn;e stinche with hony waischinge,|enplastre, &amp; hony mundificatiuis, &amp; with defensiuis aboute &thorn;e place
<PB N="92">|&thorn;at his malice mowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>moore</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;en lasse greue.  For a festre &thorn;at is in ioynturis|as &thorn;e feet ei&thorn;er &thorn;e knee, ei&thorn;er &thorn;e hand, ei&thorn;ir &thorn;e elbowe, is hard for|to heele, &amp; sumtyme impossible / &amp; if &thorn;at he be in ano&thorn;er place,|&amp; he haue corrodid ei&thorn;er rotid sumwhat of &thorn;e senewe, &thorn;ow &thorn;at it|be greuous for to cure it, &thorn;er is noon o&thorn;er wey, but a li&yogh;t cauterizacioun|of &thorn;e senewe &thorn;at is hurt / For cauterizacioun wi&thorn; hoot iren|ei&thorn;er wi&thorn; gold, &thorn;at is bettere, it clensi&thorn; &amp; drie&thorn; &thorn;e senewe &thorn;at is| corrupt &amp; rectifie&thorn; &thorn;e complexioun of al &thorn;e membre &amp; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="48a">a medecyn|caustik worchi&thorn; &thorn;e contrarie / Brennynge medicyns, bo&thorn;e &thorn;e symple|&amp; &thorn;e compound &thorn;ou schalt haue to &thorn;e fulle<NOTE PLACE="foot">See page 86, note 3.</NOTE> in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde tretis folowynge / &amp; whanne &thorn;ou hast maad a perfi&yogh;t mundificacioun</I>|struck through in red. after <I>to &thorn;e fulle in.</I></NOTE> antidotarie of &thorn;is|book, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;e maner of cauterisynge to &thorn;e fulle in &thorn;e|&thorn;ridde tretis folowynge.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou hast maad a perfi&yogh;t mundificacioun|of &thorn;ilke colose fleisch, regendre fleisch &amp; consowde with|medicyns regeneratius &amp; consolidatiuis &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ou schalt fynde|in &thorn;e antidotarie //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="13">
<HEAD>The xiij chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techinge of &thorn;e firste|tretis is of a cankre /</HEAD>
<P>Cankre I-woundid come&thorn; of openynge, ei&thorn;er of kuttinge, ei&thorn;er|of brekynge of a cankre not I-woundid, whos techinge &thorn;ou schalt
<PB N="93">|haue in &thorn;e chapitle of &thorn;e apostymes in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techinge / &amp; he|come&thorn; of a wounde yuel heelid, to whom come&thorn; a malancolient|mater rotid; or for &thorn;e mater &thorn;at come&thorn; to &thorn;e wounde is &thorn;ere corrumpid|&amp; chaungi&thorn; &thorn;e vlcus into a cankre /</P>
<P>&amp; &thorn;ese ben &thorn;e tokenes of &thorn;e cankre / &THORN;e vlcus is foul &amp; stynkynge,|&thorn;e lippis ben grete, wan, or blak, hard, &amp; wi&thorn;inne kirnely,|&amp; ouer al aboute arerid and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="48b">holowe / &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e difference bitwene |a cankre &amp; a foul vlcus &amp; an hori of whom I haue maad mencioun|aboue, &thorn;at if &thorn;at &thorn;ou waische hem bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; li&yogh;e, &thorn;e cankre schal|be palere &amp; foulere &thorn;an he was bifore, &amp; &thorn;ere schal falle out of him|pecis gobetmele.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gobetmele</I>, piecemeal.  <I>Polychron</I>., iv. 103: membratim.  See further,|M&auml;tzner, <I>Dict</I>.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;e vlcus is clensid wi&thorn; &thorn;ilke li&yogh;e, &amp; &thorn;e fleisch|is maad fairer &thorn;an it was tofore, ne &thorn;e vlcus stynki&thorn; not bi &thorn;e same|stinche as &thorn;e cankre doi&thorn;; for &thorn;e cankre ha&thorn; a propre sauour, &thorn;e|which mai not be write wi&thorn; lettre; but &thorn;ilke sauour is best knowe|of men whiche &thorn;at best han sei&yogh;e cankreis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>cankre is.</I></NOTE></P>
<P>A general rule in &thorn;e cure of a cankre is, &thorn;at a cankre mai not|be heelid, but if &thorn;at he be do awey wi&thorn; alle hise rotis / &THORN;e secunde|rule is, &thorn;at he schal not be touchid wi&thorn; hoot iren ne with hoot|medicyn caustik, &thorn;at is to seie brennynge, but he be in place
<PB N="94">|where he may al be doon awey / for &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;ou touchist him|wi&thorn; a violent &thorn;ing ei&thorn;er medicyn, &thorn;e more his malice is encreessid /|Take &thorn;anne good heede if he be in a fleischi place, where &thorn;at he|may be don al wey, &amp; &thorn;anne kutte him al awey wi&thorn; alle hise rotis /| &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;riste out al &thorn;e malancolient <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="49a">blood &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e|veynes &thorn;at ben aboute &thorn;e cankre.  &amp; aftirward brenne al aboute in|&thorn;e place &thorn;ere as &thorn;e cankre was with hoot iren / aftirward leie on &thorn;is|confeccioun maad of flour of wheete &amp; hony &amp; ius of smalache,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>smallage</I>, Halle Table, p. 12.  "Smalache, Marche, or Marshe Persley."|See Prior, <I>Dict</I>., p. 217.</NOTE> til|&thorn;at he be perfi&yogh;tliche clensid.  After regendre fleisch &amp; cicatrice.|To &thorn;is rule / take hede as ofte as &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn; sirurgie heelen a|cancre: first euacue &thorn;e malancolient mater, for &thorn;at is ypocras|techinge; &amp; if &thorn;at he be growen in sich a place &thorn;ere as he may not|be doon al awey, as in &thorn;e necke or in &thorn;e tetis, or in &thorn;e face, or in &thorn;e|arshole, or in &thorn;e mareis; &amp; also for schortere conclusioun, &amp; he be|entrid in ony place &thorn;ere as ony senewis, arteries, veynes, ben&mdash;as|ypocras sei&thorn;&mdash;it is bettere nou&yogh;t to cure &thorn;e cankre &thorn;an to cure.  For|&amp; he be curid, &thorn;at is to seie kutt or I-brent, &thorn;ei perischen &thorn;e|sunnere; &amp; if &thorn;ei ben not curid, &thorn;ei lyuen &thorn;e lengere tyme&mdash;libro|vjo. afforismorum: Cancri absconditi multum tempus perfuciunt
<PB N="95">|curati vero cicius pereunt / But defende &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at is hool aboute|with defensif of bole &thorn;at I haue ofte tymes seid &amp; waische &thorn;e|wounde of &thorn;e cankre wi&thorn; gotis whey, &amp; drie it softly, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="49b">&amp; anoynte|&thorn;e wounde wi&thorn;inne &amp; wi&thorn;oute with &thorn;is oynement of rasis &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;</I>, erroneously for <I>of</I>.</NOTE> tutie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tutie</I>, Matth. Sylvat.  "Tuchia . . Lat. Cadimia &amp; pomfolix."  Arab.|t&umacr;t&imacr;&amacr;.  Fr. tutie.  See Wr. W&uuml;., p. 559, 13.  "Tucia, i. tutie" (xiiith cent.).|It is: Oxidum Zinci impurum.</NOTE> / |take ceruse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ceruse</I>, white lead.  See <I>N. E. Dict.</I>  s. v. Ceruse.</NOTE> tutie I-waische &amp; medle hem wi&thorn; oile of rosis &amp; wi&thorn;|ius of purcelane<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>purcelane</I>, Lat. portulaca.  Halle Table, p. 90.  "Another herbe there|is also called Portulaca marina, only of the likenes that the leaves therof|haue with porcelaine."  See "Purslane," Prior, <I>Popular Names</I>, p. 193.</NOTE> or of sum o&thorn;ere cold eerbe, putte ynne sum of &thorn;e|toon, &amp; now sum of &thorn;at o&thorn;er, til &thorn;e oynement be weel I-maad /|&THORN;is oynement is myche wor&thorn; for to defende &thorn;at &thorn;e malice of &thorn;e|cancre schal not wexen, &amp; also &thorn;at &thorn;e pacient vse a good gouernaile:|as drinke good wiyn &amp; cleer &amp; lithe, &amp; he muste leeue reed|wiyn &amp; troublid &amp; &thorn;icke wiyn, &amp; he may ete good fleisch, as|motoun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moton</I>, carnes ovine, Wr. W&uuml;., 741, 39, xvth cent.</NOTE> of a we&thorn;er, kide fleisch sowkynge, capouns, hennes,|chikenes, partrichis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>partrichis, Cathol. Ang</I>., p. 270, a Partryke, perdrix.  See further|Skeat, <I>Et. Dict</I>.</NOTE> fesauntis, &amp; smale briddis, &amp; he muste leeue:|beeues fleisch<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bef</I>, added above line, in different hand.</NOTE> &amp; gotis fleisch, hertis fleisch &amp; haris fleisch, goos,|dokis, &amp; alle greete briddis &thorn;at lyuen in watri placis, &amp; al salt|&thorn;ing &amp; acute &thorn;ing: as garleek, oynonys &amp; vynegre et cetera [&thorn;at]*
<PB N="96">|&thorn;e sike man may lyue &thorn;e lengere vpon er&thorn;e / Ne&thorn;eles if vlcus be ri&yogh;t|foul &amp; haue nou&yogh;t so greet malice as a cankre, of &thorn;e which vlcus I|haue told tofore may be curid wi&thorn; poudre of affadillis, and aftirward| weel be clensid; &amp; for &thorn;at &thorn;is vlcus <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="50a">&thorn;at was so foul may be heelid /|Rogeryn and Rowlond &amp; manye o&thorn;ere settide in her bokis &thorn;e cure|of a cankre, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at he be in a senewey place, &amp; &thorn;ei seien &thorn;at &thorn;ei|han heelid him / But vndirstonde weel for certeyn, &thorn;at an olde|cankre mai not be heelid bi noon o&thorn;er wey, but bi &thorn;e same wey &thorn;at|I haue seid in &thorn;e bigynnynge of &thorn;is chapitle / &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;ou dredist|whe&thorn;er &thorn;at it be a symple vlcus or a cankre &amp; a foul, for &thorn;e signes|&amp; &thorn;e tokenes tofore seid be&thorn; doutis, bigynne to mortifie it wi&thorn; sum|maner of poudre: as wi&thorn; poudre of affadillis, &amp; bi my witt poudre|of erbe robert<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>erbe robert</I>, insertion of the scribe.  Geranium Robertianum.  See|<I>Prior</I>, p. 113.  Cronenburg.  De Compositione Medicamentorum, a. 1555,|fol. 106, A. Ruprechtskraut: Roberti herba (Geranii species).</NOTE> / &amp; loke aftirward &thorn;e prosis of &thorn;i worchinge sei&thorn;|&thorn;is boke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sei&thorn; &thorn;is book</I>, erroneously inserted.</NOTE> / For if &thorn;at he be a uerry cankre, &thorn;ou schalt se &thorn;e more|&thorn;ou woldist clense him, &thorn;e more his malice schal wexen / &amp; if he|be not a cankr&eacute;, he schal be clensid ri&yogh;t as an vlcus / Whanne &thorn;at|&thorn;ou seest &thorn;e wexynge of a cankre &amp; his malice agmenten, ceesse|from &thorn;e verry cure &amp; turne a&yogh;en to &thorn;e forseid cure of &thorn;e oynement|of tutie, &thorn;e which &thorn;at pali&thorn; &thorn;e cankre.  For &amp; &thorn;ou bisie &thorn;ee to
<PB N="97">|cure &thorn;e cankre, &amp; &thorn;ou procede in &thorn;i cure, &thorn;ou schortist &thorn;e pacientis|lijf / &amp; if &thorn;ou palist, &thorn;ou lenk&thorn;ist his lijf /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="14">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="50b">The .xiiij chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techinge of &thorn;e firste |tretis is for to remeue causis &thorn;at letten &thorn;e cure|of olde woundis /</HEAD>
<P>I tolde &thorn;ee aboue in &thorn;e general chapitle of olde woundis cause|whiche &thorn;at letten olde woundis to be heelid / &amp; also I tolde &thorn;e|techinge plenerliche &thorn;at ben nessessarie to remeue ech sengle cause|&thorn;at is nessessarie, how &thorn;at alle maner causis &thorn;at letten mai be don|awey bi a good surgien &amp; a wijs; so &thorn;at &thorn;ou ioynest &thorn;is chapitle|wi&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere chapitle tofore seid, &thorn;ou schalt han a pleyner techinge.|If &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi be ful of olde humouris ei&thorn;er in &thorn;e idropisie, loke|&thorn;at he may be heelid of &thorn;ilke disposicioun, &amp; &thorn;anne heele him if &thorn;at|&thorn;ou canst / &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator, perhaps intentionally, altered his original: si non (scis),|pete physicum qui curationem illius dispositionis faciat.</NOTE> if &thorn;at he be not ful of olde humouris whiche &thorn;at|neden no curynge of olde disposicioun.  Ne traueile not in deueyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in deueyn</I> = in veyn.</NOTE>|&thorn;e sike man nei&thorn;ir wi&thorn; medicyns corosiuis, ne wi&thorn; kuttynge, ne with|puttynge into &thorn;e woundis greete tentis; but do aboue &thorn;e vlcus li&yogh;t
<PB N="98">|mundificatiuis &amp; swete smellynge, &thorn;at kepi&thorn; &thorn;e membre li&yogh;tliche|clene &thorn;at it stynke not / &amp; whanne &thorn;at he is keuerid from an yuel|disposicioun, thanne turne a&yogh;en to &thorn;e principal cure / &amp; &thorn;is same| &thorn;ing <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="51a"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Heading to this page: <I>Causes &thorn;at lettes &thorn;e cure off old woundes.</I></NOTE>I saye of yuel disposicioun of &thorn;e lyuere of what maner cause|&thorn;at he be enfeblid; &thorn;e same I saye of &thorn;e splene / But if &thorn;ese|tweyne ben in her kyndely disposicioun, olde woundis moun not be|heelid.  If<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I> above line.</NOTE> &thorn;at greet multitude of blood letti&thorn;, &thorn;at may be knowen|bi ful replecioun of &thorn;e veines of al &thorn;e bodi, bi reednesse &amp; extencioun|of &thorn;e face, bi swetnes of &thorn;e mou&thorn;, bi flating<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flating</I>, Add. MS. <I>wlattynge</I>.  See Wright W&uuml;. O.E. <I>wlatung</I>.</NOTE> / Whanne &thorn;at a|man is fastynge, bi heuynes of &thorn;e browis, &amp; bi &yogh;ong age, &amp; his|complexioun is hoot &amp; moist, &amp; &thorn;at he ha&thorn; vsid in his dietynge|wiyn and fleisch; &amp; make him &thorn;anne be lete blood of &thorn;e veyne &thorn;e|which &thorn;at bryngi&thorn; norischinge to &thorn;e lyme, &amp; aftirward of &thorn;e veyne|&thorn;at mai best voiden &thorn;e membre &thorn;at is hurt / &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;e blood|trespace oonly in qualite, amende him as if &thorn;at he be to hoot, voide|him a litil &amp; diete him with colde metis &amp; stiptik.  &amp; aftirward|procede for&thorn; in alle maner o&thorn;ir causis as it is told in &thorn;e general|chapitle, takynge hede &thorn;at &thorn;er ben summe maner medicyns whiche|&thorn;at ben driynge &amp; clensynge, &amp; han a priuy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>privy</I>.  See <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., pryvay, occultus.</NOTE> propirte to consowde
<PB N="99">|olde woundis whiche &thorn;at ben difficult to be consowdid; of &thorn;e|whiche medicyns summe ben symple &amp; summe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="51b">ben compouuned / |Symple ben: limature of iren, flour of bras brent, vitriol leed|brent, &amp; alle scharpe corosiuis if &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben brent; for &thorn;at &thorn;ei|han vertu more to consowden, &amp; also her corrisoun is lessid / &thorn;is is|a medicyn compounned: take floris<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. flor. &aelig;ris.</NOTE> eris, limature of bras ana.  <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j.|litarge of gold, litarge of siluir, <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .viij. gumme of cipresse, <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .iiij.|sal gemme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sal gemme.</I>  A Salt so named, from its Transparent and Crystalline|Brightness.&mdash;Kersey.</NOTE> <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .ij. aristologia I-brent smal to poudre of frankencense,|ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .v. wex &amp; oile of mirtill &thorn;at suffisi&thorn; // //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="15">
<HEAD>The .xv. chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techinge of &thorn;e firste|tretis is of a crampe &thorn;at come&thorn; to a wounde /</HEAD>
<P>Nessessarie &thorn;ing is to a surgian to knowe &thorn;e causis of a crampe,|&thorn;e which &thorn;at come&thorn; to a wounde &thorn;at schulde be heelid, &amp; also &thorn;at|he knowe &thorn;e disposicioun of him &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe, &amp; also what|&thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e crampe is, &thorn;at he mowe resonabliche hele &thorn;e crampe /|&THORN;e crampe is a sijknes cordous ei&thorn;er neruous, in &thorn;e which sijknes|cordis &amp; &thorn;e senewis weren drawen to her bigynnynge; of &thorn;e whiche|drawynge &thorn;at ben .ij. causis coniunct: &thorn;e toon is repleccioun of &thorn;e
<PB N="100">|senewe, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere of &thorn;e corde, &thorn;e o&thorn;er is inanisioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>inanisioun</I>, Lat. inanitio.  Vigo. Interpretation.  "<I>Inanition</I>, emptyng."</NOTE>  He &thorn;at is| of in-anisioun, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="52a">ofte tymes he ha&thorn; a cause goynge tofore as to myche|euacuacioun of blood ei&thorn;er of sum o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, as to longe affliccioun|for long ak&thorn;e, or ellis for &thorn;e appetite of &thorn;e sike man ha&thorn; ben longe|tyme enfeblid; &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; litil &amp; litil, &amp; &thorn;e crampe &thorn;at come&thorn; of|bo&thorn;e &thorn;ese causis may not be heelid.  &amp; he &thorn;at come&thorn; of replecioun|ha&thorn; oon of &thorn;e .iij. causis goynge tofore / &thorn;e firste cause is to greet|ak&thorn;e / &thorn;e .ij. cause is cold / &amp; &thorn;e .iij. cause is putrifaccioun ei&thorn;er|rotynge / &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at oon sengle cause sumtyme suffice to make a|crampe, ofte tymes alle &thorn;ese causis happen to come togiders / And|&thorn;is crampe may be heelid or &thorn;at he be confermed, &amp; aftir &thorn;at he is|confermed seelden or neuere / A surgian muste &thorn;anne be bisy in al|&thorn;at he my&yogh;te, &thorn;at a crampe ne wexe not in &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at schulde|be heelid, wi&thorn; obuiacioun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>obuiacioun</I>, Lat. cum obuiatione defensiuorum.</NOTE> defendinge &thorn;e lyme, &thorn;at noon of &thorn;e .iij.|causis tofore seid ne come nou&yogh;t into &thorn;e wounde: &thorn;e oon is in|defendynge &thorn;e lyme from putrifaccioun / &thorn;e to&thorn;ere is for kepinge &thorn;e|lyme fro rotynge / &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is to gouerne him from a greet akynge /| for it is more sikir to defende &thorn;at a crampe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="52b">ne come not, &thorn;anne|aftir &thorn;at he is come with medicyns &thorn;at is douteful or dredeful to
<PB N="101">|do awey / For if a feuere come to an heed or to a senewe &thorn;at|is woundid, &amp; if &thorn;e crampe folowe, euermore it is deedliche.</P>
<P>Take hede &thorn;anne to aswage &thorn;e ak&thorn;e wi&thorn; anoyntynge of oile of|rosis, in doynge as I haue seid afore in &thorn;e chapitle of senewis &thorn;at|ben woundid; for ofte tymes &thorn;e crampe come&thorn; fro woundis &thorn;at|ben maad in &thorn;e heed or ellis in &thorn;e senewe / &amp; if &thorn;at ak&thorn;e were so|greet, &thorn;at maki&thorn; &thorn;e crampe for &thorn;e prickynge of a senewe or ellis of|a corde / &amp; if &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;tist nou&yogh;t defende &thorn;e crampe nei&thorn;ir wi&thorn;|blood letynge, nei&thorn;er wi&thorn; ventusynge, ne wi&thorn; clisterie, ne wi&thorn; suppositorie,|ne wi&thorn; defensif in anoyntynge &thorn;e necke, ne &thorn;e grynde,|ne &thorn;e arm hoolis, &thorn;anne it is nessessarie &thorn;at &thorn;ou kutte al atwo &thorn;ilke|senewe or &thorn;ilke corde &thorn;at is prickid, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e felynge or &thorn;e|meuynge of &thorn;e lyme to whom &thorn;ilke senewe or &thorn;ilke corde serue&thorn; in|parti or in al be lost / For it is bettere &thorn;at a man lese &thorn;e felynge &amp;|&thorn;e meuynge of a lyme, &thorn;an for to deie.  But it is bettere, if &thorn;at|&thorn;ou cowdist, to kepe a man &thorn;er-fro with o&thorn;ere <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="53a">medicyns &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;e |senewe or &thorn;e corde be kutt al atwo.  &amp; if<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>, above line.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou were not at|&thorn;e bigynnynge, &amp; &thorn;ou fyndist a man hauynge &thorn;e crampe for a|wounde, do &thorn;ou as I dide at melain.  &THORN;er was a scoler of myn &thorn;at|was a surgian &thorn;at was clepid Olyuer, which &thorn;at curide a sche&thorn;ere
<PB N="102">|of a wounde &thorn;at he hadde in &thorn;e heed; &amp; bi &thorn;ilke wounde &thorn;e pannicle|ou&thorn;ir &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at keueri&thorn; &thorn;e brayn panne &thorn;at is vnder &thorn;e fleisch|was hurt, &amp; neuer-&thorn;e-lattere &thorn;e brayn panne was not hurt.  &amp;|&thorn;ilke leche, or &thorn;anne he hadde perfi&yogh;tlich purified &thorn;ilke pannicle,|sowdide &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;</I>, extrinsecus, from without.</NOTE>; &amp; whanne &thorn;ilke wounde was|sowdid, &thorn;e pannicle &thorn;at was not weel heelid hadde a dedein<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dedein</I>, Lat. panniculus <I>indignatus</I> causa fuit spasmi.  The translator|misunderstood <I>indignatus</I>, and gives us an "indignant pannicle."  <I>indignatus</I>,|Med. Lat. damaged, hurt.  See Tommas. s. v. indegnare 3.&mdash;Compare|<I>&thorn;e ludych lorde&mdash;hade dedayn of &thorn;at dede.</I>&mdash;Allit. Poems, B. 74.</NOTE> &amp;|was cause of gendrynge of a crampe in &thorn;ilke wounde.  &amp; at &thorn;e|laste I was clepid to &thorn;e sike man, &amp; I foond him hauynge &thorn;e|crampe, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e crampe he hadde manye smale enpostymes aboute|his face&mdash;&amp; &thorn;at is an yuele tokene in &thorn;e woundis of &thorn;e heed&mdash;&amp;|&thorn;anne I demede him for deed / Ne&thorn;eles at &thorn;e instaunce of hise| freendis I wolde asaie &thorn;e worchinge of kynde vpon resoun; I made|his heed to be schaue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I made his hed to be schaue</I>, abradi caput feci.</NOTE> &amp; I kutte a&yogh;en &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at was <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="53b">consowdid|wi&thorn; a rasour to &thorn;e dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e same wounde, &amp; aftirward I|fulfillide &thorn;e wounde with hoot oile of rosis, &amp; I anoyntide al &thorn;e|heed with &thorn;e same oile of rosis &amp; a litil vynegre medlid togidere, &amp;|I anoyntide &thorn;e nolle &amp; &thorn;e necke oonly wi&thorn; oile of rosis, &amp; I dide|on &thorn;e wounde &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey wi&thorn; oile of rosis, and I boond al
<PB N="103">|&thorn;e heed wi&thorn; a boond leiynge &thorn;er vndir herdis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>herdis</I>.  See Wright W&uuml;. 614. 2.  "Stupa, herdes."</NOTE> or tow&yogh; smal I tosid,|and I openede his mou&thorn; &amp; putte into his mou&thorn; &thorn;e bro&thorn; maad of a|chiken, wi&thorn; comyn &amp; also wi&thorn; cleer wiyn medlid wi&thorn; myche water; on|&thorn;e morowe I turnede a&yogh;en &amp; I foond &thorn;e sike of bettere disposicioun,|&amp; I openede bettere his mou&thorn;, &amp; he spak bettere; ne&thorn;eles I foond|&thorn;e wounde drie, &amp; &thorn;anne I dide ofte tymes &thorn;e same medicyn &amp; &thorn;e|same oynture.  In &thorn;e &thorn;ridde dai &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e heed was maad|moist, &thorn;e which was bifore as drie as &thorn;e skyn hadde be rostid at &thorn;e|fier, &amp; in so miche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, inserted.</NOTE> &thorn;e skyn was maad &thorn;inne, &thorn;at &thorn;er was no &thorn;ing|bitwene &thorn;e skyn &amp; &thorn;e brayn panne.  &amp; at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e wounde quytturide|wi&thorn; contynuaunce of &thorn;e same cure tofore seid, &amp; in &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="54a">maner |&thorn;e &yogh;onge man was heelid bo&thorn;e of &thorn;e crampe &amp; also of &thorn;e wounde /|But &thorn;ilke crampe was wi&thorn;oute feuere; for I may not &thorn;enke &thorn;at I|haue seen a feuere in &thorn;e woundes of &thorn;e heed, or ellis of &thorn;e senewis|prickid a crampe, &thorn;at nou&yogh;t a&yogh;enstondynge remedie ei&thorn;er medicyns|&thorn;e pacient &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e crampe diede / My beste counseil is to lete|him blood in &thorn;e bigynnynge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe, namely, &amp; he be|strong &amp; replete, &amp; if &thorn;at he haue not bled ynou&yogh; at his woundis;|&amp; anoynte his nolle &amp; his necke wi&thorn; hoote oynementis as wi&thorn; oile
<PB N="104">|of nardine, euforbine, oile of rue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rue</I>, ruta.  Turner, <I>Herbal</I>, ii. 122 b.  Ruta is named in Greke Pegamon,|in English Rue or herbe grace, in French rue de gardin, in Dutch|Weinraut.</NOTE> lilijs et cetera / &amp; also to make|smale cauteries punctale, &thorn;at is to seie as smal as &thorn;e eende of a|pricke, bitwene ech whirlebon of &thorn;e necke, so neuere-&thorn;e-lattere &thorn;at|&thorn;e cauterie go not ouer depe / Aftirward bynde long wolle to his|heed bihynde &amp; to his necke &amp; to hise schuldris, &amp; do &thorn;eron hoot|oile, &amp; leie him in a soft bed &amp; lete him be in reste &amp; in pees /|But &thorn;er ben summe &thorn;at setten in her bookis medicyns &thorn;at prouoken|&thorn;e feueris; for &thorn;at ypocras techi&thorn; in .iiijto afforismoris: a| spasmo<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cramp and Tetanus.  See <I>Notes</I>.</NOTE> vel tetano<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="54b"> habito febre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>febre superveniente</I>, error for <I>febris superveniens.</I></NOTE> superueniente soluit egritudinem|/ &thorn;at is to seie: if &thorn;at a man haue a crampe or ellis a tetane|&thorn;at is a sijknes &thorn;at halt &thorn;e membre lich streit on bo&thorn;e sidis as a|crampe halt &thorn;e oon side of &thorn;e membre &amp; &thorn;e feuere come on &thorn;ilke|crampe ei&thorn;ir &thorn;ilke tetane, he distrie&thorn; &thorn;e crampe ei&thorn;ir &thorn;e sijknes; &amp;|also &thorn;ei anoynte wi&thorn; to hoot an oynement to prouoke &thorn;e feueres, &thorn;e|which &thorn;ing I ne apreue not in &thorn;e crampe of a wounde &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at|&thorn;ilke oynement my&yogh;te be profitable in a crampe wi&thorn;oute wounde, &amp;|where &thorn;at humouris abounde, namely, if it be fleume.</P>
<P>Summe ben general tokenes &amp; summe ben special of schewynge|of &thorn;e crampe / General tokenes ben &thorn;ese: to greet ak&thorn;e, crokidnes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crokidness</I>, Lat. obliquitas.</NOTE>
<PB N="105">|of i&yogh;en, &amp; crokidnes of schewynge, &amp; crokidnes of eeris, of &thorn;e nose|&thorn;rillis, &amp; of &thorn;e lippis, &amp; whanne &thorn;at a man may not speke, &amp; &thorn;e|cheke be constreyned &amp; difficulte of meuynge, and namely, of|&thorn;e necke, &amp; ofte constreynynge togidere, &amp; a sodeyn schakynge|togidere.  Special signes maken oon of &thorn;re maner of crampis: &thorn;e|toon is clepid amprostonos<NOTE PLACE="foot">Latin, <I>Emprosthotonos</I>.</NOTE>, &thorn;e to&thorn;er empistenos<NOTE PLACE="foot">Latin, <I>Opisthotonos</I>.</NOTE>, &thorn;e .iij. tetanus /|In &thorn;is maner of crampe &thorn;at is clepid amprostonos,<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="55a"> &thorn;e senewis tofore |ben drawe togidere / &thorn;e fore partie of &thorn;e heed is crokid, &thorn;e sike|man may not heuen it vp, he beri&thorn; his chyn as it lij&thorn; on his brest,|&amp; his mou&thorn; is streit &amp; he may not opene it, &amp; &thorn;e fyngris of his|hand ben folden into his fist / &amp; in empistonies &thorn;e necke is crokid,|his mou&thorn; is open, hise chekis ben open, &amp; &thorn;e fyngris of his hand|ben streyned bacward / &amp; &thorn;e tetane halt &thorn;e bo&thorn;e parties of &thorn;e|body, so &thorn;at he may not turne his necke to no partie but al &thorn;e|bodi is stif &amp; streyned, as a staf were putt yn at his necke &amp; out|at his ers / Alle &thorn;ese tokenes or ellis summe of hem schewi&thorn; &thorn;e|disposicioun of him &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe / And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ese|tokenes fallen in &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e heed, or ellis of a senewe &thorn;ei|techen bettere &thorn;e leche to fle from &thorn;e sike man &thorn;an on him to abide|&amp; cure /</P>
