<PB N="123">|take &thorn;erof good hede, &amp; do &thorn;erynne in &thorn;e wounde hoot oile of|rosis doun to &thorn;e pannicle &thorn;at byndi&thorn; boonys togidere, til &thorn;at &thorn;er be|noon akynge in &thorn;e wounde.  &amp; kepe &thorn;ilke wounde as &thorn;ou woldist|kepe o&thorn;ere woundis of &thorn;e brayn panne; &amp; kepe &thorn;e brayn fro cold|&amp; fro heete, for cold is moost greuous to boonys &amp; to panniclis &thorn;at|ben woundid.  &THORN;er ben summe maner men &thorn;at leien wi&thorn;out for&thorn;|on alle maner woundis of &thorn;e heed, whe&thorn;er it be wi&thorn; wounde of &thorn;e|brayn panne or wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e brayn panne, in what|maner &thorn;at &thorn;e heed be hurt, a lynnen cloo&thorn; wet in &thorn;e oynement &thorn;at|is maad on &thorn;is maner / Take white rosis libram <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, oile of rosis <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> v,|whi&yogh;t wex <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iij, &thorn;ei melten alle togidere in an yren panne, &amp; &thorn;ei|maken <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="65a">&thorn;erof .j. bodi, &amp; boile it aftirward in good wyn bi &thorn;e space |of an hour; &amp; &thorn;ei leten it aftirward ny&yogh; colden, &amp; &thorn;ei weten &thorn;erinne|a pece of a lynnen clout, &amp; &thorn;ei schapen &thorn;ilke pece wi&thorn; a schere|aftir &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde is, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ei ba&thorn;e &thorn;ilke pece in good wiyn, &amp;|&thorn;anne leie &thorn;ilke pece [on &thorn;e wounde]*, &amp; anoon aftir &thorn;ei leien vpon|&thorn;ilke pece on ei&thorn;ir side of &thorn;e wounde a plumaciol I-wet in good|hoot wiyn; &amp; &thorn;ei leien on a drie pelowe of herdis vpon &thorn;o two|wete pelowis, &thorn;e which drie pelewe of herdis schal comprehende &thorn;e|tweie wete, &amp; bynde hem faste; &amp; &thorn;ei &yogh;euen to summen to drynke
<PB N="124">|ri&yogh;t good wyn, &amp; to ete good fleisch of hennes &amp; of capouns; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: &amp; pr&aelig;cipiunt quod unam guttam aqu&aelig; <I>non</I> bibat.</NOTE>|&thorn;ei comaunden to drynke a drope of water; &amp; &thorn;ei gouernen on &thorn;is|maner alle men &thorn;at ben woundid in &thorn;e heed differentliche, &amp; &thorn;ei|seyn &thorn;at mo men ben heelid bi &thorn;is maner cure &thorn;an dien.  But bi as|myche as alle auctouris ben a&yogh;ens &thorn;is cure, namely in dietynge, I ne|was neuere hardi to preue &thorn;is maner cure; for in mannys bodi a| medicyn schal not be preued which &thorn;at is not acordynge to resoun /|For alle autouris acorden &thorn;at &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="65b">&thorn;at so soone greue&thorn; &thorn;e|brayn &amp; &thorn;e senewis as wiyn doi&thorn;, &amp; vsynge of fleisch is cause of|bryngynge yn an hoot enpostyme.  Neuere-&thorn;e-latter if a man &thorn;at|vsi&thorn; of custum sich a maner dietynge haue a strong heed, in his|hele him dredi&thorn; no wiyn, &amp; &thorn;e vertu of him &thorn;at is sijk be strong&mdash;in|sum manere of folk wi&thorn; &thorn;is maner gouernaile, vertu is more|strenk&thorn;id, &amp; &thorn;e sunner &thorn;ei ben heelid.  But I ne procede not wi&thorn;|sich a maner dietynge bi cause of drede lest an hoot enpostyme|schulde come to &thorn;e sore, but I procede in dietynge &amp; worche aboute|&thorn;e wounde as I haue seid tofore.</P>
