<PB N="138">|breche of ony boon, &thorn;anne do &thorn;ou as I dide to a chanoun of &thorn;e|ordre of seynt austyn.  Whanne &thorn;at he wolde haue lept vpon an|hi&yogh; hors &amp; haue seten in &thorn;e satel, &thorn;e hors areride vpon hise two|hyndere feet, &amp; &thorn;ilke chanoun fel doun bacward vpon &thorn;e er&thorn;e vpon|his heed; &amp; al his bodi was brusid &amp; namely aboute &thorn;e heed, &thorn;at|anoon he loste &thorn;e meuynge and &thorn;e felynge of al his body / &THORN;anne a| lewid leche <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="73a">&thorn;at was frend to &thorn;ilke chanoun was clepid, &amp; he cowde|not helpen him, for he hadde neuere seen &thorn;e same caas, ne he|cowde not no lettrure<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: nec sciebat aliquid de scripturis.  O.Fr. lettreure.  See <I>Piers the|Plowman</I>, ed. Skeat.  Gloss.</NOTE> / &amp; at &thorn;e laste I was clepid, &amp; I foond him|nei&thorn;er heerynge, ne spekynge, ne no &thorn;ing meuynge, &amp; I deemede|him for deed / &amp; ne&thorn;eless<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: meo tamen addens judicio quod pro centum marchis argenti non|dimitterem, quin adhuc probarem in eo, si meus esset frater, juvamenta|medicin&aelig; inducens.</NOTE> I seide, &amp; he were my bro&thorn;er, I nolde not|for an .C. mark, but I asaiede in him goodnes of &thorn;e helpinge of|medicyns / for ofte tyme kynde wi&thorn; good werkis helpi&thorn; priuyliche|&thorn;at seme&thorn; vnpossible to a leche. &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;anne preieden me with greet|instaunce / &amp; I made &thorn;e heeris of his heed to be schauen &amp; &thorn;anne|I anoyntide al &thorn;e heed wi&thorn;. iij. parties of oile of rosis, &amp; oon partie|of vynegre hoot medlid togidere, &amp; I castide aboue poudre of|mirtillis, &amp; leide aboue a sotil lynnen clo&thorn; &thorn;inne, wett in &thorn;e same
<PB N="139">|oile &amp; vynegre, &amp; aboue &thorn;at tow&yogh; smal tosid, &amp; I boond al &thorn;e heed|wi&thorn; a boond, &amp; aboue I leide a lambis skyn.  &amp; so I chaungide it|&thorn;ries ech day in anoyntynge &thorn;e nolle &amp; &thorn;e necke into &thorn;e myddil<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of &thorn;e myddil</I>, inserted.</NOTE>|of &thorn;e rigge-boon bihynde wi&thorn; hoot oile of camomille / In &thorn;e|ij. day he openede a litil hise y&yogh;en, &amp; he bigan to loke aboute|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="73b">him as it hadde be a deef man &thorn;at were in a wondring / &amp; &thorn;anne|summe wolden haue asaied if &thorn;at he my&yogh;te haue ete / &amp; I wolde |not suffre him to ete / &amp; I seide &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at he wolde ete &thorn;at he|schulde not / In &thorn;e iij. day I spak to him / he answeride me babelynge|as a child &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; to speke, but he my&yogh;te for&thorn; wi&thorn; no|word<NOTE PLACE="foot">See below, note 8.</NOTE> / In &thorn;e iiij. dai he spak boistousliche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>boistisliche</I>.  Lat.: balbutiendo, stammering, seems to connect the|sense of O.Fr. boistous, lame, with boisterous.</NOTE> / &amp; &thorn;anne I &yogh;af him to|drynke hoot ypocras<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ypocras</I>, errour for <I>ydrosacre</I>. See below.  "<I>Hydrosaccharum</I>, a Syrup|made of Water and Sugar."  Phillips.  <I>Hippocras</I>, a kind of "Artificial|Wine, made of Claret or White Wine, and several sorts of Spice."  <I>Ibid</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at is maad of sugre &amp; of watir / In &thorn;e v.|day he took &thorn;ikke ti&yogh;anne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ptisanam spissam.  Matth. Sylv.: "Tisanna i. aqua ordei uel|fariola."</NOTE> / In &thorn;e vj. dai I &yogh;af him bro&thorn; of a|chiken; and &thorn;anne he bigan to strenk&thorn;e litil &amp; litil, &amp; litil &amp; litil|to meuen / &amp; neuer-&thorn;e-lattere he my&yogh;te not walke not manye daies|aftir. &amp; whanne &thorn;at he my&yogh;te take sufficiently mete, I comaundide
<PB N="140">|him to take pilulas chochias<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cochia</I>. An ancient name for several officinal purgative pills. Dunglison,|<I>Medic. Lex</I><GAP DESC="Greek">., a pill.  Alex. Trall.  Compare Fr. coch&eacute;e.</NOTE> for to resolue bi euaciacioun &thorn;e matere|&thorn;at I-gaderide togidere in &thorn;e heed bi &thorn;ilke fallinge / &amp; I comaundide|him to ete ofte &thorn;e braynes of briddis heedis, &amp; of hennys &amp; of|smale briddis &amp; kedis / &amp; in &thorn;is maner he was hool; ne&thorn;eles he was|neuere so sotil of witt as he was tofore /</P>
<P>In &thorn;is ben yuel signes as &thorn;e face to be to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be to</I>, added in margin.</NOTE> crokid, &amp; &thorn;e y&yogh;en to| loke asquynt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="74a">ei&thorn;er crokidliche, apoplexie, crampe, to schite wi&thorn;oute|felynge, &amp; vnmouablete of alle &thorn;e membris outcept &thorn;e lacertis of|&thorn;e brest &thorn;at moun be saaf<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: pr&aelig;terquam lacertorum pectoris qui sallire videntur.  The translator|evidently read <I>salvere</I> instead of <I>sallire</I>.</NOTE> / He &thorn;at redi&thorn; &thorn;is book may chese aftir|his owne wil oon of iij. weies &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at ben now vsid / &THORN;e toon|is &thorn;e wey &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at is seid in &thorn;e bigynnynge of &thorn;is chapitle, &thorn;e|which wey manye vsen, &amp; a leche of Ianewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Anselmus de Ianua.  A. de Porte, quoted by Guy de Chauliac as|Anserinus de Ianua, XIII. cent.  Ianua is Genoa, see Eloys Dictionn.|historique.</NOTE> &thorn;at is clepid anselme|vsi&thorn; &thorn;is wey, &amp; &thorn;erbi he gate myche money / ne&thorn;eles I wiste weel|&thorn;at manye men dieden in hise handis bi &thorn;is wey / &THORN;e secunde maner|is in almaner hurtynge of &thorn;e heed to vsen terabracioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Terebration</I>, a boring or piercing; a Term more especially used in|Surgery."  Phillips.  "<I>Terebra</I>, an Awger or Wimble, a Piercer; also an|Instrument to engrave on Stones; also a Surgeon's Trepan or Trepandiron."|<I>Ibid</I>.</NOTE> ei&thorn;er remeuynge|of &thorn;e boon wi&thorn; handliche instrumentis / &thorn;e iij. is my wey &thorn;e
<PB N="141">|which &thorn;at I haue told openliche in almaner caas / &amp; I bileue, if|&thorn;at he take hede to alle &thorn;ese weyes &amp; &thorn;at he wole wisely discussen|alle &thorn;e opynyons of auctouris, &thorn;at he schal seen fewere die bi my|.iij. wey &thorn;an bi ony of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere .ij. weyes // Almy&yogh;ti god lede &thorn;e|redere of &thorn;is werk in &thorn;e best wey, &thorn;oru&yogh; whos my&yogh;tis, wordis takis|sentencis &amp; also vndirstondinge.</P>
<P>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;at we han bihoten to tretyn of anotamie<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="74b"> of membris |&thorn;at ben compound, in &thorn;e bigynnynge of eueri chapitle of &thorn;is|secunde tretis, ne&thorn;eles we leeuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. relinquimus tamen propter melius.</NOTE> it for &thorn;e bettere for to treten of|anotamie of &thorn;e visage, to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tretise, where we schulden treten|of sijknes &thorn;at comen to &thorn;ese membris, &thorn;e whiche syknessis ben non<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>now</I>.</NOTE>|woundis //  //  //</P>
