<PB N="155">
<HEAD>The .iiij. chapitle of &thorn;e .ij. tretis is of woundis|of &thorn;e spaude,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spaude</I>, spatula = scapula, shoulder-blade.  See <I>Cathol. Angl.</I>, p. 352.|"<I>spawde</I> Armus."  O.Fr. espalde.</NOTE> schuldre, arm, handis, fyngris,|brawnys, veynes, &amp; her anotamie /</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e spawde is oon of &thorn;e iiij. boonys, &thorn;e which &thorn;at mak&thorn; &thorn;e|foorme of &thorn;e schuldre / &amp; &thorn;e spawde-boon is &thorn;inne &amp; brood twoward|&thorn;e schuldris &amp; in hise endis gristly.  On &thorn;e vpper side of|him he ha&thorn; an egge sumwhat greet &amp; twoward &thorn;e arm <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82b">in &thorn;e place |of &thorn;e schuldre he is greet &amp; round; &amp; &thorn;ilke eende is holowe as a|box, &amp; &thorn;is boon is lich to a pele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pele</I>, Lat. palla.  See <I>Cathol. Angl.</I>, p. 273, note 4.</NOTE> wi&thorn; &thorn;e whiche men setten breed|into &thorn;e ouene, &amp; on &thorn;e hyndere partie of the schuldre he ha&thorn; an|eminence.  &amp; in &thorn;e box of &thorn;is boon &mdash; &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words are wanting in both MSS. (<I>entri&thorn; &thorn;e extremite of a boon</I>).|Lat.: In hac pyside sive concavitate huius ossis, intrat extremitas ossis|adiutorii.</NOTE> &thorn;e which is clepd adiutorium;|&thorn;e which is oon boon sumwhat crokid, greet &amp; holowe /|&THORN;is boon is greet for necessite of strenk&thorn;e, &amp; of schap holowe, &thorn;at|he were li&yogh;t, &thorn;at he schulde not &thorn;oru&yogh; his heuynes lette &thorn;e worchinge|of lacertis, &amp; &thorn;e round extremite of &thorn;is boon entri&thorn; into &thorn;e|holownes of &thorn;e spawde.  &amp; &thorn;ei ben bounden togidere wi&thorn; a bowable|ligament.  &THORN;e canel-boon<NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>N. E. Dict.</I>  This is the earliest reference for <I>canelbone</I> = clavicula.</NOTE> of &thorn;e brest is in &thorn;is maner maad, hauynge
<PB N="156">|an additament sumwhat round in &thorn;e ne&thorn;er partie, &thorn;e which entri&thorn;|a maner box, &thorn;e which is in &thorn;e ouer partie of &thorn;e ouer boon of &thorn;e|.vij. boonys of &thorn;e brest.  Euery extremite of &thorn;ilke vij. boonys ben|ioyned with &thorn;e spawde, &thorn;at &thorn;e schuldre my&yogh;te be &thorn;e more strengere,|&amp; forto make &thorn;is place more strengere, &thorn;er ben sett .ij. smale boonys,|&thorn;e whiche ben clepid rostralia<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rostralia</I>.  Coracoids.  "<I>Rostriformis Processus</I>, a Process of the|Shoulder-blade, and of the lower Jawbone."&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> to &thorn;e lijknes of &thorn;e bele <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83a">of a crowe,| &amp; for to fastne &thorn;e schuldre, &thorn;is boon rostral is putt in maner of a|wegge / But &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e adiutori ha&thorn; in &thorn;e ne&thorn;er partie twoward|&thorn;e elbowe .ij. eminentis, &amp; &thorn;e oon of &thorn;e eminence is more hi&yogh;ere &thorn;an|&thorn;at o&thorn;er; &amp; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ese eminence ben as &thorn;ei it were holf a boket<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Vicary</I>, p. 49, 1. 18, where the word <I>polly</I> is substituted for|bucket.</NOTE>|wi&thorn; &thorn;e which men drawen watir / &amp; &thorn;ilke .ij. additamentis ben ioyned|wi&thorn; &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e arm / &THORN;e arm from &thorn;e elbowe dounward ha&thorn; .ij.|bonys; &amp; &thorn;e ouer boon, &thorn;e which &thorn;at arecchi&thorn; fro &thorn;e &thorn;ombe to &thorn;e|boon &thorn;at is clepid adiutorium, is &thorn;e smallere boon; &amp; &thorn;e ne&thorn;ir boon|&thorn;at strecchi&thorn; from &thorn;e litil fyngir to &thorn;e elbowe is &thorn;e grettere boon.  &amp;|he ha&thorn; in &thorn;e ouer ende twoward &thorn;e elbowe an additament lijk twoward|a bille or a pike; &amp; &thorn;ilke pike maki&thorn; &thorn;e elbowe scharp whanne &thorn;e|arm is folden, &amp; it letti&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e arm may not be bowid [bakwarde]*.
<PB N="157">|&THORN;ese .ij. boonys ben so ioyned togidere, &thorn;at it seme&thorn; as &thorn;ou&yogh; it|were but oo. boon.  &amp; &thorn;e ne&thorn;ir ende of &thorn;ese boonys ben ioyned|with &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e hand, &thorn;e whiche ben clepid rasceta,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rasceta</I>, Arab = carpus.  Castelli, <I>Lexicon medic</I>., p. 139.  See|Littr&eacute;: "rachette," and Devic Suppl. to <I>Littr&eacute;. Dict.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at ben|.viij. boonys, .iiij. of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83b">hem ben ordeyned &amp; ioyned with summe|additamentis to &thorn;e .ij. boonys of &thorn;e arm / &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere .iiij. ben conteyned<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>conteyned, conteyne&thorn;</I> for <I>contynued, contynue&thorn;.</I></NOTE> |with &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e hand &thorn;at ben clepid pecten<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pecten</I>, Latin, pecten manus.  See Halle, <I>Treatise of the Anatomye</I>, p.|62 (A.D. 1562).  "And after these bones Rasseta, are constitute the bones of|the palmes of the hands, called Ostea metacarpis. i. Postbrachialia, Palma,|vel manus pectus."  The corrupt form <I>Patinis</I> occurs in <I>Vicary</I>, p. 50, 1. 9.</NOTE> / &THORN;e|firste boon of pecten is ioyned with &thorn;e first boon of rasceta,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>pasceta</I>.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e|o&thorn;ere .iij. in &thorn;e same maner outaken &thorn;e &thorn;ombe. &mdash;&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Two words (<I>&thorn;e &thorn;ombe</I>) are wanting.  Latin: Nam pollex tria habens|ossa....  He counts the metacarpal bone of the thumb as a phalanx.</NOTE> &thorn;at ha&thorn; .iij.|boonys as &thorn;e o&thorn;ere fyngris han, conteyne&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>conteyned, conteyne&thorn;</I> for <I>contynued, contynue&thorn;</I>.</NOTE> his firste boon wi&thorn; &thorn;e|extremite of &thorn;e ouer fosile,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fosile</I>, Latin: focile.  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 49, note 3.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ombe euenliche a&yogh;enstondi&thorn; &thorn;e|strenk&thorn;e of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere fyngris in clicchinge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in clicchinge</I>, Latin: (pollex) ut sit solus ex opposito comprehendens|cum aliis firmius, et firmius retinens apprehensum.</NOTE>  &amp; alle &thorn;ese boonys &thorn;at|mencioun is maad of, &thorn;at ben in ioynturis, as &thorn;e schuldris, elbowis,|raschet, &amp; &thorn;e knottis of alle &thorn;e fyngris, ben ioyned togidere bi mene|of ligamentis, as it is seid tofore / &amp; &thorn;ese boonys ben clo&thorn;id wi&thorn;|symple fleisch &amp; brawnys after &thorn;at &thorn;e dyuersite of foorme of lymes|aski&thorn; /</P>
<P>&amp; alle &thorn;e greete senewis proceden out of nucha, &thorn;e whiche|senewis ben conpounned wi&thorn; ligamentis &amp; wi&thorn; symple fleisch,|makynge brawnys meuynge &thorn;o parties; of &thorn;e whiche brawnys|summe ben open to a mannys si&yogh;t, &amp; summe ben hid; for &thorn;ei ben|departid in two <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84a">&thorn;e leeste parties<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. in tres partes minimas diuiduntur.</NOTE> / &THORN;ere ben .iiij. brawnys open in |&thorn;e fleischy partie of &thorn;e arm, bitwene &thorn;e schuldre &amp; &thorn;e elbowe: oon|on &thorn;e ynnere half, ano&thorn;ir on &thorn;e vttere half, ano&thorn;ir on &thorn;e lowere|half, ano&thorn;ir on &thorn;e hi&yogh;ere half.  Whanne &thorn;e ynnere brawn is drawe|togidere &thorn;anne is &thorn;e arme foldid ynward, &amp; &thorn;e contrarie brawn on
<PB N="158">|&thorn;e vttere half is maad long; &amp; whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e vttere brawn of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brawn</I>, struck through after <I>of &thorn;e.</I></NOTE>|arm is maad schort, &thorn;anne is &thorn;e arm drawe outward &amp; &thorn;e ynnere is|maad long; &amp; in &thorn;e same maner by<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ben</I>.</NOTE> o&thorn;ere .ij. brawnys, &thorn;e arm is|houe vp &amp; lete falle doun / &amp; whanne &thorn;at alle &thorn;e brawnys traueilen|liche myche, &thorn;e arm stant euene ri&yogh;tliche &amp; declyne&thorn; to no partie /|&amp; &thorn;ese brawnys,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I>, inserted.</NOTE> .iiij fyngir mele from &thorn;e ioynture of &thorn;e schuldre,|ben nakid cordis, &amp; &thorn;ei ben &thorn;e same from &thorn;e ioynture of &thorn;e elbowe|&amp; in &thorn;e myddil of &thorn;e adiutorie, &thorn;at is &thorn;e place &thorn;at is from &thorn;e|schuldre to &thorn;e elbowe; &thorn;e cordis ben multiplied dyuersliche wi&thorn;|fleisch to &thorn;e composicioun of &thorn;e same brawnys, .iij. fyngir mele| aboue &thorn;e elbowe. &amp; .iij. fyngir mele byne&thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84b"> &thorn;e elbowe ben nakid|cordis; &amp; &thorn;ere &thorn;ei maken ano&thorn;ir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>corde</I>, cancelled, after <I>ano&thorn;ir.</I></NOTE> brawn; &amp; in &thorn;is maner ben|maad nakid cordis &amp; generacioun of brawnys, til euery lyme haue|his meuynge, after &thorn;at it nedi&thorn; him.</P>
<P>In bo&thorn;e &thorn;e armes ben .iiij. open veynes &thorn;at comen from &thorn;e|lyuere, &amp; ben scharpeled<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben schorpeled</I>, Latin: disperguntur&mdash;O.Fr. escharpiller, mettre en|pi&egrave;ces.  See Godefroy.</NOTE> &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e arm.  For &thorn;ere is a braunchid|veyne &thorn;e which wexi&thorn; on &thorn;e vttere partie of &thorn;e lyuere, &amp; is dyuydid|in two parties: oon arisynge, ano&thorn;ir discendynge; &thorn;e veyne arisynge|come&thorn; to &thorn;e mydrif; &amp; sum partie of hir is sparpoiled<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is sparpoilid</I>, Latin: dispergitur&mdash;O.Fr. esparpeiller.  See <I>Cathol. Angl.</I>,|p. 351, note 6.</NOTE> &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e|mydrif &amp; &thorn;e lymes of &thorn;e brest / &thorn;at o&thorn;ere partie of &thorn;e veyne passi&thorn;|to &thorn;e arm-hoolis, &amp; &thorn;ere he is forkid.  &amp; &thorn;at veyne passi&thorn; byne&thorn;e|the arm to &thorn;e elbowe, &amp; &thorn;ere sche may be seen; &amp; he is clepid|basilica<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Basilica</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 52, note 5.  There is one reference for<GAP DESC="Greek">|given in <I>Stephanus Thes</I>., from Synesius, De febribus, which is a|translation of an Arab. treatise by Constant. Africanus.</NOTE> or ellis epatica, &amp; aftirward he strecchi&thorn; bi &thorn;e ne&thorn;ir partie|of &thorn;e arm to &thorn;e hond, bitwene &thorn;e litil fyngir &amp; &thorn;e leche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leche fyngir</I>.  See <I>Prompt. Parv</I>., p. 291, note 4.  O.E.<I> l&aelig;&macr;cefinger</I>,|Leechd., vol. i. p. 394.  See Notes.</NOTE> fiyngir, &amp;|sche is clepid saluatella<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Salvatella</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, p. 53, note 1.  Dufresne gives one reference|for Salvatella with a different meaning: "Pellicula involvens cerebrum."  It|occurs frequently in the Latin translations of Arab. authors, and translates|Arab. sceilem or osailemon.</NOTE> or ellis epatica in &thorn;e ri&yogh;thond, &amp; in &thorn;e lifthand|splenatica.  &THORN;e to&thorn;ir partie of &thorn;is veyne &thorn;at is dyuydid fro|&thorn;is assellari strecchi&thorn; to &thorn;e vttere partie of &thorn;e schuldre: &amp; &thorn;ere is
<PB N="159">|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85a">dyuydid.  &amp; &thorn;e oon partie goi&thorn; to &thorn;e heed &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ir partie to &thorn;e |arm.  &amp; &thorn;ilke is eftsoones dyuydid, &amp; &thorn;e oon partie is spred bi &thorn;e|arm manye weies wi&thorn;oute for&thorn;, &thorn;at is clepid funis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>funis</I>, Castelli, Lexic. Medicum, p. 351.  "Arabes venam Medianam|vocasse Funem brachii, testatur Ioh. Zecchius, lect. ii. in sect. 1. <I>Sph. Hipp</I>.|p. m. 109."  On this place <I>funis</I> evidently means not the vena mediana, but|one of the recurrent veins.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere|partie strecchi&thorn; euene to &thorn;e elbowe, &amp; &thorn;ere sche is schewid bi &thorn;e|ouer partie of &thorn;e arm; &amp; so sche strecchi&thorn; to &thorn;e hand, &amp; &thorn;ere sche|apperi&thorn; bitwene &thorn;e fyngir and &thorn;e &thorn;ombe, &amp; is clepid cephalica.  ij.|braunchis &thorn;at ben diuided &thorn;at comen fro &thorn;e schuldre, &thorn;e toon is|cephalica, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere from assillari,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vena ascellaris</I>.  Matth. Sylv.: "Vena communis nigra purpurea media|&mdash; &mdash; dicitur communis quoniam componitur ex assellari et humerali."</NOTE> &thorn;at is basilica, maken oon veyne|&thorn;at is clepid mediana ei&thorn;er purpurea.  &amp; &thorn;ere ben .iiij. veynys, as it|is seid bifore, scilicet, finis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>finis</I> for <I>funis</I>.</NOTE> brachij &thorn;at strecchi&thorn; bi &thorn;e vttere partie|of &thorn;e arm, &amp; sephelica &thorn;e which &thorn;at strecchi&thorn; bi &thorn;e ouer partie, &amp;|basilica &thorn;at strecchi&thorn; bi &thorn;e lower partie &amp; communis seu mediana|seu purpurea seu fusca quod idem est is comun veyne ei&thorn;ir myddil|veyne, &thorn;e which &thorn;at is compouned of basilica &amp; cephalica tofore|seid, &amp; sche apperi&thorn; openliche in &thorn;e foldynge of &thorn;e myddil of &thorn;e|arm. // &para; &THORN;e veynes &thorn;at comen from &thorn;e lyuere han manie departingis |<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85b">&amp; dyuers placis, &amp; for to telle alle &thorn;e departyngis, it is not profitable|for a sirurgian / Saue it suffisi&thorn; for a sirurgian, for to knowe in|what place &thorn;e grete veynes sitten &amp; &thorn;e arterijs, so &thorn;at he mowe|saue him-silf from perel &amp; helpe hem, whanne &thorn;ei ben kutt / &THORN;is|&thorn;ou schalt wite, &thorn;at from &thorn;e lyuere &thorn;er come&thorn; a veyne to euery|lyme bicause of nurischinge.  &amp; for to make &thorn;e lymes ful of lijf,|Arterijs comen &thorn;erto also.  &amp; &thorn;erfore in euery place &thorn;ere &thorn;at ben|grete veynes, in &thorn;e same place ben arterijs.</P>
<P>&para; Bi &thorn;es &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben aforseid, &thorn;ou maist wite wel &thorn;at &thorn;ere|come&thorn; greet perel of woundis, &thorn;at ben aboute &thorn;e schuldris &amp; vndir|&thorn;e arme-pittis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e arme-pittis</I>.  See Wr. W., 627. 3. xv. cent.</NOTE> &amp; in &thorn;e boon of adiutorie, &amp; in &thorn;e arm, &amp; in &thorn;e|hondis / for whi: if woundis be maad in adiutorijs &amp; in &thorn;e arme|ouer&thorn;wert, it is greet perel lest &thorn;e braun be kutt awey, wherby &thorn;e|arme schulde haue his meuynge; &amp; it is perel of kuttynge of|veynes and arterijs, lest &thorn;e blood my&yogh;te not be staunchid.  &para; And|if it be maad a wounde with a &thorn;ing &thorn;at prickide, &amp; falle vpon a
<PB N="160">| corde &thorn;at is in &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="86a">ende of &thorn;e braun, &amp; is clepid thenantos,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>thenantos</I>, sinew.  Matth. Sylv.: "Tenantos gre. est chorda que in|capitibus musculorum aggregatur."  It is a corrupt form of Gr.<GAP DESC="Greek">|(Suidas Gloss.).</NOTE> &thorn;anne|it is greet drede of &thorn;e spasme &amp; aftirward of dee&thorn;, for &thorn;e akynge|entri&thorn; in &thorn;e corde &thorn;at is prickid, &amp; so &thorn;e akynge arisi&thorn; vp to &thorn;e|brayn, &amp; &thorn;anne come&thorn; spasme.  &para; Also it falli&thorn; many tyme &thorn;at a|man is hurt &thorn;e brede of iij. fyngris wi&thorn;inne aboue &thorn;e elbowe, &thorn;er|is &thorn;e eende of &thorn;e braun &amp; &thorn;ere ben cordis; &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;er wole come|greet akynge, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e spasme aftir, &amp; &thorn;ese woundis ben mortal.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;at wounde be maad endlongis in &thorn;e arme &amp; in adiutorio,|&thorn;anne it is not so greet drede &thorn;erof, &thorn;erfore it is necessarie for a|sirurgian to knowe &thorn;e perel of woundis &thorn;at falli&thorn; in &thorn;is place, &amp;|whe&thorn;er &thorn;e wounde be ouer&thorn;wert or endelongis.  &amp; if &thorn;e wounde be|endelongis, &thorn;anne he schal ioyne &thorn;e wounde togidere &amp; sewe hem,|&amp; sprynge &thorn;eron &thorn;e poudre of lyme &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis, as it is aforeseid,|for to kepe &thorn;e sewyngis &amp; &thorn;e ligaturis togidere &amp; alle &thorn;ingis as it is|aforeseid in &thorn;e wounde of fleisch.  &para; If &thorn;er be ony nerues, or|arterijs, ou&thorn;er veynes kutt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="86b">ouer&thorn;wert: &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt worche| with &thorn;ingis &thorn;at streyne&thorn; blood, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt sewe &thorn;e hedis of &thorn;e|nerues togidere or of &thorn;e cordis.  &amp; &thorn;e pacient schal be kept from|akynge wi&thorn; good kepinge &amp; with reste, &amp; he schal ligge in an euene|bed.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt leie aboute &thorn;e wounde a defensif of bole &amp; of|oile of rosis &thorn;at is aforseid / And &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;is defensijf be for&yogh;ete in|o&thorn;ere woundis, in &thorn;is wounde it may not in no maner.  &para; &THORN;ou|schalt kepe &thorn;e sewyngis &amp; &thorn;e ligaturis with poudre &amp; lynet, as it|is aforseid / Also &thorn;is &thorn;ou must knowe if &thorn;ou sewist sich a maner|wounde of nerues &amp; cordis, &amp; if &thorn;e akynge go not awey, &thorn;ou|muste rippe &thorn;e sewynge a&yogh;en, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;is be contrarie to &thorn;e soudynge|of &thorn;e nerues, &yogh;itt it is bettere to do<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I> above line.</NOTE> &thorn;us, &thorn;ou&yogh; he lese &thorn;e meuynge|of sum lyme, &thorn;at &thorn;e nerue seruede &thorn;erfore, &thorn;an falle in &thorn;e spasme;|for &thorn;anne it were drede of dee&thorn; / &THORN;erfore it is necessarie for to|opene &thorn;e wounde &amp; fille it ful of oile of rosis &amp; of &yogh;elke of an ey.|&amp; vpon <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="87a">&thorn;e wounde leie of &thorn;e same medicyn til &thorn;e wounde quytture,| &amp; &thorn;anne make &thorn;e wounde clene with mundificatiues, &amp; &thorn;anne|regendre floisch as it is aforseid // If it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ere come ony|hoot apostymes vpon woundis in &thorn;is place: &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt|worche as it is aforseid in a propre chapitre // If it so be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou|leie vpon &thorn;e wounde oile of rosis, &amp; &yogh;elke of an ey for to do awei &thorn;e
<PB N="161">|akynge, &amp; if &thorn;ere falle a flux of blood, &amp; &thorn;anne if &thorn;ou leidist &thorn;erto|ony constreyning &thorn;ingis, &thorn;e akynge wolde be &thorn;e more, &amp; if &thorn;ou|leidist &thorn;erto &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey &amp; oile, &thorn;at wole make &thorn;e flux of|blood &thorn;e more&mdash;In &thorn;is caas what is for to done? &THORN;ou schalt brenne|&thorn;e hedis of &thorn;e veynes &amp; of &thorn;e cordis with an hoot yrn, but &thorn;ou|schalt not touche &thorn;e lippis of &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn; iren in no maner; &amp;|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt leie in the wounde &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey &amp; oile of|rosis, til al &thorn;e rynde of &thorn;e brennyng falle awei. &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt|leie &thorn;erto mundificatiues, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt regendre fleisch, and|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt soude &thorn;e wounde /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="87b">Of woundis of thoracis &amp; of &thorn;e brest &amp; of &thorn;e |membris &thorn;at ben conteyned in it, &amp; anothamia.</HEAD>
<P>Thorax is maad of .vij. boonys &amp; euery boon at &thorn;e eende is|cartilaginosum / &THORN;ese .vij. boonys ben ioyned togidere in &thorn;is|maner &thorn;at euery leene&thorn; vpon o&thorn;ir, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ese .vij. boonys ben maad|fast .vij. ribbis &thorn;at ben grete ribbis, &amp; &thorn;o .vij. ribbis ben maad fast|in &thorn;e rigge boon bihynde, &amp; &thorn;ese ribbis ben crokid / Wi&thorn;inne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn;inne</I>.  The Latin has <I>infra</I>, which the translator took for <I>intra</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ese|.vij. ribbis ben v. ribbis &thorn;at ben lasse, &amp; ben clepid litil ribbis, &amp;|ben maad fast bihynde with .v. boonys of &thorn;e rigge, &amp; in &thorn;e forside|of a man &thorn;ei haue no fastnynge to no boon, saue &thorn;ei ben maad fast|with lacertis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lacertis</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 57, note 1.</NOTE>  &amp; bitwixe &thorn;e .viij. boon &amp; &thorn;e .ix. boon, diafragma is|maad fast, for to bigynne tellyngis of boonys abouefor&thorn;.  &amp; &thorn;is|diafragma departi&thorn; &thorn;e spirituals from &thorn;e guttis. &amp; in &thorn;e holownes|&thorn;at is aboue liggi&thorn; &thorn;e herte &amp; &thorn;e lungis /</P>
<P>&THORN;e herte <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="88a">is maad of hard fleisch &amp; strong &amp; of lacertes &thorn;at &thorn;ei |mi&yogh;te be hard, &thorn;at it ne schulde take a greuaunce li&yogh;tli.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Avicenna, Lib. III., Fen XI., Tract. I., Cap. 1, ed. Venet, 1527, f. 204:|"Cor quidem ereatum est ex carne forti ut sit longinquum a nocumento."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;erfore|summen seiden &thorn;at it is al braun; but it is not so, for &thorn;e braun of|a man meue&thorn; whanne he wole, &amp; resti&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;e herte is alwei meuynge|&amp; not reste.  &amp; &thorn;e herte is schape aftir a pyne, &amp; hangi&thorn; in &thorn;e|myddil of &thorn;e hi&yogh;ere holownes, &amp; hangi&thorn; sum-what to &thorn;e liftsideward;|&amp; &thorn;e hi&yogh;ere &thorn;erof is brood, &amp; &thorn;at place is medlid wi&thorn; cartilaginosis|ligaturis, &amp; is maad fast in &thorn;e lungis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lungis</I>, a mistranslation of <I>panniculi</I>.  The pericardium is also called|panniculus cordis.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;e lungis|touchi&thorn; not &thorn;e herte, saue in &thorn;e aboue, &thorn;ere it is maad fast togidere,
<PB N="162">|&amp; &thorn;e lunge defendi&thorn; &thorn;e herte from greuaunce.  &amp; &thorn;e herte ha&thorn; two|ventriclis .i. two holowe placis wi&thorn;inne, &amp; &thorn;at oon ventricle sitti&thorn; in|&thorn;e ri&yogh;tside of &thorn;e herte, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er in &thorn;e liftside<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator has omitted the following passage: "In medio illorum|duorum ventriculorum est quedam fouca: &amp; vocatur a quibusdam ventriculus|tertius, super ventriculo dextro et sinistro.  Item duo additamenta|cartilaginosa fortia et flexibilia quandam habentia concauitatem, et constringuntur|&amp; dilatantur, &amp; recipientes &amp; retinentes nutrimentum et aerem ad|nutriendum et temperandum cor."</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;ese ventriclis|holdi&thorn; &amp; resseyue&thorn; eir &amp; norischi&thorn; &thorn;e herte / In &thorn;e ri&yogh;t ventricle|come&thorn; a greet veyne &thorn;at is clepid ramosa<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translation is not correct.  Lat.: "ad dextrum nanque ventriculum|venit una vena <I>ex ramosa vena.</I>"  This vein is the vena cava inferior, which|gets the blood from the liver by the ven&aelig; cav&aelig; hepatic&aelig;.  "The seconde|veyne is called Vena choele, or Vena concaua, and of some Vena Ramosa."|Halle, <I>Anatomie</I>, page 78.&mdash;1565.</NOTE> &thorn;at come&thorn; from gibbo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gibbus</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 69, note 1.</NOTE>|epatis, &amp; comforti&thorn; diafragma, &amp; peersi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; diafragma.  &amp; &thorn;is| veyne is ful of greet <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="88b">norischinge blood &amp; hoot, &amp; it norischi&thorn;|lymes of greet substaunce.  &amp; &thorn;is veyne goi&thorn; bi &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside of &thorn;e|herte, &amp; filli&thorn; &thorn;e herte ful of norisching blood.  &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e blood|in &thorn;e herte sutilli&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sutilli&thorn;</I>.  Latin: subtiliatur</NOTE> &amp; filli&thorn; ful &thorn;e two ventriclis of &thorn;e herte, &amp; of|&thorn;is clene blood &thorn;e spirit is engendrid; which spirit is more cleer &amp;|more schynyng &amp; more sutil, &thorn;an ony bodi &thorn;at is maad of &thorn;e iiij.|elementis.  &amp; &thorn;erfore it is turnid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>turid</I>.  Latin: vergit in naturam supracelestium corporum.</NOTE> into heuenly bodies, &amp; it is|bitwixe a mannys bodi &amp; his soule a louely byndynge.  &para; And of|&thorn;e lift ventricle &thorn;ere wexi&thorn; out ij. [arteries]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>arteries</I>, wanting.</NOTE> and &thorn;at oon &thorn;erof ha&thorn;|a maner coote, &amp; &thorn;erfore of summen it is clepid arteria venalis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Arteria venalis</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 58, note 1.</NOTE>  &amp;|&thorn;is arterie beri&thorn; sutil blood to &thorn;e lungis &amp; norischi&thorn; &thorn;e lungis / And|&thorn;at o&thorn;ere arterie ha&thorn; .ij. cootis.  &amp; of &thorn;e ilke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts, <I>ij cootis</I></NOTE> come&thorn; alle &thorn;e arteries|in a mannys bodi, &amp; ben departid in euery lyme of a mannys bodi.|&amp; &thorn;ese arterijs maki&thorn; alle a mannis lymes to haue lijf &amp; spiritis;|&amp; alle &thorn;es arterijs &amp; alle &thorn;ese spiritis &thorn;at ben aforeseid; and &thorn;ese| arterijs goi&thorn; to &thorn;e brayn <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89a">&amp; &thorn;ei goi&thorn; to &thorn;e lyuere &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; him|vertu ful myche &amp; maki&thorn; defiynge / And &thorn;ese arterijs goi&thorn; to a|mannys ballokis &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; him vertu for to engendre; &amp; in &thorn;is place|&thorn;e vertu of alle &thorn;e spiritis of a mannys bodi ben ioyned togidere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translation is corrupt.  Lat.: Iste namque spiritus cordialis, qui|per viam qu&aelig; dicta est a corde sumit originem, sicut omnes virtutes, quarum|est instrumentum, cum ad ventriculos peruenit cerebri, aliam ibi recipit digestionem,|qu&aelig; meretur formam suscipere spiritus animalis, &amp; ita ut ad epar|dirigitur, in ipso formam recipit nutritiui, et in testiculis generatiui, donec|omnis spiritus, omnisque particularis virtutis perfectio cum virtutum operationibus|coniungatur.</NOTE></P>
<P>
<PB N="163">&para; &THORN;e lungis ben maad of .iij. substauncis: of fleisch &thorn;at is|recchinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>recchinge</I>.  Latin: rara.</NOTE> &amp; braunche of arterijs, &amp; of veynis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>braunche of arteriis &amp; of veynes.</I>  Latin: ramis arteri&aelig; venalis.</NOTE> &amp; of cartilaginis|&thorn;at ben holow, &amp; &thorn;ese go&thorn; out of canna pulmonis as it is aforeseid.|&para; &THORN;e profit &thorn;at &thorn;e lungis doi&thorn; a man is &thorn;is: &thorn;e lungis drawi&thorn;|eir into &thorn;e herte, for to do awei &thorn;e fume &amp; &thorn;e vntemprid heete of|&thorn;e herte, &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e herte in tempre hete / And in tyme whanne|&thorn;e herte is constreyned, &thorn;anne it is necessarie for to drawe coold eir|to &thorn;e herte; &amp; if &thorn;e lungis my&yogh;te not drawe eir to &thorn;e herte, &thorn;e|spirit of lijf schulde be stoppid, &amp; so a man schulde be deed / &amp;|&thorn;erfore it is necessarie &thorn;at a man haue clene eir, for &thorn;e eir passi&thorn;|&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e lungis &thorn;at ben tendre &amp; goi&thorn; to &thorn;e herte; &amp; &thorn;erfore vnclene|eir doi&thorn; harm to &thorn;e lungis &amp; also to &thorn;e herte.  &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;e lungis|ben <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89b">departid into .ij. placis, &amp; if &thorn;er falle ony harm to &thorn;e oon |partie of &thorn;e lungis, &thorn;anne &thorn;at o&thorn;ere partie beri&thorn; al his charge //</P>
<P>&para; Woundis &thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;e brest.  If &thorn;e wounde go into &thorn;e|holownes, &thorn;anne it is miche to drede &thorn;erof, for &thorn;anne it mi&yogh;te falle|&thorn;at sum substaunce of &thorn;e herte mi&yogh;te be harmed, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e wounde|were mortal // &para; Ou&thorn;er if &thorn;e wounde &yogh;ede into &thorn;e lungis, &thorn;ere were|greet perel: for &thorn;e wounde mai not be helid but if it be soudid|anoon // &para; And if &thorn;e wounde go &thorn;oru&yogh; diafragma, it is mortal /|And if it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e herte be hurt, &thorn;ere lij&thorn; no<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>do</I>.  Lat.: Cor autem vulneratum curam non recipit.</NOTE> cure &thorn;eron, saue|he schal die anoon; for &thorn;e herte taki&thorn; no lijf of no lyme of al &thorn;e|bodi, saue &thorn;e herte &yogh;eue&thorn; lyues to euery lyme of &thorn;e bodi; &amp; &thorn;e|herte ordeyne&thorn; alle lymes to vertues, &amp; &thorn;e herte is &thorn;e welle of lijf;|&amp; &thorn;erfor &thorn;e herte mai suffre noon harm, saue ioie ou&thorn;er sorowe /|&THORN;erfore if &thorn;e herte be kutt wi&thorn; a swerd ou&thorn;er ony greet arterie &thorn;at|is ny&yogh; &thorn;e herte, &thorn;e wounde is mortal; for &thorn;e arterijs goi&thorn; to &thorn;e herte|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89*a">&amp; &thorn;anne al &thorn;e blood of &thorn;e herte &amp; &thorn;e spirit passi&thorn; out bi &thorn;e arterijs, |as &thorn;ou my&yogh;t se bi ensaumple of a candel.  For if a candel &thorn;at|brenne&thorn;, ou&thorn;er a weke, be putt al in oile ou&thorn;er in grese, &thorn;e fier &thorn;erof|wole out; in &thorn;is same maner is &thorn;e spirit of lijf queynt, whanne &thorn;e|herte is hurt, for &thorn;e greet flux of blood, &thorn;at falli&thorn; to &thorn;e herte &amp;|stoppi&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of lijf / Ou&thorn;er if &thorn;er be greet flux of blood comynge|fro &thorn;e herte, &thorn;anne &thorn;e spirit passi&thorn; out &thorn;erwi&thorn;; as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t|se bi ensaumple of a candel: whanne &thorn;e talow of a candel is doon,|or wex, or oile, &thorn;anne &thorn;e li&yogh;t wole passe, &amp; in &thorn;e same maner it
<PB N="164">|fari&thorn; bi a mannis lijf, as it is aforseid.  &para; &THORN;e lungis wolen take no|souding whanne &thorn;ei ben hurt, but if &thorn;e leche be &thorn;e more kunnyng|&amp; soude &thorn;e wounde or it quytture.  For if it qutture, &thorn;e lungis|moun not be maad clene but wi&thorn; cow&yogh;yng, &amp; &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;e|pacient cow&yogh;e&thorn;, &thorn;e more &thorn;e wounde wexi&thorn; // &para; Also &thorn;e lungis ben|euermore meuynge; &amp; [if] woundis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I> inserted.  Lat.: et vulnerata membra indigent ut quiescant.</NOTE> schulen be soudid in lymes, &thorn;e| lyme <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89*b">mote reste; &amp; &thorn;erfore for &thorn;e contynuel meuynge of &thorn;e lungis,|&thorn;e woundis &thorn;erof ben seid incurable // &para; Also &thorn;ou&yogh; a man wolde|soude &thorn;e woundis of &thorn;e lungis wi&thorn; ony medicyne &thorn;at is consolidatif,|it ne mai not come &thorn;erto but bi a long wey as bi &thorn;e stomak, ou&thorn;er|bi &thorn;e lyuere, ou&thorn;ir bi veynes, &amp; so &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e medicyne ne may|not come to &thorn;e lungs, but bi &thorn;e forseid weies; &amp; &thorn;erfore men &thorn;at|ben hurt in &thorn;e lungis falli&thorn; in &thorn;e tisik<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Tisica</I>, Italis et Hispanis Phthisis."&mdash;Dufresne.  "<I>Tissick</I>, an Ulceration|of the Lungs, accompany'd with an Hectick Feaver, and causing a|Consumption of the whole Body."&mdash;Phillips, 1706.  <I>tysyk</I>, Hampole, 701.|"<I>&thorn;at man &thorn;at hath &thorn;e tisik &amp; &thorn;e etik,</I>" Quintess, p. 17, 7.</NOTE> /  &para; If a man be hurt in|diafragma, &thorn;er is no remedie &thorn;erof; for diafragma is alwei meuynge,|for &thorn;at is an instrument of wijnd to the herte, ri&yogh;t as a belowe is|an instrument for a fier / For ri&yogh;t as a below, whanne he is opened,|he taki&thorn; in wijnd, &amp; whanne he is closid, he putti&thorn; out wijnd &amp;|blowi&thorn; &thorn;e fier /</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;e herte be woundid, in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe: &thorn;e|pacient schal swowne, &amp; &thorn;e blood &thorn;at come&thorn; out is blak, &amp; he schal| si&yogh;e sore, &amp; &thorn;anne he is but deed //</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;e lungis ben hurt, &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="90a">knowe in &thorn;is maner bi|cow&yogh;ynge, &amp; &thorn;e blood &thorn;at goi&thorn; out of &thorn;e wounde wole be spumous|&amp; cleer / If &thorn;e wounde hereof be streit wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, make it largere,|&amp; &thorn;anne in &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e lungis caste poudre of mastix. &amp;|olibani,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Olibanum</I>.  Thus masculinum.  Arab. al-louban (Devic. Dict.).  N.E.|oliban.</NOTE> draganti, gumme arabici, fenigreci ana; &amp; he schal ete no|mete saue &thorn;at, &thorn;at he mai soupe, &amp; penidis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Penidium</I>, barley sugar.</NOTE> medlid &thorn;eron, &amp; loke|&thorn;at he haue scielence &amp; good reste, &amp; &thorn;at he traueile not; &amp; &thorn;ou|schalt not close &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn;oute, til &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e lungis be|sowdid, &amp; &thorn;anne soude &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; //</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;at a wounde be in diafragma, &thorn;es ben &thorn;e signys &thorn;erof:|streit secchinge of bree&thorn;, &amp; greet agreuaunce for to drawe his|bree&thorn;, &amp; greet akynge in his side, &amp; greuous cow&yogh;yngs; alle &thorn;ese|ben signys of dee&thorn;, &amp; principali if &thorn;ese signys be greet &amp; greuous /
<PB N="165">|If &thorn;ese signys ben but litil &amp; not strong greuous, &thorn;anne &yogh;eue him|metis &amp; drynkis &thorn;at mowe swage<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>swage</I>.  See <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 372.</NOTE> &thorn;e cow&yogh;e, &amp; &thorn;anne take a tent|&thorn;at be not to greet, &amp; wete it in &thorn;e &yogh;elke of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="90b">an ey &amp; oile of rosis, |&amp; &thorn;anne cure &thorn;is wounde as &thorn;ou doist o&thorn;ere woundis /</P>
<P>If it so be &thorn;at a wounde be in a caua<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>canna</I>.  Lat.: Cum autem vulnus est in cassum penetrans.  <I>Cassus</I>,|Pecten.  Semibarbaris ex Arabico.  Castellus, Lex. Med.  <I>Casse</I>, Arab. Kas,|cup, calice.&mdash;Devic.  I would rather trace it from Lat. cassus adj. void,|hollow, and cassum, i = cassa, orum sb. the hollows.  The latter form cassa|gave origin to Ital. cassa f.  See cassa del cranio, etc.</NOTE> &amp; noon of &thorn;e forseid|lymes ben not hurt, &thorn;anne wete a tent in oile of rosis hoot &amp; putte|in &thorn;e wounde; &amp; whanne &thorn;ou remeuest &thorn;i medicyne ou&thorn;er leist|&thorn;erto ony medicyne, be war &thorn;at &thorn;er passe out noon eir &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e|wounde, ne entre in noon eir into &thorn;e wounde, &amp; &thorn;erfore or &thorn;ou|chaunge &thorn;i tent, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben necessarie &thorn;erfore|redi, &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde mowe be stoppid anoon, &thorn;at &thorn;ere go no bree&thorn;|into &thorn;e wounde, ne out of &thorn;e wounde / For if &thorn;er go ony bre&thorn; out,|it wole afeble &thorn;e patient, &amp; if &thorn;er go ony bree&thorn; &thorn;ere, it wole do|harme to &thorn;e spaulis.  Leie vpon &thorn;e wounde oile of rosis &amp; &thorn;e &yogh;elke|of an ey, &amp; herwi&thorn; wete &thorn;i tent til &thorn;e wounde quytture. &amp; &thorn;anne|euery dai make him to turne vpon his side, &amp; make him cow&yogh;e &amp;|spitte out &thorn;e quytture, &amp; avoide &thorn;e quytture bi &thorn;e wounde also.  &amp;|if &thorn;ere be myche quytture, &amp; may not be avoidid bi &thorn;e wounde,|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt make sich a maner waischinge &amp; putte it yn wi&thorn; |<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="91a">an instrument maad lijk a clisterie / &rx; .mel ro. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij., mirre,|fenigreci, farine lupinorum ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, boile hem to &thorn;e consumpcioun|of &thorn;e .iij. part in l&imacr; j. of swete wijn, &amp; l&imacr; j. of water, &amp; &thorn;anne cole|hem &amp; putte in &thorn;e colature as it is aforseid.  Vpon &thorn;e wounde|wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, from &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at it quytturi&thorn;, leie &thorn;is mundificatif|planed vpon a cloo&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp;.  Lat.: super pannum distensum.  O.Fr. planer, Lat. planare.</NOTE>  &rx; mel ro. l&imacr; j., farina ordei substillissimi. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>|iiij., mirre, fenigreci ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j., be &thorn;ei encorperat<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>encorperat</I>.  Lat. incorporatus, O.Fr. encorperer.</NOTE> &amp; boilid at esi|fier / &amp; whanne &thorn;ei ben weel boilid, &amp; weel medlid togidere so &thorn;at|it be &thorn;icke, do hem doun of &thorn;e fier, &amp; do &thorn;erto <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .iij. of terbentyne|waischen &amp; medle hem weel togidere.  &THORN;is emplastre &thorn;ou schalt|vse, &amp; &thorn;e waischingis &thorn;at is aforseid, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt holde open &thorn;e|wounde with a tent wet in oile, til &thorn;e quytture &thorn;at is withynne be|perfitli dried / &THORN;is &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e patient &amp; bi|&thorn;e sauour of his bree&thorn;, &amp; whanne his cow&yogh;ynge goi&thorn; awei, &amp; whanne
<PB N="166">|his vnkyndely heete goi&thorn; awei / If &thorn;ou doist alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis to him| &thorn;at ben aforseid, &amp; &thorn;e quytture <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="91b">be not wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;erwith, &amp; his|cow&yogh;ynge &amp; his akynge be not aswagid, &amp; his vertu be feble, &amp; his|spirit be nou&yogh;t, &thorn;anne do &thorn;ou nomore &thorn;erto, saue he schal al turne|him to goddis merci // &para; Saue if it so be &thorn;at he haue &thorn;e cow&yogh;e &amp;|greet quytture in &thorn;e wounde, &amp; he be strong, &amp; principali if &thorn;er|wexe ony swellyng in his side bihinde bitwixe &thorn;e .iiij. &amp; &thorn;e .v. rib,|&thorn;an &thorn;ere &thorn;ou schalt make a newe kuttyng &amp; lete out &thorn;e quytture,|&amp; bi &thorn;is place drawe out &thorn;e quytture, &amp; holde &thorn;e wounde open,|&amp; lete &thorn;e olde wounde close togidere.  &amp; if it be nede, caste yn|&thorn;e forseid waischinge bi &thorn;is wounde &amp; leie a mundificatif wi&thorn;oute|til &thorn;e quytture be al aweie, &amp; &thorn;is cure &thorn;ou schalt folowe /  It falli&thorn;|ofte tyme &thorn;at a man is hurt an hi&yogh; aboue in &thorn;is place, &amp; &thorn;anne|&thorn;e blood &amp; &thorn;e quytture falli&thorn; vpon diafragma &amp; gaderi&thorn; togidere,|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt kerue him bitwixe &thorn;e .iiij. &amp; &thorn;e .v. rib as it is|aforseid, for &thorn;e blood &amp; &thorn;e quytture mai haue no cours to &thorn;e wounde|aboue; &amp; if he is kutt so byne&thorn;e, &thorn;anne &thorn;e blood &amp; &thorn;e quytture| mai be drawe awey; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="92a">&amp; if &thorn;ou doist not &thorn;us &thorn;e pacient schal die,|&amp; if &thorn;ou doist &thorn;us &thorn;e pacient schal be delyuerid wel // Whanne|woundis ben in thorase ou&thorn;er in &thorn;e brest, &amp; &thorn;e woundis ne goon|not &thorn;oru&yogh;, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt cure him as it is aforseid in o&thorn;ere|woundis //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>Of woundis of &thorn;ornis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;orais</I>.  Lat.:  De vulneribus spin&aelig; seu spondylium &amp; eorum|anatomia.  The scribe changed <I>&thorn;ornis</I>, the translation of 'spin&aelig;,' into <I>&thorn;orais</I>,|for <I>thoracis</I>, as in the heading to Cap. V.  The words: <I>&amp; of &thorn;o &thorn;at ben conteyned|in him</I> are taken from the same Chapter-heading.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er spondilium, &amp; of &thorn;o &thorn;at|ben conteyned in him &amp; anothamie /<NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>Vicary's Anatomy</I>, page 74.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Bonys of &thorn;e necke, as we haue aforsed, ben .vij, &amp; rigge boonys|of &thorn;e brest ben .xij, &amp; of &thorn;e reynes ben .v. riggeboones, &amp;|vndir &thorn;e reynes ben .iij. riggeboones, &amp; vpon &thorn;e place &thorn;at is clepid<NOTE PLACE="foot">One word is here wanting.  Lat.: super locum qui dicitur aboratur|alahume.  <I>aboratur</I> is perhaps a corruption for <I>ab arabis, alahume</I> is the|Os sacrum.</NOTE>|&mdash;&THORN;e boon of &thorn;e tail is maad of .iij. rigge boones, &amp; &thorn;ere ben .xxx.|&para; Eueri boon of &thorn;e rigge is an hole &thorn;oru&yogh;, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e ilke hoolis|nucha<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nucha</I>, Arab. nukha', spinal marrow.</NOTE> goi&thorn; endelong &thorn;e rigge; &amp; euery boon of &thorn;e rigge ha&thorn; .iiij.|addiciouns to him, &amp; summe han mo; &thorn;is is not necessarie to telle|to a sirurgian, saue it is necessarie to a sirurgian for to knowe &thorn;is:
<PB N="167">|&thorn;at euery rig-boon ha&thorn; a greet hole, &amp; nucha goi&thorn; &thorn;er &thorn;oru&yogh;. &amp;|&thorn;er ben o&thorn;ere smale hoolis in &thorn;e boones bi &thorn;e sidis aboutfor&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ere|&thorn;oru&yogh; goon nerues for to holde &thorn;e lymes faste <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="92b">togidere.  &amp; so &thorn;ese |.xxx. boones ben bounden togidere wi&thorn; stronge ligaturis, &amp; &thorn;ei ben|so strongeli bounden togidere &thorn;at &thorn;ei seme&thorn; al oon boon.  &THORN;ese|boones bine&thorn;e &thorn;e necke is clepid &thorn;e rigge ou&thorn;er spina, &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e|foundement of al &thorn;e bodi //</P>
<P>&para; Woundis &thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;is place.  If nucha be kutt|&thorn;oru&yogh; ouer&thorn;wert, &thorn;e wounde is mortal for &thorn;e nobilte of nucha &thorn;at|come&thorn; fro &thorn;e brayn ri&yogh;t as a ryuer come&thorn; of wellis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rases, Liber ad Almansorem, Tract. I, Cap. 1, ed. Ven. 1506, fol. 2.|"Cerebrum quasi fons sensuum est et motus voluntarii, Nucha vero sicut|fluuius magnus ab eo manans."</NOTE>  &para; And &thorn;ou&yogh;|nucha be not kutt al &thorn;oru&yogh; saue hurt, it is greet perel &thorn;erof, for|&thorn;e lymes bine&thorn;e schulen lese her meuynge, for &thorn;e nerues &thorn;at ben|aboute &thorn;e boones of nucha ben kutt.  &amp; also &thorn;e rigge-boones ben|kutt &amp; herof cometh greet perel / And if &thorn;e braun &thorn;at sitti&thorn; endelongis|&thorn;e rigge in bo&thorn;e sidis of &thorn;e rigge-boon &amp; duri&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>duri&thorn;</I>.  Lat. distenditur.  As to the local sense, compare O.Fr. durer.</NOTE> from &thorn;e heed|adoun anoon to &thorn;e tail eende, &amp; if ony of alle &thorn;ese be kutt ou&thorn;er|prickid, it is greet perel for &thorn;e spasme, for &thorn;e causis &thorn;at ben aforseid /</P>
<P>&THORN;e curis herof ben lijk to &thorn;e curis &thorn;at ben aforseid of o&thorn;ere|woundis, saue it is necessarie for a cirurgian to knowe pronosticatiuis|of &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93a">place, &amp; also if a man be hurt in &thorn;at place, he mote haue |for &thorn;e causis aforseid //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<HEAD>Of woundis of &thorn;e stomac / &amp; intestinum &amp; wombe, &amp;|anothamia /</HEAD>
<P>I haue seid heretofore in what maner mery<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mery</I>, oesophagus.  Arab. <I>marijun</I>, windpipe.</NOTE> goi&thorn; doun &thorn;oru&yogh;|&thorn;e necke wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, and goi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; diafragma, &amp; is maad|fast with diafragma, &amp; diafragma goi&thorn; aboute &thorn;e mou&thorn; of|&thorn;e stomak.  &amp; &thorn;e stomak is schape in &thorn;is maner,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin is a diagram of the shape of the stomach.</NOTE> &amp; in oon|side he is gibbous, &amp; in &thorn;e to&thorn;er side he is more playn.|&amp; &thorn;e stomac is maad of .ij. clo&thorn;is.  &amp; &thorn;at oon cloo&thorn; sitt|wi&thorn;oute &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er wi&thorn;inne, &amp; &thorn;e cloo&thorn; &thorn;at sitti&thorn; wi&thorn;inne|is villosus &amp; neruous, &amp; &thorn;e cloo&thorn; &thorn;at is wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; is|fleischi /  &para; In &thorn;e ynner cloo&thorn; ben longe villis wherof|come&thorn; drawynge, &amp; &thorn;ere ben villis ouer&thorn;wert, wherof
<PB N="168">|come&thorn; wi&thorn;holdyng /  In &thorn;e cloo&thorn; &thorn;at is wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;ere ben longe|villis, &amp; &thorn;at maki&thorn; expulcioun.  &THORN;e ynner cloo&thorn; is neruous, &thorn;at it|mowe fele whanne it is ful; wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; it is fleischi for to make|him hoot &amp; moist, &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te helpe for to make digestioun.|&THORN;at skyn &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e stomak is norischid with moisture of| mete <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93b">&thorn;at is resseyued into &thorn;e stomac /  The skyn &thorn;at is wi&thorn;oute|&thorn;e stomac is norischid of blood, &thorn;at come&thorn; fro &thorn;e lyuere in smale|veynes &amp; goi&thorn; al aboute &thorn;e stomac.  &para; Also &thorn;ere come&thorn; arterijs|from &thorn;e herte to &thorn;e stomak &amp; maki&thorn; him to haue lijf, &amp; of &thorn;ese|.ij. &thorn;ingis, &thorn;at is to seie vena &amp; arteria, gibbus<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gibbus</I>, mistake for <I>&yogh;irbus</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 64, note 2; and page|86, note.</NOTE> is maad &thorn;at|gouerne&thorn; &thorn;e stomac &amp; &thorn;e guttis wi&thorn; his fatnes, &amp; maki&thorn; hem hoot.|&para; In &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e stomak &thorn;ere is a mou&thorn;, and &thorn;at mou&thorn; is more|streit &thorn;an &thorn;at aboue.  &amp; &thorn;e firste gutt is maad fast to &thorn;e lower|mou&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;is gutt is clepid duodenum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>duodenum</I>.  See <I>Ibid</I>. page 65, note 1.</NOTE>  &THORN;is is &thorn;e skille whi he is|clepid so, for he is of &thorn;e leng&thorn;e of xij. ynchis; &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ere ben|.vj. guttis bine&thorn;e him; &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;is firste gutt is maad of .ij. cootis,|as alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere guttis ben, but &thorn;e .ij. gutt is smal &amp; folde togidere.|&THORN;e .iij. gutt is clepid ieiunum,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>jejunum</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 65, note 2.</NOTE> id est, fastynge, for he is euermore|voide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Avicenna, Lib. III., Fen. XVI., Tract. I., Cap. 1, ed. Ven. 1527, f. 248.|"et nominatur hoc intestinum ieiunum, quum ipsum inuenitur secundum|plurimum inanitum et vacuum."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;at is for he is ny&yogh; &thorn;e galle &amp; resseyue&thorn; myche colre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>colre</I>.  Lat. cholera.  Choler, "Bilis."&mdash;Huloet.</NOTE> for|to avoide him, &amp; &thorn;ere goi&thorn; to him manye veynes, wherbi he is|voidid / Aftir him &thorn;ere come&thorn; a gutt &thorn;at is clepid orobum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>orobum</I>.  Lat. orbum.  The <I>Ileum</I> is here meant.</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="94a">ou&thorn;er| a sak, &amp; it ha&thorn; but oon mou&thorn;, &amp; he resseyue&thorn; alle &thorn;e fecis; &amp; &thorn;ere|is fulfillid &thorn;e firste digestioun of &thorn;e guttis / Aftir &thorn;is gutt &thorn;er is a|gutt &thorn;at is clepid colon, &amp; lij&thorn; ouer&thorn;wert &thorn;e wombe &amp; resseyue&thorn;|feces / And aftir &thorn;is gutt come&thorn; langaon,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>langaon</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 66, note 5.  Lat. longanon, longao = the|straight gut.</NOTE> &amp; is &thorn;e eende of alle;|&amp; he ha&thorn; .iiij. brawnys, &amp; &thorn;erof he ha&thorn; vertu for to wi&thorn;holde &thorn;e|fecis yn, &amp; for to putte hem out whanne a man wole / Euery|meuynge of &thorn;e guttis is kindely &amp; eueri gutt of &thorn;ese &thorn;at ben|aforseid ha&thorn; diuers kynde // &para; &THORN;er ben manye maner causis whi|&thorn;at guttis ben folde with nerues: &thorn;e firste enchesoun is &thorn;is, &thorn;at a|man schulde not as soone as he hadde ete, anoon ri&yogh;t go to sege as
<PB N="169">|doi&thorn; a beest.  &THORN;e .ij. cause is &thorn;at &thorn;e mete mi&yogh;te abide in &thorn;e stomak|for to make digestion, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at is not fulfillid in &thorn;e stomak is|fulfillid in &thorn;e guttis.  &THORN;e .iij. cause is &thorn;is, &thorn;at it first abide in oon|gutt / &amp; &thorn;anne it is sent to ano&thorn;er &amp; so for&thorn;.  &amp; &thorn;anne for to holde|alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis / &thorn;e stomak &amp; &thorn;e guttis is ordeyned a skyn, &thorn;at is |clepid &thorn;e siphac<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>siphac</I>.  See <I>Vicary</I>, page 62, note 4.</NOTE>; &amp; is a syngle skyn &amp; is not <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="94b">villous, &amp; is engendrid|bine&thorn;e as is diafragma is aboue, as it is aforeseid, &amp; is maad|fast at &thorn;e rigge bihinde, for to holde vp &thorn;e stomak &amp; &thorn;e guttis / In|&thorn;is partie bine&thorn;e &thorn;is &thorn;er ben engendrid of siphac ij. &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben|clepid dindimi<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dindimi</I>, used elsewhere to signify the Testicles.</NOTE> &amp; goi&thorn; adoun al aboute &thorn;e ballokis, &amp; is clepid &thorn;at|ynner skyn of &thorn;e ballokis; &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;is dindimi goi&thorn; arterijs &amp;|veynes to &thorn;e ballokis, &amp; maki&thorn; hem haue lijf &amp; norischinge &amp;|kynde of sperme //  &para; Alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &thorn;anne ben comprehendid in|a skyn &thorn;at is fleischi &amp; of lacertis maad, &amp; is clepid mirac, &amp; is|clepid &thorn;e vttere wombe in whiche ben lacertis, for to helpe putte out|&thorn;e fecis &amp; wijnd &amp; vrine /</P>
<P>&THORN;erfore woundis &thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;e stomac ben perilous, &amp; in|&thorn;e guttis, for manie causis / &THORN;e firste cause is &thorn;is, for her worchinge|is necessarie to &thorn;e bodi, for &thorn;ei ben &thorn;e firste instrument of digestioun,|&amp; her worchinge is so necessarie to &thorn;e bodi, &thorn;at it mai in no maner|be susteyned, ne abide wi&thorn;oute hem / &THORN;erfore if &thorn;ere be ony woundis|in &thorn;is place her worchinge<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="95a"> is lost, but if &thorn;e wounde be soudid |anoon; &amp; &thorn;at is ful hard &amp; sumtyme inpossible for &thorn;ei ben neruous,|&amp; &thorn;ere is no fleisch on hem, &amp; also for &thorn;ei ben alwey meuynge, &amp;|principali whanne woundis ben maad in &thorn;e hindere partie of &thorn;e|stomac ou&thorn;ir in &thorn;e smale guttis /  For if &thorn;e woundis falle in &thorn;e|ne&thorn;ir partie of &thorn;e stomac &thorn;at is fleischi, ou&thorn;er in &thorn;e greete guttis|bine&thorn;e, if &thorn;e leche be kunnynge, &thorn;e pacient mai lyue /</P>
<P>&para; If it bifalle &thorn;at a man be hurt in ony of &thorn;ese placis &thorn;at ben|aforseid in &thorn;e stomak ou&thorn;er in &thorn;e guttis, &thorn;e leche muste knowe|whe&thorn;er &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e guttis or of &thorn;e stomak be prickid &thorn;oru&yogh;|or no; &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi &thorn;e goyng out of &thorn;e fecis at &thorn;e|wounde, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e wounde is iugid mortal.  &para; If a man be|woundid in his stomak &amp; &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e wombe wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; ne|be not brood, &thorn;anne kutte it more &amp; &thorn;anne sewe the wounde of &thorn;e|stomak wi&thorn; a nedele &thorn;at is iiij. squar &amp; wi&thorn; a sutil &thorn;reed, &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou|schalt speciali, whanne &thorn;e wounde is in <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="95b">a fleischi place of &thorn;e stomak, 
<PB N="170">|for if &thorn;e wounde be aboue in a place of &thorn;e stomak &thorn;at is neruous,|ne traueile &thorn;ou not &thorn;ere aboute &thorn;anne, for it is an idil / Whanne|&thorn;ou hast sewid &thorn;e wounde bine&thorn;e as it is aforseid, &thorn;anne springe|&thorn;eron poudre consolidatif &amp; soude &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e stomak, &amp; holde|open &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e skyn wi&thorn;oute, til &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e stomak be|hool // &para; If it bifalle &thorn;at a man be hurt in &thorn;e greete guttis bine&thorn;e,|so &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be not to greet, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt sewe &thorn;e gutt, &amp;|&thorn;e eendis of &thorn;e &thorn;redis schulen hange out, &amp; &thorn;e vtter wounde schal|be holde open, til &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e gutt be soudid &para; If it so be &thorn;at|&thorn;e wounde of his wombe wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; be so brood &thorn;at &thorn;e guttis falle|out, putte hem yn anoon while &thorn;ei ben hote / If it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e|guttis be colde, or &thorn;at &thorn;ou come &thorn;erto, &amp; &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e wombe|be to swolle, &amp; &thorn;e guttis be chaungid wi&thorn; &thorn;e eir, wherfore &thorn;e guttis|wolen not in a&yogh;en, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou must sutilli make &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e| wombe a litil more, &thorn;at &thorn;e guttis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="96a">mowe li&yogh;tly falle yn a&yogh;en wi&thorn;oute|greuaunce.  Whanne &thorn;e guttis ben ynne, sewe mirac &amp; siphac in|&thorn;is maner togidere, so &thorn;at &thorn;ei moun bo&thorn;e be soudid togidere; for if|mirac were soudid &amp; not siphac, &thorn;anne aftir &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde|were soudid, &thorn;ere wolde leue a crepature.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crepature</I>, hernia.</NOTE>  &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou must sewe|in &thorn;is maner /  Take &thorn;at oon side of mirac &amp; siphac togidere so|&thorn;at &thorn;ei be euene, &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;i nedel be .iij. squar, &amp; &thorn;anne make|oon poynt &thorn;oru&yogh; hem ij. togidere, in &thorn;e same maner in &thorn;e to&thorn;er, &amp;|&thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;eron as manie pointis as &thorn;ou &thorn;enkist necessarie|/ And whanne &thorn;ou hast sewid mirac &amp; siphac togidere in a|good maner, &thorn;anne knytte &thorn;e &thorn;redis togidere &thorn;at &thorn;ei vnknytte not,|as &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at is to doing; &amp; lete &thorn;e eendis of &thorn;e &thorn;redis hange|out, &amp; &thorn;anne springe vpon &thorn;e sewynge &thorn;e poudre consolidatif &thorn;at|is aforseid, and holde open &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; til mirac &amp; siphac|be perfitli soudid, for in &thorn;is maner mirac &amp; siphac moun be soudid| bi &thorn;is cause: Siphac is neruous &amp; ha&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="96b">no fleisch, &amp; mirac is fleisch,|&amp; bi &thorn;e vertu of him siphac is soudid; &amp; &thorn;anne do &thorn;e cure herof|aftir as it is tofore // &para; Summen seien &thorn;at &thorn;e smale guttis moun|be sowdid in &thorn;is maner: make a pipe of eldre, &amp; putt wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e|gutt, &amp; &thorn;anne soude &thorn;e gutt &thorn;er vpon.  &amp; I seie &thorn;at it is not soo&thorn;,|for &thorn;is &thorn;ing, &thorn;e smale guttis wolen not soude, &amp; to &thorn;e greete guttis|&thorn;is queyntise is nou&yogh;t; &thorn;erfore triste to &thorn;e maner &thorn;at is aforseid,|&amp; take kepe of &thorn;e perels &thorn;at ben forseid.
</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<PB N="171">
<HEAD>Of woundis of &thorn;e lyuere &amp; splen &amp; reynes &amp; &thorn;e|bladdre, and anothamia<NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>Vicary's Anatomy,</I> page 68.</NOTE> /</HEAD>
<P>The firste schapinge of &thorn;e lyuere is maad of &thorn;e .ij. spermes as|ben &thorn;e o&thorn;ere principal lymes, saue &thorn;e greetnes of &thorn;e lyuere is|principali maad of blood &amp; is in &thorn;e hardnes of fleisch.  &amp; &thorn;e substaunce|&thorn;erof is fleischi, &amp; it is in &thorn;e maner as it were blood runne,|&amp; chilus comune&thorn; fro &thorn;e stomac to &thorn;e lyuere for to &yogh;eue him|norischynge, &amp; &thorn;e lyuere is gibbous wi&thorn;oute, &amp; wi&thorn;inne holow &thorn;at |it mi&yogh;te be &thorn;e more closynge to &thorn;e stomac.  &amp; &thorn;e heete of &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="97a">lyuere|maki&thorn; &thorn;e stomac to se&thorn;e as fier maki&thorn; a furneis to se&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">"for his heate is to the stomacke as the heate of the fyre is to the Potte|or Cauldron that hangeth ouer it."&mdash;<I>Vicary,</I> p. 69.</NOTE>  &para; The|lyuere ha&thorn; addicioun, &amp; ben diuers; for in summe ben .iiij. &amp; in|summe ben .v. &amp; in summe ben .iij.  Of sperme &thorn;e mater of &thorn;e|lyuere wi&thorn;inne is gaderid.  &amp; &thorn;erof come&thorn; a greet veyne &amp; is engendrid|in sima<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>sima</I>, concavitas hepatis.  Matth. Sylv., see Dufr. <GAP DESC="Greek">, hollow,|concave: <GAP DESC="Greek">, the bottom of the liver.  Poll. 2. 213, Galen.|It is used opposite to <GAP DESC="Greek">, convex, curved, in Galen ad Glauc. 2.&mdash;See|<I>Stephanus Thesaurus.</I></P><P>Sloane 2463, fol. 40: <I>"Syma of &thorn;e lyuer is as it were &thorn;e palme o&thorn;er|&thorn;e holwenesse of &thorn;e hond.  The vtilite, whi &thorn;at it is of suche forme o&thorn;er|schappe is because &thorn;at it schulde ben aplied o&thorn;er leyen to &thorn;e stomak as &thorn;e|hond lieth to an appull, whan &thorn;e appull is in &thorn;e hond."</I></P></NOTE> epatis, &amp; is clepid &thorn;e &yogh;ate of &thorn;e lyuere.  &amp; of &thorn;is|veyne summen seien &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben engendrid .viij. veynes, &amp; summen|seien &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben mo; &amp; &thorn;us veynes ben &yogh;atis ri&yogh;t as rootis|of a tree.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: ven&aelig; qu&aelig; sunt ipsi port&aelig; sicut radices arbori.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;ese veynes ben clepid miseraice / &amp; summe of &thorn;ese|veynes ben maad fast wi&thorn; &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e stomac, &amp; wi&thorn; a gutt &thorn;at|is clepid duodeno, &amp; summe wi&thorn; &thorn;e smale guttis, &amp; summe wi&thorn; &thorn;e|gutt &thorn;at is clepid ieiunum, &amp; summe wi&thorn; orobo ou&thorn;ir wi&thorn; &thorn;e sak //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e lyuere is maad fast to &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside of &thorn;e stomac, &amp; in &thorn;e|liftside of &thorn;e stomac sitt &thorn;e splene, &amp; is schape along, &amp; is maad|fast with o partie of &thorn;e stomac. &amp; oon partie &thorn;erof is maad fast|twoward &thorn;e rigge in &thorn;e liftside, &amp; ha&thorn; .ij. poris, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at oon|pore he drawi&thorn; malancolious blood of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="97b">&thorn;e lyuere, &amp; clensi&thorn; &thorn;e|lyuere of malancolious superfluite, &amp; &thorn;erof &thorn;e splene is norischid. |&amp; &thorn;ere is ano&thorn;er pore &thorn;at goi&thorn; to &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e stomac, &amp; maki&thorn;|&thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e stomac to haue appetite<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>De propr. rer. Trevisa</I>, Lib. V., Cap. 41, Add. 27,944, fol. 57b: <I>"&amp;|Constantyn sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e melte is i-set in &thorn;e lift side, &amp; &thorn;e schap &thorn;erof is|euelong, and is somwhat holou&yogh; toward &thorn;e stomak &amp; bunchinge toward &thorn;e|ribbis.  In &thorn;ese tweye places he is i-bounde with certeyn smale clo&thorn;inge, &amp;|me sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e melte ha&thorn; tweye veynes, by &thorn;e on &thorn;erof he drawi&thorn; blak colera|of &thorn;e blod to &thorn;e lyuour, &amp; by &thorn;e o&thorn;ir he sendi&thorn; what suffice&thorn; to &thorn;e stomak to|comforte &thorn;e appetite &thorn;erof."</I></NOTE> //</P>
<P>
<PB N="172">&THORN;e reynes ben set, &thorn;at oon in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside &amp; sitti&thorn; hi&yogh;ere, &amp; &thorn;at|oon in &thorn;e liftside &amp; sit lowere, &amp; ben maad of hard fleisch, &amp; ben|sett in two sidis of &thorn;e rigge boon.  Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e reynes hauen .ij. veynes|ou&thorn;ir .ij. neckis, &amp; &thorn;at oon is aboue, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ere is bine&thorn;e.  &THORN;oru&yogh;|&thorn;e necke aboue of &thorn;e reynes is drawe watri blood &amp; come&thorn; from|vena ramosa<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vena ramosa</I>, Vena Cava.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;is watri blood is vryne, &amp; from &thorn;e reynes it goi&thorn;|to &thorn;e necke of &thorn;e bladdre &thorn;oru&yogh; a veyne &thorn;at is clepid kylym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: per venam chylim qu&aelig; a quibusdam pori uritides dicitur =|Meatus Urinarii = Ureter. <I>Kylym</I>, from <GAP DESC="Greek">, juice.  See also <I>Vicary</I>, p. 72,|note 3.</NOTE> &amp; in|&thorn;is maner &thorn;e vryne come&thorn; into &thorn;e bladdre /</P>
<P>&THORN;e bladdre is maad of .ij. &thorn;inne skynnes, &amp; bo&thorn;e skynnes ben|neruous, &amp; &thorn;e necke of &thorn;e bladdre is fleischi.  In men &thorn;e necke is|long, for it passi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh;out &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &amp; in wymmen &thorn;e necke of|&thorn;e bladdre is schort, &amp; is maad fast to the cunte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Hec vulva, <I>cunte</I>."  Wright, <I>Voc</I>., p. 677. 32, xvth cent.  O.Fr. cunne,|Lat. cunnus, <I>cunte</I> is a diminutive form like <I>cunetta</I> of <I>cuna</I>.</NOTE> / &THORN;e necke of &thorn;e|bladdre hath oon braun, &amp; is in &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e bladdre <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="98a">&amp; &thorn;at| maki&thorn; a man holde his vryne whanne he wole, &amp; putte cut his|vryne whanne he wole, wi&thorn; help of &thorn;e wombe &thorn;at pressi&thorn;, &amp; of|lacertis // &para; Of &thorn;e galle we maki&thorn; noon anothamie, for al oure|science maki&thorn; noon mencioun of a wounde in &thorn;e galle /</P>
<P>&para; Woundis &thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;e lymes aforeseid ben euermore|perilous / For alle &thorn;ese lymes, ou&thorn;ir &thorn;ei ben principal lymes as is &thorn;e|lyuere, ou&thorn;ir &thorn;ei serue&thorn; principal lymes, wi&thorn;oute whiche lymes &thorn;e|bodi ne mai not be susteyned / If &thorn;e lyuere be hurt in &thorn;e depe|substaunce, &thorn;anne &thorn;e lyuere schal lese al hir worchinge, &amp; al &thorn;e blood|&thorn;erof wole be disturblid &thorn;at is matere of &thorn;e spirit, &amp; in &thorn;is maner|&thorn;e spirit of lijf is disturblid &amp; &thorn;e foundement of alle hise vertues;|saue if &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e lyuere be but litil it may be soudid, so|&thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be freisch &amp; not oold hurt, forwhi a principal lyme|mai not suffre longe sijknes // &para; &THORN;ou&yogh; a man were hurt in &thorn;e splene,|&yogh;itt he mi&yogh;te be wel curid, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ere were a gobet &thorn;erof kutt| awey, so &thorn;at it ne were not to myche and ouer&thorn;wert,<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="98b"> for &thorn;erof|ofte tyme falli&thorn; &thorn;e dropesie; ou&thorn;ir if &thorn;e poris were kutt, it wolde|afeble &thorn;e stomac.  &para; Woundis &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e reynes ben not curid,
<PB N="173">|for &thorn;ei ben norischid wi&thorn; watri blood, for &thorn;at is contrarious to|soudinge / &amp; for &thorn;e reynes ben alwey in meuynge, &amp; also vryne &thorn;at|alwei is bitynge goi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e reynes.  &para; &THORN;e bladdre ne mai not be|soudid if it be kutt, for it is a lyme &thorn;at is neruous &amp; ha&thorn; no fleisch,|&amp; is alwei meuynge, &amp; for he is alwei resceuynge vryne &amp; also &thorn;e|vryne freti&thorn; &amp; &thorn;at letti&thorn; &thorn;e souding / For ypocras sei&thorn; / If &thorn;e|bladdre be kutt, or &thorn;e brayn, or &thorn;e herte, &thorn;e wounde is mortal.  &para; If|a leche be sent aftir, for to come to a man &thorn;at is woundid in ony of|&thorn;ese forseid / if &thorn;e leche be a man of good loos &amp; a kunnyng man,|he schal, whanne he come&thorn; to &thorn;e pacient, &amp; see&thorn; &thorn;e perel &thorn;erof, he|schal telle &thorn;e perel of &thorn;e wounde to &thorn;e pacientis frendis, &amp; he schal|seie to &thorn;e man &thorn;at is hurt &thorn;at he schal ascape &amp; fare weel; and |first he schal make him haue hise ri&yogh;tis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: primo tamen ipsum faciat confiteri.</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="99a">of holy chirche, &amp; lete|him make his testament, or &thorn;at his vertu faile / &thorn;anne he schal|bigynne wi&thorn; his good worchinge, ri&yogh;t as he took no drede &thorn;erof /|for ofte tyme kinde worchi&thorn;, &thorn;at &thorn;at seme&thorn; vnpossible to &thorn;e leche,|&amp; principali if he worche wel.  Ne&thorn;eles &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e leche se goode|signys bi &thorn;e pacient, he schal alwei haue his owne pronosticacioun|as it is aforseid, til &thorn;e man be al hool, if he schal ascape / for ofte|tyme whanne &thorn;e pacient drawi&thorn; toward &thorn;e dee&thorn;, his passioun wole|aswage; &amp; also &thorn;e contrarie &thorn;erof is seen, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e pacient haue|greet peyne &amp; &thorn;e signes of dee&thorn;, &yogh;itt he mai ascape / &amp; &thorn;erfore for|&thorn;ese perels &thorn;at ben aforseid, he mot be war of vndirtakynge &amp; of|biheest // &para; If a leche be in straunge cuntre, he ne schal bi no maner|wei take sich a cure.  &amp; also he schal forsake alle maner of curis|&thorn;at ben harde to do, &amp; also he schal forsake curis &thorn;at ben longe for|to make ony perfeccioun &thorn;erof, &amp; he mote be war &thorn;at faire biheste,|ne veyn glorie, ne coueitise ne bigile him not /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="9">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="99b">Of woundis of &thorn;e &yogh;erde &amp; of ballokis, &amp; of &thorn;e regioun |of &thorn;e bladdre and anothamia.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Comp. <I>Vicary's Anatomy</I>, p. 81.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>God almy&yogh;ti &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis knewe tofore &thorn;e makyng of &thorn;e|world ou&thorn;ir of man, he knewe &thorn;at a man schulde be maad|of moist substaunce, as of sperme, in which natural hete schal|worche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Auicenna</I>, Lib. III., Fen. XX., 1. 1., ed. Venet. 1527, fol. 279:|"Sublimis deus creauit duos testiculos," etc.</NOTE>  &amp; for to resseyue &thorn;e mater of sperme, it is necessarie &thorn;at
<PB N="174">|a man hauo ballokis / He made ballokis as it was necessarie, &amp; &yogh;af|hem schap &amp; complexioun for to engendre / &amp; he &yogh;af a man greet|delite for to lie bi a womman, so &thorn;at a man schulde not haue abhominacioun|&thorn;erof, saue a man schal do it with greet will &amp; wi&thorn;|greet loue, so &thorn;at generacioun mi&yogh;te be multiplied wi&thorn; greet delite<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>De propr. rer</I>., Lib. V., Cap. 48, Add. 27,944, fol. 60<I>b</I>: "<I>For as Constante|sei&thorn;, to covenable getynges &amp; gendringe of bestis god ha&thorn; ordeyned &amp;|i-made couenable membres, in &thorn;e whiche he ha&thorn; i-sette &thorn;e cause &amp; mater of|generacioun, &thorn;e whiche may not come for&thorn; in dede wi&thorn;oute affeccioun of|loue.  &para; In &thorn;e membres genytal god ha&thorn; send such an appetite inseperable,|&thorn;at eueriche beest schulde be comfortid to multeplie beestis of his owne|kynde, and &thorn;at is i-doo by schewinge of god, lest &yogh;if &thorn;e doynge of generacioun|were abhominable, generacioun of best were i-lost.</I>"  This passage is taken|from <I>Constantinus Afric. De morb. cog. et. cur</I>., Lib. VI., Cap. 1, ed. Basil,|1536, p. 122.</NOTE> /|&para; Also god almi&yogh;ti schop in a man a &yogh;erde.  &amp; in &thorn;e bigynnynge|&thorn;erof ben cartilaginis &amp; ben maad fast to &thorn;e laste boon of &thorn;e rigboon,|&amp; is maad of nerues, veynes &amp; arterys, &amp; is sumwhat holow,|&thorn;at he mi&yogh;te be fulfillid wi&thorn; spirit.  &amp; in &thorn;e heed &thorn;erof is fleisch|&thorn;at is felynge, &amp; a skyn &thorn;at goi&thorn; ouer &amp; is clepid prepucium.  &amp;| &thorn;e meuynge of &thorn;at skyn <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="100a">&amp; of &thorn;e fleisch tofore helpi&thorn; for to putte|out &thorn;e sperme / &THORN;e risynge of a mannes &yogh;erde come&thorn; of a mannes|herte, &amp; witt of &thorn;e brayn, wilnynge, &amp; greet desier; &amp; watri|humour come&thorn; of &thorn;e lyuer.  &amp; ha&thorn; .ij. open holis; &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at|oon hole goi&thorn; out vryne &amp; come&thorn; fro &thorn;e bladdre, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at o&thorn;ir|hole come&thorn; sperme and come&thorn; fro &thorn;e ballokis.  &amp; &thorn;ese .ij. holis ben|good for to knowe / And auicen sei&thorn;: &thorn;at &thorn;ere is &thorn;e .iij. hole, &amp;|&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at hole passi&thorn; a maner of superfluite &thorn;at a man feli&thorn; not,|as whanne he halsi&thorn; a womman wi&thorn; hise hondis; saue &thorn;is &thorn;ridde|hole is not knowen of a cirurgian<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Avicenna l. c</I>., "Et in virga sunt meatus tres, meatus vrin&aelig; et meatus|spermatis et meatus alguadi."  <I>Matth. Sylv</I>.: "Alguedi est humor ille qui|egreditur, cum aliquis tangit mulierem."</NOTE> //</P>
<P>&THORN;e .ij. ballokis ben maad of hard fleisch in &thorn;e maner as ben|wommans brestis, &amp; &thorn;at oon ballok of a man is grettere &thorn;an &thorn;e|to&thorn;er &amp; stronger, &amp; to &thorn;e ballokis come&thorn; veynes &amp; arterijs, &amp; maki&thorn;|hem haue lijf &amp; norischinge.  &amp; superfluite of good blood &amp; clene|come&thorn; &thorn;erto of alle &thorn;e lymes, &amp; gaderi&thorn; togidere in a mannes ballokis,|&amp; &thorn;ere it bicome&thorn; whi&yogh;t &amp; turne&thorn; into sperme, ri&yogh;t as blood bicome&thorn;| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="100b">mylk in a wommans brestis / And &thorn;er ben maad fast wi&thorn; &thorn;e|ballokis .ij. vessels, &amp; ben brode vpon &thorn;e ballokis, &amp; narowe toward|&thorn;e &yogh;erde, &amp; ben clepid &thorn;e vessels of sperme, &amp; ben clepid of auicenne
<PB N="175">|barbachi,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>barbachi</I>, Arab. <I>b&aacute;rbah</I>, 'conduit of water, canal of the urine.'</NOTE> &amp; of &thorn;ese vessels come&thorn; sperme into &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e|&yogh;erde is born into &thorn;e matris of wymmen / In &thorn;ese .ij. vessels sperme|is fulfillid, saue &thorn;e hete &thorn;erof come&thorn; of &thorn;e ballokis; &amp; to &thorn;e ballokis|as it is aforseid cometh veynes &amp; arterijs, &amp; goi&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; dindimous,|&thorn;at ben maad fast to &thorn;e siphac as it is aforseid //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e maris in a womman is maad neruous &amp; is schape as it|were a &yogh;erde &thorn;at were turned a&yogh;enheer.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Galen (ed. Kuehn, vol. IV., p. 635) has originated this curious comparison,|which has been copied by the Arab. authors.  <I>Avic</I>., Lib. III., Fen.|XXI., Tract. I., Cap. 1, Ven. 1527, fol. 285<I>b</I>: "Matrix est quasi conversum|instrumentum virorum."</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;e necke of &thorn;e maris is|fleischi, &amp; brawny, &amp; felynge, &amp; gendring, &amp; in &thorn;e necke of &thorn;e maris|ben veynes &thorn;at ben to-broke whanne a womman lesi&thorn; hir maydenhode.|&amp; &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e maris is schape as it were &thorn;e case of a|mannes ballokis / And &thorn;e maris ha&thorn; .ij. brode ballokis in &thorn;e necke,|&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e ilke .ij. ballokis ben maad fast .ij. vessels of sperme, &amp; ben|more schort &thorn;an a mannes vessels of sperme / And of &thorn;ese <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="101a">vessels,|a wommans sperme goi&thorn; to &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e maris / And in &thorn;e|tyme of conseyuynge &thorn;e wommans sperme [is] medlid wi&thorn; a mannes / |And &thorn;e maris of a womman ha&thorn; wi&thorn;inne .ij. grete concauitees / And|&thorn;e maris ha&thorn; manie veynes, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e ilke veynes, whanne a|womman ha&thorn; conseyued, come&thorn; blood to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>, mistake for <I>from</I>.  Lat.: per quas sanguis ei venit ab hepate.</NOTE> &thorn;e lyuer for to norische &thorn;e|child.  And whanne a womman is not wi&thorn; childe, &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e same|veynes cometh blood of &thorn;e veynes menstrue &amp; is putt out, &amp; in &thorn;is|maner a womman is purgid of superfluite of blood; &amp; it is maad|fast bitwixe &thorn;e grete gutt &amp; &thorn;e bladdre, &amp; is hi&yogh;ere &thorn;an &thorn;e bladdre,|&amp; is maad fast to &thorn;e rigge wi&thorn; ligaturis, &amp; in tyme of child berynge|&thorn;e ligaturis recchi&thorn;, &amp; aftir &thorn;at tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words are wanting.  Lat.: partusque completo tempore constringatur.</NOTE> *&mdash;&mdash; /</P>
<P>If &thorn;ere be woundis in ony of alle &thorn;ese placis, &thorn;ei ben stronge|perilous for her sutil complexioun, &amp; for her nobilte of worchinge.</P>
<P>&para; If it so be &thorn;at a man be hurt in his &yogh;erde or ouer&thorn;wert in a|litil quantite, &thorn;ou schalt sewe &thorn;e wounde, &amp; sprynge &thorn;eron poudre,|&amp; leie &thorn;erto defensiuis, &amp; lete him blood, &amp; diete him with &thorn;inne|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="101b">mete, &amp; cure him wi&thorn; good diligence // &para; If it so be &thorn;at a mannes |&yogh;erde be kutt al off ouer&thorn;wert, &thorn;anne it is greet drede &thorn;erof / for|&thorn;e veynes &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;erto &amp; &thorn;e arterijs &amp; manie nerues, for sumtyme|&thorn;e pacient mai be deed, or &thorn;e blood mowe be staunchid / Saue
<PB N="176">|in &thorn;is cas &thorn;ou schalt take hede for to do awei &thorn;e akynge wi&thorn; oile of|rosis, anoynte him aboute &thorn;e ers &amp; &thorn;e regioun of &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &amp; brenne|&thorn;e &yogh;erde wi&thorn; an hoot irn for to constreyne &thorn;e flux of blood; for a|cauterie streyne&thorn; blood tofore alle &thorn;ingis.  &para; Woundis &thorn;at ben in|&thorn;e ballokis, &thorn;ei roten hem anoon, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; a man be not in perel of|dee&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e hurtyng of hem, &yogh;itt his generacioun is lore / A|wounde in &thorn;is place schal be curid in &thorn;e same maner as woundis in|o&thorn;ere place of &thorn;e bodi, &amp; &thorn;e cure schal not be chaungid &thorn;erof // &para; If|it so be &thorn;at a womman be hurt in her marijs wi&thorn; a swerd, ou&thorn;ir wi&thorn;|a knyf, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; a dart, &thorn;e wounde is mortal // &para; If it bifalle &thorn;at|colon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. Se si <I>collo</I> vulnus fleri accideret.  Phillips.  "Collum Uteri, the|Neck of the Womb."</NOTE> be hurt wi&thorn; sum scharp &thorn;ing ou&thorn;ir wi&thorn; hardnes of humouris,|he may wel be curid &thorn;e while &thorn;e wounde is freisch, with putting|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="102a">of vnguentum album rasis of ceruse distemprid wi&thorn; ius of arnoglossa.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>arnoglossum</I>.  Wr. W&uuml;., p. 559. 27 (XIII. cent.) "<I>Arnoglosa</I>, i. plauntein,"|O.E. <I>wegbrade</I>, waybread.</NOTE>| &amp; if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;is place be olde, &thorn;anne it|is for to make a mundificatif &thorn;erto, wi&thorn; castynge yn of gotis whay|ou&thorn;ir watir of barly //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="10">
<HEAD>Of woundis in &thorn;e haunche and of &thorn;e coxe of &thorn;e knee,|and of boonis of &thorn;e feet and of anothomia.</HEAD>
<P>Bonys of haunchis ben maad fast wi&thorn; &thorn;e lattere boon of &thorn;e|rigboon / &amp; ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e rigboon susteyne&thorn; alle &thorn;e boones aboue,|so alle &thorn;e boones bine&thorn;e ben maad fast to him / &THORN;ese boones ben|cartilaginous &amp; sutil toward &thorn;e fore partie, &amp; bine&thorn;e &thorn;ei ben more|greet; &amp; eueri of hem ha&thorn; a box &thorn;at is clepid pixis haunche &amp;|vertebrum sit &thorn;eron.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sloane 2463, fol. 42b: "<I>&thorn;ei ben cleped ylia other ossa yliorum, and in|&thorn;e vtter partie of &thorn;e mydward of hem ben concauytes other holewnesse, &thorn;e|whiche ben clepid boystes, in &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e endes of &thorn;e bones of the &thorn;i&yogh;cs ben|receyved inne.</I>"</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;at is &thorn;e eende of &thorn;e hipe boon.  &amp; wi&thorn;|this boon is maad fast &thorn;at boon &thorn;at goi&thorn; ouer&thorn;wert vndir &thorn;e ars|aboue &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &amp; is clepid os pectinis.  &amp; as summen seien &thorn;ere ben|iiij. partis, saue in cirurgie it is seid al oon. &amp; &thorn;e place of &thorn;e coniuncioun|of &thorn;ese boones is clepid &thorn;e scie.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scie</I>, Med. Lat. scia, from <GAP DESC="Greek">, it means the hip-joint.  Wr. W&uuml;,|610. 11 (XV. cent.), "Scia an<SUP>ce</SUP> the whyrlebon."</NOTE> &amp; sumtyme &thorn;ese boones| goon out of &thorn;e ioynt, as &thorn;ou schalt haue a perfit teching <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="102b">herof in|&thorn;e .iiij. tretis in &thorn;e chapiter of dislocacioun / &THORN;is hipe boon, as it is
<PB N="177">|aforseid, is maad fast aboue wi&thorn; ligaturis &amp; pannyclis &amp; nerues, &amp;|it is a greet boon &amp; miche holow wi&thorn;inne, &amp; is ful of marow; &amp; it|is greet, for it schulde be strong; &amp; it is holow, for it schulde be|li&yogh;t. &amp; &thorn;is boon is maad fast in &thorn;e knee, &amp; &thorn;ere &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e hipe|&amp; &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e leg ben ioyned togidere in a box as it is aforseid.|&amp; &thorn;ese boones ben bounden togidere wi&thorn; ligaturis &amp; senewis, &amp; vpon|&thorn;e ioynt of &thorn;ese boones &amp; for to kepe &thorn;is ioynture from harm, is|ioyned &thorn;eron a round boon &amp; is clepid rotula, &amp; of summen it is|clepid &thorn;e y&yogh;e of &thorn;e knee, &amp; alle &thorn;ese boones ben bounden togidere wi&thorn;|strong ligaturis//  &para; Vndir &thorn;e round boon of &thorn;e knee ben ordeyned|.ij. boones in &thorn;e leg, &amp; &thorn;at oon &thorn;erof is grettere &amp; sitti&thorn; tofore in|&thorn;e leg, &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er is smaller &amp; sitti&thorn; bihynde in &thorn;e leg.  &amp; in &thorn;e|ne&thorn;er partie &thorn;ei ben maad fast wi&thorn; &thorn;e boon of calcanei &thorn;at susteyne&thorn;|alle &thorn;e boones, &amp; with alkarad,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alkarad</I>, Lat. alchaab, from Arab. <I>al kab</I>, a die.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;at is a boon &thorn;at fulfilli&thorn;|&thorn;e ioynture &amp; is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="103a">ioyned wi&thorn; &thorn;e boon &thorn;at is clepid nauicula / |&para; Racheta<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Racheta</I>, Lat. Rasceta, from Arab. <I>rusgh</I>, which means the carpus or|the tarsus.  The Rasceta pedis is not exactly our tarsus, as it comprises only|the three Cuneiform bones and the Cuboid bone.</NOTE> of &thorn;e foot is maad of iiij. boonis, &amp; ben bounden|togidere wi&thorn; ligaturis.  &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ese boonys ben maad fast &thorn;e bonys|of &thorn;e toos &thorn;at ben .xiiij., for eueri boon ha&thorn; .iij. boones, saue &thorn;e|boon of &thorn;e grete too, &amp; &thorn;at ha&thorn; but .ij. boones / to alle &thorn;ese boones|come&thorn; nerues fro &thorn;e riggeboones&mdash;&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ese nerues, &amp; with &thorn;ese|ligaturis, &amp; wi&thorn; symple fleisch &thorn;ese boones ben maad fast togidere|&mdash;&amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; to &thorn;ese lymes meuynge &amp; felynge.  &amp; &thorn;er ben greete|brawnes in a mannes leggis &amp; in hise hipis, &amp; ben ful of grete|veynes &amp; arterijs &amp; senewis, &amp; ben departid into alle &thorn;e leggis &amp; to|&thorn;e feet / &amp; summe of &thorn;ese veynes come&thorn; fro a veyne of &thorn;e lyuer,|&thorn;at is clepid vena ramosa as it is aforseid in armys.  &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ese|placis ben swi&thorn;e perilous, whanne &thorn;ei ben woundid, for &thorn;e perels &thorn;at|ben aforseid.  &amp; &thorn;ese veynes ben departid in &thorn;e foot, &amp; .ij. &thorn;erof|ben in &thorn;e holow of &thorn;e foot wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;at oon veyne &thorn;erof is|clepid sciatica, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ere is clepid renalis, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="103b">&amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;us miche to|seie: &thorn;at oon veyne serue&thorn; for &thorn;e scie, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er for &thorn;e reynes / |&THORN;anne &thorn;er ben ij. o&thorn;er veynes in &thorn;e holow of &thorn;e foot withinne, &amp; &thorn;at|oon is clepid sophena, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er is clepid vena ventris, id est a|veyne of &thorn;e wombe.  &para; &THORN;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid renalis scheweth itsilf|bitwixe &thorn;e lift too &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er too next, &amp; &thorn;e blood-letyng|of &thorn;is veyne is good for &thorn;us manye &thorn;ingis: for cancrena &thorn;at ben in
<PB N="178">|&thorn;e hipis &amp; for a mormal<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for a mormal</I>, ad malum mortuum, a severe form of leprosy.  See|<I>Prompt. Parv</I>., p. 343.</NOTE>, &amp; for varices &amp; for vlcera &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e|hipis ou&thorn;er in &thorn;e leggis.</P>
<P>Bi alle &thorn;ese skillis &thorn;ou my&yogh;t wel se, &thorn;at woundis &thorn;at be maad|in &thorn;ese placis ouer&thorn;wert ben swi&thorn;e perilous for &thorn;e kutting of nerues|&amp; of cordis &amp; braun, &amp; of veynes &amp; of arterijs, for alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis|goi&thorn; endelong &thorn;e leggis &amp; &thorn;e hipis, &amp; &thorn;erfore woundis &thorn;at ben|maad ouer&thorn;wert in &thorn;is place ben swi&thorn;e perilous as it is aforseid //|&para; Woundis &thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;es placis &thorn;at ben curable, schulen be|curid in &thorn;e same maner as it is aforseid in curis of armys &amp; of|hondis / Saue of o &thorn;ing &thorn;ou schalt take kepe, &thorn;at woundis &thorn;at ben| maad iij. fyngris brede wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e knee, for &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="104a">nobilte of &thorn;e place|&amp; for &thorn;e causis &thorn;at ben forseid, &thorn;e wounde is iugid mortal / &THORN;erfor|woundis &thorn;at ben in &thorn;ese placis &thorn;at ben forseid &amp; ben curable &thorn;ou|must do good diligence &thorn;erto, &amp; be wel war of woundis &thorn;at ben|mortal as it is aforseid //</P></DIV4>
<TRAILER>&para; The techinge of &thorn;e .ij. tretis is fulfillid &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e help of god,|&amp; now schal bigynne &thorn;e techinge of &thorn;e .iij. tretis &amp; schal conteyne|.xvij. chapitris /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Inserted by the translator; the number of the chapters is incorrect.|Lat. Add. 26,106, f. 44<I>b</I>: "Incipit tractatus tertius, et erit de curis morborum,|qui non sunt vulnera, qui possunt accidere diuersis membris a capite|usque ad pedes, que veniunt ad curam cyrurgici, qui continet tres doctrinas et|est capitulum primum doctrine prime, tractatus tertii de ornatu capillorum."</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="book" N="3">
<HEAD>Here bigynne&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde book.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="1">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e engendryng of heeris //<NOTE PLACE="foot">A list of passages on the same subject from works of Lat. and Arab.|authors is given by Adams, <I>Paulus Aegineta</I>, vol. I., p. 339 (for "Rhases ad|Mansor, VI. 1.", <I>ibid</I>., read "Rhases ad Mansor, V. 1.").</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>HEeris ben engendrid of greet fume &amp; of viscous mater, &amp; &thorn;e|more hoot &thorn;at a man is, &thorn;e more heer he schal haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer. Add. 27.944, fol. 66 b.: "<I>And here is i-bred and come&thorn;|out of fumosite hoot &amp; drie</I>."  Compare <I>Vicary</I>, p. 24.</NOTE> / &amp; &thorn;er|falli&thorn; manie amendementis of heeris.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: quibus multa accidunt corrigenda.</NOTE>  &para; First we wolen speke for|to make heer fair, &amp; aftirward of o&thorn;ere sijknessis &thorn;at falli&thorn; in placis|of heeris.</P>
<P>
<PB N="179">&para; If &thorn;ou wolt make longe heeris, ou&thorn;er if &thorn;ou wolt make heeris|wexe long, dissolue a litil mustard in water of decoccioun of bletarum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bleta</I>, Alphita, p. 22, "<I>Beta major,</I> uel <I>bleta</I> uel <I>bletis</I>, atriplex agrestis|uel domestica."</NOTE>|&amp; waische &thorn;erwith ofte, &amp; &thorn;anne anoynte with comoun oile.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt make heeris &yogh;elow, &thorn;ou schalt do in &thorn;is maner.|&rx;. mirre <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij., lupinorum amarorum <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> vj., <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="104b">flos salicis, fecis vini|combusti ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .iiij., grinde hem wel togidere &amp; distempere hem|wi&thorn; lie maad of askis of vinis, &amp; herwith anoynte &thorn;e heeris aftir &thorn;e |tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben wel waissche wi&thorn; &thorn;e forseid lye //</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt make hem blac<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>blac</I>, O.E. bl&acirc;c, albus.</NOTE> &rx; stercus irundinum, &amp; enulam|siccam, &amp; orobum,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: orobum, qui appellatur in gallico uicia.</NOTE> semen raphani &amp; sulphurus, &amp; florem capillaris<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. florum cappa.; <I>capillaris</I> is a mistake for <I>capparis</I>, the caper|plant.  See <I>N. E. Dict</I>. s. v. Caper 1.</NOTE>|succus, grinde alle &thorn;ese wi&thorn; a galle of a bole ou&thorn;er of an oxe &amp;|tempere hem wi&thorn; vinegre, &amp; herwith anoynte hise heeris, &amp; first|&thorn;ou schalt fumie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fumie</I>, Lat. suffumigare.  Compare <I>Macer. Engl. Translat</I>., xvth cent.,|Sl. 2527, f. 251: <I>"make therof a suffumygacyon."</I></NOTE> hem wi&thorn; sulphur, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt do ofte.  &amp;|&thorn;ou schalt anoynte him with oile of sambuci, &thorn;at is maad of whit|flouris of ellern, &amp; leid in oile ri&yogh;t as me maki&thorn; oile of rosis.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt kepe &thorn;e eendis of &thorn;e heeris fro fretynge, kutte|hem alle euene &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;e pacient good mete, &amp; anoynte ofte his|heed with oile &amp; watir medlid togidere, &amp; anoynte herwith ofte / &amp;|anoynte it with muscillage seminis lini &amp; psillij<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>psillie</I>, Wr. W&uuml;., p. 559. 6 (XIII. cent.), "<I>psilliun</I>, i. lusesed."  Cooper,|"psyllion, the herb called fleawort."</NOTE> //</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt make heeris crisp &rx; farinam fenigreci, &amp; mirre,|&amp; semen raphani gallarum, gummi arabici, calcis abluti, &amp; wynde|alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &amp; frote &thorn;e heeris, and &thorn;ei <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="105a">wolen bicome crisp.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt kepe heeris &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulen not falle awei. &rx; |ladani<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ladanum</I>, Laudanum, Labdanum.  "A gumme that runneth from the|hearbe Lada, and is much used in Pomanders."&mdash;Cooper.</NOTE> .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, &amp; resolue it in <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij of oile of mirtilles &amp; herwi&thorn;|anoynte &thorn;e rootis of &thorn;e heeris / &para; If &thorn;ou wolt saue heeris fro|hoornes so &thorn;at &thorn;ei bicome not whit, &thorn;anne it is necessarie for to|kepe him fro al maner &thorn;ingis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; fleume, &amp; fro greet|studijnge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fro greet studijnge</I>, Lat. a fastidio.  The correct explanation is given|in De propr. rer. lib. VII. Cap. 44.  Add. 27.944. fol. 91<SUP>b</SUP>: "<I>And fastidium|is vnskilful abhominacioun &amp; wlatsomnes of mete &amp; drinke and most greue&thorn;|&thorn;e vertu of fedinge and of norischinge, for as Isidir sei&thorn;, fastidium is i-seide|as it were makinge noye &amp; disese, for a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; abhominacioun ha&thorn;|noye and disese in &thorn;ing &thorn;at anothir ha&thorn; solas in &amp; lykinge.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; fro fisch &thorn;at is rotid, &amp; fro roten wijn, &amp; he mote ofte
<PB N="180">|purge fleume with turbit, and vse strong wijn &amp; a litil, &amp; vse sutil|sauce, &amp; vse of &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis: &rx;. mirabolanorum,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mirobolans</I>, a kind of Plums.&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> kebulorum indorum,|emblicorum, &amp; bellicorum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Chebuli, Emblici</I>, and <I>Bellirici</I> are different kinds of Mirabolans.  See|Tommaseo Diz.</NOTE> ana.,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ana partes equales.</NOTE> &amp; grinde hem alle with oile of|almondis longe, &amp; &thorn;anne tempere hem vp with wijn &amp; hony, &amp; eueri|morowe he schal take &thorn;erof &thorn;e quantite of a note / And &thorn;ow schalt|die hise heeris if &thorn;ei ben white, wi&thorn; tincture &thorn;at ben forseid //</P>
<P>&para; If a man desiri&thorn; for to haue blac heeris as doi&thorn; greuis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Greeks.</NOTE> &amp;|spaynardis, &thorn;anne make &thorn;is tincture.  &rx; foliorum mirti, foliorum|papaueris rubij, capilli, ciperi, spice, seminis bletarum, apii, ana <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j.,|se&thorn;e hem in iiij l&imacr; of watir, til &thorn;ei come to o pound, &amp; &thorn;anne cole<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cole</I>, Lat. colo, strain through a sieve.</NOTE>| hem &amp; do &thorn;erto l&imacr;. j. of oile of violet <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="105b">&amp; boile hem in a double|vessel til al &thorn;e watir be waistid awey; &thorn;anne caste into &thorn;e oile <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>|of acacie, &amp; make aischis of pyne applis, whanne &thorn;e kirnels ben|taken out &thorn;erof, &amp; medle hem alle togidere, &amp; kepe &thorn;is oynement.|&amp; herwi&thorn; anoynte heeris &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt make blake.</P>
