<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>Of allopucia &thorn;at is namys of fisik &thorn;at signifie&thorn;|diuers passiouns /</HEAD>
<P>Namys of phisice &thorn;at signifie&thorn; diuers passiouns vndir oon name|ofte tyme bigili&thorn; a leche, &amp; bringi&thorn; him into greet errour /|For comounli al maner lesing of heer is clepid allopucia<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer. Add. 27,944, fol. 66 b.: "<I>And if suche fumosite faile&thorn;|nou&yogh;t, but is infect or i-lette by som o&thorn;ir humore, &thorn;an failinge and lak of heer|is nou&yogh;t propirliche ballidenes, but a special yuel &thorn;at phisicians clepen allopiciam.|&para; By &thorn;at yuel &thorn;e nurtur of heer is corrupt &amp; faile&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;e heer|falle&thorn; &amp; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e partye of &thorn;e heed is bare, and &thorn;e fur&thorn;er skyn of &thorn;e heed is|&thorn;e foulere.  &para; Soche men faren as foxes, for &thorn;e heer of hem falli&thorn; happiliche|for inmoderat and passinge hete.  &para; Allopes in grew, vulpes in latyn, a fox|in englische.</I>"</NOTE>; saue for|to seie &thorn;e so&thorn;e, allopucia is a maner spice<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spice</I>, Lat. species.  <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 355, "a Spyce; species."  As to|the pleonastic use of <I>spice</I>, compare: <I>a maner kynde of sponges</I> (leaf 109).</NOTE> of lepre &thorn;at come&thorn; of|rotid fleume / Saue in &thorn;is chapitre I wole speke of allopucia &thorn;at|falli&thorn; oonli in &thorn;e heed.  Allopix in grew, is seid a fox in latin, for|a fox in sum tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;eer his heer pili&thorn; awei, &amp; &thorn;erfore fallyng|awei of heer is clepid allopucia / &para; Tinea<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., <I>ibid</I>., fol. 80: "<I>Also &thorn;e heed is ofte disesid wi&thorn; an famuler|passioun, &thorn;at children hauen ofte, and by constantin &thorn;at yuel hatte squama,|skalle, &amp; we clepi&thorn; &thorn;at yuel tynea, mo&thorn;&thorn;e, for it freti&thorn; &amp; gnawe&thorn; &thorn;e ouer|partie of &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e heed as a mo&thorn;&thorn;e freti&thorn; cloo&thorn; &amp; cleue&thorn; &thorn;erto wi&thorn;oute|departinge &amp; holdinge &thorn;e skyn wel faste.</I>"</NOTE> is as miche to seie as a
<PB N="181">|reremous, for &thorn;e heeris of a reremous ben alwey aboute &thorn;e heed, &amp;|&thorn;erfore cirurgians maki&thorn; difference bitwixe allopuciam &amp; tineam, for|&thorn;ei <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="106a">clepid tineam &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;ere is corrupcioun in &thorn;e skyn wi&thorn; harde |crustis &amp; quytture / Saue allopucia is whanne &thorn;e heeris falli&thorn; awei|wi&thorn;oute ony wise of &thorn;e skyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>withoute ony wise of &thorn;e skyn</I>, Lat. absque cutis vitio apparente; <I>of viis|of humouris</I>, Lat. propter humorum malitiem.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; Allopucia &thorn;at is wi&thorn;oute come&thorn; of &thorn;e skyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mistranslated from the Lat. alopecia qu&aelig; sine cutis est vulnere.</NOTE> &amp; sumtyme it|come&thorn; in &thorn;e eende of a siknes for defaute of norischinge of &thorn;e bodi|&thorn;at schulde helpe to norische &thorn;e heeris, ou&thorn;ir it come&thorn;, for &thorn;e poris|opene&thorn; to myche / In &thorn;is cas it is necessarie for to augmente|norischinge of &thorn;e bodi wi&thorn; good metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; good blood, &amp;|frote wel &thorn;e heeris of his heed wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond &amp; anoynte it wi&thorn; oile|of mirtillorum / If &thorn;is suffise not, frote wel &thorn;e heeris of his heed|with &thorn;in hond til &thorn;e skyn of his heed bicome reed; &amp; &thorn;an frote it|wi&thorn; ryndis of an oynoun til it bicome drie, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ere wole arise|&thorn;ere vpon, as it were, bladdris, &amp; &thorn;anne anoynte &thorn;e place wi&thorn; grece|of a maulard.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e heeris wexen a&yogh;en, lete schaue hem|ofte, for miche schauynge is good &thorn;erfore /</P>
<P>If it so be &thorn;at allopucia come&thorn; of vijs<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note 2.</NOTE> of humouris, &thorn;at &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t knowe bi &thorn;e teching <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="106b">&thorn;at is aforseid in allopucia &thorn;at come&thorn; |of long sijknes; for if it come of vijs of humouris, &thorn;anne vlcera|wole be in &thorn;e skyn.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou must loke of what humour it come,|&thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi disposicioun of al &thorn;e bodi &amp; bi &thorn;e colour of|&thorn;e place, as if &thorn;e pacient be fleischi &amp; wel colourid, &amp; if &thorn;e fleume|of his mou&thorn; be swete, &amp; &thorn;e pustulis &thorn;at ben in his heed be reed, &amp;|if his vryne be &thorn;icke &amp; reed, &amp; if he be &yogh;ong, &amp; if he eti&thorn; metis|&thorn;at engendri&thorn; miche blood, &amp; if vlcera be in &thorn;e skyn, &amp; if al &thorn;e|skyn be reed &amp; ful of quytture, alle &thorn;es ben signys of aboundaunce|of blood.  If it so be &thorn;at his bodi be leene, &amp; &thorn;e colour of &thorn;e place|be rufus ou&thorn;er &yogh;elow, &amp; vlcer be drie, it is signe &thorn;at colre is &thorn;e|cause / If his bodi be sumwhat whijt, &amp; if he ha&thorn; smale veynis, &amp;|if he haue miche moisture in his mou&thorn;, &amp; if his vryne be whijt &amp;|&thorn;icke, &amp; if he &thorn;irsti&thorn; not, &amp; if &thorn;e place be whijt &amp; neische and|miche moisture &thorn;eron wi&thorn;outen ony brennynge, it is a signe of|fleume / If &thorn;e colour of his bodi be derk ou&thorn;er blac, &amp; if he be|leene, &amp; if his vryne be pale &amp; &thorn;inne, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="107a">&amp; if he ha&thorn; greet appetit, |&amp; if his blood be blac, &amp; if he vsi&thorn; miche for to ete beef &amp; caul, &amp;
<PB N="182">|o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; malancolie, &amp; if &thorn;e place of &thorn;e siknes be|ledy &amp; hard, &thorn;at is a signe of malancoli, saue &thorn;is passioun come&thorn;|ful seelde of malancoli, but if it be of greet corrupcioun, &amp; &thorn;anne|it is worse &thorn;an ony o&thorn;er aforseid /</P>
<P>Whanne &thorn;ou knowist of what humour it come&thorn;, first &thorn;ou|must auoide<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>avoide</I>, Lat. evacuare.  See <I>N. E. Dict.</I>, avoid, 1.</NOTE> &thorn;at humour, for &thorn;is is a general rule of .G., for as .G.|sei&thorn; / First, &thorn;ou must do awei &thorn;e cause, &amp; I woole teche &thorn;ee to|auoide &thorn;e matere with fewe medicyns &thorn;at ben approued &amp; ben|laxatiuis, profitable, &amp; ben necessarie for a cirurgian for to knowe|alle &thorn;e maner of purgaciouns, for ellis he schal neuere wel worche|in sich maner causis / If it so be &thorn;at a man be ful of humouris, &thorn;ou|must first bigynne for to lete him blood, if he be strong &amp; in age,|&thorn;at is, &amp; not to &yogh;ong ne to oold.  &amp; &thorn;an lete him blood, ou&thorn;er garse|him, &amp; &thorn;an afterward purge him, saue it is bettere to purge him| first, &amp; &thorn;anne wi&thorn;inne a few daies lete him <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="107b">blood / If it so be &thorn;at|blood be oonli &thorn;e cause, &thorn;anne it suffisi&thorn; ynow for to lete him|blood / &para; If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou dissoluest &thorn;e water wi&thorn; a laxatif, &amp;|if &thorn;ou letist not him blood tofore ne aftirward, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou art not|sure; for ofte tyme &thorn;e medicyne laxatif wole engendre a feuer, &amp;|principali if it be hoot /</P>
<P>&para; Colre schal be purgid in &thorn;is maner / &rx; violarum <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., prunorum
<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, sebesten .xv. in noumbre, iuiubas .xx., se&thorn;e hem in|iij l&imacr; of water, til &thorn;ei come to l&imacr; j, &amp; cole hem, &amp; resolue &thorn;eron|cassia fistula<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cassia fistula</I>, see <I>Alphita</I>, p. 35, and <I>Adams l. c</I>., vol. III., p. 429.|It is <I>Cassia fistula</I> L., the pudding-pipe tree.</NOTE> <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., thamarindorum, manne ana <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., &amp; boile hem a|litil togidere, &amp; &thorn;an cole hem, &amp; aneuen do &thorn;eron poudre of mirabolani|citrini &yogh;. j., &amp; of rubarbe, &amp; amorowe cole hem, saue chaufe|it a litil first, &amp; distempere it with <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> of sugre rosarum, &amp; lete|him drynke it<NOTE PLACE="foot">The following prescription is omitted in the text, but written in a|different hand at the bottom of lf. 107 bk.: <I>pro colera &rx; cantaridarum,|mane, medulle cassia fistule ana <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, myrbol, eytri[ni] <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> ij, boylle in l&imacr; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>|watir, to the halfe put therto <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j suger &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> &yogh;, &amp; drenk yt.</I></NOTE> / ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; &thorn;ese pelottis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pelottis</I>, Lat. pillis, Fr. pelote, a little ball.  Phillips.  "Pellota (in the|<I>Forest Law</I>) the ball or round fleshy part of a Dog's Foot."  Charta de|Foresta, 1225: in <I>Annales de Burton.  Annales Monast. Luard</I>, vol. I.,|p. 233: "Talis autem sit expeditatio [canum] per assisam comitatuum, quod|tres ortilli abscidantur siue <I>pelota</I> de pede auteriori."</NOTE> / &rx; aloes cicotrini<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aloes cicotrini</I>, Lat. sucotrini, for socotrini, so called from the island|Socotra.</NOTE> .&yogh; j.,|mirabolani citrini, rosarum rubearum ana .&yogh; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., scamonie quintam
<PB N="183">|partem .&yogh;. j., &thorn;at is to seie &thorn;e .v. part of &yogh;., &amp; make &thorn;erof pelottis|with sirupo violaceo.  &amp; &thorn;is is good to &yogh;eue to a strong man / Also|&thorn;ese ben good pelottis for to purge clene colre / &rx; mirabolani|citrini .<ABBR EXPAN="dram">&yogh;</ABBR> j., scamonie cocte .<ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, masticis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="108a">grana iij., grinde hem &amp; |tempere hem vp wi&thorn; ius of iouis barba,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>iouis barba</I>, med. L. for Sempervivum tectorum.  Add. 15,236, fol. 4:|"<I>Iouis barba. semperuiua idem. G. Iubarbe A. siluegrene.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; make &thorn;erof pelottis &amp;|&thorn;is ius, but collige on &yogh;est.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>zest</I>, Lat. et sit dosis una.  "Zest, a chip of orange ... it is also sometimes|taken for a short afternoon sleep or Nap: as to go to one's zest."&mdash;Phillips.|Zest (chip of orange), Fr. zeste, Lat. schistus&mdash;zest (nap), Esp.|siesta, Lat. sextus.</NOTE>  &para; &THORN;is &thorn;ou must wite &thorn;at whanne &thorn;ou|wolt purge colre, first &thorn;ou muste make a preparatijf tofore with|oxisacra<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oxisacra</I>&mdash;Oxysaccharum, a Composition of Sugar and Vinegar.&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> &amp; wi&thorn; metis &thorn;at ben colde &amp; moist &amp; wi&thorn; reste.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt purge fleume &thorn;ou schalt to &thorn;is medicyne &thorn;at|Maister William of Salerne vside / &rx; turbit albi gummosi .&yogh; j &amp;|<ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> j, dia&yogh;in&yogh;iberos .&yogh; ij., &amp; medle hem togidere &amp; make herof a gobet,|&amp; medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; a litil of sirupe of rosis.  &para; It is good forto medle|&yogh;in&yogh;iberos wi&thorn; turbit for &thorn;at wole comforte &thorn;e stomac &amp; defie|fleumatik humouris, &amp; also it is good for to ete euery dai fastyng|wi&thorn;outen ony medlynge of ony laxatif / &rx; &yogh;in&yogh;iberis albi .&yogh; j.,|liquericie rase .&yogh; iij., gariofili cardamoni, nucis muscati, granorum|paradisi .&yogh; ij., &yogh;ucare albissime .l&imacr; .ij., &amp; make herof a letuarie not|to hard soden; ou&thorn;ir wi&thorn; &thorn;ese pelottis: pulueris pigre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pigre</I><GAP DESC="Greek">, sharp, bitter.  Matth. Sylv.: "Pigra Gal. in dinamidiis|.i. amara, qu&aelig; amaritudine sua morbos &amp; humores expellunt."</NOTE> turbit electi|ana .&yogh; x, pulpe coloquintide .&yogh; iij &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> j, grynde all &thorn;ese &amp; sarce hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sarce hem</I>, Lat. cribellentur.  <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 318. "a Sarce, colum."|Phillips.  "Scarce or Sarce, a fine Hair Sieve."  Lat. serica, Ital. sargia,|Fr. sarge.</NOTE>|&amp; tempere hem vp wi&thorn; oile of almondis &amp; make &thorn;erof pelottis, &amp;|herof &thorn;ou my&yogh;t <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="108b">&yogh;eue at oonys <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> ij.  &para; &thorn;e poudre of pigre &thorn;at goi&thorn; |to &thorn;ese pelottis is good &thorn;ou&yogh; it were bi it-silf.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be it-silf</I>.  The <I>N. E. Dict</I>. s. v. by 4, gives examples for the early|occurrence of 'by oneself' = alone.  The first reference for 'by itself' is|quoted by Shaks.</NOTE>  &amp; it is swi&thorn;e|comoun, &amp; Rasis &amp; A. acorden &thorn;eron, &amp; hali abbot &amp; serapion<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hali abbot &amp; serapion</I> are not named in the Latin text.  Hali abbot,|also called Hali &thorn;e abbot, is Ali the son of Abbas, a Persian physician|(994), the author of 'al muluki' = the Royal.  See <I>Sprengel II</I>., p. 412.</NOTE> / &rx;|rosarum rubearum, masticis, xilobalsami, spice, cassie lignie, a&yogh;ari|ana,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ana partes equales.</NOTE> aloes &thorn;at it be good, double to alle.  &para; If fleume be medlid wi&thorn;
<PB N="184">|colre, &thorn;anne do [&thorn;erto]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wanting.</NOTE> &thorn;e forseid pelottis of turbit, of scamonie|.&yogh; ij. &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, sticados arabici<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stecados</I> or <I>stickadone</I>, Cassidonie or French Lavender.  Minsheu.&mdash;Stoechas|d'Arabie.  Pharmacop&oelig;a Gallica.</NOTE> .&yogh; .v, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;erto|turbit .&yogh; .v&mdash;&amp; it was aforseid .&yogh; x in &thorn;e resceit tofore&mdash;&amp; &thorn;ese|pelottis ben clepid cochium rasis, &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e beste &thorn;ing &thorn;at mai be|for to purge dyuers humouris &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e heed / I ne knewe no|medicyn laxatif &thorn;at is so good, &thorn;at is so profitable for to purge ij.|humouris &thorn;at ben medlid togidere as &thorn;is medicyn is / For &thorn;ere ben|o&thorn;ere medicyns as sure as &thorn;is, saue &thorn;ei ben not so my&yogh;ty.  Also|&thorn;ere ben o&thorn;ere medicyns more mi&yogh;ty, saue &thorn;ei ben not so sure.|&para; &THORN;ou schalt purge malancoli wi&thorn; &thorn;is li&yogh;t medicyn &thorn;at is ofte &yogh;eue /|&rx;. epithimi .&yogh; j., &amp; boile it in l&imacr; j. of gotis whey, saue &thorn;ou schalt|boile it but a while, &amp; lete hem stonde so al ny&yogh;t, &amp; a morowe| chaufe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="109a">it a litil &amp; cole it, &amp; &yogh;eue it to drynke; ou&thorn;er make it wi&thorn;|a decoccioun of Epithimi Rasis &rx; mirabolanorum indorum .&yogh; x,|pollipodij <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .v, sene <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> vij, turbit <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> iij, sticados .&yogh; x, se&thorn;e alle &thorn;es|in iij l&imacr; of watir, til it come to j. l&imacr;., &amp; &thorn;anne do &thorn;erto epithimi|&yogh; .x, &amp; lete it boile a litil, &amp; &thorn;an sette it adoun fro &thorn;e fier; &amp;|whanne it is cold cole it &amp; do &thorn;erto sugre ro. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., &amp; &yogh;eue it to|drynk in diluculo / If &thorn;ou wolt make a medicyn &thorn;at is more|strenger, &yogh;eue first bi iij. houris &thorn;ese pelottis.  &rx; aloes <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j., salis|indi <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .<ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., agarici .<ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> ij., ellibori nigri &thorn;e .iiij. part of a &yogh;., &amp; make|herof pelottis wi&thorn; hony, ou&thorn;er make herof a sirup.</P>
<P>Whanne &thorn;ou hast wel purgid &thorn;e mater, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou must go to|&thorn;e cure in &thorn;is maner / Loke if frotyngis and li&yogh;t medicyns &thorn;at ben|seid in &thorn;e firste bygynyng of &thorn;is chapiter suffise in allopucia &thorn;at|ben not vlcera, saue oonli fallyng awei of heeris.  If &thorn;e forseid|medicyns wolen not serue, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste make stronger / &rx; spume|maris, &thorn;at is a maner kynde of sponges,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See page 179, note 1.</NOTE> saue it is more sutil &amp;| more whit, <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> x. baurac<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>baurac</I>, Arab. = nitrum.</NOTE> .i. <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="109b">nitrum, in &thorn;e stide herof we moun do|&thorn;erto sal gemme, sulphuris, euforbij ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .ij., staphisagrie, cantaridarum|ana .&yogh; j, grynde alle &thorn;ese togidere &amp; make hem wi&thorn; oile,|&amp; anoynte herwi&thorn; his heed.  &para; If &thorn;ou wolt worche more stronglich|aboute &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;e heeris ben pilid awei, &amp; principaly if he be|a riche man: &rx; olium de ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Ben</I> or <I>Behn</I>, the Fruit of a Tree, like the Tamarisk, about the bigness|of a Filberd, which the Perfumers bruise to get the Oil out of it, not so|sweet smelling of it-self, but proper to receive any sort of Scent."&mdash;Philipps.</NOTE> .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., cantaridarum &amp; kutte awei &thorn;e
<PB N="185">|hedi&yogh; &thorn;erof &amp; &thorn;e wyngis ana .&yogh; j., stampe a litil cantarides &amp; leie|hem in oile of violet,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in oile of violet</I>, Lat. in oleo in fiala.</NOTE> &amp; sette &thorn;e viol<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>viol</I>, Lat. fiala.  See <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 129, s. v. fialle.</NOTE> vpon soft colis &amp; lete hem|boile, &amp; putte in a smal sticke, and alwei meue hem &amp; it wole|bicome al into an oynement, &amp; make it haue a sote smel wi&thorn;|musco, &amp; herwi&thorn; anoynte his heed; &amp; &thorn;is wole make bladdris arise|&thorn;eron, &amp; it wole make heeris to growe.  Saf &thorn;ou must take hede,|&thorn;at in medicyns &thorn;at ben cantarides ynne, &thorn;ei wolen make a greet|brennyng, and &thorn;at brennyng wole be yuel to take awei.  &amp; sumtyme|it falli&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at brennyng come&thorn; a feuer.  First, &thorn;ou|schalt helpe &thorn;is caas<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Primo casu succurre cum unctione .... in secundo casu ponas|egrum in balneo.</NOTE> in &thorn;is maner: &thorn;ou schalt anoynte &thorn;e place|with vnguentum <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="110a">album &thorn;at schal be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie / </P>
<P>&para; Vlcera &thorn;at ben in allopucia ou&thorn;er tinearum<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Vlcerosarum autem allopiciarum seu tinearum.</NOTE> summe ben curable|&amp; summe ben incurable; if it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e skyn|be not to hard, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt traueile &thorn;ereaboute.  Also if &thorn;e|skyn be hard &amp; calose,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>calose</I>, Lat. callosus.  The references in <I>N. E. Dict.</I> are later.</NOTE> &thorn;anne it is seid incurable // &para; If &thorn;ere ben|pustulis &thorn;at ben hote &amp; ful of blood, &amp; &thorn;e skyn be ful of humouris|&amp; neische, &thorn;anne it is good for to garce &thorn;at skyn, &amp; &thorn;anne waische|al his heed with &thorn;at blood hoot, &amp; &thorn;anne hile<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hile</I>, O.E. helan.</NOTE> his heed wi&thorn; caule|leuis.  &amp; &thorn;anne aftirward anoynte al his heed wi&thorn; oile of notis|ou&thorn;er of camomil hoot, til al &thorn;e scabbis &thorn;erof be wel tobroke.  &amp;|&thorn;anne bigynne for to drie with &thorn;ese driynge medicyns / &rx;, argillam|rubeam &thorn;at it be neische &amp; clene wi&thorn;outen grauel &amp; wi&thorn;outen|stoonys, &amp; distempere it with strong vinegre, &amp; make it as it were|an oynement, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; anoynte his heed // &para; Item, argillam partes|ij., sulphuris viui, cineres corticis, cucurbite siccos<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>siccage</I>.</NOTE> pulpe colloquintide|ana partem j., distempere hem with vinegre <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="110b">&amp; anoynte |herwi&thorn;.  &THORN;is is good &thorn;ing &thorn;erfore &amp; drie&thorn; swi&thorn;e vlcera &thorn;at ben|hoot, &amp; alle pustulas &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e heed &amp; in &thorn;e face; &thorn;is drie&thorn; &amp;|soudi&thorn; // &para; If &thorn;e matere be corrupt &amp; swi&thorn;e hoot &amp; brennynge,|first &thorn;ou schalt aswage &thorn;e heete wi&thorn; vnguentum album rasis &thorn;at|schal be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, &amp; anoynte &thorn;erwi&thorn; al his heed, &amp;|&thorn;anne leie &thorn;erevpon a lynnen cloo&thorn; wet in &thorn;e iuys of stooncroppe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stooncroppe</I>, Wright W., 712. 35.  "Hec vermicularis, stoncroppe."|Lat.: crassula minor Add. 15,236, fol. 175 b.: "<I>Cassula minor frigid. sicc.|teste de soriz. stoncroppe.</I>"</NOTE>
