til &thorn;e skyn be more|scabbid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scabbid</I>, Lat. ulceratus.  See <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 320.</NOTE> &thorn;an it was.  &amp; &thorn;an frote it wel wi&thorn; an oynoun til &thorn;e skyn|bicome hoot &amp; reed, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt waische his heed wi&thorn; lye|maad wi&thorn; aschis of a vine, &amp; &thorn;eron schulen be dissolued wijndrastis|brent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: in quo dissoluta sit fex vini combusta.</NOTE>  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou hast waische his heed herwi&thorn;, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou schalt anoynte his heed wi&thorn; &thorn;e oynement &thorn;at wole pile awei &thorn;e|heeris / &rx;, calcis vif .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iij., arsenec <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., aloes <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .iij., &amp; make herof|a poudre &amp; tempere hem togidere wi&thorn; se&thorn;ing hoot water, &amp; herwi&thorn;|take awei hise heeris, &amp; &thorn;an waische his heed a&yogh;en wi&thorn; &thorn;e lye &thorn;at|is aforseid til &thorn;e matere be wel dried / &thorn;an for to make &thorn;e heeris|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="111b">wexe &amp; for to regendre skyn &amp; soude it, &thorn;ou schalt anoynte &thorn;e| place with an oynement &thorn;at is maad &thorn;us /  Take aischis maad of|a mannes heer <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j, fecis of oile, lynseed ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij, mirre <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>,|staphisagre .&yogh; .ij., euforbij .&yogh; j., make &thorn;erof an oynement // &para; If|&thorn;e matere come of malancoli, &thorn;ou must take hede to make &thorn;e matere|neische and moist wi&thorn; waisching of a decoccioun of violet &amp; fumiterre|in water, &amp; anoynte it wi&thorn; oile of violet til &thorn;e matere be|resolued &amp; &thorn;e skyn bicome neische, &amp; &thorn;e pacient schal ete moist
<PB N="187">|metis, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt ba&thorn;e him in swete watir, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou must drie|it vp wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at drien &thorn;at ben aforseid /</P>
<P>&THORN;is is a medicyn &thorn;at is approued of G. &amp; is good for tineam &amp;|vlcera &thorn;at ben harde in &thorn;e heed, &amp; for pustulis &thorn;at ben clepid|saphati,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Saphati</I>, Hebr. Sapahath.&mdash;Philipps.  "Saphatum, a dry Seurf in the|head."</NOTE> &amp; for impetiginem &amp; morpheam,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>morphea</I>, a skin-disease.  See <I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 243, s. v. Morfew.</NOTE> &amp; for fallyng awei of|heeris, &amp; for al maner scabbe.  &rx;, gallarum .&yogh; iij., seminis secute|&yogh; .ij., baurac .&yogh; j. &amp; &thorn;e iiij part of [&yogh; i],<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 46 b.: et quartam partem <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> i<SUP>us</SUP>.</NOTE> sulphuris vif <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> ij. &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>.,|arsenec rubij, aristologie rotunde ana <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> ij, salis armoniaci, fulliginis,|amigdalarum <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="112a">amarum, colloquntide, eris vsti, venarum |citrinarum, &amp; in stide &thorn;erof &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t take lumbricos terestres brent,|litargirij, capparum foliorum, fice sicce,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fice sicce</I>, Lat. fisti sicce.  Halle Table, p. 87: "Fistakia so named|bothe in Greeke and Latine, and vulgarly Fistici, are the frutes of a tree."|Fisti-nut, from fistick-nut.</NOTE> radices canne siccarum, flos|eris, alumnis sicci, rosarum, mirre, aloes, olibani ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., picis|liquide, foliorum oliue, vellis vaccini, ana .&yogh; j., grinde hem sutilly &amp;|tempere hem wi&thorn; eysel, &amp; sette hem in &thorn;e sunne in a vessel of glas,|ou&thorn;er in a vessel of er&thorn;e glasid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>glasid</I>, vitreatus.</NOTE> wi&thorn;inne, &amp; meue hem wel in &thorn;e|sunne, til it bicome al an oynement, &amp; herwi&thorn; anoynte his heed, til|it be perfitly hool, saue &thorn;ou muste take kepe of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben|aforseid &thorn;at &thorn;e humouris be purgid /</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e fallynge of heeris //</HEAD>
<P>Caluiciem is a fallyng awey of a mannis heeris tofore, &amp; is as<NOTE PLACE="foot">This paragraph is omitted in the printed editions of Lanfranc's Surgery|and in Add. 26,106.  It is preserved in Roy. MS. 12. C. XIV, fol. 32, where|it forms part of cap. II, but with a separate heading.  The translator took it|for cap. III, but did not alter the following chapter-numbers.</NOTE>|miche to seie as ballid. &amp; oon cause herof [is]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>, wanting.</NOTE> kindely as|whanne a man is oold for to be ballid, &amp; oon &thorn;erof is vnkyndly,|as whanne a mannis heeris falli&thorn; awei for sijknes as it is aforseid &amp;|remedijs &thorn;erfore in &thorn;e nexte chapiter here tofore.  &amp; if &thorn;is cause|come for elde &thorn;anne it is incurable // &para; Also ballidnesse <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="112b">come&thorn; of |humouris rotid &thorn;at ben vndir &thorn;e skyn as it is in allopucia &amp; tinea,|&amp; &thorn;e cure herof is bi avoidyng of humouris as it is aforseid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. V., cap. 66, Add. 27,944, fol. 67: "<I>Ballidnes is|priuacioun and defaute of heer, and come&thorn; of defaute of moist fumosite in|&thorn;e formere partye of &thorn;e heed; so sei&thorn; constantyn.... Ofte &thorn;e heer of men|&thorn;at ofte seruen venus falli&thorn; and bredi&thorn; ballidnes litil &amp; litil.... And if a|man is withoute hed-her, he is i-holde &thorn;e more vnhonest.</I>"</NOTE> &para; &THORN;e
<PB N="188">|cause whi &thorn;at maki&thorn; a man ballid ben &thorn;ese / as whanne &thorn;e skyn|recchi&thorn; along, &amp; if his bodi be drie &amp; &thorn;inne &amp; his skyn hoot, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou must do &thorn;is cure / Take olium mirtinum &amp; olium de mastice|ou&thorn;er olium ladani, &amp; anointe &thorn;erwith his heed.  &amp; if &thorn;e tyme of|&thorn;e &yogh;eer be coold, &thorn;ou muste anointe him wi&thorn; olium de spica //|&para; Whanne a mannes heeris falli&thorn; awei so in vnkyndeli tyme, as &thorn;e|while he is &yogh;ong, &thorn;an make him a ba&thorn; &amp; anoynte him wi&thorn; camomille|&amp; wi&thorn; bittir<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>butir</I>.  MS. 12. C. XIV, fol. 32 bk.: cum amigdalis amaris.</NOTE> almondis &amp; wi&thorn; oile maad &thorn;erof // If a man|bicome ballid for cause &thorn;at his skyn is to neische, &thorn;ese ben &thorn;e|signys &thorn;erof as whanne a man ha&thorn; fewe heeris &amp; sotil / &thorn;anne take|olium mirtinum &amp; olium masticis wi&thorn; oilio laurino, &amp; herwith anointe|his heed, whanne hise heeris ben schauen awei // &para; Item, take|capilli veneris, ladani ana, grinde hem &amp; medle hem with wijn &amp;| with olio mirtino / If a mannes heed be waischen <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="113a">herwi&thorn;, it wole|make hise heeris longe &amp; make hem sitte faste / Also take water|&thorn;at bletis ben soden yn &amp; a litil mustard, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; waische hise|heeris &amp; after anointe him wi&thorn; oile // &para; Also to make heeris &thorn;at &thorn;e|falle not / take leuys of mirte &amp; sette hem in water til &thorn;e watir|&thorn;erof bicome al troubly &thorn;an take <ABBR EXPAN="[pound]">li</ABBR> .j of &thorn;e water &amp; olium enfantini|or of oile &thorn;at is vnripe &amp; medle hem togidere.  &amp; &thorn;an se&thorn;e hem til|&thorn;e water waaste awei, &amp; &thorn;anne caste &thorn;erto canel &amp; ladanum grounden|&amp; resolued in wijn, &amp; make herof an oynement &amp; anointe herwi&thorn; &thorn;e|rotis of &thorn;e heeris /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>Of litil pustulis &thorn;at wexi&thorn; in a mannes face or in|children hedis /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat., Add. 26,106, fol. 47: "pustule parue que nascuntur in capite|fronte et facie puerorum."</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Saphati ben litil pustule &thorn;at wexi&thorn; in a mannes heed &amp; in|children forhedis &amp; her face, &amp; principali in wommens facis, &amp;|also in mennys facis &thorn;at ben moist, &amp; maki&thorn; sumtyme crustis / For|to cure &thorn;is passioun, here &thorn;ou schalt haue a good medicyn of .G.|&thorn;at is aforseid of aischis of cucurbite &amp; argilla // &para; Children moun|be holpen &thorn;erof if her norice absteyne hir fro salt metis &amp; scharpe|&amp; fro strong wijn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Salic., lib. I., cap. 2, Sl. 6, fol. 55 b.: "<I>This seknesse is not|bred but in children, when &thorn;ei souken, and it ys clepid a crost, and it ys|mad in hem in &thorn;e forhed and in &thorn;e hede.... The cure of it ys &thorn;at euery|day &thorn;e place most be anointed with oyle of camomille hoot.  And &thorn;e noryse|absteine hyre fro flesses, and fro chese, and fro scharp metis.</I>"</NOTE>, &amp; &thorn;e child schal be ba&thorn;id in a decoccioun of
<PB N="189">|camomile <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="113b">&amp; rosis &amp; fenigreci, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt anointe &thorn;e place wi&thorn; |oile of camomille hoot // &para; Furfurea ben a maner of squamis .i.|schellis &thorn;at come&thorn; of brennyng &thorn;at is in &thorn;e skyn; if &thorn;ei be frotid|wel wi&thorn; a manys nailis, &thorn;ei wolen falle awei, &amp; sumtyme &thorn;ei ben li&yogh;t|&amp; wolen falle awei wi&thorn; &thorn;e heeris, whanne &thorn;ei ben schaue &amp; wi&thorn;|waischingis of hoot water / If &thorn;is suffise not &thorn;erfore, anoynte his|heed with an oynement maad of farina ciceris &amp; &thorn;e seed of malowe|uisci temperid with vinegre / If it be not remeued herwi&thorn;, anoynte|him wi&thorn; &thorn;is oynement // Take farine ciceris .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iij, farine fenigreci,|sulphuris viui, nitri croci,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>croci</I>, for <I>crossi</I>.</NOTE> sinapis ana .&yogh; .iiij., tempere hem wi&thorn;|vinegre and watir /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>Of cloo&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cloo&thorn;</I>, translated from Pannus.  Lat.: De pannis, cossis et gutta rosacea|et de lentiginibus et cicatricibus vulnerum.</NOTE> &thorn;at is clepid fraclis or goute roset.</HEAD>
<P>Pannus is a superfluite &thorn;at falli&thorn; in a wommans face, &amp; come&thorn;|ofte in childberyng, &amp; also whanne hir menstrue is wi&thorn;holde,|&amp; is as it were a maner ledi<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ledi</I>, from "lead."  Lat. lividus.</NOTE> colour or purpur, &amp; sumtyme it is|medlid myche wi&thorn; blak, &amp; it come&thorn; alwei of malancolious matere.|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt first purge &thorn;e matere with a decoccioun of epithimi &amp;|gotis whey, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="114a">he leue metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn;|malancoly, &amp; &thorn;anne take seed of raphani in a newe lynnen cloo&thorn;, |bittir almoundis, mele of benis, seed of melonum &amp; curcurbite,|stampe hem alle togidere &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; water &amp; dissolue a litil|safron &amp; hony &amp; make &thorn;erof an oynement, &amp; herwi&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt|anoynte hir face at euen late, &amp; amorowe &thorn;ou schalt waische hir|face with a colature of bran // &para; If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;is passioun be|oold, &thorn;anne &thorn;ow schalt make a stronger oynement wi&thorn; &thorn;e same|oynement, &amp; do &thorn;erto eruca &thorn;e seed &thorn;erof, &amp; argentum viuum|slayn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>slay</I>, Lat. extinguere, precipitate.  Comp. H. G. Niederschlag.</NOTE> wi&thorn; spotil, &amp; pepir &amp; mirre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mirre</I>, mistaken from Lat. <I>nitro</I>.</NOTE> &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; oximel, &amp;|sumtyme it is nede to sette vpon &thorn;e place watir lechis. &amp; after|&thorn;at anoynte it wi&thorn; &thorn;e poudre of catapucie<NOTE PLACE="foot">catapucie.  Add. 15,236, fol. 74 bk.: "<I>Catapucia, semen spurge, catapuste,|spurge sed.</I>"  The original meaning "a medicinal preparation" is|shown in Aelfr. Gloss.: "<I>Catapodia, a swylfende drenc</I>."  Compare <I>N. E. D.</I>|s. v. catapuce.</NOTE> &amp; staphisagre temperid
<PB N="190">|with hony // &para; Also a medicyn of A. for &thorn;is passioun / Take argenti|viui .&yogh; j. <ABBR>gm</ABBR> amigdalarum <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> ij. medle hem togidere &amp; stampe hem|til &thorn;ou se no&thorn;ing of &thorn;e quik siluer, &amp; do &thorn;erto seed of melonis|maad clene .&yogh; iij., stampe alle &thorn;ese togidere &amp; anoynte herwi&thorn; hir| face aneue &amp; amorowe; waische hir face wi&thorn; watir <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="114b">&thorn;at violet ha&thorn;|leye &thorn;eron / Lentigines<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Lentigo</I>, a Pimple, or Freckle; a small red Spot in the Face, or other|Part, resembling a Lentil."&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> ben purgid wi&thorn; a strong purgacioun &amp; wi&thorn;|a strong medicyn &thorn;at ben forseid for pannum //</P>
<P>&para; Cossi<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gulielm. de Salic., lib. I., cap. 63, Sl. 277, fol. 12, mentions as skindiseases:|<I>&thorn;e ampte, &thorn;e teter</I> and <I>&thorn;e ryngworm</I>.  Dunglison identifies the|ringworm with <I>cossi</I>, deriving it from Lat. cossis, or cossus, <I>m</I>., a worm that|breeds in wood.  The description given by Gul. de Sal. differs entirely from|Lanfranc's description of <I>cossi</I>.</NOTE> ben litil pustulis &amp; harde &thorn;at ben engendrid in &thorn;e face,|&amp; principali aboute &thorn;e [nose],<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nose</I>, omitted in MS., but space left free.  <I>Dubium</I> in margin refers to|it.  Lat. circa nasum.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ei maki&thorn; &thorn;e place reed, &amp; &thorn;erfore|&thorn;is medicyn is good.  &rx;, sulphuris viui .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, &amp; make it to sutil|poudre, &amp; leie it in a pound of watir of ro. in a glasen vessel, &amp;|stoppe wel the mou&thorn; &thorn;erof, &amp; hange it in &thorn;e sunne in &thorn;e mon&thorn;e of|Iulij &amp; august bi xv. daies, &amp; euery dai &thorn;ou schalt meue &thorn;e vessel, &amp;|with &thorn;is watir &thorn;ou schalt anoynte his face &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;e passioun is //</P>
<P>&para; Gutta rosacea,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. VII., cap. 65, Add. 27,944, fol. 100 b.: "<I>And nurphea|is al in &thorn;e skynne, &amp; lepra in &thorn;e fleische &amp; in &thorn;e skynne; &thorn;is infcctioun is|but litil diuers from infeccioun &thorn;at hatte gutta rosea, &thorn;at infecti&thorn; &thorn;e face|wi&thorn; smale pymples, and come&thorn; of a gleymy &amp; a MS. &amp; bloody &amp; colerik|humours, &thorn;at ben bytwene felle and fleische</I>."  Sl. 563, fol. 17 b.: "<I>&thorn;o rose|goute.</I>"  Gutta rosacea vel rosea, Rosy Drop or Whelk.  (Dunglison.)</NOTE> &thorn;at is a passioun &thorn;at turne&thorn; &thorn;e skyn of a|mannys face out of his propur colour &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e face reed.  &amp; &thorn;is|passioun come&thorn; of humouris brent &amp; abidi&thorn; in &thorn;e skyn, &amp; herfore|is a good purgacioun &thorn;at purgi&thorn; salt humouris. &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e medicyn /|&rx;, litargiri, auripigmenti, sulphuris viui, viridis eris ana<NOTE PLACE="foot">The dose is omitted, so it is in Add. 16,106, fol. 47 b.  Prints: unc. 1.</NOTE> &amp; poudre of|litil meis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>meis</I>, "mice."  Lat. pulveris parvorum suricum.  <I>meis</I> is probably an|error for <I>miis</I>.</NOTE> brent, &amp; of &thorn;is poudre half so miche as of alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere.| &amp; &thorn;is schal be poudrid wi&thorn; .ij. partis of trifolij <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="115a">&amp; &thorn;e .iiij. part of|swynys grese freisch, &amp; make of alle &thorn;ese an oynement.  &amp; on euen|anoynte herwi&thorn; his face, &amp; amorowe waische his face wi&thorn; a decoccioun|of semina frigidorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fin</I>.</NOTE> &amp; wi&thorn; a litil campher, &amp; &thorn;an make his|face clene, &amp; &thorn;an anoynte his face wi&thorn; olio tartarino,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>The translator has omitted the prescription of oleum tartarinum, given|in the Lat. Original.  It is written by a later hand on the margin of lf. 114,|bk.: "<I>oylle off tarter.  &rx;, tarter off whyt wyn made in pouder temperd wt|venygre as past, bynde yt in a clothe &amp; put yt under embers, to yt be welle|brent; &thorn;an put yt in a ston pot with an holle benethe.  &amp; &thorn;is ys oylle off|tarter.</I>"</P><P>Two prescriptions, which are not in the Lat. Original, are added on the|same place:</P><P>"<I>aqua pro guta rosacha: &rx;, lytargiri, argenty viui ana <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij, acety alby|li. i, boyll yt to conschoun</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">consumption.</NOTE> <I>in an erthen veselle, let stande &amp; clere &amp; keep yt.</I>"</P><P>"<I>&rx;. salt ar. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> i, saltpeter <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> i, salt comun <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> i, clere water <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>|iiij, mixte|togeder with ye sexte part off a <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> off camffer, let colle, put thes ij|waters togeder.</I>"</P></NOTE> &amp; al &thorn;e
<PB N="191">|remenaunt herof &thorn;ou schalt do of &thorn;is cure &amp; fulfille wi&thorn; medicyns|as it is aforseid / ad pannum /</P>
<P>&para; Cicatrices vulnerum ben remeued wi&thorn; litargirum nutricum, &amp;|is good for manie maner &thorn;ingis, for it doi&thorn; awei wennys, and it doi&thorn;|awei scharpnes of &thorn;e browis &amp; gendri&thorn; good fleisch in woundis &amp;|freti&thorn; awei wickid fleisch, &amp; is maad in &thorn;is maner / Take litarge &amp;|grinde it sotilli in a morter &amp; caste &thorn;erto a litil vinegre &amp; &thorn;anne|a litil oile of ro., &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt do til it come to a perfit|oynement /<NOTE PLACE="foot">The following prescription, translated from the Lat. Original, is written|by a later hand on the margin of leaf 115: "<I>Item gos gres &amp; dow &amp; diaculum,|alle sycatryues it rectyfyes.</I>"</NOTE></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>Of icchinge &amp; smertynge<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>smertyng</I>, Lat. pruritus.&mdash;Prurigo, emertung, Wr. W., 114. 3.&mdash;<I>emertung</I>,|is probably a mistake for <I>smertung</I>, to O.E. <I>smeortan</I>.</NOTE> and scabbe.</HEAD>
<P>Icchinge &amp; scabbe come&thorn; of salt humouris, &amp; a mannys kynde|ha&thorn; abhominacioun &thorn;erof, &amp; putte&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>putte</I>.</NOTE> hem out of &thorn;e skyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. VII., cap. 62, Add. 27,944, fol. 99: "<I>Schabbe is|corrupcioun of &thorn;e skynne, &amp; come&thorn; of corrupt humours &thorn;at be&thorn; bytwene felle|and fleissche, &amp; hurti&thorn; &amp; greue&thorn; &amp; defouli&thorn; &thorn;e body.  For as Constantine|sei&thorn;, kynde putti&thorn; out euel humours to &thorn;e vttir parties of &thorn;e body to clense|and to purge &thorn;e inner parties.</I>"</NOTE> &amp;|&thorn;is falli&thorn; ofte of salt metis &amp; scharpe metis &amp; of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="115b">wijn &thorn;at |is strong; &amp; it falli&thorn; ofte to hem &thorn;at waki&thorn; &amp; traueili&thorn; &amp;|vsi&thorn; no ba&thorn;ing &amp; weri&thorn; no lynnen clo&thorn;is, &amp; &thorn;is is oon of &thorn;e|siknes &thorn;at is contagious, for o man mai take it of ano&thorn;er / &THORN;is maner|sijknesse come&thorn; sumtyme of blood, sumtyme of fleume, sumtyme of|colre, sumtyme of malancolie / Also scabbe, sum is drie &amp; summe|is wet / If it be drie, it schal propirli be clepid icche / And if it be|moist, it schal be clepid scabbe / To &thorn;e cure herof &thorn;ou schalt avoide|salt fleume, &thorn;ou schalt defie &thorn;e matere wi&thorn; &thorn;is sirup / &rx;, abstinthij,
<PB N="192">|abrotani, cuscute, fumus terre, ana <ABBR EXPAN="[drop]"><GAP></ABBR> .j., &amp; take xx. damascenes &amp;|xij. figis, &amp; vj. datis, sene <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, thimi, epithimi .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., se&thorn;e hem wel|in l&imacr; iij of water &amp; l&imacr; j. of vinegre til &thorn;ei come to l&imacr; j. &amp; d&imacr;.  cole|hem &amp; do &thorn;erto iuys of fumi terre &amp; sugur l&imacr; .j. &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, &amp; make &thorn;erof|a sirup &amp; herwi&thorn; defie &thorn;e matere / &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt purge him wi&thorn;|&thorn;ese pelottes, &rx;, aloes optimi, cortices mirabolani, citrini, ana .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j|stampe hem &amp; tempere hem with iuys maad of fumi terre, til &thorn;ei|be &thorn;icke as it were hony, &amp; lete it drie til &thorn;er mai be maad gobetis| &thorn;erof &amp; maad &thorn;erof pelottis, &amp; herof &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="116a">wei&yogh;te of|ij. &yogh;. at oonys, &amp; &thorn;is medicyne mai be rehersid ofte.  &para; Also blood|leting is good &thorn;erfore, if o&thorn;ere particlis acordi&thorn; &thorn;erfore // &para; Also gotis|whey is good &thorn;erfore, in which be leid mirabolani wi&thorn; sugre, &amp; ofte|take, for &thorn;at clensi&thorn; miche, &amp; is maad in &thorn;is maner / In l&imacr; .j of gotis|whey leie <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j. of mirabolani citrini powdrid an eue, on &thorn;e morowe|heete hem &amp; cole hem &amp; do &thorn;erto <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .j of sugre ro. // &para; If it be drie|scabbe, hoot watir is good for to ba&thorn;e him ynne, in which is soden|fumi terre &amp; enula, lappacij acuti, &amp; in &thorn;e ba&thorn; anoynte him with|oile of ro. &amp; iuys of ache &amp; vinegre, &amp; herwith his bodi schal be|wel frotid in &thorn;e ba&thorn; ou&thorn;er in a stewe // &para; Also an oyment &thorn;at rasis|made for &thorn;e scabbe &thorn;at is drie / &rx; salis communis, salis gemme,|ellebori, nigri costi, <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .j., picis liquide <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> vj., olium violarum &amp; aceti,|&amp; herof make an oynement / &amp; anoynte herwi&thorn; in his stewe &amp; frote|him wel, &amp; aftir lete him be &thorn;erinne by an hour, &amp; aftir ba&thorn;e him|in a decoccioun of bran &amp; lappacij acuti, enule campane<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>compare</I>.</NOTE> &amp; arthemisie|// &para; If &thorn;e scabbe be moist / &thorn;an make an oynement of rasis /|&rx;, argenti viui extincti, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="116b">&amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt sle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sle</I> = slay.  See p. 189, Note 6.</NOTE> it: leie it| in a peuter disch &amp; spete &thorn;eron, &amp; frote it wi&thorn; mannes heeris, &amp; do|&thorn;erto: whit litarge, elleborum nigrum, alumen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alumen</I>, on margin.</NOTE> vetus, oleandrum ana,|grynde alle &thorn;ese togidere &amp; tempere hem with vinegre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>The following passage omitted by the translator is written on the|bottom of lf. 116, bk., by a later hand: "<I>&amp; olio communi miscantur de quo|totum corpus unguatur in cero, mane intret stupyam et cum sudaueret|ffricet corpus cum usne et aceto. vsne .i. mosse off the oke.</I>"</P><P><I>usne</I>, Arab ouchna.  See <I>Littre-Devic</I>.&mdash;"Usnea, a kind of green Moss|which grows upon Humane Sculls that have been lying in the open Air for|some years, and which is used in Physick."&mdash;Phillips.</P></NOTE> &amp; herwi&thorn; al|his bodi schal be anoyntid at euen, &amp; at morowe he schal be stewid,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he schal be stewid</I>, Lat. intret stupham.  See Skeat, <I>Etym. Dict.</I>,|s. v. stew.</NOTE>|and whanne he sweti&thorn; his bodi schal be frotid wi&thorn; vinegre // &para; Also
<PB N="193">|a&yogh;en scabbe &amp; icching, first lete &thorn;e pacient blood, &amp; make him &thorn;is|oynement / &rx;, sulphuris viui &amp; <ABBR>tm</ABBR><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>tm</I>, tantum.  This prescription is neither in the prints nor in Add.|26,106, but preserved in Roy. MS. 12 C XIV, fol. 33 b.</NOTE> de sale &amp; tartaro, grinde hem|wel togidere til it bicome in &thorn;e maner of an oynement, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is|oynement anoynte &thorn;e pacient, &amp; &thorn;is wole delyuere him fro icching //|&para; Also if &thorn;e pacient haue greet brennyng &amp; greet icching, &thorn;anne|anoynte al his bodi wi&thorn; oile of ro. &thorn;at ben good, &amp; lete him reste|so .vij. daies // &para; Also for &thorn;e same cause / &rx; succus affodillorum &amp;|distempere it wi&thorn; whit hony &amp; anoynte him herwith, whanne he|goi&thorn; out of his stewe; for &thorn;is oynement doi&thorn; awey fil&thorn;e of &thorn;e skyn|and clensi&thorn; myche /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>Of morphue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>morphue</I>.  See p. 187, Note 2.  N.E. morphew, Med. L. morphea, Fr.|morph&eacute;e, Ital. morfea, is probably the Latinized form of an Arab. past part.|marfu, connected with marf, 'thin.'  See <I>Lane Lex</I>., p. 1132.</P><P>The derivation given by Tommas: <GAP DESC="Greek">, is unsatisfactory.  Phillips:|"Morphew, a kind of white Scurf upon the Body, from the French Word|<I>Mort-feu</I>, i. e. dead Fire; because it looks like the white Sparks that fall from|a Brand extinguished."</P></NOTE> and impetigine<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>De propr. rer., lib. VII., cap. 63, Add. 27,944, fol. 99: "<I>And &thorn;is euel|hatte impetigo, for it letti&thorn; and greue&thorn; &thorn;e skyn and &thorn;e fleissch, namliche with|tikelinge and icchinge.  Also &thorn;is euel hatte serpigo, as it were a crepinge euel,|for it crepi&thorn; into &thorn;e skynne al aboute as it were a serpent o&thorn;ir an addre, &amp;|infecti&thorn; &thorn;e skynne and defoule&thorn; it wi&thorn; smale skales aftir cracchinge and|clawinge.</I>"</P><P>Lib. VII., cap. 65, fol. 100: "<I>Morphea is speckes in &thorn;e skynne, and come&thorn;|of corrupcioun of mete and drinke, and what is lepre in &thorn;e fleische is morphea|in &thorn;e skynne.  Also som morphea is white &amp; come&thorn; of fleume, &amp; som is blak &amp;|come&thorn; of malencolia, &amp; som is red &amp; come&thorn; of colera o&thorn;ir of blood.</I>"</P></NOTE> //</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="117a">Now we han medycyns drawen of .ij. wellis &amp; of manie |maistris, &thorn;at is to wite: of Salerne, &amp; of Costantyn, &amp;|Platearij, &amp; of Iohannes de sancto Paulo &amp; of o&thorn;ere manie auctouris,|as of Ipocras, Galien, &amp; Serapion, &amp; Isaac, &amp; Iohanne[s] Mesue,|Auicen / Hali &thorn;e abbot, &amp; Rasis, &amp; of o&thorn;ere manie auctouris / Alle|&thorn;ese auctouris speciali &yogh;eue it us, saue &thorn;ei acorden not in names /|<SUP>5</SUP>Forwhi impetigo, serpigo &amp; morphea ben seid in salerne diuers|names, for &thorn;at men of salerne clepen albam &amp; arabes clepen impetigo|morphea / &amp; men of salerne clepen morpheam / men in|arabie clepen it albarec /<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>5&mdash;5</SUP> The passage is corrupt.  Lat.: Nam serpigo, impetigo, morphea sumuntur|aliter apud salernitanos aliter apud arabes.  Quod enim salernitani vocant|serpiginem, arabes vocant alunda.  Et impetigo apud arabes est morphea, et|apud salernitanos aliter et aliter apud nos.  Quod autem Salernitani vocant|morpheam, arabes vocant albaras.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;erfore I wole in &thorn;is book teche &thorn;e
<PB N="194">|difference of euery of hem, &amp; after &thorn;at &thorn;e curis of hem / &amp; I|seie &thorn;at serpigo is a scharpnes of a mannes skyn, &amp; it is clepid|serpigo, for it passi&thorn; fro place to place.  &THORN;ou schalt cure it wi&thorn;|gumme of cheritrees distemperid wi&thorn; vinegre, ou&thorn;er gumme of| plumtre &amp; anoynte wi&thorn; buttir &amp; turbentyne.  &amp; &thorn;is oynement is|good &thorn;erfore / Take gres <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="117b">of a doke clene purid, ysopi humide, olium|ro., &yogh;elow wex, terbentyne, mussilaginis seminis citoniorum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Citonia</I> = Cydonia, quince.</NOTE> ana,|make of alle &thorn;ese an oynement, &amp; anoynte him &thorn;erwith amorowe,|&amp; &thorn;anne waische him in watir &thorn;at &thorn;er ha&thorn; leie &thorn;eron semen melonum|&amp; violet.  &amp; be he ofte ba&thorn;id wi&thorn; sich swete water.  &amp; good|swete mete is good for hem &thorn;at engendri&thorn; good humouris //</P>
<P>&para; Impetigo is ano&thorn;er maner passioun, as whanne a mannys|skyn chaungi&thorn; in o&thorn;er colour &thorn;an it schulde, &amp; propirli into whit|colour &amp; wi&thorn;outen ony harmyng of &thorn;e skyn.  &amp; &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing|&thorn;eron &thorn;at harme&thorn; a man, saue oonly &thorn;e colour of &thorn;e skyn chaungi&thorn;|o&thorn;ir &thorn;an it schulde be //<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. Add. 16,106, fol. 48 bk.: et non peccat ibi nisi color.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; Morphea is a passioun &thorn;at &thorn;e skyn is out of his propir colour|&amp; &thorn;e skyn is harmed &thorn;erbi.  &amp; morphea is a spice of lepre &thorn;at sitt|in &thorn;e skyn; for ri&yogh;t as lepre sitti&thorn; in &thorn;e fleisch, in &thorn;e same maner|ri&yogh;t so morphea sitti&thorn; in &thorn;e skyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Not in the Lat. Origin.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; Albaras.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Albaras</I>, Arab. al-baras, leprosy.  Compare <I>Avicenna</I>, lib. 4, fen. 7,|tract. 3, cap. 9, and ff.</NOTE>  Not oonly &thorn;e skyn, saue &thorn;e fleisch is harmed &thorn;erbi /|&THORN;is is &thorn;e difference of albaras &amp; morphea / In morphea &thorn;e vertu of| expulcion<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>expulsif</I>.  Lat.: virtus expulsiua.</NOTE> is strong / &amp; &thorn;e mater <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="118a">&thorn;erof is but litil, &amp; &thorn;erfore it is|al putt into &thorn;e skyn / In albaras &thorn;e vertu of expulcion is but feble &amp;|&thorn;e matere is corrupt, &amp; &thorn;erfor it is bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e fleisch &amp; in &thorn;e skyn,|&amp; &thorn;er is but litil difference bitwixe albaras &amp; lepre, saue albaras|abidi&thorn; alwei in oon place, &amp; lepre goi&thorn; into al &thorn;e bodi / In bo&thorn;e|&thorn;ese causis it is nede for to avoide humouris &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e cause<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>humouris &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e cause</I>.  Lat.: Conveniunt in hoc quod omnis|humoris indigent enacuatione peccantis.  <I>N. E. Dict</I>. s. v. cause, q. b. gives|references for <I>to be in cause:</I> to be to blame.&mdash;<I>Littr&eacute; Dict</I>. (14th cent.) ils en|sont en cause.&mdash;Dufr. gives several references for <I>in causa esse:</I> to be ill, from|<I>Causa</I>, morbus.</NOTE>,
<PB N="195">|saue &thorn;at oon mote haue stronger medicyns &thorn;an &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  &para; Impetigo|muste haue abstynence fro &thorn;ingis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; fleume, &amp; he|muste haue a purgacioun for to purge fleume / Anoynte &thorn;e place|wi&thorn; oile of whete &thorn;at is maad in &thorn;is maner / Take whete &amp; leie|bitwixe two platis of iren hoot / &amp; presse hem togidere &amp; &thorn;erof|wole bicome oile // &para; Also in ano&thorn;er maner / Take .ij. vessels of|er&thorn;e, so &thorn;at &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e oon vessel go to &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e to&thorn;er|vessel, &amp; &thorn;at oon vessel schal stonde in &thorn;e er&thorn;e, &amp; in &thorn;e vessel|aboue &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;i whete, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt stoppe &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e|vessel &thorn;at is aboue &thorn;at &thorn;e whete is ynne with a plate of bras ou&thorn;er|of iren &thorn;at is bettere, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="118b">&amp; &thorn;e plate schal be ful of smale holis.  &amp; |&thorn;an &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;is pott schal be ioyned to &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e pott &thorn;at|is in &thorn;e er&thorn;e with good lute, &thorn;at &thorn;ere mowe noon eir out &thorn;erof.  &amp;|&thorn;an make a fier aboute &thorn;e pott &thorn;at is aboue &thorn;e er&thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;ere wole|distille oile into &thorn;e pott &thorn;at is bine&thorn;e in &thorn;e er&thorn;e, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is oile &thorn;ou|schalt anoynte &thorn;e place ofte, &amp; frote harde.  &amp; if &thorn;is suffise not,|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt sette vpon &thorn;e place watir lechis ofte, for to do|awey &thorn;e fleumatik blood / If &thorn;is suffise not, leie &thorn;ervpon a mundificatif|of cantarides stampid wi&thorn; whete, til &thorn;e place schyne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>til &thorn;e place schyne</I>, donec locus excorietur.</NOTE>, &amp;|&thorn;an cure it vp wi&thorn; an oynment of ceruce / Frote him wi&thorn; an oynement|maad of armoniac &amp; with &thorn;e sournes of citri, &amp; nitro is|good &thorn;erfore //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e white morphu is curid wi&thorn; purgacioun &thorn;at purgi&thorn; roten|fleume, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is special medicyn / &rx;, trifere minorum .&yogh; .iiij.,|turbit, pulueris pigre .&yogh; .ij., colloquintide .&yogh; ij., make herof|pelottis|wi&thorn; hony, &amp; he schal take &thorn;erof .iij pelottis euery wike, &amp; eueri|dai bitwixe he schal take .&yogh; ij. of trifere minorum, &amp; he mote|absteyne him fro metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="119a">fleume; &amp; &thorn;e place shal be |frotid in &thorn;e sunne wi&thorn; an oynement of tapsia, &amp; &thorn;e seed of raphani,|rubie maioris / elleboro nigro &amp; mustard, &amp; distempere hem wi&thorn;|vinegre / Also froting wi&thorn; squillis is good &thorn;erfore //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e blac morphe is curid wi&thorn; ofte purging of malancoli, wi&thorn;|gotis whei, &amp; wi&thorn; epithimo, &amp; o&thorn;ere medicyns &thorn;at purgi&thorn; malancolie,|&thorn;at be forseid in allopucia; &amp; his dietyng schal be moist, &amp;|he schal absteyne him fro metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; malancolie, &amp; he|schal be ba&thorn;id ofte in swete watir, &amp; he schal be anoyntid &amp; frotid|as it is aforseid //</P>
<P>&para; Albaras &thorn;at is whit is curid wi&thorn; &thorn;e same &thorn;ingis &amp; with
<PB N="196">|stronger medicyns &thorn;at ben aforseid in &thorn;e cure of &thorn;e white morphu,|&amp; miche castyng is good for hem, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt frote wel &thorn;e place|with squillis in a stewe, &amp; after &thorn;at sprynge &thorn;eron poudre maad of|tapsia, &amp; staphisagre, &amp; &thorn;e wombis of cantarides, &amp; seed of eruce,|&amp; tordis of a culuere, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt anoynte him wi&thorn; blood of a|blac serpent, for &thorn;at is bi propirte good &thorn;erfore /</P>
<P>Albaras &thorn;at is blak is incurable, for it is a particuler lepre, &amp;| but <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="119b">if it be so &thorn;at it mowe be take awei wi&thorn; alle rootis, it schal|neuere be curid; saue &thorn;e colour of his skyn mai be amendid / &rx;,|aloxanti, &thorn;at is &thorn;e flour of &thorn;e wi&thorn;i,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. aloxantum, quod est flos salis.  The translator read <I>salicis</I> for <I>salis</I> , <GAP DESC="Greek">,|brine.  Matth. Sylv.: "Alosantus i. flos salis et invenitur|super petras nili fluminis."</NOTE> mirram, feces of wijn brent,|reed cley, &amp; alyme, poudre alle &thorn;ese, &amp; herwi&thorn; frote &thorn;e place til &thorn;e|pacient fele prickyng &amp; brennyng.  &THORN;is wole deye &thorn;e skyn for|manie daies, &amp; whanne &thorn;is faili&thorn; reherse it a&yogh;en.</P>
