<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<HEAD>// Of lepre and of &thorn;e domys of lepre<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. de lepra et indiciis leprosi  The translator read <I>iudiciis</I>.</NOTE> //</HEAD>
<P>Lepra<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 27,944, fol. 99 b.: "<I>Lepra meselrye is an universal corrupcioun of|membres &amp; of humours.</I> " Four different kinds of Leprosy are distinguished,|"1. the <I>&Eacute;laphantia</I>; 2. the <I>Tiria or Serpentyna, and ha&thorn; &thorn;at name of an|addre &thorn;at hatte tyrus, for as an addre leneth li&yogh;tliche his skynne and is skaly, so|he &thorn;at hath &thorn;is maner lepra is ofte i-strept and i-hulde, &amp; ful of skales;</I> 3. <I>alopicia|&amp; vulpina foxissch;</I> 4. <I>leonina, it freti&thorn; as a lyon &amp; destroye&thorn; all &thorn;e|membres.</I>"</NOTE> is a foul sijknes &thorn;at come&thorn; of malancolie corrupt, ou&thorn;ir|of humouris &thorn;at ben brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e forme of malancolye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;</I> inserted.</NOTE>|corrupt.  &amp; it goi&thorn; into al &thorn;e bodi, ri&yogh;t as a cancre is in oon lyme|of a mannes bodi / For whanne malancolie multiplie&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>multiplie&thorn;</I>, Lat. multiplicatur.&mdash;Multiplye, fructificare, multiplicare.|<I>Cathol. Angl</I>., p. 246.</NOTE>, &amp; a mannes|guttis ben not strong for to putte it out, &amp; &thorn;e weies bitwixe &thorn;e|splene ben stoppid &amp; &thorn;e poris of &thorn;e skyn closid, &thorn;an malancolious|blood wole rote wi&thorn;inne, &amp; roti&thorn; complexiouns of &thorn;e lymes.  &amp; &thorn;e|bigynnying of &thorn;e mater my&yogh;te be of blood ou&thorn;ir of fleume, colre,| ou&thorn;er of malancolie, ne&thorn;eles whanne &thorn;e mater is fulfild <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="120a">it is malancolie|corrupt.  &amp; &thorn;is is oon of the syknessis &thorn;at ben contagious /|&para; In &thorn;is place I wole sette curis of lepre &thorn;at ben profitable for a|cirurgian to kunne, &amp; also curis &thorn;at come&thorn; ofte to a cirurgian|handis /</P>
<P>
<PB N="197">Men &thorn;at ben leprous,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The symptoms of leprosy are similarly described by Avicenna, lib. IV.,|fen. 3, tract. 2, cap. 2.</NOTE> in &thorn;e bigynnyng her heeris of her heed|falli&thorn; awei, &amp; &thorn;e heeris of her browis, &amp; &thorn;e heeris of her berd; &amp;|her forheed bicome&thorn; reed &amp; as it were schynyng.  &para; Also in|summe &thorn;e face wexi&thorn; reed &amp; swelli&thorn; &amp; is sumwhat ledi, &amp; principali|aboute [&thorn;e nose]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e nose</I>, wanting.</NOTE> // &para; Also her vois is row&yogh; ou&thorn;er sumtyme|it is wondirly scharp, &amp; &thorn;e whit of her i&yogh;en bicome&thorn; al derk, &amp; &thorn;e|heeris goon awei of her browis / Her nose&thorn;rillis bicome&thorn; smal,|ou&thorn;er wondirly greet, &amp; her nose&thorn;rillis ben streit for to drawe yn|wijnd, &amp; her nailis bicome&thorn; ledi / Also her bree&thorn; wole stynke &amp;|her sotes / Also her pisce wole be streit<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her pisce wole be streit</I>, Lat. item accidit eis strictura pectoris.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ei schulen haue greet|snesyng / Also &thorn;ei wilne&thorn; myche to comne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>comne</I> for <I>comune</I>.</NOTE> wi&thorn; wommen / Also|&thorn;ei schulen be heuy, &amp; if her skyn be in &thorn;e coold eir, it wole bicome|as it were &thorn;e skyn of a gandir <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="120b">&thorn;at &thorn;at hise fe&thorn;eris weren pilid |awey / Also &thorn;ese ben priuy &thorn;ingis: if &thorn;ou prickist his leg bihynde,|he ne schal not fele it / &amp; if &thorn;ou waisschist hise lymes in watir,|anoon ri&yogh;t it wole drie yn // Also &thorn;ese signes ben comoun: his|y&yogh;en wolen bicome rounde, &amp; &thorn;er wolen wexe pustulis in his tunge,|&amp; her nailis wolen bicome greet, &amp; &thorn;er wolen wexe scabbis aboutefor&thorn;.|And &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;at schulde be bitwixe &thorn;e &thorn;ombe &amp; &thorn;e nexte|fyngir &thorn;erto schal be wastid awey, &amp; if &thorn;ou prickist him in &thorn;e hele|he schal not fele it, &amp; if he be lete blood, her blood wole be|scharpe &amp; as it were ful of grauel.  &amp; if &thorn;ou waischist her blood,|in &thorn;e botme &thorn;erof wole leue as it were grauel.  &amp; &thorn;is sijknes aftir|&thorn;e tyme &thorn;at it is confermed is incurable, saue in &thorn;e firste bigynnyng|it mai be curid wel //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e cure of lepre is not sett in &thorn;is book, for &thorn;is book is of|cirurgie, saf &thorn;er ben in &thorn;is solempne medicyns &amp; apreued for to|kepe a man, &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulen not wexe, &amp; for to make it priuy, &amp;|cauterijs &thorn;erfore / For alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis falli&thorn; for a cirurgian / &THORN;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="121a">&thorn;ou |schalt knowe: if &thorn;e siknes be strong, it is hard for to do ony|medicyne &thorn;erto; fforwhi, if &thorn;e sijknes be strong, &thorn;anne he muste|haue stronge medicyns, &amp; &thorn;at were greet perel, &amp; also &thorn;e medicyn|muste be ofte rehersid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 49 b.: Scias quod in egritudinibus fortibus si fuerint|cronice fortes non competunt medicine, nam licet propter egritudinis fortitudinem|medicina sit nocciua tamen dari non debet, quia medicinam oportet sepius|iterari.</NOTE>  Saue &thorn;ou schalt chese a li&yogh;t medicyn &thorn;at
<PB N="198">|wole falle for to purge &thorn;e humour li&yogh;tli // A medicyn maad of gotis|whey wi&thorn; epithimo, &thorn;is medicyn is ri&yogh;t &amp; good, for it purgi&thorn;|malancolie litil &amp; litil, &amp; also a man schal not be greued &thorn;erebi //|Pelottis &thorn;at be maad of epithimo &thorn;at ben aforseid in &thorn;e tretijs of|allopucia ben good herfore, for &thorn;in entent schal be oonly for to|purge malancolie &thorn;at is corrupt, &amp; amende his complexioun wi&thorn;|good dietyng.  Blood letyng is not good &thorn;erfore, but if &thorn;e cauce| come miche of blood / If his bree&thorn; be streit, &thorn;anne it come&thorn; of &thorn;e|veyne &thorn;at goi&thorn; to &thorn;e herte / Sumtyme it is in &thorn;e veyne of &thorn;e nose<NOTE PLACE="foot">Incorrect translation.  Add. 26,106, fol. 49 b: "Flebotomia namque|non convenit nisi quum scis lepram esse valde sanguineam cum hanelitus|strictura tunc fit de uena cordis et de duabus guides timendo suffocationem:|alia fit de venis nasi propter palliandum faciei colorem."</NOTE> /|&THORN;ou schalt &yogh;eue to men &thorn;at ben drie lepre &amp; come&thorn; myche of colre,|&thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him gotis whey ofte for to drynke, &amp; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="121b">&thorn;ou schalt, in|as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, make his complexioun moist &amp; ba&thorn;e him in|tempere ba&thorn; &amp; lete him swete &thorn;erinne; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt anoynte|him wi&thorn; oile of violet &amp; oile of cucurbita, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him|good metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; good blood, &amp; hese metis &amp; hise drinkis|schulen be in tempere heete, not to hoot ne to coold // &para; Summen|curi&thorn; hem wi&thorn; &thorn;e fleisch of a blac eddre<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., ibid. fol. 100: "<I>To hele o&thorn;ir to hide lepra as plato sei&thorn;,|best is a rede adder wi&thorn; a white wombe; &yogh;if &thorn;e venym is awaye &amp; &thorn;e tail &amp; &thorn;e|heed i-smyte of, &thorn;anne &thorn;e body i-sode in leke, &yogh;if it is ofte i-take &amp; i-ete; in &thorn;e|same wise wyne in &thorn;e whiche it rotie&thorn;, &yogh;if &thorn;e patient drinke ofte &thorn;erof, and &thorn;is|helpi&thorn; in many iueles, as he telle&thorn; of a blind mannes wif &thorn;at wolde slee here|housbonde, and &yogh;af him an addre with garlek in stede of an ele, &thorn;at it my&yogh;te slee|hym, &amp; he eet it, and aftir &thorn;at by moche swete he recouered &amp; had his si&yogh;t goode|&amp; clere.</I>"  The flesh of vipers is commended by Galen for the treatment of|elephantiasis.  Lib. II., Simpl. de carne viper&aelig;.</NOTE> &thorn;at ben in drie lond &amp;|among stones, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei kutten awey &thorn;e heed &amp; &thorn;e tail of &thorn;e eddre|&amp; doi&thorn; awei &thorn;e guttis wi&thorn;inne / &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei doon hem in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>, in margin.</NOTE> a vessel of|er&thorn;e wi&thorn; a litil peper &amp; galyngale &amp; salt &amp; vinegre &amp; watir &amp; oile,|&amp; so &thorn;ei se&thorn;e &thorn;e eddre til al &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;erof be dissolued.  &THORN;anne|&thorn;e bro&thorn; herof is &yogh;euen to drynke, &amp; &thorn;e fleisch for to ete til &thorn;e|pacient haue scotomiam<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scotomia</I>, <GAP DESC="Greek">, dizziness.  Vigo Interpret.: "They shoulde|saye Scotoma, and it is a disease, when darckenes ryseth before the eyes, and|when al thinges seme to go rounde about."</NOTE> &amp; al his bodi to-swolle / Whanne his bodi|is to-swolle &amp; he ha&thorn; had scotomiam, &thorn;an leie him in a bed &amp; lete|him ligge; &amp; if &thorn;ere falle ony &thorn;ing to him as syncopis, ou&thorn;er greet|cooldnes of hise lymes wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, or if his herte quake, &thorn;an &yogh;eue
<PB N="199">|him tiriaca maior wi&thorn; a litil musco ou&thorn;er hoot wijn // In &thorn;is maner|al his <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="122a">fleisch wole pile &amp; alle hise heeris wolen falle awei &amp; newe |heeris wolen come vp a&yogh;en / &amp; &thorn;is medicyne schal be rehersid so|ofte, &amp; kepid wi&thorn; dietyng til he be perfitli hool / Forwhi manie|men moun be delyuerid of manye greet sijknessis, if her leche is|kunnynge &amp; diligent aboute hem, &amp; bi necligence &amp; defaute of|help manie men ben perischid / Cauterijs herfore &thorn;ou schalt fynde|ynowe in &thorn;e chapiter of cauterijs, &amp; oynementis &thorn;at maki&thorn; clene &amp;|soudi&thorn;, all &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e antidotarie.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>&para; Of waastynge off membris and bicomen smal /</HEAD>
<P>A Mannes lyme bicome&thorn; smal wi&thorn; greet streynyng of ligaturis|&thorn;at taki&thorn; awei &thorn;e norisching of &thorn;e lyme, or of long akyng|of ioynt &thorn;at enfebli&thorn; al &thorn;e lyme / &THORN;ese &thorn;ingis maki&thorn; a mannes lymes|to bicome smal // &para; Also a mannes lymes bicome&thorn; greet o&thorn;er &thorn;an|&thorn;ei schulde be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. ingrossatur etiam membrum aliquod ultra debitum.  Compare <I>&thorn;e|colour ... chaungi&thorn; o&thorn;ir &thorn;an it schulde be</I>, p. 194, Note 3.</NOTE> whanne veynes ben feble &amp; matere falli&thorn; &thorn;erto &amp;|&thorn;e vertu of souding faili&thorn;, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e lyme swelli&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;e|mater is fleumatik, &amp; for defaute of heete it turne&thorn; not into|quitture <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="122b">saue it abidi&thorn; in &thorn;e lyme &amp; swelli&thorn; &thorn;e lyme / </P>
<P>&para; A lyme &thorn;at is bicome smal, in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt make it|greet: if &thorn;ere be ony &thorn;ing to take awei &thorn;erof as akynge ou&thorn;er ony|strictture, ou&thorn;er ony byndyng, &thorn;an remeue awey &thorn;at first in &thorn;e|manere as it schal be seid in &thorn;e chapiter of ioyntis.  Whanne &thorn;e|akynge is doon awei, &thorn;anne waische &thorn;e lyme wi&thorn; a decoccioun of|malowis &amp; violet &amp; rotis of bismalue in watir, saue his lyme schal|be in &thorn;e water no lenger &thorn;an it bigynne&thorn; for to bicome reed &amp; sumwhat|to swelle, &amp; be war &thorn;at his lyme be not so longe in &thorn;e water|til &thorn;at he swete, &amp; &thorn;an drie his lyme wi&thorn; a lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp; frote it|a litil wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond, &amp; &thorn;anne take a litil smal &yogh;erde &amp; bete &thorn;e lyme|&thorn;erwi&thorn; til &thorn;ou drawe blood &thorn;erto, &amp; make a plastre &thorn;erto in &thorn;is|maner.  &rx;, picis naualis, picis grece, resine albe ana, &amp; melte alle|&thorn;ese in a panne.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ei ben molten cole hem &thorn;oru&yogh; a cloo&thorn;|into coold water, &amp; &thorn;anne anoynte &thorn;in hondis with oile &amp; &thorn;an take|it vp of &thorn;e watir &amp; tempere it togidere &amp; make &thorn;erof gobetis &amp;|kepe hem for &thorn;in vss<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vse</I>.</NOTE>, herof &thorn;ou schalt plane vpon <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="123a">a le&thorn;er, &amp; |leie it to &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at is forseid, &amp; so lete it ligge adai, &amp; aneuen
<PB N="200">|drawe it awey, &amp; so lete &thorn;e lyme be til amorowe, &amp; &thorn;anne reherse|&thorn;e waischinge &thorn;at is forseid &amp; &thorn;e froting &amp; &thorn;e beting.  &THORN;is wi&thorn;outen|ony drede wole bringe [&thorn;e lyme] a&yogh;en to his greetnes as it schulde|be, but if &thorn;e lyme be out of ioynct &amp; haue be longe tyme, &thorn;an it|wole be hard, &thorn;an it is yuel to make &thorn;e lyme greet a&yogh;en as it|schulde.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; it mowe not be maad greet as it schulde be,|ne&thorn;eles bi &thorn;is maner it may be myche amendid //</P>
<P>&para; If a mannes lyme is gretter &thorn;an it schulde be, if &thorn;e cause|&thorn;erof be of fleume &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi neischenes of &thorn;e lyme,|for if &thorn;ou &thorn;riste yn &thorn;i fyngir, &thorn;er wol leue a pitt &thorn;erafter, it may be|brou&yogh;t a&yogh;en to greetnes &thorn;at it schulde be, if it be purgid ofte wi&thorn; a|medicyn &thorn;at is clepid trociscus de turbit &thorn;at is aforseid, &amp; &thorn;e pacient|schal kepe him fro alle metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; fleume, &amp; he schal be|war of greet replecioun of metis &amp; drinkis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt cure|him wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e chapiter of apostemes|of fleume / Take lye maad <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="123b">of aischis of wijn or of an ook, &amp; leie| &thorn;eron a double lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp; wete it wel, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; folde &thorn;e lyme,|&amp; &thorn;an streyne &thorn;e lyme wi&thorn; a boond, &amp; euery dai &thorn;ou schalt wete it|.ij. si&thorn;is in &thorn;at lie &amp; bynde so his lyme, &amp; in &thorn;is maner his lyme|schal drie.  Ou&thorn;er in &thorn;is maner / Take sal nitre &amp; distempere it|wi&thorn; watir, &amp; &thorn;anne take a sponge &thorn;at it be so myche &thorn;at it mowe|hile al &thorn;e lyme &amp; &thorn;an lete &thorn;e sponge drie so &thorn;ervpon, &amp; &thorn;an wete|&thorn;e sponge a&yogh;en &amp; leie it on &thorn;e lyme a&yogh;en, &amp; lete it drie a&yogh;en &amp;|alwei bynde wel &thorn;e lyme; &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou must do manye si&thorn;is.  Or take|&thorn;e leues of lilie celestie &amp; grynde hem wel and &thorn;anne leye it vpon|&thorn;e lyme, &amp; &thorn;anne bynde wel &thorn;e lyme, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e matere|wole waaste awey &amp; &thorn;e lyme wole bicome smal as it schulde / If it|so be &thorn;at &thorn;is greetnes come of malancolious blood or of greet|fleume, make him a purgacioun with gotis whey &amp; epithimo, or|ano&thorn;ir competent medicyn. &amp; first &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;e lyme neische|wi&thorn; oile of lilie, or wi&thorn; oon of &thorn;e oynementis &thorn;at ben mollificatiuis| &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="124a">schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, &thorn;anne go to &thorn;e cure &thorn;at is|forseid.  Whanne &thorn;e swellyng of &thorn;e lyme is doon aweie, if it be in|hond or in arme, &thorn;at falli&thorn; ofte tyme, or in &thorn;e foot &amp; in &thorn;e leggis &amp;|in &thorn;e knee, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt make bitwixe &thorn;e fyngris cauterijs &thorn;at|ben clepid cauterium cultellare, as &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e chapitre of|cauterijs // &THORN;e greetnes of a mannes foot &thorn;ou schalt cure as it schal|be seid in elephancia as it is conteyned in his propre chapitre /</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="2">

<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1"><PB N="201">
<HEAD>&THORN;e firste chapiter of engendering of humours &amp; &thorn;e|kindis of hem, &amp; conteyne&thorn; .xviij. chapiters /</HEAD>
<P>Everi enpostym is engendrid of .iiij. humouris, ou&thorn;ir of water,|or of wijnd.  &amp; it is impossible for a cirurgian for to kune|a cure, but if he knowe &thorn;e cause &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;erfore me &thorn;ou&yogh;te|&thorn;at it was necessarie for to make a propre chapitre of &thorn;e generacioun|of humouris<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. IV., cap. 6, Add. 27,944, fol. 33: "<I>&THORN;ise foure humores|be&thorn; i-bred in &thorn;is manere: whan mete is i-fonge in &thorn;e place of see&thorn;inge, &thorn;at is &thorn;e|stomak, first &thorn;e more sotil partie &amp; fletinge &thorn;erof, &thorn;at phisicians clepi&thorn; pthismaria,|&thorn;at is i-drawe be certeyn veynes to &thorn;e lyuore, &amp; &thorn;erby &thorn;e worchinge of|kinde hete it is i-chaungid into &thorn;e foure humoures; &thorn;e bredinge of hem bigynne&thorn;|in &thorn;e lyuer, but it endi&thorn; &thorn;ere atte fulle.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; alle &thorn;e propurtees &thorn;erof, &thorn;at &thorn;e redere of &thorn;is book|mai knowe &thorn;e causis of apostyms &amp; &thorn;e curis &thorn;erof &amp; metis &amp; drinkis|&thorn;at ben necessarie in &thorn;is cause for norisching &amp; augmenting <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="124b">of &thorn;e |lymes &amp; for to engendre natural heete / // Whanne &thorn;e mete falli&thorn;|into a mannes stomac &amp; &thorn;ou haddist anothamie &thorn;erof, &thorn;an in &thorn;e|stomak &thorn;e mete is soden, &amp; &thorn;an fro &thorn;e stomak it goi&thorn; into &thorn;e guttis,|&amp; &thorn;erof &thorn;ou haddist anothamiam, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e mete goi&thorn; anoon to &thorn;e|gutt &thorn;at is clepid orobum or &thorn;e sak.  Veynes &thorn;at ben clepid|miseraice &amp; &thorn;ere ben manie maners &thorn;erof as it is forseid, &amp; &thorn;ei ben|maad fast wi&thorn; &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e stomac &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e gutt &thorn;at is clepid|duodeno, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e smal gutt, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e gutt &thorn;at is clepid ieiunium|as it is forseid, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ese veynes bigynne&thorn; &thorn;e .ij. digestioun &amp;|beri&thorn; a veyne &thorn;at is clepid kilus<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator mistook <I>kilus</I> for the name of the Vein, perhaps in reference|to the <I>Vena cava</I>, called <I>Vena chillis</I> by the translators of Arab. medical|works, from <GAP DESC="Greek">.</NOTE> to &thorn;e lyuer, &amp; &thorn;at veyne goi&thorn; to|&thorn;e stomac fro &thorn;e lyuer.  &amp; &thorn;e .iiij. humouris of iiij. substauncis ben|engendrid in &thorn;is place of digestioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Ita in hepate ex chylo veniente a stomacho quatuor humorales|substanti&aelig; generantur.</NOTE> / For &thorn;ere is engendrid &thorn;ere a|maner spumous substaunce whanne &thorn;e digestioun faili&thorn; heete; &amp;|&thorn;ere engendri&thorn; ano&thorn;er partie &thorn;at is sutil as it were wijn; &amp; &thorn;e|greet substaunce goi&thorn; adoun &amp; stynki&thorn;.  If &thorn;ere be engendrid greet|fleume <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="125a">&amp; miche, &thorn;at is cause for it quenchi&thorn; &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e stomac / |Also in &thorn;e same placis is engendrid a subtil substaunce, &amp; scharp|hete worchi&thorn; &thorn;eron &amp; gaderi&thorn; him hete &amp; scharpnes, &amp; &thorn;is is clepid|collera rubea; &amp; if humouris wexi&thorn; to miche, it wole achaufe &thorn;e|lyuer / &amp; causis of engendring of colre ben hote metis &amp; drinkis &amp;
<PB N="202">|traueile &amp; fastyng &amp; stronge saucis // &para; Also &thorn;er is a clene substaunce|engendrid &thorn;at kyndeli hete worchi&thorn; &thorn;eron, &amp; &thorn;at is blood.|&amp; &thorn;e matere herof is good metis &amp; drynkis &thorn;at ben swete // &para; Also|&thorn;er is engendrid ano&thorn;er substaunce &thorn;at is sumwhat stynkyng &amp; is|clepid malancoli &amp; is engendrid in .ij. maners: oon maner is &thorn;is of|greet hete &thorn;at is brennyng &amp; of greet cooldnes &thorn;at wexi&thorn; hard<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of greet cooldness &thorn;at wexi&thorn; hard</I>.  Lat. ex frigiditate ingrossante.</NOTE>;|&amp; &thorn;e cause herof ben grete metis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grete metis</I>, Lat. cibi grossi.</NOTE> &amp; metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; malancoli /|And &thorn;es iiij. humouris Sanguis, Colera, fleumtica &amp; Malancolia, &amp;|euery of hem ha&thorn; diuers qualitees, for blood is hoot &amp; moist, ffleume|coold &amp; moost, Colre hoot &amp; drie, Malancoli coold &amp; drie // &para; Also| of &thorn;ese humouris <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="125b">summe ben kindeli &amp; summe ben vnkyndely, &amp;|&thorn;erfore in &thorn;is chapitre we wolen make mencioun of alle, ffor bi|gendring of &thorn;ese humouris enpostyms ben engendrid //</P>
<P>&para; Of fleume &thorn;ere ben ij. kyndis, oon is natural &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er|innatural / Natural fleume is coold &amp; moist &amp; whit, &amp; goi&thorn; sumwhat|to swetnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>swetnes</I>, a mistake for <I>whitnes</I>.  Lat. ad paucam tendens albedinem.|De propr. rer., lib. IV., cap. 9, <I>ibid</I>. fol. 35: "<I>Kyndeliche fleume is coolde &amp;|moist, &amp; white in colour, and fletinge in substaunce, a litwhat swete in sauour,|o&thorn;ir al werisch &amp; vnsauoury.</I>"</NOTE> of which lordschipe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of which lordshipe</I>, Lat. de cuius dominio.</NOTE> &thorn;er folowi&thorn; a litil wilnyng|for to comoun wi&thorn; wymmen, &amp; &thorn;e palesie, &amp; [he is]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he is</I>, wanting.</NOTE> pesible, &amp;|loue&thorn; wel for to haue reste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ibid</I>., fol. 35 bk.: "<I>a verray fleumatik man is in &thorn;e body lustles, heuy &amp;|slow&yogh;, dul of wit &amp; of &thorn;ou&yogh;t for&yogh;etteful, neissche of fleissche and quauy, bloo</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">bloo, MS. bood.</NOTE> <I>of|colour, whitliche in face, ferdeful of herte, ful of spittinge snyuel &amp; rokeinge,|ful of slouthe &amp; of slepinge, &amp; of a litil appetite &amp; of litil &thorn;urst.</I>"</NOTE> / Saue &thorn;e moost part of fleume is in|a mannes brayn, &amp; in hise lungis, &amp; in his stomac, &amp; in hise guttis,|&amp; in hise ioynctes.  And &thorn;e lordschip of fleume is in &thorn;e hynder|part of a mannes heed, &amp; in &thorn;e rigbonys.  &amp; fleume doi&thorn; &thorn;re profitis,|&thorn;e .j. is &thorn;is: sumtyme a mannes kynde faili&thorn; blood, &amp; &thorn;an|kinde worchi&thorn; vpon fleume &amp; maki&thorn; blood, &amp; of o&thorn;ere humouris &thorn;is|mai not be do / &THORN;e ij. profit of fleume is &thorn;is: for fleume goi&thorn; wi&thorn;|blood for to norische diuers lymes / &THORN;e .iij. profit of fleume is &thorn;is,|&thorn;at it acoldi&thorn; &thorn;e ioynctis &amp; maki&thorn; hem moist, for ellis in greet|meuyng &thorn;ei schulden wexe drie / Of fleume &thorn;at is innatural ben| .iiij. maners <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="126a">as: fleume dulce, fleuma acetosum, fleuma ponticum,|fleuma salsum // &para; ffleuma dulce is in .ij. maners.  &THORN;e firste maner
<PB N="203">|is &thorn;is: as whanne fleume is medlid wi&thorn; blood, or as whanne hete|worchi&thorn; wi&thorn; fleume to turne it into blood // &para; ffleuma acetosum|is seid in .ij. maners / as whanne ebullitiun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ebullitiun</I>, Lat. ebullitio.</NOTE> come&thorn; to fleume dulce|&amp; maki&thorn; him to rote, &amp; it [is] herto as it bifalli&thorn; in o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis|&thorn;at ben swete, as to swete winis whanne sournes come&thorn; &thorn;eron it|bicome&thorn; coold, &amp; in &thorn;e same manere fleuma acetosum maki&thorn; fleuma|dulce coold // &para; ffleuma salsum is moost drie of alle, &amp; &thorn;is is|whanne &thorn;er is ony part of colre medlid wi&thorn; fleume, &thorn;an it is|clepid fleuma salsum, for &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e colre maki&thorn; it salt / &para; ffleuma|vitreum was liquide fleuma, &amp; wi&thorn; cooldnes it is congilid, or sum|partie of malancolie is medlid &amp; congili&thorn; it hard // &para; Colre sum|is natural &amp; sum is innatural / Natural is li&yogh;t &amp; scharp &amp; reed in|colour &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>colour</I>, erroneously inserted.</NOTE> in substaunce, &amp; &thorn;e more hoot &thorn;at it is &thorn;e more reednes|it maki&thorn; / &THORN;anne vertues of colre ben &thorn;ese / A colerik man schal|haue hasti entendement &amp; sotil <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="126b">of witt, &amp; hardi &amp; hasti &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; |hasti answere, &amp; li&yogh;tly meued to wra&thorn;&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. IV., cap. 10, Add. 27,944, fol. 36: "<I>And so colerik|men be&thorn; generalliche wra&thorn;eful, hardy, vnmeke, li&yogh;t, vnstable, inpetuous; in|body long, sklendre &amp; lene; in colour broun, in eer blak and crips, hard and|stif; in touche hoot, in puls strong &amp; swift.</I>"</NOTE> / Of colre innatural ben .v.|maners, as citrina, [vitellina]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vitellina</I>, wanting.</NOTE>, adusta, prassina &amp; eruginosa / Colera|citrina is medlid wi&thorn; subtil fleume / Colera vitellina<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>colera vitellina</I>, called <I>&yogh;ellow&yogh; colera</I>, in De propr. rer. ibid.</NOTE> is medlid|wi&thorn; greet fleume / Colera adusta is in .ij. maners; oon is &thorn;is, &thorn;at|it is to miche brent in<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&amp;</I> for <I>in</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e lyuer; &thorn;an wi&thorn; &thorn;is brennyng &thorn;e subtil|partie departi&thorn; fro &thorn;e grete parties, &amp; in &thorn;is maner it taki&thorn; a spice|of malancoly // &para; In ano&thorn;er manere, partijs of malancoli &thorn;at ben|brent, [ben]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I>, wanting.</NOTE> medlid &thorn;erwi&thorn; // &para; And &thorn;er is iij. maner of colre|adust, &amp; is whanne his blood is adust id est brent as it schal be seid|here after // &para; &THORN;er is ano&thorn;er maner of colre &thorn;at is clepid prassina,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., <I>ibid</I>. fol. 35 b.: "<I>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde maner of colera hatte prassina,|&amp; is grene of colour and bittir scharp as an herbe &thorn;at hatte prassium, &amp; marubium,|&amp; porrus in latyn.</I>"</NOTE>|&thorn;at is swi&thorn;e bittir // &para; Eruginosa is lijk &thorn;e rust of copur, &amp; &thorn;is|maner of colre is miche freting &amp; scharp, &amp; G. sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is maner|colre is engendrid of hoot metis &amp; scharpe as oynouns, garlek,|mustard, &amp; o&thorn;ere mo // &para; Of malancoli &thorn;er ben .ij. maners&mdash;as|malancoli natural &amp; malancoli innatural / Malancoly &thorn;at is natural
<PB N="204">| ha&thorn; &thorn;ese signis / &THORN;e .j. is as it were fecis of blood,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., ibid. fol. 36: "<I>&THORN;e kyndeliche malencolie is coole and drye,|&thorn;at is i-bred in blood as drastes in wyne.</I>"</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="127a">&amp; her colour is|as it were ledi &amp; blac, &amp; her bodi schal be leene &amp; drie, &amp; &thorn;ei|schulen haue good appetit for to ete, &amp; &thorn;ei schulen haue good|mynde for to kepe &thorn;ingis in her &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; &thorn;ei schulen be dredeful &amp;|ful of enuye &amp; gile &amp; sorowe &amp; coueitous / Malancolie innatural|come&thorn; of humours brent &amp; corrupt.  Of euery of &thorn;ese humours|ben engendrid diuers maners of enpostyms / &amp; euery maner postyme|ha&thorn; diuers cure as it schal be seid here-after.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>A general word of empostyms /</HEAD>
<P>Apostyme ha&thorn; manie diuers names of diuers men, for lewid|cirurgians<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lewid cirurgians</I>, Lat. rurales cyrurgici.</NOTE> seien, &thorn;at &thorn;er is noon apostym but &thorn;at, &thorn;at maki&thorn;|quytture / Saue I seie, &amp; alle auctouris seien &thorn;at eueri swellyng in|a lyme, whe&thorn;ir it be greet or smal, it schal be clepid apostym / For|.A. sei&thorn;: litil swellyngis schule be clepid litil apostyms, &amp; grete|swellyngis schulen be clepid grete apostyms / &THORN;erfore apostym is|seid swellyng in lymes, ou&thorn;ir inflatioun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>inflatioun</I>, Lat. inflatio, O.Fr. inflacion.  <I>Vigo</I> l. c. "<I>Inflatus</I>, Puffed|vp, swellyng."</NOTE> &thorn;at chaungi&thorn; &thorn;e lyme o&thorn;er|&thorn;an it schulde be; &amp; &thorn;e mater herof come&thorn; of manie diuers &thorn;ingis;| ou&thorn;er it come&thorn; of humouris, or of watir, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="127b">or of wijnd / If it come&thorn;|of humouris, &thorn;an it come&thorn; of blood, ou&thorn;er of fleume, or of colre, or|of malancolie // Also enpostyms &thorn;at cometh of humours: summe|come&thorn; of natural humours, &amp; summe of innatural; &amp; summe of|sengle humours, &amp; summe of humouris medlid togidere / And|summe enpostyms cometh of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &amp; summe of causis|withoutforth / &THORN;e causis wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; is falling ou&thorn;er smiting, or of a|wounde, or chaunging of eir / Of &thorn;e causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;: as of|wickidnes of humours, or to ful of humouris, or to ful of water, or|of wijnd / or whanne a man is hurt wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;: or wi&thorn; greet hete|&thorn;at brenne&thorn;, or wi&thorn; greet cooldnes of eir &thorn;at constreyne&thorn;, or of|greet drienes &thorn;at constreine&thorn;, for alle &thorn;ese causis humouris gaderi&thorn;|togidere &amp; maki&thorn; enpostyms // Also if a man falle vpon a stoon or|vpon an hard &thorn;ing, or if a man be smite wi&thorn; a stoon or wi&thorn; a staf,|or &thorn;oru&yogh; prickyng of a venimous beest: alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis moun| engendre venimous<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a venimous</I>, cancelled.</NOTE> enpostyms / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="128a">schalt knowe
<PB N="205">|diuers enpostyms of what humouris &thorn;ei come&thorn; / If superfluite of|blood drawe to a lyme, as is clepid flegmon,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Halle. Table</I>, p. 84. "<GAP DESC="Greek">, id est inflammatio uel collectio, <GAP DESC="Greek">|hoc est a sanguine dicta, written moste commonly hither vnto (with|muche rudenes) <I>Flegmon</I>, is properly a symple tumore (as Galen sayeth) and|an affecte of the fleshie partes, comming of a greater fluxe of bloude then they|nede or can naturally susteyne."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;es ben &thorn;e signes|&thorn;erof: &thorn;e place wole be reed for lijknes of blood, akynge for &thorn;e|greet replecioun &thorn;erof, beting<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>beting</I>, Lat. pulsatio.  See <I>N. E. Dict</I>., s. v. beat, 13.</NOTE> for &thorn;e greet depnes of mater, or for|greet akynge / He may haue greuaunce of a feuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. VII., cap. 59, Add. 27,944, fol. 97 b.: "<I>And somtyme|it come&thorn; of ventosite &amp; of wind, &amp; hatte bubo; somtyme of a symple humour, as|of blood, and hatte flegmon; &thorn;e tokenes &thorn;erof be&thorn;</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>by</I>.</NOTE><I>: rede rednes come&thorn; of &thorn;e|colour of blood, hardenesse come&thorn; of multitude of matiere &amp; of hete &thorn;at wasti&thorn;|watry matiere, quappinge &amp; lepinge</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. pulsus i. saltus.</NOTE><I> of ventosite &amp; fumosite, schuftynge &amp;|puttinge, sore ache of &thorn;e</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ofte</I>.</NOTE> <I>strecchinge of &thorn;e place; hete come&thorn; of hote matiere, &amp;|swellinge come&thorn; of multitude of matiere.</I>"</NOTE> / If &thorn;e blood be|&thorn;inne in substaunce &amp; hoot in qualite, &thorn;an it maki&thorn; herisipulam.|&amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e signe &thorn;erof, &thorn;at in &thorn;e hi&yogh;est place &thorn;erof, it wole be|moost reed and hoot; &amp; if &thorn;ou leist &thorn;i fyngir &thorn;eron, &amp; whanne|&thorn;ou remeuyst &thorn;i fyngir, &thorn;e skyn wole be whit &thorn;ere &thorn;i fyngir was, &amp;|anoon it wole bicome reed a&yogh;en, for &thorn;e mater &thorn;erof is subtil, &amp; &thorn;e|pacient ha&thorn; greet brennyng &thorn;erof &amp; akynge // Blood in his owne|substaunce is more gretter &amp; maki&thorn; more hete, &amp; maki&thorn; apostym,|&thorn;at is clepid carbunculus / &THORN;is enpostym come&thorn; to a man whanne|he ha&thorn; haboundance of greet blood, &amp; &thorn;erfor whanne he is replete|of mete, he schulde ba&thorn;e him or traueile him-silf, &thorn;at &thorn;e blood|mi&yogh;te falle out, &amp; for his greetnes &amp; hardnes it mai not be <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="128b">resolued |with hete, &amp; &thorn;anne it leue&thorn; in &thorn;e skyn &amp; maki&thorn; apostym.<NOTE PLACE="foot">26,106, fol. 52 b.: hoc apostema fit cum homo habundat sanguine grosso,|et balneatur post ciborum repletionem aut laborat, ita quod sanguis ad extrema|movetur et propter suam grossitiem et duritiem non potest a calore resolui|remanens in cuti facit apostema.</NOTE>  &THORN;e|signes herof ben &thorn;es: &thorn;e enpostym is hard for &thorn;e &thorn;iknes of blood,|&amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof is swart reed for &thorn;e greet hete, &amp; &thorn;e greet heete<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heete</I>, in margin.</NOTE>|herof maki&thorn; a man sumtime to haue a feuer &thorn;erwi&thorn;; &amp; sumtyme it|maki&thorn; a man to haue sincopin,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Halle. Table</I>, p. 122.  "Syncope. <GAP DESC="Greek">, id est animi deliquium,|uel pr&aelig;seps uirium lapsus, that is the defecte of the mynde, or a sodeine|slyding away of the strengthe of the body, and commonly called swoundynge."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;is is speciali whanne &thorn;e matere|is brent, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e matere &thorn;erof is turned into venym /</P>
<P>
<PB N="206">Natural colre maki&thorn; herisipulam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., <I>ibid.: "herisipila, &thorn;at is holy fure per antifrasim, &thorn;at is|contrarie spekinge."</I></NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e signe &thorn;erof is hardnes|for &thorn;e greet drienes of colre.  &amp; &thorn;e heed of &thorn;e enpostym is schape|as it were a pyne, for &thorn;e grece &thorn;at it ha&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. propter igneitatem ipsius.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof is|reed medlid wi&thorn; &yogh;elow //</P>
<P>An enpostym &thorn;at come&thorn; of fleume, is clepid vdimia<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vdimia</I> <GAP DESC="Greek">, tumour.&mdash;Vigo, Chirurgery.  The Interpretation: "Undimia|is a barbarouse terme, in greke it is called oedema, in latin tumor.|For it is softe swellynge wythout payne."</NOTE> or &yogh;ima,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Zima</I>.  Sinonoma Barth, "<I>Zima</I> est apostema flancorum molle sine|dolore."  From <GAP DESC="Greek">, that which is boiled, decoction.  De propr. rer., <I>ibid.:|"In &thorn;e same manere aposteme come&thorn; of fleume, and hatte zimia o&thorn;ur palus;|for ri&yogh;t as in mures and in mareys is moche superfluyte of slyme &amp; of wose, so|in &thorn;is posteme is moche superfluyte; and if &thorn;ou &thorn;urstist &thorn;y fyngre &thorn;er vppon, hit|dyue&thorn; inne, for &thorn;e rennynge matiere wi&thorn;drawi&thorn; &amp; letti&thorn; &thorn;e vingre entre, &amp;|&thorn;anne in &thorn;e myddel is a putte as hit were &thorn;e bore of an hole; &amp; whanne &thorn;e|fingre is aweye, &thorn;e matiere come&thorn; a&yogh;en &amp; filli&thorn; al &thorn;e place."</I></NOTE>|&amp; is a neisch enpostym, &amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof is sumwhat whi&yogh;t.  &amp; if|&thorn;ou pressist in &thorn;i fyngir, &thorn;er wole leue &thorn;ere a pitt for &thorn;e gret|neischenes; &amp; whanne &thorn;i fyngir is aweie, it wole arise vp a&yogh;en.|&THORN;is enpostym is wi&thorn;out akynge, saue it maki&thorn; a greuaunce /</P>
<P>&para; Natural malancoli maki&thorn; an hard enpostym, &amp; is clepid Sclirosis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 16,106, fol. 53: apostema quod vocatur scliros ab aliis sephiros vel|sclirosis.  <I>Halle. Table</I>, p. 114.  "<I>Scirrhus</I> <GAP DESC="Greek">, id est|durities, writen of old <I>Sclirosis</I>, is (as I gat her of Galen in diuers places) a|tumore against nature, and an affecte of harde and thicke partes."</NOTE>|&amp; &thorn;e signe &thorn;erof is hardnes, &amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof is as &thorn;e| colour <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="129a">of malancolie ledi or blac /</P>
<P>Enpostym &thorn;at come&thorn; of blood &amp; watir medlid togidere.  &THORN;is is|&thorn;e signe &thorn;erof: if &thorn;ou settist &thorn;eron &thorn;i .ij. fyngris of &thorn;i .ij. hondis,|&amp; first pressist &thorn;at oon fyngir &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;at o&thorn;er, &thorn;ou schalt fele &thorn;e|watri mater remeue fro &thorn;at oon fyngir to &thorn;at o&thorn;er //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;ese ben &thorn;e differencis of apostyms &thorn;at ben symple, &thorn;at|come&thorn; of oon matere at oonis; &amp; &thorn;ese ensaumplis ben schewid|tofor, for &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;e bettir knowe enpostyms &thorn;at come&thorn; of|double matere //</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;er come&thorn; an empostym of blood &amp; colre; &amp; if &thorn;e more|partie be of blood, &thorn;an &thorn;e enpostym schal be clepid flegmonides;|&amp; if &thorn;e more partie &thorn;erof be of colre, &thorn;anne he schal be clepid|herisipilades.  &amp; &thorn;e signes herof &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi &thorn;e signes of
<PB N="207">|&thorn;e symple apostyms // &para; Also blood &amp; fleume natural [ben]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I>, wanting.</NOTE> medlid|togidere, &amp; maki&thorn; an enpostym &thorn;at is vdimia.  &amp; &thorn;e signe herof|[is]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>, wanting.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;e heed of &thorn;is enpostym is reed, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ere wole be|whit<NOTE PLACE="foot">Incorrect translation.  Add. 26,106, fol. 53: facit apostema quod videtur|vdimia, nisi quia in superficie magis rubet.</NOTE> / &para; Also blood is medlid wi&thorn; greet fleume &amp; malancolie, &amp;|engendri&thorn; glandulas &amp; Scrophulas.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Halle. Table</I>, p. 115.  "<I>Scrophula</I> (so called by Auicenna, Guidone de|Cauliaco, Bruno, Theodorico, Lanfranco, and others a <I>Scropha</I>, a pregnante|soowe: because it or the lyke, is a disease common to hogs) is a harde Scirrhous|tumore, in the glandules of the share or arme holes, but chiefly in the|necke."</NOTE>  &para; Colre medlid with fleume|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="129b">maki&thorn; fleume rennyng, &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;at fleume goi&thorn; wi&thorn; him into |ioynctis.  &amp; herof &thorn;ou schalt haue a pleyner teching in &thorn;e chapitre|of ioinctes.  &para; Also greet fleume is medlid with malancoli, &amp; &thorn;erof|come&thorn; glandula &amp; Scrophule / Also malancolie &amp; blood, colre &amp;|fleume ben medlid alle togidere &amp; maki&thorn; an enpostym &thorn;at is clepid|antrax; &amp; &thorn;e malice &thorn;erof is diuers after euery humour.  Saue if|blood &amp; colre be feruent togidere &amp; malancolie be malicious, &thorn;an|&thorn;ere falli&thorn; manie harde &thorn;ingis &thorn;erto, as quaking of &thorn;e herte, &amp;|sincopis, &amp; out of hise wittis, &amp; sumtyme dee&thorn;.  &amp; &thorn;e signes herof|ben greet hardnes of &thorn;e enpostym, &amp; &thorn;e schap &thorn;erof as it were a|pyn, &amp; greet akynge, &amp; sumtyme he schal not fele it.  And &thorn;erfore|.G. sei&thorn;: hote apostyms, if &thorn;ei be not felid, ben incurable.  &amp;|veynes &thorn;at ben &thorn;eron wolen be of diuers colouris, &amp; vpon &thorn;e|enpostym &thorn;ere wole be as it were a litil bladdre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Guilelm. de Salic</I>., I. 59.  Sl. 277, fol. 11: "<I>In &thorn;e antrax ....|&thorn;er been smale bladdres aboute &thorn;e copp of it, as &thorn;ou&yogh; fier hadde touched &thorn;e place.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof|wole be as aischis, &amp; it seme&thorn; &thorn;at it is drawe ynward wi&thorn; a &thorn;reed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. 7, cap. 59, Add. 27,944, fol. 93: "<I>And also it seme&thorn;|&thorn;at hit is i-drawe to &thorn;e ground &thorn;erof wi&thorn; a maner &thorn;rede, i-fastned to &thorn;e vttir|partye of &thorn;e bladder in &thorn;e myddel.</I>"  Not in <I>Gulielm. de Salic</I>.</NOTE>|&amp; &thorn;is enpostym is seid contagious.</P>
<P>Of humouris &thorn;at ben [in] <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>, wanting.  Lat. De humoribus autem non naturalibus.</NOTE>natural, &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="130a">folowi&thorn; &thorn;erof / |Of fleume &thorn;at is corrupt cometh Bocia &amp; testudines / Of malancolie|come&thorn; scrophule &amp; glandule, as it is aforseid.  &amp; of alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ou|schalt haue propre chapitris / Of colre &thorn;at is brent &amp; of o&thorn;ere|humouris &thorn;at ben brent &amp; corrupt &thorn;ere come&thorn; manie pustulis, &amp;|summe &thorn;erof ben ful malicious after &thorn;e malice of &thorn;e matere / Herof|come&thorn; ignis persicus, miliaris, formica, herpes, herpes estiomenus.
<PB N="208">|Ignis persicus is a signe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>signe</I>, probably mistaken for <I>siknesse</I>.  Lat. ignis persicus est egritudo|in qua sunt multe pustule.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben manie pustule &thorn;eron &amp;|venymous water.  &amp; &thorn;e pustule ben reed al aboute &amp; &yogh;elow, &amp;|occupie&thorn; al &thorn;e lyme.  &amp; it is wi&thorn; greet brennyng.  &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; of|colre brent and &thorn;inne / Miliaris ha&thorn; litil pustulis, &amp; ha&thorn; not so|greet brennyng, ne &thorn;e place &thorn;erof is not so reed.  &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; ofte|of fleume medlid wi&thorn; a litil colre // &para; fformica is a pustula &thorn;at is|swi&thorn;e feruent, &amp; ha&thorn; a cruste aboue, &amp; it come&thorn; of colre brent.  &amp;|&thorn;is is goynge &amp; freti&thorn; &thorn;e lyme aboue, &amp; it hath greet brennyng //|&para; &THORN;e firste<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. Pruna similiter est pustula.  The translator read: prima.&mdash;Phillips.|"<I>Pruna</I>, a burning or live Coal; also a Carbuncle, Plague-sore,|or fiery Botch."</NOTE> is a pustula &thorn;at come&thorn; of malancolie &amp; is blac or| ledi, &amp; it come&thorn; of &thorn;e venemous mater of malancoli / <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="130b">Herpes|estiomenus is as miche to seie as fretyng him-silf, &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; in|manie maners / It come&thorn; in medlyng of colre &thorn;at is brent &amp;|malancolie innatural &amp; brent &amp; sutil.  &amp; whanne &thorn;is falli&thorn; into a|lyme, it freti&thorn; &thorn;e lyme for &thorn;e greet malice &thorn;at it ha&thorn; // &para; Also &thorn;er|is ano&thorn;er maner passioun &thorn;at ha&thorn; manie diuers names, for summen|clepen it cancrum, &amp; summen lupum.  &amp; men of fraunce clepen it|malum nostre domine<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>malum nostre domine;</I> This name, given to <I>Erisipelas</I>, is due to the|miraculous cures of this disease by intercession of the Holy Virgin.  They|are first reported by <I>Hugo Farsitus</I>, a canon of Saint Jean des Vignes, in|Soissons.  In his book, <I>De Miraculis Maria Suessionensis</I>, he relates the|miracles, as seen by himself in the year 1128, and mentions several instances|where women suffering from a severe skin-disease have been cured by the|help of the Holy Virgin.  Further account of a plague known under the|name "mal des ardents" and of cures by the help of the Holy Virgin, is|given by <I>Gautier de Coincy</I>.  See G. d. C., ed. <I>Foquet</I>, p. 138.</P><P>The same disease is also called <I>fuoco di Sant Antonio</I>.  See Tomm. Dict.,|<I>Maladie S. Antoine</I> (Godefr. Dict.).  The Saints Germain, Main, Othoine|and Verain, have likewise given their names to the <I>erisipelas</I>.  <I>Quinte Ess</I>.,|8. 23: "fire of St. Antony, a brennynge sijknes clepid &thorn;e fier of helle."</P></NOTE> / And lumbardis clepen it fier of seint|antony, &amp; summen clepen it herisipulam.  Of alle &thorn;ese diuers|names is no charge of, saue &thorn;e signes of &thorn;is sijknes ben &thorn;ese:|freting &amp; brennyng &amp; blac colour &amp; stynkynge, &amp; &thorn;at ri&yogh;t foul|stynkyng.  &amp; or &thorn;e skyn &thorn;erof be to-broke, it wole not stynke,|saue &thorn;e place &thorn;erof wole be ledi.  &amp; if &thorn;ou felist &thorn;e place wi&thorn; &thorn;i|fyngir, &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;erof al corrupt // &para; Cancer is|a postym &thorn;at is swi&thorn;e corrupt.  &amp; is in .ij. maners: as cancer|vlceratus, &amp; cancer &thorn;at is not vlceratus.  &para; A cankre &thorn;at is not
<PB N="209">|vlceratus is in .ij. maners: oon come&thorn; of malancolie rotid, &amp; bigynne&thorn;|for to wexe in &thorn;e mychilnes of a fecche or of a pese.  &amp;|&thorn;anne it <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="131a">wole wexe alwei in a maner brennynge; &amp; euere as &thorn;e |matere wexi&thorn;, so wole &thorn;e brennyng wexe for&thorn;.  &amp; it wole haue|veynes of diuers colour.  &amp; sum colour &thorn;erof wole be ledi, &amp; sum|wole be purpur, summe &thorn;erof wole be grene.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;is is ful of|colerik matere corrupt.  &amp; it ha&thorn; greet akynge, &amp; if &thorn;ou pressist|it with &thorn;i fyngir, &thorn;e malice &thorn;erof wole be miche more / &THORN;is passioun|comounly wole wexe in placis &thorn;at ben glandule / &THORN;is maner enpostym|come&thorn; ofte in a mannes &thorn;ies &amp; in a wommans brest &amp; in|o&thorn;ere placis / Cancer vlceratus.  Alle &thorn;e signes &thorn;erof ben tofore|seid in his propre chapitre /</P>
<P>Now alle &thorn;e signes of enpostyms ben seid, go we to &thorn;e curis /|&THORN;ou must take kepe, whe&thorn;er &thorn;e enpostym come of causis wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;|or wi&thorn;inne / If &thorn;e enpostym come&thorn; of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;,|&thorn;anne &thorn;ou must purge &thorn;e matere or &thorn;ou leie &thorn;erto ony repercussijf|or ony maturatif or ony resoluyng &thorn;ing / forwhi a repercussijf<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. repercussist.</NOTE> mai|not do awei al &thorn;e matere, &thorn;ou&yogh; it sumwhat aswage &thorn;e akynge in &thorn;e|firste bigynnyng / ne&thorn;eles itt maki&thorn; &thorn;e matere hard, &amp; aftirward &thorn;e|patient <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="131b">schulde haue &thorn;e more penaunce / A resoluyng in an vnclene |bodi drawi&thorn; more matere &thorn;erto &thorn;an it resolue&thorn;.  &para; A maturatif|maki&thorn; &thorn;e enpostym to wexe more, if his bodi be vnpurgid, &amp; maki&thorn;|&thorn;e matere of &thorn;e enpostym feruent / In what maner &thorn;ou schalt|purge diuers maters, in &thorn;e chapitre of allopucia &thorn;ou schalt fynde it,|&amp; in &thorn;e chapitre de doloribus iuncturarum, &thorn;at schal be seid here|aftir / &THORN;ou schalt worche in enpostyms &thorn;at falli&thorn; in a mannes bodi|wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;.  If &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;at his bodi is replet, &thorn;is schal alwei|be &thorn;in entencioun, for to drawe &thorn;e matere awei in &thorn;is maner: / If|&thorn;e enpostym be in a mannes mou&thorn;, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make him no|gargarisme;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gargarisme</I>, a gargle.  Vigo, Chirurgery, Interpretation: "A gargarisme|is when we cause water to bubble in our throtes, not sufferynge it to go downe."</NOTE> &amp; if it be in his ers, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make him no|laxatif medicyn / &amp; if it be in a wommans maris,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maris</I>, Lat. matrix, O.Fr. marris.  Sloane 2463, fol. 194 bk.: "<I>The|moder is a skyn, &thorn;at &thorn;e childe is enclosed in his moder-wombe.  And manye|of &thorn;e sekenesses that women hauen, comen of greuaunces of this moder, that|we clepen &thorn;e marice.</I>"</NOTE> &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt|&yogh;eue hir no medicyn for to make menstrue; saue &thorn;ou schalt alwei|go to &thorn;e contrarie herof: as if enpostyms be in partijs aboue, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue catarticum / If &thorn;e enpostym be bine&thorn;e, &thorn;an &yogh;eue
<PB N="210">|him medicyns for to caste.  &para; Whanne &thorn;e matere is purgid, &thorn;an| bigynne we curis of hoot enpostyms / &THORN;ou must <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="132a">be war of repercussiuis|in ten maners.  &para; &THORN;e j. cause is &thorn;is, if his bodi be replet /|as it is aforseid.  &para; &THORN;e .ij. is, greet fume of humours &amp; venymous.|&para; &THORN;e .iij. is gretnes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gretnes</I>, grossities.</NOTE> of humours rotid.  &para; &THORN;e .iiij. cause is, if|apostym wexe in a noble lyme as in a mannes eere, or in a wommans|tetis, or in &thorn;e rigge aboutefor&thorn;.  &para; &THORN;e .v. cause is: if &thorn;e enpostym|be in &thorn;e &thorn;rote, or ny&yogh; &thorn;e brayn, or in ony place ny&yogh; &thorn;e herte, or ny&yogh;|ony lyme &thorn;at norischeth / &para; &THORN;e .vj. cause is in a child.  &para; &THORN;e .vij.|cause is, if it be in an oold man.  &para; &THORN;e .viij. cause is if it be in a|man &thorn;at risi&thorn; vp of sijknes.  &para; &THORN;e .ix. cause is if it be apostema|creticum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>creticum</I>, Lat. criticum.</NOTE>  &para; &THORN;e .x. cause is, if an enpostyme be in a noble|membre, &amp; be putt fro &thorn;at place to ano&thorn;er.  &para; In noon of &thorn;ese .x.|causis, &thorn;ou schalt make noon repercussif in hote enpostyms as &thorn;ou|schalt fynde &thorn;e maner in &thorn;e antidotarie of repercussifs / &para; To|enpostyms of blood, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t do medicyns repercussifs &amp; dissolutiuis|sotilly, so &thorn;at &thorn;e firste bigynnyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e firste bigynnyng</I>, determination of time denoted by accusative.|Add. 10,440, fol. 20: "<I>and be war, &thorn;at &thorn;e tyme of chaungynge of &thorn;is medycyn|&thorn;ou take it not awey with violence.</I>"</NOTE> repercussifs ouercome|&thorn;e mater of enpostym myche, &amp; in &thorn;e stat<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in &thorn;e stat</I>, Lat. in statu.  Add. 27,944, fol. 98: "<I>whan &thorn;e posteme is|in state.</I>"</NOTE> of &thorn;e enpostym lasse, &amp;| in &thorn;e ende &thorn;erof &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="132b">vse clene resoluyng &thorn;ingis / If &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t not wi&thorn; repercussiuis do awei &thorn;e enpostym ne resolue him,|saue he bigynne&thorn; to quytture, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;erto medicyns|maturatiuis, til it be wel quitturid.  &para; Of repercussiuis resolutiuis|maturatiuis &amp; &thorn;e manere of worching &thorn;erof &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e|antidotarie.  &para; Whanne &thorn;e enpostym is quitturid &amp; sufficiently|rotid, &thorn;is &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe whanne &thorn;e akynge is al aweie, &amp; whanne|&thorn;e matere is neische &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;an opene &thorn;e enpostym, &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest|moost competent //  Saue or &thorn;ou opene ony enpostyms, &thorn;ou must|be war of &thorn;us manie &thorn;inges: &para; &THORN;e j. is, &thorn;ou schalt opene noon|enpostym or he be perfitli rotid, but if &thorn;e enpostym rotid ony o&thorn;ir|lyme, or &thorn;at he were ny&yogh; ony noble lyme, or ny&yogh; ony ioynct //  In|o&thorn;ere causis &thorn;ou schalt abide til he be perfitli rotid.  &amp; in &thorn;e|kuttyng &thorn;ou schalt loke where &thorn;e skyn is most &thorn;inne and moost|hangyng, &amp; &thorn;ere &thorn;ou schalt opene &thorn;e enpostym.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: facias apertionem ubi materia magis dependet, et ubi pellis est|magis tenuis.</NOTE>  &para; &THORN;e .ij. entencioun
<PB N="211">|is &thorn;is, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt be war, whanne &thorn;ou openest <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="133a">an |enpostym, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hurte no senewe, ne no veine ne noon arterie.|&para; &THORN;e .iij. cause is, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt not avoide al &thorn;e mater at oon|tyme, &amp; principali whanne &thorn;er is myche matere, &amp; &thorn;e enpostym is|greet //  &para; &THORN;e .iiij. is &thorn;is, &thorn;ou schalt alwei opene &thorn;e enpostym in|endelong &thorn;e lyme &amp; not ouer&thorn;wert.  Whanne &thorn;ou hast opened &thorn;e|enpostym, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt cure him vp<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cure him vp</I>.  Compare Sloane 277, fol. 1 b.: "<I>be it flesched vp wi&thorn;|powdres &amp; oynementes incarnatifes.</I>"</NOTE> as it is aforseid in &thorn;e cure of|vlcus virulentum.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou schalt fille &thorn;e wounde &thorn;erof with oold|lynnen cloo&thorn; &thorn;at is whi&yogh;t, anoon to .iij. daies [wi&thorn;] mundificatiuis of|&yogh;elkis of eiren &amp; mele, aftir .iij. daies wi&thorn; vnguentum apostolorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">Phillips.  "<I>Apostolorum Unguentum</I>, a cleansing Ointment, so call'd,|because it is made of twelue Drugs, according to the Number of the|Apostles."</NOTE>|&amp; oon of &thorn;e mundificatiuis &thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, &amp;|wi&thorn; regendring &thorn;ingis &amp; drijng &thorn;ingis.  &para; A colerik enpostym|come&thorn; late to rotyng, but if it be rotid wi&thorn; ony mater leid wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;;|&thorn;ou shalt cure &thorn;is enpostym in &thorn;e same maner as &thorn;ou schalt|enpostyms of blood, saue &thorn;is mote haue coldere medicyns /  Carbunculis|schulen be curid as antrax, &amp; &thorn;e cure herof schal be seid|herafter.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="133b">Vdimia schal not be smiten yn wi&thorn; repercussiuis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. vdimia proprie non repercutitur.</NOTE> saue |it schal be waastid awei in &thorn;e firste bigynnyng in &thorn;is maner.  &THORN;ou|schalt purge him with trocis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>trocisce</I>, Lat. trociscus.  Sloane 277, fol. 1 b. (xvth cent.), "<I>a trosce of|&thorn;e trosces maad a&yogh;ens scrophules.</I>"  Vigo 1. c. "<I>Trochiscos</I> in Greke is a|lyttle whele.  Amonge the apothecaries, it is a confection made of sondrye|pouders and spices, by the meane of some lyquoure.  In latine they call it|Pastillum."</NOTE> de turbit, or wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er medicyn &thorn;at|purgi&thorn; fleume.  &THORN;an stewe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stewe</I>, Lat. evapora.</NOTE> &thorn;at lyme wi&thorn; a decoccioun of absinthij,|abrotane, sticados, &amp; squinanti.  &amp; take aischis of a vyne or of an|ook, &amp; make &thorn;erof lie &amp; wete &thorn;erinne lynnen clo&thorn;is &amp; leie hem|vpon &thorn;e place hoot, &amp; binde hem streite &thorn;erto &thorn;at it hile al &thorn;e|enpostym, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e matere &thorn;erof schal be drawen awei //|If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ere be ony blood medlid &thorn;erwi&thorn;, or if &thorn;er ha&thorn; be|leid &thorn;erto ony maturatif so &thorn;at &thorn;e mater &thorn;erof be rotid, &thorn;an opene|it.  Whanne it is opened, it mote haue stronger mundificatiuis &thorn;an|ony o&thorn;er for &thorn;e hardnes of &thorn;e quitture &amp; &thorn;e greetnes &thorn;erof / &THORN;is is|a mollificatif &thorn;at rasis made &amp; A. &rx;. bdellij, galbani,<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Galbanum</I>, a kind of strong scented Gum issuing out of a Plant call'd|Fennel-Giant, which grows in Syria."  Phillips.</NOTE> opoponac
<PB N="212">|ana, &amp; make hem neische with oile of lilie in a morter, &amp; grinde|hem wel togidere.  &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;erto fenigrecum &amp; lynseed as myche|as alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere &amp; medle hem wel togidere, &amp; herof leie an enplastre| vpon an hard enpostym wi&thorn; &thorn;is oonly, or medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; fatte <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="134a">figis|&amp; leie &thorn;is enplastre &thorn;erto til it be resolued &amp; maad neische / &THORN;is|medicyn maki&thorn; an hard enpostym to bicome neische &amp; resolue&thorn; him|wi&thorn;out ony swellyng / &THORN;er ben o&thorn;ere manye medicyns &thorn;at ben|mollificatif &amp; resoluyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt finde in &thorn;e antidotarie //|A watri apostym schal be curid as vdimia, saue it schal haue drier|medicyns, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt cure him in &thorn;e same maner as it is seid in|&thorn;e chapitre, whanne a mannes lyme is to gret, for to make it smal //|Ventosum apostema, &thorn;at is apostym &thorn;at is ful of wijnd.  &THORN;ou|schalt cure it wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at consume&thorn; wijnd wi&thorn;inne &amp; wi&thorn;oute|/ wi&thorn;innefor&thorn; as of vsyng of comyn &amp; carui, &amp; he mote be war|of growel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>growel</I>, Lat. legumina.  See <I>Prompt. Parv</I>., "Growelle or grewelle,|Ligumen."</NOTE> &amp; metis &thorn;at swelli&thorn;; wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; wi&thorn; oilis &thorn;at consume&thorn;|wijnd, or with &thorn;is oile, &rx;. rue, cimini, seminis fenicli, anisi, carui,|ameos<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ameos</I>.  See <I>N. E. Dict</I>., s. v. ammeos.</NOTE>, apij, ana .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., cold oile l&imacr;. <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., do alle &thorn;es in a viol of glas,|&amp; do &thorn;at glas in a vessel wi&thorn; water, &amp; make &thorn;e water se&thorn;e &amp; kepe| wel &thorn;e glas &thorn;eron &thorn;at it breke not, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is oile anoynte &thorn;e place|hoot / Item .&rx;. calcem and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="134b">distempere it wi&thorn; swete wijn, &amp; make|&thorn;erof as it were an emplastre &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon / &rx;. olii anetini<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oleum anetinum</I>, oil of Fennel.</NOTE> .&yogh; ij.,|cere. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., ysope &thorn;at it be drie &amp; poudrid. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., &amp; make herof a|plastre.  &para; Herisipilades<NOTE PLACE="foot">Phillips.  "Erysipelatodes, a Swelling like the former [Erysipelas],|the Skin being of a darker Colour, and the Symptoms more gentle: a|Bastard Erysipelas."</NOTE> or flegmonides schulen be curid in &thorn;e same|maner &thorn;at ben herisipulam &amp; flegmon / Of glandulis &amp; scrophulis,|we wolen speke in her propre chapitre //</P>
<P>&para; Antrax schal be curid wi&thorn; avoiding of noious matere, &amp; wi&thorn;|&thorn;inges &thorn;at comforti&thorn; &thorn;e herte &amp; &thorn;e vertu.  Ne&thorn;eles at &thorn;e firste|bigynnyng her vertu faili&thorn;, &amp; summe &thorn;at ben late blood or purgid|ben lost / &THORN;erfore manie men ben agast for to lete hem blood or &yogh;eue|hem ony medicyn laxatif / Ech mesel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ech mesel,</I> Lat. ego vero.  Compare <I>selwylly</I>, Prompt. Parv.</NOTE> if &thorn;e pacient be strong, I|wole lete him blood adai, &amp; in &thorn;e same ny&yogh;t I wole &yogh;eue him a|medicyn laxatif // Saue herof &thorn;ou schalt take kepe if he be feble,|&amp; his herte quake, &amp; his pous falle, &thorn;an it is folie for to lete him
<PB N="213">|blood or &yogh;eue him ony medicyn laxatif, saue take &thorn;e cure oonly in|goddis hand //  &para; I wole telle an ensample &thorn;at bifel in &thorn;e citee of|mediolanensis &thorn;at it mowe be ensample to &thorn;ee &amp; lernyng / &THORN;er was|a man of xxx. wynter oold, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="135a">&amp; an antrax come vpon him in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside|of his necke, &amp; he was so greet woxe aboute his necke &amp; his |&thorn;rote, &amp; he was so swollen, &thorn;at &thorn;ere was but litil difference bitwixe|&thorn;e gretnes of hise schuldris &amp; his necke. &amp; ne&thorn;eles I fond his vertu|strong.  &amp; I wiste what sijknes it was bi a bladdre &thorn;at satt &thorn;er|vpon, &amp; was in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside of his necke, &amp; &thorn;at was &thorn;e firste bigynnyng|of his sijknes / &amp; ne&thorn;eles &thorn;er is manye lechis of greet name|&thorn;at cowde not knowe &thorn;at passioun / Also I lete him blood in bo&thorn;e|his armis, &amp; drowe out blood ynow&yogh;.  &amp; &thorn;o I dietide him as a man|&thorn;at hadde a feuer agu.  &amp; amorowe I &yogh;af &thorn;e colature of fruit of|mirabolani citrini,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts <I>hinc</I>, referring to another chapter.</NOTE> &thorn;e which &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e chapitre of|allopucia / Vpon &thorn;e enpostym &thorn;ere &thorn;e bladdre was, I leide scabiose|grounden wi&thorn; grese.  I foond neuere bettere medicyns in &thorn;is caas &thorn;an|&thorn;ese ben / For &thorn;e man was al dissolued of his sijknes of &thorn;e brennyng|&amp; of &thorn;e akynge, saue &thorn;e place &thorn;at was to-swoollen, was not|&thorn;e lasse, &amp; &thorn;e man was not &thorn;e more feblid for his laxatif, ne for no|medicyn &thorn;at he hadde / &amp; on &thorn;e morowe I lete him blood in his|oon arm, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="135b">&amp; &yogh;aue him a medicyn laxatif in lasse quantite &thorn;an I dide |ra&thorn;ere, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e swellynge aswagide miche, &amp; in &thorn;e place &thorn;ere &thorn;e|bl[a]ddre was I fond a maner cruste as it were a &thorn;ing &thorn;at were|brent with fier &amp; was of &thorn;e brede of iij. ynchis.  &amp; wi&thorn;inne a fewe|daies &thorn;e cruste was arerid vp, &amp; &thorn;e pacient felide no greet greuaunce.|&amp; in &thorn;e same place &thorn;ere &thorn;e bladdre was, &thorn;ere was a deep|vlcus.  &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e greet hole I si&yogh; &thorn;e &thorn;rote &amp; &thorn;e gret veines, &amp; I|putte yn myn hond / &amp; I &yogh;af &thorn;e pacient good norisching metis, &amp;|I made hool vlcus wi&thorn; mundificatiuis, til he was al hool bi &thorn;e help|of god //</P>
<P>&para; Pustule &thorn;at come&thorn; of humours corrupt as ignis persicus<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ignis persicus</I>, Herpes zoster (Dunglison).  Phillips: "a Gangrene, it|is also taken for a Carbuncle or a fiery Plague Sore."</NOTE> &amp;|miliaris,<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer., lib. VII., cap. 61, Add. 27,944: "<I>amonge auctoures &thorn;is|euel is i-clepid herpes milii o&thorn;er graunlesus, an euel ful of graynes.  But|swiche bleynes be&thorn; litil and smale as greynes of mylie.</I>"  Phillips: "<I>Herpes|Miliaris</I>, or <I>Pustularis</I>, a sort of yellow Bladders or Wheals, like Millet-Seed,|that seize the Skin, cause much itching, and turn to eating Ulcers."</NOTE> &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &para; instead of <I>&amp;</I>.</NOTE> fformica<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ffornica</I>.  Vigo Interpret.  "Formica is a little excrescence, or|outgrowynge in the Skynne, somewhat brode aboute the botome, which when|it is scratched causeth as it were the styngynge of an ante, or pismare, and|therfore it is also called in greke myrmecia."</NOTE> schal be purgid wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at purgi&thorn; colre
<PB N="214">|&amp; malancolie.  &amp; &thorn;at same medicyn schal purge humours &thorn;at be|brent, as fumus terre, cuscute, lappacium acutum, cene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cene</I> for <I>sene</I>.</NOTE> absinthium|&amp; o&thorn;ere mo / Also &thorn;ou schalt voide &thorn;e matere wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at|comforten &thorn;e herte, &amp; kepi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e venym ne smite not to &thorn;e|herte; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt cure &thorn;e place with &thorn;ingis &thorn;at maki&thorn; cold vpon|&thorn;e place.  &amp; whanne vlcus is &thorn;eron &thorn;an it is no nede, saue drie it| vp as it is aforseid in &thorn;e cure <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="136a">of vlcera.  Saue aboutefor&thorn; &thorn;ou|schalt leie colde &thorn;ingis til &thorn;e cure be perfitli do / &amp; &thorn;ere come ony|bifalling &thorn;erto,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. si praua superveniunt accidentia...</NOTE> &thorn;an alwei &yogh;eue him medicyns for to comforte &thorn;e|herte, &thorn;at ben forseid in antrace // Sumtyme tofore alle &thorn;inges|pruna<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Aliquando super omnia adiuvat prunam et formicam urere.  The|translator misunderstood <I>pruna</I> (name of the disease) for <I>pruna</I> (plums).|Compare page 208, note 2.</NOTE> ben good / And formicam &thorn;ou schalt brenne / fforwhi a|cauterie drawi&thorn; out al &thorn;e matere &thorn;at is corrupt &amp; waasti&thorn; it awei.</P>
<P>&para; Herpes estiomenus<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vigo Interpret.  "If the substaunce be grosse, and aygre it vlcereth|the skynne vnto the fleshe, &amp; is called herpes esthiomenos, that is eatynge|or gnawynge herpes."</NOTE> is curid after &thorn;e purgacioun of &thorn;e matere,|&thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt algatis take hede for to do / if his vertu be strong.|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt algate aboute &thorn;e sijknes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: sed ponendo supra locum sanum iuxta <I>&aelig;gritudinem</I> defensiuum...</NOTE> leie a defensif of bole &amp;|terra sigillata &amp; oile of ro. &amp; vinegre / &THORN;is defensif, as sei&thorn; .A., &amp; I|haue ofte preued it, &thorn;is defendi&thorn; eueri lyme fro corrupcioun, &amp; &thorn;is|wole not suffre &thorn;at &thorn;e matere schal make noon vlceracioun ne no|fretyng.  &amp; vpon &thorn;e place &thorn;at is corrupt &amp; deed, &thorn;ou schalt leie an|hoot iren, &amp; do awei alle &thorn;e partis &thorn;at ben corrupt. &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou my&yogh;t|do with a medicyne corosif, saue an hoot iren is bettere / Whanne|&thorn;e rotid matere is aweie, &thorn;anne make clene &thorn;e place wi&thorn; a mundificatif|of iuys of ache, &amp; do &thorn;erto a litil mirre.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e place| is wel clensid, &thorn;an do &thorn;erto a medicin <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="136b">for to regendre fleisch, &amp;|&thorn;anne drie it vp /</P>
