<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>Of empostyms of &thorn;e heed //</HEAD>
<P>Thow&yogh; we han maad a general tale of enpostyms, ne&thorn;eles apostym|in eueri lyme ha&thorn; diuers curis / &THORN;erfore I wole make to euery
<PB N="215">|enpostym a diuers chapiter //  &para; I seie &thorn;at in &thorn;e skyn of a mannes|heed ben diuers enpostyms / If &thorn;ere be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>, above line.</NOTE> enpostym &thorn;erof sutil|fleume, ful of fleume as it schal be seid heraftir in &thorn;e chapitre of|bocium<NOTE PLACE="foot">This passage is corrupt.  Lat.: Nam fiunt ibi apostemata a subtili|phlegmate vel ab alia phlegmatis specie ut mucilaginosi et pulmosi et est|sicut cancerosi bocii erit dictum.</NOTE> / &THORN;is maner sijknes is engendrid bitwene &thorn;e skyn &amp; the|fleisch, &amp; it is su[m]what holow&yogh;, &amp; ben clepid testudines for &thorn;e|lijknes of a beest &thorn;at is clepid so, &amp; ben engendrid of hard fleume,|&amp; ben, as it were, hard knottis &thorn;at were maad fast to &thorn;e scolle, as it|were hornis / For I seie a man came to me, &amp; he hadde in his heed|vij. suche maner &thorn;ingis in diuers placis, &amp; summe &thorn;erof weren as|longe &amp; as scharp as it were a gotis horn or &thorn;e lenk&thorn;e of a mannes|&thorn;ombe, &amp; &thorn;ei weren greuous to &thorn;e man, &amp; I hadde miche wondre|&thorn;at &thorn;er were noon vlcera in &thorn;e skyn / Whanne I si&yogh; wel &thorn;at &thorn;ei|hadden her bigynnynge of &thorn;e scolle boon, I <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="137a">wolde not entermete |&thorn;erwith of &thorn;e cure, &amp; I counseilide him &thorn;at he schulde putte him|into no mannes cure for to cure him, for it &thorn;ou&yogh;te to me impossible.</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e curis of al &thorn;e enpostyms in &thorn;e heed, ben &thorn;ese / If it be|of neische matere or of rotid matere, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt not take hede|for to drie it wi&thorn; mollificatiuis, &thorn;ou&yogh; I seide so in enpostyms of|fleume in &thorn;e general chapitre; for &thorn;at my&yogh;te schende<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schende</I>.  Lat.: quia sic posset cranium inficere liquida materia.</NOTE> &thorn;e scolle wi&thorn;|liquid mater or corrupt matere. &amp; if &thorn;e matere &thorn;erof is hard, make|it neische wi&thorn; maturatiuis, saue lete &thorn;ou not it rotie to myche.  &amp;|or it be rotid to miche, opene it in &thorn;e maner of a triangle &thorn;us; for|&thorn;is empostym of &thorn;e heed for &thorn;e gretnes of &thorn;e skyn, and for it is ful|of pooris, it mai not wel be clensid, but if &thorn;e woundis were so|miche &thorn;at &thorn;e mundificatif my&yogh;te come to &thorn;e botme.  Whanne &thorn;e|enpostym is kutt in &thorn;e forseid maner, &thorn;anne avoide &thorn;e mater &amp; fille|&thorn;e place al wi&thorn; pecis wet in oil of rosis, &amp; sugre molten &thorn;eron, &amp;|alym &amp; leie &thorn;is in &thorn;e botme &thorn;erof til <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="137b">&thorn;e place be wel maad clene. |Aftirward wi&thorn; vnguentum apostolorum &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis &thorn;at engendri&thorn;|fleisch, cure him as it is forseid in &thorn;e cure of vlcers &thorn;at ben|olde //  &para; Nodus is curid wi&thorn; kuttyng of &thorn;e skyn endelongis vpon|&thorn;e place &amp; drawe him out wi&thorn; alle hise rotis.  &amp; if &thorn;er leue&thorn; ony|rote of him, &thorn;an leie &thorn;eron &thorn;e poudre of affadillorum, or of sum
<PB N="216">|li&yogh;t corosif or vnguentum viride, &thorn;at &thorn;e rotis &thorn;erof mowe frete|awei &thorn;erwi&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;an regendre &amp; &thorn;an drie it vp // Watir &thorn;at is|gaderid in children hedis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hydrocephalus and its cure is treated at some length by most of the|ancient physicians.  See <I>Paul. Aegineta,</I> ed. Adams, vol. II., p. 250.  Our|author's description is abridged from <I>Gulielm. de Salic.</I>, lib. I., cap. 1.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er it is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e scolle or wi&thorn;oute|&thorn;e scolle / If it be withynne &thorn;e scole, it seme&thorn; to me so perilous,|&thorn;at I wole bitake &thorn;e cure to god / If &thorn;e watir be withoutfor&thorn;, it|mai be curid wi&thorn; anointing of oile of camomille &amp; solfre grounden|togidere; &amp; &thorn;anne make him .iij. cauterijs: oon a litil aboue &thorn;e forheed,|&amp; oon bihinde &thorn;e nolle in &thorn;e welle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>welle</I>, Lat. fontinella.</NOTE> &thorn;erof, &amp; oon aboue &thorn;e|hindere celle.  &THORN;ese cauterijs wi&thorn; &thorn;e forseid anoyntingis drie&thorn; &amp;|waasti&thorn; &thorn;e matere of &thorn;e watir //  &para; &THORN;e water &thorn;at come&thorn; in children|hedis, is engendrid in &thorn;is manere / whanne <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="138a">&thorn;e maris of a womman| is watri, &amp; &thorn;e child &thorn;at lij&thorn; &thorn;erine lij&thorn; foldyng adounward his heed|vpon hise knees.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e moisture falli&thorn; adoun &amp; fyndi&thorn; a void|place in &thorn;e childis heed &amp; entri&thorn; &thorn;erinne / &amp; &thorn;is passion maki&thorn; a|child deed ofte, or he haue ony age for to be holpen /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>/ Of enpostyms of &thorn;e rootis of a mannes eeris //</HEAD>
<P>Apostyme &thorn;at come&thorn; in a mannes eere or in &thorn;e rotis of a|mannis eeren.  &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; sumtyme in die cretico, whanne|&thorn;at a mannes kynde is not so mi&yogh;ti for to putte out &thorn;e gretnes of|&thorn;e mater bi sote ne bi noon o&thorn;er avoiding, &amp; &thorn;an kynde worchi&thorn;|what it mai, &amp; driue&thorn; &thorn;e matere an hi&yogh; to &thorn;e heed &amp; abidi&thorn; in &thorn;e|rotis of &thorn;e eeren, &amp; &thorn;ere it engendri&thorn; apostym.  &amp; in &thorn;is place it is|perilous, for it is so ny&yogh; &thorn;e heed &amp; veynes &amp; arterijs &amp; neruys /|&THORN;is manere enpostym ofte slee&thorn; a man whanne &thorn;e matere come&thorn;|violently // &THORN;e matere of &thorn;is enpostym, ou&thorn;er it is colre, or blood,|or fleume, or malancoli; &amp; alle &thorn;e signes herof ben aforseid / &THORN;e| cure of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="138b">&thorn;is enpostym mai not bigynne with repercussiuis, saue it|mote bigynne wi&thorn; mitigatiuis, &amp; with &thorn;ingis &thorn;at putti&thorn; out &thorn;e|matere / Waische &thorn;e place wi&thorn; a decoccioun of camomille soden &thorn;erinne|/ &amp; &thorn;anne aftir &thorn;at anoynte &thorn;e same place with oile of camomille,|&amp; &thorn;an wete wolle in &thorn;e same oile &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon, &amp; bi no|maner leue &thorn;ou not &thorn;at &thorn;ou leie in his eere oile of bittir almaundis,|for it is a greet help //  &para; If &thorn;e mater be deep &amp; it be hard for to|drawe it out, &thorn;an it were good to sette vpon &thorn;e place a drie ventose
<PB N="217">|for to helpe to drawe out &thorn;e matere, &amp; aftir resolue &thorn;e matere &amp;|leie &thorn;erto mitigatiuis for to do awei &thorn;e akynge / &para; If &thorn;e matere wole|not be resolued in &thorn;is maner, saue it bigynne&thorn; to be quitture &thorn;eron,|&thorn;an wi&thorn; tempere maturatiuis &thorn;at ben not to hote, make &thorn;e enpostym|quitture / Whanne &thorn;e place is wel rotid abide &thorn;ou no brekyng of &thorn;e|enpostym, saue opene &thorn;e place sotilly wi&thorn; an instrument &thorn;at is competent|&thorn;erto / &amp; &thorn;ou muste be wel war &thorn;at &thorn;ou touche no veyne, ne|noon arterie, ne no senewe, for &thorn;erof mi&yogh;t come <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="139a">myche perel, for |&thorn;ere ben nerues in &thorn;e same place, if &thorn;ei were kutt or prickid, &thorn;e|pacient mi&yogh;te lese his vois for euere / &amp; if &thorn;ere were ony veyne|kutt &thorn;erof, &thorn;er mi&yogh;t come greet perel &thorn;erof.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e place is|opened, &thorn;an make &thorn;e place clene wi&thorn; mundificatiuis, &thorn;at schulen be|seid in &thorn;e antidotarie / &amp; whanne &thorn;e place is perfitli clene, &thorn;anne|make &thorn;e fleisch wexe &amp; do &thorn;e cure perfitli / For bi yuel curyng in|&thorn;is place mi&yogh;t engendre a festre, &thorn;at ofte tyme come&thorn; of an|enpostym /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>Apostyms of &thorn;e necke and of &thorn;e &thorn;rote /</HEAD>
<P>Apostyms &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place, or it is wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; in &thorn;e|senewis, or in &thorn;e braun, or it is wi&thorn;innefor&thorn; bi &thorn;e place &thorn;at|a mannes mete goi&thorn; doun, or bi &thorn;e &thorn;rote, or it is bitwixe &thorn;e .ij.|placis in a place &thorn;at is clepid ismon.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ismon.  Sinonom. Barth.</I>, p. 26, "<I>Ysinon</I> est inter ysofagum et tracheam|arteriam."  Read <I>Ysmon</I>.  From <GAP DESC="Greek">, neck, narrow passage.  See|<GAP DESC="Greek"> in <I>Stephanus Thesaur.</I>  De propr. rer., lib. V., cap. 24, Add. 27,944,|fol. 49 bk.: "<I>&amp; it happi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is euel matere is somtyme al i-gedred wi&thorn;inne|&thorn;e skynne &thorn;at departi&thorn; &thorn;e weye of &thorn;e bree&thorn; from &thorn;e weye of &thorn;e mete &amp;|drynke, &thorn;at hatte isophagus &amp; brede&thorn; squynancye, &thorn;at slee&thorn; in on day.</I>"</NOTE>  &amp; comounli &thorn;e enpostyms|&thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place, come&thorn; of blood, or of fleume, &amp; ful seelden it|come&thorn; of colre, &amp; more lattere of malancoli.  &THORN;e humours &thorn;at ben|in &thorn;e cause,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See page 194, note 8.</NOTE> &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi signes aforseid / If &thorn;e matere be|in &thorn;e braun of the necke wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="139b">bi schewing |of &thorn;e enpostym wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;.  &amp; bi &thorn;ese signes &thorn;ou schalt knowe|whanne &thorn;e enpostym is wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, if &thorn;er is no letting in ysophagus|&thorn;ere &thorn;e mete schulde go adoun, &amp; if wijnd be not stoppid, &thorn;an &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t wite wel &thorn;at &thorn;e enpostym is wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &amp; also bi &thorn;e schewing|&thorn;at is outward / And if &thorn;e enpostym is wi&thorn;inne, &thorn;an &thorn;e|pacient schal not swolowe adoun his mete, ne drawe wel his bree&thorn; /|If &thorn;e enpostym &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne swelle greetly, his i&yogh;en wolen swelle|&thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; he schal not suffre his tunge in his mou&thorn;, &amp; he ne schal
<PB N="218">|not speke, &amp; &thorn;er wole go out miche spume of his mou&thorn; / &THORN;anne|summe lechis &thorn;at ben hardi wolen putte a smal tree in his &thorn;rote &amp;|breke &thorn;e enpostym, &amp; in &thorn;at maner &thorn;e pacient mai be delyuered;|saue &thorn;is maner worching is not sure, for in &thorn;is maner manie men|die&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;e dee&thorn; come&thorn; not of &thorn;e sijknes, saue it is defaute in &thorn;e|leche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it is defaute in &thorn;e leche</I>, Lat. medico imputatur.</NOTE> / &THORN;is maner sijknes &thorn;at is so hid wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, it mai be helid|wel in &thorn;e bigynnyng in &thorn;is maner<NOTE PLACE="foot">Much of our author's treatment is borrowed from <I>Avicenna</I>, Lib. III.,|Fen. 19, Cap. 11, ed. Ven. 1527, fol. 188.</NOTE> / If &thorn;e enpostym be hoot, &thorn;ou|schalt lete him blood in &thorn;e veine &thorn;at is clepid basilica, &amp; if &thorn;e| patient ha&thorn; had &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="140a">sijknes longe or &thorn;ou come to him, &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt lete him blood in &thorn;e middil veyne of &thorn;e arm &thorn;at is clepid|mediana, &amp; he schal blede so longe til he swoune almoost, &amp; principali|if he be strong &amp; ful of fleisch / In &thorn;e .ij. dai &thorn;ou schalt|lete him blood in &thorn;e veines vndir &thorn;e tunge / &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou do no|&thorn;ing aftir her counseil &thorn;at seien &thorn;at in &thorn;e firste bigynnyng &thorn;ou|schalt lete him blood in veines vndir &thorn;e tunge, &amp; after &thorn;at in &thorn;e|heed veine or in sum o&thorn;ere place.  For in &thorn;is manere leting blood,|if his bodi were replet, he mi&yogh;t li&yogh;tli be achekid//  &para; Whanne &thorn;ou|hast lete him blood as it is aforseid, &thorn;an make him a gargarisme|wi&thorn; a decoccioun of ro., sumac,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sumac</I>, Fr. Sumac; Arab. Summ&amacr;q.  "<I>Sumach</I> or <I>Sumack</I>, a kind of|rank-smelling Shrub that bears a black Berry, made use of by Curriers to|dress their Leather."  Phillips.</NOTE> balaustiarum, lentium, &amp; gallarum|wi&thorn; &thorn;e which be distemperid &thorn;erwi&thorn; diameron,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>diameron</I>, <GAP DESC="Greek">. <I>Vigo</I> Interpretation, "<I>Diamoron</I>, a confection|made of mulberries."</NOTE> or tordis of|a sparow, or of an hen, or &thorn;e tord of an hound &thorn;at eti&thorn; manie|boonys &amp; noon o&thorn;er mete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">By this kind of food the <I>album gr&aelig;cum</I>, the white dung of a dog is|produced.</NOTE> or a childis tord dried while it is soukyng.|&para; Also take an houndis tord &thorn;at eti&thorn; oonly boonis &amp; of|hennis, satureye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>satureye</I>, savory.  Wr. W&uuml;l. 609, 30 (xv), sauereye.</NOTE> ana, &amp; make &thorn;erof poudre &amp; distempere it wi&thorn;|water &amp; hony, &amp; make &thorn;erof a gargarisme, &amp; he schal drinke water|of barley, &amp; he schal no &thorn;ing ete, saue a &thorn;ing maad of wheete-bran<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="140b">| in &thorn;is maner<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: nihilque comedat nisi candarusium factum de furfure in hunc|modum.  <I>Matth. Sylv</I>.: "Candaros vel candarusium&mdash;est ordeum cui non|est cortex," from <GAP DESC="Greek">, grain, groat.</NOTE> / Take newe bran of whete &amp; caste &thorn;eron hoot water|&amp; hele it &amp; lete it stonde so an hour, &amp; &thorn;anne grinde it in a morter|wi&thorn; a pestel &amp; cole it, &amp; &thorn;anne se&thorn;e it wi&thorn; a litil salt &amp; &yogh;eue it &thorn;e
<PB N="219">|pacient / &amp; do &thorn;eron penidis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>penidis</I>, Vigo Interpr.  "<I>Penidie</I> are made of the Apothecaries wyth|suggre wrethen lyke ropes."  Fr. penide; Lat. penidium, from <GAP DESC="Greek">: spool|on which the woof is wound.&mdash;Compare <I>diapenidion</I> in <I>Piers the Plowman</I>,|ed. Skeat, 1886, II. p. 77, note.</NOTE>  &amp; if he mai not swolowe it adoun,|&thorn;anne sette a litil ventuse in &thorn;e welle of his necke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>tofore</I> inserted but deleted.</NOTE> with fier &amp; &thorn;an|he schal swolowe, &amp; anoynte al his necke tofore &amp; bihinde wi&thorn; oile|of camomille.  &amp; vpon &thorn;e anoyntyng leie wolle vnwaischen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolle vnwaischen, vn</I>, in margin.  Lat. lana succida.  Lewis, <I>Latin|Dict</I>., gives a reference from <I>App. Apologia</I>: recens lana tonsa succida|appellata est.</NOTE> &amp;|make a sutil plastre of a nest of irundinis, &amp; is good for &thorn;e|squinacie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>squinacie</I>, Lat. squinatia, quinsy.  See <I>Cathol. Angl.</I>, p. 357, note.</NOTE> &amp; is maad in &thorn;is maner / Take a nest of irundinis &amp;|boile it longe in watir, &amp; &thorn;anne cole it &thorn;oru&yogh; a seue &thorn;at &thorn;e grete|gobetis moun be cast awei / &THORN;an take &thorn;e rotis of lilie &amp; se&thorn;e hem|in o&thorn;er water &amp; rotis of bismalue, &amp; &thorn;e rote of brionie &amp; leues of|malue &amp; bismalue, &amp; violet, &amp; peritorie.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peritorie</I>, Lat. parietaria; wall-pellitory.</NOTE>  &amp; whanne &thorn;ei ben|boilid, grinde hem wel, &amp; medle hem wi&thorn; water of irundinum &thorn;at|is forseid, &amp; do &thorn;erto leueyne &amp; mele of fenigreci, &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;erto|oile or grese, &amp; make herof an enplastre / &THORN;is enplastre is good to|resolue enpostym &amp; make it quitture, whe&thorn;er <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="141a">it be wi&thorn;inne or wi&thorn;oute, |&amp; make it abrood upon a cloo&thorn; &amp; leie it vpon hoot.  &amp;|anointing is good wi&thorn; oile of camomille medlid wi&thorn; butter &thorn;at it|be oold &amp; not salt, &amp; after &thorn;e anoyntyng leie &thorn;ervpon wolle|vnwaische //  &para; <NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>The passage from lf. 141, l. 5 till lf. 141, bk., l.8 (p. 220. l. 15), is repeated|in lf. 143, with some alterations.  The corresponding words from the Latin|are quoted to show the independent character of the two versions.  l. 18, 19.|If &thorn;e &mdash; &mdash; manere] It is good if &thorn;e enpostym be wi&thorn;inne or &thorn;e more partie|be withynne, &amp; if it mai not be resolued ne do awei wi&thorn; repercussiuis, &thorn;an it|is good to vse gargarisms, &thorn;at ben maturatifs, maad in &thorn;is maner.  (<I>Bonum|est etiam si apostema fuerit interius, aut maior eius pars, cum tempus prolongatur|quod non repercutitur nec resoluitur: vti maturatiuis gargarismatibus|ut hoc.</I>)  20, 21. se&thorn;e &mdash; &mdash; cole hem] putte hem in water &amp; se&thorn;e hem in|water (<I>coque in aqua</I>).  21. or] &amp; medle &thorn;erwi&thorn;.  21, 22. medled wi&thorn; butter]|&amp; butter &amp; wijn.  &thorn;at maki&thorn; &mdash; &mdash; enpostym] &thorn;is wole make enpostym &thorn;at|is withynne in &thorn;e &thorn;rote maturatif (<I>maturat omne intrinsecum apostema siue|in gutture siue in stomacho siue in intestinis fuerit generatum</I>).</P><P>1, 2. &thorn;e aswaging] cesing.  and if] if.  2. schewe] be seen.  3, 4. be &mdash;|&mdash; arterie] be wel war of veynes &amp; arterijs.  4. whanne it is opened] &thorn;an.|5. and] <I>om</I>.  6, 8. wi&thorn;innefor&thorn; &mdash; &mdash; galle] al wi&thorn;inne &amp; wole not breke wi&thorn;|&thorn;e gargarism &thorn;at is aforseid of butter &amp; figis &amp; water &amp; wijn, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt|breke him wi&thorn; a medicyn &thorn;at haly &thorn;e abbot vside as wi&thorn; a gargarism of|gallarum.  (<I>Si fuerit intra, nec rumpatur: cum gargarismate pr&aelig;dicto|de butyro, ficuum aqua et vino rumpatur cum ingenio subtili Haly ab.|scilicet cum gargarismate stypticorum sicut decoctionis gallarum.</I>)  9. &amp;|se&thorn;e &mdash; &mdash; &thorn;erof a gargarism] <I>om</I>.  10. wole breke] breki&thorn; &thorn;e.  11. &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt bringe out &thorn;e mater] drawe out &thorn;e quitture.  11, 12. &amp; &mdash; butter] &amp; a|litil butter &thorn;erinne.  12. &amp; make &thorn;erof] &amp; herof he schal make.  12, 13. &amp;|lete him vse &thorn;is gargarism] <I>om</I>.  matere be drawe out &amp; &thorn;an] quitture be|drawen awei after &thorn;at.  14. of liquorice &mdash; tamarisci] wi&thorn; liquoris &amp; thamarisci|soden in watir.</P></NOTE>If &thorn;e enpostym be wi&thorn;inne, it is good &thorn;at me leie|&thorn;erto no repercussiuis, saue vse gargarismis maad in &thorn;is manere / &rx;,|ficus siccas, semen malue, semen lini, se&thorn;e &thorn;ese in water &amp; &thorn;an cole|hem, &amp; make &thorn;erof a gargarisme; or water of figis medlid wi&thorn;|butter, &thorn;at maki&thorn; maturatif eueri maner enpostym.</P>
<P>
<PB N="220">Whanne &thorn;e enpostym is rotid; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi &thorn;e|aswaging of &thorn;e akynge, &amp; if &thorn;e enpostym schewe wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;anne|opene it wi&thorn; an instrument, &amp; be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou hurte no senewe, ne|no veine, ne noon arterie.  &amp; whanne it is opened, make it clene|wi&thorn; mundificatiuis &thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie / And if|&thorn;e enpostym be wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt not breke it wi&thorn; &thorn;is|gargarisme &thorn;at is aforseid, saue &thorn;ou schalt make a gargarism &thorn;at|haly vside / Take galle, acacie, psidiarum, balaustie, aluminis| iamini<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sinonom. Barth</I>., p. 1, "<I>Alumen iamem, A. scissum, Alimen de pluma</I>,|idem."&mdash;<I>Matth. Sylv</I>. "Iamen est prouincia Iameni uel Aliamen."</NOTE> &amp; se&thorn;e hem in water &amp; cole it &amp; make <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="141b">&thorn;erof a gargarism,|for &thorn;is gargarism wole breke enpostym / Whanne &thorn;e enpostym is|broke, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt bringe out &thorn;e mater wi&thorn; hoot water, &amp; dissolue|&thorn;erinne butter &amp; oile of violets, &amp; make &thorn;erof a gargarism, &amp;|lete him vse &thorn;is gargarism til al &thorn;e matere be drawe out, &amp; &thorn;an|after &thorn;at make him a gargarism of liquiricie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>liquiricie</I>, lycoryce, <I>Pr. Parv</I>., p. 303.  See <I>lyquoris</I> in 2nd version.</NOTE> yreos &amp; tamarisci /|If &thorn;e matere be coold, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste vse hottere gargarism, &amp; &thorn;an|&thorn;ou muste vse mundificatiuis &thorn;at per be &thorn;erinne mirre, sarcocolle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sarcocolla</I> "Is the Gumme or liquore of a tree growyng in Persia."|<I>Halle. Table</I>, p. 109.</NOTE>|&thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie in &thorn;e chapiter of mundificatiuis.|&para; It falli&thorn; sumtyme &thorn;at for reume &thorn;at falli&thorn; adoun of a|mannis heed, &thorn;er wexi&thorn; in &thorn;e rote of &thorn;e tunge a maner round &thorn;ing|in &thorn;e gretnes of an almaunde, &amp; letti&thorn; a man &thorn;at he mai not wel|drawe his bree&thorn; ne ete his mete / &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt cure|him as it is forseid wi&thorn; &thorn;ingis &thorn;at voidi&thorn; &thorn;e matere &amp; wi&thorn; resoluynge|&thorn;ingis.  &para; I wole sette in &thorn;is place a cure &thorn;at bifel in &thorn;e citee of|mediolanensis of a ladi &thorn;at was .L. wynter oold, &amp; hadde a squinacie|of fleume &thorn;at occupiede al hir necke tofore wi&thorn;inne &amp; wi&thorn;oute,
<PB N="221">|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="142a">saue wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; &thorn;e swelling was moost, &amp; &thorn;e womman mi&yogh;te not |speke, ne swolowe in no mete.  &amp; &thorn;is womman was vndir &thorn;e cure of|a &yogh;ong man pat was my scoler, and he cowde not wel fare &thorn;erwi&thorn;,|&amp; &thorn;o he was in dispeir of hir lijf, I was sent after &amp; foond hir in|wickide staat,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in wickide staat</I>, in statu pessimo.</NOTE> for sche eet no mete in manye daies tofore, &amp; sche|durste not slepe for drede, lest sche schulde be achekid.  &THORN;an I|tastide hir pous, &amp; it was wondir feble, &amp; I tastide &thorn;e place of &thorn;e|enpostym, &amp; I knewe wel &thorn;at sche schulde be ra&thorn;ere achekid &thorn;an|&thorn;e enpostym wolde breke wi&thorn;oute or withynne, for &thorn;e matere was|so greet / &amp; &thorn;an I took a rasour, &amp; lokide where &thorn;e matere was|moost gaderid for to engendre quitture, &amp; it was moost able vndir|&thorn;e chyn, &amp; I felide &thorn;e place wi&thorn; myn hond &amp; tastide it aboute &thorn;at|I mi&yogh;te be war of nerues &amp; arterijs, &amp; &thorn;ere I made a wounde, &amp;|&thorn;ere I drowe out matere &thorn;at was corrupt, &amp; it was foul stynkynge|matere, &amp; al mi&yogh;te I not avoide anoon.  &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;e pacient hadde|bettere hir bree&thorn;, &amp; hir pous was confortid, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="142b">for &thorn;e lungis mi&yogh;te take |yn eir, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;e herte was comfortid, &amp; &thorn;an I &yogh;af hir bro&thorn;, &amp;|&thorn;at &yogh;ede out &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e wounde &thorn;e moost part.  &THORN;o I studiede how|I mi&yogh;te best do, &amp; I lete make a pipe of siluir, and putte it in at|hir mou&thorn; &amp; passide for&thorn;ere &thorn;an &thorn;e wounde was, &thorn;at it mi&yogh;te fulfille|&thorn;e place of &thorn;e &thorn;rote.  &amp; &thorn;an I leide al aboute hir necke mundificatiuis|&amp; maturatiuis for to quitture &thorn;e to&thorn;er deel of &thorn;e matere, &amp;|so I kepte it til &thorn;er come out of &thorn;e wounde a greet gobet of|viscous matere &amp; stynkyng, &amp; was schape as it were a greet gutt.|&amp; &thorn;erinne &thorn;e firste matere was engendrid, &amp; whanne &thorn;is was oute,|&thorn;e stynking wente awei &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;e womman bigan to be stronger,|&amp; whanne &thorn;e wounde was maad clene I driede it vp &amp; soudide it;|&amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e pacient was maad hool.  &para; Whanne &thorn;ou fyndist|coold matere rotid in &thorn;e forseid placis, &thorn;ou schalt not abide til &thorn;e|enpostym breke him-silf, saue &thorn;ou schalt opene it as it is aforseid /|&amp; if it be not rotid, &thorn;an make it more maturatif, &amp; opene it as it|is aforseid / And &thorn;is &thorn;ou muste wite &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;te <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="143a">not abide to |longe wi&thorn; &thorn;e openyng: for &thorn;e herte &amp; &thorn;e spiritual lymes ne mowe|not longe endure wi&thorn;outen eir.
</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<PB N="222">
<HEAD>/ Of enpostym of subcilio /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: De apostemate sub titillico, id est sub ascellis.  The translator|made <I>subcilio</I> out of <I>sub ascellis; titillicum</I>, arm-pit, from <I>titillo</I>, tickle.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>This maner of enpostym ha&thorn; no nede of repercussiuis for causis|&thorn;at ben aforseid, saue it is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>, above line.</NOTE> greet nede &thorn;at he be avoidid wel|wi&thorn; purgaciouns / And if &thorn;e enpostym be hoot, &thorn;ou schalt lete him|blood in a veyne &thorn;at is clepid vena nigra,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Matth. Sylv.: "Nigra uena, purpurea, media communis."  V. media =|V. mediana.</NOTE> or in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is|clepid basilica in &thorn;e arm.  &amp; if &thorn;e matere be coold, &thorn;an avoide &thorn;e|matere wi&thorn; medicyns maad of turbit or sum o&thorn;er medicyn &thorn;at|falli&thorn; &thorn;erfore.  &amp; as myche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou schalt take &thorn;erto wi&thorn;|medicyns &thorn;at haue not to greet drawyng / For if &thorn;ou leiest &thorn;erto|&thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben to strong drawing, &thorn;an &thorn;e enpostym wole wexe &thorn;e|more / &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt anoynte him wi&thorn; oile of camomille, &amp;|leie &thorn;ervpon wolle vnwaischen.  &amp; his dieting schal be sotil.  &amp; if|&thorn;is suffise not, &thorn;an leie vpon a maturatif / &amp; whanne it is rotid &thorn;ou| schalt opene <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="144a">it, &amp; principali if it be of coold matere.  Saue if<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>save if</I>, Lat. hoc saluo, si esset ...</NOTE>|&thorn;ere be glandule &thorn;eron, as it falli&thorn; ofte, &amp; it be not ouir al rotid,|as in oon place hard ano&thorn;ir place neische, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;is|in certein, &thorn;at &thorn;is passioun schal be clepid bubo, &amp; &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof is|hard.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: tunc nullam habes viam tutam, quum tunc est bubo, cuius cura|est difficilis.</NOTE>  For if &thorn;ou drawist out &thorn;e matere &thorn;at is neische,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts &amp;.</NOTE> &thorn;e matere|&thorn;at is hard is yuel to defie.  &amp; ofte &thorn;er come&thorn; &thorn;erof sclirosis or a|festre, &amp; it wole make a man yuel disposid &amp; feuerous, as G. sei&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: "totum corpus in mala tenet dispositione febris et doloris; tamquam|qui ad suam salutem, si nisi unam habuerit viam, ut dicit Galienus|velit nolit, per eam, etsi mala fuerit, pertransibit."  A more accurate translation|of this passage is given in Sl. 2463 (xv. cent.) in a treatise on Surgery|compiled from various authors, in which several chapters of Lanfranc's work|are embodied.  Ib. fol. 110 b.: "<I>And as Galyene scith, he that hath but|oone weye to his hele allthou&yogh;e &thorn;at weye be nat good, he muste holde hit wille|he nylle he.</I>"</NOTE>|&amp; &thorn;erfore aswage &thorn;e akynge &amp; &thorn;an make rotyng wi&thorn; maturatiuis;|for &thorn;e matere &thorn;at is rotid wole helpe to rotie &thorn;e matere &thorn;at is hard.|&amp; whanne it is al neische &thorn;anne opene it / If it so be &thorn;at it breke|bi it-silf or it be ful rotid, &thorn;an do &thorn;erto mundificatiuis, &amp; vpon &thorn;e|place &thorn;at is hard leie maturatiuis, &amp; kepe wel &thorn;e place &thorn;at is open|fro festrynge.  Mundificatiuis &amp; maturatiuis &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e|antidotarie pleynlier.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<PB N="223">
<HEAD>An enpostyme of &thorn;e helpers /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. De apostematibus adiutorii.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>This enpostym if it be hoot, &thorn;an lete him blood in &thorn;e arm|afor&yogh;ens, &amp; not in &thorn;e same side in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid|basilica, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste surely leie &thorn;erto repercussiuis, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="144b">&amp; if repercussiuis|suffisen not, &thorn;an resolue it &amp; leie maturatiuis &thorn;erto, &amp; &thorn;an|abide til it be perfitli<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>curid</I>, erased.</NOTE> quitturid, but if &thorn;e matere be so violent |&thorn;at it were in poynt<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in poynt</I>, Lat.: nisi materia esset adeo violenta quod esset ad corruptionem|membri parata.  "<I>And in such poynt the body bileueth.</I>"  Wright,|<I>Popular Treatise</I>, p. 140.&mdash;<I>"Engelond &amp; normandie. in god point he bro&yogh;te."|Rob. of Glouc.</I>, 8868.  Compare Fr. embonpoint.</NOTE> to schende &thorn;e lyme, &thorn;an opene it &amp; be wel|war of the braun &thorn;at is in &thorn;at place / Manie men &thorn;at ben vnkunnyng|&amp; supposen &thorn;at place to be fer fro ony noble lyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts &amp;.</NOTE> maki&thorn;|&thorn;eron a deep kuttyng, &amp; supposi&thorn; to haue gret worschip &thorn;erof; &amp;|manie idiotis wolen preise hem<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>silf</I>, erased.  Lat.: &amp; inde laudantur ab aliquibus idiotis.</NOTE> wel &thorn;erfore. &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e lacertis &thorn;erof|ben hurt; &amp; whanne &thorn;e lacertis ben soudid a&yogh;en, &thorn;an &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at it|seruede fore schal be contract, wherfore &thorn;e mannes arm mai be lost|in sum partie or in al / &THORN;erfore whanne &thorn;ou wolt kutte &thorn;is enpostym,|&thorn;ou schalt but kutte aboutefor&thorn; in &thorn;e skyn, &amp; not to depe|bi no maner wei for drede of &thorn;e braun, &amp; of senewis, &amp; of veynes|&amp; arterijs, &amp; whanne &thorn;e place is opened, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto mundificatiuis.|If &thorn;e openyng be ny&yogh; &thorn;e elbowe, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e enpostym be|moost quitturid, &thorn;ere be wel war &thorn;at &thorn;ou opene not &thorn;e enpostym|aboue &thorn;e elbowe .iij. fyngris brede, nei&thorn;er <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="145a">wi&thorn;inne ne wi&thorn;oute.  &amp; |also ny&yogh; &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e elbowe it is perilous, for it is gret hap if|it be euere soudid.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; it be soudid, &thorn;e mouynge of his arme|schal be lost.  If &thorn;er falle ony enpostym in &thorn;is place, &amp; it come of|greet matere so &thorn;at his bodi be replet, &thorn;an he mote haue greet|avoidyng wi&thorn; laxatiuis, &amp; &thorn;an resolue &thorn;e matere, and worche as it|is aforseid in &thorn;e general chapiter.  In &thorn;e same maner &thorn;ou schalt|cure &thorn;e enpostym of his armis &amp; of hise hondis.</P>
<P>&para; Panaricium<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vigo Interpret.: "Panaritium is an aposteme about the rootes of the|nayles, and it is called in Greke Paronichia; in latyn reduuia."  See Dufr.|s. v. redubi&aelig;.</NOTE> is an enpostym &thorn;at is in &thorn;e heed of a mannes|fyngir aboute &thorn;e nail / &amp; is swi&thorn;e hoot, &amp; greuous, &amp; reed, &amp; ful of|fier, &amp; sumtyme it maki&thorn; a man to haue &thorn;e feuere, &amp; sumtyme it|freti&thorn; awei al &thorn;e poynt of a mannes fyngir / &THORN;e firste cure of &thorn;is|enpostym is, &thorn;at first &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood, so &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis
<PB N="224">|falle &thorn;erfore as elde &amp; strenk&thorn;e &amp; custum.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make|him an enplastre of vinegre &amp; opium, &amp; vpon &thorn;e plastre &thorn;ou schalt|leie a lynnen cloo&thorn; wet in a decoccioun of psillij, or anoynte it wi&thorn;| an oynement &thorn;at is coold. &amp; in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>, above line.</NOTE> al maner &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="145b">take hede to|do awei &thorn;e greet hete &amp; saue his fyngir fro corrupcioun / If &thorn;e|akinge &amp; &thorn;e brennynge go not awei in &thorn;is maner, &amp; it be in wei for|to quitture,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in wei for to quitture</I>, Lat. in via maturationis.</NOTE> &thorn;an leie &thorn;ervpon scabiose grounden wi&thorn; grese &amp; do &thorn;e|cure &thorn;erto, as &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e cure of antrax &amp; carbunculis.|&amp; enpostyms &thorn;at come&thorn; in ioynctis &thorn;ou schalt fynde in her propre|place of akynge of ioynctes /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>Apostym wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; aboute &thorn;e spaudis and &thorn;e|gibbositees<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Gibbositas</I>, tumour.  <I>Dufr. Gloss</I>.&mdash;"Gibbosity, a bunching or standing|out of any part, especially of the Back."&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> //</HEAD>
<P>Apostym &thorn;at come&thorn; aboute the spaudlis wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, leie &thorn;ou|noon repercussif &thorn;erto, saue it is better to drawe &thorn;e matere|outward.  First &thorn;ou schalt purge him, for it is greet nede in &thorn;is|place, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;erto resoluinge &thorn;ingis &amp; maturatiuis;|&amp; whanne &thorn;e enpostym is rotid &thorn;ou schalt not abide, to it breke|it-silf,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: non expecta crepationem per se.</NOTE> &amp; principali in a coold cause, saue &thorn;ou schalt opene &thorn;e|enpostym &amp; drawe out &thorn;e quitture, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;erto|mundificatiuis, &amp; fulfille &thorn;e cure as it is aforseid / In &thorn;is place &thorn;ou| schalt take <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="146a">hede &thorn;at ofte tyme whanne &thorn;e enpostym is quitturid &amp;|is not opened wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;an it breki&thorn; inward bitwene &thorn;e .ij. ribbis,|&amp; whanne it is to-broke, &thorn;e pacient feli&thorn; but litil greuaunce &thorn;erof,|&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e quitture leue&thorn; wi&thorn;inne, &amp; in long tyme herof come&thorn; a|festre.  &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt not abide til it breke it-silf outward,|saue &thorn;ou schalt opene it whanne it is quitturid, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto|mundificatiuis &amp; cure it vp, as it is aforseid in o&thorn;ere enpostyms /|&para; If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ere engendre a festre &thorn;eron, or it be maad clene|&amp; entre inward, &thorn;an he mote vse waischingis &thorn;at ben mundificatif,|&amp; caste it in wi&thorn; an instrument maad in &thorn;e maner of a clisterie.|&amp; if &thorn;e hole &thorn;erof be streit wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt putt yn a|tente of &thorn;e pi&thorn; of eldre, or of a sponge, or of malum terre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Malum terre</I>, ciclamen, panis porcinus id. g<SUP>e</SUP> dilnote and erthenote."|<I>Alphita</I>, p. 107.  mal. t.=galluc.  Wr. W&uuml;., 133. 20.</NOTE> or
<PB N="225">|brionie, or gencian, &amp; putte into &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre.  &amp; &thorn;is wole|make &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre to wexe more wide &thorn;an it was, &thorn;at &thorn;e|ende of &thorn;e instrument mowe be putt &thorn;at schal be schape in &thorn;e|maner of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="146b">a clisterie.  &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt se&thorn;e hony &amp; mirre in |watir, so &thorn;at &thorn;er be .x. partis of water, &amp; of hony .ij. partis, &amp; of|mirre .ij. partis, &amp; if &thorn;ou doist &thorn;erto ysope &amp; sauge, it wole be &thorn;e|bettir / Sumtyme it is good for to do wijn in &thorn;e stide of watir, &amp;|principali if &thorn;e place be wi&thorn;outen ony hete.  &amp; &thorn;is decoccioun &thorn;ou|schalt caste into &thorn;e festre wi&thorn; an instrument as it is aforseid, &amp;|make &thorn;at &thorn;e pacient turne hidir &amp; &thorn;idir, vpward &amp; dounward, &thorn;at|it mowe waische wel &thorn;e place &thorn;ere &thorn;e quitture is.  &amp; &thorn;an make &thorn;e|patient turne &amp; ligge vpon &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre, &amp; make him cow&yogh;e|&thorn;at al &thorn;e quitture mai goon out wi&thorn; &thorn;e decoccioun.  &amp; whanne it is|al oute, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make him a tent &amp; anoynte it in oile &thorn;at &thorn;e|wounde close not togidere.  &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt worche, til &thorn;ou se &thorn;e|waisching come out of &thorn;e festre withoute ony quitture.  &amp; whanne|&thorn;e festre is al clene, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt fulfille &thorn;e cure with oynementis|&thorn;at wolen regendre fleisch &amp; fulfille &thorn;e cure as it is aforseid / If it|so be &thorn;at &thorn;e wei of &thorn;e festre &thorn;at goi&thorn; in &amp; out <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="147a">be bicome hard &amp; |callous so &thorn;at it be a verri festre, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste hete an hoot yren|&thorn;at it be as greet as &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre &amp; brenne al &thorn;e hardnes|&thorn;erof, &amp; aftirward make &thorn;e cruste falle awei with buttir &amp; o&thorn;ere|&thorn;ingis, &amp; &thorn;anne make it clene, &amp; &thorn;an drie it &amp; soude it.</P>
<P>&para; Also it bifalli&thorn; &thorn;at children han grete bocchis in her brest, &amp;|&thorn;at come&thorn; of cow&yogh;inge &thorn;at putti&thorn; out &thorn;e matere, &amp; also it come&thorn;|of greet wynd &thorn;at putti&thorn; out &thorn;e matere / &THORN;e cure herof in &thorn;e firste|bigynnyng is in &thorn;is maner for to aswage cow&yogh;ing, as almaundis|grounden wi&thorn; penidis &amp; temperid with a decoccioun of fenel, &amp; &thorn;is|he schal vse / Also take swete almaundis .ij. partis, dragaganti,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vigo Interpr.: "<I>Dragagantum</I>.  Tragacantha is a brode. &amp; a woddy|rote appearyng about the earth, wher-oute manye lowe braunches sprynge,|spreading themselues al about.  There cleaueth to thys rote, a gummy liquour|of a bright colour, &amp; somwhat swete in tast, which they cal commenly|dragagantum."</NOTE>|semen citoniorum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>citonium</I> = Cotonea malus, Cydonea, "Quince."  Wr. W&uuml;., 13, 19.|"<I>Citonium</I>, goodaepel."</NOTE> ana, oon parti, Iulip quod sufficit.  &amp; make|herof a souping medicyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a souping medicyn</I>, Lat. medicina sorbilis.</NOTE> &thorn;at it be as &thorn;icke as hony.  &amp; whanne|&thorn;e cow&yogh;inge is aswagid, &thorn;an make him a ba&thorn; wi&thorn; rotis of altea, &amp;
<PB N="226">|leues of malue, &amp; fenigrec, &amp; lyne seed soden in watir, &amp; &thorn;is schal|be cast vpon &thorn;e enpostym wi&thorn; a vessel holden an hi&yogh;e &thorn;ere from /| &THORN;anne aftirward &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="147b">dissolue &thorn;e matere &amp; make it neische|with medycyns &thorn;at ben forseid in hard enpostyms, &amp; &thorn;an cure it vp|as it is aforseid in &thorn;e enpostyms of wijnd.  &para; A greet boch &thorn;at|come&thorn; of &thorn;e passioun of &thorn;e riggeboon, whanne &thorn;ei ben of &thorn;e ioynct,|is incurable whanne it is confermed /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="9">
<HEAD>Of an enpostym apperinge in &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e stomac /</HEAD>
<P>Whanne &thorn;ere schewi&thorn; an enpostym in &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e stomac|&amp; aboute &thorn;e regioun of &thorn;e lyuer &amp; of &thorn;e splene: &thorn;ou&yogh;|summen wollen take hede to &thorn;e contrarie, bi my general rule<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rule</I>, above line.</NOTE> it is|good &amp; profitable to comforte &thorn;e place wi&thorn; oile of mastic, &amp; oile of|spica, &amp; oile of lilie, &amp; wi&thorn; cold enplastris of rosis, &amp; of absinthio,|squinanto, cipero, citonijs wi&thorn; mele of barli &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis.  &amp; &thorn;ou|schalt be wel war of repercussiuis, whanne &thorn;e enpostym is ny&yogh; ony|principal lyme, saue &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;erto resoluyng &amp; maturatif|&thorn;ingis.  &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;ei be not medlid wi&thorn; no &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben repercussif;| for if &thorn;ou leidist repercussiuis vpon &thorn;e stomak, or <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="148a">&thorn;e|lyuere, or &thorn;e splene, &thorn;ei wolde be enfeblid &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; to al &thorn;e accioun|of &thorn;e bodi wolde be enpeirid; for &thorn;ese lymes serue&thorn; principaly for|to norische al &thorn;e bodi / &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt not vse in &thorn;is caas pure|maturatiuis, ne pure repercussiuis, ne colde &thorn;ingis / What schalt|&thorn;ou do in &thorn;is caas? &THORN;ou schalt avoide &thorn;e matere, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt comforte|&thorn;e place with stiptikis, &amp; tempere attractiuis, &amp; do awei &thorn;e|matere.  &amp; if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t not, &thorn;an resolue &thorn;e matere, for it is greet|perel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>perel</I>, above line.</NOTE> of &thorn;is enpostym, for it wole li&yogh;tli turne in to selirosym, &amp;|&thorn;an it wole be hard to resolue, &amp; aftirward it wole be cause of &thorn;e|dropesie / &THORN;erfore if &thorn;ou seest<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seest</I>, in margin.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;e enpostym bicome hard, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou muste leie &thorn;erto mollificatiuis &amp; wi&thorn; comfortatiuis.  &amp; &thorn;ou muste|be in &thorn;is caas ful wijs.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e enpostym is maturid, &thorn;an|opene it as it is aforseid, &amp; leie &thorn;erto mundificatiuis &amp; cure vp &thorn;e|enpostym as it is aforseid.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="10">
<HEAD>// Of an enpostym &thorn;at come&thorn; in iguine .id est &thorn;e|gryndis</HEAD>
<P>Apostym come&thorn; often time in iguine for vlcera of &thorn;e &yogh;erde &amp; of| &thorn;e feet, for <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="148b">&thorn;e place is discending adoun of humours to &thorn;at
<PB N="227">|place,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: S&aelig;pe prouenit apostema in inguine propter vlcera virg&aelig; et pedum:|propterea quod locus est descensus humorum ad illa loca.  The translator|mistook "descensus" sb. for descensus part.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;an it is not so greet drede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>drede</I>, above line.</NOTE> &thorn;erof.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare Guiliel. de Salic. I. 42.  Sl. 277, fol. 5 b.: "<I>This seeknesse is|cleped bubo or draguncell,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">Dufr. <I>Gloss</I>.: "Dracunculus, ulceris vel cancri species."</NOTE> <I>or aposteme of &thorn;e grynde, &amp; it is maad as oftest|of cold matere whiche is cast out of &thorn;e lyuere to &thorn;oo places, &amp; o&thorn;erwhile it|is hoot.  It is maad also, when a man is seek in his &yogh;erde for fil&thorn;ehede of|wommen or of o&thorn;er cause</I>."</NOTE>  Saf if his bodi be|ful of wickid humours, &thorn;an it is greet drede &thorn;erof / &thorn;is matere &thorn;ou|muste resolue in &thorn;is maner.  Take oile of camomille &amp; anointe &thorn;erwi&thorn;|&thorn;e enpostym, &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon wolle vnwaische, &amp; if it resolue|not in &thorn;is maner, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto maturatiuis, as it is aforseide. &para; If|&thorn;e matere be hoot, &thorn;an lete him blood in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid|sophena.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt sotille<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sotille</I>, Lat. attenuare.  O.Fr. soutilier.  Compare <I>sotilen</I> with the|abstract meaning, "argue subtly."&mdash;<I>Piers the Plowman</I>, ed. Skeat, Gloss.</NOTE> his dieting, &amp; leie &thorn;erto resoluyng|&thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben not to strong, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei drawe not to harde.  &amp;|whanne &thorn;e cours of humours ceessi&thorn;, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto stronge resoluyng|&thorn;ingis. &amp; in &thorn;is caas &thorn;is is good &thorn;erfore: lie of askis &amp; of|vryne, &amp; wete &thorn;erinne stupis &amp; leie vpon &thorn;e enpostym, for &thorn;is|maki&thorn; maturatif &amp; waasti&thorn; it sotilly &amp; drie&thorn; it / If &thorn;ou my&yogh;t not|resolue it, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto maturatiuis &amp; opene it, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto|mundificatiuis &amp; hele it vp as it is aforseid /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="11">
<HEAD>Of an enpostym of &thorn;e haunche &amp; of &thorn;e cox.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is place ofte tyme engendri&thorn; an enpostym, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt|fynde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="149a">&thorn;ere &thorn;e curis &thorn;erof in &thorn;e chapitre of dolour of ioynctis; |saue if &thorn;e enpostym be without &thorn;e haunche in &thorn;e hipe, or in &thorn;e leg,|or in &thorn;e foot, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;erto &thorn;e same cure &thorn;at is aforseid|in &thorn;e enpostyms of &thorn;e arm.  Saf herof &thorn;ou schalt take kepe, &thorn;at|oftetymes an enpostym gaderi&thorn; in a mannes hipe al wi&thorn;inne in &thorn;e|depnes of it, &thorn;at a leche schal not knowe it, but if he be &thorn;e more|wijs / &THORN;erfor ypo[cras] sei&thorn;: in placis &thorn;ere enpostym is, and &thorn;e quitture|schewe not out, it is perilous / &THORN;erfor &thorn;ou muste taste it wi&thorn;|&thorn;i fyngris, &amp; loke where it is moost maturid, &amp; opene it, and|drawe out &thorn;e quitture, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto mundificatiuis, &amp; &thorn;an fulfille|&thorn;e cure as it is aforseid /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="12">
<PB N="228">
<HEAD>Apostym of &thorn;e &yogh;erde &amp; ballokis /</HEAD>
<P>Ri&yogh;t as enpostyms come&thorn; in o&thorn;ere lymes, ri&yogh;t so &thorn;ei comen in|a mannes &yogh;erde &amp; in hise ballokis, of humours hoot or cold,|as bi &thorn;ese signes &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe.  Sumtyme a mannes &yogh;erde swelli&thorn;|with wynd, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi enpostyms of wynd &thorn;at ben|aforseid.  &amp; it falli&thorn; ofte to &yogh;onge children,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 59 b.: accidit quibusdam iuvenibus calidis.</NOTE> &amp; also &thorn;is enpostym| &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="149b">in &thorn;is maner, if &thorn;e place be hard &amp; heuy &amp; &thorn;er is|no difference bitwixe &thorn;e colour herof &amp; of &thorn;at o&thorn;er partie of his|bodi.</P>
<P>&para; In an hoot enpostym of &thorn;e &yogh;erde or of &thorn;e ballokis, &thorn;ou schalt|lete him blood in a veyne &thorn;at is clepid basilica in &thorn;e same side, &amp;|in &thorn;e .ij. dai lete him blood in &thorn;e sophene / Also &thorn;ou schalt forbede|him wijn &amp; fleisch &amp; al maner swete metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; blood or|colre.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;erto medecyns to putt awei &thorn;e mater,|&thorn;at ben maad in &thorn;is maner.  &rx;, cortices granatorum, rosas siccas,|&amp; lentes &amp; se&thorn;e hem in water til &thorn;ei dissolue, &amp; &thorn;an grinde hem in|a morter wi&thorn; oile of roses &amp; a litil vinegre, &amp; make herof an enplastre|&amp; leie it &thorn;eron hoot / Also take succi portulace siluestris, &amp;|olium rosarum &amp; a litil vinegre, &amp; wete heryn a lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp; leie|it aboute &thorn;e &yogh;erde &amp; hise ballokis / Whanne &thorn;e cours of &thorn;e mater|ceessi&thorn;, &thorn;an do &thorn;erto mele of barly &amp; of benis, or distempere &thorn;ese|wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey &amp; wi&thorn; iuys of morel &amp; oile of roses, &amp; leie|&thorn;eron.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e enpostym goi&thorn; awey, &thorn;an leie &thorn;eron enplastre| of mele of benis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="150a">&amp; of fenigrec &amp; camomille distemperid with gotis|talow / If &thorn;is enpostym gadere quitture &amp; vlcera, &thorn;an cure it as &thorn;ou|schalt fynde in &thorn;e chapitre of vlcers of &thorn;e &yogh;erde.</P>
<P>&para; A coold empostym &thorn;at is in &thorn;e ballokis schal be curid wi&thorn;|anoynting of &thorn;e matere wi&thorn; medicyns or wi&thorn; scharpe suppositorijs;|for &thorn;is drawi&thorn; &thorn;e mater fro &thorn;e ballokis / If it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e enpostym|be woxen hard in &thorn;e ballokis, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto &thorn;is enplastre|&thorn;at I haue ofte preued / Take bran of whete &amp; grinde it wel in|a morter til it bicome al poudre, &amp; &thorn;an distempere it wi&thorn; oximel|maad of .ij. partis of vinegre &amp; oon partie of hony, &amp; dissolue|&thorn;erinne gum armoniac &amp; make herof an enplastre &amp; leie it on hoot,|&amp; &thorn;is schal be remeued ofte.  &THORN;is is auicens medicyns.</P>
<P>&para; If a mannes &yogh;erde be swollen wi&thorn; wijnd &amp; &thorn;e cause be hoot,|&thorn;an lete him blood; if it be coold, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto enplastris, &amp; in|&thorn;is caas among alle opere &thorn;ingis &thorn;is is good / Take oile of roses iiij.
<PB N="229">|partis, of wex o part, melte hem togidere &amp; &thorn;an waische hem in|coold water til it bicome as it were a whit oynement, &amp; herwi&thorn;|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="150b">anoynte &thorn;e place / If it be hoot, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make him caste, |&amp; &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him agnus castus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Besides the names given in <I>N. E. Dict</I>., s. v. Agnus castus, there are:|"<I>Agnus castus</I>, frutex est, i. bischopeswort."  <I>Sinon. Barth</I>., p. 1.  "A. c.,|toutsayne."  Wr. W&uuml;. p. 562, 24 (xvth cent.). "Chastlambe" in <I>Maplet</I>.  A|greene Forest, fol. 39.  De Propr. Rer. (Add. MS. 27944, fol. 216<I>a</I>): "<I>Agnus|Castus is an herbe hoot and dryue and ha&thorn; vertu to kepe men &amp; wommen|chaste a plinius sei&thorn;.  &para; &THORN;erfore wommen of Rome vsede to bere wi&thorn; hem|&thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;is herbe in dyrige and service for dede men, whanne &thorn;ey moste|nedes lyve chaste for comyn honestee.  &para; &THORN;is herbe is alway grene as dyascorides|sei&thorn;, and platearius also, and &thorn;e flour &thorn;erof is nameliche y-cleped|agnus castus.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; seed of rue &amp; comyn &amp;|anise &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis &thorn;at waasti&thorn; wijnd, &amp; make an enplaster of|&thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &thorn;at distrie&thorn; wijnd /  &para; An enplaster &thorn;at gilbert made|for swellyng of a mannes &yogh;erde &amp; it is mitigatif .&rx;, crummis of|whit breed &amp; grinde hem in a morter &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; watir, &amp;|&thorn;an boile hem til &thorn;ei bicome &thorn;icke, &amp; do &thorn;erto a litil oile &amp; a litil|hony, &amp; &thorn;an boile hem togidere &amp; leie it vpon hoot // If a mannes|&yogh;erde be swollen wi&thorn; hete of liggyng bi a womman, &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt|helpe him / Take leues of wi&thorn;i &amp; se&thorn;e hem in water &amp; ba&thorn;e his|&yogh;erde herynne &amp; binde &thorn;erto &thorn;e leues // Also se&thorn;e lynseed &amp; leues|of malue &amp; grynde hem togidere &amp; make herof a plastre /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="13">
<HEAD>The cure of scrophularum &amp; glandulum /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, f. 97 (see p. 222, note 8): "<I>Because &thorn;at &thorn;e cure of scrophules|&amp; glaundules, as who seith, is bothe oone, but &thorn;er is a difference be as moche|as scrophules ben for &thorn;e more partie of malancolye ...</I>"</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Cure of glandularum &amp; scrophularum is almoost oon, saue|herof is a difference / Scrophule come&thorn; &thorn;e moost part of|malancoli &amp; ben worse to dissolue.  &amp; glandule come&thorn; &thorn;e most|part of fleume, &amp; ben li&yogh;ter to resolue / In bo&thorn;e causis it is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="151a">necessarie|to purge &thorn;e matere.  &amp; &thorn;e medicyn laxatijf maad of turbit is |good &thorn;erfore &thorn;at is aforseid in &thorn;e chapitre of allopucia, or in &thorn;is|maner as .A. maki&thorn; it / &rx; turbit zinzi,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ZZ.</NOTE> zucare .&yogh; .ij, &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;is|ofte, or trociscus de turbit maad wi&thorn; diarubarbe, &amp; &thorn;ou must sotile|his dietyng, &amp; he schal not ete to miche, &amp; he schal drinke no|water, &amp; he schal holde his heed an hi&yogh;, &amp; he schal kepe him fro|wepinge, &amp; he schal not, whanne he is ful, slepe anoon &thorn;ervpon, &amp;|&thorn;ou schalt anoynte &thorn;e place with oile of camomille, &amp; wi&thorn; oile of
<PB N="230">|lilie, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is oile &thorn;at is apreued / &rx;, radices electerij,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. elaterium, <GAP DESC="Greek">. <I>Alphita</I>, p. 53, "<I>Elacterium</I> succus eueurbite|agrestis idem.  sed <I>electerides</I> sunt cucumeres agrestes tam fructus|eorum quam ipsa herba."  Vigo <I>Interpr</I>.: "Elaterium is the iuice of a|wild cocomber."</NOTE> radices|malue visci,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>malua viscum</I> = Alth&aelig;a officinalis, marsh-mallow.</NOTE> &amp; kutte hem smal &amp; leie hem in oold oile of oliuarum|&amp; do hem in a vessel of glas, &amp; sette &thorn;is glas in a vessel of water,|&amp; make &thorn;e water to se&thorn;e, &amp; be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou saue &thorn;e glas fro breking.|&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is oile anointe him, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;eron wolle vnwaische / And|if &thorn;is suffise not, make him a plastre of gotis tordis &amp; oximel, or|quik lyme &amp; swynys grese &thorn;at it be freisch / &amp; oold,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words omitted.  Lat.: cum axungia porcina, sine sale antiquo.</NOTE> or &thorn;is|medicyne / &rx; staphisacre, seminis-lini,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>staphisacre seminis. nitri.</I></NOTE> farini orobi, resine <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="151b">albe &amp;| make herwi&thorn; an enplastre wi&thorn; ole &amp; vinegre / Also ano&thorn;er &thorn;at is|swi&thorn;e good.  Take radices lilij, &amp; seminis lini, ana,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>partes &aelig;quales</I> om.</NOTE> boile hem in|wijn til &thorn;ei dissolue, &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;erto of culuer tordis &amp; make it a|&thorn;icke plastre, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt putte &thorn;erto culuer toordis more or lesse|as &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at &thorn;e mater resolue&thorn; more or lesse, as &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at|it nedi&thorn;.  &para; Also diaculon<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Diachylon</I>, a Plaister made of the Mucilages or pappy Juice of certain|Fruits, Seeds, and Roots, whose Office is to ripen and soften."  Phillips.</NOTE> rasis, &amp; diaculon Iohannes Mesue &thorn;at|schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, ben good for to resolue scrophulas /|Whanne &thorn;ou resoluest &thorn;e mater &amp; sum &thorn;erof goi&thorn; awei, &amp; sum|&thorn;erof leue&thorn; hard, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;erto sumtyme mollificatiuis &amp;|sumtyme resoluyng &thorn;ingis //</P>
<P>&para; Glandule &amp; scrophule ben parti of douce fleume or of blood;|it is ful hard to make hem clene, for sum partie &thorn;erof wole leue|hard &amp; wole not bicome maturatif.  &THORN;ou schalt [not]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>not</I> om.  Lat.: Non ergo festines in earum apertura.</NOTE> haste to|opene hem saue &thorn;ou schalt leue if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, til it be al rotid, &amp;|&thorn;an open it &amp; leie &thorn;erto mundificatiuis / &amp; in &thorn;is place it is good|to leie &thorn;erto vnguentum apostolorum &amp; poudre of affodille &amp; o&thorn;ere|li&yogh;t corosiuis. &amp; &thorn;ou schalt in no maner leie &thorn;erto realgar,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>realgar</I>, Arab.  See Skeat, <I>Et. Dict.  Alphita</I>, p. 156, <I>Realgar</I> vel|<I>risalgar</I> est uena terre."  Vigo <I>Interpret</I>., "Realgar is made of brymstone,|vnslaked lyme, and orpigmente.  It kylleth rattes."</NOTE> ne noon| violent <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="152a">&thorn;ingis, &amp; leie &thorn;eron a mundificatif in which be medlid|rotis of lilie wel soden, for &thorn;is mundificatif maki&thorn; clene &amp; also|quitturi&thorn; &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;e matere / &THORN;ou must take greet diligence|for to make clene glandulas &amp; scrophulas, for &thorn;ei ben ful hard
<PB N="231">|to make clene, &amp; ofte &thorn;er engendri&thorn; &thorn;erof festris / &para; If &thorn;ou desirist|to cure glandulas &amp; scrophulas wi&thorn; kuttyng, loke wher glandula or|scrophula be neische, &amp; be war of veynes &amp; senewis, &amp; loke &thorn;at|&thorn;er be no veine &thorn;ere ny&yogh;.  &THORN;an take him vp wi&thorn; &thorn;i lift hond &amp;|drawe him vp as hi&yogh;e as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &amp; kutte &thorn;e skyn endelongis &thorn;e|necke, &amp; be war &thorn;ou touche not &thorn;e cloo&thorn; &thorn;at he is folde &thorn;erinne, &amp;|&thorn;ane score<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>score</I>.  Lat. discarnare.</NOTE> him &amp; drawe him out al hool with &thorn;e cloo&thorn;, &amp; if &thorn;er|leue ony &thorn;ing &thorn;erof, caste &thorn;eron poudre of affodille or sum o&thorn;er li&yogh;t|corosif, &amp; &thorn;anne regendre fleisch &amp; soude it vp / If it so be &thorn;at|glandula or scrophula be closid with veynes or wi&thorn; arterijs, &thorn;an|kutte him not in no maner, for &thorn;er mi&yogh;t come greet perel &thorn;erof.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, fol. 98: "<I>But if &thorn;e glandule or &thorn;e scrofule be intrikes</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. intricata.</NOTE><I> with|veynes, arteries o&thorn;er synewes, so &thorn;at &thorn;ei cleue o&thorn;er be faste knytte to hem,|for nothing &thorn;ou schall ny&yogh;e hem nother with Iren no&thorn;er with noone other|corosyue medecyne.</I>"</NOTE></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="14">
<HEAD>// &THORN;e cure of &thorn;e cancre not vlcerid &amp; his cure /</HEAD>
<P>Causis &amp; difference &thorn;ou hast herd of a cankre <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="152b">&amp; in what|maner &thorn;ou schalt cure cancrum &thorn;at is not vlceratus / Rasis |sei&thorn;, &amp; it is soo&thorn;, &amp; I haue seen ofte tyme, &thorn;at whanne ony mantouchi&thorn;|a cancre wi&thorn; iren or wi&thorn; ony medicyn corrosif, but if &thorn;ei|kutte him awey clene wi&thorn; alle his rotis, ellis &thorn;ei maki&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e|cancer is vlceratus / &amp; for to make a cancre vlceratum, it ne falli&thorn;|for no goodnes, saue it maki&thorn; &thorn;e patient haste &thorn;e fastere to his|dee&thorn;, &amp; schorti&thorn; his lijf &amp; bringi&thorn; him in turment //  &para; &THORN;erfore if|a cancre be in a place &thorn;at he mai be kutt awei wi&thorn; alle hise rotis,|whanne he is kutt awei, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt brenne &thorn;e place wi&thorn; an|hoot iren or wi&thorn; gold, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt fulfille &thorn;e cure as it is|aforseid in &thorn;e chapitre of a cancre &thorn;at is vlceratus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A different opinion is expressed in Sl. 2463, fol. 115: "<I>The cure of &thorn;e|canker is done in two maners.  The tone cure is for to kutte away all &thorn;e|membre &thorn;at &thorn;e canker is inne, with all &thorn;e syknesse; and &thorn;is is an yuell cure|and may be done, but it is not plesaunt.</I>"  Ibid., fol. 115 b.: "<I>And yf &thorn;er|be noon o&thorn;er remedie but for to cutte hit away with alle &thorn;e rotes, me thenkith|hit is more honest to leue hit &thorn;anne to do hit.</I>"</NOTE>  &para; If it so be|&thorn;at &thorn;e cancre be perfit &amp; greet, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt touche him wi&thorn;|noon iren ne wi&thorn; no medicyn corrosif, saue &thorn;ou schalt kepe &thorn;e|patient wi&thorn; good dieting, &amp; he schal ofte tymes haue medicyns for|to purge malancolie wi&thorn; gootis whey &amp; with epithimo, &amp; sumtyme|lete him blood, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt anoynte &thorn;e place wi&thorn; vnguentum rasis
<PB N="232">| de thutia, &thorn;at is<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="153a"> <NOTE PLACE="foot">In later hand at the bottom of the page: <I>contra ffetorem cancri.  &rx;|pulueris corticis quercus ffarine sileginis ana succi appii mell ana succus &amp;|amp;|mell inspissentur decoque super ynguem cum puluere ffarina.  Item decoque|puluerem corticis quersini in aqua et inde tepide laua canserem a ffetore|paliando.</I></NOTE>aforseid in cura cancri vlcerati.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt leie|&thorn;eron colde leues, &amp; alwei &thorn;is schal be &thorn;in entencioun, for to kepe|&thorn;at &thorn;e cancre wexe not ne rotie not / I haue seen ful manye lechis|&thorn;at hadden greet name in cirurgie &thorn;at founden cancris in men, and|wexe not, &amp; &thorn;e cancris were not vlcerati &amp; mi&yogh;te ful long tyme|haue lyued if he hadde be kept aftir my teching in &thorn;is book; saue|vnkunnyng cirurgians wene&thorn; &thorn;at in kutting of a cancre &thorn;ei schulde|finde quitture &amp; ben disseyued, &amp; so disseyuen hem-silf &amp; also &thorn;e|patient, &amp; &thorn;an whanne &thorn;ei han kutt &thorn;ei fynde nou&yogh;t saue fleisch|corrupt wi&thorn;out quitture in &thorn;e maner of a sponge, wherfore &thorn;e lippis|of &thorn;e wounde wole come a&yogh;en worse &thorn;an &thorn;ei were tofore &amp; more|stynking. &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e greet stynkinge &thorn;e spirit is schent, &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e|patient &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere drawe toward &thorn;e dee&thorn; / &amp; if &thorn;e cancre were not|vlceratus &thorn;e patient mi&yogh;te lyue longe &thorn;erwith.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="15">
<HEAD>Bocium &thorn;at come&thorn; of humours corrupt.</HEAD>
<P>Bocium is a postym &thorn;at come&thorn; of humours, &amp; principali it is|engendrid of fleume corrupt / Sumtyme it come&thorn; of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="153b">hote| enpostyms, as whanne &thorn;ei ben rotid &amp; not opened.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e|subtil mater be drawen out, &thorn;at o&thorn;ere part bicome&thorn; hard &amp; leue&thorn;|&thorn;ere longe tyme / &amp; sumtyme a rume<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rume</I>, rheum, O.Fr. reume.</NOTE> falli&thorn; adoun of his heed into|his necke &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e matere wexe more / &THORN;is maner enpostym ha&thorn;|manie diuers signes / Sum maner &thorn;erof is lijk as it were cley, &amp;|summe is lijk schellis.  Summe is as it were chese, &amp; summe is as|it were drastis of oile, &amp; so &thorn;is enpostym in his corrupcioun taki&thorn;|manie diuers colouris /</P>
<P>&THORN;is enpostym schal be helid wi&thorn; drawynge &thorn;ingis &amp; wastynge|&thorn;at schulen be taken bi &thorn;e mou&thorn; &amp; leid to wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; / &THORN;ou schalt|&yogh;eue him bi &thorn;e mou&thorn; a medicyn for to purge fleume, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt &yogh;eue him a medicyn for to waaste &thorn;e matere &amp; is maad in &thorn;is|maner / &rx; paruam plantam nucis a terra cum suis radicibus extirpatam|id est take a litil plauntein of a note &amp; take it vp of &thorn;e ground|wi&thorn; alle hise rotis, &amp; grynde it wi&thorn; greynes of peper, so &thorn;at if &thorn;er be|of &thorn;e notis .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij., &thorn;an do &thorn;erto of peper <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt boile
<PB N="233">|in a quart of wyn <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="154a">of paris til it come to &thorn;e half, &amp; &thorn;anne cole it, |&amp; herof &thorn;e patient schal take euery dai <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> ij. // &para; Enplastris &thorn;at|wasti&thorn; ben enplastris &thorn;at enpostyms of fleume be wastid &thorn;erwith /|If &thorn;ou desirist for to cure it wi&thorn; kuttyng, &thorn;an &thorn;ou must loke, wher|&thorn;e matere &thorn;at is wi&thorn;inne be neische or hard.  &amp; wher it be among|veynes &amp; arterijs, &thorn;ou schalt touche it wi&thorn; noon iren in no maner /|If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e mater be neische &amp; if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;te kutte it for|perels &thorn;at ben forseid, &thorn;an kutte it &amp; drawe out &thorn;e mater, &amp; leie|&thorn;erto mundificatiuis, &amp; alle &thorn;ingis as it is aforseid in &thorn;e general|chapitre / If &thorn;e mater be hard &amp; &thorn;e enpostym be hangynge &amp; be|fro veynes &amp; arterijs, &thorn;an kutte &thorn;e skyn endelongis aboue, &amp; be war|&thorn;at &thorn;ou touche not &thorn;e bagge &thorn;at bocium sitti&thorn; &thorn;eron &amp; scarre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scarre</I>.  Lat. scarnare.</NOTE> it|al aboutefor&thorn; &amp; drawe him out with al his skyn.  &amp; if &thorn;er leue|&thorn;eron ony &thorn;ing of his skyn, &thorn;an caste &thorn;eron poudre of affodille, &amp;|make it clene wi&thorn; poudre of sum li&yogh;t corrosif &thorn;erwi&thorn;&mdash;vnguentum|viride,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vnguentum viride</I>.  See Notes.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;an regendre fleisch, &amp; &thorn;an drie it vp as it is aforseid /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="16">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="154b">Of &thorn;e akynge of ioynctis. </HEAD>
<P>Now it is seid pleynlier of alle enpostyms, now speke we of|passiouns &thorn;at come&thorn; in ioynctis.  &amp; &thorn;is passioun is myche|lijk to enpostyms in causis &amp; signes &amp; curis, &amp; also it diuersi&thorn;|miche fro o&thorn;ere enpostyms / For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e place be greet to-swollen,|it come&thorn; but late or neuere to quitture.  Swellynge &amp; akynge of|ioinctis, &thorn;is passioun is vnknowen to manie kunnyng lechis &thorn;at han|greet name.  Bi &thorn;e cause &thorn;at cirurgians ben clepid algate to &thorn;is|manere passioun, &thorn;erfore I haue studied to make a general chapitre|of passiouns of ioinctis.  &amp; I haue take miche &thorn;erof &thorn;e bokis of|Rasis &amp; of myn owne worching &thorn;at I haue proued.  &para; &THORN;e causis|&thorn;at maki&thorn; akinge in ioynctis: or it come&thorn; of yuel complexioun of|lymes, or it come&thorn; of hoot complexioun &thorn;at heti&thorn;, or it come&thorn; of|coold complexioun &thorn;at cooldi&thorn; / Drie ligaturis of ioynctis constreine&thorn;|&amp; maki&thorn; akynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. sicca (complexio) ligamento junctarum astringendo dolorem aliquando|generat.</NOTE> &amp; moistnes maki&thorn; neuere akynge wi&thorn;outen|o&thorn;er <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="155a">mater / Mater &thorn;at maki&thorn; akinge of ioyncts is ofte tyme |haboundaunce of blood, &amp; ofte tyme it is raw fleume, &amp; moost|principali colre or blood medlid with fleume / &amp; it come&thorn; ful seelde|of fleume, but if it be medlid wi&thorn; ony o&thorn;er &thorn;ing as colre / In what
<PB N="234">|maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe which humour be in &thorn;e cause of akynge|of ioinctis, &thorn;ou schalt finde in &thorn;e chapitre of allopucia &amp; in &thorn;e|general chapitre of enpostyms, if &thorn;ou takist good kepe of &thorn;e signes|of &thorn;e forseid chapitris, what humour is in cause of akynge of|ioinctis / Saue &thorn;is &thorn;ou muste take hede, &thorn;at ofte tyme raw fleumatik|humouris maki&thorn; akynge of ioinctis as it is forseid, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e colour|of &thorn;e lyme schal be but litil<NOTE PLACE="foot">A second <I>litil</I> deleted.</NOTE> chaungid &thorn;erfore / &amp; &thorn;an a leche but|if he be &thorn;e more expert &thorn;eron mai be bigilid.  &amp; sumtyme a litil|quantite of colre wole schewe vpon &thorn;e lyme, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e leche wole|leie &thorn;erto coolde &thorn;ingis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e mater of fleume wole bicome hard,|&amp; so &thorn;e greuaunce wole be worse &thorn;an it was / &THORN;erfore it is greet| nede &thorn;at &thorn;e leche be kunnyng &amp; knowe wel &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="155b">mater of passiouns|of ioyntis.</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;e cure of akynge of ioinctis &thorn;at come&thorn; of yuel complexioun|oonly, &thorn;ou schalt remeue with &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben contrarie to &thorn;at complexoun:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.. Cura doloris iuncturarum qu&aelig; ex mala complexione sola est, non|est nisi cum contrariis complexionis malitiam removere.</NOTE>|as if &thorn;e mater be hoot, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt remeue it with|colde &thorn;ingis, &amp; if &thorn;e mater be coold, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt remeue it wi&thorn;|hoot &thorn;ingis, &amp; if &thorn;e mater be of drienes, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt remeue it|wi&thorn; moist &thorn;ingis, &amp; wi&thorn; metis &amp; drinkis &thorn;at maki&thorn; fatt, &amp; wi&thorn; rest<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>rost</I>.</NOTE>|&amp; wi&thorn; gladnes; for as faste as his bodi bicome&thorn; fatt, he schal be|hool of &thorn;at passioun / &THORN;is passioun &thorn;at come&thorn; of humours, is curid|with mitigacion of &thorn;e akynge, &amp; I fynde diuers opiniouns &thorn;eron /|&amp; &thorn;erfore I wole schewe hem in &thorn;is chapiter / Auicen sei&thorn;: &thorn;at|whanne &thorn;ou wolt worche in &thorn;is mater, &thorn;i principal entencioun schal|be for to do awei &thorn;e akynge / And Rasis forbedi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt|leie &thorn;erto no repercussiuis, ne noon resolutiuis but if &thorn;e mater be|avoidid tofore / For to do awey &thorn;e akynge: saue avoide &thorn;e mater,|or leie &thorn;erto a repercussif or a resolutif.  &amp; &thorn;an Rasis sei&thorn; &thorn;at| &thorn;ou schalt avoide him, &amp; auicen forbedi&thorn;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="156a"> &thorn;at / In what maner|schulen we worche &thorn;anne, whanne &thorn;ou fyndist a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; greet|akynge? /  First &thorn;ou schalt leie a plastre to &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at it be|mitigatif or an oynement &thorn;at be mitigatif, &amp; &thorn;e difference herof|schal be aftir &thorn;at &thorn;e mater is //  Also &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &yogh;eue him sumwhat|bi &thorn;e mou&thorn; for to aswage &thorn;e akynge.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt fynde greet|plente in &thorn;is chapitre of defensiuis &amp; mitagatiuis to defende &thorn;e|mater / And whanne &thorn;e akynge is perfi&yogh;tli swagid lete him blood
<PB N="235">|if &thorn;e cause be of blood.  &amp; if it be of ano&thorn;er cause avoide it.  &amp;|if &thorn;ou letist him blood, &thorn;ou schalt do it in a lyme afor&yogh;ens.  &amp; if|&thorn;ou wolt avoide &thorn;ere matere, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;e cause / for &thorn;is|is ful necessarie for a leche to kunne / Whanne &thorn;e mater is avoidid|&amp; &thorn;e akynge ceessid, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt bigynne wi&thorn; resoluynge medicyns|&thorn;at ben forseid.  &para; Also in curis of akynge in ioyntis be wel|war &thorn;at &thorn;ou feble not his appetit, for &thorn;is sijknes come&thorn; moost of|humours &thorn;at ben vndefied.  &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalt in as miche as|&thorn;ou mi&yogh;t make him haue good appetite<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="156b"> &amp; good digestioun / If &thorn;ou |fyndist oonly &thorn;e mater coold, &thorn;at maki&thorn; ful seelde ony gret akynge,|saue it maki&thorn; &thorn;e lyme heuy.  &THORN;is &thorn;ou schalt wite &thorn;at in a coold|cause &thorn;at maki&thorn; akinge in ioinctis, &thorn;ou&yogh; it be hard to do awei,|ne&thorn;eles &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him no strong medicyn ne he schal not be|purgid hastili as manie men wene&thorn;, saue it schal be do wi&thorn; a propre|medicyn &thorn;at is sure.  &amp; it schal ofte be &yogh;euen, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai|algate kepe his appetit, for &thorn;er is noon so strong medicyn &thorn;at mai|avoide &thorn;e mater al at oonys / And if &thorn;ou &yogh;euest him a strong|medicyn it wole afeble hise vertues.  &amp; &thorn;erfor &thorn;ou must chese a|li&yogh;t medicyn &thorn;at mowe comforte &thorn;e stomac &amp; &thorn;at it mowe be &yogh;eue|ofte //</P>
<P>&para; Of akynge of ioyntis &thorn;ou hast had general rulis; now we|mote speke of curis here after.  &para; If &thorn;ou be sent after to a man|&thorn;at ha&thorn; arteticam,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>artetica</I>, arthritica, gout, <I>Trevisa De propr. rer</I>., Lib. VII, Cap. 56|(Add. MS. 27,944, fol. 96 <I>b</I>.).  "<I>Arthetica is ache and evel in fingres and|tone wi&thorn; swelling &amp; sore ache / and whanne hit is in &thorn;e fyngres, hit hatte|cyragra, and in &thorn;e toone hit hatte podagra, if hit is in &thorn;e whirlebones and|ioyntes it hatte sciatica passio, and come&thorn; of colerik blood &amp; of fleumatik|humours, &amp; come&thorn; most ofte of reumatik cause.</I>"  The author of the Treatise|on Surgery, preserved in Sl. 1736, mentions this disease as a hereditary one.|Ibid. fol. 122 b.: "<I>also yt ys often tymes sene &thorn;at &thorn;is arthetica passio gose|by erytaunce as fro &thorn;e [fadyr] to the childur, and so forth to odyr.</I>"</NOTE> &thorn;at is as myche to seie as a goute, first &thorn;ou|muste loke wher &thorn;e mater be hoot or coold, or whe&thorn;er he haue|strong akynge or li&yogh;t akynge / &amp; if his akynge be strong, &thorn;an <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="157a">leie |&thorn;erto mitigatiuis / In oon maner &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him medicyns bi|&thorn;e mou&thorn; &thorn;at ben mitigatif for to take awey &thorn;e akynge, &amp; enplastris|&thorn;at ben mitigatif, &amp; leie vpon &thorn;e place.  &para; A good medicyn &thorn;at|schal be &yogh;eue bi &thorn;e mou&thorn;: &rx;, glandes &amp; leie hem in vinegre adai &amp;|any&yogh;t, &amp; after &thorn;at drie hem to &thorn;e sunne or in an ouene, &amp; &thorn;an kepe|it / &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wolt &yogh;eue it, grynde it &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;erof <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .j.; &thorn;is|medicyn maki&thorn; blood greet &amp; remeue&thorn; &thorn;er from / Also take lentes
<PB N="236">|excorticatas, semen coriandri, succum glandulum, hermodactulis<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Hermodactyla</I>, crawanleac."  Wr. W&uuml;. 137, 3.&mdash;"Hermodactylus, a|round-headed Root, brought from Syria, which is of an insipid Taste; and|gently purges Phlegm."  Phillips.</NOTE>|wi&thorn; sugre &amp; coold watir, saue herof &thorn;ou must take kepe &thorn;at &thorn;ese|medicyns schulen not be &yogh;eue but in greet nede, &amp; whanne &thorn;e|akynge is so greet &thorn;at it mai not be take awei.  &amp; &thorn;ei mai be|moost sotilly &yogh;eue whanne &thorn;e mater is subtil &amp; scharp / &amp; if &thorn;e|mater be greet &amp; miche, &thorn;an &thorn;is medicyn schal not be &yogh;eue.  &para; If|&thorn;e mater be coold &amp; of greet akyng, &thorn;an take hermodactulis, thuris|ana xx. partis, cucumeri partes .x, &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;erof <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .iij. vpon &thorn;e| place / If &thorn;e matere be litil &amp; scharp <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="157b">&amp; subtil / &rx;, amigdalas,|camphore ana, grinde hem &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; watir of roses /|Also ano&thorn;ir in &thorn;e same kinde / &rx;, mirre, panis albissimi &amp; subtilissimi
<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, opij <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, grinde hem wel &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; milk of a|cow, &amp; leie it &thorn;eron whanne it is greet nede / Item &rx;, opij, cortices|mandragorae ana .&yogh; .v, grinde hem &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of|portulacae &amp; oile of roses &amp; a litil vynegre / Also an oynement for|to ceesse &thorn;e akynge / &rx;, olium rosarum <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iiij, cere <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., melte &thorn;e oile|&amp; &thorn;e wex togidere &amp; waische it with oile of roses, &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;erto|citrini <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., opij <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> / If &thorn;e mater be myche &amp; be nei&thorn;er more in|quantite &thorn;an in qualite, &amp; &thorn;ou wolt defende more &thorn;e cours of &thorn;e|mater, &thorn;an do awei &thorn;e akynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 63: Si uero materia fuerit multa et times plus de|quantitate quam de qualitate, et uis plus prohibere materi&aelig; cursum quam|extinguere ...</NOTE>  &rx;, cortices granatoris, sandali<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sandali albi</I>,  The d in sandal is explained by influence of|Arab. sandal (Devic).  Matth. Sylvat. mentions three sorts of Sandal:|album, ruffum et citrinum.  See <I>Alphita</I>, p. 161.  <I>whit saunders</I> and <I>reed|saunders</I> are distinguished in Sloane MS. 2463, fol. 155 <I>b</I> (c. c. 1450).</NOTE>|albi, &amp; rue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rue</I> for <I>rubidi</I>.</NOTE> &amp; roses, boli armenici, ferrugine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. foenugreci.</NOTE> opij, confice cum|succo mirtillorum vel foliorum salicis, or with a decocciun of hem in|watir wi&thorn; a litil oile of roses &amp; vinegre &amp; make herof an oynement.|&amp; whanne &thorn;e akynge is aswagid, &thorn;an dissolue &thorn;e mater of blood wi&thorn;|letyng blood.  &amp; &thorn;at suffisi&thorn; as it is aforseid.  &para; Colre &thorn;ou schalt|dissolue in &thorn;is maner / &rx;, mirabolanorum citrinorum .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> vj., <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="158a">grinde| hem &amp; leie hem al any&yogh;t in l&imacr; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> of sirup of viole, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .iiij. of wijn|of pomegarnates &thorn;at ben swete, amorowe boile hem alitil &amp; do &thorn;erto|&yogh;uccare <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, hermodactylorum .&yogh; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., &amp; &yogh;eue it him in &thorn;e mornyng.|&amp; if &thorn;ou wolt make itt more coold, do &thorn;erto .&yogh; .ij. of musilaginis
<PB N="237">|psillij or <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .j.  &para; &THORN;is is a good electuarie &thorn;erfore .&rx;, citoniorum l&imacr;
<ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., &amp; make hem to gobettis, &amp; leie hem in vinegre adai &amp; ani&yogh;t / &amp;|&thorn;an wrynge hem &amp; grinde hem smal, &amp; do &thorn;erto scamonie &thorn;at it be|good .&yogh; .j, cardamomi, cubube .&yogh; .iij, spice nardi .&yogh; .j, rosis .&yogh; .v,|&yogh;uccare l&imacr; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, make herof a letuarie &thorn;at purgi&thorn; wel colre &amp; comforti&thorn;|&thorn;e stomac.  &THORN;ou schalt &yogh;eue herof .&yogh; .ij. &amp; &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t scharpe it|more if &thorn;ou wolt with a litil hermodactylis.  &para; &THORN;ese ben good|pelottis for &thorn;e same cause / &rx;, aloes .&yogh; .ij, hermodactylos .&yogh; j,|scamonie .&yogh; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>. rosis .&yogh; .j, make herof pelottis with sirupo violarum,|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue herof .&yogh; .j.  Whanne &thorn;e passioun bigynne&thorn; to go|awei with &thorn;ese medicyns, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;erto plastris &thorn;at ben|resoluynge: as of malue &amp; bismalue, camomille, mellilotum, absinthium,|peratorie, semen caulium, aneti, fenugreci, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="158b">semen lini, |furfuris, &amp; swynys grese, &amp; gandris grese, &amp; hennis grese, &amp; oile of|camfre, &amp; olium aneti.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e cours of humours ceessi&thorn;,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt vse oonly resoluynge &thorn;ingis &amp; make &thorn;erof enplastris /|Also to do awaye residue of &thorn;e akinge, &thorn;is is a good medicyn / &rx;,|olium camomille <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .iiij, cere .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., seminis aneti &amp; caulium, florum|camomille ana .&yogh; .iij. &amp; make herof an oynement / Also in ano&thorn;er|maner / &rx;, fenigreci, semen lini, aneti, &amp; tempere hem with iuys of|caulium.  &amp; herof &thorn;ou must take kepe, &thorn;at as ofte as &thorn;ou wolt vse|clene resolutiuis, &thorn;ou schalt algate waische &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at is to-swollen|wi&thorn; a decoccioun of malue &amp; bismalue, &amp; florum of camomille &amp;|melliloti, absinthii &amp; o&thorn;ere mo, &amp; &thorn;e lyme schal be waische &thorn;erwi&thorn;|til it bicome reed, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt anoynte him / And &thorn;is &thorn;ou|schalt wite &thorn;at as meuyng &amp; ba&thorn;ing greue&thorn; &thorn;e passioun in &thorn;e firste|bigynnyng, ri&yogh;t so &thorn;ei ben in &thorn;e ende ri&yogh;t greet helping / For|to stuwe &amp; ba&thorn;e doi&thorn; awei &thorn;e laste part of &thorn;e mater &amp; maki&thorn;|a mannys lymes haue her meuyng as &thorn;ei schulde haue.  &amp; also it|is good whanne &thorn;e patient goi&thorn; out of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="159a">his stue, if hise ioinctis |aki&thorn;, &thorn;an frote hem wel wi&thorn; salt grounde / If &thorn;e mater be coold &thorn;ou|schalt di&yogh;te him wi&thorn; dia&yogh;in&yogh;iberis &thorn;at is aforseid in allopucia.  &amp;|&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt dissolue wi&thorn; trocisco de turbit wi&thorn; hermodactylis|maad in &thorn;is maner / &rx;, dia&yogh;in&yogh;iberis predicti <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j. &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, turbit electi|.&yogh; .j, hermodactulorum alborum solidorum <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, &amp; viij greines of|anise, &amp; make &thorn;erof a gobet wi&thorn; a litil hony.  &amp; &thorn;is schal be &yogh;eue|in &thorn;e mornyng.  &amp; &thorn;erafter he schal drinke a litil wijn hoot &amp; a|litil water; or wi&thorn; &thorn;ese pelottis / &rx;, hermodactylorum, saturionis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Saturion</I>, iarus.  See <I>Alphita</I>, p. 158.</NOTE>
<PB N="238">|sene ana .&yogh; .v, ierapigre<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Hiera Picra</I>, a purging Electuary invented by Galen, and made of|Aloes, Spikenard, Saffron, Mastick, Honey, &amp;c.;"  Phillips.</NOTE> &thorn;at entri&thorn; in pululas cochias .&yogh; .x, pulpe|coloquintide, centaurie. ana .&yogh; .v, euforbij .&yogh;. ij, turbit .&yogh; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., cassie,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cassif.</NOTE>|sinapis, piperis, castorij ana .&yogh; .j. &amp; make herof pelottis with hony.|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue herof .&yogh; j. at oonys, &amp; &thorn;is medicyn schal be|&yogh;eue manie tymes.  &amp; in daies bitwixe he schal take dia&yogh;in&yogh;iberum|of oure makinge &thorn;at is forseid.  &amp; if it be in winter, &thorn;ou schalt|&yogh;eue him diatrion piperion<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>diatrion piperion</I>, a medicine composed of three sorts of pepper.</NOTE> or ano&thorn;er hoot eletuarie // &para; Ano&thorn;er|electuarie &thorn;at dissolui&thorn; akynge in ioyntis &thorn;at come&thorn; of raw mater.|&rx;, camedrios,<NOTE PLACE="foot">"Cham&oelig;drys, the Herb Germander, or English Treacle."  Phillips.|Camedreos ance Teterwose.  Wr. W&uuml;. 569, 47 (xvth cent.).</NOTE> centaurie minorum ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .viij, aristologia longa.| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="159b">gencian. ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .vj, agarici .&yogh; .ij, vtriusque spice ana .&yogh; .j, make|hem wi&thorn; hony.  &THORN;ou schalt &yogh;eue herof &thorn;e quantite of a note eerli|&amp; late.  Men &thorn;at ben lene schulen not take &thorn;is medicyn // Whanne|&thorn;e patient is purgid sufficiently, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt vse enplastris for to|leie to &thorn;e place / &rx;, oold swynis grese &thorn;at it be freisch l&imacr; j., &amp;|medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; quyk-lyme &amp; make &thorn;erof a plastre &amp; leie vpon &thorn;e|place / Also take stercus caprinum &amp; distempere it wi&thorn; vinegre &amp;|hony ana, &amp; leie it &thorn;eron / Also &rx;, aristologia, radices yrios,|elleborus, &amp; piper, boile hem in oile &amp; do &thorn;erto &yogh;elow wex &amp; make|&thorn;erof an oynement.  &para; Also diaquilon maad of litarge &amp; oile &amp;|iuys of mustard seed.  &amp; if &thorn;ou wolt haue mo remedies, go to &thorn;e|book of Rasis, &amp; &thorn;ere &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e chapiter of ioyntis,|medicyns ynowe &thorn;erfore.  &para; Also if &thorn;ou desirist to comforte &thorn;e|lyme &amp; do awei &thorn;e coold mater wi&thorn; repercussiuis, in &thorn;e laste chapiter|of &thorn;is book &thorn;ou schalt fynde repercussiuis &amp; mollificatiuis ynowe //</P>
