<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="17">
<HEAD>/ Of sciatica passio<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>passis</I>.</NOTE> /<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>De Propr. rerum</I>, Lib. VII, Cap. 57 (Add. 27,944, fol. 96 <I>b</I>.): "<I>Gutta|sciatica is an yuel &thorn;at come&thorn; of humours &thorn;at falli&thorn; doun into &thorn;e grete senewe|&thorn;at is bytwene &thorn;e grete brawnes of &thorn;e hanche as constantyn sei&thorn;.  &para; And|come&thorn; ofte of gleymy humours i-gadred togedres in &thorn;e holou&yogh;nes of &thorn;e ioyntes|&amp; of &thorn;e haunche / somtyme of blody humours i-medlid wi&thorn; colera &amp; alle &thorn;ese|be&thorn; ofte cause of ache &thorn;e whiche ache strecchi&thorn; into &thorn;e legges &amp; anon to &thorn;e|hele &amp; also anon to &thorn;e litil [too].</I>"</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Akynge of haunchis schal be curid wi&thorn; avoidinge of &thorn;e mater id| est laxatiuis, for repercussiuis ben not &thorn;erfore, for &thorn;e matere <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="160a">is|in &thorn;e depnes of &thorn;e lyme, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The subject is: <I>repercussivis</I>.</NOTE> ne mowe not come &thorn;erto.  Resolutiuis
<PB N="239">|ben not &thorn;erfore, for &thorn;ei mai not come to &thorn;e depnes of &thorn;e mater.  &amp;|for &thorn;e mater is so greet, it schulde more drawe to &thorn;e place humouris|&thorn;an dissolue.  Saue &thorn;ou must aswage &thorn;e akinge, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt do|awei &thorn;e akynge with oile &amp; hony &amp; fatnes &thorn;at doi&thorn; awei<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>awei</I>, above line.</NOTE> akinge.|&para; If &thorn;e mater come of blood, &thorn;an lete him blood in a veyne &thorn;at is|clepid basilica in &thorn;e same side, &amp; in &thorn;e secunde dai lete him blood|in a veyne &thorn;at is clepid sciatica, &amp; principaly if &thorn;e mater descende|adoun wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; toward &thorn;e foot, for &thorn;an it mai principaly be|holpen / If &thorn;e mater come of fleuma, &thorn;an purge him wi&thorn; pelottis|of hermodactilorum / Saue herof &thorn;ou schalt take kepe &thorn;at bifore|his purgacioun bine&thorn;e for&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bine&thorn;e for&thorn;</I>, Lat. per inferius.  See <I>N.E. Dict</I>., s. v. beneath-forth.</NOTE> he schal haue a vomet.  For if &thorn;ou make|him a medicyn laxatif bine&thorn;efor&thorn; &amp; no vomet tofore, &thorn;an it wole|drawe more &thorn;e mater toward &thorn;e place &thorn;an aweyward / &THORN;erfor first|&thorn;ou schalt make him a vomet, &amp; aftirward a medicyn laxatif / And|&thorn;erfore medicyns laxatiuis summe ben propre for akynge of &thorn;e|haunchis, as coloquintida, yrios, sarcocolla, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="160b">centaurea, agaricus, &amp; |infusioun of aloes.  For infusioun of aloes wole make blood passe|fro him at his sege, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e akinge wole go awei &amp; he schal be|hool / &amp; whanne he is perfitli maad clene wi&thorn; medicyns laxatiuis,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t leie &thorn;erto enplastris maad in &thorn;is maner / &rx;, nasturcij,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nasturtium</I>, a kind of cress.</NOTE>|peretri,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peretrum</I>, Lat. piretrum.  Anthemis pyrethrum (Dunglison), "Piretrum|. . pelestre."&mdash;<I>Alphita</I>, p. 145.  "<I>Pyrethrum</I>, Bartram, wild or bastard|Pellitory, an Herb the Root of which is very biting and hot."&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE> capparis, grinde hem &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; lie maad of askis|of a fige tree, &amp; make &thorn;erof a &thorn;icke enplaster as it were hony, &amp;|anointe &thorn;e place til it be ful of bladdris &amp; &thorn;e bladdris ful of water,|ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e place were brent wi&thorn; fier.  &amp; &thorn;an anoynte &thorn;e place wi&thorn;|butter, &amp; leie &thorn;eron caule leeues &thorn;at &thorn;e bladdris soude not togideris|anoon; for &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at &thorn;ei leue&thorn; &thorn;eron, &thorn;e bettir it wole be.|Ei&thorn;er anoynte &thorn;e place oonli with mel anacardi,<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Anacardus</I>.  Or after Ruellius <I>anacardium</I>: is the frute of a tre,|growing in Sicilia, and Apulia, called vulgarly, Pediculus Elephantis.  The|iuyce wherof is called <I>Mel Anacardi</I>, which is a ruptory medicine."&mdash;Halle,|<I>Table</I>, p. 10.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;at maki&thorn;|bladdris.  &amp; what maner &thorn;ou schalt make mel anacardi, &thorn;ou schalt|fynde in &thorn;e antidotarie &thorn;at techi&thorn; to make medicyns &amp; cauterijs /|Saue herof &thorn;ou must take kepe &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt not vse &thorn;ese medicyns|&thorn;at maki&thorn; cauterijs, but if his bodi be wel avoidid wi&thorn; medicyns|laxatiuis tofore; for if his bodi be <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="161a">not purgid, it wole drawe more 
<PB N="240">|mater to &thorn;e place &thorn;an aweyward.  &para; Also a&yogh;ens &thorn;e sciatica passio|here &thorn;ou schalt haue an experiment preued of Avicenna.  Take|gotis tordis &amp; drie hem, &amp; make hem to pouder, &amp; distempere hem|wi&thorn; strong vinegre &amp; made hoot, &amp; make herof a plastre, &amp; leie it|vpon as hoot as &thorn;ou maist suffre, &amp; anoynte &thorn;erwi&thorn; his haunche.|&para; Also a medicyn &thorn;at is forseid of camedrios &amp; centaurea<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>centaurea</I>, written above <I>cauterie</I>.</NOTE> is good|&thorn;erfore, for it wole drawe awei bi vryne / &para; Item: cauterijs maad|in &thorn;e nexte welle vnder &thorn;e place of &thorn;e akinge ben gode &thorn;erfor after|&thorn;e tyme &thorn;at his bodi is maad clene with purgaciouns, &amp; tofore &thorn;ou|schalt make him no cauterijs.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="18">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e maner of dieting of hem &thorn;at han passions in|ioinctes /</HEAD>
<P>In what maner &thorn;ou schalt diete men &thorn;at han passiouns in|iointis.  &THORN;ou schalt wite &thorn;at &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing so greuous to &thorn;is|passioun as is wyn, &amp; it is principali forbede in an hoot|cause, &amp; so it schal be in a coold cause; for whanne it is|take, it persi&thorn; li&yogh;tli to &thorn;e iointis, &amp; maki&thorn; wei to &thorn;e mater for|to falle &thorn;erto / Saue if &thorn;e passion be coold, &amp; &thorn;e patient mai| not wel <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="161b">defie his mete, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt graunte him a litil|wijn, &amp; not to miche for &thorn;e causis &thorn;at ben forseid.  &para; In an|hoot cause make him drinke &thorn;at is forseid in &thorn;e chapiter of dieting|of woundis, or he schal vse vinum granatorum wi&thorn; coold water.  &amp;|&thorn;e pacient schal absteine him fro fleisch &amp; fisch &amp; vse lactucis, portulacis|/ &amp; if he be gretli feble, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him litil|chikenys.  &amp; lete &thorn;ou not him drinke wijn bi no maner if his|passioun be hoot / &amp; whoso ha&thorn; &thorn;e coold passioun herof, he schal|holde him wel apaied<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he schal holde him wel apaied</I>, Lat. sit contentus.  See <I>N.E. Dict</I>., s. v.|apaid.  O.Fr. apaier.  Compare: je m'en tieng bien paiez.  (Littr&eacute;.)</NOTE> for to ete oonys adai &amp; not to miche.  &amp;|lete him drinke ydromel wel soden / for if he mai suffre hungur &amp;|&thorn;irst he mai soone be hool.  &amp; he schal in no maner ete, but if he|haue wil &thorn;erto.</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="3">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<HEAD>&para; The firste teching of egritudines of y&yogh;en, ou&thorn;er|passioun &amp; anothami /</HEAD>
<P>Now wolen we make a tretice of passioun of lymes &thorn;at falli&thorn;|for no woundis, &amp; curis &thorn;erof come&thorn; ofte to cirurgians
<PB N="241">|handis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Volentes tractare de passionibus membrorum particularium, que|non sunt vulnera, qu&aelig; s&aelig;pe veniunt ad manus chirurgi ... incipiemus ab|&aelig;gritudinibus oculorum.</NOTE> / I wole bigynne of sijknes of y&yogh;en &amp; to speke of anathomiam|&thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;at was not forseid in &thorn;e .ij. book / &THORN;ou schalt fynde|in summe bokis of auctoritees &thorn;at a mannes i&yogh;en ben maad of .iij.|humouris &amp; of .vij. cootis.  &amp; in sum bokis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="162a">&thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;at |&thorn;e i&yogh;en ben maad of .iij. cotis or of .iiij. or of .vij. or of .x., &amp; alle|&thorn;ei seien soo&thorn;.  Saue &thorn;e .j. coote &thorn;at maketh &thorn;e schap of &thorn;e i&yogh;e,|ben but .iij. &thorn;at scheweth out in &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &amp; &thorn;erfore me|mai seie .vj. &amp; also &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="foot">The passage is corrupt, and the corresponding Latin phrase differs:|Tunic&aelig; tres qu&aelig; in oculi formatione tres pr&aelig;cedunt humores, in ordine|causant ex ipsis tres alias, quare dici possunt sex et tres.</NOTE> / And fro &thorn;e brain tofore come&thorn; .ij. bindingis|&thorn;at ben not of nerues, saue &thorn;ei ben of &thorn;e substaunce of brain,|&amp; &thorn;at oon come&thorn; out in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er in &thorn;e liftside, &amp; ben|schape as it were &thorn;e hedis of .ij. tetis, wherbi &thorn;e witt is take.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: quibus sensus comprehenditur odoratus.</NOTE>  &amp;|after &thorn;ese .ij. come&thorn; out ij. nerues, &amp; ben fast to &thorn;e i&yogh;en, &amp; ben|schape in &thorn;is maner: <FIGURE></FIGURE> &THORN;an &thorn;at nerue &thorn;at wexi&thorn; in &thorn;e|ri&yogh;tside of &thorn;e brayn, whanne he goi&thorn; out of &thorn;e scolle boon &amp; entri&thorn;|into orbitam, &thorn;at is &thorn;e holow place &thorn;at &thorn;e y&yogh;e sitt on, &amp; goi&thorn; to &thorn;e|i&yogh;e in &thorn;e liftside.  &amp; bi &thorn;es nerues come&thorn; &thorn;e spiritis of lijf &amp; of si&yogh;t|to &thorn;e y&yogh;en / Of &thorn;e substaunce of dura matris is engendrid rethina,|&thorn;at is &thorn;e &thorn;inne skyn &thorn;at goi&thorn; without &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &thorn;at is clepid &thorn;e vilm|of &thorn;e i&yogh;e.  And &thorn;is serue&thorn; of greet seruice, &amp; &thorn;is vilm was maad|swi&thorn;e &thorn;inne &thorn;at it ne hurte not humouris, &amp; &thorn;at it lette not &thorn;e|meuynge of &thorn;e i&yogh;e, and it <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="162b">byndi&thorn; in al &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &amp; it defendi&thorn; &thorn;e i&yogh;e |fro harmynge of &thorn;e boon //<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Facta fuit ergo retina valde subtilis, ne l&aelig;deret humores: et ne|motum ipsorum in dilatatione comprimeret.  Et facta fuit sclirotica: ut|oculum totum cum cornea ligaret: et defenderet ab ossis oculi nocumento.|The translator omits the description of the Anatomy of the eye.  See Notes.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; &THORN;ere come&thorn; manye sijknessis in &thorn;e i&yogh;en, &amp; summe come&thorn; of|causis wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &amp; summe of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn; / Wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;:|as of yuel complexiouns, or of yuel humours; wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;: as of|greet hete of &thorn;e eir, or of greet cooldnes of &thorn;e eir, or of poudre, or|of fume, or of wynd / And &thorn;ere ben o&thorn;ere maner sijknes of &thorn;e i&yogh;e,|&amp; &thorn;at ben seid contagious: as obtolmia &amp; blere i&yogh;ed, &amp; alle &thorn;ese|sijknessis comen to cirurgians handis.  &amp; obtolmia is clepid a whit|welke or a reed poynt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: ophthalmia, vlcus, albula, macula simplex, punctus, rubedo.  The|translator mistook this list of names of eye diseases for a definition of|"ophthalmia."  On the other hand he took the words "Dilatacio, Pulpe,|Inuersatio, Palpebrarum" as names for four separate diseases.</NOTE> &amp; icchinge &amp; scabbe, sebel, vngula, cataracta,
<PB N="242">|dilatacion pulpe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pulpe</I>, for <I>pupillae</I>.</NOTE> inuersacion, palpebrarum, ordelus, grando, nodus,|&amp; pilus, fistula lacrimalis.  &para; Also &thorn;er ben o&thorn;ere manere sijknessis|of &thorn;e i&yogh;en: as blind &amp; hurtinge &thorn;at mowe not be curid /</P>
<P>It is forseid what &thorn;ing is enpostym in &thorn;e general capitulo of|enpostyms.  &amp; it is forseid &thorn;at euery &thorn;ing &thorn;at gaderi&thorn; humour togidere|&amp; maki&thorn; swellynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On the bottom of the page: "<I>contra obtalmia Recipe, the inner rynde|off the ceritre, sethe yt in venyger, &amp; hold a sponffulle in thy movthe lucke|warme, so do oft in &thorn;e day.</I>"</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="163a">schal be clepid enpostym<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, fol. 84 b.: "<I>As it is sayd of auctores in &thorn;e generall Chapiter|of enpostumes, &thorn;at euery flowyng of humore &thorn;at swellith a member ouer his|kyndely beyng is an enpostume, ri&yogh;t so obtalmia is cleped an enpostume of|&thorn;e eye.</I>"</NOTE> / In &thorn;e same| maner obtalmia<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>obtalmia</I>, med. Lat. form of <GAP DESC="Greek">, inflammation of the eye.</NOTE> is clepid enpostym of &thorn;e i&yogh;e.  &amp; &thorn;ere ben .iij. maners|of obtalmia: as li&yogh;t, &amp; strenger, &amp; al&thorn;er strong.  Li&yogh;t, as whanne|a mannes i&yogh;e bicome&thorn; reed &amp; ha&thorn; brennynge &thorn;erinne &amp; prickinge, &amp;|&thorn;er is no swellynge &thorn;eron.  &amp; &thorn;is mai come of a cause withoutfor&thorn;:|as of hoot eir or of coold, or of smoke, or of poudre, or of wakinge,|or of traueile.  &amp; &thorn;e cure herof is but li&yogh;t; for &thorn;is sijknes mai be|curid in &thorn;is maner.  Take &thorn;e white of an ey &amp; scume<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scume</I>, despumare.  <I>Prompt. Parv</I>., p. 450.  "<I>scummyn lycurys</I>, despumo."</NOTE> it, &amp; loke|&thorn;at &thorn;ere falle no fil&thorn;e &thorn;eron, &amp; leie it into his i&yogh;e; for &thorn;is is &thorn;e best|medicyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: quod non dicitur vilipendi. quia est nobilior medicina.  Sl. 2463,|fol. 85: "<I>and sette not li&yogh;tly &thorn;erby, for it is &thorn;e nobelest medicyne.</I>"</NOTE> among alle medicyns &thorn;at ben clepid colliries, for it wole|make coold his i&yogh;e &amp; do awey &thorn;e akynge.  &amp; it abidi&thorn; &thorn;e lenger in|his i&yogh;en, for it is viscous // &para; If &thorn;e cause be cold,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hoot</I>.  Lat si causa sit frigida.  Sl. ibid.: "<I>and yf &thorn;e cause be of|colde.</I>"</NOTE> &thorn;an &thorn;is cure|suffisi&thorn;: &thorn;anne lete him drynke a litil sutil wijn, &amp; make him a|fomentacioun of rosis &amp; flouris of camomille, &amp; fenigrec soden in|water. &amp; if &thorn;is suffise not, &thorn;an <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="163b">&thorn;ou muste lete him blood, &amp; avoide| awei &thorn;e humouris.  &amp; &thorn;ou muste caste into his i&yogh;e a whit collirium,|&amp; it is seid in o&thorn;ere spicis of obtolmia.</P>
<P>&para; Obtolmia &thorn;at is strong.  &THORN;ese ben &thorn;e signes &thorn;erof: greet|reednes, &amp; &thorn;e veynes of &thorn;e i&yogh;en be ful replete, &amp; &thorn;e corner of &thorn;e|i&yogh;e schal watri, &amp; he schal haue greet akinge &amp; pricking, &amp; sumtyme|&thorn;ere come&thorn; in &thorn;e first bigynnyng vlcera &thorn;eron, as it were
<PB N="243">|white prickis or reed, &amp; sumtyme &thorn;er ben noon sich pointis &thorn;eron|&thorn;at a man mai se, saue al his i&yogh;e is reed &amp; to-swollen.  &amp; he schal|haue greet akinge &amp; pricking.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;er be noon vlcera &thorn;eron, &thorn;e|cure mai be do al in oon maner.  &para; If &thorn;e akynge be swi&thorn;e greet,|&thorn;an aceesse &thorn;e akynge, &amp; &thorn;an lete him blood in &thorn;e heed-veyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">vena cephalica.</NOTE> &thorn;at|sitt in &thorn;e arme &amp; in &thorn;at same side &thorn;at aki&thorn;.  &amp; if he haue passioun|in bo&thorn;e his i&yogh;en, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in bo&thorn;e his armys.|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood &thorn;e quantite after his elde &amp; after his|strenk&thorn;e; or sette a ventuse vpon his schuldris, &amp; &thorn;at is more better,|for &thorn;e mater come&thorn; more <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="164a">of blood &thorn;an of colre.  &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t |knowe bi &thorn;e signes of blood &thorn;at ben forseid // &para; And if &thorn;e mater|come of colre, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi greet akinge &amp; scharp, &amp;|litil swellinge.  &amp; &thorn;e mater wole be &yogh;elow aboute hise i&yogh;en.  &amp; he|schal haue but litil reednes.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in|lasse<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. maiori.</NOTE> quantite &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at.</I></NOTE> if &thorn;e mater come of blood.  &amp; blood leting is|good in &thorn;is caas, for &thorn;e scharpnes of colre mai be take awei wi&thorn; &thorn;e|blood leting.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt purge him wi&thorn; a decoccioun of|fruitis with mirabolanis &thorn;at ben forseid in &thorn;e chapitre of allopucia.|&amp; if colre be medlid wi&thorn; ony partie of gret mater, &thorn;at falli&thorn; ofte|tyme, &thorn;an &thorn;er is no medicyn so good as cochie Rasie.  &amp; first he|schal do &thorn;ingis &thorn;erto for to aceesse &thorn;e matere / &rx;, a &yogh;elke of an eij,|&amp; as miche of oile of rosis, &amp; as miche of iuys of verueine, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> j.|of saffron, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> j. opij; medle &thorn;ese togidere, &amp; make &thorn;erof an enplastre,|&amp; leie it vpon a sotil lynnen cloo&thorn;, &amp; leie it on &thorn;e i&yogh;e.  &amp; in|his i&yogh;e leie collirium album with wommans milk<NOTE PLACE="foot">The use of woman's milk for an eye-salve is mentioned by Galenus <I>De|Compositione Medicamentorum</I>, Lib. IV. Cap. 3.</NOTE> &thorn;at noryschi&thorn; a|maide child; for .G. made &thorn;is medicyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator has omitted the following prescription preserved in Sl.|2463, fol. 85 b.: <I>and he cleped hit helpyng, for he, &thorn;at he made hit fore, was|holpen by one leyng therto.  &para; Take iiij. &yogh;. of ceruse sarsed, and distemper|hit wit water on a marbull stone tenne dayes, and kepe hit euermore couered|&thorn;at &thorn;er falle no pouder &thorn;erinne; thanne take .ij. &yogh;. and an halfe of gomme|arabik and putte hit in &thorn;e water, to &thorn;at hit be molten in &thorn;at water, and|&thorn;anne cole hit and medele yt as well as &thorn;ou may wit &thorn;i forsayd ceruse; and|whane &thorn;is medecyne is made liche paste, adde therto these thynges sotilly|poudered and sarsed twyes or thryes thoru&yogh; a sotyll lynnen clothe.  Take|amidum .iiij. &yogh;. sarcocolle, safran, opium ana &thorn;e iiij. partie of a .&yogh;. grynde|hem all wel togeder longe tyme, and make smale pillules and reserue hem,|to &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue nede, and whanne yt ys nede dystempere one of hem with</I>|(fol. 86)<I> womannes mylk and administer yt.</I></NOTE> / Rasis made collirium|album in &thorn;is maner, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="164b">&amp; it is good &thorn;ing, for I haue preued it ofte 
<PB N="244">|tyme.  Take ceruse waische .x. partis, sarcocolle greet .iij. partis,|amidi .ij. partis, draganti<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>draganti</I>, Lat. dragaganthi.</NOTE> .j. parti, opij .j <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> / Grinde alle &thorn;ese|togidere &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; rein water, &amp; make &thorn;erof pelottis as|gret as it were a pese &amp; kepe hem / &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wolt worche|&thorn;erwi&thorn;, tempere oon &thorn;erof wi&thorn; wommans milk &thorn;at it be as &thorn;icke as|it were must,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>must</I>, Lat. mustum.</NOTE> &amp; leie &thorn;erof in hise i&yogh;en &thorn;re si&thorn;is in &thorn;e dai.  &THORN;is|collirie aceessi&thorn; &thorn;e akinge.  &amp; in sumtyme it curi&thorn; obtolmiam in oon|dai as I haue preued itt manie tymes.  &amp; whanne he ha&thorn; slepe, if|hise i&yogh;en cleue togidere, &thorn;an he schal waische hise i&yogh;en wi&thorn; water of|rosis hoot, &amp; &thorn;an leie in &thorn;e corner of his i&yogh;e puluus citrinus, &thorn;at is|maad in &thorn;is maner / &rx;, sarcocolle x. partis, aloes, croci, licij ana|partes .ij., mirre partem vnam, &amp; make herof sotil poudre, &amp; leie|herof a litil in &thorn;e corner of his i&yogh;e /</P>
<P>&amp; whanne &thorn;e reednes &amp; swellyng of his i&yogh;e is aweie, he mote|be war of his dieting, for he mai ete no fleisch ne drinke no wijn,|saue he mote ete colature of bran wi&thorn; almaunde milk.  &amp; whanne| he lie&thorn; in his bed his heed mote lie hi&yogh;e, &amp; he schal ligge <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="165a">vpon &thorn;e|hool side &amp; not vpon &thorn;e soor side / &amp; if bo&thorn;e his i&yogh;en ben soor, &thorn;an|he mote di&yogh;te him as sutilli as he may.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, fol. 86: "<I>and yef bothe eyen be sore he schal lye vpward, his|hodes muste be wyde.</I>"  Lat.: caputia vestium non sint stricta.</NOTE>  &amp; he mote ofte tyme haue|&thorn;e sauour of water coold, &amp; &thorn;e sauour of wi&thorn;i &amp; campher, &amp; he|mote lie in a derk hous &thorn;at he mowe se no li&yogh;t.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e|mater goi&thorn; awei faste &amp; his bodi [is]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>, omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;an clene, &thorn;an sette him in a|ba&thorn; of swete water, &amp; lete him be &thorn;erin but a litil while<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. ibid.: "<I>And yef it be plesaunt to hym lete hym abyde therinne,|and lete hym foment his eyen and his heuede.  And yf he wexe ri&yogh;t hoot in|&thorn;e bathth, lete hym dwelle therin not passyng an houre, but &thorn;enne &thorn;e pacient|schal be purged ayen.  &para; And in &thorn;e laste ende of &thorn;e obtalmia yt ys good to|take hoot salt water, &thorn;at rosen haue be enfusyd inne, and lete hit droppe|doune fro an hy&yogh;e vpon &thorn;e hornes of his heued, &thorn;at yt mowe passe downe so|by the eyen.</I>"</NOTE> / If it be|so &thorn;at &thorn;e akynge aswage not wi&thorn; blood leting &amp; colliries &amp; laxatiuis,|&thorn;an it is a signe &thorn;at &thorn;ere is pustula woxe &thorn;erinne, &amp; it is nede for|to make it maturatif; for &thorn;e akinge wole not goon awei, til it be|maad maturatif. &amp; in &thorn;is caas ba&thorn;inge is ful noious / For if akinge|be go sumwhat awei, it wole come a&yogh;en wi&thorn; ba&thorn;ing; &thorn;erfore thou|schalt attende for to make maturatif.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>thou schalt attende for to make m</I>., Lat.: ergo in tendas ad maturandum.|Compare O.Fr. s'atendre &agrave; faire qu. ch.</NOTE>  &amp; putte in his i&yogh;e a collirie
<PB N="245">|of thus wi&thorn; al<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: cum coto, donec super cotum sanies apparebit.  The translator|read "toto."  Sl. 2463, f. 86: "<I>with cotoun, to &thorn;at &thorn;e quytture schewe vpon|&thorn;e cottone.</I>"</NOTE> togidere til &thorn;e quitture schauwie, for &thorn;an &thorn;e akinge|wole aceesse / For whanne pustula is to-broke, &amp; quitture is gaderid,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt putt &thorn;eron a collirie of leed.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt|fulfille alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at schulen be seid wi&thorn; vlceribus / A collirie of|thus &thorn;at is maturatif for <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="165b">pustulis is maad in &thorn;is maner / &rx;, thuris |albi gummosi grossi, partes .x, antimonij, sarcocolle ana. partes .v,|croci partes ij, &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; muscilage of fenigrec; &amp; make|&thorn;erof pelottis, &amp; kepe hem for &thorn;in vss.  &amp; whan &thorn;ou hast nede|herof, &thorn;an tempere a pelot with &thorn;e forseid licour, &amp; make it moist|&amp; binde it vpon his i&yogh;e, &amp; lete &thorn;is ligge til &thorn;e akynge go awei; &amp;|putte in his i&yogh;e colirium de plumbo, &thorn;at is maad in &thorn;is maner /&rx;,|plumbi vsti, antimonij, &yogh;ucare, eris vsti, gummi arabic, draganti|ana partes .viij, opij partem <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., &amp; make herof a sutil poudre, &amp;|&thorn;an tempere it wi&thorn; reyn-watir &amp; wi&thorn; water of rosis, &amp; make &thorn;erof|pelottis.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wolt vse hem, distempere oon &thorn;erof or|tweyne wi&thorn; water of rosis, &amp; binde it vpon his i&yogh;e; for &thorn;is collirie|soudi&thorn; &amp; gendri&thorn; fleisch / Aftir &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at it is soudid, if &thorn;ere|leue a litil ampulle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ampulle</I>, a tumour in the skin of the hands or the feet.  See Tomm.|<I>Dict</I>., s. v. ampolla.  The Lat. has <I>albula</I>.  Matth. Sylv.: "<I>Albule</I> id est|macule oculi albe."</NOTE> &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt cure it as &thorn;ou schalt fynde|in his propre place.  &para; ffleumatik mater maki&thorn; ful seelden ony|enpostym in &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &amp; malancolie myche latter; ne&thorn;eles we wolen|telle curis of hem.  &para; Signes of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="166a">fleum ben &thorn;ese: greet swellynge |&amp; manie teeris, &amp; litil reednes ou&thorn;er noon; &amp; &thorn;e cure herof is to|purge him wi&thorn; cochijs or wi&thorn; trocisco de turbit, saue cochie ben|more better.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt putte in his eere muscilaginem<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&amp;</I> inserted.</NOTE> fenigrec,|&amp; putte in his i&yogh;e &yogh;elowe poudre &thorn;at is forseid.  &amp; vpon his i&yogh;e &thorn;ou|schalt leie enplastre maad of aloe, mirra, acacia, &amp; croco ana, &amp;|distempere hem wi&thorn; mussilagine fenigreci.  &amp; in &thorn;is caas good wijn|wole do him good, drunken in mesure / If it come of malancolie,|&thorn;ou schalt knowe bi blaknes of al &thorn;e bodi<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, fol. 87: "<I>All &thorn;e body of &thorn;e pacient ys blakkyssh.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; leene, &amp; bi drienes of|hise i&yogh;en, &amp; ful litil reednes or noon in hise i&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;e cure herof|is for to purge wel malancolie, &amp; ba&thorn;ing &amp; fomentacion wi&thorn; rosis &amp;|violet, &amp; flouris of borage &amp; buglossa.  &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt wite &thorn;at|in euery maner of obtalmia, in &thorn;e ende &thorn;erof ba&thorn;ing ben good.</P>
