<PB N="246">&para; If &thorn;at reednes of &thorn;e i&yogh;e come of smytyng &amp; akynge, &amp;|swellynge come &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &thorn;an it is necessarie for to haue a &yogh;ong|culuer quyk, &amp; lete hir blood in a veyne vndir hir wynge wi&thorn; a|nedle, &amp; putte it in his i&yogh;e as hoot as it come&thorn; fro &thorn;e culuer.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The use of blood taken from a vein under the wings of a dove is|mentioned by Galen: De Simplicium Medicamentorum medicamentis, Lib.|X., Cap. II. 3.  Trevisa translation of <I>Bart. de Propr</I>., Lib. VII., Cap. 16,|(Add. 27,944, fol. 84), "<I>Also philosophres telle&thorn; as Constant, sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e|blood i-drawe out of &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e ri&yogh;t wynge of a culver, o&thorn;er of a swalowe.|o&thorn;er of a lepwink, &amp; i-doo in &thorn;e bygynnynge vppon &thorn;at mole, clensi&thorn; hit|mi&yogh;tyly / for &thorn;e blood of &thorn;ese foules hete&thorn; and dissolue&thorn; strongliche.</I>"</NOTE>  &THORN;is| doi&thorn; awei <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="166b">&thorn;e akynge, &amp; &thorn;e reednes &amp; &thorn;e brennyng.</P>
