<PB N="251">|i&yogh;en sodeinli anoon, &amp; loke if &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e i&yogh;e bicome whit,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whit</I> for <I>wid</I>, Lat.: vide si pupilla dilatatur.</NOTE> &amp; if|it bicome not whit, &thorn;an it is of .ij. &thorn;ingis; ou&thorn;er it is opilacioun|of &thorn;e nerue, &thorn;at come&thorn; fro &thorn;e brain &amp; is holow &amp; defendi&thorn; &thorn;e si&yogh;t,|or it is cataracta &thorn;at is greet &amp; stoppi&thorn; &thorn;e nerue, &amp; stoppi&thorn; &thorn;e weie|of &thorn;e spirit &thorn;at it mai not come to &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e si&yogh;t &thorn;at is|clepid pupilla /  If &thorn;ou frotist his i&yogh;e as it is forseid, &thorn;an lete him|do vp his i&yogh;e hastili, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt se &thorn;an vpon his i&yogh;e a whit &thorn;ing|as it were a peerle, &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t sureli worche wi&thorn; instrumentis of|cirurgie<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: quod cum videris manum ullatenus non apponas.  This method|of testing, whether a cataract is fit for operation or not, has already been|proposed by Galen, as mentions <I>Paulus de Aegina</I>, Lib. VI., Cap. 21.  We|find the same in <I>Hali Abbas</I>, Lib. IX., Cap. 28, fol. 279, ed., Lugd. 1523.|See Magnus H., <I>Geschichte des grauen Staars</I>.  Leipzig, 1876.</NOTE> / First &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;e pacient sitte vpon a stool tofore|&thorn;ee, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt sitte a litil hi&yogh;er &thorn;an he, &amp; his i&yogh;e &thorn;at is hool &thorn;ou|schalt bynde faste &thorn;at he ne mowe no &thorn;ing se &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt haue in &thorn;i mou&thorn; a fewe braunchis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="171a">of fenel, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt |breke hem a litil with &thorn;i tee&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt blowe in his i&yogh;e .ij.|si&thorn;is or iij. &thorn;at &thorn;e fume of &thorn;e fenel mowe entre into his i&yogh;e / &THORN;an|&thorn;ou schalt haue an instrument of siluir, schape in the maner of a|nedle, and it schal sitte in a greet hafte &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai &thorn;e bettir hold|it wi&thorn; &thorn;in hand, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt bigynne afor&yogh;ens &thorn;e lasse corner|of &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt putte in &thorn;in instrument anoon to &thorn;e corn|&thorn;at is in &thorn;e i&yogh;e, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou seest &thorn;e point of &thorn;e instrument|vndir &thorn;e corn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>corn</I>, a mistake; the translator did not know the meaning of "cornea."|Lat.: et impellas instrumentum usque ad corneam: quia tunc videbis illum.|Cum autem instrumentum videbis sub cornea illum impellas vsque ad aquam|qu&aelig; est coram pupilla.</NOTE> &thorn;an lete &thorn;e point of &thorn;in instrument goon anoon to|&thorn;e water &thorn;at is gaderid tofore &thorn;e i&yogh;e / And whanne &thorn;ou hast|broken &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;e water was ynne, &thorn;an presse it adounward, &amp;|drawe out al &thorn;e watir &thorn;erof clene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp; drawe out al &thorn;e watir &thorn;erof clene</I>, an insertion of the translator. The|operation which he describes is the dislocation of cataract by depression.  A|fuller and more accurate account of it is given by John Vigo, who begins his|description with the following words: "And yf the cataractes cannot be|healed, when they are confirmed, then we must turne to handy operation.|And though we counseyled to leave it to ye tothdrawers, yet we wyl declare|ye maner therof."  Traheron, <I>Vigo</I>, fol. 136<SUP>b</SUP>.</NOTE> &amp; if &thorn;er come more watir &thorn;erto,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou must reherse &thorn;is werk a&yogh;en.  &amp; if &thorn;er come no more watir|&thorn;erto, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie vpon his i&yogh;e a plastre maad of &thorn;e &yogh;elke|of an eij wi&thorn; &thorn;e white, &amp; bole leid vpon lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp; binde vpon|his i&yogh;e, &amp; lete &thorn;e patient be in a derk place, &amp; he schal heere no
<PB N="252">|greet noise, &amp; he schal not traueile wi&thorn;inne .viij. daies, &amp; he mote| be kept so &thorn;at he cow&yogh;e not <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="171b">&amp; fro wra&thorn;&thorn;e / Sumtyme &thorn;e poynt|of &thorn;e i&yogh;e si&yogh;t is stoppid wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;an he schal neuere be curid|&thorn;erof; ou&thorn;er it wole be greet maistrie for to cure it.  &amp; if it mai|be curid, &thorn;is is &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof: &thorn;ou muste purge him with pigra|rasis, &amp; wi&thorn; pululis cochijs &thorn;at rasis made, &amp; &thorn;ei muste be ofte|&yogh;eue, &amp; &thorn;ou muste do in his i&yogh;en drijnge collirijs &amp; o&thorn;ere driyng|medicyns / Ou&thorn;er it mai come of causis withoutfor&thorn; as of smitynge|&amp; &thorn;at mai li&yogh;tli be curid / First &thorn;e patient schal be lete blood, if age|mai suffre it &amp; o&thorn;ere particlis &thorn;at be forseid, for blood letynge|wole helpe for to avoide awei &thorn;e enpostym, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt make|him an enplastre wi&thorn; oon of &thorn;ese medicyns, &amp; it schal be bounden|&thorn;erto softli / &rx;, mele of beenis &thorn;at be sotil &amp; grinde it wi&thorn; wi&thorn;i|leeues smal / Also take mele of beenys &amp; flouris of camomille &amp; &thorn;e|rote of altea .&yogh;. ij., &amp; also biteine .<ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> .j., absinthium .&yogh; j. &amp; se&thorn;e|hem in water &amp; make &thorn;erof an enplastre &amp; lete &thorn;e patient reste,|probatum est.</P>
<P>&para; Ordecilus is a litil swellinge, &amp; is long &amp; smal &amp; come&thorn; to a|child whanne it is bore, &amp; &thorn;is passioun wole sitte in <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="172a">his i&yogh;e liddis /| &thorn;e cure herof is for to lete hem blood &amp; purge him of humours corrupt,|&amp; do &thorn;erto &thorn;is medicyn: medle aloes with licio<NOTE PLACE="foot">"Lycium.  Is the Juice of a thorny tree, growing chiefly in Capadocia|and Lycia, of three cubites heyght."  Halle, <I>Table</I>, p. 63.</NOTE> &amp; make &thorn;erof|a poudre / Also &thorn;ou schalt anoynte him wi&thorn; storax liquida &amp; anointe|him &thorn;erwi&thorn; / &para; Also resolue a litil opoponac in water, and make|an enplastre &thorn;erof &amp; leie vpon the place, &amp; &thorn;e same &thorn;ing doi&thorn;|diaquilon, &amp; or &thorn;ou leie ony plastre &thorn;ervpon, &thorn;ou schalt make a|fomentacioun wi&thorn; hoot water.</P>
<P>&para; Grando &amp; nodus.  Grando is as miche to seie as an hail stoon,|&amp; nodus is a knotte, &amp; &thorn;us come&thorn; in &thorn;e i&yogh;e liddis, &amp; sumtyme it|wole schewe wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &amp; sumtyme wi&thorn;oute.  &amp; whanne it schewi&thorn;|wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, opene it &amp; leie &thorn;eron diaquilon &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis for to|consume &thorn;e mater.  &amp; if &thorn;is suffise not, &thorn;ou schalt take it wi&thorn; &thorn;i|.ij. fyngris &amp; drawe it harde, &amp; &thorn;an kutte &thorn;e skyn &thorn;eron &amp; drawe|him out, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou shalt soude it wi&thorn; &thorn;e white of an eij &amp; o&thorn;ere|&thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben soudinge //</P>
<P>&para; ffistula lacrimalis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 2463, f. 90: "<I>A ffystule in &thorn;e wyke of &thorn;e eye, hit comyth of concours|of rennyng of humores to &thorn;e corner of &thorn;e eye besyde &thorn;e nose, &amp; because of her|multitude &amp; gretnesse &thorn;ey may nat passen out but abyden there &amp; maken an|emynence, as hit were a lupyne; &amp; therfore of sume hit is cleped|lupinus.</I>"</NOTE> &thorn;at is as miche to seie as a feestre wi&thorn;
<PB N="253">|teeris / &THORN;is come&thorn; in &thorn;e corner of &thorn;e i&yogh;e next &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="172b">nose, &amp; engendri&thorn; |&thorn;ere &amp; maki&thorn; a &thorn;ing as greet as it were a pese.  &amp; if &thorn;ese humours|leeue &thorn;ere longe &thorn;ei wolen rotie &amp; &thorn;ei wolen make vlcus &thorn;ere, &amp; &thorn;er|wole come manie teeris &thorn;erto, and &thorn;ei mai not be maad drie, &amp; &thorn;is|mai leeue &thorn;ere so longe &thorn;at &thorn;er wole engendre a feestre &thorn;erof.  &amp;|but if &thorn;at feestre be curid while it is freisch, it wole rote &thorn;e boon,|&amp; &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at it wexi&thorn; oold, &thorn;e worse it wole be for to cure.|&para; &THORN;e firste bigynnynge of &thorn;is cure is for to avoide &thorn;e heed wi&thorn;|cochijs &amp; wi&thorn; pigra, &thorn;an do &thorn;eron &thorn;is collirium / &rx;, aloes, thuris,|sarcocolle, sanguinis draconis, balaustie, antimonij, aluminis, ana,|floris eris a litil, as miche as wole be &thorn;e four&thorn;e part of oon of &thorn;e|forseid.  &amp; make of alle &thorn;es sotil poudre &amp; distempere hem wi&thorn;|reyn water or wi&thorn; water of roses, &amp; caste it in &thorn;e corner of his i&yogh;e,|but &thorn;e place schal be maad drie first.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;erto|oon of &thorn;e mundificatiuis &thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, or|&thorn;is medicyn &thorn;at is aproued / Take clene mirre .&yogh; .ij. &amp; make &thorn;erof|poudre &amp; make it &thorn;icke wi&thorn; &thorn;e galle of a boole, &thorn;at it be as &thorn;icke|as it were an oynement, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="173a">&amp; leie it vpon lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp; leie &thorn;is &thorn;ervpon, |for &thorn;is wole soude &thorn;e place &amp; make it clene / &para; If it so be|&thorn;at it be not curid with &thorn;is medicyn, &thorn;anne it is a signe &thorn;at &thorn;e|boon is rotid, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste opene &thorn;e skyn &amp; vnhile &thorn;e boon,|&amp; touche &thorn;e boon wi&thorn; an hoot iren as fer as it is rotid / &amp; &thorn;anne|leie &thorn;ervpon buttir or grese &thorn;at &thorn;e scar &thorn;er mowe falle awei, &amp; &thorn;an|&thorn;ou muste reherse &thorn;e cauterie a&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;anne leie &thorn;ervpon buttir,|&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou muste do til &thorn;e boon be clene, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;ervpon oile of|rosis hoot medlid wi&thorn; &yogh;elke of an ey til al &thorn;e brennynge falle awey.|&amp; &thorn;an drie &thorn;e place with drijnge medicyns, &amp; &thorn;an regendre fleisch &amp;|soude it, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt wite &thorn;at &thorn;er is noon so good maner medicyn|as &thorn;is is / For if &thorn;ou wolt leie &thorn;erto ony corosif water, &thorn;at wole|brenne for&thorn;ere &thorn;an it schulde / &amp; also it were greet perel for &thorn;e i&yogh;e|&amp; &thorn;erfore it is good for to worche as it is aforseid / <NOTE PLACE="foot">The end of this chapter, omitted by the translator, is given in Sl. 2463,|fol. 90 b.: "<I>&para; Also he</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanfrank.</NOTE> <I>seyth &thorn;at yf &thorn;e bone be schauen with Instrumentis|&thorn;at all &thorn;e corupcion is seldome taken awaye, wherefore &thorn;e corupcion comyth|ayen bycause of &thorn;e partie whiche leuyth behynde corupt.  &para; He seyth also|&thorn;at al&thorn;ou&yogh; the corupcion be taken away neuer so well, yet nature departith|a litell follikell &thorn;erfro aforne &thorn;at &thorn;e flessch mowe be faste knyt other soudid|to &thorn;e bone and what tyme &thorn;e bone is touchyd with an hoot Iryn, &thorn;anne all|&thorn;at is corrupt disseuerith fro &thorn;at ys hoole, and &thorn;e complexion of &thorn;e place is|tempered.</I></NOTE></P>
