<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<PB N="258">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e passioun of &thorn;e nose &amp; anothamia.</HEAD>
<P>As we haue bifore seid &thorn;at &thorn;er ben .ij. hoolis in &thorn;e nose &thorn;at &thorn;e|brayn is purgid &thorn;erbi of superfluite.  &amp; &thorn;e nose is not neruous,|&amp; &thorn;e nose is a propre instrument for to smelle.  &amp; &thorn;ese .ij. hoolis in|&thorn;e nose ben maad fast in &thorn;e scolle.  &amp; in &thorn;at place is ordeyned a|&thorn;ing &thorn;at is clepid colatorium,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>os colatorium</I>.  I could not find this name in the ancient authors, but|it occurs frequently in the Latin translations of the Arab authors.  The idea|that it is the function of the nose to purge the brain is an old one.  Compare|A. C. Celsus de Medicina Lib. IV. Cap. V., ed. Daremberg:  "Destillat autem|humor de capite interdum in nares, quod leve est, interdum in fauces, quod|pejus est; interdum etiam in pulmonem, quod pessimum est."  Avicenna mentions|the "os colatorium" in connection with this theory in his Canon Lib. I.|Fen. I. Doctr. V. Cap. 1., ed. Venetiis, 1527, fol. 9.  "Ossa autem porosa|facta fuerunt . . propter additionem necessitatis causa, rei alieuius, que|necesse est ut in ea penetret sicut odor, qui cum aere attrahitur in osse, collatorio|simili, et cerebri superfluitates, que per ipsum expelluntur."  We find|the same theory in the French name for a cold: "rhume de cerveau," and|for the same reason "Hellebore" is called "brain-purging."  <I>N. E. Dict</I>.,|s. v. brain.</NOTE> &amp; eir is gaderid &thorn;erinne &thorn;at maki&thorn;|vertu of smellynge.  &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at place &thorn;e superfluitees of &thorn;e brayn|ben pourgid, &amp; &thorn;er is oon hoole &thorn;erof &thorn;at goi&thorn; toward &thorn;e mou&thorn;.  &amp;|&thorn;e nose is maad of .ij. boones in &thorn;e maner of a triangle in &thorn;is|maner. <FIGURE></FIGURE>.  &thorn;e scharpe eendis &thorn;at ben aboue ben ioynynge wi&thorn; &thorn;e|boones of &thorn;e i&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e nose &thorn;at ben bine&thorn;e ben|cartilaginous for &thorn;e causis &thorn;at ben forseid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Three leaves or four are wanting, and I insert the Latin text from the|<I>Editio Argellata Ven</I>., 1546, f. 239, bk., and Add. 26,106, f. 71.</NOTE></P>
<P><I>Latin Original.</I> [In parte vero inferiori vnum quodque illorum duorum ossium|habet quandam cartilaginem propter iuuamenta que sciuisti.  In medio|vero habet aliam cartillaginem, qu&aelig; nasum in duas partes diuidit,|qu&aelig; durior et fortior est duabus aliis, qu&aelig; sunt in nasi fine.  Iuuamentum|vero illius medie cartilaginis est, ut si vni parti nasi nocumentum|acciderit, pars alia totius suppleat iuuamentum.  Duo autem ossa|nasi coniunguntur ad inuicem: &amp; fit nasi forma, qu&aelig; cum his qu&aelig;|dicta sunt, plures habet vtilitates.  Prima, vt sit tutamen &amp; coopertorium|superfluitatibus: qu&aelig; de cerebro diriuantur.  Secunda, vt|aerem recipiat, qui est ad receptionem odoratus necessarius mediator.|Tertia, quod quamuis maior pars aeris que attrahitur vadat ad pulmonem:|tamen aliqua eius pars per nasum tendit ad cerebrum.|Foraminis autem quod est inter nasum &amp; os, iuuamenta sunt tria.|Primo vt cum os clauditur, possit aeris fieri attractio ad pulmonem.
<PB N="259">|Secundo, vt per illud cerebri anterior ventriculus expurgetur.  Tertio,|ad intercisionem adiuuet literarum, &amp; voces melius explicandas:|quoniam cum in loquendo sit necessarium vocem temperare: literas|incidere: syllabas solidare: ad hoc saepe labia clauderentur &amp; dentes:|si non esset alia via, per quam posset aer superfluus exalare apud|literarum incisionem totus conculcaretur aer, qui literarum incisionem|&amp; syllabarum prolationem sua multitudine impediret: &amp; vocem etiam|generatam non claram emitteret: facit ergo in verborum &amp; vocis|prolatione foramen hoc quod facit foramen fistul&aelig; superius,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 71 b., on margin: gallice flaute.</NOTE> quod in|vocum et tonorum modulationem remanet absolutum: quare voces|&amp; toni inde magis exeunt absoluti.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The whole preceding passage about the utilities of the nose, and especially|the utility of the "nares posteriores," i. e. the communication between|the nasal cavity and the pharynx, is taken from <I>Avicenna</I>, l. c. Cap. 4.</NOTE></P>
<P>In naso vel naribus plures concurrunt egritudines.  Nam ibi|fiunt pustul&aelig;, vlcera, caro superflua, polypus, cancer, fluxus sanguinis,|fetor, &amp; olfactus priuatio.</P>
<P>Pustul&aelig; fiunt vt plurimum ab adustis humoribus, et sunt cum|punctura &amp; ardore.  Et cura est phlebotomia &amp; corporis euacuatio,|et iniectio albuminis oui cum oleo ros. in simul agitatis.  Pustulis|fractis, fiat vnctio cum vnguento albo Rasis.</P>
<P>Vlcera quoque si calida fuerint, curantur eodem modo.  Si|frigida, cum lauatione vini et mellis, &amp; cum vnguento apostolorum,|et cum vnguento viridi dicendorum.</P>
<P>Caro superflua remouetur cum instrumentis chirurgicis; si non|potest tota cum instrumentis remoueri: remouetur residuum cum|puluere asfodillorum &amp; cum vnguento viridi, &amp; apostolorum, &amp;|cunctis mundificantibus: &amp; remotis superfluis cum unguentis solidantibus|compleatur.</P>
<P>Polypus dicitur a polypo pisce: cuius malitiosa est astutia: quia|quando vult piscibus saturari, ascendit saxum quod est in litore|maris: &amp; ipsi multum assimilatur, pisces fatigati videntes saxum,|non aduertunt de polypo propter similitudinem: sed volentes quiescere,|salliunt de mari: polypus illos absorbet: &amp; in eius conuertit|nutrimentum.  Sic iste morbus cum naso magnam habet affinitatem:|quoniam eius materia est catarrhosa frigida grossa descendens a capite:|&amp; in via propter eius grossitiem &amp; tenacitatem h&aelig;ret naso seu substanti&aelig;|nasi inuiscata: et humores capitis agitatione moti natur&aelig;|volentes descendere, &amp; exire, materiam ibi recipiunt congregatam:
<PB N="260">|qu&aelig; humores illos in suam conuertit malam naturam: et ex ipsa|quotidie augmentatur.  Differentia vero est inter polypum &amp; carnem|superfluam: quoniam caro superflua, non habet profundam tenacitatem|cum nasi substantia: nec cum ipso naso nimis assimilatur:|immo potest de facili segregari: polypus vero firmiter adheret cum|naso: &amp; non sine violentia separatur.  Quorum scilicet polyporum|aliquis est curabilis: aliquis incurabilis.  Curabilis est substanti&aelig;|mollis &amp; tractabilis: nec nasum reddit durum: nec in colore nigrum|seu fuscum: nec est multum supra circa cerebri confinia inuiscatus.|Incurabilis vero nasum reddit durum, liuidum seu nigrum: &amp;|magnam profunditatem tenet, quam quanto magis videris maiori|nigredine maiorique participari duritie, maioremque profunditatem|occupare, tanto plus ab eo existima fugiendum: quoniam naturam|tunc tenet cancri: quanto plus eum curare niteris tanto plus videbis|eius malitiam augmentari.</P>
<P>Curabilis vero cura est secundum quod diximus in cura superflu&aelig;|carnis qu&aelig; ibi consurgit cum ablatione sive cum instrumentis|&amp; cum vnguentis mundificativis: &amp; aliis qu&aelig; nouisti: pr&aelig;cedente|semper corporis et capitis purgatione: sicut multoties est ostensum.|Cauteria quoque secundum quod audies, multum valent ad polypi|materiam consumendam.  Eius vero quem incurabilem diximus,|non assumas curam.  Si tamen rogaris nimis, palliatiuam curam|adhibe: sicut in cura cancri recolimus ostendisse.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>De anatomia oris, &amp; contentorum in ore, &amp; passionibus doctrin&aelig;|terti&aelig; tractatus tertii</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cap. iiii.</HEAD>
<P>Totam vero oris concauitatem interius circundat panniculus qui|continuus est cum meri, &amp; cum stomacho: quare accidit quod|mult&aelig; res tangentes palatum prouocant vomitum.  Ad oris concauitatem|du&aelig; perueniunt vi&aelig;: quarum anatomiam superius habuisti;|in earum summitate est epiglottis: qu&aelig; est creata ad perficiendum|vocem: et ut seruet aliquid de aere attracto ad anelitum.  H&aelig;c|epiglottis ex tribus est composita cartilaginibus: vna est eminens|ante &amp; dicitur clypealis &amp; a laicis dicitur guttur vel nodus gul&aelig;: alia|est posterius cum osse laud&aelig; continua et uocatur nomen non habens.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cartilago cricoidea.</NOTE>|Tertia vocatur cymbalaris siue cooperturalis:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cartilagines aryt&aelig;noide&aelig;.</NOTE> &amp; continuatur cum|nomen non habente: &amp; cooperit clypealem: et ista cymbalaris|mouetur per eius musculos: quare cum homo comedit, viam claudit
<PB N="261">|canne pulmonis: &amp; viam aperit oesophagi.  Cum autem homo|loquitur, aperit viam canne pulmonis: &amp; claudit viam oesophagi.|Quare multoties accidit, quod si homo comedens dicere vellet|aliquid ignoranter: quod aliquid viam intraret canne pulmonis:|quare natura moueretur ad tussiendum: nec cessaret, donec quod|cannam intrauerat, esset ad extra expulsum.] <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="178a">til &thorn;at mete be out |of his &thorn;rote, saue algate he schal cou&yogh;e til it be oute.  &amp; &thorn;an aboue|&thorn;is instrument is vuula &thorn;at is &thorn;e palet<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>palet</I>, palate.  See Skeat, <I>Et. Dict</I>.  The erroneous identification of|uvula and palatum is not in the original.</NOTE> of &thorn;e mou&thorn; &amp; helpi&thorn; for to|make soun / For &thorn;e wynd &thorn;at come&thorn; of &thorn;e lungis reboundi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rebound</I>, O.Fr. rebondir.  See later references in Skeat, <I>Et. Dict</I>.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens|&thorn;e palet &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e more soun.  In &thorn;e holownes of &thorn;e mou&thorn; is|maad fast &thorn;e tunge, &thorn;at is maad of whit fleisch, &amp; neische, &amp; of|nerues, &amp; veynes, &amp; of arterijs, as it is necessarie &thorn;erfore / And in|&thorn;e &thorn;rote of &thorn;e tunge ben .ij. wellis &thorn;at spotil is gaderid &thorn;eron, &amp;|holdi&thorn; alwei &thorn;e tunge moist / Also in a mannes mou&thorn; ben .xxxij.|tee&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;erof sitti&thorn; .xvj. in &thorn;e cheke boon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: XVI in utraque mandibula.</NOTE> &amp; summen han but|.xxviij. /  And for to hile a mannes tee&thorn; ben ordeined lippis, &amp;|ben as it were &thorn;e dore of an hous, &amp; helpi&thorn; forto speke &amp; to pronounce|wordis / Now to alle &thorn;ese lymes &thorn;at ben forseid: as &thorn;e palet|of &thorn;e mou&thorn; &amp; a mannes tunge &amp; &thorn;e tee&thorn; &amp; &thorn;e gomis &amp; &thorn;e lippis, alle|&thorn;ei han diuers passiouns.</P>
<P>&para; Vuula sumtyme wi&thorn; cours of humouris sumtime gaderi&thorn; an|enpostym, &amp; sumtyme vuula wexi&thorn; to long,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Vuula namque propter humorum decursum aliquando apostematur|aliquando solum elongatur.</NOTE> &amp; sumtyme apostym of|&thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="178b">palet come&thorn; of hoot cause, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt knowe bi &thorn;e reednes |of &thorn;e place &amp; bi brennyng; &amp; &thorn;anne in &thorn;e cure herof &thorn;ou schalt|bigynne for to lete him blood in &thorn;e heed veyne, &amp; purge colre wi&thorn; a|decoccioun of fretis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fretis</I>, fruit.</NOTE>  &amp; herof &thorn;ou schalt make him a gargarisme,|&amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; he schal ofte waische his mou&thorn;: &rx;, lentes, balaustias,|psidias, gallas, rosas, sumac, &amp; boile &thorn;ese wi&thorn; .ij. partis of water, &amp;|oon part of vinegre, &amp; herof make a gargarisme / Also &thorn;ou schalt|leie to his palet poudre of rosis, &amp; sandalis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts <I>&amp; rosis.</I></NOTE> &amp; balaustiarum &amp; a|litil of camphre / &THORN;is is a good help &thorn;erfore whanne &thorn;e palet is|woxe long wi&thorn; hoot humouris.  &para; If &thorn;er come an enpostym of|coold humouris, ou&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;e palet wexe long wi&thorn; coold humouris,|&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe whanne &thorn;e place is not reed, &amp; if &thorn;er be
<PB N="262">|miche spotil in his mou&thorn;, first &thorn;ou schalt purge him wi&thorn; cochijs &amp;|pigra, &amp; &thorn;an make him a gargarisme wi&thorn; &thorn;is decoccioun: &rx;, aceti|partes duas, mellis partem vnam, boile hem togidere &amp; do &thorn;erto| poudre of mirtillorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. over <I>mirtillorum</I> is written <I>mirtelberys</I>.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e seed of rosis &amp; peletre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pelletre</I>, Lat. pyrethrum.  "<I>Pyrethrum</I>, Bartram, wild or bastard|Pellitory, an Herb the Root of which is very biting and hot."  Phillips.|See <I>Pelleter</I> Cath. Angl. and Note ibid.</NOTE> &amp; &yogh;in&yogh;ibere, &amp;|&thorn;an make him poudre of pepir <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="179a">&amp; sal armoniac, &amp; make herwith a|fumigacioun wi&thorn; enbotum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>enbotum</I>, Lat. embotum.  See <I>Dufr</I>.= infundibulum.  Fr. embut, a|surgical instrument, a funnel.</NOTE>  &amp; if it be greet to-swolle, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|muste make consumynge &thorn;ingis as diameron &amp; sappa michum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sappa michum</I>, Lat. saramitum.</NOTE> / If|&thorn;e palet be recchid along, &amp; if it be so long &thorn;at it lie vpon &thorn;e|tunge, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste kutte awei as miche &thorn;erof as &thorn;ee &thorn;inki&thorn; good,|so &thorn;at it be nomore &thorn;an it schulde be; &amp; be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou kutte not|to myche &thorn;erof, for &thorn;er mi&yogh;te come greet perel &thorn;erof: as his vois|mi&yogh;te be apeirid &thorn;e while he lyuede, &amp; contynuely cou&yogh;inge, &amp; his|lungis mi&yogh;te be &thorn;e worse &thorn;erfore &amp; also his piys.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>piys</I>, Lat. pectus.  O.Fr. pis.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;erfore it is|greet perel for to kutte a mannes palet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gulielmus de Saliceto, Lanfranc's teacher, uses a cautery instead of|cutting.  I give the quotation from an English translation, MS. Sloane 277,|fol. 1 (beginning of 15th cent.): "<I>Be &thorn;e grape cutt wi&thorn; a brennynge yren|keruynge, &amp; be it putt in by a pipe to &thorn;e grape, &thorn;e mou&thorn; holden open.  Be|&thorn;e grape receyued in &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e pipe.  Whiche receyued, be putt in &thorn;ere|&thorn;e brennynge yren in &thorn;e pipe, &amp; be &thorn;e grape cauteried.</I>"</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; The tunge suffri&thorn; manie sijknessis as pustulas and swellynge|&amp; kuttynge, &amp; ofte tyme a mannes tunge bicome&thorn; schorter &thorn;an it|schulde be.  And &thorn;er is ano&thorn;er passioun &thorn;at is clepid fili ranulam<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ranula</I>, a tumor, which forms under the tongue.  (Dunglison.)  See|Vegetius, De re veterin. 4, 5, 1.  Gr. <GAP DESC="Greek">. Fr. grenouillette.</NOTE>|&amp; spasmum, &amp; sumtyme a mannes tunge wexi&thorn; to long.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The passage is corrupt.  Lat.: Lingua quoque multas patitur &aelig;gritudines,|pustulas, inflationem, scissuram, breviationem fili, ranulam, spasmum|et relaxationem.</NOTE>  &para; The|curis of pustulis &amp; vlcera schulen be seid heraftir / If &thorn;er come an|enpostym or ony swellynge to a mannes tunge, &amp; it come of hoot| humours, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt bigynne &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof in &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="179b">maner /|ffirst lete him blood in &thorn;e heed veine, &amp; &thorn;anne make him a decoccioun|&amp; a waisching as it is aforseid in apostym of &thorn;e palet: &amp; he|schal holde in his mou&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of letuse.  &amp; in &thorn;e same maner &thorn;ou|schalt cure swellynge of a mannes tunge / If &thorn;er come apostym or
<PB N="263">|ony swellynge of coold humouris, &thorn;an purge him with pillulis &thorn;at|be forseid of .G[aliens]. makinge.  &para; Ther was a man &thorn;at his tunge|was so swolle &thorn;at it mi&yogh;te not be conteyned in his mou&thorn;.  &amp; first|I made him purgaciouns &amp; waischingis, &amp; &thorn;an I made him consumynge|&thorn;ingis; &amp; in &thorn;is maner he was curid.  &para; Scissure is a|passioun in a mannes tunge &thorn;at is as it were kutting.  &amp; &thorn;at schal|be curid wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of malue soden wi&thorn; psillium &amp; medlid wi&thorn;|sugre &amp; sode, &amp; herwi&thorn; he schal waische his mou&thorn;.  &amp; he schal|drinke water of barli, &amp; his mete schal be hoggis feet wel soden, &amp;|wi&thorn; &thorn;e nerues of &thorn;e feet he schal frote wel his tunge.  &para; Also &thorn;er|is a &thorn;reed<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;reed</I>, Lat. filum.  Usually filetum.  Fr. filet de la langue.</NOTE> vndir sum mannes tunge &thorn;at he mai not put out his|tunge as he schulde, &amp; also it letti&thorn; him to speke.  &THORN;e cure herof|is for to kutte &thorn;at &thorn;reed, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="180a">&amp; &thorn;an brenne him.  &amp; it is better for to|make an instrument of goold &amp; brenne it &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; kutte also wi&thorn; |&thorn;e same instrument / &para; Also &thorn;er come&thorn; an enpostym vpon a mannes|tunge of fleume<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Ranula quoque fit sub lingua.  Sl. 2463, fol. 93: "<I>Ranula is an|emynence vnder &thorn;e tunge toward &thorn;e forther teth in maner of an enpostume,|&amp; whane &thorn;e tunge is lift vp &thorn;er schewith as it were a nother tunge vnder &thorn;e|tunge.</I>"</NOTE> &amp; also of malancolie, saue of malancolie an enpostym|come&thorn; but selden / &THORN;ese ben &thorn;e signes if it come of|malancolie: &thorn;e place wole be ledi ou&thorn;ir blak.  &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;ou no|cure &thorn;erto / If it come of fleuma, &thorn;anne frote wel his tunge wi&thorn;|salt, til &thorn;e blood come out &thorn;erof.  &amp; if &thorn;is suffise not, &thorn;an frote it|wel wi&thorn; vitriol / If &thorn;e spasme come in a mannes tunge &thorn;at wole|constryne &thorn;e tunge inward, &thorn;e cure herof is for to holde oile of|anete in his mou&thorn; &amp; of camomille hoot as he mai suffre, &amp; make an|enplastre herof medlid wi&thorn; hoot water, &amp; leie it vpon his heed &amp;|vpon his nolle hoot / If his tunge bicome neische, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste|purge him wi&thorn; pillulis fetidis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pillul&aelig; fetid&aelig;</I>, pills composed from fetid things.</NOTE> or with trocisco de turbit.  &amp; &thorn;an|do &thorn;erto &thorn;is medicyn: &rx;, grana vij. numero, recentis &amp; lucidi|euforbij,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Halle, <I>Table</I>, p. 35.  '<I>Euphorbium</I>, <GAP DESC="Greek">, is the gum or teares|of a tree called Euphorbia growinge in Lybia, found out (by the testimonye|of Dioscorides) in ye time of Iuba: and was called by that name (as saith|Ruellius) of his Phisicien."</NOTE> &amp; take vij. figis &amp; pare awei &thorn;e ryndis &thorn;erof &amp; grynde|hem wel togidere, &amp; do &thorn;erto as miche raw hony <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="180b">&amp; medle hem togidere, |&amp; make herof &thorn;e maner of a letuarie; &amp; herof he schal take|as miche as a bene, &amp; leie it vndir his tunge, whanne he were
<PB N="264">|fastynge / Wi&thorn; &thorn;is medicyn &thorn;e abbot of seint victor was maad|hool; for he mi&yogh;te not speke, &amp; herwi&thorn; his speche come a&yogh;en.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: cum hac medicina fuit restituta loquela domin&aelig; abbatiss&aelig; sancti|victoris ad ultimum, qu&aelig; propter lingu&aelig; mollificationem non poterat uerbum|intelligibile bene loqui; dedi ei hanc medicinam, et cito locuta est expedite.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; Akinge of tee&thorn;: sumtyme it come&thorn; of vijs of &thorn;e tee&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of viis of &thorn;e tee&thorn;</I>, dentium vitio.  <I>viis</I> is used synonymously with|<I>defaute</I>.  Sometimes both expressions are used.  Sloane 277, f. 12 <I>b</I>.: "<I>These|seknesses be maad of vice or defaute of &thorn;e norischinge streng&thorn;e.</I>"</NOTE> &amp;|sumtyme of &thorn;e gomis, &amp; sumtyme it come&thorn; of vijs of &thorn;e stomac, &amp;|sumtyme it come&thorn; of hoot mete, &amp; sumtyme of coold mete.  &amp; if|it come of hoot mete, make him holde coold watir in his mou&thorn;, &amp;|&thorn;at wole cure him anoon.  &amp; if it come of coold mete, &thorn;an he|schal holde in his mou&thorn; hoot oile.  &amp; if a mannes tee&thorn; aki&thorn; for sour|&thorn;ingis, &thorn;an he schal ete chese &amp; portulacas, or he schal gnawe wi&thorn;|his tee&thorn; hoot wex<NOTE PLACE="foot">This is evidently a way of filling the hole of a tooth.</NOTE> / If it come of vicis of &thorn;e heed or of &thorn;e gomis,|and &thorn;e cause come of hete, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe bi reednes of &thorn;e|place &amp; bi &thorn;e hete &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in &thorn;e heed|veine, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in &thorn;e veine &thorn;at is vndir his|tunge; &amp; &thorn;an he schal holde in his mou&thorn; oile of rosis, medlid wi&thorn;| watir, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="181a">ou&thorn;er coold watir &amp; vinegre / If &thorn;e akynge be so greuous|&thorn;at it mai not be take awei, &thorn;an aswage his akynge wi&thorn; &thorn;is|medicyn: &rx;, seminis iusquiami albi<NOTE PLACE="foot">Halle, <I>Table</I>, 52.  "<I>Hyosciamus</I>.  Henbane is called in Greeke <GAP DESC="Greek">;|in Latin:  Hiosciamus, Apollinaris, Faba suilla et Altercum; of|Apuleius: Symphoniaca; of others also Fabidum and Fabilonia, and of|some Cassilago or Caniculata; of the Apothecaries Iusquiamus.  Of Henbane|there are three kyndes: the blacke, the yelowe and the whyte."</NOTE> opij ana <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR> .j, seminis apij <ABBR EXPAN="[scruple]"><GAP></ABBR>|.j, grinde hem togidere &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; vinegre, &amp; make &thorn;erof|pelottis in &thorn;e greetnes of a pece, &amp; leie oon herof vpon &thorn;e too&thorn;, &amp;|&thorn;is wole do awei &thorn;e akinge &thorn;erof.  &amp; after &thorn;e four&thorn;e dai lete him|holde in his mou&thorn; oile of rosis, in which is dissolued masticis.|&para; If &thorn;e akynge come of coold humouris, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe if &thorn;e|place be not reed ne to-swollen, &thorn;an purge him wi&thorn; cochijs or wi&thorn;|pigra.  &amp; aftir &thorn;is he schal holde in his mou&thorn; tiriacam diatesseron.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>diatessaron</I>, an electuary into the composition of which entered four|medicines.  "Among Farriers <I>Diatessaron</I> is taken for Horse-treacle; &mdash; &mdash;.|Also an Electuary made of Gentian, Bay berries and Birth-wort, of each two|Ounces, all beaten to a very fine Powder, and work'd in like manner with|two Pounds of Honey in a Stone-mortar."&mdash;Phillips.</NOTE>|&para; Also do &thorn;is medicyn in his eere in &thorn;e same parti &thorn;at aki&thorn; /|&rx;, olium oliuarum .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> ij., aceti .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., coloquintidae, piperis ana .&yogh; .j.,
<PB N="265">|&amp; boile hem in a double vessel, &amp; distille it in his eere flaisch<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flaisch</I>, tepidus.  See p. 255, note 3.</NOTE> /|Sumtyme a mannes tee&thorn; ben frete &amp; ben holow, &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; of|humours corrupt &thorn;at falli&thorn; to &thorn;e tee&thorn;.  &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt|cure it / &rx;, olium .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., sansuci<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Samsucus</I>, maiorana," et cet.  <I>Alphita</I>, p. 161.</NOTE> sicci,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>succi</I>.</NOTE> seminis sicute ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>.|boile hem togidere, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt haue <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="181b">a cauterie wi&thorn; .ij. |pointis, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;e schap herof heraftir, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt|make &thorn;e same instrument hoot in &thorn;e fier, &amp; &thorn;an putte it in &thorn;e forseid|oile, &amp; &thorn;an putte it in &thorn;e hole of his too&thorn;, &amp; be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou|touche not his gomys wi&thorn; &thorn;e iren ne his lippis: &amp; &thorn;is medicyn &thorn;ou|muste reherse ofte tymes / &THORN;is medicyn wole bringe water out of|&thorn;e tee&thorn;, &amp; it wole do awei &thorn;e akynge.  &para; If &thorn;ou desirist to drawe|out ony mannes too&thorn; wi&thorn;outen iren: &rx;, cortices radicum mori &amp;|piretrum ana, distempere hem wi&thorn; vinegre &amp; grinde hem wel|togidere, &amp; drie hem in &thorn;e sunne, &amp; departe li&yogh;tli &thorn;e too&thorn; &amp; &thorn;e|fleisch of &thorn;e gomis &amp; leie of &thorn;e medicyn bitwixe &thorn;e too&thorn; &amp; &thorn;e|fleisch / Also lac titimalli<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lac titimalli</I>. <GAP DESC="Greek">  euforbia.</NOTE> distemperid wi&thorn; flour of amidum / Also|make poudre of peletre &amp; lete it lie in vinegre in &thorn;e somer tyme, &amp;|kepe it; &thorn;is makith neische, &thorn;at &thorn;e too&thorn; mowe be drawe out wi&thorn;outen|ony iren / If a mannes tee&thorn; ben blac, in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt|make hem whit / &rx;, farinam ordei, sal ana, &amp; leie hem in hony, &amp;|make &thorn;erof past &amp; folde it in paper <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="182a">or in lynnen cloo&thorn;, &amp; brenne |it in a furneis.  &amp; &thorn;an brenne schellis of eiren, &amp; ciperi, aluminis|ana partes duas, corticum citri siccorum, camfer ana partem vnam,|make herof poudre, and frote &thorn;erwi&thorn; his tee&thorn; &amp; hise gomis, &amp; &thorn;is|wole do awei &thorn;e blaknes of a mannes tee&thorn; /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e passioun in wommen brestis /</HEAD>
<P>God almi&yogh;ti made in a womman tetis for &thorn;e norischinge of a|child.  &amp; a wommans tetis ben maad of fleisch &thorn;at is glandulous,|&amp; of veines, &amp; of arterijs, &amp; of nerues, &amp; ben but veines &thorn;at|comen fro a wommans lyuere to hir tetis &amp; &thorn;e maris, as it is seid|here tofore, &amp; in what maner blood turne&thorn; into milk it is forseid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: et ad ubera veniunt ven&aelig; concav&aelig; a matrice, per quas, ut scivisti,|pars sanguinis attrahitur menstrualis, et sicut chylus camellinus veniens a|stomacho, cum a hepate recipitur, colorem recipit rubeum: sic sanguis a|matrice veniens rubeus albescit.  Compare <I>Avicenna</I>, Lib. IV., Fen. XII.,|Cap. 1, f. 209.  "Nam epar rubificat chilum album et facit ipsum sanguinem.|Et mamilla albificat sanguinem rubeum et facit ipsum lac."</NOTE>
<PB N="266"></P>
<P>&para; In a wommans tetis come&thorn; manie passiouns / ffor, as Egidius|sei&thorn;, &thorn;at sumtyme &thorn;er come&thorn; &thorn;erto apostym of milk, &amp; sumtyme|vlcera / And comounly enpostyms come&thorn; of blood &thorn;at is drawe to|&thorn;e tetis &amp; mai not turne into milk, or if a womman haue to miche|blood, &amp; it come&thorn; of febilnes of vertu as it is aforseid in &thorn;e general|chapitre of enpostyms.  &para; &THORN;e cure of an hoot enpostym in &thorn;e|tetis / ffirst &thorn;ou <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="182b">schalt lete hir blood in Basilica, or sette a ventuse| vpon hir schuldris.  &amp; if &thorn;e cause come of retencioun of menstrue,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue hir medicyns for to bringe out &thorn;e menstrue, or|&thorn;ou schalt lete hir blood in &thorn;e sophene, &amp; anointe &thorn;e place wi&thorn; oile|of rosis, &amp; &thorn;e four&thorn;e part of vinegre.  &amp; if &thorn;is suffise not, &thorn;an|wete a lynnen cloo&thorn; in &thorn;e iuys of solatri,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Halle, <I>Table</I>, p. 119.  "Solanum hortense, which doubtlesse Lanfranke|meaneth by Solatrum, doth Galen also call Esculentum."</NOTE> &amp; whanne &thorn;ou hast|anoyntid &thorn;e place wi&thorn; oile &amp; vinegre, &thorn;an leie &thorn;is cloo&thorn; &thorn;ervpon.|&amp; loke &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at &thorn;ou leist &thorn;erto be flasch hoot;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flasch hoot</I>, tepidus.  See p. 255, note 3.</NOTE> for &thorn;er|schal no coold &thorn;ing be leid &thorn;erto for &thorn;e place is neruous, for coold|&thorn;ing wolde greue it.  If alle &thorn;ese medicyns suffisen not, saue &thorn;e|mater bigynne&thorn; to drawe to quitture, &thorn;anne leie &thorn;erto maturatiuis.|&amp; if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t not do it awei wi&thorn; repercussiuis ne wi&thorn; resoluynge|&thorn;ingis, &amp; &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;t not make it maturatif, &thorn;an it is drede lest &thorn;e|womman bicome in a passioun &thorn;at is clepid Mania.<NOTE PLACE="foot">De propr. rer. lib. V. cap. 34.  Add. 27,944, fol. 53 b.: "<I>ypocras sei&thorn;|&thorn;at in wommen in &thorn;e whiche superfluyte of blood turned to &thorn;e pappis, it|bode&thorn; madnes.</I>"</NOTE>  &THORN;an hir heed|mote be schaue, &amp; &yogh;eue hir confortif &thorn;ingis for hir heed, &amp; &yogh;eue hir| sotil dietynge, &amp; sche schal drinke no wijn ne ete <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="183a">no fleisch.  &amp;|&thorn;ou muste worche ful sotilli, ffor I say a womman &thorn;at hadde an|enpostym in hir brest &amp; come of blood, &amp; so I tau&yogh;te hir for to do<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I>, above line.</NOTE>|as it is aforseid, &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;er come a lewid cirurgian &amp; repreuede me,|&amp; he leide &thorn;ervpon maturatiuis: &amp; &thorn;e more &thorn;at he leide &thorn;ervpon|maturatiuis, &thorn;e more &thorn;e mater wexide greet &amp; &thorn;e more brennynge.|&amp; &thorn;e same cirurgian wolde not heere my counseil / &amp; &thorn;e wommans|freendis took more hede to &thorn;e lewid cirurgian &thorn;an to me, &amp; wi&thorn;inne|.iij. daies Mania come to hir and was oute of hir witt, &amp; so &thorn;e|frenesie fil on hir / &amp; &thorn;is pronosticacioun I seide in &thorn;e bigynnynge,|but &thorn;ei wolde not leue mi wordis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: mea tamen prognosticatio multum exaltata extitit.</NOTE> / If it so be &thorn;at it make quitture,|&thorn;an opene it &amp; do out &thorn;e quitture, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto a mundificatif,
<PB N="267">|&amp; be wel war &thorn;at &thorn;ou putte &thorn;erinne no greet tent ne long, as manie|foolis doon; for a wommans tetis ben ful of nerues, &amp; if &thorn;e nerues|were pressid wi&thorn; ony tent, it wolde make gret akynge, &amp; wolde|lette &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof.  &para; Also &thorn;er ben manie foli lechis, whanne &thorn;ei|fynden <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="183b">in a wommans tetis fleisch &thorn;at is glandelous, &thorn;an &thorn;ei wene |&thorn;at it be wickid fleisch, &amp; ben &thorn;eraboute for to drawe it out, &amp;|&thorn;an &thorn;ei schendi&thorn; al &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e brest.  &THORN;ou schalt worche|wiseli &amp; &thorn;ou schalt remeue noon herof, for as it is aforseid, al &thorn;e|fleisch of &thorn;e tetis is glandelous.  &amp; whanne &thorn;at is clensid wi&thorn;|mundificatiuis &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt regendre fleisch, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt drie|it / If it be so, &thorn;at coold mater gadere to enpostym in a wommans|brest, &amp; &thorn;at come&thorn; ful selde, loke if &thorn;is mater come of fleume, &amp;|&thorn;an anoynte &thorn;e place wi&thorn; oile of camomille, &amp; oile of lilie, &amp; oile|of anete, &amp; a litil vinegre medlid &thorn;erwi&thorn;.  &amp; if it be ony nede first|make hir a purgacioun, &amp; if it resolue not, &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto maturatiuis,|&amp; &thorn;an do as it is aforseid / &amp; if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e mater turne|to hardnes &amp; blak or ledi, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou leie &thorn;erto|no medicyns &thorn;at ben to hoot, for &thorn;er mai engendre a cancre &thorn;erof|ful li&yogh;tli.  &amp; if it be so, &thorn;an be &thorn;ou not &thorn;eraboute for to make it|maturatif, &amp; do &thorn;ou no cure &thorn;erto.  &amp; summen seien &thorn;at a womman |mai be curid for <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="184a">to kutte off al &thorn;e brest, &amp; &thorn;at is al fals.  Saue|&thorn;ou schalt kepe &thorn;e place wi&thorn; vnguentum de tutia, &amp; sche mote ofte|be purgid, &thorn;at sche mowe lyue &thorn;e lenger.  &para; I-leue &thorn;e wordis &thorn;at I|seie; &thorn;ou&yogh; I haue curid manie men of diuers empostyms, I mi&yogh;te|neuere cure a verri cancre, but it were in a fleischi place &thorn;ere I|mi&yogh;te kut al awei wi&thorn;outen ony hurtyng of senewis &amp; of veines<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is no condition mentioned in the Latin original, under which the|operation might be performed.  Roy. 12. C. XIV. fol. 54 b.: de uero cancro|nunquam curare potui, licet pluries cum meis uiribus laborauerim.</NOTE> /|&amp; a wommans brest is ful of senewis &amp; veynes &amp; arterijs.  &para; Vlcera|&thorn;at ben in a wommans tetis schulen be curid as it is aforseid in &thorn;e|general chapitre, saue herof &thorn;ou muste be war &thorn;at &thorn;is lyme may not|suffre so harde corosiuis for &thorn;e greet tendirnes &thorn;erof, saue &thorn;ou|schalt do &thorn;erto medicyns &thorn;at ben mundificatif &amp; driynge / It falli&thorn;|to summe wommen &thorn;at &thorn;e point of hir tete ne goi&thorn; not out, but|ben al hid in &thorn;e tete so &thorn;at a child mai not take it in his mou&thorn; for|to souke / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt helpe it / Take &thorn;e cuppe of an|acurne, &amp; &thorn;at is lyk to &thorn;e point of a wommans tete, &amp; do &thorn;eron|terbentyn or pich, &amp; make it hoot &amp; leie it vpon &thorn;e point of hir|tete &amp; binde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="184b">it &thorn;erto faste, &amp; &thorn;is wole drawe out &thorn;e point of hir 
<PB N="268">|tete.  &para; Also it bifalli&thorn; to maidenes &thorn;at her tetis bicome&thorn; more &thorn;an|&thorn;ei schulde be bi resoun, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt helpe hem in &thorn;is maner /|Take stonys &thorn;at me whetti&thorn; knyues on, &amp; frote &thorn;ese .ij. stones|togidere in vinegre longe, til &thorn;e vinegre bicome &thorn;icke &thorn;erof, &amp; make|it hoot &amp; anoynte &thorn;er wi&thorn; hir tetis, &amp; &thorn;an binde hem / &THORN;is medicyn|defendi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulen not wexe, &amp; make hem bicome litil til &thorn;ei|come to her owne propre schap.  &para; Also take comyn &amp; make|poudre &thorn;erof, &amp; medle it wi&thorn; hony &amp; vinegre; and it worchi&thorn; &thorn;e|more strongli if &thorn;ou medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; bole armoniac &amp; terra sigillata;|grinde hem &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; vinegre, &amp; make a plastre &thorn;erof &amp;|lete it lie &thorn;eron .iij. daies, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt waische it wi&thorn; coold|water / And a womman be war herof &thorn;at sche haue no sich|medicyn, if hir brest schal wexe ony more.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator has omitted the following passage: Caueat etiam illa|qu&aelig; non vult suas ingrossare mamillas: ne illas tangat vel tangi permittat.</NOTE>  &para; If &thorn;at milk be|gaderid hard in a wommans brest for hete, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt anointe|hir brest wi&thorn; oile of rosis &amp; vinegre, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt make an enplastre| as <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="185a">of solatri, portulace, for &thorn;ese herbis han propirte for to|dissolue.  &para; &THORN;is is a plastre &thorn;at wole dissolue mylk &thorn;at is congelid|hard, and it wole make &thorn;e mater of an enpostym maturatif /|&rx;, mice panis, farina ordei, fenigreci &amp; seminis lini ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j, radicis|malue visci &amp; herbe veruce.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>herbe veruce</I>, Lat. <I>herb&aelig; eruc&aelig;</I>.  Brassica eruca L., white mustard.|The translator mistook it for Verrucaria.</NOTE> ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[handful]"><GAP></ABBR> .j.; se&thorn;e wel &thorn;ese .ij. laste, &amp;|&thorn;an stampe hem wel alle togidere &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; oile, &amp; make|&thorn;erof a plastre &amp; leie it vpon flasch hoot /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>ffor brekyng of &thorn;e siphac &amp; of his laxyng.</HEAD>
<P>Anothamia of &thorn;e siphac is aforseid / &amp; sumtyme siphac is kutt,|&amp; sumtyme it recchi&thorn; along, &amp; sumtyme it to-breki&thorn; wi&thorn; lepinge,|&amp; sumtyme for greet wepinge, &amp; sumtyme for greet crijnge, &amp;|sumtyme for greet traueile.  &para; If siphac be recchid aboute &thorn;e nauele|ou&thorn;er aboute &thorn;e heeris, &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;t knowe in &thorn;is maner: &thorn;e place|wole be to-swolle an hi&yogh; as it were an enpostym.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou|touchist it wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngir, it wole goon yn a&yogh;en.  &amp; sumtyme it wole|come a&yogh;en, &amp; it wole make noon gurgulacioun / &THORN;e cure herof is but| li&yogh;t, &amp; is wi&thorn; a ligature &amp; wi&thorn; enplastre &thorn;at schal be seid in &thorn;e brekinge|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="185b">of &thorn;e siphac.  &amp; if siphac be to-broke, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;te knowe bi &thorn;e|greet noise, whanne &thorn;ou lest &thorn;in hond &thorn;ervpon for to putte hem yn
<PB N="269">|a&yogh;en.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The distinction made between a simple protrusion and a rupture of the|siphac is, in fact, one between a less or more developed hernia.  The "gurgling|sound" has already been noticed by <I>Avicenna Canon</I>, Lib. III., Fen. 22,|Tract. 1, Cap. 3.</NOTE>  &para; &THORN;e cure herof is hard in an oold man.  &THORN;an make him a braccal<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>braccal</I>, Lat. brachale = cingulum coriaceum Dufr., from med. Lat.|brac&aelig;.  See <I>breeches, N. E. Dict</I>.  The use of the "brachale vel lumbare"|is mentioned by Gulielm. de Salie, <I>Chirurgia</I>. Lib. I., Cap. 43.  De crepatura|in inguinibus.  Engl. transl., Sl. 277, fol. 6 <I>b</I>.  "<I>Wi&thorn;oute euttynge moost|children &amp; o&thorn;ere in whiche &thorn;e guttes comen not down to &thorn;e ballock codd, &amp;|whiche &thorn;at hadde but litel schewynge wi&thorn; a lumbare or a bawdrike, &amp; oure|plastre &amp; powdre manye in my tyme I curede &thorn;e lumbare or bawdrike|owe&thorn; to be maad of lynnen clo&thorn; &thorn;refold.</I>"  Sl. 2463, fol. 123 b. says: "<I>The|cure without inscicion ... is don with a gyrdell made for &thorn;e rupture, &thorn;e|whiehe a man may fynde to sylle.</I>"</NOTE>|id est a boond &thorn;at it be &thorn;e brede of .iiij. fyngris.  &amp; it mote be|maad of lynnen cloo&thorn; maniefoold,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maniefoold</I>, Lat.: multis duplicationibus facta.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ou muste make a plate of iren,|as brood as &thorn;e brekyng is, &amp; &thorn;at mote be fooldid manie foold in &thorn;e|forseid ligature, &amp; it schal not be round, but plain.  &amp; &thorn;ou muste|ordeyne &thorn;erfore fastnyngis tofore &amp; bihinde &amp; in hise flankis, &thorn;at it|mowe be holde algate in oon place, and &thorn;ou schalt make an enplastre|for to leie vpon &thorn;e same place vndir &thorn;e bindinge in &thorn;is maner / &rx;,|glutinum piscium vel carte .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. iiij, picis grece .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. .iiij, picis naualis|armoniaci ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> ij, kutte &thorn;ese alle to smale gobetis, &amp; do hem in
<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. ij. of vinegre, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .iiij. of oile of masticis &amp; lete hem lie &thorn;eron|adai &amp; any&yogh;t, &amp; &thorn;an melte hem in a panne &amp; cole hem.  &amp; heron|medle poudre mastic &amp; thus, &amp; boli armoniaci, mummie, sanuinis,|draconis, dragaganti, farine fenigreci ana <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>. medle hem longe|togidere / Ou&thorn;ir take <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="186a">scropholarie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scropholarie</I>, scrophularia, water betony, <I>medewort</I> written above.|See Wr. W&uuml;l. <I>m&ecirc;dwurt</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e rynde &thorn;erof &amp; grinde it |wi&thorn; grese, &amp; make &thorn;erof an enplastre, &amp; of &thorn;e same rotis make|poudre, &amp; &yogh;eue him &thorn;erof eueri dai .&yogh; .j. &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>. wi&thorn; wijn / Also &yogh;eue|him euery dai .&yogh; .j &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR> of poudre maad of &thorn;e rotis of valarian|temperid wi&thorn; wijn.  &para; And if hise guttis falle adoun into his|ballok le&thorn;ir,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ballok le&thorn;ir</I>, testiculorum bursa.&mdash;<I>Cath. Angl</I>., p. 211.  Ledyr; birsa.|Sl. 2463, f. 123 <I>b.: &thorn;e purs of &thorn;e ballokes.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof schal be seid in &thorn;e nexte chapitre //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<HEAD>Of hernia<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hernio</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e ballokis //</HEAD>
<P>This siknes mai be seid in manie maners / In oon maner whanne|a mannes bowels falli&thorn; into his ballokis le&thorn;eris, &amp; &thorn;an it is|clepid hernia intestinalis / Or &thorn;er falli&thorn; watir into &thorn;e same place as
<PB N="270">|it were a dropesie, &amp; &thorn;an it is clepid hernia aquosa / Oui&thorn;ir &thorn;er|come&thorn; wijnd into &thorn;e same place, &amp; &thorn;an it is clepid hernia ventosa.|And sumtyme &thorn;er wexi&thorn; fleisch aboute &amp; is greet, &amp; &thorn;an it is clepid|hernia carnosa / And sumtyme &thorn;er ben veynes &thorn;ereaboute ful of|malancolious blood &amp; wele be gret as it were notis, &amp; &thorn;an it is|clepid hernia varicosa / The firste cause come&thorn; in &thorn;is maner: Dindimus,| &thorn;at anathomia &thorn;erof is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="186b">forseid, wexi&thorn; wide for sum moistnes|&thorn;at falli&thorn; &thorn;erto, so &thorn;at &yogh;irbus, ou&thorn;er &thorn;e bowels falli&thorn; adoun in &thorn;e|same place; and &thorn;is maner is ofte seen.  Ou&thorn;er siphac is to-broke|in &thorn;e flank wi&thorn; oon of &thorn;e forseid causis in &thorn;e chapitre tofore / &amp;|&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e same breking &thorn;e bowels falli&thorn; adoun ou&thorn;ir &yogh;irbus, &amp; bitwixe|dindimus &amp; mirac &thorn;ei fallen adoun into &thorn;e ballok le&thorn;eris.  &amp; &thorn;is|maner falli&thorn; ful selden.  &THORN;is laste maner is incurable wi&thorn; ony|medicyns, but wi&thorn; kuttynge it mai be curid &amp; sewid.  &amp; who &thorn;at|vsi&thorn; sich maner boondis aforseid, but if it be in children &amp; in newe|causis, it is al traueile in idil, &amp; &thorn;e patient ha&thorn; greet penaunce &thorn;erwi&thorn;|wi&thorn;outen ony profit.  &para; The firste may be curid / &amp; &thorn;e .ij. maner|is ful hard for to cure, &amp; &thorn;erfore it is ful necessarie for a cirurgian|for to knowe alle &thorn;e maners herof &amp; anathamiam as it is forseid|lest he falle in errour.  &para; &THORN;er ben manie men &thorn;at ben hardi for to|entermete of &thorn;ese curis &thorn;at knowen not &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e sijknes ne|&thorn;e diffence &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei falli&thorn; aldai in errour.  &amp; &thorn;e lasse| good &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="187a">&thorn;at &thorn;ei kunne, &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere &thorn;ei wole entermete of sich an|hard cause.  &amp; &thorn;is cause is ful perilous / I haue seen manie wise|men &thorn;at coude do &thorn;is cure ful wel, &amp; &yogh;itt &thorn;ei wolde not entermete|&thorn;erof / &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou muste take consideracioun sotilli, where &thorn;e|bowels falli&thorn; adoun &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e brekynge of siphac ou&thorn;ir &thorn;oru&yogh; dindimum,|&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt knowe in &thorn;is maner: &para; In &thorn;e firste caas &thorn;e|bowels or &yogh;irbus falli&thorn; doun sodeinli wi&thorn; agreuaunce, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t fele his bowels or &yogh;irbum in &thorn;e botme of &thorn;e ballok le&thorn;ir, &amp; &thorn;an|&thorn;er is but oon skyn to-broke, &amp; &thorn;at is mirac.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wolt|putte yn &thorn;e bowels a&yogh;en, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t fele in what place &thorn;ei goon in.|&amp; whanne hise bowels ben ynne, &thorn;an lete &thorn;e patient stonde vp, &amp;|hise bowels wolen falle out sodeinli a&yogh;en, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t fele in|what place &thorn;ei come&thorn; out / In &thorn;e .ij. caas &yogh;irbus or &thorn;e bowels, or|bo&thorn;e comen adoun alitil &amp; alitil, &amp; maki&thorn; miche gurgulacioun, &amp; &thorn;e|wei &thorn;at &thorn;ei come&thorn; out is algate sumwhat greet in dindimo, &amp; &thorn;at| wole not be put yn whanne &thorn;e bowels ben putt yn, saue <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="187b">wi&thorn; greet|penaunce &amp; in longe tyme.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e bowels falli&thorn; &thorn;oru&yogh; dindimum,|he maki&thorn; &thorn;e ballok le&thorn;ir neuere &thorn;e lengere, &amp; &thorn;is is a good
<PB N="271">|knowinge: whanne &thorn;ou hast take kepe of alle &thorn;ese priuitees, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou mi&yogh;t wite wherof &thorn;e cause is.  &para; Whanne &thorn;e bowels falli&thorn;|adoun &thorn;oru&yogh; a fissure, id est &thorn;oru&yogh; a brekynge, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt not|traueile forto worche wi&thorn; plastris &amp; wi&thorn; boondis &thorn;at ben forseid,|but if it be in children &amp; in causis &thorn;at ben newe.  &amp; if &thorn;e brekynge|be but litil, &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t make .v. cauterijs vpon &thorn;e skyn|wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, so &thorn;at &thorn;e cauterie perse mirac, for &thorn;at wole make an|hard drowing vpon &thorn;e brekinge / &amp; it wole not suffre &thorn;at &thorn;e bowels|schulen not falle adoun &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at place, so &thorn;at &thorn;e brekinge be but|litil.  If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e bowels falle adoun &thorn;oru&yogh; dindimum, &thorn;an|men haue&thorn; diuers curis.  Summen leien a corosif vpon &thorn;e ers wi&thorn;|dindimum, a medicyn corosif, til &thorn;e skyn wi&thorn;out be frete, til &thorn;ou|mai se dindimum, &amp; &thorn;an aftirward he freti&thorn; dindimum; &amp; summen|drawi&thorn; awei a mannes ballokis, and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="188a">summen drawi&thorn; not awei, but|bi &thorn;e wei of &thorn;e corosif &thorn;e ballokis wolen rotie afterward / &para; Also |summen maken punctual cauterijs in &thorn;e maner of a cros vpon dindimum,|&amp; &thorn;an aftirward heli&thorn; it vp / Summen kutten &thorn;e hi&yogh;er skyn|wi&thorn; a cauterie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn; a cauterie</I>, error for <I>wi&thorn;out cauterie.</I>  Lat.: Alii sine cauterio|superficialem cutem incidunt.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ei streyne&thorn; dindimum, &amp; &thorn;ei bindi&thorn; it wi&thorn;|spago<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn; spago</I>, cum spago; med. Lat. spacus, thread.  See Diez. s. v. spago.</NOTE> / Sum worchith in ano&thorn;ir maner: first, &thorn;ei kutti&thorn; &thorn;e skyn|aboue, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei maki&thorn; cauterium aboue vpon dindimum in summe|partie, &amp; in sum parti &thorn;ei leeue&thorn; hool.  &amp; &thorn;is maner is lasse worse|&thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;at ben forseid / Summen ficchi&thorn; .ij. nedlis in dindimum|wi&thorn; double &thorn;reed &amp; crossi&thorn; &thorn;e nedlis togidere, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei taki&thorn;|&thorn;e &thorn;redis &amp; lei&thorn; &thorn;ervpon martencium,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>martencium</I>, Lat. martentinum.  Name of a cautery?</NOTE> til al &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at was take|wi&thorn; &thorn;e nedelis be rerid an hi&yogh;.  &amp; o&thorn;er men han diuers werkis &thorn;at I|hadde not certeyn, for alle maners &thorn;at I heere &thorn;erof ben disseyuable|/ For sumtyme whanne a man ha&thorn; miche traueilid &thorn;oru&yogh;, &thorn;ing|&thorn;at he ha&thorn; do breki&thorn; a&yogh;en, &amp; &thorn;an it wole be worse &thorn;an it was ra&thorn;er.|&amp; among alle &thorn;e maners &thorn;at ben, &thorn;at is worst &thorn;at is doon wi&thorn;|medicyn caustica, for medicyns caustica for &thorn;e grete venym &amp; malice|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="188b">&thorn;at it ha&thorn;, maki&thorn; greet akynge, &amp; is cause to make an enpostym in |dindimo, and &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e agreuaunce &thorn;at dindimo ha&thorn;, siphac mai be|agreued &amp; diafragma.  &amp; fro diafragma it mai go<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>go</I>, above line.</NOTE> to &thorn;e brayn, &thorn;at|is &thorn;e welle of alle nerues, &amp; so &thorn;e man mai falle in a spasme, &amp; &thorn;an|he is but deed.  &para; O &thorn;ou wrecchid leche, &thorn;at for a litil money
<PB N="272">|puttist a mannes lijf in perel of dee&thorn; / for &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn;, it is better|&thorn;an ony gold or siluer, for &thorn;ou for a litil money makist him in perel|of dee&thorn; / For a man mai lyue vn-to &thorn;e tyme of his ende for &thorn;is|passioun.  &amp; &thorn;erfore I wole counseile to kutte no man / Saue bi my|counseil &thorn;ei schulen make a ligature as it is aforseid in &thorn;e brede of|.iiij. fyngris of lynnen cloo&thorn; or of sendel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sendel</I>, Lat. sindon, <GAP DESC="Greek">, a fine Indian cloth, muslin; <I>sendel</I>, O.Fr.|<I>cendal</I> is derived from <I>sindon</I>.  See Diez, s. v. zendale.  See <I>sendalle, sendylle</I>,|in <I>Cath. Angl</I>., p. 329, and note <I>ibid</I>.</NOTE> as I haue tau&yogh;t hertofore.|&amp; make &thorn;at enplastre &thorn;at is forseid, &amp; teche him good regimen &amp;|good dietynge / &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; he be not curid wi&thorn; &thorn;is medicyn he schal|lyue neuere adai &thorn;e lenger, ne &thorn;e lasse while &thorn;erfore / &para; I say .ij.|men &thorn;at hadden &thorn;e passioun, &amp; &thorn;at oon was .lx. winter oold, &amp; his|bowels fel out as it is for seid, &amp; it was ful hard<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hard</I>, in margin.</NOTE> to bringe hem in| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="189a">a&yogh;en, &amp; I made him sich a boond as it is aforseid &amp; a plastre, &amp;|tau&yogh;te in what maner he schulde diete him-silf.  &amp; I seide to him if|he louede his owne lijf he schulde go to no man to kutte him.  &amp;|he was glad of my counseil, &amp; he bar &thorn;e forseid bond &amp; &thorn;e enplastre|.ij. &yogh;eer contynueli, dai &amp; ny&yogh;t, &amp; wi&thorn;inne &thorn;at tyme he was hool, &amp;|&yogh;itt I wiste not wher he schulde be hool or no / &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ir man|was .xl. wintre oold, &amp; &thorn;er fel so greet plente out at his bowels,|&thorn;at &thorn;ei mi&yogh;te not be putt in a&yogh;en, til &thorn;e pacient were sett in a ba&thorn;.|&amp; &thorn;o I putte hem in a&yogh;en / &amp; I toolde of &thorn;e perel of kuttynge, &amp;|he bad me make sich a boond, &amp; I made him oon &amp; &thorn;e enplastre &thorn;at|is forseid.  &amp; I tau&yogh;te him how he schulde kepe him-silf, and how|he schulde diete him-silf.  &amp; wi&thorn;inne a litil tyme he come to me, &amp;|seide &thorn;at he was almost hool, &amp; &thorn;at he wolde were his boond no|lenger.  &amp; &thorn;o I repreuede him, &amp; seide &thorn;at he schulde not be hool,|but if he weride it lenger / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt teche him for|to kepe him-silf: he schal algate were his boond &amp; his plastre, saue| if he haue greet penaunce <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="189b">&thorn;erwi&thorn; whanne he goi&thorn; to his bed aneuen|he mai vndo it / And he schal in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>, above line.</NOTE> no maner ete no growel ne|raw fruit, ne no mete &thorn;at maki&thorn; inflacioun / And he schal drinke|no newe wijn, &amp; he schal ete no greet saule,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: ne comedant ad plenam saturitatem.  <I>saule</I>, O.Fr. saoul&eacute;e, from|saoul, Lat. satullus.</NOTE> and whanne he ha&thorn;|ete &thorn;an he schal reste him-silf.  &amp; he schal not arise, but if his|ligature be faste bounden, &amp; he schal not lepe, &amp; he schal not crie|ne renne, &amp; he lepe vpon an hors softli.  &amp; whanne he sitti&thorn; at
<PB N="273">|priuy he schal not streyne him-silf to harde, &amp; he schal ete no|mete &thorn;at wole make him costif.  &amp; if he wole ony &thorn;ing traueile, he|schal do it &thorn;e while he is fastynge.  &amp; if he wole holde alle &thorn;es|preceptis he mai be hool / &amp; &thorn;is medicyne is certeyn, for he schal|herfore lyue neuere &thorn;e lasse while.</P>
<P>&para; If hernia be watri, &thorn;is is &thorn;e signe &thorn;erof, &thorn;at his ballok wole|be heuy &amp; schynynge, &amp; if &thorn;ou pressist it wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngir &thorn;ou schalt|fele watrynes &thorn;eron / ffirst &thorn;ou must loke wher it be litil or myche<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words are wanting.  Lat.: <I>qu&aelig; si sit parua,</I> sufficit tibi medicamen|consumens.</NOTE>|&mdash; &mdash; &amp; &thorn;an medicyns &thorn;at ben consumynge &amp; driynge suffisi&thorn; /|&THORN;erfore &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt fynde here aftir in &thorn;e chapitre of &thorn;e dro&thorn;esie.|&para; If the <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="190a">mater be greet, &thorn;an avoide awei &thorn;e mater wi&thorn; kuttynge &amp;|wi&thorn; cauterijs.  But if &thorn;ou make cauterijs, &thorn;e watir wole come a&yogh;en |&thorn;erto, &amp; &thorn;e cauterijs wolen lette &thorn;at &thorn;er schal no more mater come|&thorn;erto.  &para; If &thorn;e mater be of wynd: &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;t knowe bi inflacioun|&thorn;at is not ledi colour<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Ventosa cognoscitur per tumorem non lucentem.</NOTE> &amp; bi felynge wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngris, if &thorn;ou felist|no watrines &thorn;eron, ne heuynes; &thorn;e cure herof is with electuari maad|of greynes of lauri &amp; o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis &thorn;at schulen be said in &thorn;e chapitre|of &thorn;e dropesi in tympanido.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: in hydropisi tympanite.  See p. 282.</NOTE>  &para; If it be superfluite of fleisch, &thorn;at &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;te wite wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngris, it wole be hard,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Signum hernie carnose est ... quod sentis, cum tangis, testiculos|dura carne circumvolutos.</NOTE> &thorn;e cure herof mai not be|do, but if &thorn;ou kutte &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at is wi&thorn;oute &amp; drawe out &thorn;e mater,|&amp; &thorn;an soude it, &amp; if it be in &thorn;e oon part hard &amp; callous, &amp; in &thorn;at|o&thorn;er part neische, &thorn;an it is better &thorn;at &thorn;ou sette noon hand &thorn;eron,|&amp; principali if it be blac &amp; ledi.  &para; Varicosa schal be curid wi&thorn;|gotis whey, &amp; with epithimo, &amp; wi&thorn; purgaciouns of malancolious|blood, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;erto &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben wastynge /</P>
