<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>&para; Of a stoon in &thorn;e bladdre &amp; reynis / <NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Celsus Medicina</I>, lib. VII., cap. 26.  The later authors followed|more or less closely.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Astoon in a man is engendrid of plente of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="190b">grete humouris|wi&thorn;inne a man, as we moun se an ensample wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; of |o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis, in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at men brennen tilis in a furneis.  &THORN;ei|maken first &thorn;e tilis of strong cley &thorn;at is viscous, &amp; whanne &thorn;ei|han schape it as &thorn;ei wolen, &thorn;an &thorn;ei leie it in &thorn;e sunne to drie / &amp;|&thorn;an &thorn;ei doon hem in a furneis wi&thorn; fier.  &amp; &thorn;e stronger fier &thorn;at &thorn;e
<PB N="274">|tilis han, &thorn;e stronger &thorn;ei wolen be, &amp; ri&yogh;t so in a mannes bodi,|whanne a man ha&thorn; miche viscous matere in his bodi &amp; mai not be|putt out for febilnes of expulcioun, &amp; &thorn;an scharp hete specialy in|&thorn;e reines falli&thorn; to &thorn;at mater &amp; makith it hard, &amp; in &thorn;is maner|engendri&thorn; &thorn;e stoon in &thorn;e reynes.  &para; Also in children a stoon engendri&thorn;|in her bladdre; for &thorn;e reynes of a child ben not so hote as a|mannes / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe wher &thorn;e stoon be in a|mannes bladdre or in his reynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Barth. <I>De propr. Trevisa</I>, lib. VII., cap. 54, indicates another symptom.|Add. MS. 27, 944. fol. 96.  "<I>And if &thorn;e ston is in &thorn;e reynes hit is i-knowe|by slepinge of &thorn;e fote and in &thorn;e ioyntes of &thorn;e lift side, and if it is in &thorn;e|bladder &thorn;e ache is in &thorn;e schare and &thorn;e twist bitwene &thorn;e genetras and &thorn;e|hole at &thorn;e rigge bones ende.</I>"</NOTE> / If &thorn;e grauel of his vrine be|whit: &thorn;an &thorn;e stoon is in &thorn;e bladdre / And if &thorn;e grauel be reed, &thorn;an|it is in his reynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator omits the passage about the causes of stone in general,|about the stone in the reins and its treatment.  The following sentence, <I>&thorn;at|I haue aforseid</I>, refers to this omitted part.  The author says that he will|speak about the causes and treatment of the stone in the reins, although it|does not properly belong to surgery.  Lat.: Ego vero, licet liber iste meus|de cirurgia dicatur, et ad instrumentum cyrurgicum de lapide renum tractare|non pertineat, tamen quoniam multum assimilatur in causis et curis, quamvis|dissimiletur in signis et curis.  Et quum ad curas lapidum renum multotiens|sum vocatus, propter gratiam scholarium modum quo usus sum in utriusque|lapidis curatione, causas, signa, et differentias ponere non postponam.</NOTE> / &para; Summen &thorn;at ben hardi wolen asaie for to|cure a man wi&thorn; kuttynge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e stoon in his reynes; for &thorn;ei| knowi&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="191a">not &thorn;e perel of woundis &thorn;at falli&thorn; in &thorn;e reynes &thorn;at I haue|aforseid, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei doi&thorn; no more saue bringe &thorn;e pacient to his|dee&thorn;.  &para; Now I wole teche in what maner a man schal kepe him|&thorn;at is disposid to haue &thorn;e stoon, he schal ete no metis &thorn;at ben|viscous ne to scharpe, &amp; tofore alle &thorn;ingis hard chese gaderi&thorn; viscous|mater &amp; hard.  &amp; he schal ete no beef, ne no fleisch of a goos, ne|no grete briddis &thorn;at swymme&thorn; in &thorn;e water, &amp; he schal ete no fleisch|of an hert, &amp; he schal ete no swete breed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: a pane azymo. <GAP DESC="Greek">, unleavened.</NOTE> &amp; al maner mete &thorn;at is|maad of swete past, &amp; he schal ete no whete soden, &amp; he schal ete|no maner &thorn;ing &thorn;at is maad of milk saue &thorn;e whey, &amp; he schal|drinke no coold watir, &amp; he schal ete no fruitis &thorn;at ben of greet|substaunce, as applis, peris, &amp; he schal drinke no newe wijn, ne no|wijn of greet substaunce, &amp; he schal ete no &thorn;ingis &thorn;at is to myche|salt, &amp; he schal absteyne him fro alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at engendri&thorn; scharpe|humouris &amp; grete, &amp; he schal not ete to greet sauly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare p. 272, note 6.</NOTE> / In &thorn;is maner|he schal diete him-silf, he schal ete breed &thorn;at is wel leueyned / &amp;
<PB N="275">|his breed wole be &thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="191b"> bettir for him if it be medlid wi&thorn; poudre |maad of fenel-seed &amp; persil, &amp; he schal drinke sutil wijn &amp; cleer,|medlid wi&thorn; fair cleer water / And if his reynes &amp; his bowels weren|hote, &thorn;an he mai drinke coold water &thorn;at be fair &amp; clene, &amp; he mai|ete fleisch of capouns &amp; hennes &amp; chikenes, &amp; partrichis, &amp; of|alle o&thorn;ere maner of briddis &thorn;at mouen in feeldis, &amp; of hem &thorn;at|wone&thorn; in watir he schal not ete.  &amp; he mai ete pork &amp; motoun &amp;|principali of beestis &thorn;at ben gildid, &amp; he mai ete fleisch of .iij.|daies poudringe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fleisch of iii daies poudringe.</I>  Lat.: porcos trium dierum salitos.|Compare <I>Liber Cure Coc</I>., p. 6.  <I>To powder befe within a ny&yogh;t.</I></NOTE> &amp; he mai ete feel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>feel</I>, vitulus.  O.Fr. veel.</NOTE> &amp; he mai ete eiren &thorn;at ben|neische soden; fisch &thorn;at ha&thorn; no schellis &amp; &thorn;e substaunce of him be|greet &amp; hard, he schal not ete &thorn;erof / Alle maner fisch &thorn;at ha&thorn;|manie schellis, is better &thorn;an he &thorn;at ha&thorn; no schellis / And of erbis:|he schal ete fenel, ache, persil, sperge, attriplicem,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Attriplex</I>, Chenopodium vulvaria.  <I>Alphita</I>, p. 16.  "Attriplex agrestis,|crissolocanna idem ang. mielde."  O.E. <I>melde</I>, Leechd. III. Gloss.  Compare|Germ. <I>Molten, Milten</I>. Dessen.</NOTE> spinochia &amp;|boraginem, erucam, melones, cucumeris, &amp; he schal be war &thorn;at he|ete no substaunce of caul, &amp; he schal ete no mustard / And he mai|ete &thorn;ese maner fruits: almaundis, auellanes, figis, notis, vuas bene|maturas.  &amp; he schal not<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>not</I>, above line.</NOTE> traueile to miche <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="192a">aftir mete, &amp; he schal |bere noon heuy bir&thorn;uns, ne he schal not be girt to