<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="11">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="204a">Of ficus, &amp; cancre, &amp; vlcer in mannes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>manner</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;erde / </HEAD>
<P>Ficus is a maner wexynge &thorn;at arisi&thorn; vpon a mannes &yogh;erde tofore.|&amp; sumtyme it wole be neische, whanne it is engendrid of|fleume / &amp; whanne it is engendrid of malancolie, it wole be hard;
<PB N="288">|[&amp; if it rotie, it wole turne into a cancre.  &para; A cancre come&thorn; in a|mannes &yogh;erde, ri&yogh;t as in o&thorn;ere lymes of a man,] &amp; vlcera come&thorn; of|hote pustulis &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;eron, &amp; aftirward &thorn;ei breke&thorn; it.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: que postea crepantur.</NOTE> Ou&thorn;er|&thorn;ei come&thorn; of scharpe humouris, &thorn;at maki&thorn; vlcera in &thorn;e same place;|ou&thorn;ir it mai come of a womman &thorn;at a man, &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e same|passioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts <I>&thorn;at.</I></NOTE> hadde leie by hir tofore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Ulcera veniunt .... ex commixtione cum feda muliere, que cum|egro talem habente morbum de novo coierat.  <I>H&aelig;ser</I>, III, p. 230, gives a|list of references, showing the early knowledge of venereal diseases in the|medi&aelig;val ages.  The earliest quotation is from Richardus Anglicus, <I>Micrologus</I>|MS., xiith cent.: "Ulcerantur utraque, virga scilicet et testiculi, tempore|menstruorum, ex coitu ex salsis humoribus et acutis et incensis, quod satis|ex colore cutis et pustularum vel saniei, et ex pruritu et punctura et ardore|perpenditur."  Richardus gives the same preventative, which is mentioned|by Lanfranc:  "Ablutio cum aqua frigida et continua abstersio &mdash; &mdash; et|maxime si post ablutionem cum frigida aqua fiat roratio loci abluti cum|aceto."</NOTE> /</P>
<P>&THORN;is is &thorn;e cure of ficus &thorn;at comith of fleume: &thorn;ou schalt binde|him wi&thorn; a &thorn;reed, ou&thorn;er kutte him al awei; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt soude|it as it is aforseid in o&thorn;ere placis / If it come of malancolie, it|mai be curid or &thorn;at it rotie, wi&thorn; tempere mollificatiuis, as it is|forseid in &thorn;e cure of sclirosis in &thorn;e general chapitre of enpostyms:|&thorn;at whanne he is maad neische, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt take him awei wi&thorn;| alle his rootis / saue it is more sure take awei it wi&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="204b">an hoot iren,|&amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;ervpon butter, &amp; &yogh;itt &thorn;ou muste touche him wi&thorn; an|hoot iren a&yogh;en; &amp; &thorn;an leie buttir &thorn;ervpon.  &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt do|oftetyme litil &amp; litil til it be al wastid awei / If it be a cancre, it|wole not be curid but if it be kutt awei wi&thorn; alle his rotis. And|&thorn;er is no wei so sure to take him awei as fier / Alle &thorn;e rotis of him|musten be brent awei, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;ervpon a mundificatif of apium,|&amp; aftir &thorn;is &thorn;ou muste leie &thorn;erto drijnge &thorn;ingis / &amp; in &thorn;is place &thorn;ou|schalt not for&yogh;ete to leie a defensif vpon &thorn;e place &thorn;at is hool, for|&thorn;is defensif schal defende &thorn;e place &thorn;at is hool fro swellynge.|&para; Vlcera &thorn;at come&thorn; in a mannes &yogh;erde: as whanne &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at is|tofore in a mannes &yogh;erde bicomith greet, &amp; &thorn;is mai not be curid|but if &thorn;at greetnes be doon awei.  &amp; &thorn;is medicyn is good &thorn;erfore /|Take whit wijn, &amp; of verte grece .&yogh; .j, auripigment .&yogh; .ij; grinde|&thorn;es .ij. sotilli, &amp; leie hem in &thorn;e whit wijn, &amp; meue hem ofte, &amp; kepe|hem for &thorn;in vss.  &amp; &thorn;e more cold<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>cold</I>.  Lat.: quanto plus <I>antiquatur</I> tanto melius.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;is medicyn is, &thorn;e better it| wole be.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt wete a lynnen cloo&thorn; in &thorn;is medicyn, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="205a">&amp;|leie vpon &thorn;e &yogh;erde / For &thorn;is &thorn;ing wole soude woundis &amp; defende &thorn;at
<PB N="289">|&thorn;er mai wexe no cancre / If it so be &thorn;at a mannes &yogh;erde be skynned,|&amp; be noon o&thorn;er passioun &thorn;eron saue &thorn;at, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;ervpon|vnguentum album, ou&thorn;er leie &thorn;ervpon a lynnen cloo&thorn; wet in|watir of rosis.  Also poudre maad of cucurbita &amp; aloes is good|&thorn;erfore / If a man wole saue &thorn;is lyme algate fro corrupcioun,|whanne he ha&thorn; leien bi a womman, &amp; he haue ony suspecioun of|vnclennes, &thorn;an he schal waische his &yogh;erde wi&thorn; coold water medlid|with vinegre /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="12">
<HEAD>Of Emeroidis &amp; fistule in &thorn;e ers /</HEAD>
<P>Emoroides ben veines &thorn;at endi&thorn; in a mannes ers &amp; ben .v.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>De propr. rer</I>., Lib. VII., cap. 54.  Add. 27,944, fol. 95 b.: "<I>Emorydis|ben fyve veynes &thorn;at strecche&thorn; oute at &thorn;e ers, of &thorn;e whiche veynes come&thorn;|diuers passiouns and euelis, as boluynge &amp; swellinge, withholdinge and flux.</I>"</NOTE>|&THORN;ese veines sumtyme opene&thorn; &amp; sumtyme &thorn;ei ben enpostymed.|Whanne &thorn;e blood &thorn;at is in &thorn;e same veines falli&thorn; adoun &amp; mai not|out, &thorn;an it engendri&thorn; apostym.  &amp; if &thorn;e blood is gret &amp; fleumatik,|&thorn;an it wole engendre ficus, &amp; if &thorn;at blood be greet &amp; colerik, &thorn;an|it wole engendre moralem.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moralis</I>, a mulberry form of tumour.</NOTE>  And if &thorn;e blood be greet &amp; malancolius,|&thorn;an it wole engen[dre] condilomata / Sumtyme &thorn;er come&thorn;|&thorn;erto <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="205b">so manie diuers humouris, &amp; maki&thorn; diuers enpostyms in &thorn;e |same maner as it falli&thorn; in o&thorn;ere lymes, &amp; ofte tyme of &thorn;is enpostym|come&thorn; a festre, but if it be &thorn;e bettir holpe; &thorn;e blood &thorn;at come&thorn; to|a mannes ers bi veynes &thorn;at ben clepid emoroides is grettere blood|&thorn;an ony blood of his bodi / &amp; if it so be &thorn;at a man haue &thorn;e flux|of blood of &thorn;e emoroidis, &thorn;ou schalt not stoppe it, but it blede so|myche &thorn;at it make &thorn;e pacient feble, saue &thorn;ou schalt kepe him wi&thorn;|good regimen, &amp; he schal vse no metis ne drinkis &thorn;at engendrith|scharp blood &amp; greet // For bi &thorn;e flux of blood a mannes bodi mai|be kept from malancolious blood, &amp; it wole kepe a man fro lepre &amp;|fro mania, &amp; fro al sijknes &thorn;at come&thorn; of malancolie / Also if a|man is woned to haue hem &amp; &thorn;ei be stoppid, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste &yogh;eue|him medicyns for to bringe hem out / And if it so be &thorn;at a man|haue so greet flux of hem &thorn;at his lyuere be enfeblid &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &thorn;an|he my&yogh;te falle in a dropesi &thorn;er &thorn;oru&yogh;, for to miche flux of blood|mai be cause of a dropesie / &THORN;erfore if &thorn;ou <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="206a">seest &thorn;at &thorn;e flux be to |greet, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt constreine blood wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at ben constrictif,|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt fynde medicyns &thorn;erfore in &thorn;e ende of &thorn;is|chapitre / Wexingis &thorn;at ben clepid emeroidis, summe &thorn;ei falli&thorn;
<PB N="290">|wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e hole of a mannes ers, &amp; summe wi&thorn;inne / Also summe|wexi&thorn; in &thorn;e for side of &thorn;e ers, &amp; summe in &thorn;e hyndir side. Sumtyme|it wexi&thorn; in &thorn;e forside toward &thorn;e rote of &thorn;e ballokis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei|maki&thorn; greet akinge / for sumtyme &thorn;ei letten &thorn;at a man mai not|make vrine.  If it be ficus, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t knowe, for it wole be|wi&thorn;oute hete<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: sine colore.  The translator read "calore."</NOTE> &amp; neische, &amp; &thorn;e cure herof is but li&yogh;t.  &THORN;ou schalt|take a strong &thorn;reed &amp; knitte &thorn;ere aboute, &amp; euery dai &thorn;ou schalt|streine it more &amp; more, til he falle awei, &amp; &thorn;an wi&thorn; driyng medicyns|&thorn;ou schalt drie it vp.  &para; Moralis maki&thorn; greet akinge &amp; ha&thorn;|manie smalle swellingis as it were mora celsi, &amp; &thorn;e colour &thorn;erof wole|be reed &amp; sumdel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sumdel</I>, altered in a different coloured ink from sumdei.</NOTE> purpur, &amp; but &thorn;is haue help for to acese &thorn;e| akinge, it wole engendre an enpostym.  &THORN;e cure herof is to lete him|blood in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="206b">basilica &amp; sophena al in oon dai,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: cura est flebotomia basilice lateris eiusdem in uno die, in alio de|saphena eiusdem lateris.</NOTE>|&amp; in &thorn;e same side &thorn;at &thorn;e passioun drawi&thorn; mooste &thorn;erto.  If he is|wont to haue &thorn;e same passioun, &thorn;an make him haue &thorn;e same flux|of blood.  &amp; if he is not wont to haue it, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue|him no medicyns for to make him haue &thorn;at flux, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt|acese &thorn;e akynge wi&thorn; &thorn;is medicyn, &amp; is good for thenasmon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vigo, Traheron Interpret.:  "Tenesmos is whan a man hathe greate prouocation|to the seege, but can do nothynge.  It commeth of tissein, whych|signifieth to stretche."</NOTE> &amp; for|alle &thorn;e passiouns of &thorn;e ers / &rx;, thuris, mirre, licij, croci, ana partem|.j, opij partes duas, grinde hem &amp; medle hem with &yogh;elke of an eij|&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of psillij, &amp; ole of roses, &amp; make &thorn;erof an oynement|/ &amp; if &thorn;e akynge be wi&thorn;inne in his ers, &thorn;anne anointe a tent|&amp; putte into his ers, &amp; if it be wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &thorn;an leie vpon lynnen|cloo&thorn; &amp; leie it vpon &thorn;e place.  &para; Also a medicyn of Haly &thorn;e|abbot / &rx;, ceruse .&yogh;. v., litarge .&yogh;. iij., iusquiami albi .&yogh;. ij., masticis,|grynde hem &amp; tempere hem wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey &amp; oile of|violet &amp; make herof an oynement.  &amp; &thorn;is oynement is good|whanne &thorn;e akinge is wi&thorn; an enpostym, for &thorn;is wole resolue &amp; make| it maturatif, &amp; doi&thorn; awey &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="207a">akinge / &rx;, foliorum malue, florum|camomille, Melliloti<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15236, fol. 5:  "<I>Mellilotum.  Corona regia. idem. G. mellilote.|A. hunisoke vel redclaure.</I>"</NOTE> ana .@. j., fenigreci, seminis lini ana .&yogh;. iij.,|lenticularum excorticarum .&yogh;. x., se&thorn;e alle &thorn;es in water til &thorn;ei|resolue &amp; &thorn;e water consume awei, &amp; &thorn;an putte hem in a morter &amp;|grinde hem wel, &amp; &thorn;an do &thorn;erto .ij. &yogh;elkis of eiren &amp; oile of violet,
<PB N="291">|&amp; make herof an oynement.  &para; If it so be &thorn;at in &thorn;is place of &thorn;e|forseid &thorn;ingis come an enpostym &amp; gadere to quitture, &thorn;ou schalt|not abide til it breke him-silf, for &thorn;an it wole make a greet hole|ynward toward &thorn;e guttis.  &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt opene it hastili, or it|wexe to miche ynward / If &thorn;e place of &thorn;e emeroide make no greet|akynge ne noon enpostym, &amp; if &thorn;ou wolt drie hem &amp; waste hem,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t worche in .ij. maners, do &thorn;erto mel anacardi &amp;|vnguentum ruptorium,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vnguentum ruptorium</I>.  Vigo Interpret.: "Ruptorie: that, that hath|strengthe to breake."</NOTE> or touche hem wi&thorn; an hoot iren &thorn;at is|bettere / If he be a delicat man or a feble, drie hem with fumygaciouns|maad of pulpa coloquintida &amp; seed of mirtillorum, &amp; &thorn;e|leeues &amp; &thorn;e ryndis of capparis, mirra, nux cipressi, &amp; gallis, &amp; make|him a decoccoun of &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis in water <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="207b">&amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">At the bottom of the page, in later hand: <I>contra emeroides vell bubo|vell tenassmoun: &rx; mer <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> ij, olibani, ameos ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j, oppij <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, gosium|gres et</I> [?], <I>ffiat decoctio cum mell vell cum pestello ellido et nido, fformetur|suppositorum.</I></NOTE> lete him sitte &thorn;eron, |for alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis maketh &thorn;e emeroidis blak &amp; maki&thorn; hem falle|awey / I nolde neuere leie in &thorn;at place corosif medicyn /</P>
<P>If &thorn;er be greetnes of veynes ful of blood wi&thorn;out ony enpostym,|&amp; &thorn;e patient haue gret akynge &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; principaly if he was wont|to haue &thorn;e flux of emeroidis wi&thorn; blood, &amp; he hadde it not longe|tyme tofore, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue him medicyns to haue &thorn;e flux of|blood, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt do in &thorn;is maner anoon, wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of a|strong oynoun, or wi&thorn; ius of lekis, ou&thorn;er if &thorn;ou makist suppositorijs|of hem &amp; frotist &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;e place, &amp; &thorn;is wole opene &thorn;e veynys|of &thorn;e emeroidis / Also &thorn;e rotis of maluis wet in &thorn;e gall of a bole /|Also take hony .ij. partis, &amp; vert de grece oon part, &amp; medle hem|togidere, &amp; herwi&thorn; anointe a suppositorie maad of lynnen cloo&thorn; &amp;|putte it yn / If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e patient blede to miche &amp; he bicome&thorn;|feble &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &thorn;an helpe him with trociscus de carabe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Matth. Sylv.: "Caraba i.  Karabe.  Electrum."  Fr. carab&eacute; Arab.|Kahrab&agrave; Devic <I>Dict</I>.  Amber.</NOTE> &thorn;at ben gode|for to restreine flux of blood of emeroides.  &amp; it is good for to|restreyne menstrues.  &rx;, carabe, gummi nucis, balaustie, lacte, succi|barbe yrcine<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alphita</I>, p. 20:  "<I>Barba yrsina ... a</I><SUP>e</SUP><I> buckestonge.</I>"</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="208a">ana .&yogh;. v., thuris .&yogh;. ij., opij .&yogh;. iij., make herof |gobettis wi&thorn; muscillagine psillij, &amp; make euery dai a gobet &thorn;e|wei&yogh;te of .&yogh;. ij., &amp; &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eue oon &thorn;erof wi&thorn; sirupo stiptico,|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt make fumigaciouns of driynge &thorn;ingis: as gallis,|balaustie, psidiorum &amp; o&thorn;ere mo &thorn;at ben forseid / &rx;, nuces cipressi,
<PB N="292">|cupularum glandulum, corticas granatorum, kutte hem a litil &amp; se&thorn;e|hem in good wijn.  &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is wijn waische &thorn;e place an euen &amp;|a morowe / Also a fumigacioun maad of tapsi barbasti<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alphita</I>, p. 182: "Tapsus barbatus&mdash;g<SUP>e</SUP>. molayne, an. catesteyl, uel|feldwrt."</NOTE> is good|&thorn;erfore /</P>
<P>It falli&thorn; ofte tyme &thorn;at after &thorn;e flux of &thorn;e emeroidis, ou&thorn;er if|enpostym be to longe maturatif in &thorn;at same place vnopened, &thorn;an it|falli&thorn; ofte tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e grete bowel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>intestinum</I>, inserted in later hand.</NOTE> is peersid.  &amp; sumtyme it|maki&thorn; a greet hole<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>callid ffestula testium</I>, inserted in later hand.</NOTE> in &thorn;e same place, &amp; &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at hole come&thorn; out|wijnd &amp; sumtyme egestioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Egestion</I>, a casting forth, avoiding: In the Art of Physick, the discharging|of Meat digested through the Pylorus, or lower Mouth of the|Stomach, into the rest of the Entrails."  Phillips.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;is hole is cleped a festre of &thorn;e|ers.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffestula</I>, inserted in later hand.</NOTE>  Of &thorn;is cure manye men ben hardi &amp; knowen not &thorn;e perels|&thorn;erof, &amp; maki&thorn; &thorn;e same medicyns in &thorn;is place for a festre as &thorn;ei| doon in o&thorn;ere placis / But &thorn;ou schalt take good <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="208b">hede of &thorn;is maner|enfestre; &thorn;ou schalt asaie if &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre go to hi&yogh;e &thorn;at it|touche &thorn;e &thorn;lace of &thorn;e lacertis of &thorn;e ers, &thorn;an &thorn;e festre is incurable,|&amp; &thorn;an a man schal not holde his egestioun, &thorn;at it nyle go out|alwei / Also &thorn;ou muste loke wher &thorn;ere go out miche quitture ou&thorn;ir|litil of &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre, or whe&thorn;ir &thorn;e quitture &thorn;erof be whit or|reed / Also &thorn;ou muste take kepe wher he haue greet penaunce &thorn;erof|or no / And aftir alle &thorn;ese diuers &thorn;ingis, &thorn;ou muste diuerseli worche.|For as it is aforseid, first &thorn;ou muste acese &thorn;e akynge &amp; &thorn;e swellynge,|&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt asaie wher &thorn;e festre go to &thorn;e lacertis; &thorn;at &thorn;ou|schalt knowe in &thorn;is maner / Putte &thorn;i fyngir as fer as it wole go, into|his ers, &amp; &thorn;an putte a pliaunt tent in &thorn;e feestre.  &amp; loke in what|place &thorn;e tent mette wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngir, &amp; &thorn;an say &thorn;at &thorn;e patient streyne|his ers, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t wite whe&thorn;er &thorn;e festre go aboue &thorn;e braun or|no.  If &thorn;e festre go aboue &thorn;e braun, &thorn;an &thorn;e patient schal lete go| out wijnd &amp; egestioun at &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e festre.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="209a">&THORN;an &thorn;ou schalt in|no maner touche &thorn;e festre wi&thorn; no medicyn corosif ne wi&thorn; noon|hoot iren; but &thorn;ou schalt teche him for to vse a waisching wi&thorn;|water &amp; hony &amp; mirre, &amp; wi&thorn; sum mundificatif, and in &thorn;is maner|he schal kepe him &thorn;at &thorn;e malice of &thorn;e festre wexe nomore.  &para; O|mi bri&thorn;eren, manye lewid lechis haue I seen &thorn;at coude on ruptorie,|&amp; &thorn;ei supposide &thorn;erbi for to cure cancris &amp; festris, &amp; al maner crepaturis,
<PB N="293">|&amp; &thorn;ei supposi&thorn; bi &thorn;is maner ruptorie<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>rurptorie</I>.</NOTE> for to surmounte Galien|in worchinge / And men &thorn;at han &thorn;is opinioun, in &thorn;e mo errouris|&thorn;at &thorn;ei falli&thorn;, &thorn;e more wroo&thorn; &thorn;ei wolen be, &amp; &thorn;e more &thorn;ei wolli&thorn; vse|her ruptorijs / And &thorn;erfore &thorn;is mai be ensaumple to &thorn;ee: if a man|haue no drinke but eysel, and ha&thorn; indignacioun for to fecche ony|o&thorn;er but halt him &thorn;erto, &amp; &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;erof to men &thorn;at ben a&thorn;irst.  &amp;|if &thorn;e drinke agreue hem, &amp; &thorn;ei speke ony &thorn;ing &thorn;erof, he wole be|wroo&thorn; &thorn;erfore, &amp; he nyle noon o&thorn;er drinke fecche, but algate &yogh;eue&thorn;|hem of &thorn;e same til her spirituals bicome drie / And if &thorn;e same <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="209b">man |hadde wijn ynow&yogh; &amp; knew wel &thorn;e vertu &thorn;erof, he wolde &yogh;eue no|man eysel for to drinke nomore / &THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt vse medicyns|&thorn;at ben appreued, &amp; do awei al medicyns &thorn;at ben false, &amp; holde|&thorn;ee apaid of &thorn;e medicyns &thorn;at ben aforseid /<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator omits a short passage about "Fissure of the Anus."</NOTE></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="13">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e cancre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cancre</I>, a mistake.  Lat. De cancrenis.  Med. Lat. cancrenum, cancrena,|is derived from Lat. canceroma, cancroma, canchrema, and has very|early been confounded with Lat. gangr&aelig;na, <GAP DESC="Greek">. Vigo. Interpret.|"Cancrena.  Gangrena is when some parte of the body thorow great inflammation|dieth, but is not yet perfitly dead; when it is perfectlye dead,|and wythout felyng: it is called sphacelos in greke, whyche they have turned|to ascachillos, sideratio in latine.  Some saye, that Gangrena is whan a|membre is apte to putrefye.  Ascachillos, when it is putrified, but hath not|all partes of putrefaction.  Esthiomenas, when a membre hath al degrees of|putrefaction."</NOTE> and &thorn;e mormole /</HEAD>
<P>Cancrene ben rounde vlceris &thorn;at falli&thorn; in a mannes leggis, &amp;|malum mortuum also, &amp; &thorn;ei falli&thorn; bo&thorn;e in oon place, &thorn;erfore I|wole make difference &thorn;erof / &para; Cancrene ben round vlcera &amp; ben|foule &amp; come&thorn; of dedinge of &thorn;e skyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of dedinge of &thorn;e skyn</I>.  Lat.: de cutis mortificatione.</NOTE> for &thorn;e natural spiritis comen|not &thorn;erto, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;e place is corrupt / &amp; if &thorn;e corrupcioun go|anoon to &thorn;e boon, &thorn;an it schal not be clepid cancrenum, but it|schal be clepid aschachiles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aschachiles</I>, the Arab. corruption of <GAP DESC="Greek">.  Fr. sphacile.</NOTE>  &amp; if &thorn;e corrupcioun ocupie al &thorn;e|lyme, &thorn;an it schal be clepid herpes estiomenus, &thorn;at is as miche to|seie as etyng him-silf.  &para; &THORN;e signes of cancrenarum ben blac|vlcera, &amp; &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;erof wole be foule &amp; of ledi colour, &amp; &thorn;e lippis|&thorn;erof wolen be gret, &amp; &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;at is in &thorn;e middil <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="210a">of vlcera wole|be corrupt.  &amp; it be miche lijk to a cancre &thorn;at is vlceratus, but |&thorn;is is &thorn;e difference &thorn;erof &thorn;at a cancre come&thorn; of corrupcioun of
<PB N="294">|malancolie, &amp; &thorn;is come&thorn; of lesynge of &thorn;e spiritis of lijf / Also|&thorn;e lippis of &thorn;e cancre ben more reuersid and more grene, &amp; a|cancre freti&thorn; more / And &thorn;erfore &thorn;is passioun is clepid of summen|a deed cancre /</P>
<P>&THORN;e cure of &thorn;is passioun is in &thorn;is maner / first &thorn;ou schalt avoide|his bodi of malancolie, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; it be not his principal cause as it is|of a cancre / &yogh;itt &thorn;e mater &thorn;at falli&thorn; to &thorn;e place is greet / &THORN;erfore it|is good for to clense his blood of malancolie; for it is good &thorn;ing in|vlcera &thorn;at ben olde, &amp; principali whanne &thorn;ei ben in parties bine&thorn;efor&thorn;|/ &amp; whanne he is clensid, &thorn;an lete him blood in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at|is bitwixe &thorn;e leeste too of his foot &amp; &thorn;e too next &thorn;erto, in &thorn;e same|leg &thorn;at &thorn;e passioun is on.  &amp; vpon &thorn;e place &thorn;ou schalt caste pouder|of affodillorum, ou&thorn;er remeue awei al &thorn;e deed fleisch / If &thorn;ou wolt| worche more surely &amp; bettere, make him a cauterie, &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="210b">it be|myche &amp; long as &thorn;e place is &thorn;at [is] corrupt, &amp; wi&thorn; an hoot iren|make a cros vpon &thorn;e middil of &thorn;e passioun as depe as &thorn;e deed fleisch|is.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;eron a plastre maad of whete mele &amp;|iuys of ache, &amp; &thorn;an cure it vp as &thorn;ou doist o&thorn;ere vlcera, as it is|forseid / And in &thorn;is caas &thorn;ou schalt not for&yogh;ete in no maner for to|leie aboute &thorn;e place a defensif of bole &amp; terra sigillata; for &thorn;at|wole suffre no wickide mater to renne to &thorn;e place, &amp; it defendi&thorn; &thorn;e|hool place fro corrupcioun.  &para; Malum mortuum is a maner scabbe,|&amp; come&thorn; of grete humouris brent, &amp; falli&thorn; to &thorn;e place.  &amp; sum|part &thorn;erof leue&thorn; in a mannys flank, &amp; engendri&thorn; glandulas &amp;|swelli&thorn; / &THORN;e cure herof is to avoide his bodi of greet humouris, &thorn;at|ben brent; &amp; lete him blood in basilica, in &thorn;e same side; &amp; lete|him blood in &thorn;e foot, as it is forseid / &amp; &thorn;ou muste dissolue|glandulus, as it is forseid in &thorn;e chapitre of glandulus &amp; scrophulis;|&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste anointe &thorn;e place wi&thorn; drijnge medicyns.  &THORN;ou| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="211a">schalt anointe al &thorn;e place with psilatro,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sinon. Barth</I>., p. 35: "Psilotrum, depilatorium idem."</NOTE> til al &thorn;e heeris falle awei|wi&thorn;outen ony violence / Take &thorn;e grete titimalle &amp; &thorn;e smale, &amp; boile|hem in vinegre &amp; in oile, &amp; do &thorn;erto a litil sope, &amp; make &thorn;erof &thorn;e|maner of an oynement; &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is oynement &thorn;ou schalt anointe &thorn;e|place harde a&yogh;en &thorn;e fier / &rx;, olei aceti ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .ij., sapponis mollis|&amp; sapponis duri ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j.; medle hem togidere, &amp; do &thorn;erto iuys|mali terre ou&thorn;er brionie .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .ij.; boile hem alle togidere, &amp; anointe|&thorn;e place &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt fynde oynementis in &thorn;e antidotarie|&thorn;at ben gode in &thorn;is caas //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="14">
<PB N="295">
<HEAD>Of varices, &thorn;at ben veynes, and elephancia.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanfranc follows the description given by <I>Avicenna</I>, Lib. III, Fen. 22,|Tract. 1, Cap. 15, ed. Ven. 1527.  Avicenna's list of the occupations that are|predisposing to this illness reminds us of the fact that he was a courtier|himself.  <I>Ibid</I>.: "Et plurimum quidem accidunt cursoribus, &amp; viatoribus,|&amp; onera portantibus &amp; coram regibus astantibus."</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Uarices ben clepid veynes, &thorn;at ben grete, &amp; grene, &amp; purpur, &amp;|sitti&thorn; aboute a mannes leggis.  and &thorn;ei comen of greet|malancolious<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>humour</I>, deleted.</NOTE> blood, &thorn;at falli&thorn; adoun.  &amp; also it come&thorn; of grete|metis &amp; of greet traueile, or it may come of greet fleume; &amp; it|wole make a mannes feet &amp; his leggis al grete, &amp; sumtyme his feet|also<NOTE PLACE="foot">Incorrect translation.  Lat.: "Elephantia dicitur qu&aelig;dam carnis augmentatio,|in qua crus vltra mensuram debitam augmentatur cum pede toto,|et fit ex grosso fleumate vel ex grossa melancolia non corrupta."</NOTE> // &THORN;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="211b">cure of varicium is in &thorn;is maner: &thorn;ou schalt purge him |wi&thorn; gotis whey &amp; wi&thorn; epithimo, for &thorn;is purgacioun is propre in &thorn;is|caas, or purge him wi&thorn; pelottis of epithimi.  &amp; lete him blood in|&thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid basilica, of &thorn;e arme in &thorn;e same side, &amp; also|in his foot.  &amp; he schal absteyne him fro metis &thorn;at engendri&thorn;|malancolie / &THORN;is passioun &thorn;ow my&yogh;t cure in &thorn;ese maners<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Locus autem tribus curatur modis.</NOTE> / &THORN;is is &thorn;e|first maner: loke in his hamme, vnder his knee.  &THORN;ere &thorn;ou schalt|se a greet veine; &amp; alle &thorn;e grete veynes, &thorn;at ben bine&thorn;e in his leg,|come&thorn; out &thorn;erof.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou schalt take vp &thorn;e same veyne wi&thorn; a|nedele.  &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou peerse not &thorn;e veyne, &amp; knytte hir wi&thorn; a|&thorn;reed.  &amp; &thorn;e brede of &thorn;i fyngir aboue &thorn;at place, putte yn &thorn;i nedele|a&yogh;en, vndir &thorn;e veyne as &thorn;ou hast do heretofore, &amp; knitte in &thorn;e same|maner wi&thorn; a &thorn;reed; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt kutte &thorn;e skyn ouer &thorn;e veyne|endelongis; &amp; &thorn;an take vp &thorn;e veyne &amp; kutte hir bitwixe &thorn;e .ij.|bindingis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is aboue schal be brent|wi&thorn; an hoot iren, &amp; &thorn;e ne&thorn;ir side <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="212a">of &thorn;e veyne schalt be vnknit. |&amp; presse out &thorn;e blood bine&thorn;efor&thorn; of &thorn;e veyne, as myche as &thorn;ou|my&yogh;t.  &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e remenaunt &thorn;ou schalt drawe wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at|ben consumynge.  &amp; &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;ere &thorn;ou madist &thorn;i wounde, &thorn;ou|schalt touche wi&thorn; an hoot iren also; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie to &thorn;e|place mundificatiuis, &amp; &thorn;an soude as it is aforseid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This mode of operation is the same as has been described by <I>Paulus|&AElig;gineta</I>, Lib. VI, 82, ed. Fr. Adams 1844, 2nd vol., p. 406, and by <I>Avicenna|l. c</I>., Cap. 18.</NOTE>  &para; Also ano&thorn;er|maner cure: lete him blood oonli in &thorn;e same veyne, &amp; take out of|&thorn;e blood as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, &amp; purge him ofte, &amp; make him
<PB N="296">|enplastris aboute his leggis wi&thorn; drijnge &thorn;ingis, &amp; diete him as it is|aforseid.  &para; &THORN;e .iij. maner is &thorn;is: &thorn;ou schalt go to no perfit cure|&thorn;erof, but &thorn;ou schalt lete &thorn;at blood falle adoun, &amp; &thorn;an a fewe|tymes in &thorn;e &yogh;eer &thorn;ou schalt purge him; &amp; &thorn;ou schalt laske his greet|blood wi&thorn; blood-letyngis, &thorn;at ben forseid, &amp; leie enplastris vpon &thorn;e|place &thorn;at ben drijnge.  &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt do til al &thorn;e swellynge be|goon awey / &amp; &thorn;is laste medicyn is &thorn;e beste for hem &thorn;at haue had|&thorn;is passioun longe, &amp; for hem &thorn;at ben olde / For if &thorn;ou kutte a| veyne in hem, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="212b">&thorn;an &thorn;er wole engendre manie sijknessis aboue, &amp;|make &thorn;e pacient deed &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere / For I si&yogh; men &thorn;at her veynes weren|so kutt &thorn;at weren algate sijk aftirward, &amp; wi&thorn;inne a litil time aftir|&thorn;at &thorn;ei diede.  &para; Elephancia<NOTE PLACE="foot">The disease which Lanfranc describes is the Elephantiasis Arabum,|commonly known as Barbadoes leg, quite different from the Elephantiasis of|the Greeks, a general term for severe leprosy.</NOTE> is incurable whanne it is confermed;|but bifore &thorn;at it is confermed, it mai be curid for to purge &thorn;e|humouris &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e cause wi&thorn; blood-leting, &thorn;at ben aforseid.  &amp;|he schal absteine him fro grete metis, &thorn;at engendri&thorn; greet humouris;|&amp; &thorn;an he schal not go ne ride, but if his leg &amp; his foot be bounden|wi&thorn; a boond faste, &amp; speciali in &thorn;e ioynct / But first &thorn;ou schalt|anoynte his leggis wi&thorn; epithimo maad of acacia, mirra, aloe, ipoquistidos,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sinon. Barth</I>., p. 25: "Ipoquistidos est succus fungi qui nascitur ad|pedem ros&aelig; canin&aelig;." <GAP DESC="Greek">, a parasitic plant which grows on|the roots of the <GAP DESC="Greek">, Cytinus hypocistis. (= Holly Rose, <I>Gerard</I>, p.|1281.)</NOTE>|&amp; alym with vinegre.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e swellynge bigynne&thorn; to|goon awei, &thorn;an make him a stuwe, &amp; lete his leggis be &thorn;erinne|longe; &amp; be it maad of askis of vines &amp; caul-seed, sticados arabici,|lupinorum, mirre, stercus caprini, fenigreci.  Also anointe him, &amp;|binde him, as it is forseid.  &amp; in &thorn;is maner I haue curid men, &thorn;at|ne weren not confermed &thorn;eron //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="15">
<HEAD>Of wertis in handis and in feet /</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="213a">Porri<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Porrus</I>, a Leak, also a kind of Wart."  Phillips.</NOTE> ben engendrid of fleume &thorn;at is greet, &amp; ben white;|veruce<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Verruca</I>, (Lat.) a Wart, a little hard brawny Swelling, which breaks|out of the Skin, and breeds in any part of the Body."  <I>Ibid</I>.</NOTE> come&thorn; of malancolie, &amp; ben blake, &amp; han mo rotis /|Scissure<NOTE PLACE="foot">"<I>Scissure</I>, a Cut or Cleft, a Rent or Chap."  <I>Ibid</I>.</NOTE> come&thorn; of malancolie brent, &amp; maki&thorn; as it were kuttyngis;
<PB N="297">|&amp; if &thorn;ei come&thorn; of cooldnes, &thorn;an &thorn;ei schulen be clepid muge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Matth. Syluat</I>.: "Perniones vel rasul&aelig;, sunt excoriationes qu&aelig; fiunt|in nimio frigore in calcaneis, qu&aelig; <I>Mug&aelig;</I> vulgariter dicuntur," probably allied|to <I>mucus, mungere,</I> <GAP DESC="Greek">.</NOTE> &para; &THORN;e|cure of porrorum is for to clense his bodi wi&thorn; trocisco de turbit, &amp;|&thorn;an frote &thorn;e place wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at ben consumptif; &amp; frote hem|wi&thorn; poudre maad of a gotis toord, &amp; tempere wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of mirti|&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e ryndis of capparis / Veruce schulen be curid wi&thorn; a|purgacioun maad of epithimi &amp; gotis whey, &amp; wi&thorn; summe o&thorn;ere|medicyn &thorn;at is proprid for malancolie, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt vse stronge|oynementis / as vnguentum ruptorium, ou&thorn;er mel anacardi or sum|o&thorn;ir corrosif, ou&thorn;er in &thorn;is maner is better / garse it al aboutfor&thorn; &amp;|binde it wi&thorn; a strong &thorn;reed, &amp; streine wel &thorn;e &thorn;red &amp; drawe him|awei wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;reed, &amp; &thorn;anne touche &thorn;e rotis of him wi&thorn; a cauterie|punctual.  &para; Scissure.  It is nede in &thorn;is passioun for to purge his|bodi of humouris &thorn;at ben brent, &amp; make <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="213b">him a ba&thorn; of swete |water.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt waische his lymes wi&thorn; a decoccioun of|bismalue in watir, &amp; a litil oile &thorn;erwi&thorn;; &amp; lete him vse metis &thorn;at|maki&thorn; moist &amp; engendrid good blood, &amp; &thorn;an anoynte him wi&thorn; &thorn;is|oynement / &rx;, olium rosarum, cere citrine, adipis anatis colatus,|Isopi humide,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>isopus humida</I>.  Sloane 2463, fol. 159 bk.:  "<I>The fyfte, whiche is|nother propurly oynement nor enplastre, but atwixe two, &amp; is cleped ysopus|humida.  Take wolle that is bytwixe the thyes and the iowes of schepe, as|moche as &thorn;ou wilt, and put as moche water thervpon as may covere hit, and|lete hit stonde so aday and any&yogh;t, and &thorn;anne boile hit with a lente fyre,|and lete hit wexe cold, and coile hit; and thanne boile hit eftesones in a|tymed panne with a li&yogh;t fyre, and thanne lete hit wexe cold, and coile hit:|butt loke thou stere hit euermore with a spature of tre till &thorn;at it be thikke|as oynement.</I>"</NOTE> muscillagine seminis citoniorum, amilum, draganti,|ana, make herof an oynement / &para; Muge schulen be curid wi&thorn; oilis|&amp; oynementis / ffirst &thorn;ou schalt aswage &thorn;e akinge wi&thorn; oile, &amp; &thorn;an|leie &thorn;erto a mundificatif &thorn;at schal be seid in &thorn;e antidotarie, &amp; &thorn;an|soude it wi&thorn; mirre / If &thorn;ou seest it at &thorn;e first bigynnyng, &thorn;an|make an enplastre of armoniaco, for &thorn;at wole resolue &thorn;e enpostym.|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;at he vse [not]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>not</I>, wanting.  Lat.: iube ne calciamenta portet stricta.</NOTE> streit schoon, &amp; he schal|anoynte his feet, &amp; principali hise heelis wi&thorn; &thorn;is oynement / &rx;,|olium de lilie <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .vj., cere <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., resine <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> ij., armoniaci <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., farine|fenigreci <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .<ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., thuris, masticis, ana <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .ij., &amp; make herof an|oynement /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gulielm. de Saliceto, <I>Chirurgia</I>, Lib. I, Cap. 57.  Sloane 277, fol. 19:|"<I>For cold in wynter &thorn;e leche may haue two consideraciouns to &thorn;e heelynge|of swiche maner seknesses: oon of partie of defense &thorn;at it come not, &amp;|another of &thorn;e partie of remevynge of &thorn;e seknesse i-made.  By &thorn;e reson of|defence that it come not, leue &thorn;e patient wi&thorn; all his witt streit schoynge, &amp;|haue he dowble schoos &amp; large, &amp; anoynte he euery ny&yogh;t &thorn;e heele with an|oynement &thorn;us maad.</I>"</NOTE></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="16">
<PB N="298">
<HEAD>Of blood-letyng //</HEAD>
<P>Blood-letyng is a craft for to-laske a mannes blood &thorn;at is in his| veynes / <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="213*a">And &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt wel wite, &thorn;at it falli&thorn; for oure|craft, &thorn;ou&yogh; we for pride take it to barbouris &amp; to wommen; &amp;|blood-letynge falli&thorn; principali for cirurgians / O lord, whi is it so|greet difference bitwixe a cirurgian &amp; a phisician, but for philosophoris|bitoken &thorn;e craft into lewid mennes hondis / or as manie men|haue dedignacioun for to worche wi&thorn; her hondis / &amp; &yogh;itt mani men|wene&thorn; &thorn;at it is inpossible &thorn;at oon man to kunne bo&thorn;e &thorn;e craftis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: "aut quum operari ut dicunt quidam cum manibus dedignantur,|aut, quod magis credo, quum operationis modum quod apud scientiam est|necessarium non nouerunt; et h&aelig;c abusio tantum valuit propter antiquam|dissuetudinem, quod apud quosdam de vulgo credatur impossibile, quod unus|hoc possit scire magisterium utriusque."</NOTE> /|But &thorn;ou schalt knowe wel &thorn;is, &thorn;at he is no good phisician &thorn;at can|no &thorn;ing in cirurgie / And also &thorn;e contrarie &thorn;erof: a man mai be no|good cyrurgian, but if he knowe phisik.  &para; Blood-letynge is vsid|bi cause for to kepe a mannes bodi hool, &amp; to remeue awei sijknessis|fro a mannes bodi / But &thorn;us manye &thorn;ingis &thorn;ou muste take kepe in|blood-leting: tyme, &amp; hour, &amp; eir, &amp; disposicioun of &thorn;e sike man /|&amp; &thorn;ou muste take kepe &thorn;at &thorn;ou lete no man blood but if he mowe|endure itt // &para; First a man schal be lete blood for to kepe him-silf,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. pro sanitate conseruanda.</NOTE>| &amp; principali hem &thorn;at eti&thorn; good fleisch <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="213*b">&amp; drinki&thorn; good wijn, &amp; eti&thorn;|metis for to engendre myche blood, &amp; traueili&thorn; but litil, &amp; principali|&thorn;e while a man is &yogh;ong, &amp; also in eelde if he be myche vsid|&thorn;erto / Also &thorn;ou schalt lete hem blood &thorn;at ben wont to haue|akynge in her ioyntis, ou&thorn;er a feuere &thorn;at is clepid sinocha<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanfranc, <I>Chirurgia Parva</I>, Cap. X, Add. MS. 10,440, fol. 25<SUP>a</SUP> (xvth|cent.): "<I>blood &thorn;erfore, &yogh;if it ouer habounde&thorn; vpon al &thorn;e body, &amp; it is hett|with hete enflammynge or brennynge &thorn;e herte, &amp; is corrupt, &amp; ne&thorn;eles it is|not roten, &thorn;erof is maad a feuere clepid</I> synocha continua.  <I>And &yogh;if he|is roten, &thorn;enne is maad &thorn;erof a feuere clepid</I> synochus continuus.</NOTE> or &thorn;e|squinacie, ou&thorn;er pleureses / Alle &thorn;ese, tofore &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben|woned to haue her passioun, &thorn;ou schalt lete hem blood or her|passioun come, &thorn;at it mowe go awey &thorn;erwi&thorn;: &amp; &thorn;is maner is clepid|preuisiuus.  &para; &THORN;e iij. maner: whanne a man ha&thorn; greet akynge in
<PB N="299">|his heed wi&thorn;outen<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Latin editions of Lanfranc read: "Tertio cum dolor fortis adest|capitis siue febres fortes squinantes pleuresos," ed. Ven. 1498, fol. 201 bk.,|Ven. 1546, fol. 249, but Add. MS. 26,106 (xivth cent.), fol. 88, shows the|correct reading, which corresponds with the translation: "Tercio cum dolor|fortis adest capitis sine febre, cum fortes squinantes, pleureses."</NOTE> a feuere, or a squinantes plureses, periplumonia,|apostema calida, &amp; eueri sijknes &thorn;at come&thorn; of to miche blood.  In|alle &thorn;ese causis &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood; &amp; &thorn;is maner is clepid|curantes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. curatiuus.</NOTE>  &para; Now I wole telle alle maners in what maner a man|schal be leten blood / ffirst, who schal lete &thorn;ee blood / &THORN;e .ij, whanne|it is necessarie for to be lete blood / &THORN;e .iij., in whiche veynes a|man schal be leten blood for diuers passiouns, &amp; in what maner &thorn;e|veyne schal be kut. &para; A man &thorn;at schal be letere blood schal be &yogh;ong,|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="214a">&amp; he schal be no child, ne noon oold man, ne he schal not quake, |&amp; he schal haue a good scharp si&yogh;t; &amp; loke &thorn;at he kunne knowe|veines, &amp; &thorn;at he kunne knowe hem from arterijs; &amp; he schal haue|manie diuers tool<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tool</I>, a survival of the O.E. t&ocirc;l, N.A. plur.</NOTE> for to lete blood &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ei schulen be clene|and cleer, &amp; not rusti; &amp; summe of his tool schulen be longe, &amp;|summe schorte, for to peerse aftir &thorn;at &thorn;e veyne is greet &thorn;erto / Also|children schulen not be lete blood, but if it were greet nede, &amp; he|were so replet of blood &thorn;at he schulde be achekid &thorn;erwi&thorn;; &thorn;at &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t knowe bi &thorn;e streitnes of his bree&thorn; &amp; fulnes of his veynes, &amp;|bi reednes of his face.  &THORN;an it is necessarie &thorn;at he be leten blood;|but it is ful greet drede for to lete a child blood, &thorn;erfore I wyle|&yogh;eue no counseil &thorn;erto.  &amp; if it so be &thorn;at he be in perel of dee&thorn;,|&thorn;an lete him blood / Now &thorn;ou art war of &thorn;is perel, do as &thorn;ou seest|&thorn;at it is to do; &amp; &thorn;ou schalt warne &thorn;e childis fadir &amp; his modir of|&thorn;e perels &thorn;at ben aforseid, &amp; saue &thorn;ee fro blame.  &para; Also olde men|schulen not be lete blood, &amp; &yogh;itt summe olde men ben strenger of|vertu &thorn;an summe &yogh;onge <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="214b">men; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt take hede to &thorn;e |rule in &thorn;is maner: &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt not lete hem blood whanne &thorn;ei|arisi&thorn; out of her sijknes / &para; Also wommen wi&thorn; childe schulen not|be lete blood, &amp; speciali not in &thorn;e .iij. firste mone&thorn;is, ne in &thorn;e laste|mon&thorn;e / Also &yogh;onge men &thorn;at ben white &amp; pale, &amp; haue&thorn; fewe heeris|in her browis, &amp; haue&thorn; smale veynes &amp; priui, ne ben not couenable|to be lete blood; ne men &thorn;at han manie humours &amp; litil blood, for|blood &thorn;at is in hem is tresour.  &para; Ffrensch men doon hem-silf|miche harme in &thorn;is caas; whanne &thorn;ei ben ful of coold humours &amp;|corrupt &thorn;ei leti&thorn; hem-silf blood, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei seen her blood corrupt &amp;
<PB N="300">|foul, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei supposen &thorn;at &thorn;ei han wel doon &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue lete out|&thorn;at blood, &amp; &thorn;e barbour wole seie &thorn;at he mote hastili be lete blood|a&yogh;en / It were wel better to him &thorn;at he hadde kept his blood, &amp;|&thorn;at &thorn;e corrupt humours hadde be voidid awei in o&thorn;er maner /|&para; Blood-letynge is not good for a man at &thorn;e firste bigynnynge of|cataracta, ne noon ventuse is not good for him / but in causis as it| is forseid, blood-letyng is good // And <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="215a">if a man eti&thorn; miche fleisch|&amp; drinki&thorn; miche wijn, for &thorn;is wole engendre miche blood / And|&thorn;an but if a man lete him blood, &thorn;an &thorn;ere wole engendre diuers|sijknes &thorn;erof, &amp; ofte tyme sodeyn dee&thorn; / Also men &thorn;at haue &thorn;e|goute of blood, he schal be lete blood tofore &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he|supposi&thorn; to haue his passioun; for ofte tyme &thorn;is wole take awey|his akynge.  &amp; in alle sijknessis &thorn;at come&thorn; principali of blood, it|is good for hem to be lete blood / Also men &thorn;at haue&thorn; synocham,|blood-letynge is ful necessarie to hem, til &thorn;ei swowne.  &amp; &thorn;is wole|do awei &thorn;e feuere, or it waasti&thorn; so miche &thorn;e mater; &amp; &thorn;an he muste|be holpen wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere medicyns, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt fynde in bokis of|phisik<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp; &thorn;an he muste be holpen&mdash;bokis of phisik</I>, inserted.  Lat.: "aut|omnino phlebotomia febrem tollit, aut adeo materiam minuit, quod in|putridam de cetero non mutatur."</NOTE> / If he be not lete blood, &thorn;an &thorn;e blood &thorn;at is in him wole|boile vpward to &thorn;e brest, &amp; gadere togidere in the brest, &thorn;at &thorn;e|pacient schal be ful ny&yogh; stoppid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. quod patiens suffocatur.</NOTE>  &amp; sumtyme a veine wole breke|in &thorn;e piyse or in &thorn;e lungis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;at veine mai not be streyned ne|stoppid, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e patient schal die &thorn;eron.  &para; In &thorn;is chapitre it is| myn entencioun forto speke oonly of openynge of veines <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="215b">&thorn;at ben|in us,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. qu&aelig; sunt in usu.</NOTE> &amp; what vertu &thorn;er is &thorn;erinne.  In bo&thorn;e armis of a man &thorn;er|ben .iij. veines &thorn;at ben in us for to be lete blood &thorn;eron / &THORN;e .i. is|clepid cephalica, &amp; is &thorn;e hi&yogh;este veine of &thorn;e arme, &amp; sitt next &thorn;e|elbowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. prima cefalica que in duobus minuitur locis prope cubiti plicaturam|aliquantulum supra.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;is veine mote be kut large, &amp; not to depe / If &thorn;at|veine be kut streit, &thorn;an ofte tyme it maki&thorn; an enpostym / &amp; also|&thorn;ou muste be wel war &thorn;at &thorn;ou touche no synewis / For &thorn;e same|cause &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t lete a man blood vpon &thorn;e hond, bitwixe his &thorn;ombe|&amp; &thorn;e nexte fyngir &thorn;erto // Basilica sitti&thorn; adoun afor&yogh;ens &thorn;e elbowe,|vndir &thorn;e arme, &amp; &thorn;is veine sitti&thorn; ful ny&yogh; &thorn;e gret arterie: &amp; &thorn;erfore|a man mote be wel war &thorn;at he touche not &thorn;e arterie veyne.  &amp; for|&thorn;e perel of &thorn;e arterie it is good for to lete him blood bitwixe &thorn;e|litil fyngir &amp; &thorn;e fynger next &thorn;erto.  &amp; &thorn;is blood-letynge is good for
<PB N="301">|alle &thorn;e placis vndir &thorn;e brest, &amp; for &thorn;e lyuere.  &para; Of &thorn;is veine &thorn;at is|clepid Basilica, &amp; of &thorn;e veine &thorn;at is c[l]epid Cephalica, come&thorn; a|veine &thorn;at is clepid Mediana / And whanne a man is lete blood in|&thorn;is veyne, it is perel of ij. grete synewis &thorn;at liggi&thorn; in bo&thorn;e sidis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="216a">of|&thorn;e veyne.  And whanne &thorn;ou &thorn;inkist to avoide al a mannes bodi, |&thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in &thorn;is veine, &amp; principali for &thorn;e herte|&amp; for &thorn;e brest.  &para; In Basilica, in &thorn;e ri&yogh;t hond, &thorn;ou schalt lete a|man blood for passioun of &thorn;e lyuere, &amp; in &thorn;e lift hond for passioun|of &thorn;e splene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Regimen sanitatis Salerni</I>, transl. by T. Paynell (1530), fol. h. iiii.:|"<I>Saluatella</I> is &thorn;at veyne betwene &thorn;e myddell fynger and the rynge fynger,|more declynynge to the myddell fynger.  Hit begynneth of <I>Basilica</I>.  This|veyne is opened in the ryghte hande for opilation of &thorn;e lyuer, and in the|lefte hande for opilation of the splene.  There is no reason why it shuld be|so, as Auicen saythe, but experyence: whiche Galen founde by a dreame, as|he saythe.  He had one in cure, whose lyuer and splene were stopte, and he|dreamed that he dyd let him blud of this veine, and so he dyd, and cured|the pacient."</NOTE> &amp; in &thorn;e liftside of &thorn;e forheed<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts <I>for</I>.</NOTE> it is good to lete|blood for akynge of &thorn;e heed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. in capite flebotomatur vena frontis propter capitis egritudines.</NOTE> &amp; principali whanne sijknes is confermed|in a mannes heed.  &amp; &thorn;is I apreuede misilf / for sumtyme|it doi&thorn; awei &thorn;e frenesi.  &amp; I si&yogh; a womman &thorn;at hadde akynge in|hir heed, &thorn;at it mi&yogh;te not be take awei, &amp; I lete hir blood in hir|hond as it is forseid &amp; purgide hir, &amp; &thorn;e veine in hir forheed &thorn;at|was gretter &thorn;an ony o&thorn;er veine in hir bodi; &amp; I openede &thorn;at veine,|&amp; anoon ri&yogh;t sche was hool / But whanne &thorn;ou wolt lete a man|blood in &thorn;at place, &thorn;ou schalt streyne &thorn;e necke &amp; kutte &thorn;e veine|endelongis; &amp; &thorn;is blood-letynge is good for tynea, &thorn;at is in a|mannes heed, &amp; for Saphati.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sanaci</I>.  The editions of Lanfranc read <I>saphati</I>, Add. MS. 26,106,|fol. 89: <I>saffira.  Matth. Sylv.</I>: "Saphiros, Sephiros idest apostema durum|cui non associatur sensus."  <I>Vigo Interpr.</I>: "Sephiros is an arabike word,|and it is called in Greke scirros, in latyne durities, that is hardenes."</NOTE>  &amp; for demigrania &thorn;ou schalt lete|blood in &thorn;e templis of his heed.  &amp; &thorn;e same blood-letynge is good|for passion <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="216b">of a mannes i&yogh;en / I hadde a &yogh;ong man in my kepinge |&thorn;at hadde demigrayn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>demigrayn</I>, Lat. emigranea.  See Skeat, <I>Et. Dict</I>., s. v. megrim.</NOTE> of hoot cause, &amp; I purgide him ofte &amp; lete|him blood, and I knytte &thorn;e arterie &thorn;at was in &thorn;e same side of his|heed, &amp; &thorn;o he was cured for euermore / Also letynge blood in &thorn;e|veynes bihinde hise eeris is good for &thorn;e dimigrayn &amp; for tineam /|Also letynge blood in &thorn;e tunge is good for &thorn;e squinacie, &amp; for|enpostyms, &thorn;at ben as it were almaundis, &amp; for brancis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brancus</I>, med. Lat. Dufr., a throat-disease.  <I>Isid</I>., Lib. 4, Cap. 7:|"branchos est pr&aelig;focatio faucium a frigido humore."  The editions of Lanfr.|read: brachiis.</NOTE> but he
<PB N="302">|schal be lete blood tofore in &thorn;e heed-veyne.  &amp; it is good for &thorn;e|i&yogh;en, &amp; it is good for icchinge &amp; for pustulis in &thorn;e nose, &amp; for|scotomia &thorn;at come&thorn; of blood / Sumtyme a man is lete blood in|veynes in &thorn;e necke, &thorn;at ben clepid gwide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. vene guidegi.</NOTE> for drede of suffocacioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">Phillips: "<I>Suffocation</I>, a suffocating, stifling, etc., a Stoppage."</NOTE>|of blood; &amp; sumtyme in leprous men, &thorn;at schulen be lete blood in|her lippis bine&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This statement is due to a wrong interpunctuation in the Latin original.|Add. 26,106: "Aliquando flebotomantur uene guidegi colli cum suffocatio ex|sanguinis timetur multitudine.  &amp; aliquando in quibusdam leprosis uene|qu&aelig; sunt in labiis inferioribus interioribus minuantur propter acola calidum|in ore &mdash; &mdash;."  A full stop ought to be between leprosis and uene.  Compare|<I>Liber Rasis ad Almans</I>, Tract. VII, Cap. 21, ed. Ven. 1506, fol. 32 bk.:|"Sed due vene que dicuntur guidegi sunt flebotomande, cum anhelitus in|lepre principio maxime angustatur."  "Vene itidem, que in labiis sunt inciduntur|cum in aliquo multiplicantur alcola et ulcera in ore et gingivis."</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;is is good for hote enpostyms in &thorn;e mou&thorn;, &amp;|for hote passiouns of &thorn;e gommys.  &para; In a mannes foot ben .iij., &thorn;at|ben profitable to be lete blood for manie passiouns / And &thorn;er is oon|veyne in a mannes hamme vndir his knee, &thorn;at is good to be lete| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="217a">blood for passiouns of &thorn;e maris, &amp; for to bringe out menstrue: &amp;|it avoidi&thorn; al &thorn;e bodi.  &para; Also &thorn;er is ano&thorn;er veine, &thorn;at sitti&thorn; bitwixe|&thorn;e holowe of &thorn;e foot wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &amp; is clepid Sophena; &amp; in &thorn;is|veyne wommen ben leten blood for passiouns of &thorn;e maris, &amp; men|ben lete blood in &thorn;e veine of &thorn;e same place for enpostyms of &thorn;e|ballokis.  &para; &THORN;e veine &thorn;at serue&thorn; for &thorn;e scie, is wi&thorn;oute bitwixe &thorn;e|heele &amp; &thorn;e holowe of &thorn;e foot wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;, &amp; blood-letynge in &thorn;is|veine is good for scia[ti]cam passionem, as it is aforseid in &thorn;e cure|of sciatica.  &para; Herof &thorn;ou schalt take kepe.  If &thorn;ou &thorn;inkist for to|lete a man blood in .ij. diuers times, &amp; not al at oonys, &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt do in &thorn;is maner; &amp; in &thorn;is caas, whanne &thorn;ou wolt lete a man|miche blood, and ne darist not do it al at oonys; &thorn;an whanne &thorn;ou|letist him blood, &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;e inscicioun of &thorn;e veine &thorn;e more|long, &thorn;at it soude not hastili; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt binde his arme, &amp;|smite &thorn;e place &thorn;ere &thorn;ou wolt lete him blood wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngir, &amp; make| him blede more, as myche as &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at good is / <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="217b">&para; Also|whanne &thorn;ou wolt wi&thorn; blood-letyng make &thorn;e mater go to &thorn;e place|afor&yogh;ens; whanne &thorn;ou hast lete out &thorn;e .iij. part off blood &thorn;at he|schal blede, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt sette &thorn;i fingir vpon &thorn;e wounde, &amp; make|him stonde vp &amp; remeue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>remeue him-silf</I> has the sense of M.E. remuen, O.F. remuer, to move,|stir.</NOTE> him-silf, &amp; lete him sitte adoun, &amp; do|awei &thorn;i fyngir &amp; lete him blede more.  &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ou schalt do .iij.
<PB N="303">|si&thorn;is or .iiij., for in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e blood drawi&thorn; more to &thorn;e partie|afor&yogh;ens, &amp; &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e pacient schal &thorn;e better be kept.  &para; Also|if a man is wont to swowne in blood-letynge ou&thorn;er falle doun, &thorn;an|lete him lie &amp; be lete blood / Also or he be lete blood, lete him ete|a schiuer of breed toostid &amp; leid in wijn of granatorum.  &para; Alle|maner veynes in blood-letinge schulen be kutt endelongis / And|whanne &thorn;ou wolt lete a man blood in &thorn;e partijs aboue &thorn;e necke, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou muste binde &thorn;e veine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. opus collum stringi donec appereant.</NOTE> til &thorn;e veyne arise &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt lete him|blood on / And whanne &thorn;ou wolt lete a man blood in his arme, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou muste binde his arme &thorn;e brede of foure fyngris aboue &thorn;e place;|&amp; &thorn;ou muste <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="218a">be wel war &thorn;at &thorn;ou streyne not to faste, as manie |men doon / Manie men binden so faste a mannes arm, &thorn;at he main|not fele his arm / Veynes of a mannes feet &amp; in his hondis, if &thorn;ou|wolt lete a man blood &thorn;eron, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste sette hem in hoot|water, &amp; lete hem achaufe &thorn;eron an hour; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste binde|his foot ou&thorn;ir his hond aboue &thorn;e ioinct wi&thorn; a boond, &amp; algate his|foot or his hond mote be in &thorn;e watir as longe as he schal blede /</P>
