<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="17">
<HEAD>Of kuttyngis and bledyngis //</HEAD>
<P>Siccia is sett sumtyme for kuttynge &amp; sumtime wi&thorn;oute kuttynge,|and sumtyme wi&thorn; kuttinge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26106, fol. 89, bk.: "Siccia aliquando ponitur sine incisione aliquando|cum incisione."  The printed editions omit this passage.</NOTE> Wi&thorn;out kutting as vpon a mannes|wombe or wommans / ffor akynge &thorn;at come&thorn; of wijnd, &amp; it is good|for to waste wijnd / Also it is sett vpon &thorn;e wei of &thorn;e stoon &thorn;at|falli&thorn; adoun of &thorn;e reynes, &amp; &thorn;an it schal be sett a litil bine&thorn;e &thorn;e|akynge &thorn;at it mowe drawe &thorn;e stoon lower &amp; lower til it come to &thorn;e|hole of &thorn;e bladdre / Also it is sett vndir a wommans tetis for to|restreyne &thorn;e blood of &thorn;e nose &amp; of &thorn;e maris / Also it is sett vpon|&thorn;e region <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="218b">of &thorn;e wombe for fallinge of &thorn;e maris, &thorn;at is clepid dislocacioun |of &thorn;e maris: as if the maris falle adoun in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside, &thorn;an|it schal be sett in &thorn;e liftside / And if &thorn;e maris falle in &thorn;e liftside,|&thorn;an it schal be sett in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside / Also it is sett vndir a mannes|eere for to drawe out a greyne or a stoon of &thorn;e eere &thorn;at is falle yn /|Also it is sett vndir a mannes ers to drawe out &thorn;e emeroidis &thorn;at|sitti&thorn; hid fer yn / And it schal be sett in eueri place &thorn;ere &thorn;ou wolt|make a greet attraccioun / Also it is good for to be sett vpon &thorn;e|bitynge of a wood hound, &amp; vpon &thorn;e biting of a venymous beest.</P>
<P>
<PB N="304">It schal be sett &thorn;eron wi&thorn; scarificacioun, also in causis &thorn;ere &thorn;ou|lettist for to drawe blood for febilnes, or for elde, or in children; &amp;|hem after .iiij. &yogh;eer oold we moun garcie, whanne blood leting is forboden|hem, &amp; speciali whanne we purposen for to drawe awei mater|&thorn;at is vndir &thorn;e skyn / Also we moun garse a man bihinde in &thorn;e nol|of &thorn;e heed &mdash; &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words are wanting.  Lat.: propter grauedinem capitis.</NOTE> &amp; for greuaunce of &thorn;e i&yogh;en, &amp; vpon &thorn;e .ij. corneris| of &thorn;e heed for tinea &amp; for pustules &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e heed vnder <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="219a">a|mannes chyn, for wennys of &thorn;e face &amp; for vlcera &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e|mou&thorn; &amp; in &thorn;e lippis &amp; for akynge of &thorn;e tee&thorn; / Also if it be sett|bytwixe &thorn;e .ij. schuldris for swownynge &amp; for quakinge of &thorn;e herte,|&amp; for hem &thorn;at han to miche blood in &thorn;at place.  &THORN;is maner letynge|blood avoidid a mannes bodi miche &amp; maki&thorn; him feble<NOTE PLACE="foot">The sentence to which this statement refers is omitted.  Lat.: "Que|vero in poplitis plicatura valent ad egritudines renum, et matricis, testiculorum|et omnium membrorum nutritiuorum ex sanguine."</NOTE> /</P>
<P>Also watir lechis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rhasis, Continens, Lib. XV. Cap. 6, ed. Brix, 1486, fol. CC. 3, bk.,|gives an interesting description of different kinds of leeches: "Sanguisugarum|vna est venenosa, que est nigra vehementer ad modum antimonii,|habens caput magnum &amp; squamas ad modum piscium quorundam &amp; habens|medium viride, etiam alia, super quam sunt pili, habet magnum caput et|colorem diuersum ad modum iris, in cuius colore sunt linee ad modum lazuli:|que quotiens mordet, inde accidet apostema cum sincopi, febre, ebrietate, et|laxitudine articulorum; tamen bona ipsarum est, que assimilatur colori aque|in qua erit viriditas, habent super se duas lineas ad modum arsenici; sed|blonde rotonde &amp; ad colores epatis apte, que veloces sunt ad attrahendum|sanguinem subtilem &amp; que assimilantur caude muris, habentes odorem horribilem|&amp; similes locuste parvule et tenui &amp; habentes ventrem ruffum cum|nigrore &amp; dorsum viride, sunt meliores; sed peiores erunt in aqua mala valde|stabili, in qua sunt ranule multe, tamen bone sunt in aqua bona &amp; optima."|This account is copied by Avicenna, Lib. I., Fen. 4, Cap. 22, ed. Ven. 1527,|fol. 62, bk.  He differs in one point: "illas elige, que in aquis colliguntur,|in quibus morantur rane.  Neque attendas illud quod quidam dicunt, quod|si sunt in aquis vbi morantur raue, sunt male."</NOTE> drawi&thorn; more blood &thorn;an &thorn;ese / In &thorn;is maner|&thorn;ou schalt knowe whiche ben gode watir lechis &amp; whiche ben nou&yogh;t.|&THORN;ei &thorn;at han blac colour medlid wi&thorn; diuers colouris, &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at haue&thorn;|grete hedis &amp; ben in foule stynkynge watris &amp; han miche spume on|hem ben nou&yogh;t / And in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe whiche ben|gode: &thorn;ei &thorn;at han reed wombis &amp; litil reed rewis in &thorn;e rigge medlid|wi&thorn; grene, &amp; whanne &thorn;ei haue&thorn; litil hedis &amp; smale tailis, &amp; whanne|&thorn;ei ben in good watir &thorn;at ben manie froggis yn.  &amp; or &thorn;ou sette|hem vpon a man, &thorn;ei schulen be kept al adai fastynge.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt &yogh;eue him a litil scharp blood for to ete, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt| waische hem wi&thorn; cleer water; &amp; &thorn;an vpon &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="219b">place &thorn;at he schal be
<PB N="305">|sett, &thorn;e place schal be wel frotid tofore, &thorn;at it bicome reed, &amp; &thorn;an|sette &thorn;ervpon a ventuse for to drawe &thorn;erto blood. &amp; &thorn;an anoynte|&thorn;e same place wi&thorn; blood, &amp; &thorn;an sette &thorn;ervpon &thorn;e watir leche.  &amp;|whanne he is ful &amp; &thorn;ou wolt do him awei, blowe vpon &thorn;e place|baurac, ou&thorn;er askis maad of paper.  &amp; whanne he is falle awei, &thorn;an|sette &thorn;ervpon a ventuse a&yogh;en to drawe more blood to &thorn;e plase.  &amp;|&thorn;an sette &thorn;ervpon ano&thorn;er watir leche, if &thorn;ere gaderi&thorn; &thorn;erto miche|mater.  &amp; &thorn;is maner is good for al maner blood &thorn;at is rotid, for it|draweth it out /</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="18">
<HEAD>Of cauterium or brennyng of large &amp; streite.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator misunderstood the meaning of the Latin, "large et|stricte," in the following passage: Cauterium dicitur duobus modis, large &amp;|stricte.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Cauterium is seid in ij. maners, &thorn;at is to seie large &amp; streit.  &amp;|cauterium is seid propurli a brennynge wi&thorn; gold or wi&thorn; sum|o&thorn;er instrument &thorn;at is hoot, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; watir or wi&thorn; oile, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn;|medicyn caustica, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; herbis / And &thorn;er ben manie medicyns|for to make cauterijs, whiche &thorn;ou schalt fynde pleynlier in &thorn;e antidotarie|/ A cauterie is clepid streit,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the preceding note.</NOTE> whanne it is maad wi&thorn; an hoot|yren, wi&thorn; gold, or wi&thorn; siluir // Cauterijs &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="220a">ben maad wi&thorn; medicyns|&thorn;at han vertu for to brenne / &THORN;er is seid a cauterie po[tentia]le |whanne it is not hoot in felinge / &amp; &thorn;at cauterie preuaili&thorn; wi&thorn;outen|brennynge as herbis / &THORN;er is ano&thorn;er maner cauterie: actual, for so|miche as it brenne&thorn; in dede / Of &thorn;is cauterie auicen<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanfranc mentions Avicenna, who has a short chapter about cauterization,|Lib. I., Fen. 4, Cap. 29; yet he chiefly follows Gulielmus de Salic., Lib.|V., Cap. I., but with many additions and alterations.</NOTE> speki&thorn; &amp; sei&thorn;,|&thorn;at it is a medicyn, miche helpinge for to defende, &thorn;at mater schal|not departe into al &thorn;e lyme; &amp; it wole comforte &thorn;e lyme, &amp; bringe|it into good complexioun a&yogh;en, &amp; it wole dissolue mater &thorn;at is corrupt,|&amp; it wole streyne flux of blood.  &amp; auicen sei&thorn;, &thorn;at a cauterie|is oon of &thorn;e beste pointis of cirurgie / for &thorn;ingis &thorn;at mowe not be|fulfillid in long tyme, wi&thorn; cauterie &thorn;ei ben fulfillid / As it is seid|phisicians leue&thorn; &thorn;is craft to cirurgians.  &amp; &thorn;erfore it is greet wondir|if &thorn;er be ony good cirurgian founde, for &thorn;ei ben alle lewid men.  &amp;|if a lewid man schal worche with cauterijs, &thorn;an he knowi&thorn; not &thorn;e|difference bitwixe a cauterie &thorn;at is clepid actuel &amp; potencial.  &amp; also|&thorn;ei knowe not in what place of a mannes bodi &thorn;ei schulen make|hem.  &amp; &thorn;is is so repreued &thorn;at it is almoost out <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="220b">of vss / Also |summen maken cauterijs in vnclene bodies &thorn;at ben ful replet of
<PB N="306">|yuele humours, &amp; &thorn;an cauterijs wolen do litil profit to passiouns|&thorn;at ben forseid, but &thorn;er wole falle &thorn;erto so manie humouris, &amp; make|&thorn;e place of &thorn;e cauterie to swelle, &amp; li&yogh;tly engendre a cancre.  &amp; &thorn;an|men &thorn;at ben vnkunnynge ben agast herof &amp; ben not hardi for to|make no mo cauterijs.  &amp; if &thorn;e patient hadde be purgid of grete|humours tofore, &thorn;an it wolde not haue fare so.  &para; And summen|vsen cantarides for to make cauterijs &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; leggen it vpon men|&thorn;at han hote complexioun &amp; drie; &amp; &thorn;is is contrarious &amp; falli&thorn;|greet agreuaunce &thorn;erof, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei seien &thorn;at cauterijs ne ben nou&yogh;t|wor&thorn; / But auicen sei&thorn;, &thorn;at a cauterie is good tofore alle medicyns|for to waaste &amp; consume mater / if &thorn;e cauterie be sett in place &thorn;ere|it schulde be, but if the mater be so miche &thorn;at &thorn;e cauterie mai not|consume it, as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t se an ensample herof: &thorn;at fier ouercome&thorn;|alle &thorn;ingis / but if &thorn;ou doist a litil fier among miche wet wode, &thorn;er| wole come smoke &thorn;erof.  &amp; the fier <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="221a">mai not ouercome to waaste &thorn;e|wode, for water &thorn;at is in &thorn;e wode is more &thorn;an &thorn;e fier / In &thorn;e same|maner it fari&thorn; of a cauterie &thorn;at is in a mannes bodi, if he be ful of|humouris, &thorn;anne &thorn;e cauterie mai not worche.  &amp; &thorn;erfor &thorn;ou schalt|purge him wi&thorn; laxatiuis tofore &thorn;e cauterie as it is aforseid / Also|&thorn;ou schalt make no cauterijs in a man &thorn;at is ful of gode humours|as of blood, for &thorn;an oonli blood-letyng suffisi&thorn; / but if &thorn;e patient|be strong &amp; &thorn;e mater on him be coold &amp; moist, &thorn;an a cauterie is|good for to driue awei &thorn;e mater.  &amp; a man schal not bere a cauterie,|but .ij. mone&thorn;is ou&thorn;er .iij. at &thorn;e mooste.  &para; Now I wole telle &thorn;ee|a good rule / If &thorn;ou fyndist in a mannes body a lyme in wei of corrupcioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: si membrum invenis in via corruptionis.</NOTE>:|as herisipula, or herpes estiomenus, ou&thorn;er formica, or in|yuel disposicioun of a wounde &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; to encancre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>encancre</I>, med. Lat. incancrire; Dufr., Ital. incancherare.</NOTE> &amp; for al|o&thorn;er corrupcioun, &thorn;an sette a cauterie in &thorn;e nexte welle to &thorn;e place,|for &thorn;e cauterie wole defende &thorn;e place fro corrupcioun.  &para; Now speke|we of particlis of cauterijs &thorn;at falli&thorn; in diuers placis of a mannes| bodi, &amp; wi&thorn; diuers instrumentis &thorn;ei schulen <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="221b">be maad, whiche &thorn;ou|schalt se portraied<NOTE PLACE="foot">The figures are omitted.</NOTE> tofore &thorn;e, &amp; her signis for&thorn;wi&thorn;.  &para; &THORN;e .i. instrument|&thorn;at is comoun &amp; moost in vss, is clepid nodulum,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. anodulum, adnodulum.</NOTE> &amp; is an|instrument maad in &thorn;is maner / Take a brood plate of iren &amp; make|&thorn;eron an hole, &amp; leie &thorn;at plate &thorn;ere &thorn;ou wolt make &thorn;i cauterie.  &amp;|&thorn;an &thorn;ou muste haue an iren maad long &amp; smal &amp; maad hoot, &amp;|putte it in &thorn;at hole of &thorn;e plate / &thorn;is plate wole saue &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;e
<PB N="307">|cauterie schal be nomore but as &thorn;ou wolt / &amp; &thorn;at iren &thorn;at &thorn;ou|schalt make &thorn;i cauterie &thorn;erwi&thorn;, schal haue a litil round knap tofore.|&amp; &thorn;at iren schal be maad hoot til it bicome reed / &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;ou|schalt make &thorn;i cauterie, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou doist awei &thorn;in iren, &thorn;ere|wole be vlcus.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;eron butter or oold grese, or|grese stampid wi&thorn; caul-leues, &amp; &thorn;at is &thorn;e best of alle, &amp; leie it|&thorn;erto, til &thorn;e cruste falle awei &thorn;at &thorn;e hoot iren made.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt do &thorn;erto a litil pelot maad of lynnen cloo&thorn; round &amp; hard.  &amp;|&thorn;at pelot schal be anoyntid wi&thorn; oile, &amp; vpon &thorn;e place leie a caulleef,|or an yue-leef, or a vine-leef, &amp; in &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="222a">maner &thorn;ou schalt holde |it open as longe as &thorn;ou wolt.  &para; The .ij. cauterie is clepid round, &amp;|ha&thorn; no knap at &thorn;e ende, but it is schape long, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou|makist &thorn;i cauterie, &thorn;ou muste be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou touche no nerues ne|veynes.  &amp; &thorn;is instrument schal be maad in &thorn;is maner, &thorn;at it make|a cauterie in bo&thorn;e endis, after &thorn;at &thorn;ou desirist, greet or smal.  &para; The|.iij cauterie is clepid punctuale, &amp; is ful necessarie whanne &thorn;ou wolt|make a streit cauterie.  &amp; is maad in &thorn;is maner.  &para; The .iiij. is|clepid radiale, &amp; is smal &amp; scharp, &amp; is good for children, &amp; is maad|in &thorn;is maner<NOTE PLACE="foot">The description of the Cauterium radiale is an insertion of the translator.|Lat.: "tertium cauterium punctuale, seu radiale, &amp; est necessarium ubi valde|strictum uolueris facere cauterium, &amp; est sic factum."  Gulielm. de Sal.|Sloane 277, fol. 45, bk.: "<I>&thorn;e fif&thorn;e is clepyd cauterium minutum, or radiale|or viduale &thorn;at is a comoun instrument to children.</I>"</NOTE> / &para; The .v. cauterie is maad in &thorn;is maner, &amp; is swi&thorn;e|comoun &amp; is clepid calcellare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26106, fol. 98, bk.: "cutellare," printed ed. "cultellare."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;is wole make a long brennyng|as ouer&thorn;wert &thorn;e heed, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wolt make vlcera long &thorn;at ben|rounde, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt worche wi&thorn; &thorn;is cauterie.  &para; The .vj. is clepid|subtile, &amp; is good for festris &thorn;at sitti&thorn; in &thorn;e corner of a mannes i&yogh;e,|&amp; it is good for yuel fleisch &thorn;at growi&thorn; in a mannes i&yogh;e, &amp; is maad|in &thorn;is maner / &thorn;is sotille <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="222b">cauterie schal be maad hoot &amp; putt in a |canel in &thorn;is maner // The .vj.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator, forgetting that he counted the "radiale" as a separate|cautery, follows again the numbers of the original.</NOTE> is clepid dactilare, for it is schape as|it were &thorn;e stoon of a date.  &amp; herwi&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt make cauterijs in &thorn;e|haunche.  &amp; &thorn;ere schal be an instrument schape as a table, &amp; schal|be leid to &thorn;e haunche in &thorn;is maner, &amp; ha&thorn; .vj. arisyngis &thorn;eron as ha&thorn;|a stoon of a date.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: et habet v. eminentias sicut ossa dactilorum factas.</NOTE>  &amp; oon &thorn;erof is in &thorn;e myddil, &amp; .ij. aboue, &amp; .j.|bine&thorn;e, &amp; oon in bo&thorn;e sidis in &thorn;is maner / Whanne &thorn;is instrument|is hoot, it schal be putt vpon a mannes haunche, &amp; a table bitwixe|maad of iren.  &amp; &thorn;is table schal be coold, &amp; &thorn;er schulen be .vj. holis
<PB N="308">|&thorn;eron, schape after &thorn;e cauterie &thorn;at ha&thorn; .vj. arisingis out as it is aforseid.|And &thorn;ou schalt make .v. cauterijs vpon a mannes haunche,|&amp; .ij. &thorn;erof schulen be aboue &thorn;e ioynct, &amp; .ij. bi &thorn;e sidis, &amp; oon|vpon &thorn;e ioynct, &amp; .j. tofore &thorn;e ioynct.  &para; &THORN;e vij. is clepid triangulare,|&amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;er mai be maad .iij. at oonys. &amp; &thorn;is cauterie is good|for &thorn;e haunche also, &amp; is maad in &thorn;is maner / &para; The .viij. cauterie|is clepid actuale,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>actuale</I>, a mistake for <I>acuale</I>.</NOTE> for sumtyme it is maad wi&thorn; a nedle, &amp; it is good| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="223a">for to make cauterijs &thorn;erwi&thorn; in &thorn;e browis, &amp; is maad sutil as a|nedele.  &para; The .ix. cauterie is clepid linguale, &amp; it is schape as it|were a tunge of a litil brid in &thorn;is maner. &amp; it is good for to make|cauterijs vpon a mannes browis / &para; The .x. cauterie is clepid ceton,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ceton</I>, med. Lat. seto, sedo; Fr. s&eacute;ton; Ital. settone, "seton."  Add.|26,106, and the printed ed. read: dicitur ad sectionem.</NOTE>|&amp; is maad triangulis holowid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: fit cum tenaculis perforatis.</NOTE> &amp; in &thorn;e hole &thorn;erof &thorn;ere may entre a|scharp instrument &thorn;at ha&thorn; a fenestre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fenestre</I>, Lat. fenestra; "la fenestre de la cannule," Par&eacute;; see <I>Littr&eacute;|Dict</I>.</NOTE> as it were a nedele, &amp; it|schal be holde with coold tenaclis, also &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt|make &thorn;i cauterie on.  &THORN;ou schalt take vp &thorn;e skyn wi&thorn; tenaclis, &amp;|putt in &thorn;in hoot iren &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e tenaclis, &amp; brenne &thorn;e skyn.|&THORN;an &thorn;ou schalt make a corde of wollen &yogh;erne &amp; wete it in blood, &amp;|drawe it &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e holis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt knytte &thorn;e .ij. endis togidere,|&amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt holde it open as longe as &thorn;ou wolt.|&THORN;is is a comoun cauterie, &amp; &thorn;is cauterie mai be maad in &thorn;e mou&thorn; of|&thorn;e stomac, &amp; vpon &thorn;e lyuere &amp; &thorn;e splene, &amp; vpon &thorn;e ballocke-le&thorn;eris /|Now &thorn;ou knowist alle &thorn;in instrumentis, for to make cauterijs with, &amp;| her names / Now telle we in what maner &amp; in what place &thorn;ou schalt|make hem / In oold heed-akynge, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="223b">whanne purgaciouns &amp; laxatiuis|&amp; gargarismis &amp; snesyngis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>snesyngis</I>, Lat. sternutationes.</NOTE> &amp; clisterijs &amp; o&thorn;ere maner of avoidynge,|&amp; wi&thorn; enplastris &amp; wi&thorn; anoyntyng, whanne &thorn;e akynge of a|mannes heed wole not go awei wi&thorn; alle &thorn;ese, ne &thorn;e epilencie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>epilencie</I>, O.Fr. epilence.  Plinius: epilenticus.  See Dufr. Matth.|Sylv.: Epilensia .i. morbus caducus.</NOTE> ne|noon passioun &thorn;at come&thorn; of &thorn;e heed, ne passiouns of &thorn;e i&yogh;en, &amp;|passiouns of &thorn;e eeren, &amp; of &thorn;e nose&thorn;rillis, &amp; oold cou&yogh;e, &amp; flux of|&thorn;e wombe &thorn;at come&thorn; of &thorn;e reume.  &para; For alle &thorn;ese passiouns &thorn;ou|schalt make cauterie &thorn;at is clepid cultellare in &thorn;e welle of &thorn;e heed<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. in capitis fontinella.  Phillips: "Fontanella, or Fonticulus, a little|Well, or Spring: In Surgery, an Issue, or little Ulcer, made in sound parts|of the Body, to let out bad Humours, and to Cure, or prevent Diseases.  In|Anatomy, the mould or root of the Nose."  It was further a name for the|place where these ulcers were produced, especially for a place between the|sutures of the skull.  Compare <I>Sowd. of Babyl</I>. 2951: <I>[he smote hir] ouer|the founte throughoute the brayn.</I></NOTE>
