<HEAD>and bigynne&thorn; &thorn;e four&thorn;e|book // Of brekyng of boonis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>bookis</I>.</NOTE> &amp; sumtyme of|brusyng of boonys, and a general techyng for|alle //<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. heading: "Explicit tractatus tertius huis libri.  Incipit quartus,|qui est de algebra, et continet duas summas.  Summa prima tractatus|quarti septem continet capitula.  Capitulum primum summ&aelig; prim&aelig; tractatus|quarti, de fractura ossium sermo generalis."  The translator has kept the|heading of the first chapter, but left out the chapter itself.  His first chapter,|which has no heading, is Lanfranc's second one: Capitulum secundum|summe prime de fractura ossium faciei.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<PB N="313"><P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="227b">A Mannes nose is sumtyme to-broken,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare: <I>Paul. &AElig;gin.</I>, Book VI., Sect. xci., ed. Adams, vol. II., p. 443,|and <I>Avicenna</I>, Lib. IV., Fen. v., Tract 3, Cap. 3, ed. Venet. 1527, fol. 365 <I>b</I>.</NOTE> &amp; sumtyme pressid |adoun. &amp; if he be hastili holpen his nose mai be restorid|a&yogh;en, &amp; if it be longe or he haue ony help, &thorn;anne he|schal be maymed for euermore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal., Sloane 277, fol. 34: "<I>Thow schalt wite &thorn;at &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e|nose is o&thorn;erwhile depressyd &amp; o&thorn;erwhile broken, &amp; &yogh;if so&thorn;ely it be depressyd,|&thorn;at is to sey born down or broken withoute wounde, anoon in &thorn;e|firste visitacion, be &thorn;e seknesse restoryd, whil it is newe, for &yogh;if it were hard,|ou&thorn;er &thorn;er schal dwelle euermore snattydnesse or euel schapp.</I>"  <I>snattydness</I>,|translates med. Lat. simitas <GAP DESC="Greek">, snubbiness.</NOTE> / If &thorn;ou comest at &thorn;e|firste bigynnyng &thorn;ou schalt do in &thorn;is maner / putte yn &thorn;e fingir of|&thorn;e lifthand anoon to &thorn;e brekyng, &thorn;i leeste fyngir or what fyngir|wole best yn, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;i ri&yogh;thond presse vpon &thorn;e brekyng, &amp; arere|vpward wi&thorn; &thorn;i fyngir withinnefor&thorn;, &amp; presse wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;|&amp; bringe it as it schulde be.  &THORN;an make a strong tent &amp; so|longe &thorn;at he mowe passe aboue &thorn;e brekyng, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;is tent schal|be di&yogh;t wi&thorn; a litil wex hoot &amp; a litil sotil poudre of mastik &amp;|sandal, &amp; schape &thorn;erof in &thorn;e maner of a candel, &amp; &thorn;an putte it into|his nose, wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; leie of consolidatiuis &thorn;at schulen be seid in &thorn;e|antidotarie, &amp; aboutefor&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt leie a defensif, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt|binde his nose wi&thorn; boondis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>broondis</I>.</NOTE> &amp; leie sutil lynnen cloo&thorn; in bo&thorn;e sidis|of his nose as <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="228a">it is aforseid in &thorn;e chapiter of woundis in a mannes |face / If &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t not putte yn &thorn;i fyngir in his nose&thorn;rel, &thorn;an make|a tent of tre &amp; hile it wi&thorn; lynnen cloo&thorn; &thorn;at it be oold &amp; neissche,|&amp; &thorn;an anointe &thorn;is tent wi&thorn; oile of rosis, &amp; putte &thorn;is in his nose&thorn;rel|in stide of &thorn;i fyngir, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; arere vp his nose wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal.  Sloane 277, fol. 34: "<I>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou may not do &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;i|fynger, putte in &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e nose on &thorn;e hurt syde a softe rownd sticke maad|euene &amp; semely, &amp; anoynted with oyle of rosis ... and &thorn;ou maist also lappe|&thorn;ilke sticke in a clene lynen clout &amp; anoynte &thorn;e clout wi&thorn; &thorn;e same oile, &amp;|&thorn;anne &thorn;e sticke schal be &thorn;e more tretable.</I>"</NOTE> &amp;|wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond wi&thorn;outfor&thorn; make his nose euene til &thorn;e boon be brou&yogh;t|in his propre place &thorn;at is to-broke.  &para; Of his dietyng, &amp; blood-letyng,|&amp; ventusis, &amp; clisterijs, ou&thorn;er suppositorijs, do as &thorn;ou seest|&thorn;at it is to do, &amp; as it is aforseid.</P>
<P>&para; If a manes cheke-boon<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Avic</I>. Lib. IV., Fen. v. Tr. 3, Cap. 2, ibid.: "<I>Si frangitur mandibula|dextra, tunc intromitte indicem, et medium manus sinistre in os infirmi, et|cet."  Gul. de Sal. Lib. III., Cap. 2.  Sl. 277. fol. 34 b: "&yogh;if so&thorn;ely &thorn;e boon|of &thorn;e vppere chawel or of &thorn;e ne&thorn;ere were maad</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sl. 6. fol. 115 <I>b, broken.</I></NOTE> <I>withoute wounde, putte &thorn;i|ry&yogh;t hond in &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e seeke.</I>"</NOTE> in &thorn;e liftside be to-broke, &thorn;an putte
<PB N="314">|yn &thorn;i strongist fyngris of &thorn;i lifthond tweyne &amp; bringe &thorn;e boon into|his propre place a&yogh;en, &amp; presse wi&thorn; &thorn;i ri&yogh;thond wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;; &amp; if &thorn;e|cheke-boon be to-broke in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tside, &thorn;anne putte yn .ij. fyngris of|&thorn;i ri&yogh;thond, and bringe &thorn;e boon to his propre place a&yogh;en, as it is aforseid.|&amp; whanne &thorn;e boon is brou&yogh;t as it schulde be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t|knowe if his tee&thorn; sitti&thorn; euene as &thorn;ei schulde do, &amp; &thorn;an binde hise| tee&thorn; wi&thorn; a strong &thorn;reed wexid <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="228b">&amp; bounden bitwixe his tee&thorn;, &amp; leie|&thorn;ervpon oon of &thorn;e consolidatiuis &amp; binde him in &thorn;e same maner, &thorn;at|&thorn;e boond be maad fast bihindefor&thorn; in his necke.  &amp; &thorn;an it schal be|turned a&yogh;en to his forheed, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt binde him wi&thorn; &thorn;i boond|manyfoold, &thorn;at &thorn;e boon &thorn;at is to-broke mowe be holde in his propre|place / And &thorn;e patient schal ete no metis but &thorn;ingis &thorn;at he may|soupe / For if he chewide, it wolde make &thorn;e boon falle out of his|place a&yogh;en, &amp; in .xx. daies &thorn;is boon mai be restorid a&yogh;en //</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>ffor brekyng of &thorn;e forke of &thorn;e &thorn;rote and of &thorn;e brest //<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanfranc divides the fourth book into two "doctrines," the one dealing|with fractures, the other with dislocations.  The scribe of the present translation|omits this division and the first chapter of each doctrine.  He also|puts the chapter on dislocation of the jaw-bone, which was originally the 2nd|chapter of the 2nd doctrine immediately after the chapter on fracture of the|jaw-bone, still retaining the heading of the 3rd chapter of the first doctrine:|"<I>ffor brekyng of &thorn;e forke of &thorn;e &thorn;rote and of &thorn;e brest.</I>"  The two tables of|contents show the same order as the original.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>The cheke-boon aboue meue&thorn; not, &amp; &thorn;at is for .iij. causis: oon|is &thorn;at &thorn;e cheke-boon bine&thorn;e is more li&yogh;t &amp; more able &thorn;erfore,|&THORN;e .ij. cause is &thorn;is: &thorn;e cheke-boon is ni&yogh; noble lymes, &amp; if &thorn;e cheke-boon|aboue meuede, &thorn;e noble lymes mi&yogh;ten be enpeirid &thorn;erbi.  &THORN;e .iij.|cause is &thorn;is: if &thorn;e cheke-boon aboue meuede, &thorn;ere nolde be noon|strong coniunccioun bitwene hem / &THORN;erfore &thorn;e cheke-boon aboue is| fast maad to &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e heed, as it is aforseid in anothomiam.|&para; The cheke-boon bine&thorn;e is maad of .ij. boonys ioyned <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="229a">togidere|in &thorn;e chyn.  &amp; &thorn;is boon is maad fast with &thorn;e cheke-boon aboue wi&thorn;|ligaturis &thorn;at ben stronge &amp; recching &amp; wi&thorn; lacertis, &amp; maketh &thorn;e|cheke-boon meue whanne a man wole, for summe &thorn;erof come&thorn;|adoun fro &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e heed, &amp; ben ioyned wi&thorn; partijs of nerues|of &thorn;e heed, &amp; of nuche, &amp; closi&thorn; togidere &thorn;e cheke-boon.  [Summe|come&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Summe come&thorn;</I>, wanting.  Lat. Add. 26106, fol. 96 bk.: "alii veniunt ab|inferius versus pectus."  The prints differ.</NOTE>] bine&thorn;e afor&yogh;ens &thorn;e brest, and ben medlid wi&thorn; nerues of|nuche &amp; opene&thorn; &thorn;e cheke-boon, &amp; summe come&thorn; fro &thorn;e sidis, &amp;
<PB N="315">|meue&thorn; &thorn;e cheke-boon round, whanne a man couwid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: in masticando.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;is cheke-boon|bine&thorn;e mai be brou&yogh;t of &thorn;e ioynct fro &thorn;e cheke-boon aboue in|.ij. maners: ou&thorn;er it goi&thorn; of &thorn;e ioynct bihindeward, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e tee&thorn;|&thorn;at ben in &thorn;e cheke-boon bine&thorn;e goi&thorn; wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e tee&thorn; of &thorn;e cheke-boon|aboue.  &amp; &thorn;an he may not opene his mou&thorn;, &amp; it goi&thorn; out of &thorn;e|ioynct forward, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e tee&thorn; &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e cheke-boon bine&thorn;e goi&thorn;|for&thorn;ere out &thorn;an &thorn;e tee&thorn; aboue.  &amp; he mai not close his mou&thorn;|togidere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal. Lib. III., Cap. 18.  Sl. 277, fol. 42 <I>b</I>: "<I>The tokenes of &thorn;e|dislocation inward ben &thorn;at &thorn;e mou&thorn; leue&thorn; opene, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e te&thorn; of &thorn;e ne&thorn;ere|chawel goon tofore &thorn;e te&thorn; of &thorn;e vppere chawl.  &para; The tokenes of &thorn;e dislocacioun|owtward ben &thorn;at &thorn;e mouth is schut &amp; in no manere may be openyd, &amp;|&thorn;e seeke may not chewe &amp; &thorn;e te&thorn; drawe vp toward &thorn;e palett, &amp; &thorn;er schewi&thorn; in|&thorn;e vttere party in &thorn;e place of &thorn;e dislocacion an opene outberynge out of|mesure, &amp; &thorn;e speche is bynomen hym.</I>"</NOTE> / These signys ben certeyn whanne &thorn;e boon is out of his|ioynct / It is greet nede for to helpe a man hastily in &thorn;is caas; for|if &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="229b">cheke-boon be out of ioincte longe, &thorn;ere ben manie nerues &amp; |lacertis &amp; arterijs &amp; veines aboute &thorn;at place, &amp; for &thorn;is cause it|wexi&thorn; hard anoon.  &amp; &thorn;is place wole soone take enpostym for|divers humours &thorn;at wolen falle &thorn;erto.  &amp; if &thorn;er falle an enpostym|in &thorn;is place, &thorn;an, for &thorn;e brayn is so ni&yogh;, &thorn;er come&thorn; a frenesie &thorn;erof|&amp; ofte tyme die&thorn; / &amp; &thorn;erfore if he be hastili holpen, &thorn;e boon wole|li&yogh;tly into &thorn;e ioinct a&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;at ioinct ha&thorn; li&yogh;t meuynge /|ffor eueri ioinct &thorn;at ha&thorn; hard meuynge, &amp; he be out of &thorn;e ioinct,|it wole be hard for to bringe yn a&yogh;en / If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e cheke-boon|be out of ioinnct hindeward, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt take &thorn;e boon|first wi&thorn; &thorn;i .ij. hondis, &amp; lete a man holde his heed &amp; drawe &thorn;e|boon for&thorn;ward.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal. Sl. 277, fol. 42 <I>b</I>: "<I>The dislocacion knowe, whe&thorn;er it be to|&thorn;e innere party or &thorn;e vttere, a wyse leche owe&thorn; to putte his &thorn;umbes wi&thorn;inne|&thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e seeke, &amp; festene hem vpon &thorn;e wange-te&thorn; of &thorn;e ne&thorn;ere iowe of &thorn;e|seeke, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere four fyngeres he schal take &thorn;e iowe dislocate fro &thorn;e|vttere, &amp; &thorn;at tyme he schal haue a mynystre, which schal holde fast &thorn;e heuyd|of &thorn;e seeke.</I>"</NOTE>  &amp; if it so be &thorn;at his mou&thorn; be closid togidere, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou schalt opene his mou&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond or with sum o&thorn;er instrument,|&amp; &thorn;an take faste &thorn;e boon &amp; drawe it to his place a&yogh;en.  &amp; in|&thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe whanne it is in his propre place a&yogh;en,|if his tee&thorn; sitten euene, &amp; if he may opene his mou&thorn; / &para; If &thorn;ou|mi&yogh;t not bringe &thorn;e boon to his propre place in &thorn;is maner, &thorn;an &thorn;ou|muste take a strong boond, &amp; sette it vndir his chyn, &thorn;ere &thorn;ou|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="230a">settist &thorn;i fyngris, &amp; ano&thorn;er man mote drawe &thorn;e boond strongly &amp; |euene, &amp; wi&thorn; a wagge &thorn;ou muste opene his mou&thorn;.  In &thorn;is maner
<PB N="316">|&thorn;ou openynge his mou&thorn;, &amp; he drawing wi&thorn; &thorn;e boond as it is aforseid,|al at oonys wi&thorn;outen drede &thorn;e boon wole come into his ioynet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26106, fol.97: ita quod tu aperiendo et minister trahendo vna hora locum suum intrat, quia sic sine dubio restaurabis.</NOTE>|&para; If it be out of &thorn;e ioinct forward, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt sette a strong|boond vpon his chin, &thorn;at it hile al &thorn;e chin, &amp; lete a man stonde|bihinde him &amp; halde &thorn;e boond in hise hondis, &amp; he schal sette his|knees vpon his schuldris, &amp; he schal drawe &thorn;e boon to him wel &amp;|euenly. &amp; &thorn;ou schalt putte a wegge in his mou&thorn;, &amp; whanne he|drawi&thorn; &thorn;e boon &thorn;ou schalt opene his mou&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e wegge al at oon|tyme, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn; boon schal falle into his ioinct. Whanne|&thorn;e boon is ynne, &thorn;an binde it faste wi&thorn; a ligature &amp; with enplastre,|&amp; lete him haue souping metis, &amp; he schal chewe no mete til &thorn;e|place be al fast / &para; If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou were not at &thorn;e first bigynnyng,|&amp; &thorn;e place is enpostymed, &amp; he haue &thorn;e feuere &amp; akynge of|his heed, &thorn;an schaue his heed &amp; anoynte it wi&thorn; oile of rosis &amp; a|litil vinegre medlid &thorn;erwi&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;ou schalt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="230b"> anoynte his heed with|sum mollificatif, or wi&thorn; dokis grese or wi&thorn; hennys. &amp; &thorn;ou schalt|worche as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t for to acesse &thorn;e enpostym, &amp; for to|cure &thorn;e feuere, &amp; for to comforte his heed, &thorn;at &thorn;e frenesie ne come|not to him / Whanne &thorn;e feuere &amp; &thorn;e frenesie &amp; &thorn;e enpostym be|remeued awei, &thorn;an cure him as it is aforseid //</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>ffor brekyng of &thorn;e forke of &thorn;e &thorn;rote and of &thorn;e brest //<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Paul. &AElig;gin.,</I> Book VI., 93, ed. Adams, vol. ii. p. 447. <I>Avicenna,</I> Lib. IV., Fen. 5, Tract 3, Cap. 4, ed. Ven. 1527, p. 365 <I>b</I>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>THe forke of &thorn;e &thorn;rote is clepid of summen patena, &amp; of summen|cathena.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>patena, cathena,</I> names for the <I>furcula,</I> as it seems peculiar to Lanfranc. The furcula, taken to be one bone, comprises the sternal bone and the clavicles. "Catena," chain, is synonymous with "clavicula;" and patena, med. Lat. = plate, is a proper denomination of the sternal bone.</NOTE> Sumtyme it is to-broke &amp; nou&thorn;er part of &thorn;e|boon ne is not ypressid yn, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof is li&yogh;t ynow.|But if &thorn;at oon ende of &thorn;e boon be pressid adoun vndir &thorn;at o&thorn;er,|&thorn;an it is ful hard for to bringe it yn a&yogh;en. Whanne nou&thorn;er partie|is pressid adoun, &thorn;an it is noon o&thorn;er nede for to haue no medicyn|but stupis wet in white of eiren; &amp; leie it vpon &thorn;e brekynge of &thorn;e|boon, &amp; binde wel &thorn;e place wi&thorn; ligaturis; &amp; his arme of &thorn;e same|side mote be hongid to his necke, &amp; in his arme-pitt &thorn;ou schalt leie|a bal of lynnen cloo&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;ou muste binde his arme &thorn;at he mowe not|meue his arm <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="231a">toward &thorn;e forke of &thorn;e brest, &amp; in &thorn;is maner he mote
<PB N="317">|be kept til &thorn;e boon be al hool. &para; If it so be &thorn;at oon ende of &thorn;e|boon be pressid adoun, &thorn;an a man mote drawe his oon arme, &amp;|ano&thorn;er man his o&thorn;ere arme, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; &thorn;in hondis drawe &thorn;e|boon to his propre place. &THORN;an &thorn;ou muste haue a medicyne consolidatif,|&amp; wete &thorn;erinne a lynnen cloo&thorn;, &amp; hile al &thorn;e brekyng of|&thorn;e boon &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon faldellas<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>faldella,</I> med. Lat., diminutive of <I>falda,</I> thread.</NOTE> wi&thorn; white of an ey, &amp;|&thorn;an binde him as it is aforseid, and his arme to his necke, &amp; in &thorn;is maner he schal be kept til he be hool.</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>&para; Of brekyng of rigboonys /<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat. de fractura spondilium et costarum.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>RIgge boonys for her schortnes &amp; for her strongnes ne ben not|to-broke, but if it be wi&thorn; greet smytyng, &amp; sumtyme &thorn;ei|ben brusid, &amp; &thorn;at maki&thorn; greet akynge. Also &thorn;er falli&thorn; manie|perels of &thorn;e boonys of &thorn;e necke if &thorn;ei ben hurt, lest nucha be|hirt also, &amp; &thorn;an it is perel of &thorn;e brayn as it is aforsed / If &thorn;ou|seest yuel signes in &thorn;at caas, go awei &thorn;erfro. &amp; if &thorn;ou seest noon|yuele signys, &thorn;an anointe &thorn;e place wi&thorn; oile of rosis hoot &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon|wolle, and &thorn;anne <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="231b">terbentine medlid wi&thorn; a litil mastic, &amp; &thorn;is medicyne &thorn;ou schalt vse til &thorn;e place be al hool /</P>
<P>&para; The noumbre of a mannes ribbis is aforeseid in &thorn;e anothamie /|A mannes ribbis ben to-broke sumtyme wi&thorn; smytyng or|wi&thorn; fallyng / Also &thorn;ei moun be plied inward &amp; not to-broke. &para; In|&thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt knowe whe&thorn;ir a mannes rib be to-broke|or no / Sette &thorn;i fyngris vpon &thorn;e place &amp; grope softli &amp; presse a litil|vp &amp; doun, &amp; if his rib be to-broke, &thorn;ou schalt heere hym sownie,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal. lib. III., Cap. 5. Sl. 277, fol. 36: "<I>&YOGH;if it happe &thorn;e rybbis to be broken in oo place or in two &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt wite by touchynge, for &thorn;ei &thorn;at of &thorn;ristynge down of &thorn;e hond vpon &thorn;e place or places, &thorn;ou schalt heere a sown &amp; with &thorn;at &thorn;e seeke schal suffre penaunce or lettynge of bre&thorn;, &amp; principally &thorn;e tyme of drawynge of wynd.</I>" The sound, "crepitus," produced by pressure of the hand on the injured place, as a test whether a rib is fractured, is already mentioned in <I>Paul. &AElig;gin.,</I> Book VI., 96, ed. Adams, vol. ii., p. 452.</NOTE>|&amp; he schal haue cou&yogh;inge &amp; akinge in his side. &para; It is ful hard|for to restore a rib &thorn;at is to-broke, for sumtyme &thorn;at oon parti plie&thorn; inward, &amp; &thorn;an it is hard for to bringe him into his propre place|a&yogh;en / And summen seien &thorn;at &thorn;e pacient schulde ete metis to swelle|him &thorn;at engendri&thorn; wijnd, &amp; wole make &thorn;e rib goon into his propre|place a&yogh;en. &amp; summen seien &thorn;at me schulde sette a ventuse, &amp; wi&thorn;
<PB N="318">|&thorn;e drawing &thorn;erof &thorn;e rib wole rise vp a&yogh;en into his propre place /|But I suppose &thorn;is wole more make agreuaunce &thorn;an helpe &thorn;e patient /| ffor &thorn;e .j. wole engendre an hoot enpostyme<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="232a"> / The .ij. it wole|drawe to &thorn;e place manie humours / If &thorn;ou wolt take &thorn;is cure, &thorn;ou|schalt do in &thorn;is maner: / ffirst &thorn;ou schalt lete him blood in &thorn;e side|afor&yogh;ens in &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is clepid basilica, &amp; &thorn;an in &thorn;e same, &amp; &thorn;an|anoynte &thorn;in hond wi&thorn; terbentine.  &amp; loke if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t take vp &thorn;e rib|&thorn;at is pressid adoun.  &amp; &thorn;in o&thorn;er hond &thorn;ou schalt sette vpon &thorn;e|place &thorn;at is not pressid adoun.  &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond &thorn;at is anoyntid|arere vp his rib. &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;e .ij. endis of &thorn;e ribbis &thorn;at is to-broke|come euene togidere, &amp; &thorn;an make &thorn;e patient to cou&yogh;e, for &thorn;is &thorn;e|beste maner for to bringe him yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal.  Sl. 277, fol. 36: "<I>make hym eft cow&yogh;e sadly, &amp; vpon &thorn;e|place &thorn;rist down or broken, &thorn;ou schalt putte a gret ventuse wi&thorn;out cuttynge.</I>"</NOTE> / If &thorn;ou dredist nou&yogh;t greet|replecioun of his bodi, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t opene a ventuse whanne &thorn;e rib is|ioyned.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt binde wi&thorn; a boond, &amp; vndir &thorn;e boond &thorn;ou|schalt leie lynnet or sum o&thorn;er neische &thorn;ing.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt binde|him in sich a maner &thorn;at &thorn;e rib &thorn;at is to-broke ne mowe not remoue|ne falle adoun a&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;e patient schal vse li&yogh;t mete as pultes de|caudarisio,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sim. de Janua: "Caudarusium, Spelta, genus frumenti, quod quidam|allicam dicunt, quidam Caudarusium."</NOTE> de amido, de tritico, wi&thorn; penides, &amp; he schal drinke| swete wijn temperatli, &amp; &thorn;ou muste defende <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="232b">him fro wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; fro|crijnge, &amp; fro alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at wolen make a man to cou&yogh;e.  &para; If it|so be &thorn;at &thorn;e akynge aceese not, &amp; &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;t not bringe his rib|as he schulde be, &amp; if he ha&thorn; greet cow&yogh;ynge &amp; acces of &thorn;e feuere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>acces of &thorn;e feuere</I>, Lat. si febris accideret.</NOTE>|whanne &thorn;ou hast lete him blood, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste kutte &thorn;e skyn|afor&yogh;ens &thorn;e rib &thorn;at is to-broke, &amp; vnhile &thorn;e same rib of al his|fleisch, &amp; &thorn;an wi&thorn; instrumentis &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond &thorn;ou muste drawe|vp &thorn;e rib, &amp; bringe him in his place as he schulde be.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou|schalt cure &thorn;e wounde as it is aforseid / // His dietynge schal be|as of pluretici til &thorn;e feuere &amp; al &thorn;e passiouns ben goon awei //</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>Of brekyng of &thorn;e helpers of &thorn;e rigboon.</HEAD>
<P>Adiutorium is to-broken ful ofte ouer&thorn;wert wi&thorn; breking / &THORN;e|nere &thorn;at it be &thorn;e ioynct, &thorn;e more perilous it is, &amp; &thorn;e worse|for to cure / In &thorn;is place I wole telle &thorn;ee in what maner &thorn;ou schalt|knowe a brekyng, &amp; in what maner &thorn;ou schalt restore it a&yogh;en, &thorn;at
<PB N="319">|it mowe be an ensample to &thorn;ee in &thorn;e breking,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. has a full-stop between <I>breking</I> and <I>if</I>.  Lat.: ut sit tibi exemplum|in ruptura brachii, crurium et coxarum.</NOTE> if a mannes arme|&amp; his leggis &amp; his hipe-boon ben broken / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt|knowe: / Lete a man holde his arme <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="233a">wi&thorn; .ij. hondis faste bi &thorn;e |schuldre, &amp; he mot holde him in &thorn;at maner &thorn;at he mowe nott|meue him-silf; &amp; &thorn;ou schalt stonde tofore him, &amp; take his arme|faste bi &thorn;e elbowe, &amp; meue his arme hidir &amp; &thorn;idir li&yogh;tli til &thorn;ou heere|sownynge of &thorn;e boon, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou knowist &thorn;e place &thorn;at it is|to-broke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: et cum tactu locum fracture cognoueris manifeste.  Gul. de Sal.,|Sl. 277, fol. 37: "<I>When &thorn;e adiutorie, or &thorn;e boon fro &thorn;e elbowe to &thorn;e schuldre|is broken, it schal be knowe to &thorn;e touchynge in &thorn;is: The leche schal drawe|&thorn;e hurt place wi&thorn; bo&thorn;e his hondes, &amp; putte &thorn;at oon hond vpon &thorn;e place hurt,|&amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er wi&thorn;inne.  &para; And haue he a mynystre, whiche schal bere vp|togidere &thorn;e elbowe wi&thorn; &thorn;e arm.  And &thorn;anne &thorn;e leche, meuynge softely his|handis, schal heere &thorn;e sown of &thorn;e broken boon, or he schal feele &thorn;e disseuerynge|of &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e broken boon.</I>"</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;is maner asaiyng is good whanne &thorn;e brekynge is so|priuy &thorn;at no partie of &thorn;e boon goi&thorn; in no side out / Whanne &thorn;ou|knowist where &thorn;e breking is, or &thorn;ou bigynne ony &thorn;ing for to worche|&thorn;eron, make redi alle &thorn;i necessarijs &thorn;at ben gode for &thorn;e bindyng.|&para; First &thorn;ou schalt make stupis &thorn;at ben euene, &amp; wete hem in hoot|water in winter, &amp; in coold water in somer, &amp; &thorn;an wrynge out &thorn;i|stupis &thorn;erof &amp; di&yogh;te oile of rosis &amp; a defensif of bole, &amp; ij. longe|boondis &thorn;at &thorn;ei be .iiij. fyngris brood, &amp; lynnen cloo&thorn; &thorn;at mowe go|aboute al his arme, &amp; a strong corde; &amp; &thorn;e corde wole be &thorn;e better|if it be playn, &amp; not round.  &amp; &thorn;ou muste di&yogh;te smale &yogh;erdis of|drie tree, &thorn;at be strong &amp; sotil.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou hast di&yogh;t alle &thorn;ese|&thorn;ingis redi, &thorn;an sette &thorn;e boon in his place as li&yogh;tli &mdash; &mdash; &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some words are wanting.  Lat.: quantumcumque potes leuius operando.</NOTE> with|&thorn;in hond wi&thorn;outen greuaunce.  &amp; &thorn;an take <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="233b">oold soft lynnen cloo&thorn;, |&amp; wete it in oile of rosis, and wijnde it aboute his arme.  &amp; vpon|&thorn;is leie a cloo&thorn; wi&thorn; medicyns consolidatif, &thorn;at schal be seid in &thorn;e|antidotarie for brekynge of boonys; &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ese .ij. lynnen|clo&thorn;is moten be large for to hile al &thorn;e brekyng / And &thorn;ou muste|haue cloutis in .ij. sidis of &thorn;e place &thorn;at is to-broke, &amp; &thorn;ervpon|&thorn;ou muste leie faldellam in bo&thorn;e sidis euene, &amp; wet in gleire of|an ey.  &amp; alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &thorn;ou schalt binde wi&thorn; &thorn;i boond, &thorn;at|schal be &thorn;e brede of .iiij. fyngris, &amp; long &thorn;at he mowe goon|aboute manifoold.  &amp; sewe &thorn;e foldyng of &thorn;e boond &thorn;at he mowe|not vndo / Vpon &thorn;is ligature &thorn;ou schalt leie faldellam maad of|stupis, &amp; he schal oonly be wet in water &amp; leid vpon.  &amp; hervpon
<PB N="320">|&thorn;ou schalt leie &thorn;i splentis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spletis</I>.</NOTE>; &amp; wi&thorn; a corde &thorn;at be brood, &amp; not|round, &thorn;ei schulen be bounden &thorn;ervpon.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt streyne|middilly,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>middilly</I>, mediocriter.</NOTE> &amp; not to faste / Herof &thorn;ou muste be war, &thorn;at streynyng|&thorn;at is in &thorn;is place &amp; in o&thorn;ere placis ne schulen not be so harde &thorn;at|&thorn;e place bicome blak, ne &thorn;at he mowe fele his lyme / Ther ben summen| &thorn;at streynen so faste a manys lyme, &thorn;at &thorn;e spirit of meuynge,<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="234a">|ne &thorn;e spirit of lijf mai not come &thorn;erto.  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei see&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e|place is to-swolle, &amp; aski&thorn; of &thorn;e patient wher he haue miche akynge.|&amp; &thorn;ei supposen to do awei &thorn;e akynge wi&thorn; &thorn;e greet binding, &amp; in &thorn;is|maner &thorn;e lyme wole rotie, &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;e patient mai falle into|a feuer &amp; &thorn;e spasme, &amp; manye men die&thorn; &thorn;eron / But &thorn;ou schalt|worche in &thorn;is maner / Whanne &thorn;ou seest &thorn;is caas, vnbinde &thorn;e lyme,|&amp; as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t do awei &thorn;e swellyng &amp; &thorn;e akynge.  Aboue|&thorn;e brekyng towardis the schuldre leie a defensif of bole // If &thorn;er|come noon akynge ne swellynge, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt lete it sitte so|boounde .x. daies in winter, &amp; .vij. daies in somer / &amp; &thorn;an vnbinde|it softly &thorn;at &thorn;e lyme ne meue not / &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;e boon sitte wel;|&amp; &thorn;an binde it al togidere a&yogh;en as &thorn;ow didist first.  Whanne &thorn;e|boon is wel soudid, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt take stupis &amp; wete hem in good|wijn hoot,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: in bono vino calido.</NOTE> &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon.  &para; Whanne it is soudid, if &thorn;er leeue|ony &thorn;ing of hardnes in &thorn;e same place, &thorn;an do it awei aftir &thorn;e| teching &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e antidotarie /</P>
<P>Sumtyme &thorn;e boonys of a mannys arme ben to-broke <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="234b">bo&thorn;e, &amp;|sumtyme &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ei ben bo&thorn;e broken, it is &thorn;e more|worse / If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;er be to-broke but oon boon, &thorn;an it is no|nede for to do but astellas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: non est tibi necessarium astellas ponere.</NOTE> for &thorn;e boon &thorn;at is hool wole saue &thorn;e|ligature wel ynow&yogh; / The boonys of a mannes fyngris ben sumtyme|to-broke, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt sette euene &thorn;e boon, &amp; binde him wi&thorn;|astelles &thorn;at ben wel maad &thorn;erfore.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e fyngir ne be but a|litil lyme, &yogh;itt &thorn;ou muste haue good kunnyng &amp; good witt for to|di&yogh;te it wel / Dietyng in alle brekyng of boonys schal be first|sotil, &amp; aftirward more greet, as it is aforseid //</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>Of breking of &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e coxe.</HEAD>
<P>Whanne &thorn;e boon of &thorn;e coxe is to-broke or ony boon of &thorn;e|foot, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt worche in al maner &thorn;ingis as it is|aforseid in &thorn;e chapitre of adiutorie &amp; of &thorn;e fyngris / But &thorn;is &thorn;ou
<PB N="321">|muste adde more &thorn;erto, &thorn;at whanne &thorn;ou hast brou&yogh;t yn &thorn;e boon of|&thorn;e leg, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste make an instrument, &thorn;at is clepid albium|ou&thorn;er coutelle; &amp; it schal be schape in &thorn;e maner of a cros.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>Lat.: in albiolo seu coutella que sit ad modum cruris formata.  The|translator read "crucis."</P><P><I>albiola</I>, (alueolus) <I>um</I>.  "ventre, panier, benne, flancs d'un navire."&mdash;Dufr.</P><P><I>coutella</I>. <GAP DESC="Greek">, anything hollow, the cup of a joint, especially of the|hip-joint.  It.: cotila.  Tomm.</P><P><I>Paul. &AElig;gin</I>., Book VI, Sect. 106, ed. Adams, vol. 2, p. 470, describes the|way of arranging a fractured leg by means of "a canal either of wood or|earthenware."  Adams l. c. gives references from Hippocrates, Celsus and|Galen, for the use of these machines.</P></NOTE>  &amp;|&thorn;eron his leg mote be sett, so &thorn;at his leg mowe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="235a">bowe to no side / |Also it is necessarie &thorn;at &thorn;e patient ligge also stille as he mai|wi&thorn;outen remeuyng, til &thorn;e boon be fast // But &thorn;ou muste be wel|war herof whanne &thorn;at a mannes leg is to-broke, ou&thorn;er his hipe,|&thorn;ou muste be war in &thorn;e soudyng, &thorn;at oon leg be not schorter &thorn;an|&thorn;e o&thorn;er / But &thorn;ou schalt mesure hem algate bo&thorn;e lich long, &amp; in &thorn;e|same mesure kepe hem /</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e cure whanne a man is smiten in &thorn;e rigbon|or ribbis.</HEAD>
<P>It bifalli&thorn; sumtyme &thorn;at a man is smyten or a man falli&thorn;, &amp;|&thorn;an tendre boonys as &thorn;e cheke-boon &amp; ribbis, &amp; [in] children|boonys of her arme &amp; of her leggis, for &thorn;e tendirnes of &thorn;es|lymes, &thorn;ei wolen folde &amp; not breke / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt|bringe hem a&yogh;en / In &thorn;is maner anoynte &thorn;in hond wi&thorn;|terbentyne, &amp; take &thorn;at boon &amp; presse it as it is forseid in &thorn;e|brekyng of a boon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: Si maxilla fuerit, manum seu digitos in os pone, premens ad|extra sicut diximus in fractura, manum aliam termentina uel pice illinitam|suauiter ab extra preme et citius eleua.</NOTE>  &amp; if it be a rib, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt presse|him vpward, as it is foreseid.  &amp; if it be in &thorn;e arme ou&thorn;er|&thorn;e leg, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste make ligaturis &thorn;erfore &amp; instrument|of tree, &thorn;at be euene, &amp; &thorn;erto his arme ou&thorn;er his leg schal be|bounden &amp; pressid, for to make him euene.  &amp; or &thorn;ou do &thorn;us, &thorn;ou|schalt make a <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="235b">vomentacioun of camomille, malue, &amp; bismalue, |fenigreci, seminis lini soden in water; &amp; &thorn;an anoynte him wi&thorn; oile|of lilie, or wi&thorn; gandris grese, or hen-grese, &amp; &thorn;an presse his arme|as it is aforseid.  Also &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t vse &thorn;is medicyn, &thorn;at is aproued|ofte tyme / leie a plate of yuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">O.Fr. yvoyre.</NOTE> in &thorn;at side &thorn;at &thorn;e boon is aplied, &amp;
<PB N="322">|&thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e yuer wole drawe &thorn;e boon as it schulde be, &amp; bringe|&thorn;e boon into his propre plite /</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e greuousnes of &thorn;e rigboon whanne he is out|of ioyncte /</HEAD>
<P>Dislocacioun of &thorn;e rigboonys is a greuous sijknes.  It is aforseid|in anathomia how manie boonys ben in &thorn;e necke &amp; in &thorn;e rig.|&amp; it is aforseid in what maner / The firste boon in a mannes necke|is bounden with manye feble ligaturis, &amp; &thorn;e ligaturis &thorn;erof ben|recching<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: hec ligatura fuit magis aliis laxa.</NOTE> &amp; feble, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne schulde lette &thorn;e meuynge of &thorn;e heed /|&THORN;e boonys &thorn;at ben in a mannes necke be&thorn; more feble &thorn;an ony o&thorn;er|rigboonys, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei goi&thorn; li&yogh;tly out of &thorn;e ioynte, &amp; it is ful|greet drede &thorn;erof / If &thorn;e hi&yogh;este boon of &thorn;e necke be oute of &thorn;e|ioynct, it is clepid decollacio, &amp; it slee&thorn; a man anoon; for &thorn;at o&thorn;er| boon &thorn;erof pressi&thorn; yn &amp; stoppi&thorn; a mannes<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="236a"> bree&thorn; anoon, &amp; in &thorn;is|maner it slee&thorn; a man anoon / And if &thorn;e ioynct &thorn;at is bitwixe &thorn;e|vij. boon &amp; &thorn;e .viij. be out of ioyncte, &thorn;an it wole stoppe &thorn;e weie|of his mete, and it wole lette &thorn;e weie of a mannes bree&thorn; also / And|if ony boon of &thorn;e rigboon &thorn;at is bine&thorn;e &thorn;e .viij. boon be out of|ioyncte, but if he be &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere holpen, he schal lese his meuyng|for euermore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal., cap. 19.  Sl. 277, fol. 42 b.: "<I>And of &thorn;e spondiles of &thorn;e|brest, for lettynge brou&yogh;t in in &thorn;e lacertis &amp; muscules kyndely &amp; wilfully|meuynge &thorn;e brest, &thorn;e lunge is lettid in his meuynge, &amp; &thorn;er falli&thorn; hasty wynd|&amp; litel, &amp; vtterlyche de&thorn;.  Of &thorn;e dislocacion of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere spondiles, &thorn;at ben 4,|&thorn;er falle&thorn; ano&thorn;or greuaunce in &thorn;e reynes &amp; &thorn;e bladdre, &amp; ak&thorn;e in &thorn;oo|membris, &amp; peyne of pyssynge or lettynge of &thorn;e weyes of &thorn;e vryne, &amp; aposteme|in &thorn;e place, &amp; feuere, &amp; de&thorn;.</I>"</NOTE> / And &thorn;erfore it is necessarie as faste &thorn;at a mannes|rigboon is out of &thorn;e ioynct, &thorn;at it be brou&yogh;t yn a&yogh;en anoon, &amp;|principali &thorn;e firste boon of &thorn;e necke, for disiunccioun of &thorn;at boon|wole sle a man anoon, as it is forseid / If &thorn;ou be in &thorn;e place, take|&thorn;e patient bi &thorn;e heeris, &amp; sette &thorn;i feet vpon his schuldris, &amp; so &thorn;ou|schalt drawe vpward wi&thorn; &thorn;in hondis, &amp; presse adoun wi&thorn; &thorn;i feet, &amp;|bringe &thorn;e boon into his ioynct a&yogh;en / Whanne &thorn;e .vij. rigboon<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rig</I>, in margin.</NOTE> is|out of his ioynct fro &thorn;e .viij. rigboon, itt mai ful litil tyme lenger|abide.  &amp; if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;is boon be pressid swi&thorn;e ynward, it wole|sle a man hastily, &amp; it wole ful late be curid / If it so be &thorn;at it|mai be curid, &thorn;er is noon o&thorn;er cure &thorn;eron, but presse adoun his| schuldris <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="236b">&amp; drawe vp &thorn;e heed, as it is aforseid / If it so be &thorn;at|ony of &thorn;ese boonys be out of &thorn;e ioynct outward, &thorn;at falli&thorn; ful
<PB N="323">|seelde, &thorn;an sette &thorn;e boonys euene, &amp; drawe his heed &amp; presse adoun|hise schuldris / If it so be &thorn;at ony rigboon bine&thorn;e &thorn;e .viij. boon of|&thorn;e necke be out of ioyncte, if &thorn;e boon go ynward, it nile take no|cure til it sle him / And if it ne be not al out of &thorn;e ioyncte, but|it pressi&thorn; nucha, alle &thorn;e lymes bine&thorn;e schulen lese her meuynge / If|it so be &thorn;at &thorn;e boon be out of &thorn;e ioyncte &amp; go outward, it is incurable,|for he schal be euermore gibbosis, id est broken-riggid.  &THORN;is|is &thorn;e cure &thorn;erof, if it mai be curid / Arere vp &thorn;e boon &amp; presse it<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>pressid</I>.</NOTE>|als so miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond, ou&thorn;er presse it yn with a|playn tree, &amp; studie &thorn;ou in &thorn;i witt as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t for to|presse it in a&yogh;en; &amp; leie &thorn;ervpon oon of &thorn;e consolidatiuis, &amp; binde|it faste / If it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ere leeue ony hardnes after &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at|&thorn;e place is soudid, &thorn;an make an enplastre of mollificatiuis &thorn;erto, &thorn;at|&thorn;ou schalt fynde in &thorn;e antidotarie; &amp; anoynte him wi&thorn; oynementis,|&thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt fynde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="237a">in &thorn;e same place in &thorn;e chapiter of mollificatiuis/ |/</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="9">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e schuldre out of his place.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Paul. &AElig;gin</I>., Book VI, Sect. 114, ed. Adams, vol. II, p. 485.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>A Mannes schuldre mai go out of &thorn;e ioynct in .iij. maners /|Oon maner is &thorn;is, whanne &thorn;e heed of &thorn;e boon of adiutorie,|&thorn;at is &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e schuldre, falli&thorn; adoun vndir &thorn;e arme-pitt; &amp;|sumtyme he goi&thorn; of &thorn;e ioynct for&thorn;ward, but &thorn;at falli&thorn; ful selden /|The .iij.: he goi&thorn; out of &thorn;e ioynct vpward; &amp; bakward he ne mai|not out of &thorn;e ioynct, for &thorn;e schuldre boon holdi&thorn; itt faste in.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gul. de Sal., Sl. 277, fol. 43 b.: "<I>For &thorn;e ofteste &thorn;e heued of &thorn;e adiutorie|is dislocate in &thorn;e schuldre toward &thorn;e place &thorn;at is called titillicum to &thorn;e|for-party, &amp; to &thorn;e hynder party anentis &thorn;e spawde-boon, it is dislocate in no|maner.</I>"</NOTE>|&para; The .j. maner &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t li&yogh;tliche knowe bi touching &amp; bi si&yogh;t, &amp;|&thorn;ou schalt fele &thorn;e boon in his arme-pitt, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ere wole be a greet|pitt aboue.  &para; If he be out of the ioynct for&thorn;ward, &thorn;an his arme|wole sitte bacward, &amp; tofore &thorn;ou schalt se a greet pitt / &para; If he be|out of &thorn;e ioynct vpward, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt knowe in &thorn;is maner: his|elbowe ne mai not be drawe along fro his body.  &amp; if &thorn;ou wolt|drawe him along, &thorn;ou schalt fynde an obstacle / The .j. maner if it|be a child, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt take his arme wi&thorn; &thorn;i lifthond, &amp; sette &thorn;i|ri&yogh;thond vndir his <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="237b">arme-pitt, &amp; drawe his arme wi&thorn; &thorn;i lifthond, &amp; |presse &thorn;e boon into his ioynct wi&thorn; &thorn;i ri&yogh;thond; &amp; in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou|schalt bringe in &thorn;e boon of a child wel ynow.  &para; If it be a miche
<PB N="324">|man, lete him ligge adoun strei&yogh;t, &amp; take a round bal of tree, &amp;|folde him wi&thorn; a cloo&thorn;, &amp; leie it vnder his arme-pitt, &amp; binde him|&thorn;ere faste, &amp; take his hond &amp; drawe it adounward, ou&thorn;er lete|ano&thorn;er man drawe it adounward, &amp; helpe &thorn;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;in hond for to|bring yn &thorn;e boon, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt presse, &amp; &thorn;e man drawe al in|oon tyme / If it ne mai not be doon in &thorn;is maner, &thorn;an ordeine a|long perche, &amp; make it fast in .ij. wallis of &thorn;e hous, ou&thorn;er .ij. postis|of &thorn;e hous; &amp; in &thorn;e middil of &thorn;e perche make a pitt, &amp; in &thorn;e same|pitt leie &thorn;e forseid bal, &amp; &thorn;e hi&yogh;nes of &thorn;is perche schal be hi&yogh;er &thorn;an|a man is long, &amp; &thorn;an sette vndir his feet a stool.  &amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;e|same bal sitte vndir his arme, &amp; lete a strong man holde doun his|arme and his hond, &amp; take awei &thorn;e stool vndir his feet, &amp; in &thorn;is|maner &thorn;e boon wole come into his ioynct / &para; If it be out of &thorn;e|ioynct for&thorn;ward, &thorn;an take a strong towail, &amp; leie him vndir his| arme, &amp; lete &thorn;e oon ende go for&thorn; bihinde his rigge, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="238a">&amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er ende|for&thorn; bi his brest, &amp; lete a strong man holde &thorn;e .ij. endis of &thorn;e|towail, &amp; &thorn;an binde his arme wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er boond aboue &thorn;e elbowe;|&amp; take it ano&thorn;er strong man, &amp; lete &thorn;ese .ij. men holde &amp; drawe al|at oonys; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt with &thorn;i .ij. hondis, whanne &thorn;ei drawi&thorn;,|presse &thorn;e boon into his ioynct / Whanne &thorn;e boon is in his ioynct,|&thorn;an &thorn;ei schulen leeue her drawyng softly.  &para; In &thorn;e same maner,|whanne he is oute of ioyncte vpward, he schal be bounden, &amp; oon|man schal drawe him abacward wi&thorn; &thorn;e towal, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er man schal|drawe his arme adounward, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt helpe for to presse yn &thorn;e|boon wi&thorn; &thorn;in hondis.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e boon is in his ioynct, &thorn;an wete|a pece of lynnen cloo&thorn; in oile of rosis, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ervpon leie a|medicyne consolidatif, &amp; &thorn;an leie &thorn;ervpon faldellas wet in gleire|of eiren, &amp; binde him faste with boondis &thorn;at his arme ne mowe not|out of &thorn;e ioynct a&yogh;en, &amp; so he schal be bounden .x. daies.  And if|&thorn;er come ony enpostym or icching, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste vnbinde him|a&yogh;en, &amp; do awei &thorn;e icching ou&thorn;er &thorn;e enpostym, and binde it a&yogh;en| as it is forseid.  &para; If it so be &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="238b">&thorn;ou ne were not at &thorn;e firste|bigynnyng, &thorn;an &thorn;ou muste make &thorn;e patient a ba&thorn; of malue &amp;|bismalue, fenigrec, lynseed.  &amp; whanne he is wel ba&thorn;id in &thorn;is ba&thorn;,|&thorn;an anoynte him wi&thorn; an oynement laxatif.  &amp; in &thorn;is maner he|muste be ba&thorn;id manie daies til &thorn;e place be wel moistid; &amp; &thorn;an|bringe &thorn;e boon into his ioynct, as it is forseid.  &para; If it so be &thorn;at|&thorn;ou come at &thorn;e firste bigynnyng, whanne a boon is out of &thorn;e|ioynct, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt not ba&thorn;e &thorn;e lyme in hoot water in no|maner.</P>
<P>
<PB N="325">&para; A mannes arme wole out of &thorn;e ioynct li&yogh;tlich at &thorn;e elbowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Original says just the contrary: difficile dislocatur, et ita difficile|restauratur.  The translator further leaves out a passage similar to the|following one, quoted from the Engl. translation of Gul. de Salic.: "<I>The|dislocacioun or restorynge of &thorn;is place is ry&yogh;t dredeful, for &thorn;e makynge of it.|For whi, &thorn;er ben smale boones &amp; havynge schapp of a rolle or polyne, to|drawe with water of wellis, whiche sumtyme, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; difficulte, or in no|manere ben restorid.</I>"</NOTE>|&amp; li&yogh;tly it wole be brou&yogh;t into his ioynct a&yogh;en / But he mai be out|of &thorn;e ioynct in .ij. maners, as for&thorn;ward &amp; hindeward, &amp; bo&thorn;e haue&thorn;|diuers cure / In &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt do whanne he is out of &thorn;e|ioynct for&thorn;ward: sette stupis in &thorn;e folding of his arme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: in curvatura vbi brachium plicari solebat.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;an|binde a boond &thorn;ervpon, &amp; lete a man drawe &thorn;at boond bakward|&mdash; &mdash;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 98: "&amp; fac quod minister trahat stupham seu bindam|ad posteriora firmiter et suaviter: et tu manum quam errexeras, plica violenter:|vt oppositum tangat pluries humerum: quoniam tunc sine dubio|est reducta.  Si vero fuerit ad posteriora, fac quod fortis minister teneat|adiutorium. et. cet."</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;an lete a strong man holde adiutorium, lest his schuldre|go out of &thorn;e ioynct.  &amp; &thorn;an anoynte &thorn;in hond wi&thorn; oile of rosis, &amp;|lete &thorn;e ij. men drawe al at oon tyme, &amp; &thorn;an presse yn &thorn;e boon into|his ioynct wi&thorn; &thorn;i .ij. <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="239a">hondis, &amp; &thorn;an hange an heuy peis at his |hond.  &amp; if &thorn;er leeue&thorn; ony greet &thorn;ing, lete it be til ano&thorn;er tyme.|&amp; &thorn;an anoynte &thorn;in hond &amp; presse it in a&yogh;en, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt|binde him with boondis &amp; faldellis, &amp; oile of rosis &amp; consolidatiuis,|as it is aforseid / But of &thorn;is caas &thorn;ou muste be war: but if his|arme be brou&yogh;t into &thorn;e ioinct hastili, &thorn;ere wole engendre in &thorn;e place|an hoot enpostym, &amp; &thorn;an aftirward it wole be ful hard to bringe it|into his ioynct a&yogh;en.</P>
<P>&para; Rasceta, &thorn;at is &thorn;e ioynct of &thorn;e hand / as it is forseid in|anathamia, is conteyned of manie boonys &amp; of manie recchinge|ligaturis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: multis ossibus composita et ligamentis pluribus tamen laxis|coniuncta.</NOTE> as it was necessarie for &thorn;e grete meuyng of &thorn;e hond.  &THORN;is|place wole li&yogh;tly out of &thorn;e ioinct, &amp; li&yogh;tli it wole come yn a&yogh;en.|&para; But if a mannes hond be out of &thorn;e ioyncte longe, &thorn;e place wole|enpostym, &amp; &thorn;an it wole be hard for to bringe it in a&yogh;en.  &para; In &thorn;e|firste bigynnyng take his arme wi&thorn; &thorn;i lifthond, &amp; sette &thorn;e boon into|&thorn;e ioynct as it is aforeseid, &amp; binde it in al maners as it is aforseid|in o&thorn;ere ioinctis.  &para; Also if a mannes fyngir be out of ioyncte,|it is but li&yogh;t for to putte it <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="239b">in a&yogh;en / In &thorn;e same maner &thorn;ou schalt |binde a mannes fyngir as it is aforseid in o&thorn;ere placis / Ther ben
<PB N="326">|manie men &thorn;at whanne a mannis lyme is out of ioynct, &thorn;ei wolen|sette &thorn;e lyme in hoot water, &amp; seien &thorn;at it wole &thorn;e better come into|his ioinct a&yogh;en / But &thorn;ou schalt wite &thorn;is, &thorn;at hoot watir in &thorn;e|firste bigynnyng maki&thorn; &thorn;e lyme recche, &amp; febli&thorn; it &amp; drawi&thorn; &thorn;erto|manye humours / &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou ne schalt do in &thorn;is maner, but &thorn;ou|schalt comforte &thorn;e lyme wi&thorn; oile of rosis, &amp; sette him into his ioinct|anoon, &amp; defende as miche as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, &thorn;at &thorn;ere come noon enpostym|&thorn;erto / But if it so be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne come not at &thorn;e firste|bigynnyng, &amp; &thorn;e place bicome hard, &thorn;an make him a fomentacioun|wi&thorn; a decoccioun of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at maki&thorn; moist &amp; resolue&thorn; as it is|aforseid /</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="10">
<HEAD>Of the haunche out of his place.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>Paul. &AElig;gin</I>., Book VI., Sect. 118, l. c., p. 498.  <I>Avicenna</I>,|Lib. IV., Fen. 5, Tract 1, Cap. 24.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Al &thorn;e coniunccioun of &thorn;e haunche is tofore seid in &thorn;e chapitre|of anathamia.  And &thorn;is place mai go out of &thorn;e ioinct in|.iiij. maners: as ynward &amp; outward, for&thorn;ward &amp; bacward; &amp; sumtyme|it come&thorn; of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, &amp; sumtyme of causis withoutfor&thorn;|/ <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="240a">Of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;: as humours of longe tyme haue falle| &thorn;erto, as it is aforseid in &thorn;e chapitre of dolour of ioinctis / Ther is|in &thorn;is place a greet box, &amp; conteine&thorn; a greet place, &thorn;at beri&thorn; al &thorn;e|bodi, &amp; it is a place &thorn;at takith miche moisture &amp; greet superfluite|of humouris, &amp; whanne &thorn;er falli&thorn; manie superfluitees to &thorn;at place,|&amp; &thorn;e pacient is not purgid &thorn;erof, &amp; traueili&thorn;, &thorn;an humours roti&thorn; in|&thorn;at place, &amp; &thorn;e ligaturis recchi&thorn; along, &amp; in &thorn;is maner vertebrum|goi&thorn; out of his ioinct / And &thorn;is caas in diuers men ha&thorn; diuers|causis / ffor summen haue&thorn; a box in her haunche swi&thorn;e holowe, &amp;|&thorn;at wole not fulli&yogh;tliche out of &thorn;e ioinct / And summen ne haue&thorn;|not so holowe boxis, &amp; &thorn;an if &thorn;e place be ful of yuele humours,|&thorn;an &thorn;e boon wole li&yogh;tliche out of &thorn;e ioincte, &amp; it wole li&yogh;tli into &thorn;e|ioinct a&yogh;en, &amp; &thorn;an it wole li&yogh;tly out a&yogh;en.  &para; Of causis wi&thorn;outfor&thorn;,|as of wrastyng or of smityng or of sum o&thorn;er &thorn;ing &thorn;at maki&thorn; vertebrum|goon out of &thorn;e ioynct wi&thorn; violence.  &para; This is &thorn;e signe|whanne it is out of ioyncte ynward: whanne &thorn;ou my&yogh;t fele &thorn;e| poynt of &thorn;e boon in his flank, &amp; his feet <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="240b">&amp; his knee turned outward,|&amp; &thorn;e pacient schal not opene his leg ne his hipe // If it goi&thorn;|out of &thorn;e ioynct for&thorn;ward, &thorn;an his leg wole wexe miche schorter, &amp;|he schal not bringe his hele to grounde, but oonly his toos.  &para; If
<PB N="327">|it be out of &thorn;e ioynct bacward, &thorn;an his hele wole wexe long, &amp; his|toos schorte, &amp; he schal bringe no &thorn;ing of his foot to grou[n]de,|but his hele //</P>
<P>Ther ben manie maners of diuers menys for to bringe boonys|into her ioynct a&yogh;en, but among alle I holde &thorn;is maner &thorn;e beste for|&thorn;is place: take a long schete &thorn;at be not brood, &amp; do bitwixe &thorn;e|patient leggis, &amp; lete &thorn;at oon ende go bifore his brest, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er|bihinde his rig, &amp; make &thorn;e .ij. endis fast to a post, &amp; &thorn;e patient|schal ligge vpon a plain place, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt binde al his hipe aboue|his knee, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e leg softly adounward, &amp; to alle &thorn;ese boondis|make faste a corde, &amp; lete &thorn;e moost fastenyng be in &thorn;e hipe aboue|&thorn;e knee, &amp; &thorn;an lete oon strong man or ij. drawe &thorn;e corde euenlich|&amp; harde withoute ony pluching.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: non duetu violenti nec tractu.</NOTE>  &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; &thorn;in hondis|putte &thorn;e boon into his ioyncte.  &amp; whanne &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="241a">boon is ynne, &thorn;an |bidde hem lete go &thorn;e corde softli a&yogh;en, &amp; leie hise feet euene togidere.|for if hise feet wollen ligge euene togidere, it is a certein signe &thorn;at|&thorn;e boon is in his ioynct. &amp; if hise feet wolen not sitte euene in &thorn;e|ioynct, it is a signe &thorn;at &thorn;e boon is not in his ioynct / whanne &thorn;e|boon is in his ioinct, binde faste his hipe, &amp; lete &thorn;e patient ligge|stille til he be al restorid / In alle curis of dislocacioun &thorn;ou hast|pleiner teching.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 26,106, fol. 99: In omnibus aliis curam consequentibus est in|precedentibus bene doctus.</NOTE></P>
<P>&para; Dislocacioun of &thorn;is place &thorn;at come&thorn; of causis wi&thorn;innefor&thorn;, it|is ful hard for to bringe it in a&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e boon be brou&yogh;t in|a&yogh;en, wi&thorn; a litil cause it wole goon out a&yogh;en.  &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;er is no|cure &thorn;erof, but avoide his bodi, &amp; make him cauterijs as it is aforseid|in &thorn;e chapitre of cauterijs.</P>
<P>&para; A mannys knee is sumtyme out of ioyncte, &amp; sumtyme &thorn;e|round boon &thorn;at is &thorn;ervpon goi&thorn; out of his place / Signys whanne|a mannes knee is out of ioyncte ben open ynow&yogh;.  &amp; if &thorn;e round|boon be out of his place, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;te li&yogh;tlich knowe it.  &para; In &thorn;is|maner &thorn;ou schalt bringe a mannes knee into his ioynct a&yogh;en / Lete|a strong man holde faste his hipe, and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="241b">ano&thorn;er man his leg.  &amp; &thorn;ou |schalt wi&thorn; &thorn;in hondis presse faste &thorn;e boon into his propre place.  &amp;|if &thorn;e place be enpostymed, first &thorn;ou muste do awei &thorn;e enpostym, &amp;|&thorn;an bringe &thorn;e knee into his place a&yogh;en.  &para; If &thorn;e round boon be out|of his place, sette &thorn;e boon into his place, &amp; &thorn;an binde faste wi&thorn;|boondis, &amp; &thorn;an binde his leg faste vp to his hipe bi an hour, &amp; &thorn;an
<PB N="328">|vnbinde his leg fro his hipe, &amp; &thorn;an binde faste &thorn;e round boon &thorn;at|it ne moue not fro his propre place, &amp; in &thorn;at maner lete it sitte,|for it wole bicome fast anoon.</P>
<P>&para; If &thorn;e ioynct of a mannes foot be out of ioyncte or his toos,|&thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;e cure in &thorn;e same maner as it is aforseid in &thorn;e hond|&amp; in &thorn;e fyngris.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. repeats this sentence.</NOTE>  &para; &THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e help of god wi&thorn;out which is no &thorn;ing|fulfillid, &thorn;e .iiij. tretis is fulfillid.  &para; Now I wole bigynne &thorn;e .v.|tretis &thorn;at schal be clepid &thorn;e antidotarie of this book. //</P>
<P>In &thorn;e fif&thorn;e tretis clepid &thorn;e antidotarie of &thorn;is book, I &thorn;inke to| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="242a">putte medicyns bo&thorn;e symple &amp; compound / &thorn;at falli&thorn; for|cirurgie &amp; be&thorn; necessarie &thorn;erfore / But I ne mai not sette alle, for|&thorn;er is no man &thorn;at can telle alle &thorn;e noumbre of medicyns but oonli|god / Ne&thorn;eles I wole sette medicyns in &thorn;is antidotarie &thorn;at I haue|longe vsid, &amp; I lernede hem of wise doctouris &amp; of philosophoris,|&amp; alle &thorn;ei ben aproued /</P>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="book" N="5">
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<HEAD>Here bigynne&thorn; &thorn;e tretise of repercussiuis //</HEAD>
<P>Repercussiuis bifalli&thorn; for hoot apostymes, &amp; principal whanne|it bigynne&thorn; in a noble lyme: as in &thorn;e herte, ou&thorn;ir in &thorn;e|brayn, ou&thorn;ir in &thorn;e heed, ou&thorn;ir in &thorn;e lyuere, &thorn;e splen &amp; &thorn;e|stomac, reynes, ballokis, &amp; in &thorn;e bladdre // It schal alwei be &thorn;in|entencioun for to putte awei greuous mater fro a noble lyme into|ano&thorn;er place.  &para; Whanne &thorn;ou wolt worche wi&thorn; repercussiuis, &thorn;ou|muste take hede to .x. condiciouns &thorn;at ben sett in &thorn;e iij. tretis in &thorn;e|general chapitre of enpostyms / &para; Repercussif is seid in .ij. maners:|as large &amp; streit<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>large &amp; streit</I>.  See p. 305, note 1.</NOTE> / large is seid: as eueri medicyne maad of coold| herbis for to aquenche hoot <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="242b">causis.  Streit is seid, whanne it putt|awei &thorn;e mater &amp; is not swi&thorn;e coold // Of repercussiuis &thorn;ere ben|manie degrees of cooldnes / Ther ben summe so coold, &thorn;at a man|mai not fele his lyme, &amp; &thorn;an it is clepid stupefactiua<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vigon transl. <I>Traheron Interpr.: "Stupefactyve</I>.  That, that hathe|strengthe to astonie, and take awaye felynge."</NOTE> / &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ou|schalt vse whanne &thorn;er is &thorn;ing &thorn;at greue&thorn; more &thorn;an &thorn;e mater.|&para; Whanne &thorn;ou ne dredist not hoot qualite oonli, but &thorn;ou dredist|&thorn;e mater, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt vse medicyns &thorn;at ben coold &amp; drie, &thorn;at|&thorn;ei mowe tempere &thorn;e complexioun of &thorn;e lyme, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;e vertu of|stiptica &thorn;ei wolen comforte &thorn;e lyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: et sua stipticitate uirtutem membri confortent.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ese ben propirli clepid|repercussiuis / Whanne &thorn;ou hast entencioun oonly for to make
<PB N="329">|coold, &thorn;an it is no force &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;i medicyn be not stiptica / But|whanne &thorn;ou wolt make ony repercussiuis, it is necessarie &thorn;at &thorn;ei|be coold &amp; drie.  &para; Medicyns &thorn;at ben coold &amp; repercussiuis, summe|ben simple &amp; summe ben compound / Of simple medicyns, summe|ben of herbis, &amp; summe ben of trees, &amp; summe ben leeues, &amp;|summe ben rotis, &amp; summe ben seedis, &amp; summe ben flouris, &amp;|summe ben greynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">The translator misunderstood the Lat. genera mineralium.</NOTE> of minerals, &amp; summe ben watris, &amp; summe|ben oilis.  And summe &thorn;erof I wole sette in &thorn;ese bokis &thorn;at ben|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="243a">greetli in vss toward us / And &thorn;ere ben medicyns coold &amp; moist |&thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t vse for to atempere &thorn;e complexioun of lymes &thorn;at ben|distemp[er]id in hete &amp; drienes.  &para; Malua, capillus<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>capillis</I>.</NOTE> veneris, psillium,|portulaca, atriplex.  Mercurialis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15,236, fol. 4 b.: "<I>Linochites, mercurialis, idem. G. mercuria,|A. smerewourth.</I>"  Compare <I>Alphita</I>, p. 116: "<I>linozostis g</I><SUP>e</SUP><I>. mercurie. a</I><SUP>e</SUP><I>.|scandany.</I>"</NOTE> Rapa, cucurbita, Melones,|Citruli,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Phillips, "<I>Citrull</I>, a sort of Cucumber or Pumpkin of a Citron-Colour."</NOTE> Semen malue, seminis iiijor. frigidorum, Semper viua, lactuca|ortulana.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Halle, <I>Table</I>, p. 57: "Lactuca satiua, or Hortensis, &thorn;at is gardin letuce."</NOTE>  &para; Iusquiamus, Mandragora, Papauere, argentum viuum,|f. &amp; h. in iiij.<NOTE PLACE="foot">frigidum et humidum in quarto gradu.</NOTE>  &para; Oilis coold &amp; moist: Oleum violacium, Oleum|nenupharinum,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nenupharinum</I>, Arab. Pers. n&imacr;tufar, n&imacr;n&umacr;far (Littr&eacute;).  Nymph&AElig;a alba.|Add. 15,236, fol. 5 b.: "<I>Nenufar .i. flos vngule, caballine aquatice A. waterlilye.</I>"|Compare <I>Alphita</I>, p. 124; <I>Barth. Sinon</I>., p. 31.</NOTE> Oleum de lilijs albis, Oleum mirtinum.  Istis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>istius</I>.</NOTE>|medicinis potest vti quum intendis infrigidare sine expulcione ut|dictum est // &thorn;ese medicyns &thorn;ou mi&yogh;tist vse whanne &thorn;ou entendist|for to make coold wi&thorn;outen expulcioun of &thorn;e mater as it is forseid.|&para; Medicyns &thorn;at ben symple coold &amp; drie, &thorn;at ben clepid verry|repercussiuis ben &thorn;ese / Solatrum, crassula maior &amp; minor,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15,236, lf. 11: "<I>Crassula maior G. crassegeline vel orpine.|Crassula minor .G. terce de soris .A. stoncrop.</I>"</NOTE> virga|pastoris / vmbilicus veneris, cicorea, Endiua, Gramen, Epatica,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15,236.  Cf. 3 <I>b</I>.: <I>Epatica .G. coper .A. liuerwort.</I>"  Ibid. lf.|11: "<I>Epatica .G. epatik vel coper .A. liurewort.</I>"</NOTE>|Ipoquistidos, veruene, Semper viua, Corigiola,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15,236, lf. 3 <I>b</I>.: <I>Corigiola.  Centinodia. lingua passerina. G.|Coriogiole.</I>"  Halle, <I>Table</I>, p. 29: "<I>Corrigiola</I>.  So called of the Apothe-caries,|and of the Frenche men Corrigiole, is oure common Knottgrasse,|called in Greke polygonon, in Latine Seminalis and Polygonum mas."</NOTE> Sanguinaria, Edera,|Acetosa, Scariola, plantago maior &amp; minor, Nenuphar.  De granis
<PB N="330">| seminibus, fructibus.  Ordeum, Silligo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Silligo</I>, a kind of very white wheat.</NOTE>; auena.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="243b">Spica,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Spata, Spleta.</I>  Lat.: Add. 26,106, fol. 109, "<I>spaca</I>"; ed. 1498,|fol, 207, "<I>spica</I>."  The preceding words show that <I>spica</I> is the correct reading.</NOTE> Lollium,|ffabe, Mirtilli, Berberis, Sumac, Pira, Poma, Sorbe, mespila, Castanea,|Glandes, Galle, Maiorana, Mora matura, vua acerba, Capreoli,|vitis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Capreoli vitis</I>, the tendrils of vine.</NOTE>  &para; De floribus folijs &amp; corticibus / Balaustie cortices,|Cortices mali granata, Cortices arborum stipticorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>stipticoris</I>.</NOTE>; Rosa, Nenufar,|fflos spine, ffolia pirorum, pomorum, sorborum, rubij, &amp; spine.|&para; ffolia / Salicis, Populi, Tremuli, Papiri, Canne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>panne</I>.</NOTE>  &para; De linis.|omnes sandali.  &para; De mineralibus &amp; lutis / Saphirus, Bolus armenicus,|Marmor, Alabaustrum,<NOTE PLACE="foot">med. Lat. alabaustrum.</NOTE> Cathinia, Litargirum, munda<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: murga uel merda.</NOTE> ferri,|Ematistes, Corallus, antimonium.  &para; De lutis.  Terra sigillata,|Argilla, lutum<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>litum</I>.</NOTE> omne, cimolea,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cimolea</I>, a kind of earth, so called after Cimolus, an island in the Cretan|sea, where it is found.</NOTE> Camfora, Cerusa.  De gummis.|Gumma pruni,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Summa pruna</I>.</NOTE> cerase, amigdale, Acacia, opium.  De olijs.  Oleum|rosarum, &amp; eueri oile &thorn;at is maad of coold &thorn;ingis &amp; drie, of flouris,|leeues, &amp; ryndis &thorn;erof / Also watir of rosis, &amp; water &thorn;at is maad|of alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben coold &amp; drie, and distillid<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: omnis aqua ex rebus siccis et frigidis distillata.</NOTE> / If &thorn;ou be|sent after into a cuntre, &thorn;ere ben noon apotecarijs, &thorn;an if &thorn;ou canst|make &thorn;ese medicyns &thorn;at ben forseid &amp; medicyns &thorn;at schulen be|seid heraftir, &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t fulfille &thorn;i purpos<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: de quo tuum poteris propositum adimplere.</NOTE> &amp; do &thorn;i cure. &THORN;ou| mi&yogh;t make <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="244a">of &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis: oynementis, epithima, cathaplasmata,|emplastra, enbrocaciouns, pultes, encatismata.  Of &thorn;ese names manie|men takith oon for ano&thorn;er, &amp; &thorn;erfore I wole telle &thorn;e diuersite of|alle.  &para; vnguentum is maad of .iiij. <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> of oile &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>. of wex in|winter, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j. in somer, &amp; <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> j. of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at &thorn;in oynement schal|serue &thorn;erfore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">et <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .i. pulueris rerum puluerizandarum, que ponuntur in unguento.</NOTE> and oynementis schulen be algatis colid.  &para; Epithima|is &thorn;is, whanne &thorn;ingis ben sotilli poudrid &amp; temperid wi&thorn; water of|roses, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; vinegre, ou&thorn;er iuys of ony herbe, so &thorn;at it be|temperid in &thorn;e &thorn;iknes of hony &amp; leid vpon &thorn;e place, &amp; hilid wi&thorn;|lynnen cloo&thorn;, ou&thorn;er wi&thorn; le&thorn;er, &thorn;is is clepid epithimum.  &para; Cataplasma|is, whanne herbis ben grounde &amp; soden ou&thorn;er raw, &amp; al &thorn;e|substaunce of &thorn;e herbe &thorn;erwi&thorn; &amp; medlid wi&thorn; mele &amp; grese, &amp; it ne|schal not be hard ne neische, but in &thorn;e meene, &amp; it schal be leid
<PB N="331">|flasch hoot vpon &thorn;e lyme.  &para; Emplastrum is seide, whanne manie|diuers &thorn;ingis, as poudris and gummis &amp; fatnessis, wex, talow, &amp;|oile ben soden togidere til &thorn;ei bicome hard, &amp; maad in gobetis &amp;|kept.  &amp; &thorn;an it schal be maad abrood vpon le&thorn;ir, &amp; leid vpon &thorn;e|place &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="244b">haue it: as diaculon, apostolicon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See p. 125, note 3.</NOTE> oxirocroceum,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oxirocroceum</I>.  Lat. oxiracroceum.  Matth. Sylv.: "oxirocroceum, i.|emplastrum compositum ex aceto et croco."</NOTE> |&amp; o&thorn;ere manie.  &para; Pultes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pultes</I>, Lat. plur. of puls, tis.  This plur. form used as sing.: Add. 10,440,|fol. 23: "<I>be &thorn;er so&thorn;en a &thorn;inne pultes or gruel of barly.</I>"  Compare the plur.|form <I>pultesses</I>, Gasc. Steel Glas 997 (Skeat, <I>Et. Dict</I>.).  For <I>poultice</I>, see|Ital. pultaceo.</NOTE> &amp; cathaplasma ben al oon, but propirli|pultes ben clepid, whanne &thorn;er is mele, watir, &amp; oile wi&thorn;outen|herbis, &amp; it schal be clepid cataplasma, whanne herbis ben medlid|&thorn;erwi&thorn;.  &para; Embroca[tio] is seid, whanne a mannes lyme is putt in|hoot watir, wi&thorn;outen ony decoccioun of herbis &thorn;eron, &amp; &thorn;at hoot|watir schal be cast vpon &thorn;e lyme from an hi&yogh;, &amp; so it schal be do|longe, &amp; &thorn;is is clepid embrocare.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>embroche</I>, Traheron Vigo Interpret.: "Embroche commeth of embrocho,|whyche signifyeth to raine.  And it is an embrocation, when we drop downe|liquour from a hyer place, vpon some parte of the bodye, and vpon the|head."  See p. 339, note 1.</NOTE>  &para; Encatisma is seid in .ij.|maners: sumtyme it is seid for a clisterie, &amp; sumtyme for a particuler|[ba&thorn;],6 anoon to &thorn;e nauele &amp; non aboue &thorn;e nauel /</P>
<P>&para; Medicyns &thorn;at ben compound togidere: Whanne &thorn;ou entendist|for to make a lyme coold, &amp; not putte awei &thorn;e mater, &thorn;ou schalt|take iuys of herbis &thorn;at ben coold &thorn;re partis, olei rosis oon part,|of vinegre half a part, &amp; medle hem togidere.  If &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt|&thorn;at it worche more strongely, &thorn;an do &thorn;erto argillam rubeam / til it|be as &thorn;icke as it were epithima, &amp; leie it to &thorn;e place.  &amp; herof &thorn;ou|must take kepe, &thorn;ou schalt vse &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben able for a mannes|complexioun / In &thorn;is maner if &thorn;ou leist coold &thorn;ingis to a place, <NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: dicitur enim clistere, aliquando dicitur particularis balneatio.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="245a">&amp; |ne hast not &thorn;i purpos &thorn;erof, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt leeue &thorn;e coold medicyns,|&amp; make medicyns &thorn;at ben competent to &thorn;e same complexioun / for|sum medicyne is for peter &thorn;at is not good for poul, for &thorn;e diuersite|of complexioun.  &amp; al &thorn;is teching &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t fynde generalich in &thorn;e|tretis of enpostyms. / ffor if peter be of complexioun hoot &amp; moist,|&amp; poulis complexioun be coold &amp; drie, oon repercussioun wole not|serue hem bo&thorn;e in oon point.  &amp; for &thorn;is cause &thorn;ou muste diuerse &thorn;i|medicyns; for &thorn;is is al dai preued bi experiment as &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t se|ofte tyme, &thorn;at crassula maior is a good repercussif for coold mater,
<PB N="332">|&amp; vmbilicus veneris is coold in &thorn;e same degre, &amp; &yogh;itt it is not so|good repercussif for &thorn;e same mater /</P>
<P>This is a good medicyn repercussif &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;er is miche discracia|hoot &amp; litil mater / &rx;, sandali albi, spodij, acacie, ana .&yogh;. ij,|camphore .&yogh;. j., opij .&yogh;. <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, distempere hem wi&thorn; &thorn;e iuys of a coold|herbe, &amp; oile of violet, &amp; a litil vinegre / Item ano&thorn;er. &rx;, ossa|sicca &amp; combusta, cerusam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ceresaris</I>.  Add. 15,236, lf. 3: "<I>Cerusa. flos plumbi id. G. blonc|plome A. wyt lede</I>."</NOTE> amidum, ana .&yogh;. ij., tempere hem as it|is forseid / Item ano&thorn;er &thorn;at is comoun &thorn;at is recordid in manie|placis.  &rx;, boli armenici .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., olei ros. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iij., aceti .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j., &thorn;at is &thorn;at| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="245b">defensif &thorn;at is aforeseid in manie placis for to kepe a lyme fro corrupcion.|&para; Also enplastris &amp; epithima, &thorn;at ben forseid in doloribus|iuncturarum of hoot cause ben good.  &THORN;erfore ioyne hem wi&thorn; &thorn;ese.|&para; Herof &thorn;ou muste be war, &thorn;at whanne &thorn;ou leist repercussiuis to a|place, &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;er is miche mater, &amp; if &thorn;e place bicome ledi, &thorn;an|&thorn;ou schalt contynue nomore wi&thorn; pure coold &thorn;ingis; but do &thorn;erto|iuys of coriandre grene &amp; barli mele, for &thorn;is maki&thorn; coold &amp; resolue&thorn;.|&para; If &thorn;er be no ledi colour but &thorn;e mater is greet, &amp; nyle not be|doon awei wi&thorn; repercussiuis, whanne &thorn;e flux of humours is acesid,|&thorn;an biginne for to medle &thorn;erwi&thorn; resolutiuis; &yogh;itt &thorn;ou schalt contynue|wi&thorn; repercussiuis &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;er is greet akynge / an ensaumple|hereof / If &thorn;e akinge be in a mannes knee, &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt first|leie medicyns vpon &thorn;e knee, &amp; &thorn;an aftirward &thorn;ou schalt not leie it|ri&yogh;t vpon his knee, but a litil aboue his knee, &thorn;at &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e|medicyn mowe touche &thorn;e firste parti of &thorn;e akynge.</P>
<P>&para; Coold mater as it is aforseid, ne schal not be putt awei wi&thorn;| repercussiuis, but wi&thorn; medicyns &thorn;at ben hoot and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="246a">drie in tempere,|&thorn;at &thorn;ei mowe wi&thorn; her heete chaunge &thorn;e coold complexioun, &amp;|wi&thorn; her dreines comforte &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e lyme, &amp; defende &thorn;at &thorn;er|come no more mater to &thorn;e lyme, &amp; if &thorn;e mater be litil, putte it|awei, &amp; if &thorn;ou ne wolt not putte it awei, defende &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;er|falle nomore mater &thorn;erto<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: "materia ne ad membrum veniat prohibetur et etiam plerumque|repellitur si sit pauca, sed etsi non omnino repellitur tamen locum ita|deffendit, quod tanta non potest in ipso materia congregari."</NOTE> / And alle &thorn;ese ben hote wi&thorn; a maner|bittirnes: as absinthium, squinantum, abrotanum, polium, sticados,|centaurea maior &amp; minor,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add. 15,236, lf. 3: "<I>Centaurea. fol terre idem .G. centore .A. cristes|laddir</I>."  ? In Britten and Holland's English Plant-names <I>Centaury</I> is at|p. 96.  <I>E. P. N.</I>, p. 37: "eor&eth;-gealle."  These names refer to <I>Centaurea|minor</I>, see <I>Alphita</I>, p. 37.  Centaurea maior = narca vel gentiana.  <I>Ibid</I>.</NOTE> aristologia longa &amp; rotunda, mauribium,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mauribium</I>, Corp. Gl. M. 43: "<I>Marubium. biowryt vel hune</I>."  Wr.|W&uuml;. 136, 12 (XII. cent.), "<I>harhune</I>."  Add. 15,236, lf. 5: <I>Marubium prassium|idem. G. marole. A. horehune. vel horehound</I>."</NOTE>
<PB N="333">|mirta, mastix, lupini, oleum de masticis, &amp; de absinthio / Herof &thorn;ou|shalt take kepe: manie men seien, &amp; it wole li&yogh;tly be leeued of|lewid men, &amp; &thorn;at is yuel &thorn;ing for to leie a repercussif to ony mater|for to driue it awei, but it is bettir to drawe out &thorn;e mater wi&thorn;|enplastris, &amp; if &thorn;er come&thorn; out &thorn;erof miche quitture, &thorn;ei seien &thorn;at a|mannes bodi is wel purgid &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; schal be longe &thorn;e holer &thorn;erfore|/ And if &thorn;e mater be doon awei wi&thorn; repercussiuis &amp; &thorn;e enpostym|be defendid, &thorn;an if &thorn;e same man be sijk aftirward, &thorn;an men wolen|seie &thorn;at it was defaute in &thorn;e leche, for if &thorn;e enpostym hadde be|maad maturatif <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="246b">&amp; &thorn;e quitture drawe out, &thorn;an &thorn;e man hadde be |hool, &amp; alle &thorn;ese opiniouns ben false / And &thorn;ou schalt wite &thorn;is certeynli:|if &thorn;ou takist kepe of &thorn;e .x. consideraciouns &thorn;at ben forseid|in enpostyms, &amp; principali whanne his body is maad clene wi&thorn;|laxatiuis &thorn;at ben competent &thorn;erfore / It is bettir to putte awei &thorn;e|mater wi&thorn; comfortyng of &thorn;e lyme, &thorn;an lete &thorn;e mater conferme / for|if &thorn;ou kepist wel &thorn;e condiciouns &thorn;at ben aforseid, the mater mai be|putt awei, &amp; &thorn;e man schal not be peirid //</P>
