<DIV2 TYPE="book" N="1">
<PB N="7">
<HEAD>[SCIENCE OF CIRURGIE.] Addit. MS. Brit. Mus. 12,056.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="1">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<P>Now the Chapitelles of &thorn;is bok bu&thorn; y-ordeynde, y wyl fulfylle|my purpos, pursuynge every chapytell by ordere, &amp; confermynge|my wordys after &thorn;e Autorite of myn Autores, &amp; wi&thorn; experyment|&thorn;at y haue longe tyme y-vsyde with help of god.</P>
<P>Al thynge &thorn;at we wolde knowe, by on of &thorn;re maneres we mowe|knowe, o&thorn;ere by hys name ore by hys worchynge, o&thorn;ere by hys|verrey beynge schewynge propirte of hym selff.  In &thorn;is &thorn;re manere|we mowe knowe surgerie by expownynge of hys name; ffor syrugie|cometh of syros, &thorn;at ys a word of grew&yogh;, &amp; in englyssche syros ys|an hand, &amp; gyros grew&yogh;, &thorn;at ys worchynge an Englyssche; for &thorn;e ende|&amp; &thorn;e prophyte of surgerye ys* of hand wyrchynge.  Of &thorn;e Name|of a thynge Galyen seyth: he &thorn;at wyl knowe* so&thorn;fastnesse of a|thynge, besye hym no&yogh;t to knowe &thorn;e name <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="33b">of a thynge, bute &thorn;e |worchynge &amp; &thorn;e Effecte of &thorn;e same thynge; where fore he &thorn;at wyl|knowe surgerie ys, he mote vndirstonde, &thorn;at yt is a medycineal|sciense, whyche techi&thorn; vs to worche with handes in Mannes body, in
<PB N="8">|kuttynge ore opnynge &thorn;o partyes &thorn;at ben hol, &amp; in helynge &thorn;o that|ben tobroken o&thorn;ere kutte, as &thorn;ey were to fore, o&thorn;ere ellys as ny&yogh; as|a Man may, and al so in doynge aweye &thorn;at ys to myche above &thorn;e|schyn: as wertys, o&thorn;ere wennys, o&thorn;er flesch to hy&yogh;h.</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>&para; The secunde Chapitell of &thorn;e ffurste Tretys is of &thorn;e|qualites, maners and cunnynge of a surgien.</HEAD>
<P>Nedfful ys &thorn;at a surgien be of a Complexioun wel proporcyonede,|&amp; &thorn;at is complexioun be temperat.  Rasys sei&thorn;, whose face ys|nou&yogh;t semlye, ys inpossible to hauen gode maners; *&amp; Auicenne:|euyle maners* be&thorn; folwynge &thorn;e lyknesse of an yuele complexioun.|A surgien moste han handys wel schape, longe smale ffyngres, and|hys body nought quakynge, &amp; alle hys lymes able to fulfyllen gode|werkynges of hys soule.  He most ben of sotyl wytt, ffor alle &thorn;ynge|&thorn;at longyth to surgerye may nought wi&thorn; lettres ben wryten.  He|moste stodyen in alle &thorn;e partyes of naturell ffylosophye &amp; in logyk,|&thorn;at he mowe vndirstonde scriptures; in gramere, &thorn;at he speke congrulyche;|in art, &thorn;at techyth hym to preven ys proposiciones with|gode resoun; in retoryk, &thorn;at techith hym to speke semlyche; be he|non glotoun, non spowsbrekere, ne Envyous, ne no nygarde; be he| trewe, vmbelyche <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="34a">&amp; plesynglyche bere he hym-self to hys pacientis;|speke he non Rybaudye in &thorn;e seke mannys house, ne in &thorn;e seke
<PB N="9">|Mannes house gif non counseyle bote he be y-askyde, ne speke he with|non womman in no<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I> above the line.</NOTE> folye in &thorn;e seke Mannes howse, ne chyde nought|with &thorn;e seke Man ne with none of hys meyne; but curteslye speke|to &thorn;e syke man, &amp; in alle manere syknesse behote hym hele, &thorn;ow&yogh;|&thorn;ou be of hym dyspeyred; but neuere &thorn;e lattere seye to hys frendys,|&thorn;e cas as yt stant.  Loue he non harde curys, &amp; entyremete he|nought of &thorn;o &thorn;at be&thorn; in dyspeyre.  Pore men helpe he be hys myght,|&amp; of ryche men aske he gode rewarde.  Preyse he nought hymselff|with hys owne mouth, ne blame he nought scharplye o&thorn;ere lechys;|loue he alle lechys &amp; Clerkys, &amp; by hys myght make he non leche|hys enmye.  So clo&thorn;e he hym with vertues, &thorn;at of hym mowe|a-rysen gode fame &amp; name, &amp; &thorn;is techyth Etyk.  So lerne he ffysik,|&thorn;at he mowe with gode rulys hys Surgerye deffende, &amp; &thorn;at techith|ffysik.  Na&thorn;eles yt ys necessarye a surgien to knowe alle &thorn;e partyes|in eche sengle partye of a medycine, ffor &yogh;if a surgien knowe no&yogh;t|&thorn;e sciens of Elementis, whiche &thorn;at bu&thorn; furst Meverys of naturel|&thorn;ynges &amp; of dyuerse lymes, he may no&yogh;t knowe sciense of coniunctiounes,|&thorn;at ys to seye, medlynges &amp; complexiouns &thorn;at be&thorn;|necessarye to hys crafte.  A surgien most knowe &thorn;at alle bodyes|&thorn;at ben medlyde, &thorn;at ben vndire &thorn;e cercle of &thorn;e Mone, ben engendryd
<PB N="10">|of foure symple bodyes, here lyknesse eche in o&thorn;ere medlyng;|&thorn;at ys to sugge, fyr &amp; eyre, er&thorn;e &amp; water.  &THORN;ese elementys, ffor &thorn;e|outemast ende &amp; outemast contraryousite of here qualites, weren fer| drawen from bodily lyffe; but whanne here <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="34b">qualytes, &thorn;at is to|sugge manere of beyinge, comyn in to medlynge, so &thorn;at &thorn;e leste|partye of &thorn;at on entre in to &thorn;e leste partye of &thorn;at o&thorn;ere partye,|medlynge brekyth here contrariosite, &amp; &thorn;ere of comme a newe forme|&amp; a newe complexioun of &thorn;e medlynge of here substaunce.  Al so|&thorn;e medlynge of &thorn;e qualitees &amp; &thorn;e quantites ys fer drawyn from &thorn;e|contraryousite of &thorn;e same elementes, &amp; so complexioun is ny&yogh;h|brought to a mene, &amp; so &thorn;at &thorn;at ys medlyde ys more able to resseyuen|&thorn;e noble forme of lyff, &thorn;e whiche noblete aboffe alle bodyes y-medlyde|ys y-founden in Mannys spiryt.  But for &thorn;at &thorn;e qualites, &thorn;at with &thorn;o|bodyes of Elementes comyth in to Medlynge&mdash;&amp; yt ys vnpossible to|departe &thorn;o qualites from bodyes&mdash;ben foure: hot, colde, moyst, &amp;|drye, &amp; complexiouns ben by ham, yt ys necessarie to fynden in|bodyes &thorn;at ben medlyde, foure complexiouns; Complexioun ys|no&thorn;ynge ellys but a manere qualite medlyde in worchynge, &amp;|suffrynge of contrariose qualites &thorn;at bu&thorn; founden in Elementis, so|&thorn;at &thorn;e leste partye of eche elemente entre in to &thorn;e leste partye of &thorn;e|o&thorn;ere partye.  And for &thorn;at &thorn;ilke foure complexiouns: hot, colde,
<PB N="11">|moiste &amp; drye, sumtyme ben y-componyd, &thorn;at ys to sugge medlyde,|&thorn;ere comen of hem VIII, as hote &amp; drye, hote &amp; moist, colde &amp;|drye, colde &amp; moiste; ffoure of &thorn;ese ben symple, &amp; foure ben componyd.|And for &thorn;ilke VIII sumtyme ben with mater, sumtyme|withoute mater, &thorn;ere ben XVI; &amp; for &thorn;ilke XVI, after sum consideracioun|mowe ben naturell to sum Man, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="35a">&amp; to sum man vn |naturell, &thorn;ere mowe ben XXXII.  Nevere &thorn;e lattere amonge alle|&thorn;e complexiouns &thorn;at man may fynden, &thorn;at is componyd of dyuerse|qualites, &thorn;ere nys non so temperat as ys mannes complexioun;|havynge rewarde to mannes complexioun, alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynge ys*|clepyde colde, hote, moyste, o&thorn;ere drye.  Whanne &thorn;at a mete, o&thorn;ere|a medycine, hath y-suffryde kendlye hete &thorn;at ys in Man, &amp; hetyth|hym no&yogh;t &amp; colyth hym nau&yogh;t, ne drye&thorn; hym no&yogh;t, ne moysted hym|no&yogh;t, so &thorn;at mannes complexioun may no&yogh;t conseyven whe&thorn;er yt|colde hym, ore hete, dry&yogh;e, o&thorn;ere moyste, yt is clepyde temperat; &amp;|&thorn;ilke thynge we sigge is hot in &thorn;e firste degre, &thorn;at ys y-hatte of|kendlye hete, &thorn;at ys in oure bodyes &amp; hetyth oure bodyes withouten|grevaunce, &amp; &thorn;ilke we siggen be hote in &thorn;e secunde degre, whiche|&thorn;at ys y-hette of oure kendlye hete, so hetyth oure body, &thorn;at he ne|my&yogh;te hete vs namore withouten greuaunce; hot in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde degre:
<PB N="12">|&thorn;ilke we sigge to be hot in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde degre, whiche &thorn;at ys y-hatte of|kendlye hete, brynge&thorn; to oure bodye sencyble greuaunce; hot in &thorn;e|four&thorn; degre: and &thorn;ilke in &thorn;e four&thorn; gre &thorn;at is y-hat of kendly hete,|dystroye&thorn; &thorn;e body opynlyche; &amp; in &thorn;is same manere &yogh;e may knowe|degrees &thorn;at ben colde, &amp; y may preve in &thorn;is manere &thorn;at yt is|necessarye a surgyne to knowe complexiouns of bodyes, lymes, &amp; of|medycynes.  &para; Take two men &thorn;at ben off one age, &amp; lete hem ben|y-woundyde with a swerd o&thorn;ere a knyffe twarte offere &thorn;e arme, in| one oure &amp; in <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="35b">one place.  One of &thorn;o men ys of an hote complexioun|&amp; a moyste, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere of a colde &amp; a drye; &thorn;e comyne siggynge of|lewyde men ys, &thorn;at &thorn;ey scholde bo&thorn;e by helyde aftere o manere.|But resonable surgye wel y-proved, techith vs &thorn;at &thorn;ey ne schulle|no&yogh;t bo&thorn;e ben y-helyde aftere on manere; for he &thorn;at ha&thorn; an hot|complexioun &amp; a moyst, may ly&yogh;tliche haue an hote enposteme, &thorn;at|ys an hote swellynge, &amp; &thorn;at may be cause of an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an</I> above the line.</NOTE> hote ffevyre.  What|schaltou &thorn;anne do?  &THORN;ou moste loke whe&thorn;er he haue y-bled myche|blod at hys wounde, &amp; &thorn;enne it ys wel, ellys lete hym blod of &thorn;e|contraryose arme, o&thorn;ere ellys* on &thorn;e fot on &thorn;e same syde; &yogh;if streng&thorn;e|&amp; age acorde, o&thorn;ere ventuse hym on &thorn;e tweye buttokkys; gif &thorn;at he|be feble, &yogh;if he may no&yogh;t go to sege onys a day, helpe hym &thorn;ereto
<PB N="13">|o&thorn;ere wit clysterye, o&thorn;ere with suppositorye; &amp; brynge &thorn;ou &thorn;e|partyes of &thorn;e wounde to-gedire, o&thorn;ere with sowynge, o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; plumaciolus&mdash;&thorn;at|be&thorn; smale pelewys&mdash;o&thorn;ere with byndynge, &yogh;if &thorn;at|sowynge be no&yogh;t necessarie.  And &thorn;enne worche aboute &thorn;e wounde,|as it ys tolde aftere in &thorn;e boke; but aboue &thorn;e wounde leye a|Medycine defensiue, of bol Armonyac, oyle of rosys, &amp; a litel|vynegre, so &thorn;at &thorn;e medycine touche &thorn;e sydes of &thorn;e woundes, &thorn;at|humours mowe no&yogh;t hauen here cours to renne to &thorn;e wounde.  And|we forbyde hym wyn, Milke, &amp; eyren, &amp; fysch, &thorn;at engendrith|myche blod; but he schal ete for his Mete gruell y-made of ote|Mele, o&thorn;ere barly mele with Almaundes, &amp; generaliche he schal vsen a|streyt <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="36a">doynge, tyl &thorn;ou be sykere &thorn;at he schal haue non enposteme. |And &yogh;if &thorn;at we cunne dyffenden hym from a ffevyre &amp; aposteme, &thorn;e|science of hys complexioun techyth vs &thorn;at he may of hys seknesse|sone be hol.  &para; &THORN;e o&thorn;ere of &thorn;e colde complexioun ne schal no&yogh;t be|leten blod ne ventusyde, ffor blod scholde be kepte in hem as for|tresoure; forbyde hym nei&thorn;ere wyn ne flesch; for &thorn;e stomak &thorn;at ys|so feble, ne my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t engendre necessarie mater of blod &thorn;at|longyth to &thorn;e wounde; ne we dredyth no&yogh;t in hym &thorn;e ffevyre, for|his complexioun ys no&yogh;t able to resceyuen &thorn;e ffevyre.  We mowe
<PB N="14">|fynden a Medycine made in o manere &thorn;at wirchith dyuerse effectis,|&amp; he be y-leyde to dyuerse complexiouns.  Grene vytreole, &amp; he be|done to a Man of dry&yogh;e complexioun, engendrith flessch; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou|leggen hym on a moyste complexioun, he greuyth no&yogh;t onlyche, but|corodu&thorn; yt.  And na&thorn;eles vitreole ha&thorn; but one manere wyrchinge,|&thorn;ou&yogh; he wirche dyuerslyche in dyuerse complexiouns, ry&yogh;te as &thorn;e|wirchynge of &thorn;e sonne ys dyuerse&mdash;no&yogh;t for &thorn;e sonne, but for &thorn;e|wyrchynge of dyuerse bodyes in whom he wyrchyth.  Vitreole|drye&thorn; wonderlyche muche, &amp; in dry&yogh;e bodyes he fynde&thorn; &thorn;e smale|lymes myghty to ageyne stonden hys streng&thorn;e.  Wherefore he may|nought but drye &thorn;e superffluites &thorn;at he fynte in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wound</I>, cancelled because blotted after <I>in &thorn;e</I> and re-written.</NOTE> wounde; &amp;|whenne &thorn;o ben y-dreyede, kynde engendryth fflesch.  In moyste|bodyes, ffor &thorn;at &thorn;e smale lymes be&thorn; feble, &amp; mowe no&yogh;t withstande|&thorn;e strengthe off &thorn;e vytreole, &thorn;e flesch meltyth vndire yt, &amp; so be &thorn;e|vitreole &thorn;e flesch rotyth; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at ys seyde of dyuerse complexiouns,|ys y-seyde of dyverse lymes.  Galyen: &yogh;if &thorn;at tweye| woundes <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="36b">ben evyne i quyter, &amp; &thorn;e on be in a dry&yogh;e lyme, &amp; &thorn;e|o&thorn;ere in a moyste lyme, &thorn;at &thorn;at is in &thorn;e dryore lyme nedi&thorn; &thorn;e dryore|medycine.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at two lymes ben y-wounded &thorn;at ben lyche in
<PB N="15">|complexioun, &amp; &thorn;at on ha&thorn; myche quyter and &thorn;e o&thorn;ere lyte, he &thorn;at|ha&thorn; myche quyter nedyth to haven &thorn;e dryere medycine.  Iohannes|damacenus: Medycines &amp; enplastres scholde ben acordynge to &thorn;e|lymes &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben y-leyde on.  Galienus: a kendlye thynge schal|be kepte with &thorn;ynge &thorn;at ys kendlye &thorn;ere to; and &thorn;at &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyne|kynde schal be done away with &thorn;ynge &thorn;at is contrarye &thorn;ere to.  &YOGH;if|&thorn;at a surgien knowith no&yogh;t complexiouns of lymes &amp; of bodyes, he|schal no&yogh;t kunne to chaungen hys medycines aftere &thorn;at kynde|aske&thorn;.  A surgien moste knowe generacioun of humours, &yogh;if he|wolde knowen &thorn;e sciense &amp; &thorn;e helynge of Apostemys, as yt schal ben|declared in &thorn;e tretys of apostemes; he moste knowyn &thorn;e dyuersite,|&amp; &thorn;e profytes, &amp; &thorn;e offices of lymes, &thorn;at he mowe knowen what|lymes han grete wyrchynge in mannys body, &amp; whiche ben of grete|felynge, &amp; whiche mowe bere a stronge Medycine; &amp; &thorn;e vertues of|lymes he moste knowe, &thorn;at he se whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e worchynge of enye|vertue fayle&thorn; in enye lyme, &thorn;at he mowe helpe &thorn;e vertue in &thorn;e same|lyme faylinge.  And &yogh;if he haue &thorn;e science of knowynge of vertues,|&thorn;e sciense of spiritus ne schull no&yogh;t ben y-hud from hym.  Alle &thorn;ese|&thorn;ynges before seyde be&thorn; natureles, &amp; &thorn;ey be&thorn; techynge of medycine|speculatyff.  Also he moste han knowynge of thynges &thorn;at be&thorn; no&yogh;t|natureles, &thorn;at he kunne chesen gode eyre to hym &thorn;at is y-woundyde,
<PB N="16">|o&thorn;ere ellys ha&thorn; a bocche.  Woundes mowe no&yogh;t ben y-dry&yogh;ed in a|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="37a">moyste eyre &amp; a vaporose, but &thorn;ey &thorn;at ben y-woundyde most bene| y-chaungyde from &thorn;at moyste eyre to a swote cler eyre &amp; a dry&yogh;e.|In wyntere he moste kepe hym from colde, ffor no&thorn;inge grevyth so|myche bonys &amp; synwes &thorn;at bu&thorn; y-woundyde as colde.  And in|somere he moste han a temperable eyre; hit ys necessarye &thorn;at he|kunne dyoten hys pacient, as y schal tellen in &thorn;e same Chapytell of|dyotynge.  Also he moste ordeyne moffynge &amp; reste, as yt nede&thorn; to|&thorn;e same syke man; ffor &yogh;if &thorn;at he be woundyde in &thorn;e hed, o&thorn;ere|haue eny puncture off enye synwe, it ys necessarye &thorn;at he reste:|dwelle he in styllenesse, &amp; haue an euene bed &amp; a softe, leste he|suffren enye trauaylle of hys lemys; but &yogh;if &thorn;at olde woundes,|wi&thorn;outen akynge, weren in hys Armes, hit were gode to hym &thorn;at ys|seke to walken on hys fete, &amp; bere hys arme y-bounden to hys|nekke; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be in hys schynys &amp; in hys ffete, hit|were gode &thorn;at he ley&yogh;e &amp; trauellyde with hys handes.  Also a|surgien, in alle &thorn;at he myghte, he moste atempre a syke Mannes|slepynge, ffor to myche slepynge engendre&thorn; superffluyte, &amp; feblyth|his vertues, &amp; coldyth &amp; losyth alle hys bodye; to myche wakynge|dyssolfi&thorn; &amp; consume&thorn; hys spirites, &amp; makyth scharpe hys humores,
<PB N="17">|&amp; hit brynge&thorn; vnkyndly drow&thorn;e to woundes, &amp; ys cause of akynge;|also he moste kunne evacuen hym &thorn;at ys ful of euele humores, &amp;|fulfylle hym &thorn;at ys wastyde, &thorn;at he brynge seke men to gode|temperaunce; ellys a wounde may no&yogh;t ben helyd; entempre he &thorn;e|hert of hym &thorn;at ys seke, ffor to gret wratthe maky&thorn; &thorn;e spirites renne|to myche to &thorn;e wounde, &amp; &thorn;at ys cause of swellynge; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="37b">to grete drede, |o&thorn;ere vntryst of helpe of hys wounde holdi&thorn; spyrites withynne hys|body, &thorn;at mater may nou&yogh;t come to hele &thorn;e wounde.  &THORN;ese sixe|thynges ben y-clepyde vnnaturell, whiche techith a Man speculatyff|of leche craft.  He mot knowen &thorn;e seknesse, as olde wounde, festre,|cancre, &amp; alle o&thorn;ere sores, &thorn;at he traveylle no&yogh;t in deveyne, &amp; brynge|&thorn;e seke man to hys de&thorn;:  ffor eche dyverse sore nedith dyverse|helpynges.  He mote knowe &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e wounde; ffor a wounde|&thorn;at is mad with a swerd o&thorn;ere a knyff mote o&thorn;ere weys ben helyde|&thorn;en he &thorn;at is y-makyde with ston, o&thorn;ere with fallynge, &amp; a wounde|&thorn;at is byten with an hounde schal o&thorn;ere weys ben helyde &thorn;en he &thorn;at|ys y-byten with a wod hound, as &thorn;ou schalt fynde tolde in &thorn;e boke|hereaftere.  And he mot knowe &thorn;e Accidentes &thorn;at bu&thorn; aboute a|wounde, ffor the wounde schal nevere hele tyl &thorn;e Accidentes ben|remevyde awey.  Accidentis ys a &thorn;ynge &thorn;at falli&thorn; to &thorn;e wounde out
<PB N="18">|of kynde, as hete, colde, drow&thorn;e o&thorn;ere to gret moistnesse, crampe, &amp;|o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynges a&yogh;eyne kynde.  A surgien mot ordeyne dyetynge in|dyverse manere, as it is tolde in &thorn;e Chapitell of dyetynge.  Whenne|&thorn;at it is nedful, he mote &yogh;yve dyverse drynkes.  Galien: laxativis|&amp; vomytes bu&thorn; necessarie to hem &thorn;at han olde, rotyde, stynkynde|woundes; ffor whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e body is purgyde from evyle humours,|&thorn;e wykkednesse of &thorn;e matere renne&thorn; from &thorn;e wounde, &amp; so &thorn;e|wounde is sonnere y-helyde.  He &thorn;at byholde&thorn; alle &thorn;e partyes of a| medycine, he may wel se <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="38a">that it is necessarie a surgyne to knowen|ffysyk and o&thorn;ere dyverse science, as hit is tolde tofore in &thorn;is boke.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>&para; The &thorn;ridde Chapitele of &thorn;e furste techynge is of|Intencioun off a Surgyne.</HEAD>
<P>Alle &thorn;e entencioun of surgerye, how dyverse &thorn;at it be, yt is on|*of &thorn;re maneres: &thorn;e ffurste ys undoynge &thorn;at &thorn;at is hol; secunde ys|helpynge of &thorn;at &thorn;at is tobroke; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ys remevynge of &thorn;at &thorn;at|is to myche, so &thorn;at it be do with hande crafte; ffor alle &thorn;e entencioun|of a surgien ys vndire one of &thorn;is &thorn;re entensiouns, o&thorn;ere ellys|vndire one of hem.  A surgyne vndo&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at ys hol, whanne he|letyth blod ore garsyth o&thorn;ere brenne&thorn;, o&thorn;ere sette&thorn; on waterlechys,
<PB N="19">|ffor &thorn;is ys a surgyns craft, &thorn;aw&yogh; we for oure pride have y-lefte yt to|laborers &amp; to wommen, for Galien &amp; Rasys dyden it wi&thorn; here|handes as here bokys telly&thorn;.  And we vndo&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at is hol, whenne|&thorn;at we kutte&thorn; &thorn;e veynes &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e templys &amp; &thorn;e forhed, &amp;|makyth cauterisaciones from &thorn;e seknesse of &thorn;e ey&yogh;en, &amp; whenne &thorn;at|we maken Cauteries in &thorn;e hed &amp; in dyverse places of &thorn;e body as y|schal telle in &thorn;e chapitell of Cauterysynge.  &THORN;e secunde entencioun|ys to hele &thorn;at &thorn;at is tobroke as: woundes, olde woundes, ffestres,|Cancres, and in bringynge to here place Ioyntes &thorn;at bene oute, &amp;|in helynge bonys &thorn;at ben tobroken.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde entencioun is to|remevyn &thorn;at &thorn;at ys to myche as scurffyls of &thorn;e hed &amp; &thorn;e nekke, &amp;|o&thorn;ere partyes of &thorn;e body, &amp; Cataractis &thorn;at ys a water &thorn;at comyth|bytwene &thorn;e whyte of &thorn;e ey&yogh;e &amp; &thorn;e Appul.  Sebel &thorn;at be&thorn; veynes|&thorn;at bu&thorn; in &thorn;e whyte of &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, &amp; be&thorn; ful of blod.  Vngula, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="38b">&thorn;at ys |a thynge &thorn;at bygynne&thorn; by &thorn;e nese &amp; goth overe &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, tyl he|keffere alle &thorn;e ey&yogh;e &amp; knottes &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, &amp; o&thorn;ere seknesse|of &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, &amp; in doynge awey polippes &thorn;at is flesch &thorn;at growi&thorn; with|ynne &thorn;e nese, wertys &amp; wennys, fficus &thorn;at is a superffluyte &thorn;at growi&thorn;|vp on &thorn;e skyn off &thorn;e pyntellys hed withouten, emeraudes &amp; a schyn
<PB N="20">|&thorn;at enclosyth a wommans prive membre, &thorn;e sixte fynger of &thorn;e hand,|and manye superfluytes &thorn;at beth nought semlye to mannys body.</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="2">
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1"><HEAD>&para; The ffurste Chapitell of &thorn;e secunde tretys ys an|universel word off smale lymes, &amp; here helpynges|of generacioun of enbrion &thorn;at is child in &thorn;e moder|wombe.</HEAD>
<P>Galien seith &thorn;at it ys necessarie a Surgien to knowe Anotomye,|ne leffe heno&yogh;t &thorn;at iche brode ligament &thorn;at ys a schyn, &amp; iche|rounde ligament to ben a synwe, &amp; so be hys opynioun he my&yogh;te|fallen in erroure.  &THORN;erefore i &thorn;ynke to ordeyne a Chapitell of &thorn;e|kynde &amp; of &thorn;e fforme &amp; &thorn;e helpynge of alle smale lymes.  Avycene|seith, knowlechynge of a &thorn;ynge &thorn;at ha&thorn; cause may no&yogh;t be knowe|but by hys cause, &thorn;erefore we mote knowe &thorn;e cause membrorum|consimilium: &thorn;at ys to sigge smale lymes.  Y wyl telle &thorn;e generacioun|of embrion, &thorn;at ys to sigge, how a childe ys bygete in &thorn;e modire|wombe.  Galien and Avycene tellen &thorn;at of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes of Man|&amp; womman&mdash;wirchynge &amp; sofferynge togedires, so &thorn;at iche of hem|wirche in o&thorn;ere &amp; suffren in o&thorn;ere&mdash;embrion ys bygete.  But &thorn;e| worchynge of Mannes kynde is more my&yogh;tyere, &amp; wommans <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="39a">kynde
<PB N="21">|ys more ffeblere.  Ffor ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e rendelys of chese ha&thorn; hym by|weye of worchynge, &amp; &thorn;e Mylk be weye off suffrynge, so to &thorn;e|generacioun of embrion, Mannes sperme<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spernes</I>.</NOTE> hath hym be weye of|worchynge, &amp; wommans sperme<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spernes</I>.</NOTE> be weye of suffrynge, &amp; ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e|rendles &amp; &thorn;e mylk makyth a<NOTE PLACE="foot">Above line.</NOTE> chese, so bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spernes</I>.</NOTE> of man &amp;|womman maky&thorn; &thorn;e generacioun of embrion.  &THORN;ow&yogh; &thorn;at alle &thorn;e smale|lymes of a childe be y-geten of bo&thorn;e two spermes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spernes</I>.</NOTE> na&thorn;eles to clo&thorn;e|hem with fflesch &amp; with fatnesse come&thorn; to hem menstrewe blod.  &THORN;e|marys of a womman ha&thorn; an able complexioun to conseyven, &amp; of|here kynde sche castyth &thorn;e spermes to &thorn;e deppeste place off here,|and of here nature sche closyth hire mouth &thorn;at &thorn;ere my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t|entre &thorn;e poynt of an nedle.  And &thorn;enne &thorn;e formal virtue whiche|&thorn;at almyghty god ha&thorn; &yogh;euen to the marys, ordeyne&thorn; &amp; deff[e]nde&thorn;|every party of &thorn;ese spermes in here kynde, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e childe ben|ybore.  Understande &thorn;at &thorn;e flesch &amp; &thorn;e fatnesse ys y-mad of menstrewe|blod, the bonys &amp; &thorn;e grustlys, ligamentes, synwes, cordes,|Arteries, veynes, pannycles, &thorn;at bu&thorn; smale clo&thorn;es &amp; &thorn;e schyn bu&thorn;|engendred of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e spermes, as Avicene &amp; o&thorn;ere Autores tellyn.|&YOGH;if &thorn;at enye of &thorn;e lymes &thorn;at bu&thorn; engendrede off the spermes be don|away, *he may nevere verrelyche ben restoride, ffor &thorn;e matere of
<PB N="22">|hym ys &thorn;e sperme of &thorn;e fadire &amp; &thorn;e modere.  But &thorn;e flesch whose|matere ys blod &thorn;at is al day engendred in vs may wel &amp; verreliche|be restoryde.  &THORN;ese smale lymes han dyverse formes, complexioun,|&amp; helpynges after the dyversite of &thorn;e proportiouns of &thorn;e mater| whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="39b">mad of; ffor &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at alle the lymes be mad of|on matere y-medlyde, na&thorn;eles in eche of &thorn;e smale lymes &thorn;ere is a|dyverse proposicioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">read "proporcioun."</NOTE> of matere, for the whiche matere &thorn;ey taken|dyverse forme &amp; dyverse helpe.  Almyghty god gevyth to effrye|&thorn;ynge of hys forme after &thorn;at hys matere *proporcioned deservyt.</P>
<P>&THORN;e bon is furst of consimile membris &thorn;at is on off smale|lymes, &thorn;e whiche ys colde &amp; drye, &amp; he ha&thorn; dyverse formes in|mannes bodye, for he helpi&thorn; dyversliche; &thorn;e cause why &thorn;ere ben|many dyverse bonys in mannys body is,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I> above line.</NOTE> ffor sum tyme it ys nede|to meffyn o lyme without an o&thorn;ere, &amp; &thorn;at were inpossible, &yogh;if in alle|&thorn;e body were but on hol bon.  An o&thorn;ere cause is why &thorn;ere ys many|bonys; for sum diffenden &thorn;e principal lymes from harme, as &thorn;e|brayn scolle &thorn;e brayn of &thorn;e hed; somme ben ffundamentys, as &thorn;e|bonys of &thorn;e rugge, &amp; of &thorn;e schynes, &amp; of &thorn;e Armes.  Some ben as|armure, as additamentys, &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e syde of &thorn;e rugge bon, &amp;|somme fulfylle &thorn;e holwenesse of somme Iunttes, as &thorn;e handys &amp; &thorn;e
<PB N="23">|fete, &amp; somme &thorn;ere ben &thorn;at &thorn;e roundnesse of on bon my&yogh;te entre in|to &thorn;e holwenesse of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere bon &amp; na&thorn;eles scholde no&yogh;t lakken hys|meffynge, as &thorn;e schulder bonys, &amp; the hepe bonys.  &THORN;ou maiste fynde|hou many bonys &thorn;ere ben in &thorn;e secunde tretys where schal be tolde|plenerliche&mdash;&thorn;e Anotamye of consimile membrys of alle <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="40a">&thorn;e body, |from &thorn;e hed to &thorn;e fot.  A grustyll ys cold &amp; drye, &amp; is nesschere|&thorn;enne a bon, &amp; hardere &thorn;anne &thorn;e flesch, &amp; in &thorn;e flesch hath vi|helpynges.  &para; Helpynge &thorn;e grustel.  The ffurste &thorn;at &thorn;ere scholde be|a Mene, bytwene &thorn;e vtter ende of &thorn;e hard bon, &amp; &thorn;e nessch flesch.|&para; &THORN;e secunde, &thorn;at &thorn;e harde scholde no&yogh;t hurt &thorn;e nessche, namlyche,|in &thorn;e tyme of comprission, &amp; in &thorn;e tyme of smytynge.  &para; The|&thorn;ridde, &thorn;at &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e bonys, whiche &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e Iunttes|scholde han a softere confricatioun in here Iunttes.  &para; &THORN;e iiij, &thorn;at|he scholde fulfille &thorn;e office of &thorn;e bon, to susteyne a brawne meffynge,|a membre &thorn;at ha&thorn; non bon, as &thorn;e overe lyd of &thorn;e ey&yogh;e.  &para; &THORN;e|v. for his necessarie a grustyll to be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no&yogh;t</I> above line.</NOTE> in a place &thorn;at ys no&yogh;t ful|hard, as &thorn;e &thorn;rote bolle; ffor &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e &thorn;rote bolle ys grustlye.|&para; &THORN;e vi. for it is necessarie some lymes to han a sustentacioun &amp;|a plicacioun, &thorn;at is a foldynge, to be streynde &amp; drawen abrod, as &thorn;e|nese &thorn;rylles &amp; &thorn;e grustle of &thorn;e ere.</P>
<P>
<PB N="24">Ligamente is colde &amp; drye, &amp; go&thorn; out of &thorn;e bonys, &amp; ha&thorn; &thorn;e|forme of a &yogh;enewe, &amp; he may be bowyde, but he feli&thorn; no&yogh;t, &amp; he|ha&thorn; iiij helpynges.  &THORN;e fyrste ys &thorn;at he knytte on bon with an|o&thorn;ere.  It is necessarie &thorn;at o bon be knytte with an o&thorn;ere, &thorn;at|manye bonys my&yogh;te make on body as on bon, &amp; nevere &thorn;e later eche|membre my&yogh;te meffyn by hym-selfe, &amp; &thorn;ere fore &thorn;e ligamente was|bowable &amp; insensible; for &yogh;if &thorn;at yt had y-be sensible, &thorn;ey my&yogh;te|nou&yogh;t have susteynde the travaylle &amp; &thorn;e meffynge of &thorn;e Iunttys;|and &yogh;if &thorn;at he hadde be inflexible as a bon, of whom &thorn;at he comy&thorn;| of, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="40b">on lyme my&yogh;te no&yogh;t han meffyde withouten an o&thorn;ere. &THORN;e secunde|help ys, &thorn;at he ys joynede with &yogh;enewys to make cordys &amp; brawne.|&THORN;e &thorn;ridde helpynge ys, &thorn;at he scholde ben a restynge place to summe|senewys.  &THORN;e four&thorn;e, &thorn;at be hym &thorn;e membris &thorn;at ben withynne &thorn;e|body scholde ben tyede, whiche &thorn;at nedy&thorn; hongynge.</P>
<P>A corde ys colde &amp; drye, &amp; he comyth from &thorn;e brayn o&thorn;ere fro|&thorn;e nuca, &thorn;at ys &thorn;e marye of &thorn;e rugge bonys.  &para; From &thorn;e brayn come&thorn;|vij peire cordys, &amp; &thorn;ey bu&thorn; y-clepyde sensible &yogh;enewys, from &thorn;e nuca|&thorn;ere comyth xxx peire cordys, and on by hym selffen &amp; &thorn;ey bu&thorn;|mevable; &amp; alle &thorn;e cordys &thorn;at comyth of &thorn;e brayn, &amp; &thorn;e nuca
<PB N="25">|habbe&thorn; bo&thorn;e felynge &amp; meffynge. &amp; &thorn;e cordys ben whyte, bowable,|stronge, &amp; tow&yogh;; &amp; of here kynde &thorn;ey brynge meffynge &amp; felynge|to lymes.  &amp; for &thorn;at hit is longe to devyde&thorn; alle &thorn;e partyes of|&yogh;enewes; *in &thorn;e secunde tretys y schal ordeyne Anotamye of|&yogh;enewes &amp; here place,* as &thorn;ey ligge; in &thorn;e whiche place &thorn;ou moste|be ware, whenne &thorn;ou schalt kutte o&thorn;ere brenne, whenne &thorn;at we|schulle ordeyne Anotamye of official membris &amp; of here woundes.|Official membre ys to sigge: a ffynger, a Ioynt, an hand, o&thorn;ere a|fote *ore o&thorn;ire lymes of ofyce.</P>
<P>Arteries be&thorn; hote, no&yogh;t for here owne kynde, but for &thorn;e hote|blod &amp; lyf &thorn;at go&thorn; in ham from &thorn;e herte.  Of here kynde &thorn;ey ben|colde &amp; drye, &amp; &thorn;ey han tweye clo&thorn;es, outsepte on &thorn;at goth to &thorn;e|longes.  &THORN;e innore cote <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="41a">is grettere &amp; strengere, &thorn;at he mowe withholde |a Mevable matere &amp; an hote.  &amp; here bygynnynge is of &thorn;e|lyfte syde of &thorn;e herte.  &amp; &thorn;ere bygynne&thorn; tweye Arteries, on go&thorn; to|&thorn;e longe &amp; ha&thorn; bot on cote &amp; sprat in &thorn;e same longe, &amp; &thorn;ere endyth|&amp; brynge&thorn; blod to &thorn;e longe, by whom he ys y-norysschyde, &amp; spirit|of lyf, &amp; &thorn;at he my&yogh;te brynge from &thorn;e longe eire<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ei&thorn;ere.</I></NOTE> to &thorn;e herte, for to|entempren &thorn;e fumose hete of &thorn;e same herte.  &amp; &thorn;is Arterie ys clepyde
<PB N="26">|venalis, &amp; yt is a manere veyne, ffor as myche as he may haue|but o cote, &amp; &thorn;erefore he is &thorn;e more obedient to be drawen abrod|&thorn;orwe out alle &thorn;e longes &amp; also &thorn;at &thorn;e blod &thorn;at norysschith &thorn;e|longe my&yogh;te li&yogh;tlokere swete out of &thorn;is arterie.  &THORN;e o&thorn;ere Artery, &thorn;at|comyth out of &thorn;e lefte syde of &thorn;e herte, ha&thorn; two cotys, because &thorn;at|on my&yogh;t no&yogh;t ageyne stonde &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e spirites, and also &thorn;at|&thorn;at is wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;e Arterye is ful derwarde &amp; nedi&thorn; gret kepynge.|&THORN;ere ben &thorn;re helpynges of &thorn;e Arteries: on is &thorn;at colde eyre by hem|my&yogh;te be drawe &amp; y-brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e herte, whenne &thorn;e arterye is drawe|abrod; &thorn;e secunde ys pat &thorn;e fumosite my&yogh;t be caste out, whenne|sche is constreynyde; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ys &thorn;at &thorn;e spirite of lyf my&yogh;te be|bro&yogh;t by hem to alle &thorn;e body.  &THORN;ese Arteries be&thorn; devydyde many|weyes, whose divisiones Man may no&yogh;t conseyve by hys wyt, ne &thorn;ey|ne be&thorn; no&yogh;t dredful to surgiens crafte; but whenne &thorn;ou schalt drede|&thorn;e arterye i schal tellen &thorn;e in here places.</P>
<P>Veynes by cause of here bodyes be&thorn; y-demyde colde &amp; drye; but|for &thorn;e blod &thorn;at is withynne hem &thorn;ey be&thorn; y-demyde hote, &amp; alle &thorn;e| veynes han here <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="41b">bygynnynge of &thorn;e lyffere, in &thorn;e whiche lyffere two|veynes han pryncipal begynnynge.  On veyne bygynne&thorn; of &thorn;e holwe|syde of &thorn;e lyvere, &amp; ys y-clepyde Porta, &thorn;at ys a &yogh;atte, &amp; here ofyce|is to drawe chilum from &thorn;e stomake &amp; &thorn;e guttes by mene of &thorn;e
<PB N="27">|veynes miscraykus; &thorn;ilke chylum sprede&thorn; &thorn;orwe al &thorn;e lyffere by|mene of veynes Capillares.  Chilum ys &thorn;e licoure of mete &amp; of &thorn;e|drynke, whenne yt go&thorn; out of &thorn;e stomake &amp; &thorn;e guttes.  Veynes|miserayke be&thorn; smale veynes, &thorn;at comyth out of &thorn;e veyne &thorn;at is|y-clepyde porta, &amp; clevyth on &thorn;e stomake &amp; &thorn;e gottys.  Veynes|capillarys &thorn;at be&thorn; veynes, as yt were herys of a Mannes hed.</P>
<P>&para; After hem comyth pannyceles, &thorn;at ys to sigge, a smal cloth,|&thorn;at ys mad of sotyll &thorn;redys of synwis veynes &amp; arteries, where|fore &thorn;ey ben colde &amp; dry&yogh;e &amp; sensible, &amp; &thorn;ey han &thorn;re helpynges.|&THORN;e firste is &thorn;at they mowe bynden manye &thorn;ynges in on forme, as &thorn;e|pannicle of &thorn;e hed bynde vii bonys; &thorn;e secunde Iuvament is &thorn;at|&thorn;ey hongen &amp; bynden somme membrys with o&thorn;ere, as &thorn;e reyns to &thorn;e|rugge &amp; &thorn;e marys to &thorn;e rugge bon; &thorn;e &thorn;rydde helpynge ys &thorn;at some|membrys &thorn;at be&thorn; insensible by here kynde, by &thorn;e pannycles &thorn;at|wreye&thorn; hem ffeli&thorn; by accydent, as &thorn;e longes, &thorn;e lyffere, &amp; &thorn;e splene,|&amp; &thorn;e reynes; &thorn;ese lymes by here kynde ha&thorn; non felynge, but what|&thorn;at &thorn;ey felyn it ys by Accident of &thorn;e pannycle &thorn;at wreye&thorn; hem.</P>
<P>&THORN;e flesch is no&yogh;t hot, but yt is moist, &amp; ha&thorn; &thorn;re manere lyknesse;|on ys symple flesch, &amp; hys helpynge ys to fulfylle &thorn;e voyde placys
<PB N="28">|of smale lymes, to bryngen hem to a gode schappe, &amp; &thorn;at iche harde|lyme <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42a">ne scholde nou&yogh;t hurten o&thorn;ere with confricacioun togedire.| An o&thorn;ere manere flesch ys &thorn;at is glandelose, &thorn;at ys as hyt were|achcharnes, &amp; hys Iuvamente is &thorn;at he turnyth vmydites to here|hete: as &thorn;e glandelose flesch of wommans brestys, whyche &thorn;at|turnyth &thorn;e blod &thorn;at ys drawe from &thorn;e marys into &thorn;e mylk, &thorn;e glandelose|flesch of &thorn;e ballokes, &thorn;at turnyth &thorn;e blod into sperme, &amp; &thorn;e|glandelose flesch off the chekys &thorn;at engendre&thorn; spotel.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde|manere of flesch ys a flesch &thorn;at is in brawnys, &thorn;at ys y-clepede a|brawny flesch, ffor he ys medlyde wi&thorn; sotyl &thorn;redys of cordys, as y|schal tellyn aftere, whose helpynge schal be tolde in &thorn;e Anotamye|of &thorn;e brawne.</P>
<P>At &thorn;e laste is &thorn;e schyn, &thorn;at is temperat in al here qualite, &amp; is|y-mad of smale &thorn;redys of veynes, synwes, &amp; Arteries, &thorn;at make&thorn; hym|sensible, and geve&thorn; hym lyf and norisschynge, &thorn;at he be governoure|of alle &thorn;e body.  &amp; &thorn;e skyn ys y-mad temperat, for he scholde knowe|hot, colde, moyste &amp; drye, softe &amp; hard, scharpe &amp; sme&thorn;e; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e|skyn were as sensible as a &yogh;enewe, a man my&yogh;te no&yogh;t dwellen in|colde eyre, ne in hote eyre; ne &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e fyngres endys, whiche|&thorn;at ys more temperat &thorn;enne eny o&thorn;ere skyn of &thorn;e body, ne scholde
<PB N="29">|no&yogh;t ben a gode demere in knowynge hot, cold, hard o&thorn;ere scharpe,|softe o&thorn;ere nessche.</P>
<P>&para; Brawnys &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;ey ben mad of matere y-medlyde, nevere &thorn;e|latere &thorn;ey be&thorn; y-reknyde amonge membrys consimiles, for &thorn;ey comen|to &thorn;e makynge off Membrys-officiales.  Brawne ys y-mad of fflesch,|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42b">&yogh;enewe, &amp; ligamente, &amp; &thorn;ey ben Instrument off voluntarie mevynge. |&THORN;e &yogh;enewe &thorn;at comyth from &thorn;e brayn &amp; &thorn;e nuca, &amp; go&thorn; for&thorn; to meve|the lymes, ys y-medlyde with a ligamente, &amp; whenne &thorn;e &yogh;enewe &amp; &thorn;e|ligamente be&thorn; medlyde togedyre, yt ys clepyde a corde, &amp; the corde|ys y-made for &thorn;re skylles: &thorn;e ffurste for a symple senewe ys to|sensible, &amp; &thorn;e &yogh;enewe by hym-self ne my&yogh;te no&yogh;t suffren to grete|travaylle &amp; mevynge, but &thorn;e felawschipe of &thorn;e ligamente, &thorn;at ys|insensible, lutli&thorn; &thorn;e felynge of &thorn;e synwe, and brynge&thorn; hym to a|profitable temperaunce.  &THORN;e &yogh;enewe hadde tweyne o&thorn;ere defautes:|nesschenesse &amp; litylnesse, but &thorn;o tweyne defautes, &thorn;e medlynge of|&thorn;e ligament ffulfille&thorn;; for the neschenesse ys entempred &amp; y-strengthyde,|and &thorn;e lytelnesse ys y-made more.  The nesschenesse comyth of|&thorn;e brayn, ffor it ys nessche; and &thorn;e lytelnesse come&thorn; of &thorn;e Nuca,|for it ys lytel.  &THORN;at &thorn;at is mad of &thorn;is nerff &amp; &thorn;is ligamente ys|clepyde a corde, whiche &thorn;at mevi&thorn; &thorn;e lymes to wyl of &thorn;e soule,
<PB N="30">|whenne &thorn;at it is schortid o&thorn;ere y-drawe, aftere &thorn;at &thorn;e lyme bowyth|to &thorn;is corde.  ffor &thorn;ere ys Asosyed a symple *fflesch forto maken a|brawne for &thorn;re proffytes: &thorn;e furste profyt, &thorn;at bo&thorn;e in drawynge &amp;|wi&thorn;drawynge of &thorn;e corde, the flesch scholde be as a pylwe, vp on|whom he my&yogh;te reste; &thorn;e secunde cause, &thorn;at &thorn;e flesch &thorn;at is nessche| &amp; moyst schulde kepen &thorn;e corde, &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43a">sche drey&yogh;ede no&yogh;t in here|mevynge; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;at &thorn;e makynge of lymes were &thorn;e more schap-lokore.|&THORN;e brawne is made bowynge, as a bowe &thorn;at ys y-bent; &amp;|for &thorn;at kynde wolde kepe &thorn;ys compositioun, he clothyde &thorn;e brawne|wy&thorn; a pannycle.  &THORN;e corde whenne he entrith in to &thorn;at brawne, ys|departyde in to many smale &thorn;redys, &amp; &thorn;ey ben clepyde vylles, &thorn;at|ys to sugge, wrabbynges.  &amp; &thorn;ese villes bene of &thorn;re maners, in|leng&thorn;e&mdash;by whom vertue &thorn;at drawe&thorn; ha&thorn; my&yogh;t, in brede&mdash;by whom|vertu &thorn;at castyth out ha&thorn; my&yogh;t, in twart ofere&mdash;by whom vertu|*&thorn;at wi&thorn;halt ha&thorn; my&yogh;t; &amp; at &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e brawne &thorn;ilke &thorn;redys be&thorn;|gadride to gedre to maken a corde, after &thorn;at it is necessarie, many|cordys o&thorn;ere brawnys to ben engendride.  &amp; official membrys ben|y-mad of &thorn;ese consimile membrys, whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; instrument to|resonable sowle.  And in &thorn;e secunde tretys y wyl tellen &thorn;e anotamye|of lymes of ofice.</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="treatise" N="3">

<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="1"><PB N="31">
<HEAD>The ffurste Chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge is of difference|of woundes &amp; olde woundes &amp; off generall|cures.</HEAD>
<P>&para; We schulle vndirstonde &thorn;at wounde, olde wounde, ffestre, cancre|y-wondyde, a bon out of loynt, a bon tobroken, Aposteme, alle &thorn;ese|ben y-clepyde vndoynge of &thorn;at &thorn;at ys hol, &amp; alle &thorn;ese seknesse &amp;|manye o&thorn;ere as wel mowe fallen to consimile membrys. as to oficial|membris.  Vulnus is a newe wounde.  Vlcus ys an olde rotyde|wounde.  I schall <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43b">tellen in here place &thorn;e dyfference of festre &amp; |cancre &amp; apostemys.  Plage comynliche ys y-taken of an olde wonde;|and ofte tyme we fynden, &thorn;at an olde wounde ys y-clepyde Vulnus,|as Ipocres sei&thorn;: Vulnera Annua necesse est in eis os tabefieri &amp;|cicatrices concavas fieri.  &para; That is to sugge, it ys ned, &thorn;at &thorn;e bon|in an olde wounde to be rotyd, &amp; &thorn;e Cicatrices to be holwe.  Cicatrice|ys &thorn;e place of &thorn;e skyn above the wounde, whenne &thorn;at yt is|hol.  Some wounde bu&thorn; symple &amp; some ben componyde.  In tweye|manere he ys clepyde a symple wounde.  On manere, for he ha&thorn;|no&yogh;t leste of flesch; an o&thorn;ere maner, for he ha&thorn; non o&thorn;ere seknesse|with hym, ne is no&yogh;t distempride.  A wounde componed ys y-clepyde|contrarye to hym &thorn;at is symple.  But bo&thorn;e symple &amp; also componyd
<PB N="32">|some tyme is in &thorn;e flesch o&thorn;ere in &thorn;e synwe o&thorn;er in bon,|o&thorn;ere in veyne, o&thorn;ere in arterie.  Also &thorn;ese wondes han dyverse|causes.  Some comen from wi&thorn;ynne of &thorn;e malice, o&thorn;ere of to gret|multytude of humores; *forto gret multitude of humores o&thorn;ere while|tobrekyth &thorn;e membre, &thorn;at wi&thorn;holdi&thorn; &amp; woundi&thorn; hym cold matere|streyne&thorn;, drye matere kutte&thorn;, moistnesse withouten matere make&thorn; no|wounde, but selden with matere, but he drawi&thorn; &thorn;e lyme to brode.|And also &thorn;e cause wi&thorn;out may be dyverse, o&thorn;erwhyle with a swerd,|ore with a &thorn;ynge &thorn;at kutte&thorn; alonge, o&thorn;erwhile with a knyff, o&thorn;ere a| spere, o&thorn;ere an arwe &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44a">pryke&thorn;, &amp; somme ben made wi&thorn; a stafe,|o&thorn;ere with a ston, o&thorn;ere with fallynge, &amp; somme ben mad with bytinge|of an hound, o&thorn;ere of a wod hounde; &amp; alle &thorn;ese ben dyverse,|after &thorn;e dyverste of here cause; &amp; also &thorn;e manere of helynge ys|dyverse.  Alle &thorn;e entensioun of helynge of woundes, ys forto sowdyn|&amp; to helyn, &amp; to restoren &thorn;at &thorn;at is departyde, whiche &thorn;at may no&yogh;t|overe al be don.  Ffor &yogh;if &thorn;at membres of offyce ben kutte of, &thorn;ey|mowe nevere ben restoryd; ne non of &thorn;e consimile membres may be|restoryde, &amp; he be don awey: as bonys, pellicules, grustles, ligamentis|&amp; schyn.  Ffor &thorn;e cause of here generacioun is &thorn;e sperme of|&thorn;e ffadire &amp; &thorn;e modere, as y tolde tofore; but in place of thynge|&thorn;at is lore, kynde restoryth &thorn;at &thorn;at is most convenient to &thorn;at place;|but the flesch may be restoryd, by cause &thorn;at &thorn;e blod ys engendred
<PB N="33">|al day in vs, &amp; &thorn;e blod ys &thorn;e matere of flesch; &amp; somme suggen &thorn;at|veynes, synwes, &amp; arteries my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t be restoryde as &thorn;ey were|tofore; but &thorn;ey mowe be restoryd as bonys bu&thorn;.  But Galien &amp;|Avycene, &amp; I &thorn;at am expert here suggynge, suggen &thorn;at &thorn;ey mowe be|restoryde with verrey consolidacioun, whanne &thorn;at here kuttynge ys|lytell, &amp; whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e synwys &thorn;at bu&thorn; newe kutte be&thorn; so wyde|a&yogh;eyne; but &thorn;ey mowe no&yogh;t be consouded, whanne &thorn;at here kuttynge|ys gret &amp; myche; &amp; resoun grauntyth yt.  Synwys by kynde|bu&thorn; nessche and viscose; &amp; &thorn;erefore &thorn;ey mowe ben consouded.  &THORN;e|veynes &amp; &thorn;e arteries mowe be consouded by resoun of &thorn;e blod &thorn;at ys|in hem.  I &thorn;ynke to ordeynen eche Chapitell <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44b">be hym selven, aftere |&thorn;e dyversite of lymes &amp; of placys, whyche &thorn;at &thorn;ey bu&thorn; y-made yn;|&amp; y wyl begynne at a symple wounde y-mad in flesch.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>&para; &thorn;e secunde Chapitell off &thorn;e thridde techynge off the|ffurst tretis is of cure of a wounde y-mad in|fflesch.</HEAD>
<P>Now we willen treten of a wounde y-makyd in fflesch.  We|wylle begynne at a symple wounde, y-mad wi&thorn; knyff o&thorn;ere wi&thorn;|swerd ore spere, o&thorn;ere with arwe, o&thorn;ere with enye o&thorn;ere thynge
<PB N="34">|semblable to hem.  Bynde togedyre &thorn;ilke wounde with a band &thorn;at|close &thorn;e wounde to gedire, &amp; kepe &thorn;e wounde from swellynge, with &thorn;e|whyte of an ey&yogh;e y-leyde aboue &thorn;e wounde, &amp; lete &thorn;at wounde ben|in reste, &amp; &thorn;ere nedyth none o&thorn;ere cure, namlye, whanne &thorn;e wounde|ys withouten akynge; but and &thorn;ere be in wounde gret akynge, &thorn;anne|&thorn;ere is a tokne &thorn;at &thorn;ere ys a synwe prikyde vndire &thorn;e wounde, o&thorn;ere|a pannicle &thorn;at ys betwene &thorn;e flesch &amp; &thorn;e bon, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ere ys al an|o&thorn;ere cure, as y schal telle in &thorn;e chapitell of the puncture of a synwe.|And y haue helyd a man &thorn;at was *sefenty &yogh;ere olde, &thorn;at was y-smyten|wi&thorn; a spere &thorn;orwe &thorn;e flesch of &thorn;e buttoke by &thorn;e leng&thorn;e of a fote *&amp;|more, but &thorn;ilke wonde touchyde non synwe; &amp; &thorn;at y wiste sykerliche,|for he had non akynge; y helde the wounde opyn al a day,|with a lyte smal tente &amp; a schert &thorn;at y my&yogh;te wyte, &yogh;if &thorn;at he scholde|ake on &thorn;e morwe &amp; I comaundyde hym to reste, and on &thorn;e morwe y|fonde non inflacion ne akynge, &amp; &thorn;enne y caste aweye &thorn;e tente &amp;|lete &thorn;e wounde closen, &amp; so y comaundide hym to reste, &amp; wi&thorn;ynne|&thorn;e &thorn;ridde day he was al hol.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at a wounde were mad wi&thorn;| a swerd, o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; eny &thorn;ynge &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45a">kutte&thorn; in leng&thorn;e, a man most loke|&yogh;if &thorn;e wounde be so litel &thorn;at he nede non sowynge, &amp; &thorn;enne brynge|&thorn;e parties of &thorn;e wounde togedyre, &thorn;at it may wel ben y-joynede, &amp;|leye above &thorn;e wounde a poudere y-mad of on partye of ffranke-Ensence,
<PB N="35">|&amp; of two partyes of sancdragoun &amp; of &thorn;re parties of quykelyme,|&amp; lete no&yogh;t &thorn;e poudre entre wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;e wounde but above,|for &thorn;ere schal no&thorn;ynge entre withynne &thorn;e wounde, &amp; kepe &thorn;e parties|of &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at bu&thorn; brou&yogh;t togedire with a plumacyole &thorn;re corneled|y-made of hurdes o&thorn;ere tow&yogh; in &thorn;is manere <FIGURE></FIGURE> on be &thorn;e sydes of|&thorn;e wounde, so &thorn;at bo&thorn;e &thorn;ilke plumacioles holde &thorn;e wounde &thorn;us|y-closyde <FIGURE></FIGURE> &amp; joynde togedire, as yt was joyned ere &thorn;enne|yt was ykutte; &amp; bynde &thorn;e wounde togedire abouen &thorn;e plumacioles,|with a rolle &thorn;at goth twartoffere after &thorn;is lettere XX, &amp; take a lynnen|cloth &amp; wete hym in two parties of whyte of an ey&yogh;e, &amp; in on|partie of oyle of roses i-bete togedire, vndire &thorn;e plumacioles abofe &thorn;e|wounde, &thorn;at ys y-brow&yogh;t togedyre, forto kepe &thorn;e poudre, &amp; do no&yogh;t|awey &thorn;e medycine tyl foure dayes ben ago, but &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde|ake, o&thorn;ere ellys be to-swollyn; &amp; &thorn;enne bynde &thorn;e wonde as yt was|toforne, with &thorn;e whyte of &thorn;e ey&yogh;e, oyle, poudre, &amp; plumacioles.  But|&yogh;if &thorn;e wounde were so myche, &thorn;at &thorn;e byndynge wolde no&yogh;t suffice,|o&thorn;ere were kutte twart offere &thorn;e lyme, so &thorn;at &thorn;e partyes of &thorn;e lyme|my&yogh;t no&yogh;t wel be brow&yogh;t togedire, &thorn;anne sowe &thorn;e wounde on &thorn;is|manere: joyne &thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e wounde togedire, &amp; ware &thorn;at non oyle|*ne dust, ne no&thorn;ynge ellys &thorn;at lattyd consolidacioun, falle bytwene
<PB N="36">|&thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e wounde, &amp; haue an nedle <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45b">&thorn;re kornerde, whose ey&yogh;e|scholde be holyde on bo&thorn;e sydes, so &thorn;at &thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ridde</I> cancelled before <I>&thorn;rede.</I></NOTE>&thorn;rede &thorn;at is in &thorn;e nedle| may ligge in &thorn;e holwe place, &amp; &thorn;ilke schal be twynede, &amp; withoute|knotte &amp; ywaxide, &amp; &thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e wounde schulle ben sowyde|togedyre, &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;rede schal be knette with two knottes in &thorn;e firste|place; in &thorn;e secunde place with on knotte, &amp; so make as manye|punctis as yt is necessarie, &amp; eche puncte schal be from o&thorn;ere by &thorn;e|brede of a lytel ffyngere, &amp; streyne &thorn;e wounde wi&thorn; knettynge, &amp; &thorn;e|sowynge of &thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e wounde togedire &thorn;at he ake sumwhat,|but no&yogh;t to myche, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere nede mo punctis to be &thorn;ere &thorn;en|two, efire more &thorn;ere schal be odde punctys, as &thorn;re, fyfe, o&thorn;ere seuene;|&amp; &thorn;e on puncte schal be fyrst from &thorn;e on ende of &thorn;e wonde by &thorn;e|<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sp</I>. cancelled before <I>brede</I>.</NOTE>brede of a litel fyngire, &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere puncte schal be at &thorn;e o&thorn;ere ende|of &thorn;e wounde, &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde puncte schal be in &thorn;e myddul of &thorn;e|wounde; &amp; &yogh;if it be nede to haue mo punctis, &thorn;ou schalt begynnen|at &thorn;e myddel puncte, &amp; make as manye punctes on bo&thorn;e &thorn;e sydes, as|yt ys nede, tyl &thorn;ou come to bo&thorn;e endys; ffor by &thorn;is manere of|sowynge nei&thorn;ere partye schal be crokyde, &amp; so &thorn;e place may fairere|ben restoryde.  And eueremore take hede, *&yogh;if &thorn;e wounde be no&yogh;t|depe, &thorn;y sowynge schal be nou&yogh;t depe.  And &yogh;if &thorn;y wounde be depe|&thorn;y sowynge schal be depe, &thorn;at alle &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e wounde mowe
<PB N="37">|be joyned togedire.  Ffor &yogh;if &thorn;e wounde were depe, &amp; &thorn;y sowynge|were no&yogh;t depe, nedys &thorn;ere moste ben in &thorn;e dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e wounde a|gret holwenesse, to &thorn;e whiche holwenesse blod &amp; quyter scholde be|cast; &amp; &thorn;ilke quyter &amp; blod scholde lette &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="46a">helynge of &thorn;e wounde. |And &thorn;e poudre &thorn;at ys seyde in &thorn;e same chapytell schal be leyde|aboue &thorn;e same sowynge, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt kepen &thorn;e sowynge &amp; &thorn;e parties|of &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;at bu&thorn; brou&yogh;t togedyre, with plumacioles &thorn;re cornelyd|&amp; with alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynges &thorn;at be&thorn; in &thorn;is chapytel forseyde.  And &yogh;if|&thorn;at a wounde haue be to longe in &thorn;e eyre opyne, whiche &thorn;at ys|cause of quyter &thorn;at latte&thorn; consolidacioun, &thorn;enne we moste clense &thorn;e|wounde with<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at.</I></NOTE> &thorn;is mundificatyff, &thorn;at is mad of floure, of whete &amp; hony|&amp; watyre o&thorn;ere mel rosate, &amp; colat &thorn;at ys y-clansed from &thorn;e roses, &amp;|of barly mele.  Of &thorn;ese mundyficatyfes &thorn;ou schalt han a ful techynge|in &thorn;e laste tretys.  But &yogh;if &thorn;e wounde be y-componed, a leche|moste han as manye intensiones as &thorn;ere ben accidentys to &thorn;e wonde.|Y sette ensaumple: y suppose &thorn;at a wounde be componed with holwenesse|&amp; lesynge of fflesch &amp; of skyn, &amp; &thorn;ere be myche quyter &amp;|al so &thorn;ere be a posteme &amp; &thorn;ere be grete akynge, al this ys clepyde a|wounde componyde.  &THORN;anne we schulle no&yogh;t only take hede to consolidacioun|of &thorn;ilke wounde, &thorn;at is to sigge helynge, but firste we
<PB N="38">|schul aswagen ak&thorn;e &amp; aposteme, as yt schal be tolde in &thorn;e chapitle|of aposteme &amp; of akynge; aftirwarde we schullen clanse &thorn;e quyter,|&amp; aftere &thorn;at regenere fflesch, &amp; at &thorn;e laste brynge ouere a Cicatrice.|In alle &thorn;e werkynges of medicine, where &thorn;at ak&thorn;e ys, ffirste we|schulle aswagen akynge; ffor abouen alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynge stronge|akynge, ouere come&thorn; my&yogh;te of vertu &amp; streng&thorn;e, &amp; also resoun|tellyth; membrys &thorn;at han ak&thorn;e, &thorn;ilke ak&thorn;e ys cause of drawynge|from o&thorn;ere places to &thorn;e membre &thorn;at ake&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ak&thorn;e.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e worste &thorn;ynge of &thorn;e| humoures.  Avicene seyth humours be&thorn; drawen to <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="46b">lymes &thorn;at aken|for two causes: On cause, for kynde *&amp; Spiritus and humoures|rennyth &thorn;edyre; &thorn;e secunde cause, for ak&thorn;e feblyth &thorn;e lyme, &amp;|humours *&amp; spiritis renne to &thorn;e feble lymme.  &THORN;e swellynge schal|ere ben y-helyde &thorn;en &thorn;e wounde.  Galien &amp; Avycene tellen &thorn;at alle|&thorn;ynge &thorn;at consoude&thorn; &thorn;e wounde, grefy&thorn; &thorn;e wounde, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere be|aposteme with &thorn;e wounde, &amp; &thorn;e quyter schal ben y-clansyde, ere &thorn;enne|&thorn;ou legge enye generatyff to holwe woundys.  Avicenne tellyth a|cause, why &thorn;at yvele flesch growith in a wounde, &yogh;if &thorn;at a leche|wolde besy hym with a medycin regeneratyff to engendre flesch in|a wounde, ere &thorn;anne &thorn;e quytire were clansede.  And whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e|wounde ys clensyde, &thorn;enne we schulle fulfyllen &thorn;ilke holwnesse with
<PB N="39">|flesch, ere &thorn;anne &thorn;at wounde ben y-helyde; leste &thorn;at &thorn;ere dwellen an|holwnesse vndire &thorn;e wounde whenne &thorn;at he ys helyde, in whom &thorn;at|quyter scholde be engendryde, &thorn;e whiche eche day scholde augmente|&thorn;ilke holwnesse, &amp; so we moste ben constreynede to opyne an o&thorn;ere|tyme &thorn;at, &thorn;at was helyde tofore.  &THORN;ou mayste fynden aftere in &thorn;e|chapytell of woundys of synwes how &thorn;ou schalt aswagen ak&thorn;e, and|in the sixte Chapitell of &thorn;is techynge &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;e cure of a|wounde, &thorn;at hath a swellynge, and ys out of kynde dystempryde,|and &thorn;ou schalt have in &thorn;e chapitle of olde woundys; how thou schalt|clense, quytyre, and regendre flessch //</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="47a">Cap. iii. of the &thorn;ridde techynge of the ffurst tretis is |of helynge of a wounde y-makyde in synwe.</HEAD>
<P>Almi&yogh;tie god hath &yogh;ife to synwe gret felynge, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at he be|hurt he suffrede grete akynge.  Galien: a synwe that is more|felynge &thorn;en ano&thorn;ere *lyme yt is nessessarie &thorn;at he have gretter|akynge.  Vndirstonde &thorn;at a wounde &thorn;at is y-makyde in a synwe,|may nou&yogh;t ben wi&thorn;outen akynge.  The woundes &thorn;at be&thorn; y-makyde|in synwe, o&thorn;er &thorn;ey ben in lengthe o&thorn;ere &thorn;ey be&thorn; in brede.  &THORN;o|woundes &thorn;at be&thorn; y-mad in lengthe of &thorn;e synwe be&thorn; lasse perylous,
<PB N="40">|&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at be&thorn; in brede of &thorn;e synwe be&thorn; more perilous.  O&thorn;ere whyle|a synwe ys y-kut al atwo, &amp; &thorn;enne &thorn;ilke lyme to whom &thorn;ilke|synwe serfede, lesi&thorn; &thorn;e menynge &amp; &thorn;e felynge &thorn;at &thorn;ilke synwe|brou&yogh;t to hym from &thorn;e brayn.  O&thorn;ere while &thorn;ulke synwe is nou&yogh;t y-kut|a two, but he is y prikyde, and &thorn;enne it is perel lest &thorn;e crampe|come for to gret ak&thorn;e.  For ak&thorn;e entrith in to &thorn;e part of &thorn;e synwe|&thorn;at is y-kut o&thorn;er priked, &amp; by &thorn;e party of &thorn;e synwe &thorn;at is hol|ak&thorn;e is brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e brayn, &amp; so crampe may comen to &thorn;e wounde|by on of &thorn;re weyes, &thorn;at is to gret ak&thorn;e colde o&thorn;er rotynge.  Of &thorn;ese|&thorn;re o&thorn;ere ellys of on by hym self, may come a drawynge togedre|of a synwe &thorn;at is a cause of a crampe; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at is seyde of|wounde of a symple synwe, oft-tymes may fallyn in a wounde of a|corde &amp; a brawn, &amp; namlyche of a corde &thorn;at is in &thorn;e bygynninge|of a brawn.  &THORN;e woundes &thorn;at ben in &thorn;ese &thorn;re consimel membris, &thorn;at|is *to sigge, synwe, corde, &amp; brawn, habben on drede in course of &thorn;e|crampe, &amp; also on drede of lesynge, felynge, &amp; menynge, &amp; &thorn;erfor|be war in &thorn;e cure of a wounde i-makyde in synwe, whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ere|be a prikynge, o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;e synwe be y-kut twartofere, o&thorn;er ellys|be y-kut only by his lengthe.  &YOGH;if only he be y-prikyde &thorn;e wonde|of &thorn;e skyn is hol, &amp; &thorn;enne it is clepyde a blynde puncture, o&thorn;er &thorn;e|wounde is opene &amp; it is clepide an opene prikynge.  In a blynde
<PB N="41">|prikyne hit is necessarie to opyn &thorn;e skyn, &amp; afterwarde held in to|&thorn;e hole, as <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="47b">hot as he may suffren, oyle of roses swote smyllynge,|&thorn;at is y-made of oyle de olyffe, &thorn;at is nou&yogh;t rype tyl &thorn;e wounde be |al ful.  &amp; aboue &thorn;e wounde leye whyte terbentyne y-drawe abrod|betwene tweye cloutes, &amp; anoynt al &thorn;e membris about &thorn;e wounde|wi&thorn; hote oyle of rosys, y-made &thorn;ikke wi&thorn; bol Armonyak, &amp; after &thorn;at|leye a lynne cloth y-hat aboue, &amp; after &thorn;at a gode quantyte of tow&yogh;|y-tosyd, &amp; bynde &thorn;e lyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lynne.</NOTE> softlyche wi&thorn;out streyninge; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e|ak&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;is medycine wolde nou&yogh;t cese, remeffe &amp; chaunge &thorn;is|same medycine oft tymes in &thorn;e day &amp; in &thorn;e ny&yogh;t, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e prikynge|be in &thorn;e fot, anoynte &thorn;e grynde wi&thorn; hote comyn oyle, &amp; vndire &thorn;e|Arme holys &amp; in &thorn;e nekputte, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e prikynge be in &thorn;e hande.|For &thorn;ys vncture ratefie&thorn; &amp; efeny&thorn; &thorn;o placys by whom ak&thorn;e goth to|&thorn;e brayn, &amp; it latti&thorn; drawynge togedre of &thorn;e synwe, &amp; &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at|&thorn;ou sest nou&yogh;t ak&thorn;e, sese in some men, as hastly as &thorn;ou woldyst,|nevere &thorn;e later chaunge nou&yogh;t &thorn;y medycine, for &thorn;ere may be no|bettere medycine.  But &yogh;if &thorn;at ak&thorn;e dure ouere longe yt is nou&yogh;t|efel to putte a lutyl opin to &thorn;e oyle of rosys and &thorn;e bol armoniak,|&thorn;at &thorn;ou leydest aboute &thorn;e wounde.  &THORN;e seke man most reste, &amp; by
<PB N="42">|no weye he scholde nou&yogh;t be wro&thorn;, hys bed most be made softe|euene &amp; sme&thorn;e &thorn;at he my&yogh;te haue rest.  Whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e ak&thorn;e|aswagyth &amp; &thorn;e wounde gyueth sum qyter, &thorn;an &thorn;e syke man ys saf|from al manere peryle, but &yogh;if he do enye newe error.  Of &thorn;is|wounde ypocras speki&thorn;: In vulneribus malis &amp; fortibus sanie non|aparente malum, &thorn;at is to seye: in evyle woundys &amp; stronge|woundes, &yogh;if no quyter apere, hit is yuele.  Stronge woundes ben|y-clepyde woundys &thorn;at sore aken.  Iuel woundes be&thorn; &thorn;o, to whom|scharpe humores rennyth &amp; be&thorn; nou&yogh;t obedyent to kyndlie hete to|ben turnyde into quyter &amp; &thorn;erefore ypocras seyde, &thorn;at whanne &thorn;at|akynge sesyth &amp; quyter aperith, yt is a tokne of hele.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde| signe a man moste <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="48a">knowe in &thorn;is place, &thorn;at lewyde men seyne|akynge &amp; swellynge in a lyme y-woundyde, leggen &thorn;ereto a maner|potage y-mad of erbys &amp; swynes grese, water, &amp; floure of whete,|corupyn &thorn;e lyme, &amp; &thorn;ilke corupcioun is cause of &thorn;e crampe; for|Galyen sei&thorn; &thorn;at a synwe is mad of a moiste matere &amp; a cold, &amp; he|rotyth of hete &amp; moistnesse.  Also sum men forto aswage &thorn;e ak&thorn;e|of a synwe &thorn;at is y-prikyde, putte&thorn; &thorn;e lyme in to hote water,* o&thorn;er|ellys caste it on &thorn;e lyme hot water,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hot water, insertion.</NOTE> &thorn;e whiche water is most grefes|to &thorn;e synwe.  Galyen: hote water &thorn;ow&yogh; it aswage ak&thorn;e, to the
<PB N="43">|prikynge of a synwe ys most greuest; colde also gefyth sore &thorn;e|synwes as wel in somere as in wyntere.  Ypocras in &thorn;e ferthe|partye of his Amphorismes: colde is bytinge and grefes to woundys;|and also in &thorn;e chapitell nexte folwynge, bot it be in a crampe wi&thorn;|out wounde.  Galyen sei&thorn; in &thorn;e ende of his comente: colde is most|grefest, to a synwe lyme &thorn;at is y-woundyde &amp; ys toswolle, namly,|&amp; he haue &thorn;e crampe.  Hit sewi&thorn; &thorn;enne &thorn;at an hote medycine &amp; a|drye is most accordynge to synwes &thorn;at be&thorn; y-woundyde; bot nou&yogh;t|to hot a medycine, leste &thorn;at he make &thorn;e lyme toswellyn; &amp; drye|nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; stipticite, lest he close &thorn;e pores of &thorn;e schyn.  Galyen sei&thorn;:|it is yuel to close &thorn;e pores of a lyme &thorn;at is y-prikyde.  &THORN;e medicyne|&thorn;enne most ben hote &amp; drye, wi&thorn; subtilite as terbentyne to moiste|bodyes; &amp; to drye bodyes, he most be medlyde wi&thorn; a lytel eufforbium.|Asa fetida is best medycine, &yogh;if &thorn;ou make of hym emplaster,|serapinum, &amp; &thorn;e feces of wax, &amp; &thorn;e fylthes of vesselis of been, alle|&thorn;ey ben gode to a synwe, &thorn;at is prikyde, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou put iche be|hymself o&thorn;er opyn hem; &amp; &thorn;ou schalt fynden a ful techynge of &thorn;ese|medycines in &thorn;e Antitodarie of &thorn;is boke.  &THORN;ou schalt nou&yogh;t closen
<PB N="44">|a wounde, where &thorn;at &thorn;e prikynge of a synwe is, ere &thorn;an &thorn;e synwe|be perfitlye clansyde &amp; helyd, &amp; ere &thorn;ou be sykere &thorn;at &thorn;e place|schal nou&yogh;t swelle.  Galyen tellyth of a man wi&thorn; a poyntel in &thorn;e| pawme of &thorn;e hand, to whom come one of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="48b">Tesilies clerkys, &thorn;e|whiche toke hede to helyn alle woundis generalyche, &amp; he leyde to|&thorn;ilke prikynge a consoudynge oygnement &thorn;at was more acordynge|to a wounde y-makede in fflesch, &amp; he leyde &thorn;ereto a maturatyff|plastre, where fore al &thorn;e hand rotyd, &amp; he fel into a crampe, &amp; so|he dyede ere &thorn;e vii dayes were passyde; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ilke leche hadde|y-made &thorn;ilke wounde braddere, &amp; &thorn;enne &amp; hadde y-helde in &thorn;e|wounde hote oyle of rosys, and &thorn;enne hadde abyde quyter wi&thorn; hote|medycines sotyl &amp; dreying, &amp; no&yogh;t wi&thorn; moiste medycines, &thorn;ilke man|ne scholde nou&yogh;t haue ben ded.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at a synwe hadde ben kut|twart ouer al atwo &thorn;enne, &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at tedericus &amp; summe o&thorn;ere sigge|&thorn;e contrarye, hit is good &thorn;at &thorn;ou sewe togedre &thorn;e hedys of &thorn;e|synwys &thorn;at be&thorn; y-kutte, wi&thorn; &thorn;e sowynge of &thorn;e skyn &amp; abouen &thorn;ilke|maner of sewynge, &thorn;e first day leye oyle of roses, in &thorn;e whiche oyle
<PB N="45">|Maddokkys, &thorn;at be&thorn; wormys of &thorn;e erthe, haue ben boyllede; and|caste aboute &thorn;e wounde &thorn;e poudre &thorn;at kepyth &thorn;e sowynge a day|o&thorn;er two afterward, &amp; kepe &thorn;e sowynge wi&thorn; plumacioles &thorn;re kernellyde|&amp; wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn;</I> above line.</NOTE> byndynge, &amp; kepe &thorn;e lyme from swellynge, ffor by|swyche a manere sowynge of &thorn;e synwe &thorn;ou maiste consoude &thorn;e|synwe ageyn, for &thorn;e lym scholde haue lost in party o&thorn;er in al the|meuynge, &thorn;at was y-brow&yogh;t to hym from &thorn;e brayn, for by &thorn;ilke|synwe &thorn;at lyme may rekeueren hys felynge, &amp; so &thorn;e restorynge of|&thorn;e brayn may be more schaplokere &amp; fastere.  Ne &thorn;ou ne schalt|no&yogh;t drede of &thorn;e akynge &thorn;at scholde be made of &thorn;e prekynge of &thorn;e|nelde, for &thorn;e ak&thorn;e schal be don awey by one leggynge to o&thorn;ere|tweyne of &thorn;ilke oyle; ne swyche manere ak&thorn;e may no&yogh;t make &thorn;e|crampe, for &thorn;e synwe ys al kutte atwo.  Ne no man *make an|obiectioun wi&thorn; galyens wordys, &thorn;at we scholde be ware in ioyninge|&thorn;e partyes of a wounde togedre, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="49a">&thorn;at non here ne oyle ne scholde|no&yogh;t entre wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;e lippes 4of a wounde, &thorn;at be&thorn; y-brou&yogh;t togedre.* |To &thorn;ilke obiectioun we answeren, &thorn;at &thorn;e stipticite of &thorn;e|roses &amp; &thorn;e oyle &thorn;at was nou&yogh;t ripe, &amp; &thorn;e glutinosyte of &thorn;e wormys|of &thorn;e erthe remywen &thorn;e ak&thorn;e of &thorn;e synwes, &amp; al &thorn;e harme &thorn;at|scholde comen of &thorn;ilke sewynge.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at a synwe were woundede|in leng&thorn;e he may be wel &amp; ly&yogh;tlyche y-soudyde togedire, wi&thorn;
<PB N="46">|ioynynge of &thorn;e lippys &amp; wi&thorn; sowynge &amp; wi&thorn; kepynge of &thorn;e lym, &thorn;at|he scholde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scholde</I>, error for <I>swelle</I>, or it belongs to: <I>scalle, scalde, scalled, scab</I>.|See W. Wright, and <I>Cathol. Angl.</I></NOTE> no&yogh;t.  Understande here in &thorn;is place, &thorn;at &thorn;ere is no|&thorn;ynge more worschipful to a leche ne more profytable to a seke|man, &thorn;enne to kepe a lyme y-woundyde from swellynge, &amp; na&thorn;eles|it is hard to kepe synwys &thorn;at be&thorn; woundyde from swellynge.|Na&thorn;eles a leche here schal take hede aftere &thorn;e techynge &thorn;at schal|be geuen to hym in hys chapytell of &thorn;e cure of a wounde, whanne|&thorn;at &thorn;ere ys wi&thorn; hym a swellynge.  &YOGH;if a wounde were chaungyd of|&thorn;e eyre and mad quyter, &thorn;at &thorn;e sowynge were tobroke, &amp; &thorn;e|punctis weren vndo, &thorn;enne make a medycine mundyficatyff, &amp;|leye hym abrod on a lynne cloth, &amp; leye it aboue &thorn;e wounde, &amp;|put a lytel smal tent in &thorn;e one ende of &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at is most|declynynge; &amp; &thorn;ilke tent schal touche non synwe, ne make non|ak&thorn;e, vndire &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ilke wounde be wel dryede.  A mundificatyff|medycine of synwes y-woundyde ys y-made in &thorn;is manere:|&rx;. mel rosat colat <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iii smal floure of barly <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>, &amp; medle hem togedre|&amp; boyle hem sly&yogh;ly &thorn;at &thorn;ey brenne no&yogh;t, &amp; remywe hem from &thorn;e|fyre &amp; bete hem togedre longe wi&thorn; a spator, &amp; &thorn;enne put &thorn;ere to <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>.|of whyte terbentyne, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou maiste fynde no whyte terbentyne
<PB N="47">|wassche it wyth colde watyre, tyl it be whyt; &amp; whenne &thorn;at by &thorn;is|medycine &thorn;e wounde is almost drye, &thorn;enne put in &thorn;e same medycine|a lite smal poudre of franke ensence, mastike, &amp; sank dragoun, &amp;|medle hem to gedre, &amp; leye aboue &thorn;e wounde tyl it be al hol; &amp;|whanne &thorn;at it is hol manye dayes aftere, leye flax in gode stronge|hot wyn, tyl yt be al hol perfitlyche.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere leue enye|hardnesse <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="49b">in mevynge, aftere &thorn;at it is hol, &thorn;enne &thorn;ou schalt vse |the techynge &thorn;at schal be geuen to &thorn;e in &thorn;e laste tretys, &thorn;at schal|be antitodarye in &thorn;e chapitle of medycine, molyficatyffes; &thorn;ere &thorn;ou|schalt fynde &thorn;e manere how &thorn;ou schalt helpyn beste lymes, &thorn;at be&thorn;|y-helyde &amp; mowe no&yogh;t ry&yogh;t wel meffen.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>The fur&thorn;e techynge of &thorn;e firste tretys is of helynge of|a wounde y-makyde in bon.</HEAD>
<P>Whenne &thorn;at woundes be&thorn; so depe &thorn;at only &thorn;e flesch is nou&yogh;t|y-woundyde, but &thorn;e bon &thorn;at is vndire &thorn;e flesch &amp; &thorn;e synwe, &thorn;enne a|man most byholde whe&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;e bon be kut al atwo, as ofte tymes|yt may happen in &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e thy&yogh; &amp; &thorn;e schynebonys, &amp; &thorn;e bonys|of &thorn;e Arme, &amp; &thorn;enne &thorn;ylke wounde is ful perylouse; and namlye,|&yogh;if &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e thy&yogh; ore &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e arme, from &thorn;e schuldre to &thorn;e|elbowe, be y-kutte al atwo, so &thorn;at &thorn;e marye gon out.  But ofte tymes
<PB N="48">|on bon of &thorn;e schyne, o&thorn;ere in bon of &thorn;e Arme, ys ykutt al atwo|twartofere, &amp; na&thorn;eles afterward may be restoryde; o&thorn;er a bon ys|nou&yogh;t ykut al atwo, but sum of his substaunce ys done aweye, and|&thorn;ilke substaunce o&thorn;ere he ys don al aweye, o&thorn;ere he hongyth to|gedre.  A general rule ys in cure of woundes in whom bonys ben|woundyde, &thorn;at neuere by a leche flesch shal be y-sowdyd aboue &thorn;e|bon, but first &thorn;e bon plenerlyche be repeyrede; ffor &thorn;e bon may|neuere with verrey consolidacyoun ben consouded, for his matere|was &thorn;e sperne of &thorn;e fadire &amp; &thorn;e modire, but in somme children for|&thorn;e ny&yogh;te of tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ey were sperme (sic); but &thorn;ere schal be mad|a manere restorynge in plas of &thorn;e bon &thorn;at was broken o&thorn;ere lost.|&thorn;at men clepen porrus sarcoydes o&thorn;ere ellys caro poroydes, &amp; &thorn;at|manere thynge &thorn;at is restoryd is hardere &thorn;e flesch &amp; nesschere &thorn;en|&thorn;e bon; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ilke mater &thorn;at is restoryde by neye<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ne&thorn;e.</NOTE> as hard as|yt were a bon, yt is clept porus sarcoydes; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ilke mater be| nou&yogh;t harde, but sumwhat<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="50a"> nessche, yt is clepyde caro poroydes;|&yogh;if &thorn;at a nesch fflesch &amp; a moist were no&yogh;t regenered vpon bonys|&thorn;at ben set togedre, a man scholde no&yogh;t han his purpos to helyn &amp;|to consoude &thorn;e wounde.  Loke &thorn;enne whe&thorn;ere &thorn;e bon be kutte a-two
<PB N="49">|al togedre twartofere, &thorn;at &thorn;ou brynge togedre, &amp; bynde the|partyes of &thorn;e wounde as yt schal be tolde in &thorn;e ey&yogh;te chapytell|folwynge, where &thorn;ou schalt han hou a wonde schal ben helyde &thorn;at|is out of joynt, y-kutte atwo &amp; tobroke.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at a bon be no&yogh;t|kutte atwo al togedre twartofere, loke &yogh;if enye pece of &thorn;e bon|dwelle sadlyche to &thorn;e on partye of &thorn;e hole bon, &amp; &thorn;enne &yogh;if &thorn;ou|my&yogh;te brynge &thorn;ilke pece to &thorn;e place &thorn;at he was yn tofore with|&thorn;rustynge don &thorn;ilke pece with sum Instrumentis acordynge &thorn;ereto,|&amp; sowde &thorn;ilke pece wi&thorn; &thorn;e hole bon with &thorn;e poudre, &thorn;at y schal|tellyn afterwarde; for so &thorn;e schap of the lyme may dwelle fairere|&amp; strengere.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ilke pece haue no fastnesse to &thorn;e hole bon,|do &thorn;at pece awey, &amp; &thorn;enne regenere in &thorn;e place of &thorn;e bon &thorn;at was|lost a repairment.  Ffor &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at ypocras &amp; Galyen tellyn &thorn;at it|ys necessarie aftere &thorn;e quantite of a bon &thorn;at is lost, an holwe cicatrice|to be alwey, na&thorn;eles wi&thorn; &thorn;is poudre &thorn;e generacioun of &thorn;ese|pores may be mendyde no&yogh;t a lytel, but ry&yogh;t myche.  &THORN;is is &thorn;e|poudre: Take ffrank ensence, Mastyke, Mirre, dragagantum gu. arabyke|ana. <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. ij., flour of ffenngreke, <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>, <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, cast &thorn;is poudre a gode|quantite vpon &thorn;e defaute of the bon &thorn;at was lost, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue|a plenere repeyrment *&amp; a restauracioun.  &THORN;enne &amp; no&yogh;t ere|brynge ouere fflesch ouere &thorn;e repeyrment with *generatyffes, mundificatyfes,
<PB N="50">|&amp; consolidatyfes, aftere &thorn;e techynge that &thorn;ou haddyst|toforn.  Undirstonde &thorn;at alle &thorn;ynge &thorn;at ys seyde of bonys in &thorn;is|chapitle, ys of alle &thorn;e bonys of &thorn;e body saff &thorn;e hed; &amp; of &thorn;e|bonys off the hed y schal make a chapytle by hym-selff.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>&THORN;e ffye Chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge of &thorn;e furst| tretis is of woundis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="50b">that beth y-mad with|smytinge.</HEAD>
<P>The woundys &thorn;at be&thorn; mad wi&thorn; brosynge, as wi&thorn; smytynge of a|staf, o&thorn;ere ston, o&thorn;er fallynge, o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; smytynge of an hors, o&thorn;er|wi&thorn; enye thynge semblable to hem, habbith gret differens from|woundis &thorn;at be&thorn; y-made wi&thorn; kuttynge: as wi&thorn; swerde, knyf, ore|arwe prikynge, &amp; in o&thorn;ere manere &thorn;ey schulle ben helyde.  For|&thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at verreye consolidacioun be &thorn;e first &amp; &thorn;e princypal Intencioun|of helynge of a wounde, to &thorn;is chapitle it acordyth no&yogh;t, ffor in|smytinge, &thorn;e flesch &amp; &thorn;e veynes, synwes &amp; arteries ben y-brusyde;|for in &thorn;e ynnere part of &thorn;e lyme &thorn;e bon a&yogh;eyne stonde, &amp; on &thorn;e vtter|part &thorn;e &thorn;ynge &thorn;at smyteth &amp; kutte&thorn; no&yogh;t, wherefore it is necessarie,|&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere scholde ben a wounde, &thorn;at alle &thorn;e smale lymes &thorn;at be&thorn;|bytwene &thorn;e bon &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ynge &thorn;at smyteth, scholde be brusyde; &amp;
<PB N="51">|o&thorn;erwhyle &thorn;e flesch &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere consimele membris be&thorn; brusyde|witout wounde, wherefore &thorn;e cures of bo&thorn;e y wyl ordeyne in this|chapytle.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at a leche wolde enforce hym to Iune to gedire|with consolidatyfes &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at is mad wi&thorn; smytinge, nedys<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. nedyth.</NOTE>|quyter &amp; corupcioun by &thorn;ilke consolidatyff, most be vndire &thorn;e|wounde; &thorn;e whiche quyter scholde corumpe &thorn;ylke lyme &amp; brynge|hym to putrefactioun, but &yogh;if &thorn;e kynde were so my&yogh;tye, &thorn;at he my&yogh;te|eftesonys opyne &thorn;ylke wounde, &thorn;at was consouded by a sorye leche,|o&thorn;ere &thorn;at a gode leche come &amp; knewe &thorn;ilke dispocisioun, &amp; cou&thorn;e|helpe wi&thorn; propre cure to rettefien &thorn;e corupcioun off &thorn;ilke lyme.|What schaltou &thorn;anne do?  &THORN;ou most loke whe&thorn;ere that &thorn;e body be|ful of yuell humores, o&thorn;er be clene; &yogh;if &thorn;at he be ful, lete hym|blod, &yogh;if alle partikelere &thorn;ynges acorden: as vertu, Age, complexioun|&amp; consuetude; &amp; &thorn;ese &thorn;ynges &thorn;ou most alweye taken in &thorn;y mynde,|&thorn;ow&yogh; alweye &thorn;ey ben nou&yogh;t y-nempnyde, &amp; namlye vertue; &amp; he|be nou&yogh;t stronge &amp; alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynges acorden, &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t leten|blod, bot &thorn;ou <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="51a">maiste ventosen, &yogh;if &thorn;at it be necessarie, o&thorn;er ellys |lose *&thorn;e wombe &yogh;if &thorn;at he be costyff; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at he be feble, &amp; the|brosure were in &thorn;e ouere party of &thorn;e body, voyde &thorn;e feces of hys
<PB N="52">|wombe by clisterye.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt lete blod, &thorn;ou shalt lete blod|on &thorn;e contrarye party of &thorn;e veyne, bryngynge norysschynge to &thorn;e|lyme &thorn;at was hurt; &amp; &thorn;ilke veyne &thorn;ou schalt y-knowe, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou|knowist plenerlyche Anotamye, &thorn;at y haue tau&yogh;te &thorn;e in &thorn;is same|boke.  &amp; whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e body ys y-clansyde, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e brosure be|wi&thorn;out &thorn;e wounde, anoynt &thorn;e membre &thorn;at is y-brusyde, whiche &thorn;at|begynne&thorn; to han a postum, wi&thorn; hote oyle of roses, &amp; cast aboue a|poudre y-mad of &thorn;e sed of mirtylles &amp; bynde it softlye, for ofte|tymes it nedyth non o&thorn;er cure.  For &thorn;is medycyne fastnyth &thorn;e|place, &amp; defendyth hym from putrefacioun, &amp; &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;is medycine|mowe no&yogh;t letten alle &thorn;e mater from rotynge, na&thorn;eles yt deffendyth|myche of &thorn;e same matere fro rotynge; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at al &thorn;e matere may|nou&yogh;t be defendyde fro putrefactioun, but sum partye &thorn;ereof|putrefie&thorn;, opene &thorn;e place &amp; exclude &thorn;e quyter, &amp; clanse al &thorn;e place.|&amp; his cure schal be seyde in &thorn;e tretys of apostomes &amp; of exitures.|But &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e brosure were wi&thorn; a wounde, anoynte about &thorn;e wonde|o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;e place &thorn;at is y-brusyde, wi&thorn; &thorn;e forseyd oyle of roses,|&amp; caste aboue &thorn;e forseyde poudre of mirtillyes, for &thorn;is medycine|fastnyth &thorn;e place, ne yt ne lette&thorn; no&yogh;t corupcioun to spredyn, o&thorn;ere|to be drawe abrod, &amp; it castith to &thorn;e wounde &thorn;e corupt mater, &thorn;at
<PB N="53">|is in &thorn;e place &thorn;at is brusyde.  Wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;e wounde leye &thorn;e &yogh;olke of|an eye with oyle of roses, with stupes o&thorn;ere ellys wi&thorn; lynte; &amp; leye|aboue &thorn;e wounde a potage y-made off foure partyes of water &amp; o|partye of oyle d'Olyve &amp; floure off Whete &thorn;at suffyse&thorn; to &thorn;e|medycine, &amp; leye &thorn;is medycine to &thorn;e wounde, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e ak&thorn;e be|aswagyde &amp; tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e quyter be engendryde; afterwarde clanse &thorn;e|wounde, aftere &thorn;e clensynge regenere, &amp; at &thorn;e laste cicatryce, &amp; &thorn;ou|schalt haue a ful techynge in &thorn;e Antiodarie of mundificatyfes,|maturatyfes, &amp; &yogh;icatrisatifes.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="51b">But &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e membre &thorn;at was |y-brusyde ys ful of synwes, as &thorn;e honde o&thorn;er &thorn;e fot, &thorn;ou schalt no&yogh;t|chaunge &thorn;y cure &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere be no wounde; but &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ere be a|brusure in a synwy membre y-woundyde, ne leye no&yogh;t &thorn;ere &thorn;e|potage forseyd, but only hote oyle of roses, &amp; aboue &thorn;e oyle poudre|of mirtilles, &amp; aboue &thorn;e wounde leye terbentyne iwassche &amp; drawe|abrod betwene tweye clo&thorn;es lynnen.  &amp; make enplastre of pych,|hony &amp; bene flour, &amp; leye aboute a lym ful of synwes: as &thorn;e fot|o&thorn;ere &thorn;e hand, &amp; specialyche whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e flux of humours sese&thorn;.|&amp; &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;i cure be drawe along, ne go no&yogh;t awey fro &thorn;is cure;|&amp; whenne &thorn;at al &thorn;e ak&thorn;e ys y-sesyd, &amp; alle &thorn;e swellynge ys aswagyde,|forto clanse &thorn;e wounde, vse &thorn;e medycine of mel rosat colat with
<PB N="54">|barly mele, y-sayd in the wounde of synwes.  &THORN;is cure ys aprefyde|by galyen, &amp; y haue preffyde &thorn;is medycine ofte tymes.</P>
