<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="7"><PB N="59">
<HEAD>&para; The vij Chapitelle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge is off a|wounde y-made of a wod hounde, o&thorn;ere of eny|o&thorn;ere venymouse bestys.</HEAD>
<P>Whenne &thorn;at an hounde hath byten a man, ffirste loke &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e|hounde be wod; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e hounde be no&yogh;t wood, hele &thorn;e wounde|as &thorn;ou dost o&thorn;ere comyn woundys; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e hounde were wood,|&thorn;ou schalt y-knowe yt by certeyne causes, &amp; by disposiciouns.<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="53b">  Ffor |a wod hounde fleyth mete, &amp; ffleyth watere, &amp; o&thorn;erwhyle he dyeth|whenne &thorn;at he se&thorn; water; &amp; he rennyth hydirwarde &amp; &thorn;edirwarde,|as a dronken man, wi&thorn; opyn mou&thorn; &amp; hys taylle bytwene his leggys,|hys tunge hongyth out, he wolde byte alle men, ne he ne knowyth|nou&yogh;t &thorn;o men &thorn;at ben his housholde, he berkyth no&yogh;t; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at|he o&thorn;erewhyle berke, hys voys ys ful hors, &amp; o&thorn;ere houndys flen|from hym &amp; berkyn vpon hym.  Also &thorn;ou schalt y-knowe by|dysposicioun of &thorn;e same wounde, for &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wetyst a crumme|bred in &thorn;e blod of &thorn;e wounde &amp; geuyste yt to an o&thorn;er hounde to|etyn, he wyl no&yogh;t etyn yt, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e hounde ety&thorn; yt he wyll deyen;|o&thorn;ere ellys take a note &amp; stampe yt, &amp; leye on &thorn;e wounde al ny&yogh;t,|&amp; on &thorn;e morwe &yogh;if yt to an henne, sche wyl no&yogh;t etyn hyt; &amp; &yogh;if|sche etyth yt sche wyl deyen.  &amp; anone as &thorn;ou wost &thorn;e hounde ys
<PB N="60">|wod, sette a gret ventuse aboue &thorn;e wounde &amp; drawe out myche blod|out of &thorn;e wounde, &amp; afterwarde drawe abrod &thorn;e wounde; &amp; abouen|alle o&thorn;ere thynge brennynge of hote eyren to &thorn;e dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e wounde|ys most proffytable, &amp; aftere leye aboue &thorn;e wounde attractyfes, to|drawe out &thorn;e venym.  Some of &thorn;ese attractifes be&thorn; symple, &amp; some|be&thorn; componyd.  Symple ben: &thorn;e lyffere of &thorn;e same wod hounde|&thorn;at bote &thorn;e man, garlyke y-stampyde, salt fyssch, asschys of vyne,|Opopanac ys wondirful, &thorn;e leuys of a Gourde, &amp; &thorn;e rote of ffynegreke,|&thorn;e gele of fyssches, &amp; amptes y-stampyde.  &THORN;ese medycynes|ben componyde: vryne of a &yogh;onge man, with nytre o&thorn;er myntes,|i-stampyde with salt &amp; distempred with vynegre, &amp; y-mad in emplastre.|An o&thorn;ere medicyne componyd: &rx; floris eris &amp; salt ana|ten parties, &amp; &thorn;e fat of a calff twelf partyes, &amp; make a plastre.|An o&thorn;ere: take schepys talw&yogh; &amp; buttre, &amp; make emplastre.  &THORN;is|wounde schal ben y-holde opyne at &thorn;e leste fourty dayes; al &thorn;is| schal be do about &thorn;e place.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="54a">In an o&thorn;ere manere regimen vndirstande,|&thorn;at &thorn;e man &thorn;at is y-bete ne schal nou&yogh;t be lete blod in the|bygynnynge, lest &thorn;e venym be drawe abrod by o&thorn;ere lymes.  Ne|&thorn;ou ne schalt &yogh;if hym non laxatyff, lest yt drawe &thorn;e venym to &thorn;e|entraylles withynne; but &thorn;ou schalt setten on &thorn;e place a stronge
<PB N="61">|ventuse, as yt is seyde tofore, &thorn;at he mowe drawe myche of &thorn;e blode.|&amp; whenne &thorn;at &thorn;re dayes ben passyde, yt is nou&yogh;t yuele to leten|blod, &amp; to purge with a ly&yogh;t purgacioun, &thorn;at purgith &thorn;e malyncolye,|as with decoccioun of Epytemum, with gotys whey&yogh;; &amp; norissche|hym with dyetynge, &thorn;at fattyth hym &amp; make glad &amp; bli&thorn;e; &amp;|wassche hys hed with decoccioun of water, &thorn;at &thorn;e fet &amp; &thorn;e hed of|a we&thorn;ire ben y-sodyn yn.  Ne lete hym nou&yogh;t &thorn;rustyn, ne suffren|hungyre ne trauell, &amp; so &yogh;if &thorn;at god wyl, &thorn;ou maiste kepen hym|from peryle.  &amp; euery day to a mone&thorn; ende, he schal taken o&thorn;ere|symple medycynes, o&thorn;er componed.  *Symple bu&thorn;: Asa ffetida.|Asa dulsis, polm,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>polium</I>, Paley.</NOTE> terra sigillata, Wermot, Kockull,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Kockull</I>, Nigella.  See <I>Prompt. Parv.</I>, p. 86.</NOTE> mirre &amp;|gencyane.  Medycynes componed gode: *&rx; &thorn;e assches of crabbys|y-brent in an Offyn .iiij partyes, of ffrankensens vij partyes, make a|poudre; &thorn;e pacient schal take iche day of &thorn;is poudre <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .ij wi&thorn; wyn.|An o&thorn;er: &rx; &thorn;e poudre of crabbys y-brende vj partyes, of gencyane|iij. parties, terre sigillate one partie, make poudre.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou|were no&yogh;t at &thorn;e bygynnynge, &amp; he bygynneth to haue yuele Accidentes,|as yuele &thorn;ou&yogh;tes, schrewyde metynge in his slepe, &amp; &thorn;at he|be wroth &amp; grucche &amp; wot no&yogh;t why, &amp; &yogh;if men aske hym enye|&thorn;ynge he &yogh;euyth no gode answere &thorn;ere to, &amp; ffley&thorn; ly&yogh;t, &amp; he hath|alle o&thorn;ere signes of malencolye, &thorn;anne &yogh;if to hym a medycine y-made
<PB N="62">|of cantarydes.  Take olde grete kantarydes &amp; do aweye &thorn;e hed &amp;|&thorn;e wynges &yogh;. ij., lentys I-clansed &yogh;. j., saferen, spikenard, clowys,|canell ana &yogh;. <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>.&mdash;in o&thorn;ere bokys&mdash;ipone hem wel &amp; make of hem|smale ballys &thorn;at wey&yogh;en j. penye wy&yogh;t; &amp; &yogh;if a ball at &thorn;re tymes,|at iche tyme &thorn;e wy&yogh;t of vij cornys of whete, tyl &thorn;at he pysse blod,|for &thorn;enne he schal be saff.  Ffor whenne &thorn;ou art sykere, hele &thorn;e| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="54b">wounde after &thorn;at fourty dayes ben passyde, in &thorn;e same maner.|&YOGH;if &thorn;at a wounde were mad of &thorn;e bytinge of an eddre, o&thorn;ere of eny|o&thorn;ere venymouse beste, &thorn;e leche schal take hede to drawe abrode &thorn;e|wounde &amp; setten abouen a ventuse &amp; drawe out myche blod, &amp; yt|is myche wor&thorn; to enviroun &thorn;e place abouten &thorn;at is y-betyn wi&thorn;|brome y-stampyde.  Ffor &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e prikynge be in &thorn;e fot o&thorn;ere in|&thorn;e hande, &yogh;if &thorn;ou enviroun &thorn;e arme o&thorn;ere &thorn;e legge with brome, yt|latte&thorn; &thorn;e venym to gone vpwarde; &amp; &yogh;if hym &thorn;e medycines y-wryten|aboue, &amp; also tryacle, &amp; lete &thorn;e wounde be opyne, tyl al &thorn;e venym|be escludyde.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>The viij. Chapytelle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge of the ffirste|tretys is of a wounde y-made in a joynt &amp; is dislocat.</HEAD>
<P>Whenne &thorn;at a wounde is in a lyme &amp; &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e same lyme|ys tobroken atwo &amp; is dislocat&mdash;&thorn;at is to sigge, out of joynt,
<PB N="63">|&thorn;anne it is gode &thorn;at &thorn;ou putte in &thorn;e wounde, whanne &thorn;e blod is y-staunchyde,|&amp; also aboue &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;e &yogh;olke of an ey&yogh;e, with oyle|of roses, &amp; anoynt alle &thorn;e lyme aboute &thorn;e wounde, wi&thorn; two partyes|of oyle of rosys, &amp; wi&thorn; half on party of vynegre, y-made &thorn;ikke with|bol Armonyake, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e quyture be engendered,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. engenderes.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;ou be sykere|&thorn;at none Aposteme schall come.  Ne take none hede to brynge togedere|&thorn;e parties of &thorn;e bon &thorn;at is tobroken o&thorn;ere dislocat, tyl viij|daies ben go in &thorn;e wyntire, &amp; fyff in the somere; for &thorn;enne yt|schal make quytere, &amp; be sykere from swellynge; &amp; &thorn;enne brynge|togedire &thorn;e brekynge o&thorn;ere &thorn;e dysynncture aftere &thorn;e techynge &thorn;at|schal be seyde in &thorn;e Chapytell of Algebra.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e brekynge|o&thorn;ere &thorn;e dyslocacioun nedy&thorn; splyntes, make &thorn;at &thorn;e splyntes &amp; &thorn;e|byndynge faylen aboue &thorn;e wounde; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou maiste do, &yogh;if &thorn;at|&thorn;ou kyttest &thorn;e splyntes &amp; &thorn;e byndinge aboue &thorn;e wounde with a knyf|o&thorn;ere a rasoure, &amp; in drawynge abrod &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e bonde aboue &thorn;e|wounde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="55a">wi&thorn; a nedle, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou maiste by &thorn;ilke hole euery day |chaungen &thorn;e medycine of &thorn;e wounde withouten chaungynge of &thorn;e|bonde, &thorn;at &thorn;ou madest firste aboute &thorn;e bonys &thorn;at were broke o&thorn;ere|dislocat.  &THORN;e whiche bonde &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t remeffen, tyl &thorn;e tyme|&thorn;at schal be tolde in hys place; bote you schalt bynde aboue &thorn;ilke
<PB N="64">|bonde a newe bonde, &thorn;e whyche &thorn;ou schalt remeffe, as often as &thorn;ou|chaungiste thy wounde.  &amp; whanne &thorn;ou art sykere from empostomynge|&amp; &thorn;ou haue sette togedire &thorn;e bonys &thorn;at were sette togedire &amp;|dislocat, &thorn;enne leye vpon &thorn;e wonde by &thorn;e hole &thorn;at &thorn;ou madyst in|&thorn;e band a mundifycatyff of mel rosat colat, &amp; of barlye mele, tyl|&thorn;e wonde be clansyde; &amp; leye on &thorn;ilke mundyficatyff &thorn;redys of|olde clene whyte lynne clo&thorn;, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be ful clansyde;|afterward regenere fflesch, &amp; aftereward consoude wi&thorn; regeneratyfes|&amp; consolidatyfes, whiche &thorn;at schullen ben seyde in &thorn;e ende of|&thorn;e boke.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="9">
<HEAD>The ix Chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge is of fflux blod|off a wounde.</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;ere be&thorn; two manere causes &thorn;at makyth blod to bleden out of|mannes body; &thorn;at on cause is clepyde cause conjuncte, &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er|cause antecedent.  &THORN;e encheson of cause conjuncte ys openynge of|&thorn;e mou&thorn;es of &thorn;e veynes &amp; &thorn;e Arteries, o&thorn;er ellys whanne &thorn;at the|veynes be&thorn; kut atwo, o&thorn;er ellys corosion of &thorn;e bodyes of &thorn;e same|veynes &amp; arteries, o&thorn;er ellys to gret feblenesse, o&thorn;ere to gret losnesse.|&amp; &thorn;ere be&thorn; manye enchesouns &amp; causes antecedente: as to myche
<PB N="65">|fulnesse of blod, o&thorn;er ellys to myche Acuyte of blod &amp; also manye|o&thorn;ere causes; and &thorn;ere be&thorn; o&thorn;ere causes &thorn;at be&thorn; clepyd causes|prymytiff; as smytinge &thorn;at wondi&thorn;, to gret lepynge, cryinge,|wra&thorn;&thorn;e, chydinge, &amp; so many<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. may.</NOTE> o&thorn;er &amp; iche of &thorn;ese causes tofore|seyde ha&thorn; hys manere helynge by hym-selfen in fesyke medecynal.|Bot it ys no&yogh;t &thorn;e entencyoun of &thorn;is boke, to tretyn but of blod, &thorn;at|bledi&thorn; of wounde, &thorn;at is y-mad wi&thorn; wounde, the <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="55b">whiche may be |restreynde by crafte of surgerye.  In flux of blod, that comyth of|a wounde, &thorn;e leche most loke &thorn;e disposicioun, &thorn;e Abytude, Age,|vertu &amp; complexioun of hym &thorn;at is y-woundyde; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ese|acorden, &amp; he be my&yogh;tye in vertue, he schal blede myche blod at|hys wounde, &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e leche be clepyde at &thorn;e bygynninge, bot &yogh;if|it so be &thorn;at he feble ouere gretlyche. &amp; &yogh;if nede constreyne &thorn;e leche|to staunche &thorn;e blode, he most loke &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e blod go out of &thorn;e|Veynes capyllares, &thorn;at be&thorn; smale veynes as herys of mannys hed;|&amp; &thorn;anne only &thorn;e whyte of an ey&yogh;e, y-leyde aboue wi&thorn; tow&yogh; of flex|suffise&thorn;, whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e wounde be&thorn; brou&yogh;t togedire;|&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou cast aboue &thorn;e poudre of lyme, tofore seyde in the chapytell|of sowynge of woundes, yt schal be &thorn;e betyre; for &thorn;e poudre|wi&thorn;streyne&thorn; &thorn;e blod &amp; consoude&thorn; &thorn;e partyes of &thorn;e wounde, togedire.
<PB N="66">|&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e blod come from gret Veynes, he may no&yogh;t so sumtyme be|constreynde, but it nedi&thorn; a strengere medycyne &amp; also a more|cautele; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e blod go out of an arterye, &thorn;ou schalt y-knowe yt|be constructioun &amp; dilatacioun, of &thorn;e same arterye&mdash;&thorn;at is to sigge,|&thorn;at &thorn;e blod go&thorn; out with lepynge, &amp; o&thorn;er whyle with wi&thorn;drawynge,|&amp; &thorn;enne sette &thorn;y fyngere vpon &thorn;e mou&thorn; of &thorn;e gret veyne, o&thorn;ere ellys|&thorn;e Artarye, &amp; holde &thorn;y fyngere &thorn;ere on by a grete oure; for &thorn;enne|by hap sum grete drope of blod may be congelyde togedre, &amp; &thorn;ereby|vertu may be myche y-comfortyde.  Afterewarde leye plentyfullyche|of &thorn;is medycine vpon &thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wounde</I>, cancelled before <I>veyne</I>.</NOTE>Veyne o&thorn;ere &thorn;e arterye &thorn;at is kut atwo.|&rx; ffrancencens, why&yogh;t gommous &amp; fat &yogh;. ii., Aloes &yogh;. i., make|poudre &amp; distempre with &thorn;e why&yogh;t of an ey&yogh;e as &thorn;ykke as hony;|after take herys of an hare smale &amp; kutte, medle al &thorn;is &thorn;ynge togedire,|&amp; &thorn;ere ys no medycine so gode as &thorn;is medycine is, in streyninge|of blod &amp; consoudynge &thorn;e Veyne.  Bot whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ou comyst|to chaunge &thorn;e medycine of &thorn;y wonde, do no&yogh;t awey &thorn;e medycine| wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e, but <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="56a">leye aboue of &thorn;e same medycine moist, to nessche|&thorn;e firste medycine, &thorn;at yt my&yogh;te fallyne awey by yt-selff.  Na&thorn;eles|yt is possible, &thorn;at a medycine caustyke, &thorn;at ys to sigge a medycine
<PB N="67">|&thorn;at brennyth, sennore staunchyth blod, &thorn;enne &thorn;is medicine of encense;|&amp; &thorn;ou schalt haue gret plente of medycine caustyke in &thorn;e antitodarye,|but we be&thorn; nou&yogh;t sykere &thorn;at &thorn;e blod of &thorn;e Veyne, o&thorn;ere &thorn;e|arterye an o&thorn;er tyme wyl gon out, whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e serche of &thorn;ylke|caustyke medycine ys remywed awey.  But &thorn;y medycine of ensence,|with &thorn;e herys of an hare, no&yogh;t only staunchi&thorn; &thorn;e blod, but also consoude&thorn;|&thorn;e Veyne, &amp; &thorn;e Arterye, as y haue preuyde yt ofte tymes.|And forto &yogh;if Autorite, I sette an saumple, &thorn;at come sum tyme to|myn handys: A childe of &thorn;re &yogh;ere olde, hadde a lyte knyf in hys|hande, &amp; he fel on &thorn;at knyf, &amp; &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e knyf, in &thorn;e fore|partye of &thorn;e &thorn;rote, persyde &thorn;e Veyne organys; ne &thorn;ere ne cou&thorn;e no|man yt staunche, &amp; &thorn;anne y was y-clepyde &amp; y come to &thorn;e child in|gret haste, &amp; he hadde almoste loste hys syght; for hys ey&yogh;en in|hys hed were turnyde vp so doun, &amp; &thorn;e blode come out of &thorn;e|wounde, whyte as whey&yogh;e, ne he ne hadde no pous, &amp; &thorn;enne y|leyde my fyngere on &thorn;e hed of &thorn;e veyne, &amp; y helde faste &thorn;at|no&thorn;ynge my&yogh;te go out, &amp; so y helde &thorn;e veyne by a grete houre, &amp;|&thorn;e vertue of hys body &thorn;at was almost lost quyknede a&yogh;eyne, &amp; &thorn;e|pous bygan to apere ffeblyche as yt were a smal &thorn;reed.  &THORN;anne y
<PB N="68">|sente to &thorn;e spysers schoppe, &thorn;at was a grete weye from me, ne y ne|remywede no&yogh;t awey my fyngere from &thorn;e place tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e messagere|come a&yogh;eyne, &amp; &thorn;e childe &thorn;enne bygan to opene hys ey&yogh;en; and|&thorn;anne y ordeynde &thorn;ilke medycine to be mad, &amp; plentyffuliche y|leyde it abouen &thorn;e wounde, and y bonde &thorn;e wounde with plumaceoles|&amp; with stupes y-leyde in why&yogh;t of an ey&yogh;e, &amp; with a bande y bonde|yt streytlye, &amp; y comaundede hem to gyuen hym crommys of brede,|y-leyde in water; and on &thorn;e morwene y come a&yogh;eyne, &amp; &thorn;enne y|fonde &thorn;e childe y-cunffortede &amp; neuere &thorn;e latere y wolde nou&yogh;t vndo| &thorn;e medycine; &thorn;e ffadire <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="56b">preyde me wi&thorn; grete instaunce to se &thorn;e|wounde, but y wolde nou&yogh;t; &amp; so y lete yt be, tyl foure dayes were|passyd, withouten remeffynge &amp; na&thorn;eles y vysitede hym every day;|in &thorn;e four&thorn;e day y vndyde &thorn;e bande, &amp; &thorn;e medycine was drye aboue|&thorn;e wounde, so &thorn;at y my&yogh;te no&yogh;t haue remywede hyt withouten grete|Vyolence. &amp; &thorn;enne y leyde aboue &thorn;e whyte of an ey&yogh;e, with a lytel|oyle of roses, &amp; so y lafte yt by on day.  On &thorn;e morwen y turnyde|a&yogh;eyne, &amp; &thorn;enne y remeffyde awey &thorn;e medycine withouten Vyolence,|&amp; &thorn;enne y fonde &thorn;e wounde &amp; &thorn;e Veyne al hol.  And of &thorn;is helynge|&thorn;e fadire &amp; alle his ney&yogh;hboures hadden gret wondire.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at|with &thorn;is medicyne &thorn;ou maiste no&yogh;t soude &thorn;e Arterye, ne &thorn;e Veyne, ne|&thorn;ou ne maiste no&yogh;t constreyne &thorn;e blod for sum o&thorn;ere Impedement,
<PB N="69">|&thorn;an &thorn;ou moste o&thorn;ere bynde &thorn;e Veyne, o&thorn;ere drawyne here out of|here place, &amp; wynde &thorn;e hed of &thorn;e Veyne o&thorn;er Arterye, o&thorn;er &thorn;ou most|brenne here wi&thorn; hote yren, &amp; maken on here hed a grete croste &amp; a|depe.  An o&thorn;ere exaumple: &thorn;ere was a childe of xv &yogh;ere olde, &thorn;at|smot hym-self with a smal knyff, &amp; &thorn;ilke knyff persyde on Veyn of|&thorn;e Arme, &amp; prikyde a Veyne &thorn;at lay vndire &thorn;ilke synwe. &amp; for &thorn;e|prikynge of &thorn;ilke synwe he hadde grete akynge, &amp; blod ran to &thorn;e|wounde &amp; no&yogh;t a&yogh;eynestondynge medycines &thorn;e blod ran out at &thorn;e|wounde.  Kolde medycines weren profitable to bledynge of wounde,|and colde medycines be&thorn; greffes to prikynge of synwes; for &thorn;ey|stoppyn &thorn;at lyme &amp; &thorn;at ys contraryus a&yogh;eyns &thorn;e synwys; and|&thorn;enne y demyde necessarye to drawe out alle &thorn;e Veyne out of here|place &amp; to bynde here &amp; to helpen &thorn;ilke synwe with oyle of roses.|But &thorn;e modire of &thorn;ilke childe sende for a lewyde leche, whyche &thorn;at|reprevyde fouliche my doom, &amp; he behy&yogh;te to helyn safflyche &thorn;e|childe.  He dwellyde on &thorn;e cure, &amp; y went my weye.  &THORN;e whyche|leche toke hede to hym be ten dayes, &thorn;at nei&thorn;ere &thorn;e akynge sesyde|ne &thorn;e blod was no&yogh;t y-staunchyde, &amp; so &thorn;e syke man was <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="57a">ny&yogh;h ded. |And at &thorn;e laste y was clepyde &amp; y wolde no&yogh;t come to &thorn;e pacient.|But &thorn;enne a ffysisyen &thorn;at was frende to &thorn;e man of &thorn;e pacyent,|blamyde &thorn;e modire &amp; here frendys, &thorn;at &thorn;ey hadde lefte my consaylle
<PB N="70">|for &thorn;e byhestys of &thorn;ylke ydyote; &amp; &thorn;ilke ffysisyens proposyde,|aftere &thorn;at he had herde my counseylle, &thorn;at &thorn;ere was non o&thorn;ere wey|&thorn;at my&yogh;te saue &thorn;e syke man from &thorn;e de&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;enne he askyde a|surgyne, whe&thorn;ere he cou&thorn;e don as y hadde seyde byfore; &amp; he|seyde &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e so don, &amp; so he dyde.  He kutte &thorn;e skyn aboue|&thorn;e Veyne, &amp; twynede &thorn;e veyne in his handys, &amp; bonde &thorn;e ende of|&thorn;e Veyne wi&thorn; a &thorn;rede, &amp; afterwarde he hylde on &thorn;e synwe hote oyle|of rosys, &amp; so by &thorn;is counseyle he was restoryde a&yogh;eyne to hele.|But ho so &thorn;at wolde aske how &thorn;at he my&yogh;te so manye dayes be|kepyde from &thorn;e crampe, for &thorn;at he suffryde so grete ak&thorn;e, I answere|&amp; sigge: &thorn;at &thorn;e cause was, for he bledde at &thorn;e wounde eche day, so|&thorn;at &thorn;e synwe ne my&yogh;te no&yogh;t be to myche replet o&thorn;ere fulfyllede of|blode.  Alle &thorn;ese thynges y haue tolde, &thorn;at he &thorn;at redyth hem may|&thorn;e wyslocor in semblable causes wyrchen.  And &yogh;if be &thorn;is medycyne|he my&yogh;te no&yogh;t sykerliche be restreynede, &thorn;at fallyth ry&yogh;te selden,|&thorn;enne me moste brenne &thorn;e hed of &thorn;e Veyne o&thorn;ere of &thorn;e synwe wi&thorn;|hote yren, &thorn;at &thorn;ilke hote yren my&yogh;te maken an harde croste.  And|be war &thorn;at &thorn;ou touche no&yogh;t &thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e wounde, ne &thorn;e synwe,|ne non o&thorn;ere thynge, bot only &thorn;e veyn with hote yren.  And &yogh;if al|&thorn;is crafte wolde no&yogh;t helpyn me, men most drawen out &thorn;e Veyne, &amp;
<PB N="71">|flene &thorn;e flesch aboue here &amp; wynde &thorn;e Veyne sadlyche &amp; bynde here|hed with &thorn;yn handys.  And sum tyme yt happyth, &thorn;at an Arterye|is y-broke o&thorn;ere y-kutte, &amp; &thorn;e flesch &thorn;at is abouen ys hol &amp; no&yogh;t to-broke|ne y-kutte, o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;e flessch &thorn;at is aboue &thorn;e Arterye ys|y-helyde &amp; no&yogh;t &thorn;e Arterye, &amp; vndire &thorn;ilke flessch &thorn;ere is a swellynge|of blode <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="57b">that is y-clepyde Aporisma o&thorn;ere matere Sanguis &amp; |&thorn;ere of &thorn;e pacient hath grete drede, lest &thorn;at &thorn;e skyn tobreke &amp; &thorn;e|blod gone out, &thorn;e whiche blod is hard to restreyne.  Of &thorn;is manere|seknesse spekyth Galyen, &amp; sei&thorn; &thorn;at a seruaunt of swyche a dysposisioun|was y-helyde of a lewyde man, &thorn;at tau&yogh;te hym &thorn;at he|scholde legge snow&yogh; vpon &thorn;at seknesse, wherfore a man may vndirstande,|&thorn;at to swyche empostemys colde medicynes &amp; drye beth|necessarye.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="10">
<PB N="72"><HEAD>&para; The x Chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge of &thorn;e firste|tretys is of men that beth y-woundyde.</HEAD>
<P>Many men discorden of dietynge of men &thorn;at ben woundyde, for|sum men &yogh;euen to alle men &thorn;at ben woundyde, whe&thorn;er &thorn;at it be in|&thorn;e hed o&thorn;er in enye o&thorn;ere place, gode wyn &amp; stronge flesch of|capouns &amp; of hennys; and &thorn;ey affermen &thorn;at by swyche a manere|weye seke woundyde men sonnere ben y-helyde, ffor &thorn;ey siggen &thorn;at|watyre putrefye&thorn; lymes, &thorn;at be&thorn; woundyde, &amp; engendrith Apostemys|&amp; corumpyth &amp; feblyth complexiouns, &amp; makyth many harmys.|Sum o&thorn;ere men gouernen alle manere of syke men &thorn;at be&thorn; woundyde|with brede &amp; water &amp; Applys y-sodyn, tyl x dayes ben passyde, &amp;|&yogh;if &thorn;at god wyl ende &thorn;is bok, yt schal be remeffynge awey Errores,|&amp; declarynge &amp; opnynge Dowtous.  Y sigge, &thorn;at bo&thorn;e &thorn;ese sectes|erryn in here opyniouns, ffor &thorn;ey taken hede onlyche to here experymentys,|no&yogh;t considerynge resoun of &thorn;e complexioun of hym &thorn;at|is y-woundyde.  The firste secte of &thorn;ese *seyth &thorn;at some men, onlye|etynge bred &amp; watere, in so myche ben y-feblyde, &thorn;at blode &amp;|matere in here bodyes may no&yogh;t be restoryde; &thorn;e whiche were suffisaunt
<PB N="73">|to hele with here woundys, bot &thorn;ey ben so feble &thorn;at &thorn;ey dy&yogh;en,|o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;ey langoren longe tyme; ne &thorn;e lyme may no&yogh;t resseyuen|resonable vertue, as he scholde; &amp; &thorn;ese manere of men ben of a|colde complexioun &amp; a drye, &amp; here bodyes weryn feble.&mdash;*The|secunde secte seyth &thorn;at some &thorn;at dronken <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="58a">wyn &amp; etyn flesch hadde |in &thorn;e membre &thorn;at was y-woundyde a gret enposteme &amp; a ffeuyre&mdash;|and &thorn;o be&thorn; &yogh;onge men &thorn;at be&thorn; of an hot complexioun &amp; a moyst&mdash;|wherefore &thorn;ey comaundyde to alle o&thorn;ere manere complexiouns, &thorn;at|&thorn;ey scholde no&yogh;t drynken no wyn, ne eten non flesch.  &THORN;e vnderstandynge|of bo&thorn;e &thorn;ese sectes nys no&yogh;t comendable and &thorn;erefore y|folwynge &thorn;e doctryne of rasys, Avence, galien, &amp; of o&thorn;er doctoris,|&amp; also experymentis, &thorn;at y haue longe y-preuyde, sigge &thorn;at it is|nedefull in &thorn;e bygynnynge &thorn;at a woundyde man Absteyne hym|from wyn &amp; namlye &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be in &thorn;e hed, o&thorn;ere in eny|partye of a synwe.  For &thorn;ere nys no&thorn;ynge &thorn;at so sone smyte&thorn; with|grevaunce &thorn;e hed o&thorn;ere &thorn;e synwe as wyn; for he ys sone conuertyde|of kendlye hete, and for he ys so sotyll, he persyth swi&thorn;e into &thorn;e|synwes &amp; he assendyth sone into &thorn;e hed, bryngynge with hym|humores and spirites.  Yt trublyth a mannys wyt, &amp; wyn greuyff|alle men that ha&thorn; a feble hed; &amp; &thorn;ere fore in alle manere woundys
<PB N="74">|of &thorn;e hed &amp; off synwes, he schal be forebode in &thorn;e bygynnynge, &amp;|namlye to &thorn;o &thorn;at han hot complexiouns &amp; moiste, into &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at|&thorn;e cure be ful endyde; &amp; to &thorn;o &thorn;at be&thorn; of colde complexioun,|whenne &thorn;re dayes ben passyde, &thorn;ou maiste &yogh;euen to drynke a smal|temperat wyn, &amp; afterewarde a lyte strengore; aftere &thorn;at &thorn;ou art|sykere, &thorn;at &thorn;ere schal no&yogh;t comen to &thorn;e membre non Aposteme., But|his drynke schal be watyre of barlyche o&thorn;ere watire &thorn;at crommes of|brede ben sodyn yn, wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere colde watyr &amp; namlye in sommere,|&amp; to &thorn;o &thorn;at be&thorn; woundyde drynke watyre, o&thorn;ere ellys wi&thorn; ten&thorn;e|partye of wyn of pome garnettys, o&thorn;ere ellys wyth sixte partye of|wyn agreste &thorn;at is smal broske wyn, o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;is is a perfyte|drynke to wondys of &thorn;e hed &amp; of synwys: Take a potell of watyr|&amp; of barlyche y-meynde <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. iij, juiube, sebesten, ana .&yogh; <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, of drye|prunes of damacynes <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> .j., sucre of rosis <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> ij, sethe hem to &thorn;re|partyes ben consumed, &amp; &thorn;enne lete hym drynken yt.  Sothlye &thorn;is|drynke ys alteratyff: &thorn;at ys to sigge chaungynge, ne hyt ne swellyth| no&yogh;t. &amp; yt latte&thorn; fumosites to arysen to &thorn;e brayn.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="58b">Of mete
<PB N="75">|y sigge: &thorn;at to hym &thorn;at is of an hot &amp; moiste complexioun, be|non manere weye ne scholde no&yogh;t be &yogh;effen flesch, ffysch, Mylke,|eyren, ne no manere conuertyble mete, bot &yogh;if &thorn;ey weryn ouere come|with to gret febylnesse; but he moste holde hym content with Iuse|of barlyche, o&thorn;ere ellys of otys wi&thorn; almaunde mylke; out take|wounde of &thorn;e hed, where y ne Apreue no&yogh;t Almaundys, ne non o&thorn;ere|vaporose frutys, as notys o&thorn;er walnottys o&thorn;er Avelanes, for &thorn;ey|hauen a manere fumose proprete greuynge &thorn;e hed; he may etyn|Amidun, betes, letuse &amp; bred y-wassche wi&thorn; succre, &yogh;if &thorn;at he were|feble.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at my&yogh;te no&yogh;t Abstynen hym from flesch, &yogh;if hym|flesch of smale chyknes, &amp; of smale briddys: as larkys &amp; o&thorn;ere|sengle briddys, &amp; kyddes &amp; lambres, &amp; kalffes I-saveryde with|agresta, o&thorn;er with wyn of pom garnett; &amp; &thorn;is dyetynge he schall|vse, tyl he be sykere from swellynge, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt y-knowe,|whenne &thorn;at Akynge, swellynge &amp; extencioun of &thorn;e lyme ben secyde|&amp; &thorn;e wounde is almost consouded.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at it was a wounde &thorn;at|was sowyde o&thorn;ere brou&yogh;t togedyre with byndynge, in whom quyter|was no&yogh;t engendryde, and &yogh;if &thorn;at it was a wounde y-mad wyth|smytinge&mdash;o&thorn;ere ellys y-chaungyde with &thorn;e eyre, in whom yt is nedfull|engendrynge of quyter, &thorn;enne yt is sykere &thorn;at yt schal nou&yogh;t
<PB N="76">|enposteme, whenne &thorn;at he maky&thorn; quyter plentyouuslyche; &amp;|whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e lyme ys wel dysposyde &amp; no&yogh;t toswolle, ne y-drawen|abrode. &amp; ys wi&thorn;outen akynge, &amp; &thorn;anne chaunge a lytel &amp; a lytel|hys dyetynge, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;ou come to hys dyetynge, &thorn;at he was wont|to vse tofore.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e pacient were of a colde complexioun|&amp; a drye &amp; &thorn;at he hadde by nature o&thorn;ere by costeme a feble stomak,| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="59a">&thorn;anne yt were necessarye to &yogh;euen hym at &thorn;e bygynnynge flesch a|lytel y-saueryde with swote spysorye: as kanell gyngeffre &amp; o&thorn;ere|semblable to hem &amp; to &yogh;euen hym in &thorn;e bygynninge Julep&mdash;&thorn;at is a|syripe y-mad only of watyre &amp; of sucre&mdash;&amp; aftere &thorn;re dayes ben|passyde, wyn, and bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e on complexioun &amp; in &thorn;e o&thorn;ere complexioun.|&YOGH;if &thorn;at a bon were y-broke, wi&thorn; a wonde ore wi&thorn;outen|a wounde, aboute &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e cure, &thorn;at is to sigge, whenne &thorn;ou art|sykere from a posteme &amp; swellynge, yt is gode to &yogh;if norysschande|mete, &thorn;at it my&yogh;te make a gode &amp; a stronge repayrment of &thorn;e bone|&thorn;at was tobroke: as with ffurmente y-sode, &amp; potage of floure wel|y-sode, &amp; with &thorn;e extremetes of bestys, as fette &amp; swynes groynes &amp;|oxe wombys wel y-soden, &amp; with swiche o&thorn;ere &thorn;ynges by whom a|gode ligamente &amp; a stronge may wel be engendrede.  Where fore|yt is necessarie to a surgyne to knowe in hys dyetynge, vertues of|complexiouns, Ages, regeouns consuetudes &amp; &thorn;e tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, &thorn;at
<PB N="77">|he mowe chaungen his dyetynge, aftere &thorn;at dyverse condycioun|askyth*.  Ne he ne schal no&yogh;t aftere on manere of counseylle proceden|in hys dyetynge.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="11">
<HEAD>&para; The xi. Chapitle of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge of &thorn;e firste|tretys is of olde woundes.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Olde woundes ben mad of kuttynge o&thorn;er of openynge of a|posteme, o&thorn;ere ellys of a wounde &thorn;at is no&yogh;t helyde in his tyme, o&thorn;er|ellys of sum manere fleynge o&thorn;er of brennynge, o&thorn;er of to grete hete,|o&thorn;er of to grete drov&thorn;e, o&thorn;er to gret colde constreynynge, o&thorn;ere of to|grete Abundaunce of moist mater corumpynge.  For euery olde|wounde, hauynge rotenesse o&thorn;ere virus &thorn;at is &thorn;enne venemy quyter,|o&thorn;er eny o&thorn;er &thorn;ynge &thorn;enne gode quyter nys no&yogh;t y-clepyde wounde,|but is y-clepyde vlous &thorn;at is an olde wounde.  And of &thorn;is Vlcus,|Rouland &amp; Rogerine, &amp; &thorn;e most partye of men &thorn;at ben now, clepyde|it festre, o&thorn;er cancre.  But it is nei&thorn;ere festre ne cancre, but festre &amp;|cankre habbe dyfference from &thorn;is.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="59b">Vlcus, as a propre &thorn;ynge hath |dyfference, from a &thorn;ynge, &thorn;at is comyn; for euerye festre &amp; euerye|cankere, &thorn;at is y-woundyde, ys y-clepyde Vlcus, but yt ne syweth|no&yogh;t &thorn;at euerye Vlcus, ys clepyde cankre o&thorn;ere festre, as y schal
<PB N="78">|tellen opynlyche in euerye chapytell be hym-self.  Auesene seyth|&thorn;at &thorn;ere ben sixe manere of &thorn;ese Vlcus, for sum ben Venemy, sum|hory, some depe, some cauernouse o&thorn;ere y-hud, sum corosyff, sum|rotyne, some Ambulatyff&mdash;&thorn;at is spredynge abrode, &amp; some hard|to consouden.  Of &thorn;ese manerys tofore seyde, some hath acordynge|with festres in toknes &amp; in fourmes: as Venemy &amp; holwy, &amp; sum|han acordynge with cancre: as spredynge abrode &amp; fretynge hym|self.  And na&thorn;eles &thorn;ey habbe difference as yt is conteynede in &thorn;e|chapytelles of cancre y-woundyde &amp; of festre.  &amp; alle &thorn;ese tofore|seyde habbith difference from a wounde, for in a wounde &thorn;ere ys|whyte quyter &amp; euene in al his partyes &amp; hol &amp; no&yogh;t departyde,|&mdash;&amp; withouten stynke.  &THORN;is manere of quyter is engendrede, of|godnesse of kendlye hete &amp; is perfitlye deffyede.  But vemyn,|rottenesse, &amp; croste, &amp; alle o&thorn;ere superfluyte of olde woundes ben|engendred of a straunge vnkendlye hete.  A venemy Vlcus is, in|whom habunde&thorn; venym sotyl &amp; liquydy.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at yt be red o&thorn;ere|&yogh;olwe, o&thorn;ere a partye redyssche, &amp; scharpe bytynge &thorn;e lyme, hit|synifie&thorn; lordschipe of straunge hete.  An hory olde wounde ys|y-clepyd, &thorn;at ha&thorn; sum grete crostes, o&thorn;ere ellys sum grete awrotynge
<PB N="79">|proud flesch to hy&yogh;e.  A depe Vlcus is &thorn;at &thorn;at ha&thorn; a gret depnesse|&amp; an holwe, &amp; peraunter crokynge.  A wrotynge vlcus is &thorn;at of|hys malyce wrote&thorn;, bycause &thorn;at &thorn;e blod &thorn;at is sent to hym, is to|scharpe.  Galien: scharpe blod no&yogh;t onlyche cordyth no&yogh;t *flesch in|woundes, but also hol flesch.  A rotyde vlcus is stynkynge, habbynge|a straunge hete in his grounde, &amp; out of hym passith out a|stynkynge smel o&thorn;ere smoke, as &thorn;ere do&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="60a">out of flesch &thorn;at is |y-rotyde.  A walkynge Vlcus is &thorn;at walke&thorn; hyderwarde &amp; &thorn;edirwarde|&amp; na&thorn;eles he profunde&thorn; no&yogh;t depe into &thorn;e grounde.  An|Vlcus &thorn;at is hard to helyn, is he &thorn;at for his yuele proprete, &thorn;at is|sende to hym fro al &thorn;e body, latte&thorn; hym to hele.  &amp; forto helyn|euery manere of &thorn;ese hulkes, &thorn;ere ben manye dyverse rulys.  &THORN;e|firste rule ys &thorn;at &thorn;ey mowe no&yogh;t ben helyde, but &thorn;e superfluytes|&thorn;at ben in hem ben dryed.  &THORN;e secunde rule ys &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e body|o&thorn;ere membre be out of hys naturell complexioun, ere &thorn;an &thorn;ou|&thorn;ynke to hele &thorn;ilke Vlcus, &thorn;ou moste bryngen a&yogh;eyne to hys due
<PB N="80">|complexioun distempride<NOTE PLACE="foot">At the margin.</NOTE> &thorn;ilke body o&thorn;er membre.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde rule|ys, &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e lyfere o&thorn;ere splene ben y-greuyde, as yt happyth|ofte tymes in olde woundes, &thorn;ou most retyfien hem.  The fourth|rule ys: &thorn;at &thorn;e qualites &amp; quantytes of humours scholde be tempride|with blodletynge, &amp; purgatiouns &amp; with gode governaylle; and|&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e eyre be yuel, &thorn;e syke man schal be chaungyde into gode|eire.  And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e leche ha&thorn; tofore seye alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ynges,|&thorn;enne he may go to hys cure.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e Vlcus be Virulente, &thorn;at|is to sigge Venemy, loke &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e Venym &thorn;at go&thorn; out be redyssch|o&thorn;ere &yogh;olwe, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at the lyme haue enye manere hete; &amp; &thorn;enne|wassche it wi&thorn; water &thorn;at rosys &amp; barlyche Alum &amp; balaustia &amp;|lentilis with honye symple o&thorn;ere componed ben sodyn In.  And lete|&thorn;is watere percen to &thorn;e depthe of &thorn;e wounde.  And &yogh;if &thorn;e Virus be|withouten hete &amp; &thorn;e membre haue non hete, wassche it with water|o&thorn;ere wy&thorn; wyn, &thorn;at Mirre, wermot, horhowne, sauge, pympirnel,|honye symple o&thorn;er componed ben sodyn In.  Clanse &thorn;e wounde|perfitlye &amp; engendre flesch &amp; afterwarde consoud it with &thorn;is propre|oygnement, &thorn;at in olde foule venemy woundys o&thorn;er Vlcus engendreth
<PB N="81">|flesch, clansyth &amp; helyth as Auecene &amp; Rases wytnessith,|litargium nutritum.  &rx; litarge as myche as &thorn;ou wylt &amp; stampe it|&amp; put it in a mortere &amp; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="60b">putte wi&thorn; hym gode oyle of roses &amp; |vynegre, now &thorn;e on now &thorn;e o&thorn;ere, alweye steryinge, tyl it be perfitlyche|augmentyd &amp; come to &thorn;e fourme of an oygnement.  &amp; &thorn;is|oygnement&mdash;litargirum nutritum&mdash;&thorn;at is to sigge litarge y-noryssched,|&thorn;at is profitable in many casis.  Afterwarde take of &thorn;ilke litarge|viij partyes, &amp; of alym, &amp; of balaustie o&thorn;ere ellys, in &thorn;e stede of|balaustye, wormys of &thorn;e er&thorn;e y-brend, brend bras, brent led, gallys,|sanke dragoun, cathimie, Argenti ana as mychel as ys .xij partyes|of alle &thorn;e oygnement, and medle al togedre, &amp; make an Oygnement.|&THORN;is oygnement schal be leyde withynne &thorn;e woundes &amp; aboue|&thorn;e wounde, for yt dryeth &thorn;e wounde, &amp; engendrith gode flesch &amp;|consoud.  Take hede to &thorn;is rule, &thorn;at in helynge of alle olde|woundes, aftere &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben clansyde, aboue &thorn;e oygnement yt is|gode of one a lynnen clo&thorn;, forto dystende abrode on of &thorn;e mundyficatyfes|of hony whiche &thorn;at schulle be tolde in &thorn;e antitodarye.  And|leye aboue aboute &thorn;ilke vlcus, &amp; specialiche from &thorn;e ouere partye,|fro whom humores flotyn, a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&amp;.</I></NOTE> defensif of bol Armonyake &amp; terra
<PB N="82">|sigillata &thorn;at is mad on &thorn;ys manere: &rx; bol armoneake <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> j terre|sigillate <ABBR EXPAN="[dram]">&yogh;</ABBR> <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>., oyle of rosis &amp; vynegre, &thorn;at suffyse&thorn;, now do in &thorn;e on,|now &thorn;e o&thorn;er, tyl &thorn;e oygnement be ful mad &amp; lyquyde ynow&yogh;; so|&thorn;at of &thorn;e oyle of roses be duble as myche as of &thorn;e vynegre.  &THORN;is|diffensiff defendi&thorn; a membre fro corupcioun, &amp; also Vlcus &thorn;at he|sprede no&yogh;t abrode.  An hory wonde ys y-helyde, in remeffynge|awey &thorn;e croste o&thorn;ere &thorn;e fylthe &thorn;at is in hym with poudre of affodylles|schal be sayde in &thorn;e ende, o&thorn;ere with sum o&thorn;ere mundificatyfes;|afterwarde consoude yt with consolydatyfes.  A depe wounde ys| y-helyde in castynge in to &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="61a">dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e wounde with an instrument|y-mad to &thorn;e lyknesse of a clisteyre, any of &thorn;e wasschynges &thorn;at be&thorn;|seyde in &thorn;e Venemy wounde aboue, after &thorn;at &thorn;e disposisioun of &thorn;e|membre aske&thorn; of hete o&thorn;er of cold.  And aftere &thorn;at he is y-clansyde,|in castynge in water o&thorn;ere in wyn &thorn;at mastyke o&thorn;ere frankensence|ys y-soden yn, &amp; in leggynge without, on of &thorn;e mundificatyfes of|hony, &thorn;at schal be sayde aftere.  &amp; also it is gode to ordeyne &thorn;e|lyme, so &thorn;at &thorn;e mouth of &thorn;e wounde honge dunwarde, &amp; streyne &thorn;i|ligature at &thorn;e grounde of &thorn;y wounde &amp; bynde it looslye at &thorn;e mou&thorn;|of &thorn;e wounde.  And also yt were gode, &yogh;if &thorn;at it my&yogh;te be, &thorn;at &thorn;ere|were made a newe wounde in &thorn;e place &thorn;at is most hongynge &thorn;at &thorn;e
<PB N="83">|rotnesse &amp; &thorn;e quytere my&yogh;te &thorn;e betyre gone out, for so &thorn;ilke Vlcus|my&yogh;te sunnere be helyde.  A ffretynge vlcus ys y-helyde, in leggynge|specialiche aboute hym colde &thorn;ynges, whiche &thorn;at obtunden o&thorn;er|castyn bach &thorn;e scharpnesse of &thorn;e same Vlcus, &amp; also in amendynge|with metys &amp; with drynkes the scharpnesse of &thorn;e same blod, &amp; in|purgynge &thorn;e rede colore &amp; with anoyntynge wi&thorn; colde oygnementes|&amp; consolidatifes, &amp; &thorn;ereto is myche wor&thorn; vnguentum album Rasis,|&thorn;at schal be told in &thorn;e antitodarye.  A stynkynge wounde ys|y-helyde in remevynge awey &thorn;e stenche &amp; &thorn;e rottenesse, &amp; &thorn;erto ys|myche worth a wasschynge of ydromel &thorn;at is hony &amp; water y-sode|togidre wi&thorn; mirre, &amp; a mundyficatiff y-mad with Ius of wermot &amp;|barly mele &amp; hony &amp; mirre, &thorn;at is made on &thorn;is manere: take jus of|wermot .<ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR>. iiij, of hony <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> iij, of barly mele .&yogh;. ij, off mirre <ABBR EXPAN="[ounce]"><GAP></ABBR> .j.,|compone hem togedire, &amp; fulle &thorn;e wounde, wi&thorn;ynne forth wi&thorn;|lynete of lynnen clo&thorn;.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at wormys ben engendride in &thorn;e|wounde, sle hem wi&thorn; jus of calamynte, o&thorn;ere with &thorn;e juse of &thorn;e leuys|of pechys, o&thorn;ere ellys persicarie, o&thorn;er with decoccion <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="61b">of ellebre. |And whanne &thorn;at a perfyte mundyficacioun is mad engendre flesch|&amp; consoude, as yt is seyde tofore.  A walkynge Vlcus ys y-helyde|with flebotomye &amp; ffarmasye &thorn;at is laxatyfes purgynge &thorn;e colere &amp;
<PB N="84">|brende humoures, &amp; in leggynge aboute a defensif of bol &amp; terra|sigillata &thorn;at is seide tofore in &thorn;e same Chapytle, &amp; with on of &thorn;e|colde mundyficatyfes &amp; sum tyme men most cauterise &thorn;e Vlcus|aboue with an instrument of gold.  for &thorn;ilke manere of brennynge|rectefie&thorn; wel &thorn;e membre.  &THORN;e cause why &thorn;at sum Vlcus is hard to|consoude is, for an yuel disposicion ys y-hydde in &thorn;e bodye, &amp; &thorn;erefore|it nedyth to retyfien &thorn;e membre &amp; &thorn;e body as y haue seide to-fore.|And &yogh;if &thorn;e cause be opene, on o&thorn;ere manye, do aweye &thorn;ilke|causes o&thorn;er ellys &thorn;o manye causes, ere &thorn;anne &thorn;ou go to &thorn;e pryncipal|cure.  &THORN;ese ben &thorn;e causes &thorn;at lettyn consoudynge of olde woundes,|an yuele disposisioun of alle &thorn;e body: as dropsye, o&thorn;er ellys an iuele|disposisioun of &thorn;e lyuere: as &yogh;if &thorn;at he be to feble, as to hot o&thorn;ere|to colde, to moiste o&thorn;ere to drye, with mater ore withouten matere,|as wi&thorn; to grete hardnesse; o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;e spleen is to feble to purge|&thorn;e malancolyent blod; o&thorn;ere ellys to myche blod, o&thorn;ere ellys to|acute blod; o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;e veynes be&thorn; to ful of blod, &thorn;at go&thorn; doun|to &thorn;e Vlcus; o&thorn;er ellys curnellys &thorn;at glandeles, &thorn;at be&thorn; kurnellys|&thorn;at be&thorn; in &thorn;e grynde, &thorn;at sendi&thorn; doun matere to &thorn;e Vlcus &thorn;at is in|&thorn;e thy&yogh;es &amp; &thorn;e legges, o&thorn;er ellys &thorn;e lippes of &thorn;e Vlcus be&thorn; to grete|&amp; hard, o&thorn;ere ellys to myche flesch, o&thorn;er ellys mysordeyninge of
<PB N="85">|dyetynge, o&thorn;er ellys an vncouenable medycine to &thorn;ilke membre,|o&thorn;er ellis &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at ys y-hurt ha&thorn; an yuele discrasie, o&thorn;ere ellys|&thorn;ilke Vlcus is an yuele place&mdash;as in &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e elbowe, o&thorn;ere ellys |&thorn;e Vlcus ys al rounde, o&thorn;ere ellys &thorn;e bon &thorn;at is vndire <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="62a">&thorn;e vlcus is|corupte.  Alle &thorn;ese tofore seide lette&thorn; Vlcus to by helyde, wherefore|yt nedi&thorn; &thorn;e, to take kepe to alle &thorn;ese thynges tofore seyde, &amp;|to amendyn alle &thorn;e body, &amp; namlye &thorn;e lymes &thorn;at habbi&thorn; principalte|in mannes body, &amp; kepe alle &thorn;e lymes &thorn;at be&thorn; in here naturell|disposisioun wi&thorn; &thorn;ynges &thorn;at be&thorn; acordynge to here naturel disposisioun,|&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ey ben discrasyede, remywe &thorn;ilke discrasye with &thorn;at,|&thorn;at is contrarye to &thorn;ilke discrasye.  Also tempre &thorn;e qualyte &amp; &thorn;e|quantyte of &thorn;e blod, &amp; streyne &thorn;e veynes &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ey brynge &thorn;edire|blod.  O&thorn;er ellys &yogh;if it is possible, lete &thorn;e blod aweye.  Vndo|glandeles, &thorn;at be&thorn; kurnell &thorn;at sende&thorn; &thorn;edire mater, &amp; remywe ded|flesch, smale lippes of &thorn;e woundes &thorn;at be&thorn; grete, &amp; kytte hem awey,|&yogh;if &thorn;ou maiste do non o&thorn;ere weys; amende his dyetynge, &amp; brynge|a&yogh;eyne &thorn;e roundnesse of &thorn;ilke Vlcus in to a longe fourme, aftere &thorn;e|leng&thorn;e of &thorn;e membre, wi&thorn; a knyf hot brennynge, but &yogh;if &thorn;at a|synwe o&thorn;ere a Veyne latte.  And &thorn;ou schalt remywe &thorn;e bon, &thorn;at is|corupe on &thorn;is manere: unwrey al &thorn;e bon, in kuttynge awey al &thorn;e|flesch,*&mdash;&thorn;e bon &thorn;at is corupte with an yren, o&thorn;er wi&thorn; a medicyne|&thorn;at schal be seyde in &thorn;e laste ende of &thorn;is boke.  O&thorn;er ellys it is
<PB N="86">|bettere to don it awey with hot yren &amp; whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e bon &thorn;at is|corupte is vnkeueryde, schaue yt no&yogh;t as many men don, but touche|harde &thorn;ilke bon with hot yren &amp; afterewarde helde on &thorn;ilke bon|hot oyle of rosys, &amp; leye on one of &thorn;e mundyficatyfes &thorn;at be&thorn; in &thorn;e|antitodarye, whiche &thorn;at wylle remywe &thorn;e rotyde bon withoute violence.|Ffor vndirstond wel, &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ou clanse &thorn;e rotyde bon with|schavynge o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; vylinge with vyolence, neuere &thorn;e latere kynde|wyl afterwarde don aweye a schelle of &thorn;ilke same bon, no&yogh;t a&yogh;enstondynge|&thorn;y schauynge &amp; &thorn;y raspynge; wherefore in remefynge|&thorn;ilke bon, &thorn;ou multiplyest &thorn;y trauell, &amp; &thorn;ou makyste no mundificatioun|to &thorn;e folle; &amp; &thorn;erof may come ofte tymes, an yuele festre.|And inconuenient medycine ys amendyde, in consyderynge &thorn;e| complexioun <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="62b">of alle &thorn;e bodye, &amp; &thorn;e complexioun of &thorn;e lyme, &amp; &thorn;e|gree of &thorn;e medycine; for &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e membre be drye as &thorn;e erys, nose&thorn;rylles|&amp; alle bony &amp; grestly lemes, &amp; &thorn;ey han grete putrede &amp;|roteschippe, &thorn;enne &thorn;ou nedyste a ful drye medycyne; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e|body o&thorn;ere &thorn;e membre be naturellyche moist, &yogh;if &thorn;at he haue a lyte|putrede o&thorn;ere roteschippe, &thorn;anne thou nedyste a medycine &thorn;at ys|lyte dryinge.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at the body o&thorn;ere &thorn;e lymes ben mene|betwene fatnesse and lenesse&mdash;&thorn;at nys nei&thorn;ere to fatte ne to lene,|&thorn;enne &thorn;ou nedyst a medycine &thorn;at is in kynde, mesurablyche dryinge.
<PB N="87">|And &yogh;if &thorn;at two membrys ben in complexioun i-lyche euene, &amp; &thorn;e|on haue myche quyter &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere lyte quyter, he &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e more|quyter nedyth &thorn;e dreyere medycine,*&mdash;&mdash;afterwarde it nedi&thorn; by|mesure &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepe naturel &thorn;ynge, with &thorn;ynge &thorn;at is acordynge to|&thorn;e same nature, and also to remeffe with mesurable contraryouste|&thorn;ynge &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyns kynde.  But &thorn;e quantite of medicynes &thorn;at|scholde<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at scholde</I>, twice.</NOTE> be leyde to &thorn;e sore, as Galien witnesse&thorn;, ne may no&yogh;t with|lettres ben wryten.  Neuer &thorn;e latere it suffisith, &thorn;at a man defye &thorn;e|medycine, aftere &thorn;e complexioun may bere; ffor kynde &thorn;at is|wondirfull fulfylle&thorn; &thorn;ynge &thorn;at is absent &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at is to myche|castyth aweye, but &yogh;if &thorn;at it be to myche a&yogh;eyne kynde; &amp; &thorn;anne|kynde most nedys faylen in his kendlye wirchynge.  A medycine|mundyficatyff &amp; exsiccatif &thorn;at is necessarie in eche olde holwe,|vlcere,*&mdash;may be knowe by &thorn;is manere: &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e medycine make|&thorn;enne quyter &amp; blody &amp; make &thorn;e wounde holwere &thorn;an he scholde|be, &thorn;enne ys &thorn;e medycine to acute; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e quyter be &thorn;ikke &amp;|tow&yogh;, &thorn;enne ys &thorn;e medycine to lythye; and also an o&thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>medycine</I>, cancelled before <I>signe</I>.</NOTE> signe &thorn;at
<PB N="88">|&thorn;y medycine is to scharpe, &thorn;at &thorn;e place about &thorn;e wounde ys to grene,|blake, red o&thorn;ere to &yogh;elwe &amp; &thorn;e syke man fely&thorn; to grete hete <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="63a">&amp;| brennynge, &amp; also &thorn;e Venym of &thorn;e wounde multiplyeth, and whanne|&thorn;e vnkunnynge leche se&thorn; &thorn;ese Accidentes tofore seyde, he ordeyne&thorn;|a dryere medycine; &amp; so eche day &thorn;e wounde apeirith.  And &thorn;e|signe &thorn;at &thorn;e medycine is of feble dreyinge is &thorn;at &thorn;e quyter &amp; &thorn;e|rotnesse, &thorn;at go&thorn; out &thorn;ere of, ys gret in substaunce, ponderose &amp;|vneuene, wan o&thorn;er pale; &thorn;e membre is colde whyte o&thorn;er wan, o&thorn;er|clere in coloure, o&thorn;er softe, &amp; &thorn;e syke man felyth colde in his|membre, &amp; whenne &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowist &thorn;ese &thorn;ynges in &thorn;e firste cas,|make no&yogh;t &thorn;y medycine so drye.  In &thorn;e secunde cas make &thorn;y medycine|more drye, &amp; so chaunge &thorn;y wirkynge, as condyciouns of kynde|askyth, bo&thorn;e of body &amp; of membre, as wel symple as componede|medycines.  He &thorn;at knowi&thorn; no&yogh;t &thorn;ese kanones wel*&mdash;schal helen|olde woundes; wherefore manye lechys brynge ly&yogh;te woundes wi&thorn;|here iuele wirchynge, into &thorn;e worste olde woundes, &thorn;e whiche mowe|no&yogh;t aftere be helyde by a gode leche.  &THORN;ese ben ly&yogh;te medycines,|whiche &thorn;at drye olde wondys &thorn;at neden a lytel dry&yogh;inge; mastyke,|ffrankensence, barlymele.  &THORN;ese medicynes be&thorn; sumwhat dreyere:|yreos. Aristologia. Orobum &thorn;at is wilde Tare, lupines, &thorn;e rotenesse
