<HEAD>&para; Cap. xiii off &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge off &thorn;e ffirste tretys|is Off a Canker.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Cankyre y-woundyde comyth of opnynge, o&thorn;ere of kuttynge,|o&thorn;ere of brekynge of a cancre no&yogh;t y-woundyde, whose techynge &thorn;ou
<PB N="93">|schalt habbyn in &thorn;e Chapitle of enpostemes in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge|&amp; he comyth of a wounde yuele y-helyde, to whom comyth a maly-colient|rotyde matere, o&thorn;er for &thorn;at &thorn;e matere come&thorn; to &thorn;e wounde is|&thorn;ere coruppyd, &amp; chaungyth &thorn;e Ulcus into a Cankere.  And &thorn;ese be&thorn;|&thorn;e toknys of &thorn;e cankere: &thorn;e Ulcus ys foule &amp; stynkynge, &thorn;e lippes|be&thorn; grete, wanne, o&thorn;ere blake, harde, and wi&thorn;inne kernelly, &amp; ouere|alle aboute areryde &amp; holwy, &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e dyfference bytwene cancre|&amp; a foule Ulcus &amp; an hory, of whom y haue made mensioun aboue,|&thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wassche hem bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>o&thorn;ere.</I></NOTE> wi&thorn; ley&yogh;e, &thorn;e cancre schal ben|pale &amp; foulere &thorn;enne he was tofore, &amp; &thorn;ere schal fallen out of hym|pecys, gobetmele.  And &thorn;e Ulcus ys y-clansede with &thorn;ilke ley&yogh;e, &amp;|&thorn;e flesch ys made fayrere &thorn;enne yt was tofore, ne &thorn;e Ulcus stynke&thorn;|no&yogh;t by &thorn;e same stenche as &thorn;e cancre do&thorn;; for &thorn;e cankre hath a|propre saffoure, &thorn;e which may no&yogh;t be wryten wi&thorn; lettres, but &thorn;ilke|safoure ys best knowyn to of men, whiche &thorn;at beste han seye|cankrys.  A <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="65a">generall rule in &thorn;e cure of cankre ys, &thorn;at a cankyre |may no&yogh;t ben helyde bot &yogh;if &thorn;at he be done awey wi&thorn; alle hys|rotys.  The secunde rule ys, &thorn;at he schal no&yogh;t ben touchyde with|hot yren ne wi&thorn; hot medycyne caustyk&mdash;&thorn;at is to sigge, brennynge
<PB N="94">|&mdash;but he be in place, &thorn;ere he may al be don away; ffor &thorn;e more|&thorn;at &thorn;ou touchiste hym with a vyolent thynge o&thorn;er medycine, &thorn;e|more hys malys is encressyde.  Take &thorn;enne gode hede &yogh;if he be in|a fleschlye place, where &thorn;at he may be don al aweye, &amp; &thorn;enne kutte|hym al aweye wi&thorn; alle hys rotys, &amp; &thorn;ruste out &thorn;e malencolyent blod|&thorn;at ys withynne &thorn;e Veynes, &thorn;at be&thorn; aboute &thorn;e cancre, &amp; afterwarde|brenne alle aboute in &thorn;e place, &thorn;ere as &thorn;e cankre was, wi&thorn; hote|yren.  Afterward leye on &thorn;is confectioun y-mad of floure of whete|hony, jus of smallache, tyl &thorn;at he be perfitly y-clansyde.  After|regenere flesch &amp; cycatrice.  To &thorn;is rule take hede as ofte as &thorn;ou|wylt wi&thorn; surgerye helyn a cancre: furst evacue &thorn;e malencolyent|matere, ffor &thorn;at is ypocras techynge, &amp; &yogh;if he be growen in swyche|a place, &thorn;ere as he may no&yogh;t be done alle aweye, as in &thorn;e nekke ore|in &thorn;e tetys, o&thorn;ere in &thorn;e face, ore in &thorn;e ers hole, o&thorn;er in &thorn;e marys,|and also for the schortere conclusioun, &amp; he be entrede in enye|place, &thorn;ere as enye Veynes, synwes, &amp; arteryes bu&thorn;, as ypocras|seith, yt ys betyre no&yogh;t to cure &thorn;e cancre, &thorn;en to cure; ffor he be|curyde, &thorn;at is to sigge, y-kutte o&thorn;ere y-brent, &thorn;ey perysschen|sonnere; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ey be no&yogh;t curyde &thorn;ey lyuen longe tyme&mdash;libro|sexto afforismorum Cancri absconditi multum tempus per ficiunt
<PB N="95">curati vero cicius pereunt.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Regula</I>, in margin.</NOTE> &para; But diffende &thorn;e lyme &thorn;at is hol|aboute with defensiff of bol, &thorn;at y haue ofte tymes seyde, &amp; wassche|&thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e cancre with gotys whey&yogh;, &amp; drye yt softlyche &amp;|anoynt &thorn;e wounde withinne &amp; without, with &thorn;is oygnement of rasys|of tutye, &rx; ceruse, tuthye, y-wasschyn and medle hem wi&thorn; oyle of|roses &amp; wi&thorn; jus of poslane, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="65b">o&thorn;ere of sum o&thorn;ere colde erbe, now |puttynge in sum of &thorn;e on &amp; now sum of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere, tyl &thorn;e oygnement|be ful mad.  &THORN;is oygnement ys myche worth forto diffende; &thorn;at &thorn;e|malys of &thorn;e cancre &thorn;at is y-woundyde schal no&yogh;t waxen, and also|&thorn;at &thorn;e pacient vse a gode gouernaylle: as drynkinge gode wyn &amp;|clere &amp; ly&yogh;t, &amp; he mote leuen red wyn and troblyde &amp; &thorn;ykke wyn;|&amp; he may eten gode flesch, as motoun of a we&thorn;ire, kyde fflesch|sokkynge, Capouns, hennys, Chykenys, partryches, ffesauntes, &amp;|smale briddes, &amp; he moste leuyn beffys flesch, gotys fflesch, hertys|flesch, harys fflesch, goses, dokys, &amp; alle grete briddys. &thorn;at lyuen|in watrye places, &amp; alle salt &thorn;ynge &amp; acute &thorn;ynge: as garlyke,|Oynouns, vynegre, &amp;c.;, &thorn;at* &thorn;e syke men mowe lyuen &thorn;e lengere vpon
<PB N="96">|erthe.  Na&thorn;eles &yogh;if vlcus be ry&yogh;t foul &amp; hath nou&yogh;t so gret malys as|a cancre, off &thorn;e whyche Vlcus y haue tolde tofore, may ben y-curyde|wi&thorn; poudre of affedylle, and afterwarde wel be clansyde, &amp; for &thorn;at|&thorn;is Vlcus &thorn;at was so foul may be helyde.  Rogeryne &amp; Rouland|&amp; manye o&thorn;ere settyde in here bokys &thorn;e cure of &thorn;e cancre, &thorn;ow&yogh;|&thorn;at he be in a synwy place, &amp; &thorn;ey siggen &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue helyde hym.|But vndirstande wel for certeyne, &thorn;at an olde cancre may no&yogh;t ben|helyde by none o&thorn;ere wey, bote by &thorn;e same wey, whiche &thorn;at y haue|seyde in &thorn;e bygynnynge of &thorn;ys chapytell.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou dredyst,|whe&thorn;ere &thorn;at yt be a cancre o&thorn;ere a symple Vlcus &amp; a foul, for &thorn;e|signes &amp; &thorn;e toknys tofore seyde be&thorn; doutes, begynne to mortefye|yt wi&thorn; sum maner poudre as wi&thorn; poudre of affodylles, &amp; loke after-warde|&thorn;e processe of &thorn;y worchynge; ffor &yogh;if &thorn;at he be a verrey|cancre &thorn;ou schalt se, &thorn;e more &thorn;ou woldyste clansen hym &thorn;e more|hys malys schal waxen, and &yogh;if he be no&yogh;t a cancre, he schal be| clansyde ry&yogh;t as an Vlcus.  Whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ou seste &thorn;e waxyng <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="66a">of|&thorn;e cancre &amp; hys malys augmenten, sese fro &thorn;e verreye cure &amp; turne|ageyne to &thorn;e forseyde cure of &thorn;e oygnement of tuetye, whiche &thorn;at|palyth &thorn;e cancre.  ffor &amp; &thorn;ou bysy &thorn;e to cure &thorn;e cancre, &amp; &thorn;ou procede
<PB N="97">|in thy cure, &thorn;ou schortest &thorn;e pacientes lyff.  And &yogh;if &thorn;ou|palest &thorn;ou lengthiste hys lyff.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="14">
<HEAD>&para; Cap. xiiij of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde techynge of &thorn;e furste tretys,|is forto remefe causes &thorn;at latten &thorn;e cure of olde|woundys.</HEAD>
<P>&para; I tolde &thorn;e aboue in &thorn;e general Chapytle of olde Woundes, causes|whiche &thorn;at latte&thorn; olde woundys to by helyde.  And also y telde &thorn;e|techynges plenerlyche &thorn;at be&thorn; necessarye to remywe eche sengle|cause, &thorn;at is necessarye to be done awey.  And now y schal in &thorn;is|specyal chapytle teche, how &thorn;at alle manere cause &thorn;at lettyth may|be done awey by a gode surgyne &amp; a wyse, so &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ou joynest|&thorn;is chapitele with &thorn;e o&thorn;ere chapytell to fore seyde, &thorn;ou schalt han a|plenere techynge.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;e body be ful of elde humores, o&thorn;ere in|&thorn;e dropsye; loke &yogh;if &thorn;at he may be helyde of &thorn;ilke disposicioun, &amp;|&thorn;enne hele hym &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst, and &yogh;if &thorn;at he be no&yogh;t ful of elde|humorys; whiche &thorn;at nedyth to curynge of olde disposicioun.  Ne|traueyle no&yogh;t in deveyne &thorn;e syke man, now&thorn;ere with medycines|corosifes, ne with kuttynges, ne with puttynges into &thorn;e wounde grete|tentys; but do aboffe &thorn;e Vlcus ly&yogh;te mundyficatyfes &amp; swote
<PB N="98">|smellynge &thorn;at kepyth the membre ly&yogh;tlyche clene, &thorn;at he stynke|no&yogh;t.  And whanne &thorn;at he is curyde from an yuele disposicioun,|turne a&yogh;eyne to &thorn;e princypal cure; &amp; &thorn;is same &thorn;ynge y sugge of|yuele disposicioun of &thorn;e lyfere, of what manere cause &thorn;at &thorn;e|enfeblyde; &thorn;e same y sigge of the spleen, ffor but &yogh;if &thorn;ese tweyne|ben in here kendlye dysposicioun, olde woundes mowe no&yogh;t ben|helyde.  &YOGH;if &thorn;at grete multitude off blode lette &thorn;e, &thorn;at may be|knowe by ful replecioun of &thorn;e veynes of alle &thorn;e body, by rednesse|&amp; extension of &thorn;e face, be swetnesse of &thorn;e mouth, be wlattynge,| whenne &thorn;at a man ys fastynge, by <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="66b">heuynesse of &thorn;e browys, &amp; by|&yogh;onge age, &amp; &thorn;at hys complexoun ys hot &amp; moyst, and &thorn;at he hath|y-vsyde in hys dyotynge wyn &amp; fflesch, and &thorn;enne make hym be|lete blode on &thorn;e veyne, whiche &thorn;at bryngeth norysschynge to &thorn;e|lyme, &amp; afterwarde of the Veyne &thorn;at may beste voyden &thorn;e membre|&thorn;at ys y-hurt.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e blode trepasse onlye in qualyte,|amende hym as &yogh;if &thorn;at he be to hot, voyde hym a lytel &amp; dyote|hym wi&thorn; colde metys &amp; styptyke.  And afterwarde procede forth in|alle o&thorn;ere manere cases as it ys tolde in &thorn;e generall chapytell, takynge|hede &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben sum manere medycines, whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; dry&yogh;inge|&amp; clansynge, &amp; haue a prefe proprete to consoude olde woundys,
<PB N="99">|whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; deffykel to be consoudyde, of &thorn;e whyche medycines|some beth symple &amp; some be&thorn; componed.  Symple be&thorn;: lymature|of bras, lymature of Iren, ffloure of bras brent; vytreol rede y-brent,|and alle scharpe corosifes, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben y-brent. ffor &thorn;at &thorn;ey han|&thorn;e more vertue to consouden, and al so here corosion ys y-lassyde.|&THORN;is ys a medycine componyde: &rx;. ffloris eris, lymature of bras ana|.&yogh;. j., litarge of gold, litarge of syluere ana. &yogh;. viij., gumme of cypresse|.&yogh;. iiij, sal gemme .&yogh;. ij, Aristologie I-brende, smal poudre of ffrank|Ensence ana. &yogh;. v., wax &amp; oyle of myrtyne &thorn;at suffyse&thorn;.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter" N="15">
<HEAD>&para; Cap. XV. off the &thorn;ridde techynge of &thorn;e ffirste tretys|is off a Crawmpe, that comyth to a Wounde.</HEAD>
<P>Necessarye thynge ys a surgyne, to knowe &thorn;e causys of &thorn;e|crampe whiche &thorn;at comyth to a wounde &thorn;at scholde ben y-helyde,|and also &thorn;at he knowe &thorn;e dysposicioun of hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe.|And also what &thorn;ynge &thorn;e crampe ys, &thorn;at he mowe resonablyche hele|&thorn;e crampe.  The crampe ys a seknesse cordouse, o&thorn;ere ellys nervose,|in the whiche syknesse &thorn;e cordes &amp; &thorn;e synwes were drawyne to|here bygynnynge; of &thorn;e whiche drawynge &thorn;ere be&thorn; tweye causes
<PB N="100">|conjuncte: &thorn;e on ys repletion of &thorn;e synwe, o&thorn;ere of &thorn;e corde, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere|is Inanysion.  He &thorn;at ys in<NOTE PLACE="foot">Scribal mistake.</NOTE> avision ofte tymes ha&thorn; a cause goynge| to fore, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="67a">as to myche evacuacioun of blod, o&thorn;ere of sum othire|thynge; as to longe afflictioun for longe ak&thorn;e, o&thorn;ere ellys, for &thorn;e|Apetite of the syke man hath be longe tyme enffeblyde; &amp; &thorn;is|comyth lytel &amp; lytell, and &thorn;e crampe &thorn;at comyth of bo&thorn;e &thorn;ese|causys may no&yogh;t ben helyde.  And he &thorn;at comyth of repletion hath|on of &thorn;re causys goynge tofore: &thorn;e firste cause ys to grete ak&thorn;e, &thorn;e|secunde cause ys colde, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ys putrefaccioun o&thorn;er rotynge;|and &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at one sengle cause sumtyme suffiseth to maken a crampe,|ofte tymes alle &thorn;ese causes happe to come togedres.  And &thorn;is crampe|may ben y-helyde ere &thorn;at he be comfermyde, &amp; after &thorn;at he ys confermyde|selden o&thorn;ere neffere.  A surgyne moste &thorn;enne be busye;|in alle &thorn;at he my&yogh;te, &thorn;at a crampe no wexe no&yogh;t in &thorn;e wounde &thorn;at|scholde be helyde, wi&thorn; obuiacion dyffendynge &thorn;at none of &thorn;e &thorn;re|causes tofore seyde ne come no&yogh;te to &thorn;e wounde; &thorn;e one ys in deffendynge|&thorn;e lyme from putrefaccioun, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere is in kepynge &thorn;e lyme|from rotenesse, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is to gouerne hym from gret akynge; ffor|it is more sykere to dyffende, &thorn;at a crampe ne come no&yogh;t, &thorn;enne|aftere &thorn;at he ys come with medycine &thorn;at is doutes o&thorn;ere dredful to
<PB N="101">|don aweye, Ffor &yogh;if &thorn;at a ffeuyre come to an hed o&thorn;ere to a synwe|&thorn;at ys y-woundyde, &amp; &thorn;e crampe folwe euyre more, yt ys dedlyche.|Take hede &thorn;enne to aswage &thorn;e ak&thorn;e with anoyngtynge of oyle of|rosys, and in doynge as y haue seyde tofore in &thorn;e chapitle of synwes|&thorn;at be&thorn; y-woundyde; ffor ofte tymes &thorn;e crampe comyth for woundys,|&thorn;at be&thorn; made in &thorn;e hed o&thorn;ere ellis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ellis</I>, above line.</NOTE> in &thorn;e synwe: And &yogh;if &thorn;at ak&thorn;e|were so grete, &thorn;at makyth a crampe for &thorn;e prikynge off a synwe o&thorn;er|ellys of a corde, and &yogh;if &thorn;ou my&yogh;test no&yogh;t deffende &thorn;e crampe, newhere|wi&thorn; blode letynge, ne wi&thorn; ventosynge, ne wi&thorn; clysterye, ne wi&thorn; suppositorye,|ne with defensif in anoyntynge &thorn;e nekke, ne &thorn;e grynde, ne &thorn;e|arme holys, &thorn;enne yt is necessarie &thorn;at &thorn;ou kytte alle atwo &thorn;ilke synwe|o&thorn;ere corde &thorn;at is y-prikyde, &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e ffelynge o&thorn;ere &thorn;e meffynge|of &thorn;e lyme, to whom &thorn;ilke synwe o&thorn;ere corde servyde, in party o&thorn;er|in al be loste.  Ffor yt is bettyre <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="67b">&thorn;at a man lese &thorn;e felynge &amp; &thorn;e |meffynge of a lyme &thorn;enne &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at he dey&yogh;e.  But yt is bettyre &yogh;if|&thorn;at &thorn;ou cou&thorn;est kepen a man with o&thorn;ere manere medycines, &thorn;enne|&thorn;at &thorn;e synwe o&thorn;ere corde be y-kutte al atwo.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou were|no&yogh;t at &thorn;e bygynninge, and &thorn;ou fyndest a man hauynge a crampe|for a wounde, do &thorn;ou as y dyde at Melan.  &THORN;ere was a Scolere of|myne &thorn;at was a Surgyne &thorn;at was y-clepyde Olyfere, whyche &thorn;at
<PB N="102">|curyde a schepere of a wounde &thorn;at he hadde in the hed; &amp; by &thorn;ilke|wounde &thorn;e pannycle o&thorn;ere &thorn;e skyn &thorn;at keueryth &thorn;e breyne panne,|&thorn;at is vndire &thorn;e fflesch, was y-hurt, &amp; nere &thorn;e latere &thorn;e breyn panne|was no&yogh;t y-hurt.  &amp; &thorn;ilke leche, ere &thorn;anne he hadde perfytlyche|y-puryfiede &thorn;ylke pannycle, soudyde &thorn;e wounde withouten forth; &amp;|whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ilke wounde was y-sowdyde, &thorn;e pannycle &thorn;at was no&yogh;t|wel helyde hadde a dedeyne, &amp; was cause of engendrynge of a|crampe in &thorn;ilke wounde.  And at &thorn;e laste y was clepyde to &thorn;ilke|syke man, &amp; y fonde hym habbynge &thorn;e crampe, &amp; with &thorn;e crampe|he hadde manye smale enpostemes aboute hys face, &amp; &thorn;at ys an|yuele tokne in &thorn;e woundys of &thorn;e hed, and &thorn;enne y demyde hym for|ded.  Na&thorn;eles at &thorn;e instaunce of hys frendys y &thorn;at wolde assaye &thorn;e|worchynge of kynde vpon resoun, I made hys hed ben y-schaue, and|y kutte a&yogh;eyne &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;at was consoudid, with a rasoure to &thorn;e|dep&thorn;e of &thorn;e same wounde, &amp; afterewarde y fulfylde &thorn;ilke wounde|with hote oyle of rosys, &amp; y anoyntede alle &thorn;e hed with &thorn;e same|oyle of roses &amp; a lytell vynegre y-medlyde togedre, &amp; y anoyntede &thorn;e|nolle &amp; &thorn;e nekke onlye wi&thorn; oyle of rosys, and y dyde on &thorn;e wounde|&thorn;e &yogh;olke of an eye with oyle of rosys, and y bonde alle &thorn;e hed wi&thorn; a
<PB N="103">|bonde leggynge &thorn;ere undyre hurdys o&thorn;ere tow&yogh; smal tosyde, and|y opnyde hys mouth &amp; put into hys mouth &thorn;e broth of a chyken|y-made with comyn, and also clere wyn y-medlyde with myche|watyre.  On &thorn;e morwe y turnyde a&yogh;eyne &amp; y fonde &thorn;e syke of|bettyre dysposicioun, &amp; he opnyde bettyre hys mouth, &amp; he spak|bettyre; &amp; na&thorn;eles <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="68a">y fonde &thorn;e wounde drye, &amp; &thorn;enne y dede efte |sonys &thorn;e same medycine &amp; &thorn;e same vncture.  In &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day &thorn;e|skyn of &thorn;e hed was y-mad moyst, whyche &thorn;at was to forne as drye|as a skyn hadde be rostyde to &thorn;e fyre, and in so myche &thorn;e skyn was|y-made &thorn;unne, &thorn;at &thorn;ere was no&thorn;ynge betwene &thorn;e skyn &amp; &thorn;e breyne|panne.  &amp; at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e wounde quyteryde wi&thorn; contynewaunce of &thorn;e|same cure tofore seyde, &amp; in &thorn;is manere &thorn;e &yogh;onge man was helyde|bo&thorn;e of &thorn;e crampe &amp; eke of &thorn;e wounde.  But &thorn;ilke crampe was withouten|ffeuyre; ffor y ne may no&yogh;t &thorn;ynke &thorn;at y haue seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a wounde</I> struck through after <I>seyn</I>.</NOTE> a ffevyre|in &thorn;e woundes of synwes, o&thorn;ere ellys of &thorn;e hed precede a crampe, &thorn;at|no&yogh;t a&yogh;eyne stondynge remedye / o&thorn;ere medycynes &thorn;e pacient &thorn;at|hadde &thorn;e crampe ne deyede.  My beste conseyle is to letyn hym blod|in the bygynninge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe, namly, &amp; he be stronge &amp;|replete, and &yogh;if &thorn;at he haue nou&yogh;t bled ynow&yogh; at hys wounde; and|anoynte hys nolle &amp; hys nekke wi&thorn; hote oynementys, as with oyle of
<PB N="104">|nardyne, enforbine, Oyle rewe, lylyes &amp;c.;, and also to make smale|cauteryes punctales, &thorn;at is to sigge as smale as &thorn;e ende of a prykke,|bytwene euery whirlebone of &thorn;e nekke, so neuere &thorn;e latere &thorn;at &thorn;e|cauterye go nou&yogh;t ouere depe.  Afterwarde bynde longe wolle to|hys hed be hynde, &amp; to his nekke, &amp; to his schuldres, &amp; do &thorn;ere|on hote oyle, &amp; leye hym in a softe bed, &amp; lete hym ben in reste &amp;|in pees.  But &thorn;ere be summe &thorn;at setten in here bokys medycines,|&thorn;at provocen &thorn;e ffeuerys; ffor &thorn;at ypocras techyth in quarto afforismorum:|a spasmo vel detano habito febre superveniente soluit|egritudinem &thorn;at ys to sigge; &yogh;if &thorn;at a man haff &thorn;e crampe, o&thorn;ere|ellys a tetane, &thorn;at is a syknesse &thorn;at halt the membre y-lyche streyt|on bo&thorn;e &thorn;e sydes, as a crampe halte &thorn;e on syde of &thorn;e membre, &amp; &thorn;e|ffeuere come on &thorn;ilke crampe o&thorn;ere &thorn;ilke tetane, he distroyeth &thorn;e|crampe o&thorn;ere &thorn;e seknesse, and also &thorn;ey anoynte with to hote oynement|to provoke &thorn;e ffeuerys, &thorn;e whyche &thorn;ynge y ne apreff nou&yogh;t in|&thorn;e crampe of a wounde, &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke oynement my&yogh;te be profitable| in a crampe withouten <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="68b">wounde, &amp; where &thorn;at humores habounde,|namlye, &yogh;if yt be fflewme.  Somme ben general toknys, &amp; some be|speciall of schewynge of a crampe.  General toknys ben &thorn;ese: to
<PB N="105">|gret ak&thorn;e, crokydnesse of ey&yogh;en, &amp; crokydnesse of erys of nose &thorn;rell|&amp; of lyppes, &amp; whenne &thorn;at a man may no&yogh;t speke, &amp; &thorn;e chekys ben|constreynde, &amp; dyficulte of swolwynge, &amp; diffyculte of mevynge,|namlye of &thorn;e nekke, &amp; ofte constreynynge togedre, &amp; sodeyne|schakynge togedire.  Special signes maken one of pre manere of|crampes: &thorn;e on ys y-clepyde Emprostonos, &thorn;e o&thorn;ere Empistonos, &thorn;e|&thorn;ridde tetanus.  In &thorn;ese manere of crampe &thorn;at is clepyde Emprostonos|&thorn;e synwes tofore be drawen togedire, &thorn;e fore party of &thorn;e hed|ys crokyde, ne &thorn;e syke man ne may no&yogh;t heffyn it vp, he berith hys|chyn as yt leye on hys brest; hys mou&thorn; is streyte, ne he ne may|no&yogh;t opyne yt, and &thorn;e ffyngres of hys hande ben foldyde into hys|fust.  And in Empistonos &thorn;e nekke ys crokyde, his mou&thorn; is opyne,|his chekes be&thorn; opyne, &amp; &thorn;e fyngres of hys handys ben streynde|bakwarde, and &thorn;e tetane halt bo&thorn;e &thorn;e partye of &thorn;e body, so &thorn;at he|may nou&yogh;t turne hys nekke to non partie, but alle &thorn;e body is styffe|&amp; streynde, as a staf were put in at hys hed &amp; out at his ers.  Alle|&thorn;ese toknys o&thorn;ere ellys sum of hem schewith &thorn;e disposicioun of hym|&thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e crampe.  And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ese toknys fallyn in &thorn;e|wounde of an hed o&thorn;ere ellys of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>, above line.</NOTE> a synwe, &thorn;ey teche bettire &thorn;e leche|to fle from &thorn;e syke man, &thorn;enne on hym to abyde &amp; cure.  The firste
<PB N="106">|tretys ys y-endyde wi&thorn; helpe of almy&yogh;tie god, now with &thorn;e helpe of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>of</I> twice.</NOTE>|&thorn;e same y go to &thorn;e secunde.</P></DIV4></DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="book" N="2">
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="1"><HEAD>&para; Now begynne&thorn; &thorn;e secunde tretys off particuler|woundes of membris of office from &thorn;e hede to|&thorn;e ffot, and ffirste y begynne at the Anotamye|off the hed.</HEAD>
<P>Al thynge breffliche y-ordeynde, aftere &thorn;e devysinge of my| Symple wytt, whiche &thorn;at longith to &thorn;e firste tretys of this <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="69a">boke|whiche &thorn;at holdyth certeyne rulys &amp; techynges off surgerye vndire|general chapitelis, as we han byhey&yogh;t.  Now we wylle begynne to|tretyn of certeyne cures, aftere &thorn;at &thorn;e lymes ben in mannys body.|&amp; firste y wyl begynne at &thorn;e hed &amp; at hys anotamye, &amp; so &thorn;e processe|for&thorn; to eueryche membre devysinge &thorn;e Anotamye of euery|membre, &amp; in ordeynynge &thorn;e cures of woundys &thorn;at be&thorn; made in eche|sengle membre, I sigge &thorn;at &thorn;e hed ys made of &thorn;re partyes: of a|ffleschy party, a bony partye, and a braynie partye.  &THORN;e fflesch|partye is aboue &thorn;e brayn panne, whiche &thorn;at is made of an herye|skyn; &amp; &thorn;ilke skyn ys fulfylde with brawnys in euery place.  &THORN;e
<PB N="107">|herys off &thorn;e hed were for grete proffyte y-ordeynde, &thorn;at nei&thorn;ere|colde ne hete ne scholde no&yogh;t sodeynliche entre &thorn;e pores of &thorn;e skyn,|&amp; neuere &thorn;e lattere &thorn;at &thorn;e fumosyte of &thorn;e hed my&yogh;te go out be &thorn;e|pores &thorn;ere as &thorn;e here growyth, and &thorn;at &thorn;e hed my&yogh;te be &thorn;e more|semlykere, and &thorn;at &thorn;e coloure of &thorn;e herys my&yogh;te schewe &thorn;e complexioun|of &thorn;e hed.  &THORN;e skyn &thorn;at is abouen &thorn;e breyne panne ys|lacertos &amp; ful of &thorn;ykke flesch, &thorn;at he my&yogh;te wreyen &thorn;e breyn panne,|&thorn;at he scholde no&yogh;t fele to sodeynlyche nei&thorn;ere to grete hete ne to|cold.  &THORN;e whiche skyn ys made of sotyll &thorn;redys of synwes &thorn;at|come&thorn; from &thorn;e brayn &amp; of veynis &amp; of arteryes sotylliche y-mad;|and so &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e hed ys sotylliche y-Ioyned with &thorn;e skyn off|alle &thorn;e bodye, and also &thorn;e skyn of &thorn;e hed ys more &thorn;ykkere &thorn;enne &thorn;e|brayne scolle, &thorn;at it scholde be more rare &amp; more porose &thorn;at is to|sigge more ful of holys.  &THORN;e lacertes of &thorn;e skyn proceden after &thorn;at|&thorn;e goynge procedyth of &thorn;e herys, &thorn;e brayn panne ys mad of manye|bonys.  &THORN;e fyrste summe, whiche &thorn;at wi&thorn;holdyth &thorn;e profites &thorn;at|longyth to &thorn;e brayn panne, ha&thorn; tweye helpynges; on helpynge ys,|&thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at an hurtynge come to on bon, neuere &thorn;e latere he scholde|no&yogh;t fallen to alle &thorn;e bonys; &thorn;e secunde helpe is &thorn;at on bon &thorn;at is|to harde in on partye, ne scholde no&yogh;t be so <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="69b">hard in an o&thorn;ere 
<PB N="108">|partye.  Secunde summe, whiche &thorn;at withhalt helpynges, &thorn;at be&thorn;|vnder &thorn;e brayn panne, ha&thorn; with hym iiij helpynges; &thorn;e whiche|helpynges be&thorn; ful mad be &thorn;e semys &thorn;at be&thorn; of &thorn;e breyn panne.  Ne|&thorn;o helpynges ne my&yogh;te no&yogh;t be mad, but &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere were manye|bonys.  &THORN;e firste helpe ys, &thorn;at &thorn;e veynes my&yogh;te go doun by the|semys of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> above line.</NOTE> &thorn;e brayn panne, berynge norosschynge to &thorn;e same brayn.</P>
<P>Secunde helpe ys &thorn;at &thorn;e synwes, &thorn;at comyth out of &thorn;e brayn,|my&yogh;te habbe wey in goynge out.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde helpe ys, &thorn;at &thorn;e fumes|of &thorn;e brayn my&yogh;te habbe wey of smokynge out.  &THORN;e ffour&thorn;e ys, &thorn;at|nei&thorn;ere dura mater ne pia mater, &thorn;ere as &thorn;ey ben y-hongyde, ne|my&yogh;te no&yogh;t greue &thorn;e brayn.  Sytthe &thorn;at &thorn;e breyne panne ys made|of two sme&thorn;e ly&yogh;te tablys, &thorn;at one ys aboue &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere byne&thorn;e, &amp;|&thorn;ey be sumwhat spongyouse in &thorn;e myddel &amp; rare, &thorn;at &thorn;e smokys of|&thorn;e hed my&yogh;te &thorn;e bettyre passen out, &amp; &thorn;ey be sme&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;te|no&yogh;t greue &thorn;e brayn.  Dyuerse men &thorn;at makyth dyuerse Anotamye|devyde&thorn; &thorn;e breyn panne dyuerslyche.  Somme nowmbryth mo|bonys. &thorn;enne summe o&thorn;ere spekyn of; but so&thorn;enesse ys that &thorn;ere|ben sixe; &amp; one whyche &thorn;at susteyne&thorn; &thorn;o sixe.  &THORN;e ffyrste bon ys|clepyde &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> above line.</NOTE> fforhed o&thorn;ere ellys coronale, &amp; he bygynne&thorn;|from &thorn;e browys, &amp; lastyth vnto &thorn;e seme &thorn;at departyth &thorn;e hed
<PB N="109">|twarte offere.  And &thorn;ylke bon is y-clepyde coronale: &thorn;is bon hath|in some manere of men a smal seme in &thorn;e ffoldynge of &thorn;e fforhed,|&amp; &thorn;ere fore sum men sigge&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ere be&thorn; tweye bonys.  Tweye|o&thorn;ere bonys be&thorn; y-Ioyned wi&thorn; &thorn;ylke bon coronale in &thorn;e myden of|&thorn;e hed twarte offere, &amp; &thorn;ey ben y-bounde togedyre by one Iucture,|&thorn;e whiche &thorn;at strecchi&thorn; from tofore to byhynde, by the lengthe|of &thorn;e hed, &thorn;e whiche ys y-clepyde sagyttalis by as myche as he|ys schapyde lyke an arwe.  And &thorn;ese tweye bonys be&thorn; y-clepyde|Nerualia, by cause of &thorn;e ffigure of the seme &thorn;at ys wi&thorn; &thorn;e coronale,|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="70a">ys &thorn;e ffigure of a synwe o&thorn;ere of a corde.  And &thorn;ese bonys ben in |&thorn;e heyest coppe of the hed, and behynde in &thorn;e nolle &thorn;ere ys a bon|whyche &thorn;at is y-clepyde Alauda, &amp; ys y-made to &thorn;e Symilitude of|&thorn;is cyffre of Augrym <FIGURE></FIGURE>, whiche &thorn;at ys Ioynede with &thorn;e bonys|nerualibus tofore seyde, by &thorn;e mene of on &yogh;em y-mad to &thorn;e lyknesse|of &thorn;e bon tofore seyde.  &amp; &thorn;ese &thorn;re &yogh;emes whiche &thorn;at Ioyne&thorn; togedyre|&thorn;e foure bonys to fore seyde, ben y-made as yt were tweye<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>tweye</I> twice.</NOTE>|&yogh;awes, whos teth joyned eche of hem in o&thorn;ere in thys manere /<FIGURE></FIGURE>|&amp; &thorn;is ioyninge togedire of on bon with an o&thorn;er was y-made|by-cause Iuvamentes &thorn;at y haue tolde beforn; &thorn;ere nys no bon|y-ioynede with an o&thorn;ere as &thorn;ese bonys ben.  Undire &thorn;e bon &thorn;at ys
<PB N="110">|y-clepyde Alauda, &thorn;ere ys a ful harde bon &amp; y-holyde in &thorn;e myddle,|&thorn;e whyche bone susteyneth alle &thorn;e bonys of &thorn;e hed.  &THORN;e whiche|bon ys y-clepyde Passilus, &amp; he ys ioynede byne&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;e fyrste|bon of &thorn;e nekke.  &THORN;e schappe of &thorn;e coniuccioun of &thorn;e fife bonys of|&thorn;e hed ys in &thorn;is manere <FIGURE></FIGURE>.  Bothe on &thorn;e ry&yogh;te syde &amp; on &thorn;e|lefte syde of &thorn;e forseyde bonys whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; y-clepyde nerualia,*|whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; in lengthe in &thorn;e heyest place of &thorn;e hed, &thorn;ere ben|twey bonys on ei&thorn;ere syde*; &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; vndiresetterys to &thorn;o|bonys &thorn;at be&thorn; y-clepyde nerualia; &amp; &thorn;o bonys &thorn;at vndire setten,|ben y-clept ossa mendosa.  And &thorn;ese bonys in one partye ben ful|harde, &thorn;ere as &thorn;e hole of &thorn;e ere passyth &thorn;orw&yogh;, &amp; &thorn;ey ben y-clepede|<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. petotra.</NOTE>petrosa &amp; sum men siggen &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben foure bonys, two on eythere|syde.  &amp; whanne &thorn;at alle bonys of &thorn;e hed be Ioynede togedire &thorn;ou|schalt fynde in sotfastnesse, &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben but sixe bonys whanne|&thorn;at &thorn;ou reknyste os<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. as.</NOTE> coronale ffor on bon, &amp; tweye bonys &thorn;at be&thorn;|y-clepyde mendose tweyne &thorn;at be&thorn; &thorn;re, and o bon &thorn;at ys y-clepyde|Alanda, &amp; tweye bonys &thorn;at is y-clepyde nerualia&mdash;&thorn;at be&thorn; sixe,|and &thorn;e vij bon ys y-clepyde passillare, &thorn;e whiche ys nought of &thorn;e|bonys of &thorn;e hed, but he susteyneth alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere bonys of &thorn;e hed.|And &thorn;re maner of semys makyth coniuccioun of alle &thorn;e bonys on &thorn;is
<PB N="111">|manere <FIGURE></FIGURE>, &amp; with tweye semys mendose in &thorn;is manere <FIGURE></FIGURE>.|And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e corone of &thorn;e hed ys perfyt, &thorn;e hed <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="70b">ys mad in|&thorn;is manere <FIGURE></FIGURE>.  &THORN;is ys &thorn;e forme of an hed wel proporcionede, |&thorn;at he be ronde because &thorn;at he myghte &thorn;e more withholde, &amp; &thorn;at he|my&yogh;te &thorn;e lasse be y-hurt, and &thorn;at he be longewarped havynge tofore|&amp; behynde eminence &thorn;at is to sigge aperynge, &thorn;at &thorn;e synwes &thorn;at|comyth out of &thorn;e brayn, myghte haue a porose place of goynge out.|And na&thorn;elese as ypocras &amp; galyen, whiche &thorn;at expone&thorn; ypocras,|tellyn: it is possible to fynden &thorn;re o&thorn;ere manere makynge of hedys.|On manere is, &yogh;if eminence be no&yogh;t in &thorn;e partye of &thorn;e hed tofore;|for &yogh;if &thorn;at he be pleyn in &thorn;e partye tofore, by &thorn;at pleynnesse &thorn;e|seme is y-lost &thorn;at is y-clepyde coronalis.  Secunde ys &yogh;if &thorn;e hed|haff non eminence behynde, but &thorn;at &thorn;e hyndore party be playn,|and by &thorn;at playnnesse &thorn;e seme ys y-lost &thorn;at ys y-clepyde Alauda.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Abauda</I>.</NOTE>|&THORN;e &thorn;ridde ys &yogh;if &thorn;ere be non eminence tofore ne behynde in &thorn;e|hed, but alle &thorn;e hed ys rounde as a cercle.  And &thorn;enne &thorn;ere nys|but on sem in &thorn;e myddel of &thorn;e breyn panne, ffor it is vnpossible &thorn;e|hed to habben enye o&thorn;ere schappe wi&thorn;outen lesyng of some party|of &thorn;e brayn; &amp; &thorn;at were contrariouse a&yogh;eyne lyf.  By &thorn;e myddele|seme, whiche &thorn;at is in &thorn;e hed, &thorn;ere dissendyth a veyne comynge
<PB N="112">|from &thorn;e lyffere, by &thorn;e breyn ponne, of a bon whiche &thorn;at is y-holyde.|&thorn;at is y-clepyde pasillaris.  And by &thorn;e same weye &thorn;ere arysith an|Arterye comynge fro &thorn;e herte, and &thorn;ey ben Ioynde togedire, &amp; of|&thorn;e weffynge of &thorn;o tweyne &thorn;ere is y-mad an hard pannycle &thorn;at is to|sigge a cloth &thorn;at is vndir &thorn;e brayn panne, and he is hongyde wi&thorn;|sum smale ligamentys to &thorn;e brayn panne in some of &thorn;e semys, &thorn;e|whych pannycle bynde&thorn; &thorn;e bonys togedire, &amp; it is clepyde dura|mater.  And yt is ry&yogh;tful &thorn;at an Arterye scholde arysen vpwarde|from byne&thorn;yne, for &thorn;e blod &thorn;at ys in hym &thorn;at is sotyll, &amp; hys|meffynge &thorn;at ys pulsatyff<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>prilsatyff</I>.</NOTE>; and he hadde discendyde from aboue| dunwarde, he scholde han discendyde wi&thorn; to gret <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="71a">an hastynesse,|but &thorn;e ascendynge temprith &thorn;ulke fflux.  And yt is couenable &thorn;at|&thorn;e veyne discende, bycause &thorn;at &thorn;e blod &thorn;at ys in &thorn;e veynes ys more|&thorn;ykkore, &amp; &thorn;e blod &thorn;at is in &thorn;e veyne ge&thorn; doun softliche.  &amp; bo&thorn;e|&thorn;ese veynes &thorn;at bu&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bu&thorn;</I>, above line.</NOTE> pulsatyf &amp; nou&yogh;t pulsatyf be&thorn; y-Ioynede wi&thorn;|dura matre.  And also &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;e veyne streche more lowere, &amp; of|hem ys engendryde pia mater.  Afterward &thorn;ey descenden doun to|&thorn;e brayn.  &amp; &thorn;ey bryngen lyf &amp; dywe norysschynge &amp; cordyal|spirites, &thorn;e whiche is in &thorn;e brayn and &thorn;ere is diffyede, &amp; &thorn;ere|resseyue&thorn; naturel forme of vnderstondynge.  Pia mater environe&thorn;|al &thorn;e brayn, &amp; departyth hym into &thorn;e &thorn;re celoles<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>cololes</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at be&thorn; chaumbres:
<PB N="113">|&thorn;e firste, &thorn;e myddle, &amp; &thorn;e laste.  And &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at alle &thorn;ese ben|diffyede senglerlyche by hem selffyn, yt seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e celele &thorn;at is|tofore in &thorn;e brayn ys departyde in two parties, &amp; by &thorn;at cause|sum men siggen, &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben foure ventricles of &thorn;e brayn.  &THORN;e|fur&thorn;ere part of &thorn;e brayn ys gret &amp; brod, by cause &thorn;at he scholde|resseyue manye spirites &thorn;at ben y-sende to hym for &thorn;at place is|propre instrement of y-maginacion, &thorn;e whiche resceyue&thorn; &thorn;ynges &thorn;at|bu&thorn; comprehendide of fantasie; and &thorn;o &thorn;ynges comen vndirstondynge|resceyue&thorn; by propre Instrementys &thorn;at longyth to hym, and|&thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at al &thorn;e brayn, in comparson of &thorn;e herte &amp; of alle o&thorn;ere|membres of &thorn;e body, be y-demyde colde &amp; moist, &thorn;is celule hauynge|comparson to o&thorn;ere celules ys y-demyde hot &amp; dry&yogh;e.  &THORN;e myddel|part of &thorn;e brayn ys lasse &thorn;en eny of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere two partyes, &amp; here|forme ys pyneat, brod towarde &thorn;e fur&thorn;ere syde of &thorn;e hed and|scharpere towarde &thorn;e hyndor syde, &thorn;at he my&yogh;te be &thorn;e more able to|resceyue y-maginatyf &thorn;ynges &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;ynges to &yogh;efe to &thorn;e ynnere|partye &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;ynges &thorn;at be&thorn; y-&yogh;efe to with holde.  &THORN;is ventricle ys|y-sette bytwene tweyne additamentes of &thorn;e brayn, &thorn;e whiche additamentes|ben y-liche &thorn;e two buttokkes of a man &thorn;at be&thorn; y-Ioynede|togedre, and &thorn;ey be&thorn; to *&thorn;is ventricle as yt were a syttynge place
<PB N="114">|o&thorn;ere a couche, vpon . &thorn;e whyche he ys drawyne abrode, whenne|&thorn;at he resseyue&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="71b">y-maginatyff &thorn;ynges.  And afterwarde he ys| y-drawe togedire as a worme, whenne &thorn;at he resceyueth y-maginatyff|&thorn;ynges; and whenne &thorn;at &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;ilke y-magynacioun|ys y-brought forth, &thorn;enne &thorn;ilke ventricle ys y-drawe alonge.  And|also &thorn;e smallere ende of &thorn;is ventricle entrith into &thorn;e ventricle &thorn;at|ys behynde in &thorn;e hed, and &thorn;is ventricle ys myche lasse &thorn;enne &thorn;e|o&thorn;ere tweyne bycause &thorn;at non synwes procedent not out of hym,|and &thorn;at manye &thorn;ynges myghte be endyde in litel* place, &thorn;at vertue|of wytt myghte &thorn;e sonnere be y-gedryde togedre to taken hys|counseyll.  And thys ventrycle to comparson of o&thorn;ere ventricles ys|y-demyde hot &amp; drye.  After &thorn;at ys &thorn;e hyndere ventricle, whiche|ys grattere &amp; hardere &thorn;enne thys; &thorn;e whiche in *comparson of &thorn;e|o&thorn;ere tweyne ys y-demyde colde &amp; drye, &thorn;e whiche is brod towarde|&thorn;e fore partye of &thorn;e hed &amp; scharpe bachwarde, &thorn;e whyche resseyuyth|sentense &thorn;at be&thorn; schewyde &amp; kepyth hem priuyliche as a|chest kepyth tresore.  And out of hym goth out<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in &thorn;e a,</I> struck through after <I>goth out.</I></NOTE> nucha<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nucha</I> on margin.</NOTE> &thorn;rowe &thorn;e|hole of &thorn;e bon &thorn;at ys y-clepyde passilarys.  And &thorn;ilke nucha ys|y-clothyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ys y-clothyde</I> twice.</NOTE> wi&thorn; tweye pannycles &thorn;at goth out of &thorn;e brayn.  And|alle &thorn;e brayn ys y-demyde colde &amp; moyst. bycause &thorn;at he scholde
