<PB N="137">|and &thorn;at &thorn;e vertue of &thorn;e medycine, &thorn;at ys y-mad of honye of|roses &amp; oyle of roses, may drawe fro byne&thorn;e &thorn;e brayn-panne; and|y do in &thorn;is cas al &thorn;ynge, as yt declarith nexte aboffe.  And &yogh;if|men make obiectioun a&yogh;eyns me by constantine o&thorn;ere ellys by hym,|&thorn;at seyth &thorn;at by alle oure myght we enchewyn &thorn;at ne&thorn;ere oyle ne|non vncomys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Corrupt, probably for <I>vnctouys</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ynge falle no&yogh;t withynne &thorn;e brayn-panne, I answere|with Avecene, &thorn;at seyth: &thorn;at he wirche&thorn; ry&yogh;tfulliche &thorn;at vsith|certeyne oyles, &amp; &thorn;e same telli&thorn; galien &amp; serapion, and also y seye|&thorn;at oyle of roses, whiche &thorn;at be mad of grapes of Olyue tres &thorn;at be&thorn;|no&yogh;t ripe, is no&yogh;t vnctuose, but is drey&yogh;e; &amp; it is clepyde oyle|Omfacinum, &amp; namlye whanne &thorn;at roses ben y-medlyde with &thorn;at|oyle, &thorn;ilke oyle hath y-gete to hym a swete smellynge &amp; a drey&yogh;inge,|cumffortynge animal spirites; and also &thorn;ilke oyle hath a vertue|expressif, as galien tellyth in the bok of symple medycines, by &thorn;e|whyche &thorn;e brayn ys conffortyde &amp; ak&thorn;es ben aswagede, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ere|be mad enye gret blod, yt is y-made Sotyll; &amp; whenne alle &thorn;ese|&thorn;ynges ben y-gadryde togedyre &amp; leyde abouen, dura mater ys|clansed.  Sumtyme &thorn;e brayn ys meffyde of sum gret hurt o&thorn;ere of|sum fallynge, o&thorn;ere of sum smytynge withouten eny wounde ore enye
<PB N="138">|breche of eny bon, &thorn;an do &thorn;ou as dyde y to a Chanoun of &thorn;e ordre|of seint Austyn.  Whanne &thorn;at he wolde haue lopyn vpon an hye|hors and haue seten in &thorn;e sadyll, &thorn;e hors areryde vpon hys two| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="79b">hyndere fete, &amp; &thorn;ilke chanoun fel doun bakwarde vpon &thorn;e erthe|on hys hed; &amp; alle hys bodye was y-brusyde, and namlye aboute &thorn;e|hed &thorn;at anon he lost &thorn;e ffelynge &amp; &thorn;e meffynge of alle his bodye.|&THORN;anne a lewyde leche &thorn;at was frende to &thorn;ilke Chanoun was y-clepyde,|&amp; he cou&thorn;e helpe hym no&yogh;t, for he had neuere seyne &thorn;e|same cas, ne he ne cou&thorn;e no&yogh;t on lettre.  And at &thorn;e laste y was|clepte, &amp; y fonde hym no&yogh;t herynge ne spekynge ne nothynge|mevynge, I demyde hym for ded, and na&thorn;eles sauyde, &yogh;if &thorn;at he|were my bro&thorn;ere y nolde nou&yogh;t for an hundrede mark, but y sayede|in hym &thorn;e godnesse &amp; &thorn;e helpynge of medycines; ffor ofte tymes|kynde with gode werkys helpith preueliche &thorn;at semyth vnpossible|to a leche.  And &thorn;enne &thorn;ey preyede me with gret Instaunce, and y|made the herys of hys hed to be schaffen and &thorn;enne y anoynt all &thorn;e|hed with &thorn;re partye of oyle of roses, &amp; on partye of vyneger hot|y-medlyde togedyre, &amp; y caste abouen &thorn;e poudre of mirtylles, and y|leyde abouen a sotyll &thorn;enne cloth y-wet in &thorn;e same oyle &amp; vynegre,
<PB N="139">|&amp; aboue &thorn;at tow&yogh; smale y-tosyde, &amp; y bonde alle &thorn;e hed with a band,|&amp; abouen y leyde a lambys skyn, &amp; so y chaungede yt twyes euerye|day; in anoyntynge &thorn;e nolle &amp; &thorn;e nekke into &thorn;e myddell of &thorn;e|rygge-bon byhynde wi&thorn; hote oyle of Camamylle.  In &thorn;e secunde|day he opnyde a lyte his ey&yogh;en, &amp; he bygan to loken aboute hym|as it hadde be a deff man, o&thorn;ere ellys a man &thorn;at were in a|wondrynge; and &thorn;enne some wolden haue assayede &yogh;if &thorn;at he wolde|eten, &amp; y wolde nou&yogh;t <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80a">Suffren hym to eten, &amp; y seyde &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at he |wolde eten he scholde no&yogh;t.  In &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day y spak to hym, &amp;|he answerde me bablynge as a childe &thorn;at begynne&thorn; to speke, but he|my&yogh;te formen non worde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lat.: verbum non potuit formare.</NOTE>  In &thorn;e four&thorn;e day he spak bostynglyche,|and &thorn;enne y gaf hym to drynke hot ydrosacre, &thorn;at ys y-mad of Sugre|&amp; of watyre.  In &thorn;e ffyfte day he toke &thorn;ikke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ilke.</NOTE> tysan.  In &thorn;e sixe day|y gaf hym &thorn;e broth off a chykne, &amp; &thorn;enne he gan to streng&thorn;e litel|&amp; lytel &amp; lytel, &amp; lytel to meffen, &amp; neuere &thorn;e latere he my&yogh;te no&yogh;t|walkyn by manye dayes.  And whanne &thorn;at he my&yogh;te take Suffisauntlye|mete, y comaundyde hym to take Pylulas Cochias, for to
<PB N="140">|resolfe by evacuacioun &thorn;e matere &thorn;at was y-gadrede togedire in &thorn;e|hed by &thorn;ilke fallynge.  And y comaundyde hym to eten ofte &thorn;e|braynes of briddys hedys, as of hennys &amp; of smale bryddes, &amp; also|of kyddes; and in &thorn;is manere he was hol; na&thorn;eles he was neuyre|so sotyl of wyt as he was tofore.  In &thorn;is cas bu&thorn; yuele signes:|as &thorn;e face to be crokyde, &amp; &thorn;at on ey&yogh;e to loken asquynt o&thorn;er|crokydlyche, apoplexie, crampe, to schyte wi&thorn;out felynge, &amp; vnmevablete|of alle &thorn;e membris outsepte &thorn;e lacertes of &thorn;e brest &thorn;at|mowe be saff.  He &thorn;at redith &thorn;is bok may chesen after hys owne|wyl, one of &thorn;re weyes whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; now y-vsyde, &thorn;at on ys &thorn;e|wey whiche &thorn;at ys seyde in &thorn;e bygynninge of &thorn;is chapitell, &thorn;e|whiche weye many vsen, and a leche o Ianewe &thorn;at is y-clepyde|Anselme vsith &thorn;is weye, &amp; &thorn;ereby he gat myche moneye, na&thorn;eles y|wyste wel &thorn;at manye men dy&yogh;eden in his handys by &thorn;is wey.  &THORN;e| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80b">secunde weye is in alle manere hurtynges of hed to vsen terebracioun,|o&thorn;ere ellys remeffynge of &thorn;e bon with handlyche Instrumentes;|&thorn;e &thorn;ridde ys my weye whiche &thorn;at y haue tolde opynlye in
<PB N="141">|alle manere of cas; and y beleue &yogh;if &thorn;at he wyl take hede to alle|&thorn;ese weyes, &amp; &thorn;at he wyll wyslye dyscussen &thorn;e opyniouns of|Auctores, &thorn;at he schal se fewere dy&yogh;e be my &thorn;ridde weye &thorn;enne by|enye o&thorn;ere.  Almy&yogh;tie god lede &thorn;e redere of &thorn;is werk in &thorn;e beste|wey, &thorn;orwe whose my&yogh;te, wordes takyth sentence &amp; echyn vnderstondynge.|&THORN;ow&yogh; &thorn;at we han behoten to treten of Anotamye of|membres &thorn;at ben componed, in &thorn;e bygynninge of euery chapytell of|this secunde tretys, na&thorn;eles we leuen yt for &thorn;e bettire for to treten|of &thorn;e Anotamye of &thorn;e vysage, to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tretys, where we schulle|tretyn of seknesse &thorn;at comyth to &thorn;is membres, whyche seknesse|be&thorn; non woundes.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>&para; Cap. off woundes of &thorn;e face &amp; Anotamye of &thorn;e same.</HEAD>
<P>Woundes &thorn;at ben made in &thorn;e face, o&thorn;ere &thorn;ey be&thorn; mad with a|swerde, ore wi&thorn; sum thynge ellys &thorn;at wounde&thorn;, o&thorn;ere &thorn;ey ben mad|wi&thorn; prikynge of a knyf, arwe, o&thorn;ere spere.  Yt is necessarye, &thorn;at a|surgyne haue more diligence in &thorn;e woundes of &thorn;e face, for it is a|place &thorn;at is myche y-seyne, &amp; yt ys wel y-do to make a sotyll cicatryce.|A wounde &thorn;at ys mad with a swerde o&thorn;ere with sum &thorn;ynge
<PB N="142">|semblable &thorn;at is alweye in lengthe, a man moste sotylliche sowyn &amp;|gedre &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e wounde.  And for &thorn;at many men ly&yogh;en <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81a">of| &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e nese, &thorn;ey sey&yogh;en &thorn;at on bare hys nose y-kytte of in|hys hande, &thorn;e whiche nose was afterwarde y-sette a&yogh;eyne in hys|owne kynde; &thorn;e whiche ys an opyn lesynge, for &thorn;e spiryt of lyf of|felynge &amp; of meffynge passith aweye, whanne a membre is departyde|from &thorn;e body.  I wylle begynne at &thorn;e wounde at &thorn;e nese &thorn;at is|y-kutte in lengthe, wose cure ys ly&yogh;t to hele; brynge &thorn;e parties togedre|of &thorn;e wounde &amp; sowe hem, &amp; wirche aboute the wounde as y|haue seyde tofore in &thorn;e chapitle of wondes.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e nese|were y-kutte twarte offere doun to &thorn;e ouere lippe, &amp; na&thorn;eles &thorn;at &thorn;e|ouyre lippe &amp; &thorn;e nose were no&yogh;t kutte al awey, but &thorn;at it helde|faste at bo&thorn;e &thorn;e endys of &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;anne sette a&yogh;eyne &thorn;e nose in|his propre place, &thorn;e nose&thorn;rellys yche a&yogh;eyns o&thorn;ere as &thorn;ey were tofore,|&amp; make two smale tentys of wex, &amp; putte in bo&thorn;e &thorn;e nose&thorn;rellys|aboue &thorn;e wounde, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist, &amp; &thorn;enne make a poynt|by &thorn;e space of a litel fyngere from &thorn;at on ende of &thorn;e wounde,|&amp; an o&thorn;ere poynt at &thorn;e o&thorn;ere ende of &thorn;e wounde, and an o&thorn;ere|poynt in &thorn;e myddel of &thorn;e nose anentys &thorn;e forhede; &amp; afterwarde|a poynt on ei&thorn;ere syde of &thorn;e nose, afterwarde make a poynt*|betwene evyry poynt, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue in noumbre of alle &thorn;e poyntes,
<PB N="143">|whenne &thorn;ey ben ful mad, .IX. Caste &thorn;e poudre &thorn;at is tofore seyde|vpon &thorn;e wounde, &thorn;at is y-mad of lym, ffrank ensence, sancdragoun,|&amp; take whyte of an ey &amp; oyle of roses and bete hem togedire, &amp;|leye &thorn;ereynne a lynne clo&thorn; &amp; leye abouen &thorn;e wounde, aftirwarde|[bynde]* &thorn;ereto &thorn;re plumaciolus, one <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81b">vndirene&thorn;e, &amp; on on &thorn;at o syde, |an o&thorn;ere on &thorn;e o&thorn;ere syde; &amp; &thorn;anne bynde &thorn;e nose wi&thorn; tweye bandys,|&thorn;at on schall holden vp &thorn;e nose &thorn;at he may nou&yogh;t discendyn dunward,|&thorn;at o&thorn;ere schal be leyde aboffe &thorn;at he mowe kepyn &thorn;e plumacyolus,|poudere, &amp; &thorn;e sowynge.  And &thorn;ilke bande &thorn;at ys vnder &thorn;e|nose &thorn;at halt &thorn;e nose vpwarde, schal be knett abouen on &thorn;e hed,|and aftirwarde he schal be turnyde twarte offere &thorn;e forehed, &thorn;at he|mowe holde &thorn;e bande, &amp; &thorn;e nose declyne to nei&thorn;ere syde.  And &thorn;e|bande &thorn;at ys leyde aboffe &thorn;e nose, schal be bounden behynden in &thorn;e|nolle; and afterwarde he schal turnen a&yogh;eyne aboffe &thorn;e nose, holdynge|&thorn;e plumacyoles &thorn;at &thorn;ey mowe no&yogh;t wagge on neythere syde|aboute &thorn;e sewynge; &amp; aboute &thorn;e forhed &thorn;ou schalt legge &thorn;e deffensif|of bol, and aftirwarde &thorn;ou schalt worche on &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e nose|as y haue seyde in a wounde of flesch in &thorn;e firste tretys.  &THORN;e|woundes &thorn;at be&thorn; y-mad in o&thorn;ere partye of &thorn;e face as with a swerd|ore o&thorn;ire &thorn;ynge semblable, brynge hem togedire, sowe hem, &amp; cure|hem, as yt ys conteyned in generall chapitle of woundys, takynge
<PB N="144">|hede hereto, &thorn;at &thorn;e sowynge &thorn;at ys y-mad in &thorn;e face, schal be more|sotyl &amp; fairere, &thorn;anne in enye o&thorn;ere party of &thorn;e body.  And &thorn;ou|maiste maken a sowyng in &thorn;e face, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be nou&yogh;t to|myche, on &thorn;is manere.  &rx; mastyk &amp; sangdragoun &amp; poudre hem &amp;|tempre hem togedire wi&thorn; &thorn;e whyte of an ey&yogh;e to &thorn;e &thorn;yknesse of|hony, &amp; wete &thorn;ereynne tweye pecys of lynnen clo&thorn; as longe as &thorn;e| wounde, &amp; leye one on &thorn;at o syde of &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82a">wounde, &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere on &thorn;at|o&thorn;ere &amp; lete hem drey&yogh;en, and afterwarde make &thorn;e wounde sum|what to blede, &amp; &thorn;enne brynge &thorn;e partyes of &thorn;e wounde togedires;|&amp; sowe &thorn;ilke two pecys togedres, &amp; caste aboue &thorn;e poudre of lym,|ffranc ensence, sancdragoun tofore seyd, &amp; wete a clo&thorn; in &thorn;e whyte|of an ey&yogh;e &amp; oyle of roses, &amp; leye abofe al togedyre, and kepe &thorn;e|partyes with ligature, &amp; procede for&thorn; in alle &thorn;ynges as y haue tofore|seyd.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be y-mad with a dart o&thorn;ere with an|arwe, &amp; &thorn;e arwe ben y-drawe out and &thorn;e wounde be myche y-sene,|&thorn;enne &thorn;e cure ys &thorn;e same &thorn;at was seyde in &thorn;e same chapytell o&thorn;ere|ellys in &thorn;e firste tretys, whe&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;ere be a synwe prikyde o&thorn;ere|none.  But &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e arwe-hed were entrygede in enye privy place of|&thorn;e face, so &thorn;at yt my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t ben sey&yogh;en, &thorn;enne euerye man bysie|hym be his wyt, to knowe how &thorn;e seke man stod, whanne he was y-smete,|&amp; whennys &thorn;at &thorn;e arwe come, &amp; to what party &thorn;e wounde|strecchith, &thorn;at he mowe loke &yogh;if &thorn;at he mowe fynden enye manere
<PB N="145">|wey, how he may drawen out &thorn;ilke arwe-hed; and &thorn;enne drawe|hym out &thorn;e beste manere &thorn;at he may.  And &yogh;if he may nou&yogh;t, helde|into &thorn;e wounde oyle of roses, &amp; medle he oyle of roses &amp; &thorn;e &yogh;olke|of an ey&yogh;e togedre, &amp; helde into &thorn;e wounde, &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is medycine|worche in &thorn;e wounde, tyl &thorn;at kynde schewe sum manere wey.|Manye men han born an arwe-hed in &thorn;at partyes of here face by|longe tyme; and aftere kynde ha&thorn; cast out &thorn;ilke arwe-hed, o&thorn;ere|ellys ha&thorn; schewyde sum weye by whom &thorn;ilke arwe-hed my&yogh;te be|taken out.  And &thorn;ou moste taken hede be al &thorn;y myght &thorn;at whanne|&thorn;at &thorn;ou sowyste &thorn;e woundes of &thorn;e face &thorn;at &thorn;e mou&thorn; be no&yogh;t crokyde,|but make so slylye &thorn;y sowynge &thorn;at &thorn;ylke accident may no&yogh;t <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82b">ffallen; |&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou maiste do wel, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou cou&thorn;est ordeyn wel &thorn;y sowynge|&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou cou&thorn;est kepen wel &thorn;y sowynge wi&thorn; plumacyolus &amp; wi&thorn;|byndynges.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>&para; Cap. iij. tretis ij is off woundes of &thorn;e nekke &amp;|Anotomye of &thorn;e same.</HEAD>
<P>&para; By the nekke is contynwede alle &thorn;e place &thorn;at is bytwene &thorn;e|hed &amp; &thorn;e schuldres, whose Anotamye y wyll tellen as y haue|behyght.  &para; Some men makyth dyfference bytwene &thorn;e nekke &amp; &thorn;e
<PB N="146">|wesant &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;rote-bolle, and alle &thorn;ese be conprehendyde vndire &thorn;e|name of &thorn;e nekke.  In &thorn;e nekke &thorn;ere ben vij spondiles&mdash;&thorn;at is to|say, whirle bonys of &thorn;e rigge.  &THORN;e furste of &thorn;e bonys ys y-bounde|wi&thorn; a bon of &thorn;e hed &thorn;at ys y-clepyde passilare wi&thorn; manye smale|feble ligamentys; &amp; &thorn;ey weren feble bycause &thorn;at &thorn;ilke Iuncte|nexte &thorn;e hed my&yogh;te meffe manye weyes.  And &thorn;e cause why &thorn;at|&thorn;ere were manye smale lygamentes multeplyede in &thorn;at Iuncte, &thorn;at|manye smale my&yogh;te susteyne a grete burthyne as wel as a fewe|grete; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ere were a fewe grete, &thorn;ey were nou&yogh;t so able to|be meffyde.  The firste spondyle ys y-bounden to &thorn;e secunde, &thorn;e|secunde to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde to &thorn;e four&thorn;e, &thorn;e iiij. to &thorn;e v., &thorn;e v. to|&thorn;e vi., &thorn;e sixte to &thorn;e seven&thorn;e, &thorn;e vij. ys y-bounden loselyche to &thorn;e|fyrste spondile<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Whenne &thorn;at &thorn;ou reknyst from &thorn;e hed</I>, struck through, after <I>spondile</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e rugge, &thorn;at &thorn;e nekke my&yogh;te more ly&yogh;tlyche|meffen, whiche ys clepyde &thorn;e viij. spondile, whenne &thorn;at &thorn;ou reknyste|from &thorn;e hed dunwarde.*  vij. peire off synwes growi&thorn; out by &thorn;ese|.vij. spondelis.  &THORN;e firste peire of synwe procede&thorn; out* bytwene| &thorn;e fyrste spondile <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83a">&amp; &thorn;e bon of &thorn;e hed &thorn;at ys y-clepyde passilare;|&thorn;e secunde peire of synwes ys y-bore bytwene &thorn;e firste spondile &amp;|&thorn;e secunde, &amp; so euery peire passith out bytwene euery spondile.
<PB N="147">|&THORN;ese Synwys bu&thorn; devyeded manye weyes by &thorn;e hed, &amp; &thorn;e nekke, &amp;|&thorn;e face, &amp; &thorn;e breste, schuldres, &amp; &thorn;e armes; &thorn;e braunches of &thorn;e|synwes of the hed in some place be&thorn; contynwede &amp; Ioynde with|&thorn;ese synwes.  And &thorn;ese synwes bu&thorn; y-clepyde meffynge ry&yogh;te as|&thorn;e synwes &thorn;at comyth of &thorn;e fore partye of &thorn;e brayn be&thorn; y-clepyde|felynge &amp; &thorn;ese habbi&thorn; also felynge.  Of &thorn;ese Synwes &thorn;at comyth|of &thorn;e spondlis of &thorn;e nekke &thorn;ere be&thorn; mad brawnys, &thorn;e whiche be&thorn;|instrumentes of mevynge of &thorn;e partyes.  In &thorn;e nekke behynde,|&thorn;ere ben y-ordeynde opyn veynes comynge from &thorn;e lyffere whiche|&thorn;at ascendyn to &thorn;e hed, and vndire &thorn;o Veynes &thorn;ere ben Arteryes y-hud|priuelyche, comynge ffrom &thorn;e herte &amp; goynge to &thorn;e hed for|notable profetes.  And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ey han do al here office in &thorn;e|hed, &thorn;ey descenden doun by &thorn;e place &thorn;at be&thorn; behynde &thorn;e erys &amp;|&thorn;ey bryngen materie spermatice, &thorn;at is to say mater of sperme, don|to &thorn;e ballokes, &amp; &thorn;erefore it ys y-seyde: &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;o Veynes weren y-kutt,|a man scholde neuere engendre.  On &thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde &amp; eke on|&thorn;e lefte syde of &thorn;e nekke &thorn;ere ben y-ordeynde tweye nolles, &thorn;e|whyche be&thorn; of lygamente mater, &thorn;e whiche procede&thorn; out of &thorn;e bonys
<PB N="148">|of &thorn;e hed &amp; of &thorn;e spondiles, &amp; &thorn;ey strecchen doun to &thorn;e ers in|leng&thorn;e besydes &thorn;e spyne bon, &amp; &thorn;ey ben a couche &amp; a restynge|place to &thorn;e synwes &thorn;at comyth out of &thorn;e nucha.  In &thorn;e fore partye|of &thorn;e nekke &thorn;ere ys gula whiche &thorn;at strecchi&thorn; from &thorn;e chyn doun to|&thorn;e furcle of &thorn;e brest; and bytwene &thorn;e nekke &amp; &thorn;e gulam wi&thorn;ynnefor&thorn;| &thorn;ere ys <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83b">y-ordeyned mery&mdash;&thorn;at ys to seye &thorn;e wesand; &thorn;e whiche|&thorn;at discendi&thorn; of a smal schyn environynge alle &thorn;e mouth withynnefor&thorn;,|&amp; so goynge doun to &thorn;e Stomak, &amp; he ys hol &amp; conteynde wi&thorn;|&thorn;e Stomak, &amp; ys of Substaunce of &thorn;e same stomak, &amp; he dissendi&thorn;|doun by &thorn;e hyndere partye of &thorn;e nek clevynge to &thorn;e spondelis; tyl|&thorn;at he come to &thorn;e .v. spondile of &thorn;e rugge, &amp; &thorn;ere he ys departyde|from &thorn;e spondelis and declyne&thorn; into &thorn;e Innere partye tyl &thorn;at he|perce &thorn;orwe &thorn;e mydryff, &amp; he ys componed of twey pannycles, and|in &thorn;e Innore clo&thorn; &thorn;ere ben brawnys in lengthe, by &thorn;e whiche drau&yogh;te|ys made of mete &amp; drynke, and in &thorn;e vtter clo&thorn; &thorn;ere bene brawnys|in brede by whom ys made castynge out of superfluyte; and he ha&thorn;|non transversarye, &thorn;at ys to seye goynge twartoffere, ffor wythholdynge|ys nou&yogh;t nedfful to hym.  And in &thorn;e fore partye of &thorn;e brest|&thorn;ere is y-set &thorn;e canne of longes, &thorn;e whiche ys componed off grustlye
<PB N="149">|rynges y-bounde togedire wi&thorn; panycleris ligamentes, habbynge in|&thorn;e Innore partye a ful sme&thorn;e pannicle Ioynynge togedire &thorn;ilke|grustly rynges.  And &thorn;ilke rynges, whenne &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben ioynede with|mery, &thorn;ey ben defautyf anonde &thorn;e mery.  And &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e canne|of &thorn;e longes [is]* as yt were &thorn;e forme of a cane&mdash;&thorn;at is to say a reed,|of &thorn;e whiche reed &thorn;e four&thorn; part were kutt away in lengthe, &amp; aftereward|&thorn;e canne ys y-wreye wi&thorn; a sotyl cloth, &thorn;at whanne &thorn;at a grete|mossell of mete passe doun be &thorn;e mery, he scholde han non lettynge,|but &thorn;ilke pannicle of mery &yogh;euyth stede to &thorn;e grete mete passynge|doun to &thorn;e stomak. &THORN;e &thorn;rotbolle &thorn;at is mad of &thorn;re grustlys, ys y-sette|aboue &thorn;ese <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84a">two wey&yogh;es.  And bo&thorn;e on &thorn;e ry&yogh;te syde &amp; eke on &thorn;e |lefte syde of &thorn;e cane of &thorn;ese longes, &thorn;ere be&thorn; tweye grete veynes &thorn;at|be&thorn; y-clepyde organice o&thorn;ere ellys guydes.  &amp; vndire &thorn;e veynes|&thorn;ere ben grete arteryes, and of &thorn;e kyttinge of &thorn;ilke Veynes &amp;|Arteryes &thorn;ere comyth ofte tymes gret peryle &amp; sumtyme sodeyne|de&thorn;; for &thorn;e grete afynite<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>, above line.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ey han in &thorn;e herte &amp; &thorn;e grete noyenesse|&thorn;at &thorn;ey han to &thorn;e lyffer, sennore by hem blod ys evacued,|wherefore spirites exale&thorn; whyche &thorn;at bu&thorn; frendys, bo&thorn;e to &thorn;e body &amp;
<PB N="150">|eke to &thorn;e soule.  &THORN;e ligamente of &thorn;e &thorn;rote ys y-clepyd &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>, above line.</NOTE> eminence|o&thorn;ere &thorn;e hek&thorn;e of &thorn;e epiglote, &amp; in &thorn;e sydes of &thorn;e &thorn;rote &thorn;ere is y-set|gula. &amp; &thorn;e goynge of brawnys, cordys, synwes, veynes, arteryes &amp;|here braunchys by parties of &thorn;e hed proceden aftyre &thorn;e ordre of|heres, &amp; &thorn;ey ben ordeynde in &thorn;e nekke &amp; in &thorn;e gula aftire here|leng&thorn;e.  And hereby &thorn;ou maiste ysene, how &thorn;at yt is necessarye a|surgyn to maken hys kuttynges, &amp; hys brennynges by leng&thorn;e of &thorn;e|nekke &amp; of &thorn;e &thorn;rote, and &thorn;at &thorn;e woundys &thorn;at ben y-mad twarte|offere be&thorn; more perylose, &thorn;en &thorn;o &thorn;at bene in lengthe.</P>
<P>Wonde of &thorn;e nekke.  &para; Now we wyl tretyn of woundes &thorn;at|be&thorn; mad in &thorn;is place wi&thorn; a swerd o&thorn;ere with sum &thorn;ynge semblable|to hym, o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; an arwe, o&thorn;ere with sum &thorn;ynge semblable to hym.|And &yogh;if it be wyth a swerde, o&thorn;ere yt ys twarte offere ore in lengthe;|and &yogh;if it be twart offere, and &thorn;ere ben y-kutt grete Veynes o&thorn;ere|arteryes, hit ys gretly to dreden.  Na&thorn;eles &thorn;ou schalt helpe to|staunche &thorn;e blod &amp; to consoude &thorn;e veyne, aftere &thorn;e techynge tofore|asygned in &thorn;e chapytle off fflux of blod.  And &yogh;if &thorn;ere be a synwe|kutte, brynge &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e synwe togedyre, &amp; sow&yogh; &thorn;e pellykles|of &thorn;e synwe with &thorn;e sowynge of &thorn;e wounde, as y haue tau&yogh;t tofore| in &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84b">place of sowynge of synwes, and leye aboffe lumbricus of &thorn;e
<PB N="151">|erthe &thorn;at be&thorn; erthe wormes y-stampyde &amp; boylled wyth oylle of|roses, &amp; kepe &thorn;e sowynge with byndynge, and so procede for&thorn; in alle|&thorn;ynge in &thorn;e cure, as yt is tolde in the chapitle tofore schewyde.|And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e wonde were in leng&thorn;e, yt ys no&yogh;t necessarie but|forto sowe &thorn;e wounde &amp; to casten aboue, &thorn;e poudre of lym, ffrank|ensence &amp; sank dragoun, &amp; to kepe &thorn;e sewynge &amp; &thorn;e poudre with|byndynge, tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde be ful consouded.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e|wounde were y-mad in &thorn;o parties with an arwe o&thorn;ere a knyff, o&thorn;ere|a spere, o&thorn;ere sum &thorn;ynge semblable to hem, and &yogh;if &thorn;ere be an arwe,|drawe hym out, and &yogh;if &thorn;e arwe be drawen out, loke &yogh;if &thorn;ere folwe|emorosogie, &thorn;at ys to seye, a gret flux of blod, &amp; &thorn;enne staunche hym|aftere &thorn;e doctryne y-told tofore.  &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ere be non flux of blod,|loke &yogh;if &thorn;ere be ak&thorn;e; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ere be ak&thorn;e, put into &thorn;e wounde a|lytel tente &thorn;at may holde &thorn;e wounde opyn al day, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may se|&thorn;at &thorn;e wounded man schal han non ak&thorn;e.  And &yogh;if he haue non ak&thorn;e,|lete &thorn;e wounde be consoudyde; ffor sum tyme it happith, &thorn;at an|arwe, o&thorn;er sum thynge semblable passith &thorn;orwe &thorn;e nekke &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;rote,|&amp; &yogh;it he touchi&thorn; no&yogh;t veyne, arterye, ne synwe, &amp; &thorn;enne it nedi&thorn;|no&yogh;t but &thorn;at &thorn;e wonde be consouded.  And &yogh;if &thorn;ere were ak&thorn;e o&thorn;ere|ellys a bygynnynge of swellynge, &thorn;an yt were necessarie to fulfylle|&thorn;e wounde wi&thorn; hot oyle of roses &amp; to put in a tente no&yogh;t to grete,
<PB N="152">|y-wett in &thorn;e &yogh;olke of an ey&yogh;e &amp; oyle of roses hot, &amp; so holde &thorn;e|wounde open to &thorn;at he &yogh;yfe quyter, &amp; afterwarde clanse hym &amp;|afterwarde consoude hym.  Nota: vndirstande &thorn;e peryles &thorn;at come&thorn;| from wondys* &thorn;at ben mad in &thorn;is place.  &THORN;e firste <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85a">Perel ys: &yogh;if|&thorn;at &thorn;e nekke be kutte twarte offere with a swerd, so &thorn;at &thorn;e nekke-bon|&amp; &thorn;e marye of &thorn;e nekke-bon be y-kut al atwo, yt is dedlyche;|and &yogh;if &thorn;at nucha, &thorn;at ys &thorn;e marye of &thorn;e nekke-bon, is no&yogh;t y-kut al|atwo but ys y-hurt, yt is peryle of leosynge, ffelynge &amp; meffynge, &amp;|at &thorn;e laste to be ded, but &yogh;if &thorn;e medycines &thorn;at y schal tellen afterwarde|mowe helpen.  And &yogh;if &thorn;at enye Veynes o&thorn;ere enye gret|synwe be y-kut twart offere, y suppose &thorn;at he be helyde, &thorn;e nekke|schal neuere haue hys fre meffynge; and &yogh;if enye of the veynes|organyk whiche &thorn;at be&thorn; clepyde guydes, o&thorn;ere ellys enye of &thorn;e|arteries &thorn;at be&thorn; vndire hem be&thorn; y-kut, yt ys drede of sodeyne de&thorn;,|ffor sodeyne exalacioun of &thorn;e spirites &amp; also for Afynyte of &thorn;e|herte; &amp; also &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e canne off &thorn;e longes be y-kut twarte offere al|atwo, for &thorn;e more partye it is dedlyche; &amp; so it ys seyde &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;e|veynes &thorn;at be&thorn; behynde &thorn;e eres be y-kut al atwo, he schal nevire|engendre.  Also sum tyme ys y-kut o&thorn;ere y-prekyde &thorn;e synwe &thorn;at is|clepyde reuersiff, &thorn;at ys vndire bo&thorn;e &thorn;e sydes of &thorn;e ere, of whose|kuttynge o&thorn;ere prekynge euere more ys mad horsnesse.  And &yogh;if
<PB N="153">|&thorn;at place ben y-perced with an arwe, &amp; &thorn;ow&yogh; &thorn;at trachea arteria be|y-percyde o&thorn;ere ellys ysophage, so &thorn;at Nucha be no&yogh;t &thorn;rillede be &thorn;e|mydle, &thorn;ey mowe ben y-helyde with gode medycines &amp; acordynge.|&THORN;ou schalt helpe Nucha &thorn;at ys y-hurt in &thorn;is manere: &thorn;ou schalt|helden into &thorn;e wounde in &thorn;e bygynninge oyle of roses &amp; afterwarde|leye aboffe oyle of roses &amp; &thorn;e &yogh;elke of an ey&yogh;e, and &thorn;ou schalt be|busy in alle manere to aswage ak&thorn;e; &amp; whenne &thorn;at quyter ys y-mad,|&thorn;enne leye a mundificatyff wi&thorn; medicynes confortatyff and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85b">Incarnatyfes |y-mad in thys manere: &rx;. oyle of rosis colat .&yogh;. iiij, with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn;</I> for <I>wex.</I></NOTE>|resyne ana. &yogh;. ij, terbentyne &yogh;. iij, frank ensence, mastyk ana. &yogh;. i,|mirre, sarcocolle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sarcticolle</I>.</NOTE> mumie ana .&yogh;. <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>, barly mele .&yogh;. <ABBR EXPAN="[one half]">ss</ABBR>; streyne it on a|clo&thorn; &amp; leye yt on &thorn;e nucha &thorn;at is hurt.  And &thorn;aw&yogh; &thorn;at hereof euere|more pronosticacion scholde go tofore whiche scholde sownen to|yuele, na&thorn;eles by &thorn;is medicine &thorn;ere comyth rectificacioun to &thorn;e nuca,|&amp; amelioracioun off mevynge of lymes &thorn;at be&thorn; bene&thorn;e &thorn;e place of &thorn;e|nuca &thorn;at ys y-hurt, more helpynge, &thorn;enne semyth possible to &thorn;e leche.|For &thorn;ere ys no&thorn;ynge vnpossible to Stalworth nature; namlyche|whanne &thorn;at yt is holpen wi&thorn; a gode leche &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ynges, &thorn;at be&thorn;
<PB N="154">|helpynge &amp; acordynge to a gode entencioun.  Here vndirstande &thorn;at|alle manere wounde &thorn;at persith to &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e brayn o&thorn;ere|ellys to &thorn;e nuca, so &thorn;at by &thorn;e hurtynge of &thorn;e nuca &thorn;e meffynge &amp;|&thorn;e ffelynge of some lymes ben y-lost, namlyche from &thorn;e whirlebonys|of &thorn;e rugge, of &thorn;e reynes vpwarde, &amp; alle manere wounde &thorn;at|ys mad in &thorn;e extremites of &thorn;e lacertes as &thorn;re fyngremele brede in|&thorn;e schuldres, o&thorn;ere &thorn;re fyngre mele brede aboue &thorn;e elbowe o&thorn;ere byne&thorn;en,|o&thorn;ere &thorn;re fyngre mele aboue &thorn;e kne o&thorn;ere byne&thorn;ene, &amp; euery|wounde &thorn;at ys in a synwye place with strengest ak&thorn;e &amp; hardnesse,|schal be demyde dedlyche: ffor &thorn;e noblete of &thorn;ilke brayn, &amp; for &thorn;e|Affynite of nuca wyth &thorn;e brayn, of &thorn;e whiche nuca passith as &thorn;e|Ryuere from a welle, &amp; for &thorn;e Afynite of &thorn;ilke Synwes wi&thorn; &thorn;e brayn,|by mene of &thorn;e Nuca, of whom &thorn;ey passen out as of a flod, wherefore| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="86a">&thorn;ou schalt euyre more in swiche manere woundes pronostiken|de&thorn;, and euere more fle as myche as &thorn;ou mayst from vnresonable|cures, but &yogh;if &thorn;ou be wi&thorn; &thorn;e more Instaunce y-prey&yogh;ede.  Na&thorn;eles|sumtyme nature with gode helpynges worchith &thorn;at seme&thorn; to the|leche vnpossible.  Neuere &thorn;e latere loue non swiche cures* but &yogh;if|&thorn;ou be gretliche y-preyede, and &thorn;enne entyremete of &thorn;e cure of &thorn;e|syke man.
